   &UR; For WEDNESDAY PMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for PMs of Wednesday, Aug. 18.
</P>
<P>
   The PMs news desk, 212-556-1927, opens at 7 a.m. Eastern Time.
To get story repeats before this hour call 212-621-1595 for reruns
on AP DataFeatures or 214-980-8305 or 8367 for repeats on UPI
DataNews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SIERRA-LEONE (Freetown, Sierra Leone) _ Five weeks after signing
a peace treaty to end a catastrophic eight-year civil war, the
leader of the rebellion in Sierra Leone has yet to return. He is
said to be concerned over his safety, his accommodations here in
the capital and, perhaps most significantly, his travel
arrangements. By Norimitsu Onishi.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Locator map has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-CRIME (Austin, Texas) _ Law and order has always been part
of George W. Bush's politics. He ran for governor of Texas in 1994
with a series of commercials depicting a man abducting a woman at
gunpoint in a parking garage, and a moment later, a police officer
draping a blanket over the woman's body. Bush promised to get
tougher with criminals, and that stand helped him win. An
examination of his record for the five years he has been governor
shows he has been consistent in pressing a law-and-order agenda.
But how Bush's record on criminal justice will appeal to voters in
other regions remains to be tested as he campaigns for the
Republican nomination for president. By Fox Butterfield.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   ANIMAL-RIGHTS-LAW (Undated) _ More than a generation after civil
rights and environmental lawyers took their battles to the courts,
there are now lawyers who say they are following in those footsteps
on behalf of clients with names like Freckles and Rainbow. Fighting
for creatures like performing orangutans and dogs used in
experimentation, the lawyers are creating a new field of animal law
with far more ambitious goals than traditionally weak anti-cruelty
laws. They are filing novel lawsuits and producing new legal
scholarship to try to chip away at a fundamental principle of
American law that animals are property and have no rights. By
William Glaberson.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON _ (Moved in ``w'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-NUKE _ The former head of counterintelligence at the Los
Alamos National Laboratory in New Mexico says in an interview that
Wen Ho Lee,, the American scientist who is the top suspect in the
Chinese atomic spy case, was unfairly singled out for federal
investigation because of his race. By William J. Broad.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ATT-MEDIAONE (Washington) _ Two federal agencies that have begun
separate reviews of AT&AMP;T's $58 billion bid to buy Mediaone Group
are facing competing arguments from the company and its critics
about whether the deal is, in essence, too large to block. By
Stephen Labaton.
</P>
<P>
   DISNEY-EISNER (Burbank, Calif.) _ As Michael Eisner, chairman of
Walt Disney Co., struggles to overcome sagging earnings and the
fallout from his feud with his former studio chief, Jeffrey
Katzenberg, he has suddenly begun playing Mr. Nice Guy. Perhaps
humbled by bad publicity and weak profits, he seems determined to
assure outsiders that Disney is again poised for growth, which may
be good news for Wall Street. By Geraldine Fabrikant.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   EMERGING-MARKETPLACE (New York) _ The world's emerging markets
are showing some small signs of stress. After soaring a collective
40 percent in the first half of the year, their stock markets have
fallen 7 percent more recently, leaving investors to wonder whether
the rally is over. By Richard A. Oppel Jr. (ART ADV: Graphic has
been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-AD-COLUMN (Undated) _ Advertising on the Internet, like
most uses of this new medium, is still in the early stages of a
long and presumably fruitful evolution. In other words, it is long
on potential but, so far, short on success stories. By Bob
Tedeschi.
</P>
<P>
   SUV-PICKUPS (Philadelphia) _ Looking at why auto makers are
introducing hybrids of pickup trucks and sports utility vehicles
for the fall. By Keith Bradsher.
</P>
<P>
   BRAZIL-ECON (Sao Paulo) _ New data indicate that Brazil is
officially out of a recession. By Simon Romero.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-FISH (Vladivostok, Russia) _ Half the catch of North
Pacific whitefish, used everywhere from British supermarkets to
McDonald's deep fryers, comes from 11 Russian supertrawlers. So a
recent decision by the Russian government to void a contract with a
U.S.-Russian joint fishing venture and transfer its ships and catch
quotas to a debt-ridden Russian rival has roiled the
multibillion-dollar fishing industry and raised the possibility
that foreign creditors will seize the ships. By Russell Working.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Map has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CULTURE (Moved in ``e'' category) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   STAGE-FRIGHT (New York) _ A former Green Beret helps performers
overcome stage fright. By Ralph Blumenthal.
</P>
<P>
   AMPLIFIED-OPERA (Undated) _ Electronic sound enhancement turns
out to be more widespread in American concert halls than previously
believed. By Anthony Tommasini.
</P>
<P>
   TUSCANY-ART (San Casciano Dei Bagni, Italy) _ It isn't often
that a 68-year-old retired produce vendor beats out world-class
artists to win first prize in an international art competition. It
also isn't often that world-class artists find themselves vying for
prizes in small Tuscan towns better known for their thermal baths.
But then it isn't often that medieval towns do become maverick
centers of contemporary art. That is exactly what has happened in
this town of 650 in the province of Siena, since an independent
curator, Cornelia Lauf, opened Camera Oscura, an avant-garde
micro-gallery, three years ago. By Elisabetta Povoledo.
</P>
<P>
   TV-NOTES (Undated) _ News and notes on televison. By Bill
Carter.
</P>
<P>
   ROPES-FILM-REVIEW (Undated) _ ``On the Ropes'': Nanette Burstein
and Brett Morgen, directors; a documentary. Reviewed by Stephen
Holden.
</P>
<P>
   ELIOT-BOOK-REVIEW (Undated) _ ``T. S. Eliot,'' by Lyndall Gordon
(Norton). Reviewed by Richard Bernstein.
</P>
<P>
   TV-MILLIONAIRE-REVIEW (Undated) _ On ABC, ``Who Wants to Be a
Millionaire?'' with Regis Philbin. Reviewed by Ron Wertheimer.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY (Moved in ``k'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   DOWD-COLUMN (Washington) _ Maureen Dowd writes about Gov. George
W. Bush and the cocaine issue.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SPORTS (Moved in ``s'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   FBN-FREEMAN-COLUMN (Jacksonville, Fla.) _ Sports of The Times
column: Tom Coughlin is the only coach the Jacksonville Jaguars
have had, and the five-year franchise has done just fine under him,
with a better playoff record in that span than most of the
established franchises. By Mike Freeman.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DINING (Moved in ``d'' category) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NY-PICNIC (New York) _ For me, picnics involve packing up a
meal, hiking a trail of sidewalks to Central Park and hunkering
down to a meal on grass, nestled among ranges of buildings in one
of America's most densely populated restaurant cities. But they are
a form of escape _ from reservations, from a cramped city kitchen,
from the madness of supermarkets. With all this in mind, I recently
set out to plan a picnic in the park. Not just any picnic. But a
meal that brought together all that I like about a picnic and all
that I like about eating in New York. By Amanda Hesser.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   TADICH-ANNIVERSARY (San Francisco) _ For those among the
fortune-seeking forty-niners who survived scurvy and shipwreck on
the voyage around Cape Horn, and for those who survived snow and
starvation traveling overland, San Francisco presented a gaudy
spectacle of freedom, where the restraints of the East fell away.
You could grab a cup of coffee at a little tent on Long Wharf,
where three Croatian immigrants set up shop in the very first year
of the gold rush, 1849, the year before California joined the
union. Landfill projects, earthquakes and commercial exigency have
forced repeated moves since, but the business has prospered under a
succession of Croatian-American owners. It still does. It is now
called the Tadich Grill, after a former proprietor who went to work
there in 1876. It is one of the state's oldest businesses, still a
favorite of visitors and locals. By R.W. Apple Jr.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   PEPPERS-EATING-WELL (Undated) _ The column: Red peppers, at
their peak for flavor and nutrition. By Marian Burros.
</P>
<P>
   SIMPLE-COOKING (Undated) _ The column: salmon poached in butter.
By Mark Bittman.
</P>
<P>
   SUCKLING-PIG (Undated) _ The strange phenomenon of suckling pig,
heavy and fatty, in hottest summer. By Eric Asimov.
</P>
<P>
   MASTER-CHEF (Undated) _ The column: Quail with an herb salad. By
Waldy Malouf.
</P>
<P>
   MEAT-BOOK-REVIEW (Undated) _ Amanda Hesser reviews ``Prime Time:
The Lobels' Guide to Great Grilled Meats'' (Macmillan, $25).
</P>
<P>
   WINE-TALK (Undated) _ The wine column: a review of ``Drink: A
Social History of America.'' By Frank J. Prial.
</P>
<P>
   WINE-TASTINGS (Undated) _ A capsule wine review.
</P>
<P>
   FOOD-BITS&AMP;BITES (Undated) _ The column: Replacement parts for
kitchen appliances, on the Internet. By S.A. Belzer.
</P>
