<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-18 00:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1047 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BKL-COMETS-HENNING-HN     08-18 0722
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKL-COMETS-HENNING-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALAN TRUEX  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
The pressure could have overwhelmed someone trying to replace a
teammate ravaged by cancer of the brain and lungs. And when she
joined the Comets before the season began, Sonja Henning recognized
she couldn't be the point guard Kim Perrot was for two years.
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``I didn't come in with the idea that I'd replace Kim,'' Henning
said after Tuesday's practice at Westside Tennis Club. ``She's a
great player who has done great things. She was obviously
instrumental in the team winning two championships.''
</P>
<P>
   Perrot buzzed around the basketball court in a frenetic hustle
accentuated by her 5-5 size. Henning, 5-7, brought a less
spontaneous, more measured approach to the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's smarter than her coach,'' Van Chancellor said of
Henning, ``and that doesn't bother me. She's very analytical, like
a lawyer. Which she is.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Henning, 29, excels in courts of law as well as the
basketball kind. She has a law degree from Duke, obtained after a
bachelor's degree from Stanford, which followed a high school
grade-point average of 4.3 on a 4.0 scale.
</P>
<P>
   But being smart is a mixed blessing in most sports, including
basketball.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes I think Sonja is too analytical,'' Chancellor said.
``I'd like her to be more emotional.''
</P>
<P>
   He is careful not to add: ``the way Kim was.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the Comets were slightly better when Perrot was calling
their shots, they are grateful for Henning's smooth floor direction
as the team works a pendulum offense _ back and forth between
Cynthia Cooper and Sheryl Swoopes.
</P>
<P>
   Entering tonight's game against Phoenix at Compaq Center, the
Comets are 24-5. They were 26-3 at this point last year.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, wins and losses seem sadly irrelevant as the Comets
ponder the helplessness of Perrot, breathing through a respirator
at M.D. Anderson Cancer Center.
</P>
<P>
   Chancellor visited Perrot after Monday's nine-point win over
Utah.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was lying there sleeping,'' he said. ``I just told her how
much I cared about her. She's still on this team, very much part of
this team.''
</P>
<P>
   After Tuesday's practice, Henning said: ``I can't begin to
describe how much Kim affects the team. But the players understand
we have to be professionals and do our job. That's the way Kim
would like it to be.
</P>
<P>
   ``For that two hours, we have to focus and refocus more than
usual. But the second we walk off the court, basketball is done and
over with. I think it will be that way through the rest of the
season.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if she felt special pressures as the stand-in for Perrot,
Henning said: ``Not really, only because the entire team has been
so welcoming to the new players coming in.''
</P>
<P>
   Henning has hesitated to mix too much of herself into the team's
chemistry, which may explain her understated style of play.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coming in, I didn't want to shake up anything,'' she said. ``I
just wanted to ease in and go unnoticed.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a team with strong personalities already,'' she said,
chuckling. ``And that's not a bad thing. Actually, it's a great
thing. But as a newcomer, you try to read and get accustomed to
other people instead of trying to be outgoing and outspoken.''
</P>
<P>
   The outspokenness she can save for her law practice, which has
waged a tug-of-war with basketball for her attention. After
graduating from Stanford in 1991, Henning played professional
basketball in Sweden for a year. Then she entered law school.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, she practiced labor and employment law in Los Angeles
for a large firm, Littler-Mendelson, which has a branch office in
Houston. When the American Basketball League first sought her
services as a player in the spring of 1996, Henning declined. She
changed her mind, however, when she talked with her new law
partners.
</P>
<P>
   ``They encouraged me to play,'' she said. ``They pointed out
there's only a small window of opportunity, that I should give it a
try and practice law later.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, she intends to do that in the offseason when she
returns to Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   But first there is a third consecutive WNBA championship to be
won. As Henning and the other Comets are saying, ``Kim wants us to
win.'' The way they see it, that is is the least _ and perhaps the
most _ they can do.
</P>
</TEXT>
