<HEADER>
A1053 &Cx1f; tth-z
u a BC-SEWAGE-CANADA-SPI &LR;      08-18 1109
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SEWAGE-CANADA-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VICTORIA, B.C., GETS FLUNKING GRADE FOR SEWAGE TREATMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOEL CONNELLY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A new study calls the discharge of raw sewage into Canadian
waterways a ``national disgrace'' and cites Victoria as the worst
offender, flunking British Columbia's capital with an ``F minus''
grade for continued dumping into the Strait of Juan de Fuca.
</P>
<P>
   The National Sewage Report Card to be released on Wednesday is a
successor to a 1994 study and finds that treatment has improved in
eight Canadian cities out of 21 surveyed. One is Vancouver, which
has upgraded two plants on the Fraser River from primary to
secondary treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Its lowest grades are reserved for Victoria as well as St.
John's, Newfoundland, and Dawson City in the Yukon.
</P>
<P>
   The report was prepared by the Sierra Legal Defense Fund, a
Vancouver-based environmental group, on behalf of the United
Fishermen and Allied Workers Union and Georgia Strait Alliance. All
are critics of Victoria's sewage discharges.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our sewage problems are comprehensive and countrywide, from
sea to stinking sea,'' concluded the report, which looked at
communities ranging from Toronto, with a population of 2.4 million,
to tiny Dawson City with only 1,700 year-round residents.
</P>
<P>
   ``Halifax and St. John's on the east coast, and Victoria on the
west coast, have no sewage treatment at all,'' it reported.
``Together, they discharge about 122 billion litres (about 35
billion gallons) of raw sewage into the Atlantic and Pacific Oceans
each year.''
</P>
<P>
   Halifax, Nova Scotia's capital, escaped an ``F'' because it is
developing plans for treatment plants and diverting toxic
substances out of its sewage system.
</P>
<P>
   Victoria dumps more than 20 million gallons of untreated waste
each day into the Strait of Juan de Fuca, an international waterway
shared by the United States and Canada. It does screen large solids
out of its sewage.
</P>
<P>
   The sewage comes from 322,000 people in the British Columbia
capital and nearby suburbs, which constitute one of the
fastest-growing areas in Canada.
</P>
<P>
   Although no toxicity testing is required, Victoria-area
municipal governments have insisted that discharges from the
Macaulay Point and Clover Point outfalls cause only ``minimal''
environmental impacts.
</P>
<P>
   In an assessment released last spring, the Capital Regional
District, an umbrella organization of local governments, said:
``Water quality at beaches in the vicinity of the outfalls is not
adversely affected by the two outfalls.''
</P>
<P>
   That claim is vigorously disputed in the Sierra Legal Defense
Fund's report.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although sewage effluent is discharged into a large body of
water with strong currents and tidal movements, bacterial and metal
pollution extends from one to two kilometers (.62 to 1.25 miles)
away from the MacAulay Point outfall,'' it reported.
</P>
<P>
   The report also noted that ``an extensive area'' in the Strait
of Juan de Fuca has been closed to shellfish harvesting by order of
Canada's fisheries ministry.
</P>
<P>
   The Capital Regional District has committed since 1986 to
acquire land for construction of a sewage treatment plant. Eleven
years ago, it began discussing land acquisition with Canada's
Department of National Defense for a treatment plant near Macauley
Point, located in Esquimalt just west of Victoria.
</P>
<P>
   But the district has yet to set aside land for a sewage
treatment plant ``nor does it appear to have any intention of doing
so,'' according to the report card.
</P>
<P>
   The district has recently negotiated a deadline extension until
July 2000 for delivery of a waste management plan, designed to
include a schedule for upgrading to primary and secondary
treatment. In 1991, Canada's environment and fisheries ministries
first instructed the district to upgrade at least to primary
treatment of Victoria-area sewage.
</P>
<P>
   Cost estimates for treating Victoria's sewage have ranged from
$90 million to $600 million (Canadian), and neither the provincial
nor Canadian federal governments have shown any eagerness to pay
much of the bill.
</P>
<P>
   The status quo has a powerful defender in David Anderson,
Canada's minister of the environment and Victoria's member of the
federal parliament in Ottawa. In a recent interview, Anderson
argued that cold, fast-moving waters of the Strait of Juan de Fuca
effectively disperse and oxygenate the sewage.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sewage is treated naturally,'' Anderson said. ``Within
meters of the discharge outfalls, you have sailboarders. Within 400
meters, the sewage is barely detectable. It is one of the few
places in the world where this occurs.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, in a discussion with Seattle Post-Intelligencer
editors, Anderson added: ``The best wind surfing we have in
Victoria is off Dallas Road, right between the two outfalls. They
don't glow as they walk down Government Street. They don't drop
dead.''
</P>
<P>
   Beginning in 1983, however, the fisheries ministry closed down
shellfish harvesting in waters near the discharge outfalls in
Victoria and Esquimalt. The closure area now totals more than 30
square miles of the Strait of Juan de Fuca.
</P>
<P>
   In February, the Sierra Legal Defense Fund sought to bring a
private prosecution _ which is legal under Canadian law _ against
the Capital Regional District for violating federal fisheries law
as well as British Columbia's waste management act.
</P>
<P>
   The sewage report card gives a ``C minus'' grade to Vancouver.
It notes upgrading of the two Fraser River treatment plants, and a
sharp reduction in sewage overflows.
</P>
<P>
   But Vancouver's largest treatment plant, at Iona Island, offers
only primary treatment and ``is the single biggest source of
pollution in Georgia Strait,'' the report concluded.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sewage is not just human waste,'' added the report. ``Studies
show that typical municipal sewage contains some 200 synthetic
chemicals.''
</P>
<P>
   Secondary sewage treatment, a process adopted by U.S. cities on
Puget Sound and the Strait of Juan de Fuca, kills bacteria and
removes both solids and nutrients from sewage. It requires
construction of a treatment plant, which holds ponds in which
solids are settled. The remaining liquid sewage is treated with
micro-organisms, which remove objectional materials.
</P>
<P>
   Across the strait from Victoria, Port Angeles, Wash., has spent
more than $31 million on a secondary sewage treatment system. Port
Townsend, Wash., has estimated its costs at $10 million.
</P>
<P>
   Victoria is looking at several options for treatment. One is
simple screening, in which sewage is chopped up. Another is sand
filtering. A third is treatment with chemicals.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
