<HEADLINE>
ABBOTT'S AWESOME FOR M'S 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN RALEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ Passing through customs today, they'll ask him if he
brought anything back from Canada that he didn't take in.
</P>
<P>
   For Paul Abbott, the answer is yes.
</P>
<P>
   A career-high nine strikeouts, a career-best fourth victory in a
big-league season, even greater job security.
</P>
<P>
   The well-traveled Abbott, playing just about everywhere but
north of the border in a 15-year pro career, Tuesday night
continued to do whatever the Mariners ask of him. Against the
Toronto Blue Jays, the former starter-turned reliever-turned
starter again gave them 61/3 innings in an 8-5 victory at SkyDome,
overcoming the occasional slip-up with determined stuff.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being 4-and-0 is really big for me,'' Abbott said. ``I want to
stay here for awhile. A fast start is something I felt I needed to
show people to prove I belonged.''
</P>
<P>
   The win was the third consecutive for the Mariners (59-60),
flirting once more with the .500 mark, a place they haven't been in
two weeks. They polish off a six-game road swing through the East
today with a 10 a.m. getaway game against the Blue Jays, now losers
of six straight.
</P>
<P>
   Abbott wasn't sharp at the outset, but teammates Edgar Martinez
and Ken Griffey Jr. were. Martinez unloaded two home runs in the
first three innings, his 17th and 18th, while Griffey cranked his
American League-leading 37th in the third, helping build a 6-1
lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners' starting pitcher nearly didn't stick around long
enough to enjoy it.
</P>
<P>
   In the bottom of the third inning, Abbott was face to face with
manager Lou Piniella and a possible hook after giving up a pair of
runs and going six-deep in the Toronto batting order. But the
right-hander remained cool under the inquisition.
</P>
<P>
   ``He asked me how I felt, and I said, `Fine,''' Abbott said.
``He said, `Well, I'm not.' So I tried to accommodate him and make
him feel better.''
</P>
<P>
   With two runners on and two outs, the pitcher found the proper
remedy. He got the next hitter, Darrin Fletcher, to ground back to
the mound.
</P>
<P>
   For the 31-year-old Abbott, it has been a long, grinding journey
to reach this point. He didn't join the Mariners until June 25,
recovering from offseason knee surgery. He has bounced between the
rotation and the bullpen since. For that matter, he has bounced all
over baseball, unable to make a breakthrough until going 3-1 for
the Mariners in a September callup last season _ matching the
number of wins he had for Minnesota in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Against the Blue Jays and in just his third start this season,
Abbott was convinced he lacked velocity and tried to compensate.
That made him wild. Then his patience and changeup took over. He
retired 11 batters in a row, striking out five of them.
</P>
<P>
   Abbott was pulled when Toronto's Homer Bush ended his string
with one out in the seventh. Homer hit a homer over the
center-field fence, pulling the Blue Jays within 7-4. Normally
unflappable, Abbott was shown slapping the bench hard several times
with his glove by a TV camera, action that made him turn sheepish
later when told that it had been captured on tape.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, no, my kids are going to see that,'' he said. ``I wanted
to get through the seventh inning and help the bullpen out. That's
why I was upset.''
</P>
<P>
   Once over the initial frustration, Abbott was informed he had
surpassed a personal big-league best in strikeouts by two.
Satisfaction set in.
</P>
<P>
   Teammates have come to expect just about anything from him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He knows what he has to do,'' said Griffey, supporting his
pitcher with his 99th and 100th RBIs. ``He's been around. He's
overcome arm and knee surgery. He knows what it takes to be in a
battle.''
</P>
<P>
   Said left fielder Brian Hunter, ``I think he's here for good and
making a name for himself at an important time for this team.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners had to use four relievers to finish the job, which
is never easy with this club. Jeff Fassero ended the seventh, using
one pitch to draw a double-play grounder with two on. An inning
later in a similar situation, Jose Paniagua needed just two pitches
for another double-play ball.
</P>
<P>
   Jose Mesa, pitching for the fourth consecutive day and facing
four batters, closed out the ninth for his 27th save in 30 tries,
six off the club record.
</P>
<P>
   Customs agents will want to know what Abbott was doing in
Canada. Considering his wayward background, he might need to show
documentation.
</P>
<P>
   The box score should work.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
