<HEADLINE>
SEATTLE SHOULD SING PRAISES OF HAWKS' SINCLAIR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHENEY _ Given what happened with Randy Johnson and Shawn Kemp,
what happened with Michael Sinclair should have been a bigger deal.
</P>
<P>
   But what's happening with his teammate, Joey Stay-away, is the
latest local hoo-hah over money in pro sports. So the good news
rarely makes the front page.
</P>
<P>
   Against all conventional wisdom and advice of friends, Sinclair,
30, recently signed a seven-year contract extension worth $35
million, including a $6 million signing bonus, to finish his career
with the Seahawks.
</P>
<P>
   Granted, nothing but the bonq! is guaranteed. But the NFL sack
leader last season, and for the past three seasons combined, had
enough career achievements that at any recent time he could have
complained of insult, lamented about the team direction, demanded a
trade to a bigger media market, and generally held the franchise
hostage.
</P>
<P>
   You know. What Johnson did. What Kemp did.
</P>
<P>
   It's what many star athletes do, which is why some of them said
what they said to Sinclair, a sixth-round pick out of Division II
Eastern New Mexico _ who, it could be argued, is the best
dollar-for-dollar defensive investment in Seahawks history, ahead
of high first-round picks Kenny Easley, Jacob Green and Cortez
Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Guys told me I was crazy for staying in Seattle, a team that
wasn't going anywhere,'' he said after practice this week. ``They
said you need to be in a large television market because nobody
knows about you.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I wasn't interested. That doesn't make me a better
player because people know about me.''
</P>
<P>
   Nor was the Texas native interested in uprooting his family,
leaving his adopted hometown or quitting on his often-lamentable
franchise.
</P>
<P>
   Then he really pinned the needle the wrong way on the Pro
Athlete Indulgence Meter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Me and my w`vd (Betty) 7e{e talking to each other and saying,
`How much money do you need to be happy? Is $2 million better than
$1 million? You sB
</P>
