<SLUG> BC-BKN-SONICS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOSTER READY TO RUN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JIM MOORE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ After enduring the past two seasons with a couple of
rim-rattling, air-balling centers, the Sonics decided Tuesday to
hire one who could fill the lane as well as the hoop.
</P>
<P>
   Shaquille O'Neal might not be trembling with the news that the
Sonics signed Greg Foster to a three-year contract, but the free
agent from Utah should provide more firepower than his
predecessors, Jim McIlvaine and Olden Polynice.
</P>
<P>
   ``He brings us experience, versatility and depth,'' said coach
Paul Westphal. ``He's gone against the best guys in the West and
his team has come out all right. We're comfortable with him as
another piece up front.''
</P>
<P>
   Added team president Wally Walker: ``He's a skilled big guy. Our
emphasis is with the big men shooting the ball. ... He's a perfect
fit for the way we hope to play.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics want to run this season. Foster is eager to get in
the starting blocks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm excited about getting up and down the floor,'' he said.
``At Utah, we were half-court oriented. We'll be playing an
exciting brand of basketball.''
</P>
<P>
   The 6-foot-11, 250-pound Foster arrives with career averages of
4.3 points and 2.8 rebounds. Seattle is his seventh stop in nine
years.
</P>
<P>
   Foster, a teammate of Gary Payton's at Skyline High in Oakland,
will start or back up Horace Grant, whose more natural position is
power forward. But Grant is known for his low-post defense on
larger opponents.
</P>
<P>
   Foster's addition is the final one of note for the Sonics. The
team is out of cap room and will bolster its training camp roster
with lesser-known players signing minimum contracts.
</P>
<P>
   The only major move remaining is the signing of free agent Vin
Baker in a deal that could be announced later this week. Last
season an overweight Baker floundered. Westphal anticipates that
Baker will find his All-Star form from two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll be shockingly disappointed if I don't see that,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Sonics dumped 10 players who were on last year's
roster and added six new ones, Walker believes they will be able to
contend with Pacific Division champion Portland.
</P>
<P>
   ``Absolutely,'' he said. ``It's going to be a very competitive
team. It's a playoff team.''
</P>
<P>
   Westphal realizes the enormity of the challenge but thinks the
Sonics, who were 25-25 last year, have made enough offseason
acquisitions to factor into the playoff race.
</P>
<P>
   ``This team got old,'' he said. ``People have to come to grips
with that. We're trying to reshuffle and get younger and still
compete at a high level. We'll go to war and see how good we are.''
</P>
<P>
   When the Sonics enter training camp Oct. 4, their biggest hole
will be at small forward, where Detlef Schrempf manned the position
for the past six seasons until defecting to Portland earlier this
month.
</P>
<P>
   Second-year players Vladimir Stepania, Rashard Lewis and Ruben
Patterson will lodge a battle for the majority of playing time.
Westphal said Brent Barry, Vernon Maxwell and Grant could play
small forward, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have any one dominant guy,'' Westphal said. ``At the
same time, we can match up a lot of different ways.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
