<HEADLINE>
JAIL'S BAN ON SEX MAGAZINES UPHELD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY KAMMER AND JIM WALSH  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a rare move, a federal appeals court reversed another
appellate ruling Tuesday, upholding a ban on ``Playboy'' and other
sexually explicit materials at Maricopa County jails.
</P>
<P>
   The 7-4 vote by the 9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals said the
regulation, imposed in 1993 by Sheriff Joe Arpaio, reasonably
ensures jail safety without violating inmates' First Amendment
rights.
</P>
<P>
   A three-judge appellate panel ruled last year that the ban was
unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   Arpaio, who received complaints from female guards that ``girlie
magazines'' were used to harass them, hailed the ruling.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it sets a standard,'' he said. ``I always said I'd go
to jail before I'd give back those ``Playboys.''''
</P>
<P>
   Attorney Nicholas Hentoff, who argued in court against the ban,
called the decision ``extremely bad case law that is going to have
a devastating impact throughout the 9th Circuit,'' which covers
nine Western states.
</P>
<P>
   ``No court has ever upheld a policy that infringes upon inmates'
rights as severely as this does,'' said Hentoff, who may ask the
U.S. Supreme Court to review Tuesday's ruling.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, a three-judge panel of the 9th Circuit said the
regulation, which bans photographs and drawings that show frontal
nudity, was too sweeping. The panel said the ban could be applied
to publications such as ``National Geographic'' or books containing
well-known works of art.
</P>
<P>
   But late last year, at the county's request, the full 9th
Circuit withdrew that decision without explanation, scheduling the
case for review by a special 11-judge panel.
</P>
<P>
   Such ``en banc'' reviews are rare and generally indicate a
concern to clarify a significant point of law.
</P>
<P>
   The initial decision in the case, issued in 1998 by U.S.
District Judge Robert Broomfield, also upheld the ban. Broomfield
said there was a ``logical connection'' between banning sexually
explicit materials and preventing problems in jail.
</P>
<P>
   Appellate Judge Thomas Nelson, author of Tuesday's ruling,
agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The relationship between the possession of sexually explicit
materials and the problems sought to be addressed by the policy _
sexual harassment of female officers, jail security and
rehabilitation of inmates is clear,'' he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   In a dissenting opinion, Judge Betty Fletcher noted that many
jail inmates are pretrial detainees, not yet convicted of any
crimes. She said the ban was ``an imposition . . . totally out of
proportion to the problem at hand.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The majority apparently concludes that the First Amendment
does not protect the right of, for example, a non-violent,
non-harassing pretrial detainee to pursue his general equivalency
diploma by reading a Western Civilization textbook containing a
chapter on the art of the Renaissance,'' Fletcher wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Inmates at the Madison Street Jail were outspoken Tuesday in
their disappointment over the court's ruling, arguing that sexually
explicit magazines reduce violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think that was fair. Looks don't create problems,''
said Darrin Casey, 35, who is awaiting trial an a charge of
aggravated assault on a police officer.
</P>
<P>
   Casey said inmates would only use the magazines for sexual
gratification.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that (a sexually explicit publication) stops a lot of
the violences in the jails. I think it helps more than it creates
problems,'' he said. ``A lot of these guys are sexually active.
These books keep the tension down and brings down the stress.''
</P>
<P>
   Othoniel Echavarria, 18, said allowing the magazines could
reduce the contraband problem at the jails.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would cause guards less trouble, searching through the
mail,'' said Echavarria, who is awaiting trial on a charge of armed
robbery.
</P>
<P>
   But he also considered how sexually explicit magazines could
have an undesirable effect.
</P>
<P>
   ``They'll get (sexually excited) or something and want to
sexually assault women,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Carlton White, 33, who is in jail for marijuana possession, said
he does not understand why the court would allow his First
Amendment rights to be violated by the ban.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's our constitutional right to look at magazines,'' White
said. ``It's a human body. There's nothing wrong with looking at a
human figure, and it relieves stress that could be put on other
inmates.''
</P>
<P>
   Judge Nelson wrote that the court should apply ``a deferential
standard of review'' to the regulation ``and uphold it if it is
reasonably related to legitimate penological interests.'' He said
harassment incidents were reduced sharply after imposition of the
ban.
</P>
<P>
   But in another dissenting opinion, Judge Andrew Kleinfeld said a
trial should be held to test, among other things, whether the ban
was intended to punish inmates. Kleinfeld noted that a press report
about Arpaio's defense of the ban quoted him as saying, ``Jail
means punishment.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Arizona has to convict these people before it is entitled to
punish and rehabilitate them,'' Kleinfeld wrote.
</P>
<P>
   In a reference to ``Alice in Wonderland,'' he wrote, ``We must
not follow the Red Queen's injunction, `Sentence first - verdict
afterward.' '' &QL; 
Jerry Kammer can be reached at &QL; 
jerry.kammer(at)pni.com or at (602) 444-8185. &QL; 
Jim Walsh can be reached at (602) 444-7984 or at
jim.walsh(at)pni.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
