<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-QUAKE-LOCAL-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RELATIVES HALF A WORLD AWAY RELIEVED TO HEAR FROM LOVED ONES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN IWASAKI  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Two minutes after a devastating earthquake shook
Turkey early Tuesday morning, the telephone jangled at Tuna
Ertemalp's office at Microsoft Corp. in Redmond, Wash. The frazzled
voice at the other end of the line was his mother, a half-world
away in Istanbul.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess a major earthquake happened here,'' she told Ertemalp,
a software development manager. ``I just want you to know it was
fine.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the line went dead a few minutes later as circuits
overloaded, Ertemalp felt relief, an emotion shared by several
other local residents who heard Tuesday from family and friends in
Turkey by phone or e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   But for Jamil Razzak, spokesman for Idriss Mosque in Seattle's
Northgate area, every passing moment is filled with uncertainty
about his sister and her family in Istanbul.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no idea how they are,'' he said softly. ``I can't get
through _ the telephone network is jammed. It's terrible. ... I
don't know what to say. I have to hope for the best.''
</P>
<P>
   John Gokcen, a Boeing engineer who leads a local Turkish
cultural group, is collecting relief items that he wants shipped in
a new Boeing 737 that's coincidentally scheduled for delivery
Thursday to Turkish Airlines.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you watch disasters on the other side of the world, you
(feel like you) can't do anything,'' said Gokcen, a Kirkland
resident and vice president of the Turkish American Cultural
Association, which has about 1,000 members. ``So it would be a
great help to get donations and send them to people.''
</P>
<P>
   No formal plans for the relief shipment have been approved at
the corporate level, but ``we're going to work with (Gokcen) to
make it possible,'' said Craig Martin, a Boeing spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Gokcen and his wife, Feral, have not strayed far from their
television, watching Turkish news coverage of the 7.8-magnitude
quake via satellite. The Anatolia news agency in Turkey sets the
death toll at 2,138 and the number of injured at 13,179.
</P>
<P>
   Although both of their families survived the quake in Istanbul,
``you don't know what will happen next,'' Feral Gokcen said. ``It's
so hard to hear about all those people who were hurt badly. A lot
of people are under the buildings. They cannot reach them.''
</P>
<P>
   Her husband said Turkish TV showed five-story buildings that
``collapsed like a playing-card tower,'' with hospitals seeking
help from residents with even a minor medical background.
</P>
<P>
   ``We went to school there. All our relatives are there _
parents, sisters, brothers, siblings, plus our classmates,'' John
Gokcen said. ``It's very tough.''
</P>
<P>
   Redmond research engineer Hakan Urey said that when he called
his brother in Istanbul, ``he was shaking very badly. He tried to
get out of bed three times and couldn't. A wardrobe was falling on
top of him. Once the quake stopped, he got up and spent the night
in the street, like everyone else.''
</P>
<P>
   At the University of Washington in Seattle, the Jackson School
of International Studies heard Tuesday via e-mail from Associate
Professor Resat Kasaba, who taught earlier this summer in an
exchange program at the University of Botacizi in Istanbul.
</P>
<P>
   ``We spent most of the night awake because of the earthquake,''
Kasaba wrote. ``All is well where I am, but large parts of
(Istanbul's) surrounding regions and several large cities in
western Turkey are damaged quite extensively.''
</P>
<P>
   After the initial call from his mother, Ertemalp, the Microsoft
manager, could not reach her again by phone for 12 hours. He sent
e-mail to friends in Turkey and was surprised that they were able
to respond so quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ``They said they were fine and happy that I checked on them,''
he said. ``They're scared and are listening to the radio and
watching TV.''
</P>
<P>
   Since much of Turkey rests on a fault line, minor earthquakes
with a magnitude of 4.0 _ the kind that sets Seattle news crews
scrambling _ cause hardly a stir. Even when a 5.6-magnitude quake
would strike, ``people just look at each other and say, `Oh, an
earthquake just hit,''' Ertemalp said.
</P>
<P>
   Turkey sits on ``an earthquake valve,'' said Istanbul native
Sevgi Baran, a computer support technician at Seattle Central
Community College. ``Shakes happen once in a while. But this is a
major one.''
</P>
<P>
   Baran tried 45 minutes Monday (Seattle time) before getting a
phone call through to relatives. All were safe except for an uncle
in the nearby town of Golguk, whom no one has been able to reach.
Two cousins searched for him Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Baran is a member of the Turkish American Cultural Association,
many of whom came to Washington to work at Boeing, Microsoft or in
the medical field, John Gokcen said.
</P>
<P>
   Feral Gokcen said she is moved by the relief efforts under way
from people worldwide, as well as by those in Turkey.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even the hurt people, we see from TV, are trying to help
others,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Editor's note: Those wishing to donate clothing, canned food or
blankets should contact the Gokcens at 425-739-6722 or Hakan Urey
at 206-794-2973.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
