<SLUG> BC-FBC-NEUHEISEL-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONTRACT FOR NEW HUSKY COACH A REAL TAIL-WAGGER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TED MILLER  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Seven months after he became the University of
Washington's head football coach, Rick Neuheisel signed a contract
that will make him the wealthiest coach in the Pac-10 and among the
highest paid in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   The five-year deal announced Tuesday could pay Neuheisel up to
$997,000 annually if he achieves academic and performance
incentives written into the contract, which includes a provision
for a two-year extension.
</P>
<P>
   The school also will pay off in three installments an $800,000
home loan Neuheisel secured when he was Colorado's head coach. This
pushes his annual compensation to $1.157 million over the next five
years.
</P>
<P>
   Athletic director Barbara Hedges rejected the notion that paying
a football coach such a hefty salary betrays the mission of an
educational institution, where the university president and top
professors earn far less.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a totally different arena,'' Hedges said. ``The
reality is that you have to be in the market place. This is a very
visible position. It has a lot of responsibility. We do generate a
substantial amount of money in our football program, which places a
certain amount of pressure on the coach. As a result, we
compensated the coach for that responsibility.''
</P>
<P>
   Neuheisel's salary at Colorado was $650,000. Florida coach Steve
Spurrier is the nation's highest-paid coach with a $2 million
annual package. Florida State coach Bobby Bowden, Tennessee's
Phillip Fulmer, Ohio State's John Cooper, Penn State's Joe Paterno,
Kansas State's Bill Snyder and Texas' Mack Brown also make $1
million or more per season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm excited that the university feels about me in such a way
to merit this kind of salary,'' Neuheisel said. ``I'll try to prove
over the next several years that I'm worth it.''
</P>
<P>
   The delay in finishing Neuheisel's deal developed because of a
new state ethics law that restricted how state employees may obtain
outside income. That forced money Neuheisel will receive from KOMO
($125,000) and Fox Sports Northwest ($100,000) to be paid through
the university.
</P>
<P>
   Neuheisel's only outside income will come from Nike ($60,000)
and a guaranteed $25,000 from ``other corporate opportunities.''
</P>
<P>
   Neuheisel's base salary will be $225,000.
</P>
<P>
   The contract contains two incentives: one based on the Huskies'
graduation rate and a lump payment of $40,000 if the team plays in
a bowl game.
</P>
<P>
   If the team graduation rate is 75 percent, he will receive
$60,000. If the rate is between 70-74 percent, he earns $40,000. He
gets $20,000 if the rate is 65-69 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The team's most recent graduation rate was 57 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Neuheisel is free to pursue personal endorsements as long as he
doesn't use the university's name or logo. He can make additional
income from summer football camps.
</P>
<P>
   If the university fires Neuheisel, it must buy out his contract.
Neuheisel will get $560,000 for the first year. If he has
additional years remaining on his contract, he will get $420,000
the second year and $280,000 the third year.
</P>
<P>
   The university is not responsible for these payments if it
terminates Neuheisel with cause, such as NCAA violations or a
serious act of misconduct.
</P>
<P>
   If Neuheisel leaves before his contract is over, he must pay the
university $100,000.
</P>
<P>
   Other contract details:
</P>
<P>
   --A $160,000 annual housing allowance.
</P>
<P>
   --Two courtesy cars and $2,000 a year for mileage.
</P>
<P>
   --The school will pay for Neuheisel's wife, Susan, to attend all
away football games, all postseason events and two additional
business-related trips. The Neuheisels also will get $25,000
annually for family travel expenses.
</P>
<P>
   --Membership at the Broadmoor Golf Club.
</P>
<P>
   Though the raise from his days at Colorado is significant,
Neuheisel insisted it wasn't the only reason he decided to leave
Boulder for Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Money was not the deciding issue,'' he said. ``Money gave me
cause to really investigate and learn as much as I could about the
University of Washington. When I looked into my own personal
crystal ball, I thought this was the place to be.''
</P>
</TEXT>
