<BODY>
<HEADLINE>
A'S HOMERS OVERPOWER RED SOX
</HEADLINE>
 BBA-ATHLETICS-REDSOX-BOS (For use by New York Times News Service clients) 
By GORDON EDES 
c.1999 The Boston Globe 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   So much for the Red Sox basking in the afterglow of Brian
Daubach, mythmaker.
</P>
<P>
   That notion was snuffed out like a sidewalk cigarette butt
Tuesday night, as the Sox were exposed to the double horror of Bret
Saberhagen breaking down and John Wasdin melting down in the course
of the same evening.
</P>
<P>
   With Saberhagen gone after just two innings and conceding that
he may be headed back to the disabled list for a third time, the
Oakland Athletics cruised to a 12-1 win over the Sox, who offered
Wasdin as a human sacrifice in the seventh inning, when the
visitors sent 12 men to the plate and scored eight times.
</P>
<P>
   The win pulled the pesky A's within a game of the Sox in the
wild-card race, as they put on the same show of power they used to
sweep three games in Toronto over the weekend while scoring 31
runs, or just over 10 a game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's gotten to the point, `Am I going to be helping myself or
hurting the team?' '' said Saberhagen after his shortest outing in
18 starts, which he left down, 4-0. ``Obviously, tonight was a
situation that didn't help the team.''
</P>
<P>
   Because the muscles in his shoulder are so weak, Saberhagen
said, they're not holding his rotator cuff in place and
inflammation has resulted. He has backed off his weightlifting
program, hoping he would feel less pain between starts, but that
has not been the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``There have been times he has come into the clubhouse and
wanted to cry, but he's a brave man,'' said Pedro Martinez, who
caused a brief stir after the game when he said he'd been alerted
he might pitch Wednesday night because Pat Rapp was attending to a
family matter, though club spokesman Kevin Shea later said Rapp
will take his turn.
</P>
<P>
   ``My choice is to miss a start, go on the DL, or change my
workout program and try not to miss any starts,'' Saberhagen said.
``I need to come in tomorrow and talk to a few people. No sense in
jumping in right now.''
</P>
<P>
   But the fact that he even would utter the words suggests that
Saberhagen likely is headed to the DL. If that happens, expect to
see Tim Wakefield back in the rotation. Jimy Williams tipped his
hand by sending his closer to the bullpen in the first inning
Tuesday night and bringing him in at the start of the third to
throw 85 pitches, though Williams insisted he did so only because
Wakefield was the freshest arm in the pen.
</P>
<P>
   With just 43 games left, this is no time for the Sox to be
losing Saberhagen. They're 13-5 in games he has started.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to be here one way or the other,'' he said.
``Whether I'm shutting it down, getting it right, or working
through it, I'm just one player of 25,'' he said. ``With or without
me, we're going to carry on and do well.
</P>
<P>
   ``To go down a player is not going to make or break this team.''
</P>
<P>
   The A's, who have homered in 18 straight games and 36 of their
last 37, went deep three times Tuesday night, as shortstop Miguel
Tejada and first baseman Scott Spiezio hit three-run blasts and
left fielder Ben Grieve hit a two-run shot. That was plenty for Gil
Heredia, the righthander who lost to the Sox, 7-2, on May Day but
now has won seven straight decisions after his 10-hit complete
game.
</P>
<P>
   The only Boston run came on Mike Stanley's 16th home run in the
fifth, when the Sox still had a chance to be in it, but John
Valentin grounded into a double play with the bases loaded.
</P>
<P>
   By the time this lost cause was over, Butch Huskey was the new
third baseman, Scott Hatteberg was catching, and Martinez's double,
Bryce Florie, was back to his customary role of mopping up somebody
else's mess.
</P>
<P>
   Saberhagen knew he was a beaten man early, as he went single,
single, home run, single to the first four batters in the second
inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't have anything,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Saberhagen gave up a bloop RBI single to Randy Velarde and hit
Grieve with a pitch before finally getting out of the inning, but
not before the A's had an early 4-0 lead for the second straight
game.
</P>
<P>
   Wakefield actually gave a good accounting of himself, holding
the A's to two singles over four scoreless innings. But that all
evaporated in the seventh, when Velarde hit a one-out single and
Grieve hit a 3-and-1 knuckler over the bullpen wall.
</P>
<P>
   When Wakefield walked John Jaha and Matt Stairs doubled,
Williams beckoned for Wasdin. Spiezio greeted him with a three-run
home run to make it 9-1, and there was no reason for Williams to
burn another pitcher in the inning.
</P>
<P>
   So Wasdin was left to absorb three more runs on three hits and a
walk, as the crowd of 31,246 left jeers with their beers as they
departed in droves.
</P>
<P>
   Florie, Saturday's substitute starter for a tardy Martinez,
worked the last two innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Heredia pitched a strong game for them,'' Williams said. ``And
of course, their bats speak for themselves.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
