<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIVERSITY-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRIVATE SEATTLE U. LAW SCHOOL FILLS THE GAP IN DIVERSITY AFTER
LAW'S PASSAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RUTH SCHUBERT  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ This summer, a classroom on the Seattle University
campus was the scene of something that no longer exists at the
University of Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Students studying criminal law created a strikingly diverse
portrait: 10 African Americans, 10 whites, six Asians, three
Hispanics and two Native Americans.
</P>
<P>
   All came into the SU Law School through an admissions program
that gives special consideration to minority applicants.
</P>
<P>
   When Washington voters approved Initiative 200 last November,
they banned the UW and other public universities from using
affirmative action to bring in minority students. Indirectly, that
vote also challenged private institutions, not bound by I-200, to
keep the door open to more minority students.
</P>
<P>
   But with relatively high tuitions, it's not certain private
institutions can do the job _ particularly in a field like law. In
attracting minority students, the SU Law School has to contend with
a tuition of $19,110 a year, compared with the UW's in-state
tuition of $6,009 and out-of-state cost of $14,802.
</P>
<P>
   SU has a $1.3 million scholarship fund for law students and
doles out awards of between $2,500 and $11,000 annually, said Carol
Cochran, SU's acting director of law admissions. But that's not
enough for most students _ even adding in federal loans of up to
$18,500 a year _ to cover tuition and living expenses.
</P>
<P>
   Cochran is also concerned that I-200 is having a chilling effect
on applications to Seattle University, particularly when
out-of-state students who may perceive the state as unfriendly to
affirmative action.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're doing a great job with what we have, but I would have
liked to have seen more applicants of color,'' Cochran said.
</P>
<P>
   This fall, SU and the UW will enroll about the same proportion
of minorities in their entering law classes: 23 percent for SU, 22
percent for UW.
</P>
<P>
   For the UW this represents a sizable drop. The percentage of
incoming minority students is at its lowest since 1989. SU, on the
other hand, is holding steady.
</P>
<P>
   To Roland Hjorth, dean of the UW Law School, the prospect of SU
becoming the more diverse school is the ultimate irony. Hjorth has
long maintained that a diverse student body adds not only to the
the classroom, but also to society's trust in the legal system.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's vital that everybody has faith in the legal system, and
it's difficult for people to have faith in the legal system if
they're not in it,'' Hjorth said.
</P>
<P>
   The UW leadership has said the school will look for ways to
maintain racial diversity within the bounds of the law. This year's
numbers, however, are not encouraging.
</P>
<P>
   SU, too, has long emphasized the need for lawyers from diverse
racial and economic backgrounds _ a philosophy in keeping with the
Jesuit ideals of service and justice that guide the school.
</P>
<P>
   The special admission program took effect in 1987. In its first
six years, it helped the law school recruit two-thirds of its
African American and Native American law students and half of the
Hispanic students.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've always seen that as part of what a law school ought to
be about and what a university ought to be about _ to meet the
needs of society,'' said David Boerner, an SU law professor who
teaches in the program.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond race, however, SU's program searches for those students
who are long on potential but short on academic preparation _
people from impoverished backgrounds or those who have been away
from college for years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those people could not get into the University of Washington
Law School,'' said the Rev. William Sullivan, SU's president for 20
years and current chancellor.
</P>
<P>
   Without SU's special program, they may not make it into law
school and, thus, into the legal profession at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``It isn't just a matter of get out and do anything you can to
get your percentages up,'' Sullivan added. ``It seems to me more of
a case of: here are some population groups who are not going to be
well-represented in the legal profession in the future unless some
special educational efforts are made to bring them in and support
them academically.''
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, law schools around the country have been a
focal point in the national debate over affirmative action.
</P>
<P>
   The first successful reverse discrimination case to hit the
courts this decade was filed by three white applicants to the
University of Texas School of Law, who said they were rejected
because of admissions practices that favored blacks and
Mexican-Americans. In a major victory for affirmative action foes,
the 5th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in 1996 ruled that UT's
admissions policies were unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   Similar cases are pending against the University of Washington
and University of Michigan law schools.
</P>
<P>
   To defend against those lawsuits, institutions are increasingly
searching out studies that demonstrate the value of diversity to
every law student's education and to bolster contentions that
standardized tests such as the LSAT are biased.
</P>
<P>
   One analysis that examined applicants to 173 law schools in
1990-91, showed that if decisions were made entirely based on
grade-point averages and test scores, only 687 of the 3,435 black
applicants who were accepted to law school would have made it in.
The analysis, by Professor Linda Wightman, appeared in the New York
University Law Review in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   More recently, researchers at Harvard commissioned Gallup to
survey 1,820 law students at Harvard and the University of Michigan
about how racial diversity affected their educational experience.
</P>
<P>
   About 70 percent of the students surveyed said the racial
diversity of their law school classes enhanced or moderately
enhanced how they and their peers thought about problems and
solutions in class. Nearly three-quarters said having students of a
different race in class was a ``clearly positive'' element of their
educational experience.
</P>
<P>
   SU's Alternative Admissions program admits about 10 percent of
every class based on factors beyond grades and test scores.
Students must attend a summer course that combines criminal law,
legal writing and study strategies. Extra academic support is
available through the first year from the school's Academic
Resource Center. The support is critical to helping these students
graduate and pass the bar exam.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't think we do anyone a favor just by letting them in
and letting them crash,'' Boerner said. ``It wouldn't make any
sense just to admit people if you don't make any attempt to make
sure they succeed. We want to produce lawyers, not just students.''
</P>
<P>
   The law school is very protective of the students admitted
through the alternative program, promising them anonymity as they
go into the highly competitive first year of law school.
Administrators fear that students would face a bias that they
aren't qualified or resentment from other students who don't get
the additional academic support.
</P>
<P>
   Blanca Rodriguez, a 1997 graduate who came in through the
alternative admissions program, said she was the first in her
Spanish-speaking family to go to college. She graduated from
Pacific Lutheran University with a decent grade point average and
so-so LSAT scores.
</P>
<P>
   Her application to SU explained that she wanted to take her
legal expertise back to the Yakima Valley, where her parents toiled
as farm workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to come back to this community, the farm worker
community, and I wanted to help this community gain access to the
things they are lacking _ working conditions, collective bargaining
contracts, things like that,'' said Rodriguez.
</P>
<P>
   Being Hispanic was far from the only factor that qualified her
application for special consideration _ a point that SU
administrators make strongly. Students come into the program for a
number of different reasons.
</P>
<P>
   Debra Wiley, a 1994 graduate, entered law school after a 12-year
hiatus from higher education.
</P>
<P>
   ``It promotes a richness and diversity that's defined in so many
other ways than the way me may traditionally think of diversity as
along the lines of race and gender,'' Wiley said of the program.
</P>
<P>
   SU doesn't have a recent analysis of how well students admitted
through the special program do, but a 1990 comparison of
alternative admissions students to the closest 10 percent of
regular students showed that their academic performances were
essentially the same, said Paul Lustbader, director of the Academic
Resource Center.
</P>
<P>
   Adolfo Ojeda, who graduated from SU's law school this spring,
was an undergraduate at the UW. While there, he was active in the
community of Hispanic students. He, for one, hopes that SU will
provide even greater opportunities for poor and minority students.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did respect the UW's efforts in recruiting minorities, and
I'm sure they'll do what they can, but they definitely have one
hand tied behind their back,'' Ojeda said. ``I hope in this area
Seattle U. can pick up the slack.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-18-99 0100EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990818.0016 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-18 01:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1067 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BBA-DAUBACH-BOS     08-18 0827
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE>
DAUBACH PROVIDES QUIET THUNDER FOR SOX
</HEADLINE>
 BBA-DAUBACH-BOS (For use by New York Times News Service clients) 
By SHIRA SPRINGER 
c.1999 The Boston Globe 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sometimes you must draw close to hear Brian Daubach clearly. The
Red Sox hero-of-the-moment has the unpretentious habit of talking
softly toward his shoes.
</P>
<P>
   Seated in the clubhouse Tuesday with his right foot propped
against his locker stall, the rookie quietly engaged reporters with
stories from his baseball past. Daubach does not shy away from
retelling the now-familiar tale. A Midwestern upbringing and nine
years in the minor leagues have made him too polite to turn down
interview requests.
</P>
<P>
   He candidly recounts his long conversion into a power hitter,
who at 27 leads American League rookies in extra-base hits,
doubles, and home runs and ranks near the top of the freshman class
in hits, RBIs, and multihit games. In his last 12 games, Daubach
has batted .460, with eight home runs, seven doubles, one triple,
and 24 RBIs. He mentions with all modesty that when he started as a
professional in 1990 with the New York Mets organization, he was
unable to hit or run well. And the rookie claims he still can't
run.
</P>
<P>
   But the reigning American League Player of the Week stops short
of saying he enjoys all the attention recently heaped upon him. His
three-run, game-winning double Monday against Oakland and his
heroics against Seattle over the weekend changed the rookie's world
without giving him much time to take measure of his growing
popularity or celebrate.
</P>
<P>
   When asked whether people on the streets recognize him, Daubach
said, ``I think a little bit more, especially when I'm leaving the
ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   ``Again, I don't really care about any of that. I just enjoy
being here a lot. I like the fans here. They've been great to me.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's new. In the minor leagues, there's not that much
coverage. Here, especially us being in a wild-card race, it's a new
experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just go along and enjoy it. Actually, during the games I
don't notice it that much. It's easier to relax during the games.
It's a bit overwhelming, for sure. I've come a long way and the
fans here love the players so much. They're behind us so much. It's
definitely an experience that I'll never forget.''
</P>
<P>
   Being new to the hero role, Daubach did not hold a special
celebration Monday night. He did not call home to Belleville, Ill.,
and relive his latest highlight with his parents, who watch most of
his games on satellite television. And he had no trouble falling
asleep or reporting for designated hitter duties Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I stayed the same,'' said Daubach. ``Nothing was different.''
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, the rookie assessed his new situation correctly.
The Fenway autograph-seekers still clamor for Nomar Garciaparra.
Parents have to point out the man shagging ground balls and list
his recent accomplishments before a glimmer of recognition crosses
their children's faces.
</P>
<P>
   During Tuesday night's game, however, Daubach was greeted with a
standing ovation before his first two plate appearances. The same
fan enthusiasm accompanied his six-minute at-bat Monday night. For
many recently converted Daubach admirers, the attraction lies in
his low salary ($230,000), his long road to the major leagues, and
the element of surprise he has provided.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm trying to keep myself in my seat and stop myself from
going over there to get an autograph,'' said Karen Hart of West
Boylston, who made her first trip to Fenway Tuesday night in large
part to see Daubach. ``I saw an interview with Brian on one of the
local channels when he first came up. He was so humble and shy. I
was just taken with him right away because he did his time in the
minors.''
</P>
<P>
   Recent feats by the rookie had even general manager Dan Duquette
sounding downright giddy. He likened Daubach's Monday night hit _
on a full count, in the ninth, with two outs, the bases loaded, _
to the stuff of Little League dreams, the ultimate childhood
fantasy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Very rarely do you see a ballplayer compose himself the way
Daubach did after he hit a ball (foul) out of the park,'' said
Duquette. ``He composed himself and went the other way.''
</P>
<P>
   The GM sees little reason to send the AL Rookie of the Year
candidate back to winter ball. A break from the game will be a
change for Daubach, who has spent past offseasons selling shoes and
playing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what he'd have to work on,'' said Duquette.
</P>
<P>
   That compliment comes a year after Boston considered picking up
Daubach from Florida. Originally, the Red Sox thought they could
sell the lefthanded hitter to a Japanese team. Instead, the Marlins
released the career minor leaguer in the fall with an early-morning
phone call. The news woke up Daubach. As he remembers, he fell back
asleep, only to have the reality of his situation set in later.
</P>
<P>
   Daubach can insist that nothing is different after the last
week, but no doubt his dreams are sweeter.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
