<HEADLINE>
BAN URGED ON CUTTING OLD PINES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE YOZWIAK  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Arizona and New Mexico environmentalists are urging a halt to
the cutting of large, old ponderosa pines north of the Grand
Canyon.
</P>
<P>
   And they are calling for the firing of John Bedell, supervisor
of eastern Arizona's Apache-Sitgreaves National Forest, alleging
failure to protect wildlife and coziness with the timber industry.
</P>
<P>
   These efforts follow one environmentalist group's victory
already this summer.
</P>
<P>
   Santa Fe-based Forest Guardians challenged a plan to cut up to
90 percent of the trees surrounding Flagstaff in order to stop
fires, starting with an experimental grove below the San Francisco
Peaks.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Forest Service in Albuquerque upheld the group's
appeal, ruling Aug. 3 that Coconino National Forest officials
failed to consider the project's impact on potential archaeological
sites and places considered sacred by Arizona tribes.
</P>
<P>
   The regional office also ruled that the project _ planned over
10 years to cover up to 100,000 acres _ may produce results
requiring more extensive review and hearings. It ordered Coconino
officials to further investigate the proposal.
</P>
<P>
   The Flagstaff victory was followed Friday by an appeal by a
consortium of Southwest environmental groups to block a proposed
timber sale on the Kaibab National Forest, north of the Grand
Canyon.
</P>
<P>
   The appeal said the estimated 1,800 truckloads of logs that
would be cut across 6,000 acres in the proposed Dry Park timber
sale would decimate some of Arizona's last good stands of
old-growth ponderosa pines.
</P>
<P>
   ``The North Kaibab Ranger District is an ecological treasure as
well as the gateway to the Grand Canyon National Park,'' said Brian
Segee, forest defense coordinator for the Center for Biological
Diversity, which filed the appeal with the Sierra Club and the
Southwest Forest Alliance.
</P>
<P>
   ``People visit the area to see one of the natural wonders of the
world, not a bunch of stumps,'' Segee said.
</P>
<P>
   He called the proposal ``nothing more than a desperate attempt
to keep a dying timber industry alive.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials of the Kaibab National Forest could not be reached for
comment. Pat Jackson, appeals review officer for the Southwest
office of the U.S. Forest Service, said he could not comment on a
pending appeal.
</P>
<P>
   However, the Forest Service policy in Arizona and New Mexico is
to keep at least 20 percent of the forests in an old-growth
condition, meaning there is a variety of age, size and condition of
trees. Biologists and environmentalists contend that old-growth
forests provide the best habitat for wildlife, especially for many
species in danger of extinction.
</P>
<P>
   Marlin Johnson, the Forest Service regional director of forest
health, said the forests north of the Grand Canyon have enough
old-growth trees to allow some to be harvested by the timber
industry. Thinning some of the older trees, he said, could enable
other trees to get bigger.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, Johnson said, ``some of our sites would never become
old growth.''
</P>
<P>
   Martos Hoffman, executive director of the Southwest Forest
Alliance, said that with nearly 95 percent of Arizona's original
old-growth forests already cut, now is the time for a moratorium on
cutting all large trees.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's time for the Forest Service to realize that the logging
of big, old-growth trees is not compatible with saving our forest
eco-systems,'' said Hoffman, whose group represents 70,000
environmentalists in Arizona and New Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Hoffman said the move is toward saving all trees 16 inches in
diameter and bigger, and to log only the smaller, fire-prone trees.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a Washington, D.C., group of environmentalists who
work for the Forest Service and other federal agencies is calling
for the firing of John Bedell, who since 1990 has been supervisor
of the Apache-Sitgreaves National Forest.
</P>
<P>
   Public Employees for Environmental Responsibility, in a letter
dated Aug. 5 to Forest Service Chief Michael Dombeck, claimed
Bedell has:
</P>
<P>
   Consistently made decisions ``with an emphasis on commodity
production over balanced and scientifically based resource
management.''
</P>
<P>
   Created a hostile work environment for Forest Service employees
and hostility toward members of the environmental movement.
</P>
<P>
   Fostered a hostile political climate in commodity-dependent
small towns, including a radio program in which Bedell blamed
recent drops in timber production on efforts to save Mexican
spotted owls, which since 1993 have been threatened with
extinction. Environmentalists contend that the drop was caused by
overcutting the forests in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Dyson, spokesman for the Apache-Sitgreaves National Forest,
said that Bedell was sent a copy of the firing demand, but that no
action has been taken and that neither he nor Bedell would comment.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be inappropriate for us to respond to that. It's not
addressed to us,'' Dyson said.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Zabinski, spokeswoman for the regional office of the Forest
Service in Albuquerque, said her office had not seen the letter and
could not comment. &QL; 
Steve Yozwiak can be reached at (602) 444-8810 or at
steve.yozwiak(at)pni.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
