<SLUG> BC-EDBRD-EVOLUTION-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAWMAKERS CONSIDER MOVE TO ELIMINATE KANSAS BOARD OF EDUCATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN L. PETTERSON and JOHN A. DVORAK  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOPEKA _ When state Sen. Rich Becker of Lenexa was vacationing
in London last week, he picked up a copy of the Evening Standard
and was shocked at what jumped out at him.
</P>
<P>
   In the London newspaper was a story about the Kansas Board of
Education voting to leave evolution out of the state standards for
teaching science in public schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``I showed it to a couple of people and they said, `Boy, Kansas
really is the laughingstock of the world now,' &UR; '' Becker said.
</P>
<P>
   The 6-4 vote touched off renewed interest among some lawmakers
in eliminating the elected 10-member board, making it appointive or
stripping it of its power to act without legislative direction.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has been a strong breach of good sense,'' Rep. Ralph
Tanner, a Baldwin City Republican who heads the House Education
Committee, said of the board's action.
</P>
<P>
   Tanner, Rep. Tom Sloan of Lawrence and Sen. Barbara Lawrence of
Wichita, who heads the Senate Education Committee, are scheduled to
meet this afternoon with Gov. Bill Graves. The state board's future
is on the agenda.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this issue will galvanize a number of people to do
something,'' said Tanner, who requested the meeting with the
governor.
</P>
<P>
   Those on both sides of the issue freely acknowledge that it will
not be easy to make a change.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly, it's going to be one of the biggest issues we face
in the year 2000,'' said Rep. Susan Wagle, a Wichita Republican who
does not like the idea of eliminating the elected board.
</P>
<P>
   Any revision would require a constitutional amendment. Before an
amendment could be placed on the ballot, two-thirds of the House
and Senate members would have to agree, and such majorities are
hard to obtain.
</P>
<P>
   Linda Holloway of Shawnee, who heads the state education board,
doesn't expect any move toward abolishing the board or
restructuring it to be successful.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess I'd be surprised if there is a big change,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas voters, she said, do not like the idea of losing their
opportunity to vote for a state board member. In 1990 they rejected
a constitutional proposal to allow the Legislature to decide how
the board would be selected.
</P>
<P>
   Holloway, who voted with the majority on the science standards,
said: ``Here are elected officials going to the public and saying,
`You don't have enough sense to vote for an elected board of
education, but vote for me.' That's kind of a schizophrenic
message.''
</P>
<P>
   House Minority Leader Jim Garner, a Coffeyville Democrat, also
said he was reluctant to eliminate an elected board.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the solution is electing better people to the state
Board of Education. Maybe this incident will heighten interest and
increase the awareness of the importance of this office,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   There is support among leaders in the Senate and House for
moving away from the elected board.
</P>
<P>
   Senate President Dick Bond, an Overland Park Republican, is
among those who would like to make the board appointive.
</P>
<P>
   By sparking undesirable publicity, members of the education
board increased chances the Legislature would try to abolish their
group, Bond said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We should send the state board a `thank you,''' he said.
``Sometimes it takes some pain to get a cure.''
</P>
<P>
   House Speaker Robin Jennison, a Healy Republican, would like to
abolish the board or make it appointive. In any event, he believes
the governor should appoint the state's education commissioner.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people go to the ballot box and vote for their board
member having no idea what their board member wants to do with
education,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   One of the arguments sure to be forwarded by those who want to
change the board is what they consider a blemish on the state's
image caused by the evolution vs. creation debate.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you are promoting your state for new business, or for
tourism, when you're working at the national level to bring
opportunities into the state, this kind of publicity is damaging,''
said Lt. Gov. Gary Sherrer, who heads the state's economic
development efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Companies study a variety of factors when they make decisions
about locating in Kansas. Sherrer and his aides work constantly to
portray Kansas as a good place to live and work.
</P>
<P>
   As lawmakers and others begin to campaign for change, the
governor is stepping back.
</P>
<P>
   ``My preference is we elect professionals to the state Board of
Education who in turn rely on the advice and opinion of Kansas
education professionals and make and set public policy,'' Graves
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
