<HEADLINE>
RANGERS BURY INDIANS UNDER 19-HIT ATTACK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND _ The Rangers looked sluggish against the Chicago
White Sox last week and positively comatose against the Toronto
Blue Jays on the last homestand.
</P>
<P>
   So what happens when they face the All-Star-laden Cleveland
Indians before nightly sellout crowds at Jacobs Field?
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers transform themselves into the 1927 Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   Go figure.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers flogged Indians pitching for the second consecutive
night with 19 hits, including home runs from Juan Gonzalez, Rafael
Palmeiro and Luis Alicea, and muscled their way to a 15-4 victory.
The Rangers remain 5 1/2 games ahead of Oakland in the American
League West and closed to within two games behind the Indians in
the home-field advantage competition.
</P>
<P>
   For a team that tediously espouses the one-at-a-time adage, the
Rangers seem to be playing with a little more fire against the
Indians than the Blue Jays or White Sox.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the team gets a little more fired up here,'' third
baseman Todd Zeile said. ``You hear so much about Cleveland,
especially the fact they're an offensive team and have a reputation
for being such good sluggers. That's one of the reasons we match up
so well with them, when it comes to slugging, we can hang in there
with anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   The beating started early with six runs in the first inning off
Indians starter Mark Langston and six more in the next two innings
off reliever Tom Martin.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of the third, the Rangers were up 12-1, starter Aaron
Sele was well on his way to his 13th victory and some of those same
Indians fans who perhaps stuffed the All-Star ballot box earlier in
the season were now lustily booing their heroes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we were a little motivated coming in here,'' shortstop
Royce Clayton said. ``Anytime you come up against the caliber of
team they have over there, you have to raise your game. We did.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers have scored 28 runs on 35 hits in two nights against
the Indians. Combine the final four innings of Monday's game and
the first three innings yesterday and the Rangers scored 23 runs on
24 hits in a seven-inning stretch.
</P>
<P>
   Throw in their 10-0 victory over the White Sox on Sunday, their
only victory in Chicago, and the Rangers have scored 38 runs on 51
hits in three games.
</P>
<P>
   They've been doing it with some serious muscle, hitting 12 home
runs in three games. The Rangers have also hit 50 home runs in
their last 26 games after hitting just two in their first seven
games after the All-Star break.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, the Rangers are clobbering the ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to explain because this team is better than the
White Sox,'' Palmeiro said. ``You just have to play hard every day.
Sometimes you win big, sometimes you run into something like
Chicago, where things don't go right.''
</P>
<P>
   The most important hitting was done in the first inning against
Langston. The Rangers loaded the bases with one out on singles by
Rodriguez and Rusty Greer and a walk to Gonzalez. Langston then
struck out Palmeiro, giving the lefty a chance to get out the
inning.
</P>
<P>
   But Zeile, revived after a case of food poisoning, came through
with a two-run double to left-center, his 11th hit in 18 at-bats
with the bases loaded this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Todd Zeile had the big at-bat of the night,'' Rangers manager
Johnny Oates said. ``Bases loaded and he \RLangston\S struck out
Raffy; he's got a chance to get out of the inning without giving up
any runs. But Todd's hit got us going, and we were able to add
on.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers followed that with a run-scoring infield hit by
Roberto Kelly and a two-run double by Clayton. When Langston,
thoroughly frustrated, totally misplayed Tom Goodwin's infield
roller and allowed Clayton to race home from second, the Rangers
were leading 6-0.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
