<SLUG> BC-GUNSHOW-SALES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUPERVISORS WANT TO BAN GUN SHOWS ON COUNTRY PROPERTY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DOUGLAS HABERMAN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- One week after the shooting rampage in the San
Fernando Valley, two county supervisors said that they want to ban
gun shows at the county fairgrounds and other Los Angeles
County-owned locations.
</P>
<P>
   A third member of the five-person Board of Supervisors said he's
willing to consider the ban on gun shows at the Fairplex in Pomona
east of Los Angeles, while a fourth was out of town but considered
likely to support a ban.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gun violence, especially gun violence perpetrated with illegal
automatic and semiautomatic weapons, has torn at the heart of this
county,'' said Supervisor Zev Yaroslavsky, who called for the ban.
</P>
<P>
   Gun shows like the one in Pomona, he said Tuesday, are ``the
great commons of America when it comes to the distribution of
illegal weapons. Everybody knows it.''
</P>
<P>
   But the operations manager of the Pomona gun shows, Chad Seger
of Great Western Shows, said security has been tightened in the
past few months to prevent illegal sales.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we even suspect someone of criminal activity, we'll kick
them out,'' Seger said. Buyers face a 10-day waiting period, so
they cannot walk out of the shows with guns, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Buford O'Neal Furrow Jr., a white supremacist who FBI officers
said admitted killing letter carrier Joseph Santos Ileto in
Chatsworth and wounding five people at the North Valley Jewish
Community Center in Granada Hills on Aug. 10, evidently bought one
or more firearms at gun shows, Yaroslavsky said, speaking at a news
conference.
</P>
<P>
   Yaroslavsky also said the federal Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and
Firearms found that the gunmen in a ferocious 1997 shootout at the
Bank of America in North Hollywood obtained weapons from vendors
they met at gun shows, including the Pomona show.
</P>
<P>
   Supervisor Yvonne Brathwaite Burke said she supports a ban.
Supervisor Don Knabe made no commitment but said he is ready to
consider a ban.
</P>
<P>
   Supervisor Michael D. Antonovich wants to see the language of
the proposed ordinance but opposes a ban on constitutional grounds,
said spokesman Cam Currier.
</P>
<P>
   Supervisor Gloria Molina was on vacation Tuesday, but sources
close to her said she is likely to support Yaroslavsky's motion.
</P>
<P>
   Yaroslavsky formally asked on Tuesday for a report from the
county's in-house lawyers to be made at the Board of Supervisors
meeting next week on the options available to the county, including
an ordinance banning sales or possession of firearms and ammunition
on county property. The ban would exclude those who carry weapons
in the line of duty, such as law enforcement officers.
</P>
<P>
   Great Western Shows pays rent to hold four gun shows a year at
the county-owned Fairplex.
</P>
<P>
   Sheriff Lee Baca favors a ban on gun shows at the Fairplex,
Deputy Steve Sciacca said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Fair Association, which leases the Fairplex from the county,
says a ban would take away almost one-third of its yearly revenues.
Gun shows generated $600,000 for it last year.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
