r s BC-BBA-RANGERS-RODRIGUEZ     08-18 0491
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-RODRIGUEZ-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS MANAGER THROWS SUPPORT TO RODRIGUEZ FOR MVP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND _ Rangers manager Johnny Oates made his endorsement
official yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   Oates said catcher Ivan Rodriguez should win the American
League's Most Valuable Player Award.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, with all due respect to the other guys, I've seen him
every day and I know how valuable he is,'' Oates said. ``I can be
prejudiced, but it would be tough for me to vote for any other
guy.''
</P>
<P>
   There is nothing surprising about a manager endorsing his own
player. Oates actively campaigned for Juan Gonzalez in 1996 when he
believed his right-fielder wasn't getting enough attention.
</P>
<P>
   But Gonzalez was the Rangers' only MVP candidate that season.
They have two this year: Rodriguez and designated hitter/first
baseman Rafael Palmeiro.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Raffy's numbers are deserving,'' Oates said. ``But you
look at Pudge's offense, what he's done for our ballclub, the way
he shuts down other teams' running game, playing every day, the
possibility he could have 100 runs scored and 100 RBI, I think
Pudge is deserving of being most valuable player.''
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez entered yesterday's game hitting .331 with 85 runs
scored, 28 home runs and 85 runs batted in. He had also thrown out
55.5 percent (30-of-54) of base runners attempting to steal, the
highest percentage in the majors, and he had picked off seven
runners.
</P>
<P>
   ``The MVP would be nice,'' Rodriguez said. ``It would be great,
but I'm trying not to think about that. I just need to keep doing
what I'm doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Palmeiro entered yesterday's game hitting .335 with 31 homers
and 103 RBI. But knee surgeries in February and March have limited
him to designated-hitter duty for much of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Oates admitted it would be tough for a DH to win the award.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm glad we have both of them on the ballclub,'' Oates said.
``But with everything else being equal, the two most demanding
positions are catcher and shortstop. For someone who has been
basically a DH, he would have to have overwhelming numbers.''
</P>
<P>
   The last catcher to win the American League MVP was Thurman
Munson of the New York Yankees in 1976. Don Baylor of California
won the award in 1979 while playing 65 games at designated hitter
and 97 in the outfield. That's the most games at DH by an MVP
winner. Palmeiro has started 98 games at DH.
</P>
<P>
   Other top MVP candidates include Boston Red Sox shortstop Nomar
Garciaparra and Yankees shortstop Derek Jeter, who are 1-2 in the
American League in hitting; Mariners outfielder Ken Griffey Jr.,
who leads the league in home runs; and Cleveland Indians outfielder
Manny Ramirez, who is way ahead in RBI.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, offense gets more recognition,'' Oates said.
``But Pudge could score 100 runs and drive in 110 and save another
30 runs with his defense. You've got to add that in.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
