<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-18 01:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1075 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BBN-ASTROS-BREWERS-HN     08-18 0817
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-BREWERS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOSEPH DUARTE  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
Ken Caminiti wants to take things one step at a time. But he's
clearly making strides.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Caminiti hit a go-ahead two-run single in his second game since
coming off the disabled list Tuesday night as the Astros held on
for an 8-6 victory over the Milwaukee Brewers before a crowd of
20,558 at the Astrodome.
</P>
<P>
   ``Definitely baby steps right now,'' said Caminiti, who had
returned to the lineup Monday for the first time since May 21. ``I
got a little better timing, but I'm still trying to see like a
hitter, think like a hitter. I'm just going up there hacking. You
always wish you could do more than what you did, but I'll take what
I did. It could have been a lot worse.''
</P>
<P>
   With their second straight win over the Brewers, the Astros kept
pace with the Cincinnati Reds in the National League Central. The
Reds, who remain percentage points ahead of the Astros, beat the
Pittsburgh Pirates 7-4 in 12 innings.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros have won six of eight meetings with the Brewers this
season. Scott Elarton (7-3), pitching on 10 days' rest Tuesday,
allowed four runs and eight hits and struck out seven in six
innings. The righthander also added his first major-league RBI in
the second inning.
</P>
<P>
   Craig Biggio hit a two-run homer in the eighth that proved to be
the difference as the Brewers rallied for two runs in the ninth
inning.
</P>
<P>
   When Jay Powell couldn't nail things down in the ninth for the
Astros, Billy Wagner entered with runners at second and third and
two out and struck out pinch hitter Alex Ochoa for his 29th save in
31 chances this season.
</P>
<P>
   In the first two games of this series, Wagner has a pair of
saves. He has struck out all four batters he has faced, needing
only 14 pitches to do it.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Wagner is on, he's unhittable,'' Milwaukee manager Jim
Lefebvre said. ``I think they have the best staff in the National
League. Atlanta's got great starters, but their bullpen is
susceptible.''
</P>
<P>
   Caminiti, 0-for-3 Monday in his return from a strained right
calf, sparked a three-run third inning with a bases-loaded single
to center off Cal Eldred (1-6) that gave the Astros a 4-3 lead.
Lance Berkman added a sacrifice fly in the inning.
</P>
<P>
   Caminiti, who said his timing isn't where he wants it, played
nine innings for the second straight game. He will not be in the
starting lineup tonight.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like the second and third weeks (of spring training). My
body is pretty achy,'' said Caminiti, who has played in only 38 of
the Astros' 121 games this season. ``I'm just trying to go out and
do the best I can and not try and hit the ball out of the park. The
pressure is not on me to win every game by myself. That's not my
job.''
</P>
<P>
   Much like Caminiti, Elarton was pleased to be back on the field.
Days off in the schedule and lingering stiffness in his right
shoulder had kept Elarton out of the rotation since Aug. 7. The
rustiness showed early as he allowed four hits, three runs and a
walk through two innings. Two of the runs came on a double to the
center-field wall by Eldred.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a little bit tentative,'' Elarton said. ``I never let it
go in the bullpen (during pre-game warm-ups), and I paid for it
early. I don't know if I was scared or what. I got back into a
rhythm and started letting it go.''
</P>
<P>
   Elarton, who is 2-1 since moving into the starting rotation July
3, helped his cause with a run-scoring single down the right-field
line in the second, the third hit of his career and his first RBI
in 17 career at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got lucky,'' Elarton said.
</P>
<P>
   Milwaukee broke a 21-inning scoreless drought in the first
inning when Mark Loretta's double-play grounder scored Ron Belliard
from third. Jeff Bagwell, who had his second straight two-hit game,
tied the score at 1 with a ground-rule double to right-center field
in the bottom of the first.
</P>
<P>
   Eldred, who allowed five runs, five hits and five walks in five
innings, hit his two-run double in the second as the Brewers
regained the lead 3-1.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros bounced back with three runs in the third, two coming
off the bat of Caminiti.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, that's the biggest hit of the game,'' Biggio said.
``That gave us a little confidence and momentum.''
</P>
<P>
   In the fifth, Milwaukee got singles from Belliard, Rich Becker
and Dave Nilsson, the last driving in a run that sliced the Astros'
lead to 5-4. The Brewers threatened in the seventh inning with a
runner at first base, but Carl Everett caught a fly ball to right
and doubled up Brian Banks heading back to first.
</P>
<P>
   Everett hit a sacrifice fly off Dave Weathers in the sixth, and
Biggio hit a two-run homer to left-center field in the eighth off
Rocky Coppinger to make the score 8-4.
</P>
<P>
   Milwaukee pulled within 8-6 in the ninth on a two-run single by
Belliard, who was 3-for-5, off Powell.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
