<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-18 01:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1077 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a BC-BIGONE-PREDICTED-LADN     08-18 0976
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIGONE-PREDICTED-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BY MICHAEL COIT 
</HEADLINE>
 
FAULT IN TURKEY SIMILAR TO L.A.'s 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- The Big One _ an earthquake on the magnitude that
caused the catastrophe in Turkey _ would cause massive damage in
the Los Angeles area, but tougher building codes here could keep
the death toll lower, seismologists said.
</P>
<P>
   There are notable similarities between the North Anatolian Fault
in Turkey and the San Andreas Fault in California.
</P>
<P>
   Both are strike slip faults nearly 1,000 miles long, storing
tremendous energy generated at the confluence of tectonic plates.
Both are located relatively close to millions of people. Both have
produced deadly quakes.
</P>
<P>
   There is one main difference that gives scientists reason to
pause. While the North Anatolian has a track record in this
century, producing a domino effect of seven earthquakes between the
first in 1939 and the latest Monday, the San Andreas hasn't let
loose in nearly a century, and its southern half hasn't shaken the
earth in more than 300 years.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists have warned for years that the San Andreas' southern
half is in the ``window'' of probability for a temblor potentially
on the scale of the great San Francisco Earthquake of 1906 that hit
7.9 or 8.0.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just like bending a stick, and if you keep bending and
bending, you've stored up more energy than the strength of the
fault. Bingo,'' said James Dolan, an earthquake geologist with the
Southern California Earthquake Center at the University of Southern
California.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're talking about a large earthquake potentially much larger
than this one,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   That is a frightening prospect given the toll in Turkey: More
than 2,000 people were killed, 10,000 injured and thousands more
were missing following 45 seconds of shaking felt as far as 200
miles away.
</P>
<P>
   Geophysicists at the U.S. National Earthquake Information Center
described the quake as one of the most powerful recorded in the
20th century.
</P>
<P>
   But experts said the toll in Los Angeles and neighboring areas
from an earthquake on a similar magnitude could be different given
building and safety codes tightened in the wake of Southland
earthquakes _ the most devastating being the 1994 Northridge
Earthquake that hit 6.7.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not because we're the great innovators. It's because we
have more earthquakes,'' said Bob Steinbach, principal building
inspector for the city of Los Angeles Department of Building and
Safety.
</P>
<P>
   ``We take every opportunity to learn. Hopefully we will be in a
position to learn from what happened in Turkey as well,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Since Northridge, the city has required structural engineering
inspections of steel-frame high-rises given concerns over cracked
welding. The city also adopted an ordinance for concrete
warehouses.
</P>
<P>
   An existing city ordinance that required retrofitting of
unreinforced masonry buildings proved critical when the Northridge
Earthquake hit. All but 200 of the 8,500 buildings covered by the
ordinance had been retrofitted and none fell. Owners leveled 52
that suffered damage, Steinbach said.
</P>
<P>
   The Big One on the San Andreas, however, would put building and
safety standards to the test.
</P>
<P>
   Major earthquakes on any of the Southland's major fault systems
would create strong, violent shaking. These faults under urban
areas include the major blind-thrust fault systems like the
Oakridge system that triggered the Northridge event and the Puente
Hills Fault, south of downtown, that was discovered this year
through oil and gas data.
</P>
<P>
   The Big One on the San Andreas, however, would generate longer,
stronger waves that lose energy more slowly, said Ned Field, a
seismologist for the earthquake center at USC.
</P>
<P>
   The ground movement could last 40 seconds to more than a minute.
Wood frame homes could withstand the impact better than high-rise
buildings and freeway bridges, Field said.
</P>
<P>
   ``A home will be like a little boat in a sea of huge waves. A
bridge would be like a tanker and could be broken down the middle
because one side might be going up while the other side is going
down,'' Field explained.
</P>
<P>
   When the ground will move with such destructive force is the one
question scientists can't answer.
</P>
<P>
   A decade ago, a team of scientists calculated there was a 60
percent to 70 percent chance of a magnitude 7.5 earthquake on the
San Andreas within 30 years. Three years ago, one of those same
scientists said such a Big One could be larger, in the range of
magnitude 8.5 or greater, but might not come in anyone's lifetime.
</P>
<P>
   Most in the field, however, contend the San Andreas isn't
capable of generating any magnitude beyond an 8.0 because the Big
One likely will hit on the southern half and the entire fault would
be needed to generate a more powerful force.
</P>
<P>
   The debate, though, indicates how the seismic science continues
to evolve. Turkey's latest earthquake provides another laboratory
for learning more about their locations, size and frequency.
</P>
<P>
   ``Big earthquakes are about the best chance we have to watch
these faults in action,'' said Susan Hough, a seismologist with the
U.S. Geological Survey office in Pasadena. ``There's not a lot of
them this big that produce earthquakes this large.''
</P>
<P>
   Dolan, with the USC Earthquake Center, was preparing to return
to Turkey soon after learning of the earthquake. He completed an
annual research trip to study the North Anatolian Fault less than
two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is one of those rare instances where if you ask any
seismologist where the next big earthquake will be in Turkey, this
was the next most likely place,'' Dolan said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The physics of that fault is similar to the San Andreas. We
know that we could have it here,'' he said. ``It's ripe, it's
mature.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
