<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEIBOWITZ </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INFLATING THE COST OF 'FREE AIR' 
</HEADLINE>
 COL-AZR   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID LEIBOWITZ   
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   After decades in critical condition, customer service in America
officially died last Friday. That's when I stopped at Circle K,
shiny quarter in hand, desperate to inflate my right front tire,
and instead made a horrific find.
</P>
<P>
   The price of air had doubled.
</P>
<P>
   Hey, I didn't believe it, either. But there it was, written
large on the Air-Serv tire inflation machine.
</P>
<P>
   Fifty cents.
</P>
<P>
   Feel free to repeat after me, fellow consumers: ``Why, those
lousy, price-gouging, two-quarter-wanting (at)$)(s!''
</P>
<P>
   Which is what I thought upon paying Circle K's 100 percent price
hike for a few measly seconds of air, and what I was still thinking
later, when I phoned the Massachusetts Institute of Technology.
</P>
<P>
   There, in the Department of Earth, Atmospheric and Planetary
Sciences, I found Dr. Ronald G. Prinn, who heads the Advanced
Global Atmospheric Gases Experiment. Prinn is an author and a NASA
consultant. His resume requires its own glossary. His expert
opinion? &QL; 
THE EXPERT SPEAKS &QL; 
``I think I can say with some authority that I know of no
scientific reason why the air in Arizona has doubled in price.''
</P>
<P>
   OK, so science is out. This leaves . . .
</P>
<P>
   PURE CORPORATE GREED!
</P>
<P>
   While on hold with Tosco, Circle K's corporate parent, I spent a
minute reliving the good old days in America: when a motorist could
pull into a gas station and be met by a large, toothless man in a
John Deere cap and greasy uniform. Not only did this man pump your
gas, he would also check to make sure your tires were properly
inflated. If they weren't, he would give you as much air as needed,
an unlimited amount of air, absolutely gratis.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, I wasn't alive to see that, but the story has been
passed down from generation to generation in my family.
</P>
<P>
   As for the story at Circle K, it was predictably complex.
</P>
<P>
   Spokeswoman Julie Igo said Tosco doesn't actually own the air
machines, but merely rents the space to vendors. Recently, the
management firm overseeing the air contractors OK'd the price hike,
said Igo. Tosco Corporate had no clue. &QL; 
CHANGE IS COMING &QL; 
``When we found out about it,'' she said, ``the very first thing
was, `No way, not gonna happen.' We forced them to change it. It's
just going to take about two weeks. It's an error, but we're
definitely going to change them back to 25 cents.''
</P>
<P>
   Which sounds good to you, maybe, but not to me. It's time for a
stand.
</P>
<P>
   For years, I've loyally shopped Circle K, paying a premium for
the ``convenience'' of a quick buy. Not any more, thanks to an
inspiration provided by California Assemblywoman Nell Soto.
</P>
<P>
   Soto has sponsored a bill declaring air and water essential to
the safe operation of motor vehicles and ``therefore public safety
requires that free air and water be accessible at all service
stations.''
</P>
<P>
   AB531 has passed the California Assembly, despite loud
opposition from lobbyists for the petroleum industry, and next week
moves to the state Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ``They used to be service stations, and they had to give you
service,'' said Soto. ``Now, if you're lucky, you get a human being
to take your money.''
</P>
<P>
   At least until they figure out how to replace humans with
coin-operated robots. I'm not waiting around for that, though.
</P>
<P>
   While I'll still buy air at Circle K, I'm going to pass on my
$30 a week in gas. Although many big chains also charge for air,
I'm not resting until I've found a gas station where air is free.
</P>
<P>
   As the Good Lord intended air to be.
</P>
<P>
   Losing my $1,500 a year in business surely won't bother Tosco,
but I figure why concede the point?
</P>
<P>
   First it's 25 cents for air. Next, the toilet stall gets a
coin-operated lock. After that, they turn the store into a vacuum
chamber and rent you scuba tanks to breathe.
</P>
<P>
   I know what you're thinking: Leibowitz, calm down, take a deep
breath. And I may, soon.
</P>
<P>
   While a deep breath is still free of charge. &QL; 
David Leibowitz can be reached at (602) 444-8515 or at
david.leibowitz(at)pni.com. Catch his radio show on KTAR-AM (620)
weeknights, 9 p.m. to midnight. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-18-99 0135EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990818.0029 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-18 01:38 </DATE_TIME>
