<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-PADRES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PADRES DEFEAT METS, 3-2 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ Al Leiter's control was like the picture on an old
television set, fading in and out.
</P>
<P>
   Leiter walked a season-high eight batters, and when he finally
located his rhythm, the New York Mets' usually high-powered offense
could only scratch out five hits. The result was a 3-2 loss on
Tuesday night to the San Diego Padres at Qualcomm Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets and Atlanta Braves remained tied atop the National
League East with identical 73-48 records.
</P>
<P>
   Each time the Mets scratched their way back into the game, the
Padres scored an insurance run. After the Mets had pulled within
2-1 in the top of the seventh, the Padres added a run in the bottom
half on Tony Gwynn's sacrifice fly.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets scored once more on Rey Ordonez's run-scoring single in
the eighth but they could not score again, not even after Rickey
Henderson opened the ninth with a double off the left-field fence
against the Padres' closer, Trevor Hoffman.
</P>
<P>
   Henderson stayed at second base as Edgardo Alfonzo grounded out,
and John Olerud struck out. That brought Mike Piazza to the plate.
On April 28 in New York, Piazza hit a game-winning home run off
Hoffman. On Tuesday night, Hoffman won the duel, getting Piazza to
ground out to second base for his 31st save.
</P>
<P>
   Four of Leiter's walks came consecutively at the start of the
second inning, enabling the Padres to score a run without the
benefit of a hit.
</P>
<P>
   For three-plus innings, Leiter (10-8) flirted with a no-hitter
of his own, one night after Octavio Dotel had held the Padres
without a hit for six innings in the Mets' 4-3, 10-inning victory.
</P>
<P>
   While the Padres' hitters had trouble with Dotel, they had
little difficulty with Leiter because the Mets' starter could not
find the plate. With two outs in the first, Leiter walked Tony
Gwynn and Phil Nevin. Even though he was able to extricate himself
from the jam, it was a harbinger of things to come.
</P>
<P>
   The 33-year-old left-hander lost his control again at the start
of the second inning. Wally Joyner led off with a full-count walk,
and Leiter fell behind Ruben Rivera, 3-0, prompting a visit to the
mound from catcher Mike Piazza. The next pitch? Ball four.
</P>
<P>
   Leiter is an emotional player, and after he walked Rivera, he
went behind the mound and squatted down with the resin bag. Out
came Dave Wallace, the pitching coach, for a visit.
</P>
<P>
   The next batter was Chris Gomez. Leiter walked him on a
full-count pitch. The bases were loaded, and there was nobody out.
And the Padres still did not have a hit.
</P>
<P>
   Up stepped Woody Williams, the Padres' pitcher, who had been an
All-Region shortstop at the University of Houston. Pat Mahomes
hurriedly began to warm up in the bullpen as Williams took four
straight balls to force in a run on Leiter's fourth consecutive
walk.
</P>
<P>
   By now, Leiter had already thrown 39 pitches _ 28 of which were
balls.
</P>
<P>
   And then, all of a sudden, his control returned.
</P>
<P>
   Leiter struck out Damian Jackson on three pitches. On a 1-1
pitch to Eric Owens, Owens grounded into a third-to-first double
play. Just like that, the rally was done.
</P>
<P>
   But the Mets' hitters were having little luck against Williams,
who entered the game with a 5-11 record and a bloated 5.04 earned
run average. Meanwhile, Leiter tossed a perfect third. And then his
defense let him down.
</P>
<P>
   Entering the fourth, the Padres were still searching for their
first hit. Joyner nipped any thoughts of another extended no-hit
bid by leading off with a single. An out later, Gomez grounded a
ball back up the middle.
</P>
<P>
   Leiter instinctively went for it, and his glove knocked the ball
off its route. Alfonzo, who had won Monday night's game with his
10th-inning home run, fielded the ball with time to throw Gomez out
at first for the second out.
</P>
<P>
   But Alfonzo, who had gone 78 consecutive games without an error,
hurried ever so slightly and threw the ball away. Joyner scooted to
third as the ball bounced around in foul territory. The Padres had
runners on first and third with one out. And Alfonzo had committed
just his third error of the season, his first since May 20.
</P>
<P>
   Up stepped Williams, who this time showed what he can do with
his bat. The pitcher ripped a 2-1 pitch over Henderson's head in
left field. After Henderson played the ball off the fence, Williams
had a run-scoring double and the Padres led, 2-0.
</P>
<P>
   Two pitches later, the inning was over after Jackson popped out
in foul territory and Owens grounded to second. But the run proved
to be much-needed insurance for Williams.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
