<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TURKEY-VISITORS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
L.A. QUAKE VETERANS RIDE OUT TURKEY TRAGEDY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DOMINIC BERBEO AND PHILLIP W. BROWNE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Two hours before a massive earthquake hit Turkey,
a Bible study group from the Granada Hills community of Los
Angeles' San Fernando Valley arrived in Istanbul, but its members
remained calm through the fierce shaking that brought back memories
of the 1994 Northridge temblor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone in our group is fine,'' Bill Creasy, a professor at
the University of California, Los Angeles, who is leading the
44-member group, said Tuesday in a telephone interview.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a lot like the '94 Northridge Earthquake, with a lot of
bumping and thumping for about 45 seconds, but most of us here are
earthquake veterans from Southern California and we weren't shaken
up too bad.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bible study group went back to sleep.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of the hotel guests who weren't used to earthquakes were
more shaken up and spent the night at a park across the street,''
said Creasy.
</P>
<P>
   The temblor struck as members of the group were settling into
the Hotel Mercure in downtown Istanbul.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were without electricity and water for nearly a day, but
the hotel was not seriously damaged and we were able to go with the
flow and continue our itinerary without problems,'' Creasy said.
</P>
<P>
   The group is on a 12-day trip through Turkey and Greece to study
the biblical journeys of St. Paul. The section of Istanbul where
the group was staying was relatively untouched compared with other
parts of the country.
</P>
<P>
   Creasy said the group visited the Hagia Sophia and the Blue
Mosque on Tuesday, and were about to go to Greece.
</P>
<P>
   He said many Turks were busy recovering from the quake, and that
even the famous Grand Bazaar in Istanbul was closed.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
