<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-CSUN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR MATADORS, A LOT DEPENDS ON CORNERBACK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRIS BRANAM  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Jeremy Golden, the team's leading tackler, is out
for the season. Mel Miller, a starting cornerback, is fighting to
stay academically eligible.
</P>
<P>
   Cal State Northridge's football season opener is 17 days away,
and who will start in the Matadors' secondary has become a primary
concern. If Miller, a senior who starts opposite Chazz Moore, a Big
Sky Conference Honorable Mention performer last year, can't become
eligible...
</P>
<P>
   ``(Miller) is in summer school,'' CSUN interim head coach Jeff
Kearin said. ``He's taking an independent study course. If he
finishes that, he'll be with us. He is the master of his own
destiny.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller has been to all the Matadors' practices and he's
scheduled to start in Saturday's team scrimmage. If one asks
Miller, it sounds as if he's already determined his fate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to be eligible,'' he said. ``That's all I have to
say. There's nothing to talk about. I'll be the starter.''
</P>
<P>
   Foster Andersen, CSUN's defensive coordinator, said transfers
Shawn Watson (Saddleback College) and Jermaine Hunsicker
(Washington State) have played well in practice and are potential
future starters.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're both good,'' Andersen said, ``but they both have to
learn our system. Steve Forte is playing safety and he is... a good
football player.''
</P>
<P>
   Wounded: Hassan Abdul-Malik, a sophomore listed at No. 1 on the
depth chart at strong safety, didn't practice Tuesday because of a
sore left hamstring.
</P>
<P>
   Abdul-Malik wasn't alone on the sideline. Aaron Arnold, who
became the fourth CSUN receiver to break the 1,000-yard mark
(1,020) last year, dislocated a finger on his left hand Monday and
was held out of some drills.
</P>
<P>
   Marquis Brignac, a freshman running back, has a bruised knee and
didn't practice for the second consecutive day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard, `This isn't high school anymore Brignac,' '' said
Brignac, about the ribbing he took from the defense the day he got
hurt.
</P>
<P>
   Ashcon Majdid, a 300-pound freshman offensive lineman from L.A.
Baptist, has a bad hip and hasn't been cleared to practice.
</P>
<P>
   Waiting game: Barret Woods, a freshman linebacker from Esperanza
High, hasn't been admitted to school yet and didn't practice
Wednesday afternoon. Kearin said Woods' eligibility to play this
season is doubtful.
</P>
<P>
   Auditioning: With the impending transfer of Anthony Ramos to
Washington State, the Matadors are looking for a kick returner.
</P>
<P>
   Terrence Jones, a senior transfer from Fresno State, returned
punts and kickoffs Wednesday. Jones (5-foot-11, 180 pounds) had 17
receptions for 265 yards and three touchdowns for the Bulldogs in
1997 before sitting out last year.
</P>
<P>
   Full contact: The players get to wear pads today and Kearin is
going to allow tackling in some team drills.
</P>
<P>
   The Matadors' defense didn't wait to throw some guys down,
though. Fullback Jaumal Bradley was hit hard twice Wednesday,
including a hit by linebacker Cos Abercrombie that had the entire
defense yelling and exchanging high-fives.
</P>
<P>
   Kearin was upset when Bradley was hit hard again 20 minutes
later. He ended practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were getting a little spunky out there,'' Kearin said.
``I want us to practice like a big-time college program.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
