<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-REWRITE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDD'S NO DUD, BUT DODGERS GO THUD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(OPTIONAL: New lead, adds quotes, details) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Back in the fall of 1997, the Los Angeles Dodgers
left Eric Karros, Eric Young and Todd Zeile unprotected in the
expansion and decided to protect a young pitcher whom very few
people knew.
</P>
<P>
   That was right-hander Mike Judd, who's biggest claim was being
coveted by the Dodgers and then getting pounded when he finally
made it to the big leagues.
</P>
<P>
   Now, partially by default and partially by performance, he's
piqued the interest of the Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   A week ago he got his first major-league win in his first start.
Tuesday against the Florida Marlins, he made his second start and
lost for the first time, a 6-1 setback at Dodger Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   But Judd (1-1) did enough in his six-plus innings to keep the
respirator going and earn another start. In turn, it will provide
the Dodgers another chance to evaluate the 24-year-old, and maybe
further map out how he will be used in the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got the arm to be a starter,'' Dodgers pitching coach
Claude Osteen said. ``He needs to polish a few things.''
</P>
<P>
   First on that list is his breaking pitches. When he accelerated
through the Dodgers' minor-league system in 1997, going from
Single-A to the Dodgers in a matter of months, his breaking pitches
lagged in development.
</P>
<P>
   He also doesn't hold runners on well, as the Marlins' four
stolen bases attest. With a catcher who has struggled throwing the
ball throughout the season, the last thing needed was a pitcher who
was methodically slow to the plate. Judd was that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like what I've seen, but he's got to learn to hold runners
on better,'' Dodgers manager Davey Johnson said. ``Young pitchers,
they'll make a few mistakes. It's part of the learning of a young
player.''
</P>
<P>
   But that Judd will last for a third start is also a testament to
his ability.
</P>
<P>
   True, the Dodgers lack other options at the minor-league level
to fill the void left when Carlos Perez was shipped to Triple-A
Albuquerque. But when Judd arrived in Montreal for his first
major-league start last Thursday (his ninth appearance), he was
there to pitch one day and return to the minors.
</P>
<P>
   Though he gave up four runs in 61/3 innings, he allowed only one
run through the first six. It earned him the start against Florida.
And the potential in him has brought him another opportunity on the
upcoming road trip. He'll pitch in Milwaukee.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a good pitcher right now, not afraid to come inside to
the right-handers,'' Dodgers catcher Todd Hundley said. ``He has a
great change-up, great splitter. He has to learn to throw them for
strikes. That's part of the development.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really impressed with him. Once he gets to know all the
hitters in the league better, he's going to be a quality pitcher.
His change-up is the best I've seen out of anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Understanding when and how to use his pitches will be Judd's
key. While his change-up is strong, it was his change-up that Bruce
Aven hammered over the left-field fence in the first inning to give
the Marlins a 2-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   But the fact Judd has pitched well enough to hang around is
stunning. In his previous two stints with the Dodgers he pitched to
a 12.21 ERA. Before being recalled from Albuquerque, he was an
unimpressive 8-7 with a 6.67 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the last month and a half, two months, they found him a
slot (over the top) where we thought he can be effective throwing
the ball,'' Osteen said. ``He's up top and driving down on the
ball. Now, he just has to iron a few things out. One thing he
didn't have when I was there (earlier in the season) is he bulked
up a lot. He's stronger. His legs are bigger.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Judd's first loss came at the expense of Florida's A.J.
Burnett, who allowed one run in 52/3 innings for the win.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a big adrenaline rush for me,'' said Burnett, who gave
up a Todd Hollandsworth homer in the sixth. ``I pitched a calm,
good game. It was great to come out here to play and I'm
disappointed that I'm going back (to Double-A). Hopefully, I'll
come back in September.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
