<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-18 03:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1149 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-BEETLES-EXPLODING-SFC     08-18 0738
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEETLES-EXPLODING-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DON'T MESS WITH BOMBARDIER BEETLE _ EXPLODING REAR A
POTENT  DEFENSE
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By DAVID PERLMAN 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Beware the bombardier beetle, whose rear end can explode a nasty
spray powerful enough to put predatory enemies to flight in a
hurry.
</P>
<P>
   In a series of experiments with those ground-dwelling beetles,
famed naturalist Thomas Eisner and his colleagues at Cornell
University have photographed one species of the African carabids,
known scientifically as Stenaptinus insignis, showing that they can
send out their noxious spray in any direction _ from side to side,
from top to bottom, and even behind their backs.
</P>
<P>
   Eisner, a pioneer in the study of chemicals that living
organisms either use for their health or emit for their defense,
has found thousands of such examples of ``chemical ecology.'' As a
result, he is a leading and militant advocate of preserving the
Earth's biodiversity.
</P>
<P>
   In a paper published Tuesday in the Proceedings of the National
Academy of Sciences, Eisner and Daniel J. Aneshansley, an
electrical engineer, reveal the technology of the bombardier
beetle's remarkable defense system.
</P>
<P>
   ``Beetles have a problem,'' Eisner and Aneshansley note, because
unlike flies or butterflies it takes them a good deal of valuable
time to unfurl their wings for flight.
</P>
<P>
   ``Delays are unaffordable in emergencies, and it should come as
no surprise that many beetles have evolved means for buying time
when under attack,'' the scientists write.
</P>
<P>
   Because ground beetles live at soil level, they are in constant
danger of being attacked by ants, and so evolution has given them
just the right weapons for defense: dischargeable glands that can
spray out acids and other noxious chemicals _ often at high
concentrations.
</P>
<P>
   The best marksmen in the defensive game are the bombardiers,
Eisner says. In a series of experiments, he and Aneshansley were
able to photograph the bombardier beetle's spray at the precise
instant of a feigned attack, using forceps manipulated in the hands
of the researchers rather than living ants.
</P>
<P>
   The spray of the bombardiers comes from a mixture of two
chemicals, each carried like storage chambers in two separate
glands, Eisner explained. The larger gland holds irritants called
hydroquinones, plus a supply of hydrogen peroxide, while the
smaller gland contains the enzymes needed to make the defensive
spray explode.
</P>
<P>
   Then when tiny hairs all over the the beetle's body sense an
enemy _ whether it's a scientist's forceps or a hungry ant _ the
beetle emits the two chemicals in an explosive burst of spray with
a loud popping sound. The chemicals combine instantly to become a
powerful irritant, spurting out as hot as boiling water.
</P>
<P>
   For their experiments the two Cornell scientists devised a flash
camera triggered by the noise of the explosive chemicals shooting
out of the beetle's body. They discovered that a bombardier beetle
could fire its defenses 20 times in a row before emptying its
chemical supply.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview Tuesday, Eisner said he has been fascinated by
insect defense systems ever since he first handled a bombardier
beetle 45 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nasty chemical sprays are a prime form of defense among many
insects that can't take flight with speed when enemies attack,'' he
said. ``The beetles are incredibly well built for defense, and
that's probably why evolution has enabled them to succeed so well
for millions of years.'' The insect world is filled with creatures
that can put their enemies to flight or even poison them, Eisner
said.
</P>
<P>
   The whip scorpion, for example, sprays a liquid from its tail
that is 84 percent acetic acid and can sting a predator that dares
approach.
</P>
<P>
   ``I found that out the hard way,'' Eisner said, ``when I was
looking at one too closely and got a dose in my face.''
</P>
<P>
   But that highly toxic and irritating spray is what has enabled
whip scorpions to thrive in a hostile world, Eisner noted, for they
are one of nature's oldest creatures _ at least 300 million years
old.
</P>
<P>
   Millipedes, beetle larvae and many moths defend themselves with
an even more toxic chemical, Eisner said. When attacked they spray
out a mixture of two chemicals that produces cyanide gas, which can
kill virtually any enemy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an amazing thing that they don't poison themselves,''
Eisner said. ``That's something we still have to discover.'' &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
