<SLUG> BC-SETI-LISTEN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HUNT FOR LIFE IN OUTER SPACE DRAWS MILLION VOLUNTEERS 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID PERLMAN 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;   &LR;  No one has yet captured a signal from any alien beings in the
cosmos, but more than a million people around the world are now
tuned in for a message on their computers every day.
<P>
   The Berkeley-based global project called SETI &LR; home has already
enlisted that many computer users in 233 countries who have
volunteered the idle downtime of their desktop machines in the
search for extraterrestrial intelligent life, according to the
Berkeley scientists running the quest.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've created the largest supercomputer in the whole world
with all those volunteers,'' said Dan Werthimer, a researcher at
the University of California's Space Sciences Laboratory.
</P>
<P>
   Werthimer and project director David Anderson began recruiting
computer users for their worldwide effort at ``distributed
computing'' only three months ago, and the response has been
phenomenal, Anderson said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   With a million computer volunteers, the central computers at
Berkeley are now crunching unprecedented numbers in search of
unexpected signals from space.
</P>
<P>
   ``In one day, we're getting a thousand years of computing
time,'' Anderson said.
</P>
<P>
   To join the project, computer users can log on to
setiathome.ssl.berkeley.edu and download a free screen saver that
serves as an automatic signal processor whenever the computer is
idle.
</P>
<P>
   Versions of the free SETI &LR; home software are available for
Windows, Macintosh and virtually every Unix operating system.
</P>
<P>
   ``With a million volunteers, this is also the most sensitive sky
survey ever conducted,'' said Werthimer. ``SETI &LR; home is so powerful
because we're using the world's largest telescope, and we are able
to use it continuously, 24 hours a day, by piggybacking on other
observations.''
</P>
<P>
   The original signals come to the SETI seekers from the powerful
1,000-foot radio telescope at Arecibo in Puerto Rico, and one of
these days _ just maybe _ a strange, anomalous signal may _ just
possibly _ reveal that an intelligent civilization on some distant
unknown planet is sending out a message that says, ``We're here.''
</P>
<P>
   If that happens, the Berkeley computers will automatically know
just which prosaic desktop computer, somewhere on Earth, picked up
the message with its software, and that computer's owner will go
down in history.  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-18-99 0339EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
