<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OSTLER-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT ONLY HEARST WHEN I LAUGH
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By SCOTT OSTLER 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;   &LR;  I don't know anything.
<P>
   People keep asking what's up with this newspaper merger, for
instance.
</P>
<P>
   I have no idea, but we're all keeping an eye out for the Turk.
</P>
<P>
   The Turk is the generic title for the front-office flunkie on
every NFL team whose job in preseason training camp is to knock on
the door of players who are being cut.
</P>
<P>
   The Turk knocks and says, ``Coach wants to see you.''
</P>
<P>
   Then he delivers the verbal coup de grace: ``And bring your
playbook.''
</P>
<P>
   Here at The Chronicle, the Turk will probably stand at the stack
of the day's fresh newspapers, under the sign ``Free for
employees,'' and say, ``Uh, that will be 50 cents, sir.''
</P>
<P>
   Then: ``And bring your stylebook.''
</P>
<P>
   (Is ``stylebook'' two words? I told you I know nothing.)
</P>
<P>
   But these are nervous times all over. Maybe it's the coffee
finally kicking in.
</P>
<P>
   That pesky FBI investigation of the Housing Authority, for
instance, has many folks on edge. There are rumors in high places
that indictments are on the way. Does the FBI have a Turk?
</P>
<P>
   And then there are rumors that two male staff members at an
important city government agency have charged the agency boss with
sexual harassment.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor's office says, essentially: Nope, not that we know of.
</P>
<P>
   So relax, everyone. We're all going to be fine.
</P>
<P>
   KULTURE NEWZ: He tried to make an artistic and political
statement by being sodomized with a Jack Daniel's bottle, and now
it's coming back to bite him in the butt.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, the city's power elite flocked to a birthday
party for political campaign genius Jack Davis. Steven Leyba stole
the show with the old bottle sodomy trick, and that was the tame
part of his performance. It made national headlines and threatened
to undermine the mayor's drive for voter approval of a 49ers'
stadium/mall.
</P>
<P>
   Leyba, an ordained priest in the Church of Satan, was recently
commissioned to paint a ceiling mural in a Lower Haight bar,
Chances. The 50-foot-long mural, ``Flying in the Bay of San
Francisco's Sin,'' featured various birds with bodies depicted as
booze bottles.
</P>
<P>
   The mural was three days old when one of the bar's three owners
reportedly ordered it painted over, and it was, and the Rev is mad.
He heard that the partner nixed the work after learning who painted
it.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the owner thought a mural created by a devil-worshipper
would cast a pall over happy hour. Maybe he just said, ``The hell
with it.''
</P>
<P>
   OVERHEARD ... somewhere. They were scrambling at the Ramada
Plaza Civic Center on Market recently. The hotel's owner,
84-year-old Dr. Ho of Macao, was on his way to town with his young
wife and their infant child.
</P>
<P>
   The wife, it is said, preferred to stay at a ritzier hotel _ not
that the Ramada is in any way shabby _ but every hotel in town was
booked. So Ramada management spent a week frantically converting
seven rooms into a lavish suite fit for royalty.
</P>
<P>
   IN OTHER hotel news, the Fairmont's major overhaul could benefit
you if you're a Dorothy Draper fan, and who isn't?
</P>
<P>
   Draper was, of course, the famed designer and innovator who
redecorated the Fairmont in '45. Her lavish creation worked well
for half a century, but a new century looms, so Draper's lobby
furniture is outta there, trucked to Los Angeles to be auctioned
Sept. 15. at Christie's.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not sure what artistic mind is in charge of the Fairmont
re-do, but it's probably not the Rev. Leyba.
</P>
<P>
   WHERE HAVE all the Doggie Diner heads gone, long time passing?
</P>
<P>
   Alert motorist Dan Guerra spotted not one but  &UR; two  &LR; Doggie Diner
heads! He saw the revered San Francisco commercial relics in Sonoma
County, near Jack London State Park. There's a house on a large
piece of property, and on the house are mounted two of the
cartoonish pooch heads.
</P>
<P>
   This means that the dog head mounted on a pole at The Burger
Stand Formerly Known as Doggie Diner on Sloat Blvd., around which
is swirling a storm of preservation-vs.-progress controversy, is
not the world's last existing Doggie head.
</P>
<P>
   The ramifications of this discovery boggle the mind, especially
if the mind has a very low threshold of boggle.
</P>
<P>
   THIS WOULD BE an only-in-San Francisco item, except that it's in
Mountain View.
</P>
<P>
   They pack 'em in two nights a week at the Daybreak, a lesbian
bar, for ``Karaoke with Abe.'' The emcee is a man dressed in full
Lincoln regalia, including stovepipe hat.
</P>
<P>
   One night last week, reports Daryl Glen, there wasn't a dry eye
or undamaged ear in the place when a transvestite in full drag
belted out ``Don't Cry for Me, Argentina.''
</P>
<P>
   OVERHEARD at a lost-luggage desk at SFO: ``If you can fly 2,000
miles in the dark and find San Francisco, you can find my bags.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-18-99 0340EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990818.0050 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-18 03:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1153 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-BUSH-WILSON-SFCHRON &LR;      08-18 0699
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-WILSON-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 BUSH CAMP DENIES EX-CALIFORNIA GOV. WILSON IS ON BOARD JUST YET  &HT;     By CARLA MARINUCCI 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
SAN FRANCISCO _ As Texas Governor George W. Bush prepares a trip to
California for the express purpose of appealing to Latinos, his
state organization has distanced itself from reports that former
Governor Pete Wilson will definitely play a formal role in the
campaign.
<P>
   Gerald Parsky, chairman of the California campaign for GOP
front-runner Bush, has denied published reports suggesting that
Wilson's role is a ``done deal.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There's clearly no decision that has been made about any sort
of role at all. ... We have a campaign structure that is in place.
We're building it with a lot of different people,'' Parsky told The
Chronicle.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would certainly welcome the support of a lot of people,
including Pete Wilson, if he proposed to support (Bush),'' Parsky
said. ``But any reference to a `done deal' is not accurate.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush is scheduled to appear September 2 at the Latin Business
Association's 1999 Business Expo in Los Angeles, which is expected
to draw 3,000 Latino entrepreneurs, the organization confirmed
Tuesday. One association staffer said demand for tickets has been
``astonishing.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush plans a heavy California presence in the coming weeks, with
additional trips tentatively planned for September and October,
according to campaign sources.
</P>
<P>
   His outreach to Latino voters here comes at a time when Bush has
been the focus of sharp criticism. The Texas governor riled Latino
leaders recently by declining to address the National Council of La
Raza, a Latino advocacy group, and passed on an invitation to speak
to minority journalists at the Unity journalism conference in
Seattle in July despite being there at the same time for a
fund-raising visit.
</P>
<P>
   But Patricia Perez, a board member on the Latin Business
Association, called Bush's appearance next month a ``very
positive'' move.
</P>
<P>
   ``We welcome him because we want to get to know him,'' said
Perez, principal partner in the Pasadena-based public relations
agency Valencia Perez &AMP; Echeveste. ``He's going right to the
business sector. ... He's going to his strength.''
</P>
<P>
   With Bush appearing to try to make amends, California political
insiders suggest that the key question now regarding any successful
Latino outreach is the role of Wilson _ the leading proponent of
Proposition 187, the controversial anti-illegal immigration
measure.
</P>
<P>
   Sean Walsh, Wilson's longtime spokesman, declined to comment
this week on a role for Wilson in the Bush campaign. But Democrats
have promised that should Wilson surface in Bush's campaign,
they'll use it to their own advantage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Big mistake by Bush. We'll wrap that around his neck in the
Latino community,'' Bob Mulholland, campaign adviser to the state
Democratic Party, told the Associated Press. Some Republicans
agree.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be a disaster,'' said one leading GOP strategist, who
complained that Wilson's ties to Proposition 187 have alienated
Latino voters from the Republican Party. ``I don't know what
they're thinking.''
</P>
<P>
   But others suggest that the twice-elected former governor could
be tapped not only to endorse Bush, but to raise funds, use his
organizing prowess and draw attention to issues crucial to the
GOP's fortunes in the 2000 election.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson, now a fellow at the Hoover Institution, also heads the
Bear Flag Forum, a nonprofit foundation whose goals include
promoting job growth, educational issues and debating illegal
immigration and affirmative action.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some folks forget ... that at the time 187 passed, without my
support, Republican registration was 40 percent ... and it got 59
percent of the vote,'' notes state Assemblyman Rod Pacheco, a
Republican from Riverside. ``Folks across the board supported it.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether or not Wilson winds up playing a high-profile role,
Democrats have made it an issue already because they know Wilson
``is a popular governor,'' said Walsh. ``He left office tied in
popularity with Ronald Reagan. ... He still has a very strong
rating, both from a personal perspective as well as on his
(issues).''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
