<SLUG> BC-SPECIALS-BUDGET-NYTSF </SLUG>
  
 ENTERTAINMENT SUMMARY 440 - August 18, 1999 
<TEXT>
<P>
   1. PIERCE BROSNAN'S LATEST 'AFFAIR' Now that Pierce Brosnan has
revitalized the James Bond film series as the most money-making
Bond ever, he says he feels at the top of his game. His latest film
is ``The Thomas Crown Affair,'' a remake of the 1968 Steve McQueen
crime thriller. Brosnan explains how he made sure his suave, heroic
art thief hero was neither an imitation of McQueen or Agent 007.
What is really provocative about the screen romance in this film is
that it takes place between an actor who is 46 and an actress (Rene
Russo) who is 45, and not a 60-year-old male star with an actress
barely in her 20s. Brosnan thought it was high time to show a movie
romance with a little more age parity. ``I wanted a woman for the
role,'' he says, ``I didn't want a girl. I wanted someone who could
be my equal.'' By Joshua Mooney. BPI. 1,000 words + photo.
_____________________________________________________________ 2.
CITIZEN HURT With more than 20 major films to his credit, Academy
Award-winning actor William Hurt has long been viewed as a thinking
person's movie star with a track record of intellectually
challenging films. Hurt, 49, has demonstrated a winning combination
of substance and sex appeal. His latest film, ``The Big Brass
Ring,'' based on a screenplay co-written by Orson Welles is a
political drama about a man's quest to become governor of Missouri
in the year 2000. Co-starring with Hurt are Nigel Hawthorne,
Miranda Richardson and Irene Jacob. ``One thing the film does, is
it assumes that people are human, that they have weaknesses and
that they're doing their best,'' says Hurt. By Tamara Conniff. BPI.
1,000 words + photo.
_____________________________________________________________ 3.
SENSE OF A WOMAN The perks of being a rising star for Olivia
Williams are the premieres, the pampering, the opportunities to
work with such megastars as Kevin Costner and Bruce Willis. But she
has just discovered a new advantage : free photocopying at her
agent's office. In the two years since Kevin Costner plucked her
from relative obscurity to appear in his ill-fated movie, ``The
Postman,'' her film career has taken off. Williams, 30, is still
exuberant about her rapid rise, especially because she almost gave
up on acting. Now she's being noticed for her beauty, her talent -
and her nude scenes. She doesn't see it as a big deal. ``There's a
</P>
<P>
   confusion in a lot of people's minds between nudity and sex,''
she says, adding that she won't do any scenes that involve sex and
violence. By James Fallon. From Women's Wear Daily. 800 words +
photo.
_____________________________________________________________ 4.
HALLE BERRY'S ROAD TO 'DOROTHY DANDRIDGE' They are from different
generations - indeed, from different worlds - but Halle Berry says
she has no difficulty identifying with the trials and tribulations
of the late star Dorothy Dandridge. Both actresses have the face of
angels and both embody a smoldering sexiness that captivated
Hollywood in their respective eras. (Dandridge made film history in
1954 when her performance in ``Carmen Jones'' led her to become the
first black ever nominated for an Oscar as Best Actress.) Halle
Berry talks about her performance in ``Introducing Dorothy
Dandridge.'' By Ivor Davis. 1,300 words + photos. (N/A Great
Britain and Australia.)
_____________________________________________________________ 5.
JAMES CAAN : MIRRORED TO THE MOB Once upon a time he was Sonny
Corleone in ``The Godfather'' (1972,) and one of Hollywood's most
respected actors. But then James Caan lost his way, letting a drug
problem drag him down and virtually end his career. After being
absent from the screen for most of the 1980s, Caan has made a
comeback and earned new respect. Now he co-stars with Hugh Grant in
the mob comedy ``Mickey Blue Eyes,'' Caan talks about the film, his
odd-couple pairing with the dapper, self-deprecating Grant, why he
doesn't mind if he is sometimes typecast as a mobster after ``The
Godfather,'' and how cocaine almost ruined his life before his son,
actor Scott Caan, saved him. By Ian Spelling. 1,400 words + photo.
_____________________________________________________________6.
MICHELLE WILLIAMS IN 'DICK' ``Dick,'' one of the funniest comedies
of the summer, is set in the 1970s and deals in madcap, surreal
fashion with the Nixon White House. Though slapstick, it is also a
sophisticated satire of a bygone era. Columbia Pictures is aiming
this film squarely at the teenage market - at kids who weren't
alive during any part of the '70s. They are counting on the appeal
of the film's two teenage stars, Kirsten Dunst and Michelle
Williams, who accidentally stumble into the inner workings of the
Nixon White House. (They walk Nixon's dog, accidentally feed pot
brownies to major political figures and manage to bring down the
president and his crooked staff.) By Joshua Mooney. BPI. 1,100
words + photo.
_____________________________________________________________
Please fax to Paris 33.1.47.42.80.44 or 33.1.47.42.18.81 I am
interested in story no. ______ from summary 440
