<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   COURTS-INTERNET (San Francisco) _ When murder suspect Cary
Stayner was scheduled for an arraignment at the federal courthouse
in Fresno last month, staff there braced for a media circus. But
the least of their problems, surprisingly, has been meeting the
demand for records requests. Since the case broke, almost every
Stayner-related legal document has appeared on the court's Web site
an hour after filing. By PETER HARTLAUB.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CAREERS (San Francisco) _ In that great bumbling wasteland of
television, there are a few classics _ and they stand out for the
same reasons that great workplaces stand out. They may have a star
or two, but mostly they have a talented ensemble. All the
characters have qualities that make them stand out as individuals,
and new people are brought in to keep it fresh. Here are five
classic workplace comedies, and a lesson you can learn from each.
By DAVE MURPHY.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   JAMES-BOND (San Anselmo, Calif.) _ The sense and sensibilities
of American life, as if they aren't under enough attack by our
infamous politicos, have suffered another blow at the hands of
Hollywood's power mongers. The political correctness police think
they've hit pay dirt, but all I see is a horny feminist's
nightmare. I'm suddenly longing for the old days. Maybe you've
already heard. James Bond has quit smoking. By TERRY NORTON.
</P>
<P>
   TV-CABLE (Undated) _ ``Thank God for cable'' in the summer, when
the networks ignore viewers almost entirely and finding something
other than a rerun _ or please, no, please not another ``Dateline''
_ is difficult. By TIM GOODMAN.
</P>
