<P>
   MORSE-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ An outfit called Jupiter
Communications, which is holding a forum in New York this week for
the online advertising industry, reports that 64 percent of online
consumers don't trust Web sites. ``The intense media coverage of
the online privacy issue is fueling consumers' fears,'' said
Michele Slack, an analyst for Jupiter. I'm sorry, but there's more
to it than that. And let me add my 5,595 cents' worth to the
intense media coverage. By ROB MORSE.
</P>
<P>
   LYNCH-COLUMN (Albany, N.Y.) _ Jeff Tolbert, parking ticket
writer, angered a woman driver for giving her a ticket. She twice
backed her car into him, hurting his knee. He asked that the woman
be arrested and he ended up suing the woman. After several knee
operations, he took a settlement of $40,000. As it turned out,
though, while the woman was issued another ticket for unsafe
backing, nobody arrested her. Why not? By DAN LYNCH.
</P>
