<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE RISKY WORLD OF XXX-COMMERCE 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROB MORSE  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ An outfit called Jupiter Communications, which
is holding a forum in New York this week for the on-line
advertising industry, reports that 64 percent of on-line consumers
don't trust sites on the World Wide Web.
</P>
<P>
   ``The intense media coverage of the on-line privacy issue is
fueling consumers' fears,'' said Michele Slack, an analyst for
Jupiter.
</P>
<P>
   I'm sorry, but there's more to it than that. And let me add my
5,595 cents' worth to the intense media coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, my Visa bill had a strange $55.95 charge from
something identified by a string of seemingly meaningless lowercase
letters ending in ``.com.''
</P>
<P>
   I almost downloaded lunch, so strong was the sinking feeling.
I'd never used a credit card for an on-line purchase in my life.
</P>
<P>
   Someone in Internet-land was pretending to be me.
</P>
<P>
   The feeling is perhaps worse than the one that comes with having
your credit card physically stolen. When somebody steals your
plastic, you cancel it. When somebody has your card number out in
cyberspace, you don't know what else they have on you.
</P>
<P>
   It's the technophobe's ultimate technological phobia. Someone
might be out there accessing your cards to their limits. Someone
could be hacking a hole in your bank accounts and retirement funds.
</P>
<P>
   You could have a stalker out there, far beyond the reach of
restraining orders, Mace or small arms fire.
</P>
<P>
   There are things you can do, though. First, I called up the
string of seemingly meaningless letters ending in ``.com'' (well,
actually, I had my non-technophobic wife do it). The charge was
from an Internet billing company with a completely unhelpful Web
site.
</P>
<P>
   No wonder people don't trust Web sites. This one just had a
company name and logo, and no telephone number for all the
complaints the company probably gets.
</P>
<P>
   Tell me who wants to send a complaint by e-mail. You can't get
an immediate response or use a stern voice. What do you do, end
with a frowny face?
</P>
<P>
   I never thought I'd utter these words in my life, but thank God
for the Bank of America.
</P>
<P>
   I looked up a number for credit card inquiries at Bank of
America (you won't find it on the back of your Visa bill) and got a
pleasant woman who immediately gave me the Internet billing
company's 800 number. The woman told me to send a letter to the
bank if I didn't get satisfaction.
</P>
<P>
   Then the bad news. When I asked the guy at the Internet billing
company what the $55.95 bill was for, I learned that I was being
billed for porn somebody else was ogling.
</P>
<P>
   I was too weirded-out at the moment to write down the name of
the porn site, but it sounded like he said the bill was from some
Web site with ``sexhaven'' in the name, dot something or other.
</P>
<P>
   Frankly, I cared more about making sure I got my $55.95 refund,
and the man at the billing company said he'd process it
immediately, as well as block my credit card number from further
use.
</P>
<P>
   I thanked him, but since I'd only heard the Webby-sounding name
of his company for the first time five minutes before, I wasn't
exactly confident.
</P>
<P>
   If on-line commerce is going to flourish, they're going to have
to change some of the names of those companies. When I get a bill
from an outfit called Williams-Sonoma or L.L. Bean I may feel
poorer, but I feel like I'm doing business with real people _ say,
Chuck Williams and the descendants of Leon L. Bean.
</P>
<P>
   When I get a bill from a seemingly meaningless string of
lowercase letters ending in .com, I start feeling e-paranoid.
</P>
<P>
   There was only one thing left to do: Check out the porn I'd
supposedly been consuming as an on-line consumer.
</P>
<P>
   When I looked up the porn site, I found out there are five
variations of ``sexhaven'' available on the Internet, with post
office boxes or street addresses in Brooklyn, Ohio; North Easton,
Mass.; Highland Beach, Fla.; Beaverton, Ore.; and Chester, England.
</P>
<P>
   What these places seem to have in common is that they all have
garages large enough to hold desktop computers.
</P>
<P>
   If there are five on-line outfits with ``sexhaven'' in their
names, imagine how many other Web sites there are with variations
on the word ``sex.'' E-commerce is badly named. It should be called
X-commerce.
</P>
<P>
   I left it all to the imagination and didn't call up any of the
sex havens. The last thing I wanted was to become further ensnared
in the Web sites that were costing me money with no sight of skin
in return, and making me distrust my cute little iMac.
</P>
<P>
   And I'm not sure I want my cute little iMac looking at stuff
like that. I'm canceling its credit card.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rob Morse is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner, P.O.
Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-18-99 1236EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990818.0055 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-18 12:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1404 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k BC-LYNCH-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      08-18 0659
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LYNCH-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOO FEW BLACKS IN THE BLUE UNIFORMS 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN LYNCH  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Jeff Tolbert was on the job, scouting for
illegally parked cars downtown. He saw this car in what appeared to
be a handicapped space. So, Tolbert did what the City of Albany
pays him for. He wrote a parking ticket.
</P>
<P>
   Nineteen months later, Tolbert has a smashed up knee and a
profoundly suspicious attitude toward his bosses. His bosses, in
turn, seem to have decided that this guy is a malcontent.
</P>
<P>
   Tolbert is 26. He's black, which becomes relevant to this story.
On Jan. 29, 1998, he was writing the parking ticket when the car's
owner, a white woman, came out a nearby doorway.
</P>
<P>
   Tolbert told me, ``She crumpled it up in front of my face. She
didn't throw it at me, but she crumpled it up. She said a lot of
stuff to me. OK, so I was walking away, and right when I got behind
the car _ 'cause I was walking down the hill toward Lodge Street _
she hit me with her car twice and said, `Take that, (very bad word
here). Go bother some black people.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``And she backed her car right into you?'' I demanded.
</P>
<P>
   ``Twice,'' Tolbert said.
</P>
<P>
   The woman drove away and parked in front of City Hall, a half
block away. Tolbert called for help. Some cops showed up. The woman
was severely agitated. She and one of the senior cops on the scene
got into a serious shouting match. Tolbert was sent off to Albany
Medical Center to have his knee checked out. He asked that the
woman be arrested.
</P>
<P>
   Tolbert ended up suing this woman. After several knee
operations, he took a settlement of $40,000. As it turned out,
though, while the woman was issued another ticket for unsafe
backing, nobody arrested her. Why not?
</P>
<P>
   Frankly, that's not at all clear to me, despite lengthy
conversations with police brass on this issue. Tolbert's bosses in
the Albany Police Department told me that they just didn't believe
his story. Well, why doubt him? Had he been a bad employee? No, not
at that time, the cops say. They've had some problems with him
since, though. They refused to be specific about that, even after I
had Tolbert give them a waiver so they could talk to me about his
employment record and even after I nagged them repeatedly.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Tolbert conceded that he has been late for work a
few times, but he has the impression that he's being singled out
for criticism.
</P>
<P>
   The woman involved in this incident could have political
connections. Hey, this is Albany, after all. If so, though, I
couldn't run them down. But here you have a parking officer with a
knee seriously injured by a car during the course of his official
duties. You have a woman clearly furious at him _ and with some
reason, it turns out, since she hadn't really been parked in a
handicapped space.
</P>
<P>
   And you have the parking officer saying that she'd purposely run
into him.
</P>
<P>
   That seems precisely the sort of case where cops press charges
and let a judge sort it out. The Albany cops just wouldn't do that,
though.
</P>
<P>
   Some months later, another parking officer was punched by an
angry citizen. The citizen was promptly busted. In that incident,
the officer was white and the assailant was black _ precisely the
reverse of Tolbert's situation. He draws conclusions from that.
</P>
<P>
   In a city where one in four citizens and two in three arrestees
are minorities, the Police Department's membership remains 95
percent white. Believe me, I'm not a quota kind of guy. But here's
the bitter truth, whether anybody likes it or not:
</P>
<P>
   Tolbert could have felt just a bit better about this whole
business. All it would have taken would have been for at least one
of the cops involved in deciding not to arrest this woman to have
been a member of his race.
</P>
<P>
   And not hers.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Lynch is a columnist for the Albany Times Union, P.O. Box
15000, Albany, NY 12212.)
</P>
</TEXT>
