<SLUG> BC-TV-CABLE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CABLE OFFERS A RESPITE FROM NETWORK RERUNS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TIM GOODMAN  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Thank God for cable in the summer, when the
networks ignore viewers almost entirely and finding something other
than a rerun _ or please, not another ``Dateline'' _ is difficult.
</P>
<P>
   All through the summer, cable and, to be fair, PBS, have been
giving viewers something new. Often these shows are small, ignored,
ultimately inconsequential. But the point is this: At least they're
new. And those shows, whether ``Random Play'' on VH1 or ``GvsE'' on
USA, often turn out to be fun. A major network probably wouldn't
air them, they may never topple ``ER,'' but they are welcome
options.
</P>
<P>
   Cable is precisely the reason some of these shows turn out to be
gems. Cable is more aggressively original and daring than the
networks. Thank God, then, that Comedy Central thought enough of a
quirky little show called ``Frank Leaves for the Orient'' (Thursday
nights) to give us all a glimpse.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a distant cousin feel to the kinds of oddball flashbacks
that initially distinguished ``Ally McBeal,'' no network would air
what Comedy Central is calling ``television's first
stream-of-consciousness'' show.
</P>
<P>
   Produced by a two-man creative partnership called LaFong _
multimedia writer-designer Michael Kaplan and Berkeley-based video
artist John Sanborn _ ``Frank Leaves for the Orient'' is like
nothing you've seen on TV before (unless there was something on
cable).
</P>
<P>
   Frank (Stan Cahill) is bored with his job. He's bored with his
life, basically. After coasting most of that life and not really
living it, Frank decides to go to Japan. On Friday. The series _
eight episodes _ is built around Frank trying to cross items off
the necessary lists, thus allowing him a clean break and the
do-over he so eagerly wants in Japan.
</P>
<P>
   The hook of this show is that Kaplan and Sanborn have created a
visual stew that incorporates everything from flashbacks, cartoons,
re-enactments, special effects and text. ``Frank Leaves for the
Orient'' tells a story in fits and starts but never manages to lose
you because the graphic elements are half the fun.
</P>
<P>
   For Frank to go to Japan, he first needs to split with his
girlfriend, Gwen (Rebecca Chambers). His friends, Laura (Peggy Jo
Jacobs) and Ed (Chris Tallman), also must be dealt with. That's
episode one. He has to quit his job in episode two, but his boss
freaks out. In episode three, Ed can't deal with being left behind.
Then there's the lure of the sexy ex (episode four), telling the
folks (episode five), selling his stuff (episode six), dealing
still with his current girlfriend (episode seven) and training his
replacement (episode eight).
</P>
<P>
   In the pilot, it may be hard to sympathize with Frank. But he
grows much more likeable as a loser in each episode. The theme song
to the show says ``he's a lot like you'' and if you've ever been a
slacker who has let life happen to you, then this is your life.
</P>
<P>
   Although the writing on ``Frank'' is funny and the sight gags
(including a chorus of cave men) are amusing, it's the visual work
of Kaplan and Sanborn that keeps the viewer hooked, that makes the
show seem indescribable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frank'' veers wildly from style to style, with Kaplan and
Sanborn displaying a kind of confident swagger that says they can
pull it off. This isn't easy on a show in which five seconds don't
go by without some kind of inner-thought of Frank being spun into a
visual pun.
</P>
<P>
   His co-workers sing ``We're your fake family'' to him. When Gwen
says she would like to go to Japan with him, a chorus screams ``Run
away! Run far!'' When Ed realizes that he's basically Frank-lite,
the two morph into one. Frank's boss has the air _ literally _
taken out of him when Frank says he's quitting. Ed momentarily gets
his own theme song, just like Frank, but the lyrics suggest that
he's a loser who likes beer and ``SportsCenter'' and will be
perpetually alone, never going anywhere close to Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Whereas these diversions may seem, in the first episode, to
replace a plot or be a crutch that props up a flagging joke, pretty
soon you realize that the montages are the show, and you adapt to a
new way of watching a sitcom.
</P>
<P>
   Kaplan and Sanborn are the creative duo behind ``Dysson,'' an
e-mail hoax, ``Paul Is Dead,'' an interactive rock mystery, and
``Psychic Detective,'' an interactive movie/game.
</P>
<P>
   Sanborn's video art has been exhibited in museums throughout the
world, including the Museum of Modern Art in New York and Centre
Pompidou in Paris.
</P>
<P>
   And now, of course, on cable. ``Frank Leaves for the Orient'' is
a small, eccentric, original piece of work that arrives just before
the fall-season onslaught from the networks.
</P>
<P>
   Seek it out and give thanks to cable for saving us from rerun
boredom.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Tim Goodman is the television critic for the San Francisco
Examiner, P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. His electronic
mail address is goodman(at)examiner.com).
</P>
</TEXT>
