<SLUG> BC-CPT-BET-INTERNET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICROSOFT AND MEDIA COMPANIES TO BACK WEB SERVICE FOR BLACKS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By SAUL HANSELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A group of big media and technology companies has agreed to back
BET Holdings, which operates several black-oriented cable
television stations, in establishing an elaborate Internet service
aimed at African-Americans.
</P>
<P>
   BET has raised $35 million for the project from Microsoft Corp.,
USA Networks, News Corp., and AT&AMP;T's Liberty Media unit, which is a
minority owner of BET. The service, which is known as BET.Com, is
scheduled to be introduced on Nov. 1 and will replace the company's
existing joint venture with Microsoft, MSBET.
</P>
<P>
   While the earlier site mainly focused on links to programming on
BET's Black Entertainment Television network, the new site will
have a broader range of offerings including news, electronic mail,
shopping and, most important, chat rooms and other features to
build a community within the site.
</P>
<P>
   So far, African-Americans have been less active on the Internet
than the population overall. Forrester Research estimates that 23
percent of the 12 million black households are online, compared to
34 percent of white households. But online usage by blacks is
increasing faster, Forrester notes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until now, African-Americans have found the Internet hard to
use, expensive and at the end of the day they said ``there's
nothing here for me,'' said Robert L. Johnson, the chairman and
majority owner of BET. ``We're going to change that.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said the audience is poised to increase now that the
price of computers and Internet access has fallen sharply and in
some cases can be had for free.
</P>
<P>
   The company hopes to make money by selling advertising and by
selling merchandise including urban apparel, black oriented music
and collectable items.
</P>
<P>
   The BET venture will compete with several existing sites aimed
at African-Americans, all of which are backed by major media
companies. The largest is BlackVoices.Com, an offering of Tribune
Co., which claims to serve 500,000 users a month who look at a
total of 14 million pages. A close second is NetNoir.com, 20
percent owned by America Online. Cox Communications also operates
BlackFamilies.Com.
</P>
<P>
   E. David Ellington, the chairman of Net Noir, said he isn't
worried about the BET venture, despite the company's well known
name and the promotional power of its television network.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a new medium and it needs new brands,'' he said.
``Name a big media company that has done well on the Web.''
</P>
<P>
   Ellington said Net Noir is raising $10 million to $15 million
from venture capital funds and is about to add new features to its
site.
</P>
<P>
   Barry Cooper, the president of Black Voices, said that Tribune
is considering selling a portion of Black Voices in order to raise
money to compete with BET.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it takes $35 million to stay at the top, we'll raise $35
million,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Cooper said Black Voices had found limited success trying to
sell advertising and merchandise online.
</P>
<P>
   ``African-Americans are new to the Internet, and to expect them
to give their credit cards online is a bit of a stretch,'' he said.
The company has found a profitable niche selling job listings from
large companies that want to attract a diverse work force. This
need works well with the largest group of African-Americans online:
Office workers who surf at their jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, however, said that BET expects that its consumers will
ultimately shop online and that the service can help enable a new
group of black entrepreneurs who will find ways to sell their
products online.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is tremendous wealth being created in the Internet
economy that African-Americans should be a part of,'' he said.
``The Internet can give us the opportunity to control our own
destiny by cutting out the middle man.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-08-11-99 2015EDT &QL;
</P>
