<HEADLINE>
MCI OUTAGE COULD DRIVE NET PROVIDERS OUT OF BUSINESS
</HEADLINE>
 
(Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By MATT RICHTEL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The 10-day partial outage of MCI Worldcom's high-speed data
network took a cataclysmic toll on dozens and possibly hundreds of
small Internet service providers who were forced to shut down
altogether last week. Some say they may go out of business as a
result.
</P>
<P>
   These mom-and-pop players, along with more than a quarter of all
Internet service providers nationally, rely on MCI to route
subscribers onto the Internet. The network outage also took its
toll on regional and national Internet service providers, including
America Online, which said Monday that 2 million subscribers from
its combined America Online and Compuserve services may have been
affected.
</P>
<P>
   But small service providers felt the biggest impact because
unlike their larger counterparts they typically cannot afford a
backup _ that is, a contract with a second major network company.
So when MCI went down, they went down with it.
</P>
<P>
   ``For our industry, this is a killer _ a company killer,'' said
A.K. Jordan, president of Intellitech, a service provider in
Highland Park, N.J., with about 500 dial-up customers.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan said that starting on Aug. 7, the company's subscribers
were no longer able to access the World Wide Web and were able to
get e-mail only from other Intellitech customers. He said he was
told MCI was assuring customers that the problem was due to
congestion and would be up and running in two hours _ a message he
passed along to subscribers who called to complain.
</P>
<P>
   ``We came out looking like liars and incompetents,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   When the situation did not improve, Jordan and his business
partners took the extraordinary step of telephoning roughly
one-quarter of their subscribers to explain the situation and to
ask them not to quit the service. He said he now planned to give
his customers a free month of access.
</P>
<P>
   His situation is not unique, according to DataXchange, a
Washington-based company that buys Internet access wholesale from
MCI and sells it to small providers, like Jordan's Intellitech.
Mark Stutz, a spokesman for RMI.Net, the Denver parent of
DataXchange, said that of the 150 small service providers to which
it re-sells MCI services, 66 ``lost their networks completely.''
</P>
<P>
   Stutz estimated that due to those failures alone, some 250,000
subscribers lost Net access. He said that some of the providers
said they had seen so many subscriber cancellations they might go
out of business.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't get any worse than this,'' Stutz said. ``It's hard
to imagine a worse case scenario for our industry.''
</P>
<P>
   An MCI Worldcom spokeswoman, Linda Laughlin, said the company
would offer customers two free days of Internet access for each day
they had been unable to use MCI's network to access the Net. Ms.
Laughlin characterized the partial outage as an ``unsatisfactory''
performance and said MCI Worldcom expected it would take ``several
weeks'' to regain the trust of its customers.
</P>
<P>
   Some industry analysts said MCI might be underestimating the
public relations toll.
</P>
<P>
   Jeanne M. Schaff, senior analyst with Forrester Research, a
Cambridge, Mass.-based market research firm, speculated that
``most'' of the stranded Internet service providers would look to
one of the other major Network providers for access to the Net.
</P>
<P>
   For now, though, MCI is the biggest player. According to a
survey released in July from Cahners In-Stat, a San Jose, Calif.,
market research firm, MCI Worldcom provides national backbone
access to 40.9 percent of national service providers and to 23.6
percent of small and regional providers _ defined as those serving
fewer than 25 area codes.
</P>
<P>
   Most, if not all, larger and regional providers rely on more
than one company for backbone Net access. For example, Earthlink
Network, a Pasadena, Calif.-based service with 1.4 million
subscribers, employs MCI and six other backbone providers,
including AT&AMP;T, IBM and Sprint, and thus experienced only minor
headaches last week, said Steve Dougherty, director of technology
acquisition for Earthlink. He said the company simply rerouted
traffic that would have gone over the MCI network to another
provider.
</P>
<P>
   At America Online and its subsidiary Compuserve about 2 million
of 20 million subscribers were vulnerable to the network failure
over the weekend because the primary access numbers they use to
dial into the Internet rely on the MCI backbone. In most of those
instances, America Online urged customers to try a different access
number; however, in the case of 50 communities, representing
roughly 500,000 subscribers, there was no second access number
available, the company said.
</P>
<P>
   For those customers, America Online created a toll-free number.
However, some subscribers might not have been apprised of the
change since they were unable to sign onto the Internet in the
first place to receive an update.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-08-16-99 2149EDT &QL;
</P>
