<SLUG> BC-KELSO-COLUMN19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    These kids deserve a break today
 &HT;    By John Kelso
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ The kid sitting next to me with the Rugrats
lunch box got busted for smashing his cookie on the table.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want you to do that,'' Shannon Sellstrom, assistant
principal at Mollie Dawson Elementary, told him. ``What would
happen if everybody did that to the table?'' Nobody can take a joke
anymore.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at this,'' said a little girl, probably 5, sitting across
the table from me. She was showing me how you can blow up an empty
aluminum bag of Capri-Sun wild cherry drink like a balloon by
blowing on the straw that goes through the little hole into the
bag.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as teachers are concerned, not the best invention on
the market,'' said substitute teacher Tami Lewis. ``Those things
squirt.''
</P>
<P>
   Since school is back in session in Austin, on Friday I dined
with the kindergartners and second-graders during lunch at the
Dawson cafeteria. This is my review of the establishment.
</P>
<P>
   Look at it this way: The food must be pretty good because there
is always a line to get in.
</P>
<P>
   The school has about 500 students ages 3 through 12, so there's
always plenty of interesting table talk.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mother has a lot of boyfriends,'' said a little girl
sitting at the table next to Lewis. I don't know what brought that
up.
</P>
<P>
   Friday at Dawson was, as is usual on Friday in the Austin
Independent School District, ``hamburger day.'' You got your choice
of a hamburger or a chicken patty sandwich (or, gag, the yogurt
plate), carrots or french fries, apple chunks and low-fat chocolate
or low-fat regular milk. Snack offerings included vanilla pudding
or blue Jell-O (food isn't supposed to be blue), a bag of Chester's
Popcorn, Bighorn Beef 'N Chicken Jerky (I'll bet the kids don't get
jerky in Hoboken, N.J.), and Blue Bell Mooo ice cream bars.
</P>
<P>
   For my entree, I selected the hamburger with the fries, regular
low-fat milk, apple chunks and the jerky. I forgot to eat the
jerky.
</P>
<P>
   The milk and the apple were standard fare, but the burger and
fries were a disappointment. They were what I refer to as luke
cold.
</P>
<P>
   I thought the children should have sent the hamburgers and fries
back to the kitchen and demanded that they be reheated. But nobody
did.
</P>
<P>
   Diners are seated at long tables, and you never know who's going
to sit next to you. So you're bound to find yourself engaged in
some interesting chitchat with your dining companions.
</P>
<P>
   One boy sitting across from me, probably 5 years old, had a
Band-Aid on his forehead.
</P>
<P>
   ``My sister was pulling my shirt, and then she let me go, and
then I hit my head on the headboard,'' he explained. He was eating
a bag of H-E-B thin sour cream and onion potato chips. ``Where'd
you get those?'' I asked him. I hadn't seen the chips offered when
I went through the line. Turns out the boy had brought the chips
from home. I was a little jealous because my hamburger bun was dry
and could have used some grease.
</P>
<P>
   The service in here is impeccable, and I was it once. ``Hey,
mister, can you open this for me?'' a boy asked, handing me his
jerky.
</P>
<P>
   The decor was a little thin. Hanging art consisted of a bulletin
board decorated with Goofy and a hippo holding a pencil, and a sign
that tells you not to share your food.
</P>
<P>
   So, of course, I reached over and ate a chunk of apple off a
kid's plate. ``You ate the seed,'' said a boy sitting across from
me, looking surprised. Yeah, well, so what? I said. ``You like the
seed?'' the kid said, giggling.
</P>
<P>
   This kid had a lot of business laughing at me for eating the
seed. Shoot, he was eating the blue Jell-O.
</P>
<P>
   I would dine again at Mollie Dawson. But I would recommend
returning on a Monday, when they have pizza.
</P>
<P>
   John Kelso writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas. E-mail: jkelso(AT)statesman.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
