<HEADLINE>
TRAVELING THE WEB WITHOUT LEAVING FOOTPRINTS  
 AIMING A LITTLE PERSUASION AT MAKERS OF TV RECORDERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Privada Inc. of San Jose, Calif., is betting that when typical
consumers become aware of how exposed they are to invasions of
privacy on the Internet, they will part with $5 a month for a cloak
of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   Depending on a user's computer setup and Internet service
provider, a single visit to a Web site, for instance, can often
reveal the Internet address assigned to the visitor's computer, the
visitor's e-mail address, the browser and operating system being
used, and what plug-ins or Active-X controls have been installed.
It can give away even more information if the user has not removed
the unique serial numbers embedded in Microsoft's Windows 98
operating system and Intel's Pentium III microprocessor.
</P>
<P>
   Little wonder that a recent Harris poll for Business Week found
that fears of losing privacy were the top reason people decided not
to go online and that among those who do, only three out of 10 give
valid information when asked to register at a site.
</P>
<P>
   Privada plans to unveil a new service Monday, called Web
Incognito, that lets users make all of their Internet activities _
e-mail, online chats, Web browsing and even purchases _ completely
anonymous. The service works by encrypting the data flowing out of
a subscriber's computer and redirecting it to the Privada service
after it leaves the Internet service provider.
</P>
<P>
   Web Incognito masks the data's origins and sends it on to its
intended destination. Responses, like those from Web sites or
e-mail recipients, flow back to Privada, which passes them back to
the subscriber. The service, which can be switched on and off, also
stores the subscriber's ``cookies,'' files that identify the user
to Web sites, so it does not interfere with standard Web surfing.
</P>
<P>
   Web Incognito differs from other anonymity software in two
important ways. It covers all Internet activity, not just Web
browsing or e-mail, for instance. And the identity it protects can
be shared with police officers who have appropriate warrants.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our service is for protecting the privacy of consumers, not
for hiding criminals or criminal activities,'' said Barbara
Bellissimo, Privada's chief executive. While she said the company
expected to take some heat from privacy rights groups, she added,
``We felt it would be irresponsible not to give law enforcement
agencies the information if they have valid warrants.''
</P>
<P>
   The free software and information about the subscription service
are available at http://www.privada.net/.
</P>
<P>
   _ ROB FIXMER
</P>
<P>
   Speaking Up Early on Copyright Infringement
</P>
<P>
   It sounded like saber rattling when a consortium of television
networks and programming companies decided last week to issue a
public threat against the makers of personal video recorders _
devices that some believe will revolutionize the way people watch
television. But the reaction was neither fear nor anger _ and
certainly not one of quaking in corporate boots.
</P>
<P>
   A little nod and a smile were more like it.
</P>
<P>
   That was because the consortium making the threats is made up
mostly of companies already in business with one of the two
entities being threatened.
</P>
<P>
   The issue is copyright infringement, and the consortium wants
mainly to establish that any new company getting into the business
of marketing the recorders, known as PVRs, must agree to enter into
licensing agreements with program suppliers before it re-uses the
material for its own purposes.
</P>
<P>
   Two companies, ReplayTV and Tivo Inc., are already marketing
PVRs, digital devices that make it much easier for home viewers to
create their own programming lineups and potentially to eliminate
commercials. Both companies have actively courted deals with the
big program suppliers. Tivo has already sold minority interests to
four of the companies involved in the consortium: Walt Disney, CBS,
News Corp. and Discovery Communications.
</P>
<P>
   Bert Carp, a Washington-based lawyer who represents the
consortium, the Advanced Television Copyright Coalition, and Turner
Broadcasting, whose parent, Time Warner, is in the consortium, said
the purpose of last week's action, reported first in The Wall
Street Journal, was not to file suit against the two PVR companies,
though such a threat was specified in its press release.
</P>
<P>
   What the consortium is doing, he said, is putting on the record
its expectation that PVR companies must adhere to existing
copyright laws. The consortium is concerned about what happened to
Hollywood studios in the 1970s when they sought to stop Sony Corp.
from selling videocassette recorders.
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court ruled 5-4 against the studios, in part because
the studios were late in asserting their rights, waiting until long
after the machines were in wide use.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you wait until you're actually hurt,'' Carp said, ``you
might be making a big mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   He noted that other companies are expected to enter the PVR
market, and that some of them might not be as ready to become the
partners of the program suppliers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not trying to choke off the technology,'' Carp said.
``We've just learned that in some cases you need to speak up early
to protect your position.''
</P>
<P>
   _ BILL CARTER
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-08-15-99 1803EDT &QL;
</P>
