r k BC-MINOR-COLUMN19-COX     08-18 0573
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MINOR-COLUMN19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    You have to be a flyweight to fly in a 17-inch seat
 &HT;    By Emily C. Minor
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Bad news, ladies and gentlemen.
</P>
<P>
   The airlines _ those good folks who delay your flight when the
plane's not full and then leave your luggage behind _ have been
fiddling around with your derriere.
</P>
<P>
   What I mean, specifically, is that if you have to fly somewhere
_ say to a convention in Topeka next May or your class reunion in
the year 2010 _ you might want to start slimming down. Now.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe you could start by having pretzels for dinner tonight
instead of peanuts.
</P>
<P>
   Because, from what I can gather, that feeling you get when
you're on an airplane? Like you're in a cage? Like the stupid
seat's not as big as it used to be?
</P>
<P>
   It's for real.
</P>
<P>
   Here's the skinny:
</P>
<P>
   Years ago, in the 1960s when flying meant white gloves for the
ladies and jackets for the men, airline seats were 18 inches wide.
That was considered the smallest seat acceptable.
</P>
<P>
   Today? Chances are that seat you're sitting in is just 17 inches
wide. And your leg room? The space set aside for one row of seats?
It's called ``seat pitch'' and, says the Wall Street Journal, has
gone from 34 inches to 32 inches this decade alone. This is done so
that the airlines can fit more people on their planes.
</P>
<P>
   See, we're not nuts. We're not even fat. We're simply the
victims of yet another corporate conspiracy. We lose the weight,
they make the money.
</P>
<P>
   I can hear the check-in questions now:
</P>
<P>
   ``Did you bring your driver's license?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Did you pack your own bags?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Did you eat those two cold chicken nuggets off your kid's
plate last night instead of throwing them in the trash like you
should have?''
</P>
<P>
   I swear, if a sky cap ever whips out a yardstick _ a ruler won't
do _ and tries to measure my backside, I'm taking the train.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Mixon knows of what I speak. Mixon, 53, who lives outside
Atlanta, flies a lot, always coach. Maybe once or twice a week he's
on a plane. A computer specialist who helps travel agents install
their software programs, he's got this whole traveling thing down.
He gets to the airport early. He checks his luggage instead of
trying to cram it into the overhead bin.
</P>
<P>
   And he always asks for the aisle seat. At 6-feet-1 and 205
pounds, Mixon needs that little bit of extra space.
</P>
<P>
   ``Flying,'' says Mixon, ``is not what it used to be, and praise
be to God if someone could bring it back.''
</P>
<P>
   If Mixon's able to get an aisle seat, that's ``livable.'' The
window seat's ``kind of livable.''
</P>
<P>
   But the middle seat? That tiny claustrophobic spot between the
stinky old lady and the jittery kid?
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no way that's comfortable,'' Mixon says.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Sheppard, 24, has to be even more of a soldier when he
flies. Sheppard is 6-feet-4 and weighs 280 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't matter at this point,'' said Sheppard, also from
Atlanta. He says his knees practically touch his chin. If the
person in front of him reclines the seat, ``it's all over.''
</P>
<P>
   And he can't put his tray table down. But I figure that last
thing's just another part of the airline industry's big corporate
plan. Has been all along.
</P>
<P>
   They don't want any of us to eat ever again.
</P>
<P>
   Emily C. Minor writes for The Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
