r l BC-DIGITAL-PHOTOS19-COX     08-18 1518
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIGITAL-PHOTOS19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Digital touch-ups a real Trompe L'Oeil
 &HT;    By Paul Reid
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Once upon a simpler time, Henry VIII
fell in love when he beheld a portrait in oil of his betrothed,
Anne of Cleves.
</P>
<P>
   Alas, when Anne showed up for the wedding, Henry _ who had never
met her _ took one look and underwent an immediate and total change
of heart. Anne was ugly. Henry was royally ticked off. Anne was
sent packing and her embellished portrait consigned to the royal
attic.
</P>
<P>
   She was pretty as a picture, but pictures can lie.
</P>
<P>
   Photos do not. Well, they're not supposed to. A photo supposedly
captures an image of what is, not what might be.
</P>
<P>
   But with the coming of the digital age, a sweep of a computer
mouse can turn the objective reality of the camera's eye into
subjective unreality. Where the artist employs a brush and paint to
reduce the curvature of a nose, the digital technician employs his
mouse to add hair, delete frowns, straighten a nose.
</P>
<P>
   Or clean up a crime scene.
</P>
<P>
   Or make a missile silo disappear from the landscape.
</P>
<P>
   Or accidentally ``cure'' a ruptured spleen in a CAT scan.
</P>
<P>
   And there's no way to detect the manipulation. Reality is at the
mercy of the mouse.
</P>
<P>
   O.J. Simpson's skin was digitally darkened for a Time cover.
Prince William's sourpussed face was expunged from a royal wedding
photo, replaced by a smiling Willie. Dustin Hoffman won a lawsuit
after Los Angeles Magazine ran a doctored photo of him in drag. The
magazine claimed Hoffman was a public figure, known for his
cross-dressing role in ``Tootsie,'' and therefore open to humorous
portrayal. The court said false is false, judgment to Hoffman.
</P>
<P>
   The parents of a Connecticut high school student didn't like his
yearbook picture _ he had shaved his head _ so they had a photo lab
add digital hair.
</P>
<P>
   JC Penney ran a photo program where guest photographers snapped
portraits, then worked with customers to eliminate blemishes, lose
weight and add sparkle to eyes.
</P>
<P>
   The new _ virtually _ you.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, air-brushing of photos has been around for almost as long
as photography, and artists have added color to black and white
photos since the days of glass negatives. But a colorized print can
be detected from afar, and an airbrushed print can be compared with
the original film negative in order to detect manipulation,
according to Pete Cross, photo director at The Palm Beach Post.
</P>
<P>
   Negatives, says Cross, cannot be doctored without changing the
physical characteristics of the negative. Original negatives never
lie.
</P>
<P>
   But digital images are just collections of electronic signals,
bits of information. The original photo image is converted to
signals, then reformatted into an image. During the reformatting
process, the signals can be changed to produce different images.
And if done without an electronic audit trail, nobody can tell the
difference.
</P>
<P>
   So, unless a photo is accompanied by the original negative, you
can't be sure it hasn't been doctored.
</P>
<P>
   That raises some questions.
</P>
<P>
   Can a digital image be used in a courtroom?
</P>
<P>
   Are high school yearbooks of the future going to be flights of
fashion fancy rather than accurate pictorial representations of
students, zits and all?
</P>
<P>
   Where does a photo editor at a magazine or newspaper draw the
line at redrawing the lines?
</P>
<P>
   ``We will not change a news photo,'' says Cross. ``We'll select
a photo from among many, the one that best conveys the scene, but
we won't doctor it.''
</P>
<P>
   National Geographic magazine has a two-page photo policy, the
gist of which is: no tricks. The policy evolved after Geographic
rearranged the Great Pyramids of Giza in a photo in order to fit
their image onto a cover. Now, except for adjustment to shading and
light, and to protect identities, content alteration of Geographic
photos ``is unacceptable, using any form of technology.''
</P>
<P>
   The Associated Press photo policy is simple: ``The content of a
photograph will never be manipulated or changed in any way.''
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers are not under such tight constraints and are preparing
for courtroom changes. ``We haven't seen a lot of digital
photographs,'' said a lawyer in the office of the State Attorney.
``But we can anticipate the changes. Crime scene photos have
traditionally been of poor quality, not so much because of the
photography, but because crime scenes are such a mess, dark,
confusing. Any attempt to `clean up' crime scene photos by digital
retouching would raise eyebrows. Digital imaging is a new
ballgame.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I see significant questions,'' says Stuart lawyer Willie Gary.
``From now on, I want to see the electronic trail that produces a
photograph used in evidence. Even two or three years ago, I
wouldn't have thought this way. But things have changed big time.
Bodily injuries or property damage can be made to simply disappear
in digital photos. You could lose a case if you tried to use
doctored photos. For that matter, you could lose if the other guy
got away with using doctored photos. So you have to know: Where did
the image come from?''
</P>
<P>
   Without an electronic watermark, that's impossible, says Elmo
Sapwater, resident technical genius and managing editor of PEI,
Photo Electronic Imaging magazine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Several software companies are coming out with watermarks,''
says Sapwater. ``Each time an image is altered a new watermark will
overlay the old, leaving an audit trail. If the image is passed
along without change, it will retain the original mark. This will
make life easier for lawyers, technicians, doctors.''
</P>
<P>
   Doctors?
</P>
<P>
   ``Say your doctor sends a digital image over the phone to a
doctor in Hong Kong, for diagnosis. And the image gets reformatted,
changes. So the broken arm looks healed, or the tumor looks like it
is smaller than it really is. That would be a nightmare,'' says
Sapwater. ``But an electronic watermark would tip off the receiving
doctor that something happened to the image.''
</P>
<P>
   When the digital image comes from outer space, all sorts of
possibilities exist.
</P>
<P>
   ``NASA has used a dual format for years with digital
photography. When NASA photos are beamed down from space, they come
in pairs. One set of digital information cannot be altered. Raw
formatting. The other, identical image, can be altered by
scientists on the ground, for clarity or color, whatever they want.
But one set cannot be touched. That protects the integrity of the
information.
</P>
<P>
   ``Imagine a spy satellite photographing enemy troop movements or
a missile silo. And the enemy can hack into the transmission and
make their soldiers `disappear.' You need to know your information
is pure. If it isn't, you need to know it's been fooled with,''
Sapwater says.
</P>
<P>
   That sounds logical enough to be a national security matter.
</P>
<P>
   It is, says Sapwater.
</P>
<P>
   Kodak, Nikon and Sony have offered such technology to government
scientists for years, he says. Now, the big camera-makers are
working on products for general use that will include raw format
features and watermarks.
</P>
<P>
   The days of leaving no fingerprints on an altered digital image
may be numbered. But the price of truth is high.
</P>
<P>
   A top-of-the-line digital camera can cost more than $20,000.
Computers and processing equipment can run another $40,000.
</P>
<P>
   West Palm Beach portrait photographer Mike Moya keeps his Sony
digital camera locked up in a five-ton safe.
</P>
<P>
   The digital age has changed Moya's profession _ and his outlook
on human nature.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have always airbrushed,'' says Moya. ``Take away gray hair,
tuck in a shirt, remove a mole. But digital photography can create
new worlds. One of my clients was an older lady who had caught a
big marlin on a fishing trip. She had only one photograph of her
trophy. In it she was holding the fishing rod while her guide stood
next to the fish. Nobody believed she had caught the fish. So we
curved her arm, moved the fish over to her side of the picture, put
the rod in the guide's hands. Now, people believe she caught the
fish.''
</P>
<P>
   Moya has added a healthy eyeball where the original was damaged.
He has shot families in the studio and placed them in a field of
flowers or on a pure white beach. He has put heads on bodies
dressed in tuxedos, removed unwanted guests from wedding photos,
made kids gone bonkers look saintly by switching torsos or faces.
He has created family portraits of families that didn't actually
sit for the portrait and then put the families in places they've
never been.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of this is vanity,'' he says. ``But some is simply a way
to capture a client's mental image, maybe their idea of peace or
beauty. Their dream. Think of it as a very technical form of
artistic expression.''
</P>
<P>
   Or think of it as the painless nose job.
</P>
<P>
   Digital wizardry still wouldn't have helped Anne of Cleves. A
rose is a rose and ugly is ugly. We wear truth on our faces.
</P>
<P>
   Even digital mirrors won't change that.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Reid writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
