<DOCNO> NYT19990818.0073 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-18 13:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1459 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-GUNS-NEXTDOOR19-COX     08-18 1211
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUNS-NEXTDOOR19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The guns next door
 &HT;    By Michele Chan Santos
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Matt Alexander's 9-year-old daughter was playing
at a friend's house. When he went to pick her up, he noticed an
antique gun mounted on the living-room wall.
</P>
<P>
   After they went home, Alexander sat down with his daughter and
talked with her about gun safety.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did you notice they had a gun?'' he asked her. She said yes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you know what to do if you find a gun in someone's house?''
he asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not touch it,'' his daughter answered.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's right. Don't play with it,'' he told her. ``Stay away.
Don't touch it.''
</P>
<P>
   Next time, Alexander says, he'll probably have her friend over
at their home instead, or he and his wife might ask the other
parents some questions about gun safety.
</P>
<P>
   It's an awkward subject to bring up, he admits, because the
other parents might become ``embarrassed or defensive, and then if
you were in a conflict with them, you wouldn't want your kid over
there,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   With school shootings seemingly in the headlines every month,
and a growing awareness of the dangers of children and guns, more
parents are adding gun safety to their list of concerns.
</P>
<P>
   There are a multitude of worries parents can have when their
children are playing at someone else's home, but this one is
particularly scary. Every two hours, a child is killed with a gun,
according to the American Academy of Pediatrics, and gunshot wounds
cause one of every five admissions to pediatric trauma centers.
</P>
<P>
   Fueled by images from thousands of movies, television shows and
video games, guns hold a fascination for children that other
dangerous items, such as kitchen knives or lawn equipment, don't
have. Pediatric experts warn parents to tell their children,
repeatedly if necessary, that in real life, children are killed and
hurt badly by guns.
</P>
<P>
   In Texas, it is illegal to leave a loaded gun where someone
under 17 can find it if you haven't locked it up or otherwise
rendered it inoperable. Still, many parents find gun safety a
touchy subject to broach with other families.
</P>
<P>
   Carl Pickhardt, a psychologist in private practice in Austin and
the author of several parenting books, suggests putting the
emphasis on yourself when asking other parents about guns in their
home.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can say, `I'm probably being oversensitive, but it would
ease my mind to be able to clear this with you,' '' Pickhardt
advises. ``Say, `I know this may sound a little out of bounds, but
with all the stuff that's been happening, I want to know if you
have guns and what kind of security they are kept under.' ``
</P>
<P>
   Gun safety is ``not a hard hazard to ask about,'' Pickhardt
says. ``It's not like asking if they abuse alcohol or drugs.''
</P>
<P>
   If you are not comfortable with their answers _ if the other
adult says, ``We own guns but the kids don't know where they are,
so they're not locked,'' or something else that makes you nervous _
simply thank them for their time and let your child know that he
can have his friend over at your home, but you are not comfortable
having him play over there.
</P>
<P>
   It's also crucial, Pickhardt says, to educate your child about
gun safety and other issues. A whole host of hazards could reside
in a home your child visits, from drugs and alcohol to
inappropriate movies and games. Tell your children that if they
encounter something hazardous or dangerous, they need to avoid it
while they're there, and let you know about it when they come home,
he says.
</P>
<P>
   Some parents feel that the most crucial element in keeping your
children safe around guns is educating them. A child who knows how
to use a gun, who realizes how dangerous it is, who has been
schooled by his or her parents in gun safety will keep themselves
safe, these parents say. And their children agree.
</P>
<P>
   Erin Henry, 18, recently graduated from high school and will be
a freshman at St. Edward's University this fall. She and her
siblings, Katie, 11, and James, 9, were taught how to use, take
apart and assemble a gun as young children. Erin says she can't
remember not knowing about gun safety.
</P>
<P>
   Her parents showed her ``how to use one, the consequences of
having one, what happens when you fire that gun,'' Erin says. ``I
grew up around a lot of police officers. I wish every parent would
teach their child the same thing.''
</P>
<P>
   As a child, she remembers ``that if I pointed a fake orange gun
at someone,'' her father would take the toy away. ``We don't play
toy shooting at each other,'' he would tell her.
</P>
<P>
   Erin clearly remembers one of her family's police-officer
friends telling her and her siblings the dangers of toy guns.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it was dark and you pointed a toy gun at me, and I didn't
know it was a toy, you could get hurt,'' the officer told them.
</P>
<P>
   Linda Swanson, Erin's mother, learned how to use a gun from her
own father.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody in my family hunts, but we had five guns in the
house,'' she says of her childhood. ``We knew what they were, what
they could do.''
</P>
<P>
   Swanson keeps a gun at home; her ex-husband also keeps guns in
his house.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've never had an incident,'' she says of her children and
firearms. ``It's not something they are ever allowed to touch. Our
children were appropriately taught, and they are very respectful of
that.''
</P>
<P>
   As for their friends, ``I'm sure my kids would feel
uncomfortable playing with someone who didn't respect guns, and
they would tell me about it,'' Swanson says.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, one of her younger children got into an argument at
school, and the other child said he was going to ``get a gun and
shoot'' Swanson's child. Swanson told the other child's parents, as
well as the police. Now that some time has passed, her child and
the boy are friends again, but ``I would not have that child over
to play,'' she says. ``I'm disappointed in how many children are
being raised.''
</P>
<P>
   Every six to eight weeks, Todd Maxson, a pediatric trauma
surgeon at the Children's Hospital of Austin, finds himself in the
sad situation of treating a child under 14 who is injured with a
gun.
</P>
<P>
   He has heard parents say the same thing over and over: ``I
didn't think the kids knew where the gun was,'' or ``I didn't think
it was loaded.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Children have an amazing amount of curiosity and
resourcefulness,'' Maxson says. ``They will be able to
circumnavigate halfhearted attempts at storage.''
</P>
<P>
   Maxson has discussed gun safety with adults in other households
where his children are playing _ including his wife's family
members, who are avid hunters and sportsmen.
</P>
<P>
   ``We say, `This is an important safety issue for us,' '' Maxson
says. ``We'd like to be sure guns are stored properly.''
</P>
<P>
   He advises parents to think about gun safety the same way they
would any other product.
</P>
<P>
   ``You would ask families to be sure that your child wears a life
preserver if they were in their boat, that a dog was leashed around
small children or that electrical outlets were covered for
toddlers,'' he says. ``It's the same thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Michele Chan Santos writes for The Austin American-Statesman,
Austin, Texas. E-mail: msantos(AT)statesman.com
</P>
