<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-18 13:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1460 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS19-TAKE     08-18 1577
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS19-TAKE1-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Q &AMP; A ON THE NEWS
 &HT;    (EDS: Take one of two takes.)
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Have a question about the news? Colin Bessonette will try to get
an answer. Call 404-222-2002, or write him at The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta, Ga. 30302, or e-mail
him at
</P>
<P>
   q&AMP;a(AT)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Q: A few months ago, it was reported that an Alabama jury
awarded a couple an enormous amount of money for the overcharging
of a satellite dish. What was the amount awarded? And what's the
status of the case?
</P>
<P>
   A: The amount awarded in May by a jury in Hale County, Ala., was
$581 million, of which $580 million was punitive damages. The
judgment is expected to be reduced drastically on appeal.
</P>
<P>
   The case involved door-to-door sale of $1,100 satellite dishes
which sold for $199 at stores. The plaintiffs claimed the scheme
preyed on the elderly and illiterate, and that the defendants used
credit card financing to conceal the number of payments due.
</P>
<P>
   But the jaw-dropping award raised the issue of whether huge
punitive damage awards should be restricted. It's a particularly
heated issue in Alabama, where critics say juries commonly dispense
``jackpot justice.''
</P>
<P>
   In the aftermath of the $581 million award, the Alabama
Legislature has passed new tort reform laws which were signed by
Gov. Don Siegelman. Under the new laws, punitive damages in
non-bodily injury cases are limited to $500,000 or three times
compensatory damages, whichever is greater.
</P>
<P>
   And suits may be filed only in the county where the injury took
place, where the plaintiff lived at the time of the injury, or
where the defendant has its main place of business. Formerly,
injured plaintiffs could move and file suit in what they considered
more ``friendly'' counties known for large verdicts and hostility
to corporations.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Like thousands of others, I mourn the passing of Atlanta
Journal-Constitution columnist Celestine Sibley. Articles point out
that she was only the second woman to receive the Lifetime
Achievement Award from the National Society of Newspaper
Columnists. Who was the other?
</P>
<P>
   A: Molly Ivins, Fort Worth (Texas) Star-Telegram. These are all
the organization's winners: 1993, Herb Caen, San Francisco
Chronicle; 1994, Ivins; 1995, William Raspberry, Washington Post;
1996, Art Hoppe, San Francisco Chronicle; 1997, David Broder,
Washington Post; 1998, Richard Reeves, Universal Press; and 1999,
Celestine Sibley.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I'm distressed about the death of my favorite columnist,
Celestine Sibley of The Atlanta Journal-Constitution. I have 15 of
her books and am always looking for others. Can you list all her
titles?
</P>
<P>
   A: Years published, titles and publishers:
</P>
<P>
   1958, ``The Malignant Heart'' (Doubleday); 1963, ``Peachtree
Street USA: An Affectionate Portrait of Atlanta'' (Doubleday);
1964, ``Christmas in Georgia'' (Doubleday, reissued in 1985 and
1991 by Peachtree Publishers); 1967, ``Dear Store: An Affectionate
Portrait of Rich's'' (Doubleday, reissued in 1990 by Peachtree);
</P>
<P>
   1967, ``A Place Called Sweet Apple'' (Doubleday, reissued in
1973 and 1985 by Peachtree); 1969, ``Especially at Christmas''
(Doubleday, reissued in 1985 by Peachtree); 1970, ``Mothers Are
Always Special'' (Doubleday, reissued in 1985 and 1994 by
Peachtree); 1972, ``The Sweet Apple Gardening Book'' (Doubleday,
reissued in 1989 by Peachtree);
</P>
<P>
   1975, ``Day by Day With Celestine Sibley'' (Doubleday); 1976,
``Small Blessings'' (Doubleday); 1978, ``Jincey'' (Simon &AMP;
Schuster); 1980, ``The Magic Realm of Sally Middleton'' (Oxmoor
House); 1981, ``Children, My Children'' (Harper &AMP; Row); 1982,
``Young 'Uns'' (Harper &AMP; Row); 1984, ``For All Seasons''
(Peachtree);
</P>
<P>
   1988, ``Turned Funny'' (Harper &AMP; Row); 1990, ``Tokens of
Myself'' (Longstreet Press); 1991, ``Ah, Sweet Mystery: A Kate
Mulcay Mystery'' (HarperCollins); 1992, ``Straight as an Arrow: A
Kate Mulcay Mystery'' (HarperCollins); 1993, ``Dire Happenings at
Scratch Ankle: A Kate Mulcay Mystery'' (HarperCollins); 1994,
``Touch of the Shepherd: Reflections on the Life of Vernon S.
Broyles, Jr.'' (Bemis Publishing);
</P>
<P>
   1995, ``A Plague of Kinfolk: A Kate Mulcay Mystery''
(HarperCollins); 1997, ``The Celestine Sibley Sampler''
(Peachtree); 1997, ``Atlanta's Half Century With Furman Bisher and
Celestine Sibley (Longstreet); and 1997, ``Spider in the Sink: A
Kate Mulcay Mystery'' (HarperCollins).
</P>
<P>
   Q: A tourist attraction in Chattanooga, Tenn., uses the slogan
``See Seven States From Rock City.'' I can understand being able to
see Tennessee, Georgia, Alabama and maybe North Carolina, but what
are the others?
</P>
<P>
   A: The other three are South Carolina, Virginia and Kentucky.
It's not just ``tourist hype'' that visitors can see all seven,
said Rock City Gardens spokeswoman Lydia Thompson, but she added
that conditions have to be right: clear skies, and knowing exactly
where to look, especially for the sometimes hard-to-see mountain
peaks in Kentucky and Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I've read that it's possible to have a star named for
someone. What is the procedure?
</P>
<P>
   A: It's simple. It can be done online at www.starregistry.com or
by calling 1-800-282-3333. The registry, a commercial venture based
in Illinois, was founded in 1979 by an astonomer in Canada. The
company emphasizes that people aren't buying stars, as some think;
they're simply buying a certificate saying a star has been named
for someone. Many people do it as a birthday or other gift, a
spokeswoman said.
</P>
<P>
   A ``star kit'' includes a certificate bearing the chosen name
and telescopic coordinates for locating the star; a sky chart with
the chosen star circled for identification; and a booklet on
astronomy. The cost is $48 with an unframed certificate, $91
framed, plus shipping charges.
</P>
<P>
   Q : Being one of Tom Brokaw's ``The Greatest Generation''
prompts me to ask: How is the World War II Memorial in Washington
coming along?
</P>
<P>
   A: It's still in the fund-raising stage. As specified in Public
Law 103-32, it will be funded almost entirely by private
contributions. The capital goal for donations is $100 million. As
of June, about $60 million had been raised from individual donors,
corporations and foundations, veterans' groups and associations.
</P>
<P>
   The memorial will be on the Mall at the Rainbow Pool site at the
east end of the Reflecting Pool between the Lincoln Memorial and
Washington Monument. The site was dedicated on Veterans Day, Nov.
11, 1995. Groundbreaking is projected for Veterans Day, 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Information: 1-800-639-4992. Donations can be mailed to World
War II Memorial, P.O. Box 96766, Washington, DC 20090-6766, or can
be made online at www.wwiimemorial.com or www.WWIImemorial.com
</P>
<P>
   Q: Who makes the decision about recipients of the Presidential
Medal of Freedom? When was this medal established?
</P>
<P>
   A: It's entirely up to the president to decide who gets the
lustrous red, white and blue enameled medal, the nation's highest
award for civilian achievement.
</P>
<P>
   It was created by President Kennedy in 1963. According to
Congressional Quarterly's Guide to the Presidency, Kennedy wanted
to create an award for civilian achievement soon after he took
office in 1961. After considerable study, the White House decided
to revamp the existing, but little-used, Medal of Freedom, which
had been created by President Truman in 1945 to recognize
contributions to America's national security.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy was assassinated before the first awards ceremony on
Dec. 6, 1963, but President Johnson and Kennedy's widow,
Jacqueline, decided that going ahead with the ceremony as scheduled
would help the nation begin the process of healing.
</P>
<P>
   Q: There's been a lot of publicity about a Toyota reaching the 1
million-mile mark. Does a Toyota's odometer really register that
high?
</P>
<P>
   A: Odometers on Toyota vehicles don't show 1 million miles, but
they indeed do go up to 999,999, said company spokesman Sam Butto
in Torrance, Calif. Then the odometers turn over to all zeros _ the
millionth mile. Butto said his company frequently gets letters from
people whose vehicles have registered 300,000 or more miles ``and
still are running great.''
</P>
<P>
   In the million-miler case, it was Douglasville, Ga., resident
Jim Jeter's 1982 Toyota Starlet reaching the milestone. He appeared
on ``The Late Show With David Letterman'' on Aug. 2. Earlier that
day, Jeter's car hit the magic number with a TV camera focused on
the odometer when it read 000,000.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Does the Red Cross test for hepatitis B, thalassemia minor
and HIV before or after taking blood from a donor? How long does it
take to get the blood to patients?
</P>
<P>
   A: No blood center, including the American Red Cross, performs
tests for inherited blood disorders such as thalassemia major and
thalassemia minor, according to Red Cross spokeswoman Karen Eisele.
These tests can be performed easily by one's primary physician, she
added.
</P>
<P>
   But the American Red Cross does test blood for Hepatitis B, in
addition to a number of other potentially infectious viruses, such
as HIV. These tests are done on a sample from the blood after it
has been donated and are completed within 24 hours. With other
preparation, labeling and ``quality steps to ensure the safest
blood products,'' the majority of blood is available within 48
hours, Eisele said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
