<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-18 13:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1461 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS19-TAKE     08-18 1402
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS19-TAKE2-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Q &AMP; A ON THE NEWS
 &HT;    (EDS: Take two of 2 takes.)
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: We haven't seen anything reported about the funeral of Mark
Barton, the Atlanta mass killer, or the disposition of his body. Do
you have any information?
</P>
<P>
   A: Funeral arrangements were handled by his family at a private
service, according to the Cobb County (Ga.) medical examiner's
office. The burial site has not been revealed.
</P>
<P>
   Q: When people don't pay their income taxes, I end up paying
more, so they are stealing from me. Is there a way to report
someone to the Internal Revenue Service?
</P>
<P>
   A: Yes. IRS spokesman Eric Roberts advises you to call the
agency's tax fraud hotline at 1-800-829-0433. The IRS, by the way,
pays the whistleblower up to 10 percent of the additional amount
it's able to collect.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I know you've printed information on this subject before, but
it's back. My daughter saw something on the Internet claiming that
a Procter &AMP; Gamble official, appearing on ``The Sally Jessy Raphael
Show,'' said the company is somehow involved with Satanism. The
Internet item said anyone who didn't believe it could send $3 to an
address and a transcript of the program would be sent to them. Do
you know anything about it?
</P>
<P>
   A: Don't send any money to anyone. Rumors linking Procter &AMP;
Gamble and its moon and stars trademark with Satanism have been
circulating since 1980-81. A few years ago, it was said that the
president of P&AMP;G admitted on ``The Phil Donahue Show'' that the
story was true. The Donahue program quickly branded the tale a
hoax.
</P>
<P>
   The latest wrinkle on the story involves Raphael. Her executive
producer, Maurice Tunick, has responded with this statement, dated
July 27: ``It seems impossible that the rumor of an appearance by
the president of Procter &AMP; Gamble on `The Sally Jessy Raphael Show'
is still circulating after more than a decade. There is absolutely
nothing to this rumor. The president of P&AMP;G has never appeared on
`The Sally Jessy Raphael Show,' nor has any other P&AMP;G executive.
Anyone who claims to have seen such a broadcast is either mistaken
or lying. It never happened!''
</P>
<P>
   Similiar denials of the rumor, in all its variations, have been
issued by Cincinnati-based Procter &AMP; Gamble itself; the General
Council of the Assemblies of God; the office of the archbishop of
the Archdiocese of Cincinnati; Liberty University and Jerry
Falwell; Phil Donahue; the Southern Baptist Convention; the
Episcopal Diocese of Southern Ohio; and the Billy Graham
Evangelistic Association. Signed statements by all of them can be
viewed online at www.pg.com/rumor/ Procter &AMP; Gamble, by the way,
says it has filed 15 lawsuits, six against Amway distributors
accused of spreading the Satanism rumors. All were concluded in the
company's favor, according to P&AMP;G.
</P>
<P>
   Q: News reports are warning of bean sprouts contaminated with
disease-causing bacteria. Would they be safe to eat if cooked? How
much nutritional value would they lose if stir-fried or steamed,
for instance?
</P>
<P>
   A: The bacteria doesn't seem to be destroyed by heat, so cooking
doesn't make contaminated sprouts safe, said Chris Rosenbloom,
Georgia State University nutritionist and a spokeswoman for the
American Dietetic Association. The people most at risk are those
with weakened immunity, such as those taking chemotherapy, the very
old and very young, and anyone with HIV, she added. Healthy people
wouldn't have a huge risk using small amounts of bean sprouts, for
example, on a sandwich or in stir-fry recipes.
</P>
<P>
   So far as nutritional values, any method of cooking would not
alter the nutrient content significantly. But sprouts aren't a
powerhouse of vitamins and minerals under any circumstance,
Rosenbloom said.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Has Bruce Lindsey left the White House? We used to see him on
TV constantly with President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   A: Lindsey is still there. And he's still in the same position,
serving as deputy counsel to the president, said White House
spokeswoman Elizabeth Newman.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Q&AMP;A recently reported on the passenger ship United States. I
believe it was built as the luxury liner United States before World
War II, then was recommissioned as the West Point and converted
into a troop carrier. I crossed the Atlantic on it in 1944. Am I
correct?
</P>
<P>
   A: No, but the confusion is understandable. The blueprints for
the SS United States were developed by the naval architects Gibbs &AMP;
Cox in July 1945. The superliner's keel was laid in February 1950
and it first set sail in July 1952. It operated for 17 years,
making 800 crossings, before being retired. As reported, it's now
docked in Philadelphia, with an uncertain future.
</P>
<P>
   The ship that was renamed West Point _ the one you're referring
to _ originally was the America, and was owned by the same company
that later built the United States, said Ray Mann of the Navy
Historical Center. The United States replaced the America as the
company's flagship.
</P>
<P>
   Q: At least several times a year, I find small, brown scorpions
in my house. What can you tell me about them?
</P>
<P>
   A: The scorpion found in the southeastern United States is the
common striped scorpion (Centruroides vittatus), said Beverly
Sparks, entomologist with the University of Georgia Cooperative
Extension Service. Its sting causes only temporary local pain,
tingling and itching, and some localized swelling or tenderness.
For most people the feeling is comparable to a bee sting. But,
Sparks added, an allergic response can result in some people and it
could be life-threatening.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Three baseball players were in the news recently for their
milestones: Tony Gwynn and Wade Boggs for reaching the 3,000-hit
plateau, and Mark McGwire for hitting his 500th home run. These
feats bring Ted Williams to mind. I know he had 521 career home
runs. How close was he to getting 3,000 hits? What was his career
batting average? How much playing time did he miss serving his
country in World War II and Korea?
</P>
<P>
   A: Williams had 2,654 hits in 2,292 games in his 19 seasons with
the Boston Red Sox. His lifetime batting average: .344. His career
was interrupted twice by military service as a Marine Corps pilot.
He missed the 1943, 1944 and 1945 seasons during World War II, and
most of the 1952 and 1953 seasons during the Korean War.
</P>
<P>
   Q: An article reported on the inaugural rally of the Southern
Party, a new political party proclaiming itself to be the
philosophical heir to the Confederate States of America. How can
someone contact it?
</P>
<P>
   A: There are several ways. Letters can be addressed to: Southern
Party, P.O. Box 2582, Chesterfield, VA 23832, or P.O. Box 8546,
Woodland, TX 77387. Or you can call Jerry Baxley, the party's first
vice chairman, at 804-675-7717. Online information can be found at
this Web site: www.southernparty.org
</P>
<P>
   Q: My son said he had heard of a comedian who made his living
reciting the poem ``Casey at the Bat'' while touring the country.
Do you know who that comedian was? And can you print the text of
the poem?
</P>
<P>
   A: The poem, by Ernest L. Thayer, first appeared in the June 3,
1888, San Francisco Examiner. It attracted little attention until
it was recited later that year by William DeWolf Hopper, a
Shakespearean actor, singer and comedian.
</P>
<P>
   Hopper, the person your son is thinking about, went on to recite
the poem more than 10,000 times during his lifetime _ immortalizing
it to such an extent, in fact, that an early pamphlet version of
the poem had Hopper's photo on the cover, but didn't mention Thayer
at all. And Hopper's bust _ not Thayer's _ is at the Baseball Hall
of Fame in Cooperstown, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   The poem, which over the years has appeared in many variations,
deals with a batter named Casey who strikes out at a crucial moment
in the game. ``Doing a Casey'' or ``pulling a Casey'' has become a
common term for one who fails in the manner of Casey.
</P>
<P>
   The poem is too long to reprint in its entirety, but here's the
last stanza, which is frequently quoted:
</P>
<P>
   Oh! Somewhere in this favored land the sun is shining bright;
</P>
<P>
   The band is playing somewhere, and somewhere hearts are light.
</P>
<P>
   And somewhere men are laughing, and somewhere children shout;
</P>
<P>
   But there is no joy in Mudville _ mighty Casey had struck out.
</P>
<P>
   (ENDIT)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
