</P>
<P>
   Q : Being one of Tom Brokaw's ``The Greatest Generation''
prompts me to ask: How is the World War II Memorial in Washington
coming along?
</P>
<P>
   A: It's still in the fund-raising stage. As specified in Public
Law 103-32, it will be funded almost entirely by private
contributions. The capital goal for donations is $100 million. As
of June, about $60 million had been raised from individual donors,
corporations and foundations, veterans' groups and associations.
</P>
<P>
   The memorial will be on the Mall at the Rainbow Pool site at the
east end of the Reflecting Pool between the Lincoln Memorial and
Washington Monument. The site was dedicated on Veterans Day, Nov.
11, 1995. Groundbreaking is projected for Veterans Day, 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Information: 1-800-639-4992. Donations can be mailed to World
War II Memorial, P.O. Box 96766, Washington, DC 20090-6766, or can
be made online at www.wwiimemorial.com or www.WWIImemorial.com
</P>
<P>
   Q: Who makes the decision about recipients of the Presidential
Medal of Freedom? When was this medal established?
</P>
<P>
   A: It's entirely up to the president to decide who gets the
lustrous red, white and blue enameled medal, the nation's highest
award for civilian achievement.
</P>
<P>
   It was created by President Kennedy in 1963. According to
Congressional Quarterly's Guide to the Presidency, Kennedy wanted
to create an award for civilian achievement soon after he took
office in 1961. After considerable study, the White House decided
to revamp the existing, but little-used, Medal of Freedom, which
had been created by President Truman in 1945 to recognize
contributions to America's national security.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy was assassinated before the first awards ceremony on
Dec. 6, 1963, but President Johnson and Kennedy's widow,
Jacqueline, decided that going ahead with the ceremony as scheduled
would help the nation begin the process of healing.
</P>
<P>
   Q: There's been a lot of publicity about a Toyota reaching the 1
million-mile mark. Does a Toyota's odometer really register that
high?
</P>
<P>
   A: Odometers on Toyota vehicles don't show 1 million miles, but
they indeed do go up to 999,999, said company spokesman Sam Butto
in Torrance, Calif. Then the odometers turn over to all zeros _ the
millionth mile. Butto said his company frequently gets letters from
people whose vehicles have registered 300,000 or more miles ``and
still are running great.''
</P>
<P>
   In the million-miler case, it was Douglasville, Ga., resident
Jim Jeter's 1982 Toyota Starlet reaching the milestone. He appeared
on ``The Late Show With David Letterman'' on Aug. 2. Earlier that
day, Jeter's car hit the magic number with a TV camera focused on
the odometer when it read 000,000.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Does the Red Cross test for hepatitis B, thalassemia minor
and HIV before or after taking blood from a donor? How long does it
take to get the blood to patients?
</P>
<P>
   A: No blood center, including the American Red Cross, performs
tests for inherited blood disorders such as thalassemia major and
thalassemia minor, according to Red Cross spokeswoman Karen Eisele.
These tests can be performed easily by one's primary physician, she
added.
</P>
<P>
   But the American Red Cross does test blood for Hepatitis B, in
addition to a number of other potentially infectious viruses, such
as HIV. These tests are done on a sample from the blood after it
has been donated and are completed within 24 hours. With other
preparation, labeling and ``quality steps to ensure the safest
blood products,'' the majority of blood is available within 48
hours, Eisele said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
