r s BC-FBN-BENGALS-HALL19-CO     08-18 0443
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-BENGALS-HALL19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hall turning heads at Bengals camp
 &HT;    By Chick Ludwig
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GEORGETOWN, Ky. _ The kids leaning over the railing in the
bleachers at Georgetown College's Rawlings Stadium scream his name:
``Cor-eee! Cor-eee! Can I have your autograph?''
</P>
<P>
   Bengals safety Cory Hall signs everything shoved his way . . .
including Corey Dillon and Corey Sawyer football cards.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's OK,'' he said, laughing at the mistaken I.D.
``Hopefully, one day, they'll know I'm Cory Hall.''
</P>
<P>
   The 6-foot, 210-pound rookie third-round draft pick from Fresno
State is turning heads at training camp with his explosive speed
and smooth moves _ just like he did at the NFL Combine in February.
</P>
<P>
   Some experts picked him to be a seventh rounder or as a
non-drafted free agent because they doubted he could make a quick
transition from the Western Athletic Conference to the NFL. Now
it's payback time.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you're going to see from Cory Hall is better play than
what a lot of people expected,'' he said. ``I've got a lot of
people to prove wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Talk about a lack of name recognition. When you toil for Fresno
State, you have to kick, fight, scratch and claw for national
attention. Hall didn't get much respect until the pro scouts
visited. What did they see?
</P>
<P>
   ``A guy that's aggressive to the ball and a flat-out
playmaker,'' he said. ``You're getting a guy that's 210 pounds
running just as good as the cornerbacks out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Bengals head coach Bruce Coslet said, ``We were criticized when
we took him because there were some bigger name safeties still
there. But that's why we go out scouting. We liked him. He's fast,
and a good tackler. He's a tough guy. He'll hit you.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's helped him is that he was in a similar defense in
college. I'm sure the calls are different. But the principals (of
the 3-4) are the same with the zone blitzes.''
</P>
<P>
   Bengals director of pro/college personnel Jim Lippincott raves
about Hall.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's decisive, diagnoses things well and reacts correctly,''
he said. ``He's been everything we expected and more.''
</P>
<P>
   Hall is second string behind Greg Myers, but a starting job
isn't that far away.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a process you have to go through,'' he said. ``I
understand that. I'm not the kind of guy that's revengeful and
hateful. I'll sit back and wait my turn. But eventually . . .''
</P>
<P>
   Hall didn't finish the thought. He was too busy signing Corey
Dillon and Corey Sawyer football cards.
</P>
<P>
   Chick Ludwig writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
