<HEADER>
A1468 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d BC-FOOD-PEACHES19-COX     08-18 0357
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-PEACHES19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Peaches are ripe for the picking
 &HT;    By Ann Heller
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Peel, pit and eat. It's the best part of summer.
</P>
<P>
   We're talking peaches, and that means juicy peaches. If you're
still buying California peaches at the supermarket, you're missing
the point. Local fruit is truly tree-ripened.
</P>
<P>
   When the peaches are this good, you don't have to do much to
them. Just make sure they're perfectly ripe by putting them in a
paper bag for a day or two. After eating some out of hand,
preferably over the kitchen sink, it's time to gild the gold.
</P>
<P>
   Here are four peachy ideas to gussy up the harvest with a
minimum investment of time. The only thing that takes a bit of work
is peeling the peaches. To make that easy as can be, drop them in a
pan of boiling water for just 10 seconds. Then the peel can be
slipped off with a flick of the knife.
</P>
<P>
   It only takes a couple minutes to slice or chop the peaches.
Taste and add a bit of sugar if they're not quite sweet enough to
suit you. And, if it's going to be a while until dinner, squeeze a
little lemon juice over them so they don't turn brown.
</P>
<P>
   All you need for a fine finale is some ice cream or pound cake,
or a pint of blackberries as a partner. Or pick up a split of
inexpensive (translate that as not-too-dry champagne). Pop the cork
and pour over the peaches and celebrate summer.
</P>
<P>
   _ Fill a champagne glass with sliced peaches. Pour champagne,
Asti Spumante or any other sparkling wine over and serve while it's
bubbling.
</P>
<P>
   _ Layer blackberries, diced peaches and freshly whipped cream in
a wine goblet. Sprinkle with toasted almonds.
</P>
<P>
   _ Spoon sliced or diced peaches over scoops of top quality
vanilla or peach ice cream. Pour a shot of hazelnut liquor
(Frangelico) over the top and scatter chopped toasted hazelnuts on
top.
</P>
<P>
   _ Drape sliced, sweetened peaches over slices of pound cake or
angle food cake. Drizzle with warm caramel sauce.
</P>
<P>
   Ann Heller writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
