 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
Gizmos 98 may have a useful one for you 
By Jack Warner  
c. 1999 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Gizmos 98 is another one of those packages which, we are led to
believe, contain all the good stuff that Microsoft forgot to put
into Windows.
</P>
<P>
   Well, maybe. Depends upon what you want out of life, what you
want out of your computer, and whether you, like Play Inc., which
published this program, are chiefly interested in graphics. But to
take Microsoft's view, you've got to stop somewhere.
</P>
<P>
   In my view, there is one thing, or group of things, in this
package which Microsoft might well have put into the Windows
accessory package, and that's a calendar.
</P>
<P>
   Gizmos gives us a bunch of calendars _ weekly, monthly, yearly
and a single day. (Why a single day? Well, because that's how you
make and save your appointments.) My problem with the calendars is
my main problem with the whole thing _ they're ugly. But then, what
do I know?
</P>
<P>
   All right, let's enumerate all the things that Play Inc. thinks
Microsoft cheated us out of with Windows:
</P>
<P>
   _ Picture Explorer, which displays in thumbnail form all the
pictures in your hard drive.
</P>
<P>
   _ A programmable CD music player.
</P>
<P>
   _ Four different clocks, each fancier and uglier than the last.
</P>
<P>
   _ All those calendars.
</P>
<P>
   _ Six different card games, including ``Freecell'' and
solitaire. I prefer Windows' versions. I never heard of the other
four.
</P>
<P>
   _ A stupid jigsaw puzzle game. All jigsaw puzzle games are
stupid, by definition.
</P>
<P>
   _ Four calculators, each more complicated than the last. Not too
ugly, though.
</P>
<P>
   _ A program called Performer, which you can use to turn all
those pictures in your computer into a slide show, with fancy
effects and sound. Neat if you like that kind of thing.
</P>
<P>
   _ An incredibly annoying screen saver.
</P>
<P>
   _ A much-less-annoying screen saver that sends 360-degree
scenics scrolling across your screen.
</P>
<P>
   _ A color organ screen saver that adapts its incredibly annoying
pulsations to whatever music your programmable CD player is
playing.
</P>
<P>
   _ A video cube screen saver which will rotate a cube covered
with photographs of a young lady who is billed as the co-founder of
Play Inc.
</P>
<P>
   _ A security device called a Vault, into which you may drop
files and then password-lock the vault. Could be useful.
</P>
<P>
   _ A file shredder.
</P>
<P>
   Now, if you think all that might be worth $50, go to
www.play.com and check it out further.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: jwarner(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   We want to hear from you but can't acknowledge every message.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-08-16-99 1129EDT &QL;
</P>
