<SLUG> BC-CPT-TECHREPORT17-COX </SLUG>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
Poll: Computers positive for kids 
By Mark Clothier  
c. 1999 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Maybe all those hours glued to the computer monitor are a good
thing.
</P>
<P>
   A poll sponsored by FamilyPC magazine, the results of which were
published in the September issue, asked 615 families about the
effects of PC use on their kids. Most of those polled, 68 percent,
felt PC use made their kids smarter, but 13 percent said they
didn't think so. About 19 percent weren't sure.
</P>
<P>
   Most parents polled, 61 percent, said they thought computers
made their kids more creative as well. And 79 percent of the
parents polled said PCs helped their kids develop problem-solving
skills.
</P>
<P>
   One expert cited in the story thinks parents are doing their
kids a disservice by not teaching them how to understand the
intellectual culture computers carry and how to navigate the
digital divide between the haves and have-nots.
</P>
<P>
   Parts of the story are available at FamilyPC's Web site, www
</P>
<P>
   .zdnet.com/familypc/.
</P>
<P>
   Music on the Web has its own awards
</P>
<P>
   TV, CDs and magazines still dominate the music industry. But the
Internet might change all that.
</P>
<P>
   Yahoo Internet Life magazine stays a step ahead by conducting an
annual poll looking at the best the music industry has to offer the
Web.
</P>
<P>
   For the 1999 version of the magazine's Online Music Awards, the
guy who used to call himself Prince won for Best Net Single. The
former Prince used the Internet to distribute ``The War,'' a
20-minute single that was available from his Web site, www
</P>
<P>
   .love4oneanother.com.
</P>
<P>
   Sarah McLachlan won Best Net Album for adding ``to the glow of
online commerce to her reflective pop by distributing her live
album `Mirrorball' through an exclusive deal with Amazon.com.''
</P>
<P>
   The ex-Prince was among six musicians honored for having the
best official sites. The Beastie Boys' site, www.beastieboys.com,
won the category, followed by Tori Amos, www.tori
</P>
<P>
   .com; David Bowie, www.davidbowie.com; Marilyn Manson,
www.marilynmanson.net; and Public Enemy, www.public-enemy.com.
</P>
<P>
   Other sites were noted for their excellence as reference
sources. Ultimate Band List, www.ubl.com, was voted the best for
music news, online radio and links to record labels. All-Music
Guide, www.allmusic.com, is one of the largest online music
reference books, including artist biographies, record reviews and
daily music news updates. International Lyrics Server,
www.lyrics.ch/index.htm, was also included.
</P>
<P>
   The August issue also lists a group of Incredibly Useful Sites.
This month's collection includes a nutrition analysis tool, www.ag
</P>
<P>
   .uiuc.edu/(tilde)food-lab/nat
</P>
<P>
   /mainnat.html, and a way to search for Web broadcasts,
realguide.real.com.
</P>
<P>
   Dissecting those cell phone pricing plans
</P>
<P>
   Have cellular phone prices dropped enough for you yet? Are the
inexpensive phones and even-less-expensive calling plans starting
to make you think about buying one?
</P>
<P>
   One Web site, www.point.com, is a way to cut through the details
of a multitude of calling plans out there and find one that suits
you.
</P>
<P>
   The site lets visitors sort plans by phone and by calling plan.
It searches both categories based on your ZIP code.
</P>
<P>
   Point.com, formerly Wireless Dimension, searches 200 phone
models and 3,000 calling plans in 50 markets.
</P>
<P>
   New radar detector has its own compass
</P>
<P>
   Radar detectors are not quite as popular as they were in their
1980s prime, but the product keeps evolving. Precision Navigation
has developed what it claims to be the first radar/laser detector
with a built-in compass.
</P>
<P>
   The RX5000, which sells for about $200, weighs 6 ounces. The
device alerts drivers to all forms of radar. It has 360 degrees of
laser protection and warns drivers of road hazards, including
approaching emergency vehicles, roadwork and upcoming train
crossings, using a eight-digit text display.
</P>
<P>
   The compass displays direction with digits and cardinal points.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-08-16-99 1129EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
