<HEADLINE>
EXPERTS SAY Y2K BUG WILL NOT SHUT DOWN THE INTERNET
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  By MARILYN GEEWAX  
c.1999 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Software glitches will not shut down the Internet
on Jan. 1 because the world's largest computer network is
``self-healing,'' capable of bypassing any local failures caused by
the Y2K bug, Internet experts said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   On New Year's Day, ``the Internet should bend and not break,''
said Donald Heath, chief executive of the Internet Society, a
non-profit group that helps set Internet infrastructure standards.
Because of the vast network's resilient and decentralized
structure, ``the sky is not even thinking about falling,'' he said
at a press conference called by the President's Council on Year
2000 Conversion.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Internet operations could temporarily fail in some cities
because of local interruptions in telephone service or electricity,
or because a particular Internet service provider did not prepare
for the rollover to 2000, the experts said. Internet disruptions
may be greater in foreign countries where phone and power companies
are less prepared for Y2K than their U.S. counterparts.
</P>
<P>
   Heath and other Internet authorities were called together by the
White House to discuss Y2K's impact on the Internet. With
electronic commerce and messaging now so vital to the economy, the
Clinton administration wants to avoid problems caused by the
software programming flaw, widely known as the Y2K bug. The flaw
may cause many older computers to misunderstand dates beyond Dec.
31, 1999, leading to widespread equipment malfunctions.
</P>
<P>
   Because the Internet is a collection of mostly independent
computer networks, operated worldwide and largely without
government supervision, information about Y2K preparations has been
difficult to gather. The President's Council convened a meeting of
Internet experts July 30 to better assess the problems. Tuesday's
press conference summarized their findings. Among the key points
were:
</P>
<P>
   -- While some elements of the Internet, such as routers and
switches, could be unprepared for the date change, the network's
key ''backbone'' components have been updated and tested.
</P>
<P>
   -- The Internet has so many thousands of local service providers
that some problems are bound to occur. That means some Internet
users who depend on the Internet for communication or commerce
should be prepared with contingency plans in case they lose service
for hours, or even days, after Jan. 1.
</P>
<P>
   -- Y2K problems will have little impact on on-line stock trading
because major markets will be closed at midnight Jan. 1. Computer
programmers will have a full weekend to patch problems before
markets open on the first Monday of the new year.
</P>
<P>
   -- The threat from computer viruses will not be increased by Y2K
bugs. But electronic terrorists who want to cause trouble might
target Jan. 1 to get extra attention. Whether New Year's Day will
generate an epidemic of new viruses is ``more of a human question
than a technological question,'' Heath said.
</P>
<P>
   -- Mass e-mailings of New Year's greetings Jan. 1 could clog the
network, just as any huge sudden surge in messaging might do, with
or without Y2K bugs.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-08-17-99 1550EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-18-99 1331EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
