<DOCNO> NYT19990818.0094 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-18 13:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1491 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-ONJOBS-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      08-18 1079
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONJOBS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FACING DOWN THE THREATS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE E. LEWIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Engineer Anita W. had every reason to be scared: A male
subordinate had threatened her for giving him a negative
evaluation.
</P>
<P>
   Over the next few months, the worker's intimidating behavior
escalated. He used foul language, elbowed Anita, struck her on the
arm, and said he had thought about shooting another supervisor.
</P>
<P>
   Weeks after she reported the incidents to management, Anita
resigned. Three months after that, she filed a lawsuit against her
former employer alleging, among other things, failure to ensure a
safe work environment and negligent hiring, supervision, and
retention.
</P>
<P>
   Increasingly, US workers are holding employers accountable for
violent acts in the workplace, and for hiring threatening or
violent employees, says Mark Braverman, author of a book about
workplace rage that discusses Anita's case.
</P>
<P>
   ``There have been numerous cases where companies, in stumbling
over how to solve a problem and in not having the right tools,
wound up being charged by their own employees,'' Braverman said.
</P>
<P>
   Last spring, the families of two men who were killed when a
laid-off worker went on a rampage were awarded $7.9 million in
damages after a jury found that the workers' Charlotte, N.C.
employer had not protected them. Two days before the shooting, on
May 17, 1995, the gunman had been fired for a series of violent
acts.
</P>
<P>
   And seven postal employees who were held hostage on Christmas
Eve last year sued the US Postal Service, saying they had failed to
provide a safe work environment. The lawsuit alleges that the
employees had suffered emotional trauma after they were held in a
Denver post office at gunpoint for 10 hours.
</P>
<P>
   Workplace violence continues to top the list of major concerns
among the country's biggest employers, acccording to Pinkerton's,
the international security firm.
</P>
<P>
   And the US Justice Department says that each year, more than 1
million employees are subjected to various forms of violence at
work, including minor assaults (615,000), aggravated assaults
(264,000), and rapes (13,000).
</P>
<P>
   Some behaviors, experts say, are critical signs that a worker is
having difficulty either at work or at home. These signs include
increased reliance on drugs or alcohol, unprovoked outbursts,
suicidal thoughts, increased debt, obsessive physical complaints,
severe mood swings, and empathy for those who commit aggressive or
violent acts.
</P>
<P>
   Braverman, author of ``Preventing Workplace Violence: A Guide
for Employers and Practitioners,'' recommends that employers
consider the following steps to guarding against violence at work:
</P>
<P>
   --Get support from the top. Nothing will be accomplished without
the support of the chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   --Form a team. When Air Products and Chemicals Inc. of
Allentown, Pa., developed its crisis management policy, it included
a requirement that a team be formed consisting of the heads of
security, human resources, the law department, labor relations, and
various company departments. ``Our team meets quarterly,'' said
Larry Piotti, corporate security manager. ``We look at troubling
situations and employees. We decide who should be referred to
counseling. We also train supervisors and managers to recognize and
diffuse aggressive behavior. Separate training sessions are held
for all employees.''
</P>
<P>
   --Hold a workplace violence risk audit. Braverman advises
managers to talk directly to employees about safety and security
issues, to review records for past violent incidents, and to
conduct an internal security check.
</P>
<P>
   --Based on the information gathered, develop policies and
procedures. Then, make sure everyone knows what they are. Define
workplace violence for employees, indicate that there will be no
tolerance for it, specify how incidents should be reported, and
make it clear that employees who make reports will be kept safe.
</P>
<P>
   --Train managers and workers. ``The primary goal of training is
to make sure employees at every level are willing to make a phone
call,'' Braverman said.
</P>
<P>
   An AT&AMP;T spokesman, Burke Stimson, says confronting a troubled
worker and delivering a pink slip are among the most difficult
assignments a supervisor can face. ``It takes a good deal of
self-confidence to ask someone into your office to discuss what you
perceive as emotional troubles,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Stimson said front-line managers and workers often are the first
to recognize workplace problems. ``People in the neighborhood might
say, `Oh, Haskins was a pleasant guy,' but you can bet his
co-workers saw the signs.''
</P>
<P>
   --Give workers access to medical and mental health expertise.
Standard assessments determine whether a person is fit to do his
job. This is different. The goal here is to find out if someone is
dangerous and, if not, to determine the nature of the problem and a
possible solution.
</P>
<P>
   At Air Products and Chemicals, for example, workers have access
to a 24-hour crisis center, and a 1-800 crisis hotline number. The
company, which operates 24 hours a day, seven days a week, says the
system was designed to respond to any incidents that might occur at
night, but is now available around the clock.
</P>
<P>
   --Develop layoff and termination policies.
</P>
<P>
   Braverman notes that most of the calls he receives are from
managers whose firms do not have termination policies or
procedures. As a result, many are afraid confronting a worker will
lead to the violence they fear.
</P>
<P>
   That isn't surprising, said Donald Gibson, a professor at the
Yale School of Management. ``Much of the anger people are
expressing is associated with the feeling that the employer has
violated promises that had been made.''
</P>
<P>
   Gibson, coauthor of a 1996 Gallup workplace violence study,
presented this month at the Academy of Management in Chicago, said
that nearly 25 percent of the 1,000 people surveyed said they often
felt angry at work.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we questioned people, we found that there was a sense of
feeling betrayed,'' he said. ``And, when we asked whether the
company's values and the employee's values were similar, many said
no. So the anger is associated with the feeling that the company
has let them down. These feelings of anger or rage are also linked
to feeling stressed, overworked, or stuck in one door, with no
alternatives.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Contact Diane E. Lewis at work(at)globe.com, or 617-929-2069.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
