<SLUG> BC-CPT-ACCESS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
 Tech Heavy Hitters Join Open-Access Fray  
 By Deborah Solomon   
 c. 1999 San Francisco Chronicle   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Some of the biggest names in the high-tech industry are coming
out in support of AT&AMP;T and ExciteAtHome in the fight over ``open
access.''
</P>
<P>
   The Information Technology Industry Council, which includes
heavy hitters such as Cisco Systems, Apple, 3Com and Intel, sent a
letter to the Federal Communications Commission, saying it favors a
national policy that would not force AT&AMP;T to open its cable TV
lines to competitors.
</P>
<P>
   Today, some additional technology companies, such as General
Instrument, WebMD and Broadcom, also plan to ask the FCC to avoid
imposing open access.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T and Redwood City's ExciteAtHome are locked in a fierce
battle with America Online and other Internet service providers
over who should control AT&AMP;T's cable TV lines. The ISPs and some
consumer groups want the government to force AT&AMP;T to lease space on
its wires to other companies that want to offer high-speed Internet
service via cable TV lines.
</P>
<P>
   Several cities, including San Francisco, have been debating
whether to impose ``open access'' as a condition of approving
AT&AMP;T's purchase of TCI and MediaOne. So far, just Portland, Ore.,
and Broward County, Fla., have approved open access, while San
Francisco decided to delay a decision until December.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T and ExciteAtHome have asked the FCC to intervene and set a
national policy _ one that opposes open access. The companies argue
that local municipalities don't have the right to impose open
access and say that forcing AT&AMP;T to open its cable TV lines will
delay the development of new technology.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T has been trying to drum up support for its position since
June, when a federal judge in Portland ruled that city officials
could force AT&AMP;T to share space on its cable lines.
</P>
<P>
   The decision is now on appeal at the U.S. Court of Appeals in
San Francisco, which will hold hearings in October. Meanwhile, the
parties involved have been filing ``friend of the court'' briefs in
support or against the Portland ruling.
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday, the FCC filed a brief in support of AT&AMP;T's position.
ExciteAtHome plans to file a similar brief today, company officials
said.
</P>
<P>
   On the flip side, a coalition of consumer groups sent a letter
to the FCC several weeks ago, saying that consumers would benefit
from open access because they could get high-speed Internet service
from a number of providers, not just AT&AMP;T.
</P>
<P>
   In its letter to the FCC, Information Technology Industry
Council President Rhett Dawson said regulators should not impose
restrictions on companies that want to offer high-speed Internet
service.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because cable Internet access is an emerging service and the
providers currently lack market power in the Internet access
market, they should not be subject at this time to open network
requirements,'' the letter said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &LR;
</P>
