<HEADER>
A1495 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-BANKING-COMMERCE-ART-     08-18 1760
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BANKING-COMMERCE-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMERCE: MOVING FROM MINORITY TO MAINSTREAM 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNNLEY BROWNING  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Nestled in a stately building in Dudley Square, the
Boston Bank of Commerce is an emblem of the struggle by
minority-owned financial institutions to survive in the
ever-shifting world of banking.
</P>
<P>
   Competition is everywhere _ established banks, criticized for
shunning poor urban neighborhoods, are now opening branches in
inner-city communities. Technology is changing old ways of doing
business. And consumers are more demanding than ever.
</P>
<P>
   But New England's only black-owned bank is not sitting still. At
its modern downtown headquarters, the company is putting the
finishing touches on a bold plan to expand at warp speed. Under
chairman Kevin Cohee, the Boston Bank of Commerce is looking to
grow its assets eightfold by acquiring up to 18 branches that Fleet
Financial Group and BankBoston, the region's two biggest banks, are
selling as part of their $16 billion merger.
</P>
<P>
   Cohee is also attempting to take over the struggling Carver
Federal Savings Bank in New York, the nation's largest black-owned
bank. Carver, which wants to remain rooted in Harlem rather than
build a national franchise, has twice rebuffed his overtures.
Undaunted, Cohee is trying to garner support from other
shareholders to win a seat on Carver's board.
</P>
<P>
   As if all that weren't a big enough challenge, Cohee is also
eyeing a Florida bank.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will be the biggest black bank in America,'' Cohee said
recently in his executive suite, where the atmosphere seemed to
pulse with empire-building plans. ``The goal is to take our model
and to expand it on a nationwide basis.''
</P>
<P>
   It will not be easy.
</P>
<P>
   Some observers see a basic contradiction between the bank's
national ambitions and the community focus that has kept it rooted
in Boston's minority neighborhoods. Others see a more fundamental
problem: Cohee may be taking on too much, too fast. Indeed, for a
bank that barely a year ago shuttered one of its three branches to
save money, the proposed expansion is gargantuan. Cohee is also
squaring off against competitors eager to acquire the same branches
from the Fleet-BankBoston deal. And he must raise of hundreds of
millions of dollars to finance his plans.
</P>
<P>
   He could find out as early as next week if he has won any
branches. Some in Boston financial circles say he will get a
fraction of what he wants _ if anything at all.
</P>
<P>
   But Cohee, a former Salomon Brothers investment banker, and the
only banker in New England who can match Fleet chief executive
Terrence Murray's bulldog opportunism, is convinced his plan can
work.
</P>
<P>
   Four years after he took over a dying Boston Bank of Commerce
and restored it to health, Cohee has made it among America's
most-watched minority banks _ and a barometer of what the future
for black-owned financial institutions may look like.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boston Bank of Commerce is a test case in American banking,''
said Dina Nichelson, president of the American League of Financial
Institutions, a trade group for minority-owned thrifts. ``The
question is whether his vision of an expanded bank will be
supported by the community _ and by the economy.''
</P>
<P>
   The privately held bank is one of the nation's half-dozen
``community financial development institutions'' _ small banks,
usually minority-owned, that offer traditional checking and savings
but that also finance projects in low-income neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   The bank has had a part in many local projects _ in Roxbury, it
has helped finance the construction of People's Baptist Church, New
Covenant Church, and Muhammad's Mosque. Since mid-1998, Cohee has
spent more than $15 million on inner-city nonprofits and
businesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``The world is changing,'' he said. ``And we have to make sure
that back at the ranch, somebody is serving these communities.''
</P>
<P>
   Financing and lending to minorities is an especially charged
issue in Boston, the birthplace of banking more than two centuries
ago and the locus of a patrician financial industry. In 1991, a
landmark Federal Reserve study found that local banks were engaging
in some of the nation's worst discrimination against black home
borrowers.
</P>
<P>
   That history, combined with questions over whether Fleet and
BankBoston will pull back from inner cities after they merge, makes
it especially important to community activists and others that
Boston Bank of Commerce flourish.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bank is important and symbolic because it has managed to
carve out a niche for itself and for the community it serves _ a
niche that nobody wanted,'' said state Representative Dianne
Wilkerson, a Roxbury Democrat. `And they have made it work.''
</P>
<P>
   Now Cohee, 41, must convince investors that his proposal to buy
up to $650 million in deposits from Fleet will work. The New York
investment bank Cohee hired to help with his bid, Sandler O'Neill,
is scrambling to gain financing from minority venture capitalists
and banks on Wall Street. One potential supporter, BankBoston, has
balked, wary of the conflict of interest in being the co-seller of
the branches Cohee covets, even though the branches technically
belong to Fleet. Although it has invested around $2 million in
Cohee's bank, BankBoston is loath to bolster an institution that
seeks to compete with its own inner-city branches.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has been very aggressive in generating political support
for his bid,'' said one lawyer who requested anonymity, referring
to backing that Cohee secured from Massachusetts legislators and
the Rev. Al Sharpton. ``But he may be overreaching and trying to
bite off more than he can chew.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the hurdles, Cohee's proposed leap is what makes Boston
Bank of Commerce a standout among the nation's 180 minority banks.
``What makes them unique is their risk-taking posture,'' said
William Cunningham, president of Creative Investment Research, a
Washington, D.C., firm that tracks minority and women-owned banks.
``Traditional black bankers have not had that mindset.''
</P>
<P>
   And for good cause.
</P>
<P>
   Black-owned banks first emerged in response to Jim Crow laws and
multiplied during the 1960s civil rights movement. Chronically
short of capital, many have spent their lives seeking not to expand
but merely to hang on. Even Carver, the largest minority-owned
bank, has only two-thirds of the $600 million in assets held by the
average thrift. At $107 million in assets, Cohee's bank is smaller
still. Descended from the Unity Bank &AMP; Trust Co., which was founded
by Roxbury civil rights activists in 1968 but which later
collapsed, Boston Bank of Commerce has had to claw its way back to
life.
</P>
<P>
   Against that backdrop, Fleet's and BankBoston's sale of 290
branches with $12.5 billion in deposits is a once-in-a-lifetime
chance.
</P>
<P>
   A Harvard Law School graduate, Cohee has an aggressive style.
``He basically retained that Salomon attitude of, `We're going to
be bigger, badder, and better than everybody else,' '' Creative
Investment Research's Cunningham said.
</P>
<P>
   It is a trait Cohee showed early in his banking career.
</P>
<P>
   One year after joining Boston Bank of Commerce in 1994, he
staged a palace coup, injecting $1 million of his own money into
the company and kicking out its chief executive, Ronald Homer. At
the time, the bank was drained of reserves and under a
cease-and-desist order from federal regulators. Leveled by years of
soured real estate loans, the company was on its deathbed.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with profits for the second year running after years of
seven-figure losses, Boston Bank of Commerce is back on track. The
bank earned $704,000 last year, and has a return on assets of over
1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The company has stumbled, too.
</P>
<P>
   Its $229,0000 investment in a project with a local minority
development group, Columbia Plaza Associates, to erect the Ruggles
Center building in Roxbury turned sour when the edifice was
discovered to have environmental problems. While the Boston bank's
majority stake in an ambitious Columbia-led plan to build a
37-story skyscraper in the Leather District may fare better, it has
yet to get off the ground.
</P>
<P>
   A second high-profile venture failed to take off. The bank's
Unity credit card, which donates a percentage of its profits to the
United Negro College Fund and other charities, was designed to
appeal to moderate-income and professional blacks. But despite a
boom in consumer spending, the card has attracted only several
thousand holders, according to Teri Williams, the bank's marketing
executive and Cohee's wife. Nonetheless, Cohee said he planned new
Unity-branded products, including debit cards.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is the competition.
</P>
<P>
   On a Friday summer morning, there were only three customers in
Boston Bank of Commerce's quiet Roxbury branch. Loan officers'
desks stood empty.
</P>
<P>
   The branch shares a 19th-century building with Citizens Bank _ a
larger institution, with more services and products. Up the block
is a full-service BankBoston outlet.
</P>
<P>
   Federal law requires all banks to lend to underserved
communities. For areas that until recently had only pricey
check-cashing shops, the changes have been a blessing.
</P>
<P>
   But for minority banks they have been a nightmare. Lacking
capital for on-line banking, mutual funds, mortgage lending, and
financial planning, most minority banks missed the financial
services revolution. ``Fifty years ago, nobody even looked at our
market,'' said Deborah C. Wright, Carver's new president. ``Now
there's no way we can underwrite a mortgage at the same rate these
giant competitors can.''
</P>
<P>
   One result is that many minority banks provide fewer services to
the areas they hope to improve. In 1991, Boston Bank of Commerce
made 101 home loans in the Boston area, according to professor
James Campen, a community reinvestment specialist at the University
of Massachusetts in Boston. Four years later, the number had
dwindled to 14. In the past two years, Campen said, the bank has
not provided a single home loan in the area.
</P>
<P>
   Cohee wants to reverse the pattern.
</P>
<P>
   ``Capital,'' he said. ``We need to make acquisitions so that we
can have the capital base to expand. African-American communities
can't grow unless we have capital to help them do it. We have to be
viable and strong, and we have to be extraordinarily good at what
we do. Because a lot of people are depending on us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-18-99 1333EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
