<HEADLINE>
ENGLISH ACTIVIST MONITORS CRA RESULTS IN BOSTON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Pat Mallon came to Boston last week to learn about the Community
Reinvestment Act, the law that requires banks to make loans in
low-income neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   It's too bad Senator Phil Gramm couldn't have come along. Gramm,
the Texas Republican who is doing his best to gut the law, might
have learned a thing or two about CRA, and why, for all its flaws,
it is worth preserving.
</P>
<P>
   Pat Mallon is an activist in her native England.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm from Liverpool,'' she said, when she introduced herself.
``It's where the Beatles are from.'' A tiny woman of 61, with big
gold loop earrings, Mallon got involved in banking issues two years
ago when Lloyd TS Group, a big British bank, decided to close its
branch in her working-class neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   Another big bank had previously pulled out, and the neighborhood
was about to be left with just a single bank branch.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would have been a great inconvenience, especially for older
people,'' said Mallon who, on her own, organized a petition drive
to keep the bank from closing.
</P>
<P>
   She got 4,000 signatures, delivered them to the bank's
headquarters in London, and won at least a temporary stay of
execution for the branch. ``Pat Saves Bank: Gran wins reprieve for
local branch,'' read the headline in the Liverpool Echo, a tabloid
newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   The British Broadcasting Corporation heard about Mallon's
exploits and decided it would make a good story to bring her to
America to see how city neighborhoods fare in a country where banks
are legally required to invest there. Britain has no equivalent of
the CRA law.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Britain, low-income customers are viewed as a nuisance,''
said Paul Charles, one of two BBC reporters who came last week.
</P>
<P>
   The reporters picked Boston, specifically BankBoston, after
surfing the Internet and discovering that the bank has a good track
record of urban investment.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't your usual tour of Boston. No Freedom Trail or Fenway
Park. Mallon and the two reporters drove through Roxbury and
Dorchester, and heard about the progress the neighborhoods have
made with the help of bank lending. All of Boston's major banks
have beefed up their central city investments, particularly home
mortgage lending.
</P>
<P>
   At lunchtime the group gathered at BankBoston's Codman Square
branch for a discussion about banks and poor neighborhoods. The
issue is of concern on both sides of the Atlantic.
</P>
<P>
   In the United Kingdom, Prime Minister Tony Blair has focused
attention on the plight of the ``socially excluded'' _ British for
poor _ and he wants the private sector to do something about it.
``Social exclusion can only be overcome with the help of business
which has abandoned many inner-city areas,'' said Blair in a recent
speech.
</P>
<P>
   The banks in England have a presence in low-income areas, but it
has been shrinking. According to Mallon, customers have been put
off by high fees and complicated rules that make many people
ineligible to have bank accounts.
</P>
<P>
   In England, as here, the banks, looking to cut costs, want
customers to do business over the Internet and the phone rather
than in traditional branches. Mallon made it clear that she and her
friends don't have computers and aren't comfortable banking by
phone. For them, the bank branch is vital to the health of the
whole community.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without the banks, the whole area would go; it would be a
ghost town,'' she said of her Liverpool neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   In Boston, there are bank branches sprinkled throughout the
city. In part, that is because of CRA. Under pressure from both the
law and community activists, the local banks made a commitment to
the neighborhoods that continues to this day. The banks went in
grudgingly, but along the way they made a discovery: They could
actually make a buck in low-income neighborhoods on everything from
mortgages to mutual funds.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Callahan said CRA was critical to the process.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without it, the banks would have continued to ignore the
opportunities in these neighborhoods,'' said Callahan, head of the
Massachusetts Affordable Housing Alliance.
</P>
<P>
   The banks have learned to live with CRA. But not Phil Gramm. The
program sticks in his conservative craw. Gramm says the law
``collectivizes the American financial market,'' and is a
government scheme to redistribute wealth. He also argues that
community groups have used the law to extract ``outright bribes''
from banks that need regulatory approval for mergers.
</P>
<P>
   Gramm has a point there. Activists sometimes have used CRA to
extort money from banks. But, on balance, the law has done more
good than harm. It has helped bring poor neighborhoods into the
economic mainstream and minimized the ``social exclusion'' some
city dwellers might otherwise feel. Sometimes the free market needs
a push in the right direction. CRA has provided that shove.
</P>
<P>
   Pat Mallon seemed to agree. There are cultural differences
between England and America, she said, but the notion that banks
should be required to invest in urban neighborhoods makes sense in
both places.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a good idea,'' said Mallon about the CRA concept. ``It
makes things better for people.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Steven Syre and Charles Stein can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
