<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-18 13:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1510 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-COX-MILLENNIUM-BARNST     08-18 1771
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COX-MILLENNIUM-BARNSTABLE22 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CHRISTIANITY AT 2000: Pilgrim church has changed, but principles
remain
 &HT;    Eds: This is the third installment in Cox News Service's
Millennium series, Christianity at 2000. The first installment, in
January, focused on the birth of Christianity nearly 2,000 years
ago. The second installment looked at the spread of Christianity
through Europe. This third installment looks at Christianity in the
New World. (Followup stories to this installment will move for the
weekend of Aug. 29.) The fourth installment, due at Christmas, will
look at Christianity's future.
 &HT;    This package includes photos and the following stories, all of
which are embargoed until Sunday, Aug. 22: MILLENNIUM-NEWWORLD,
-BARNSTABLE, -CATHOLIC, -BLACK and -PROFILES. This package will be
the CoxNet Focus page for this weekend. It will be available to
non-Cox papers (for a $20 download fee) by 5 p.m. Friday at
www.nytsyn.com/pageexpress.
 &HT;    Stories are moving in National and Lifestyle categories.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By Bob Dart
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST BARNSTABLE, Mass. _ From the high pulpit, the Rev. Reed
Baer gazes down upon a congregation with a lineage beginning before
the Pilgrims landed.
</P>
<P>
   From the hard wooden benches and ancient family pews known as
``sheep pens,'' the West Parish flock listens to Baer's challenge
to ``live up to the vision of our founders.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You get a very personal feeling in this old church. The way
it's laid out. The sense that the congregation is a caring
community. The connection to history,'' observes Gary Morris, a
young businessman sitting near the back with his wife, Meg, and
their infant son, Ian. ``You can't help thinking back to a time
when church was a much bigger part of people's lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Such are Sundays in the oldest continuously operating
Congregational Church in America, where the Sabbath is heralded by
the pealing of a bell made by Paul Revere.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1717, worshippers have assembled in this steepled, wooden
meeting house on Cape Cod. The congregation traces its roots back a
century more, however, to a group of religious reformers led by
Henry Jacob. These so-called Separatists first met secretly outside
London in 1616, four years before the Pilgrims came to the New
World and settled in nearby Plymouth.
</P>
<P>
   Henry Jacob called his new church ``Congregational.'' While
Puritans wanted to reform or ``purify'' the Church of England,
Separatists wanted to break away completely. Believing that each
congregation could perform all church functions and choose its own
leaders, the Congregationalists were among the Separatists.
</P>
<P>
   Eight years after Jacob died in 1624, about 30 of his followers
came to Massachusetts with their new pastor, the Rev. John Lothrop.
Lothrop led the Congregationalists to found Barnstable in 1639. The
settlement grew and divided into East and West Parishes as the
1700s began. The West Parish Meeting House opened its doors in
1717.
</P>
<P>
   Much has changed in this historic church. The ``tithingman'' no
longer sits beneath the high pulpit wielding a long pole with a
feather on one end and an iron ball on the other. If a man dozed
off during the service, the tithingman would rap his head with the
ball. A sleepy woman would be tickled under the nose with the
feather.
</P>
<P>
   Sermons lasted two hours back then, pointed out Baer, compared
to about 15 minutes nowadays.
</P>
<P>
   Before joining West Parish, pioneer members had to credibly
testify to their redemption. Testimony of a conversion experience
is no longer required. The ``sheep pens'' are no longer deeded to
prominent families; anyone can sit in these family pews. While
early members sang psalms without musical instruments, today's
congregation is accompanied on hymns by a pipe organ.
</P>
<P>
   However, the church clings to a heritage of independence. West
Parish still has its own covenant, promising not only ``to walk
together in Christian love'' but also to ``forswear all pettiness,
gossip and slander,'' and members agree to abide by its rules.
</P>
<P>
   Church leaders are still elected. Before being hired about a
year ago, Baer was required to preach a trial sermon and then leave
the church while the congregation voted.
</P>
<P>
   Approval was unanimous.
</P>
<P>
   Who's in the pews
</P>
<P>
   The parish has about 280 members, plus 110 children who aren't
counted until their confirmation in about the ninth grade.
</P>
<P>
   ``People come for many different reasons,'' Baer said. Some are
following a family tradition. Others are on a spiritual search.
Many come for their children, he said. They grew up in the church,
drifted away as young adults, then returned to give their offspring
the same religious grounding their parents gave them.
</P>
<P>
   ``A precious few come for the preaching,'' the minister said
with a smile.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps personifying how the Lord works in mysterious ways, the
reverend himself took a roundabout route to the pulpit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a recovering lawyer,'' he explained. ``This is my first
church.''
</P>
<P>
   A practicing attorney for 12 years near Boston, Baer was a
deacon and Sunday school teacher in a Congregational church and the
father of two young children when his wife was diagnosed with
breast cancer. The crisis caused both to examine their lives.
</P>
<P>
   After considering teaching, ``I began to realize that I was
called to the ordained ministry,'' Baer said. ``I believe there is
more need in the world for my work in the church than there was for
my work as a lawyer. It seems there are plenty of lawyers to make
the world go around.''
</P>
<P>
   After his wife died, he graduated from theological school. He
has since remarried, and his second wife had a son several weeks
ago.
</P>
<P>
   At the urging of a visitor, he reflected on history and religion
in this historic community he now calls home.
</P>
<P>
   ``The early Separatists and Puritans viewed themselves as living
in exile, as conducting an experiment in the wilderness _ which it
was, literally,'' he explained. ``Some would view the church today
as also in a time of exile. We are no longer in a churched society.
While as recently as the '50s, being a church member was part and
parcel of the American experience, today church is increasingly an
option that many in our society don't take up.
</P>
<P>
   ``The church no longer has the power and influence it once
wielded,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Wide-ranging beliefs
</P>
<P>
   On page 365 of the Pilgrim Hymnal is the song ``Faith of Our
Fathers,'' with its stirring chorus, ``Faith of our fathers, Holy
Faith. We will be true to thee 'til death.''
</P>
<P>
   But the founding fathers of West Parish might be surprised at
the wide-ranging faith of their spiritual heirs on Meeting House
Way.
</P>
<P>
   ``Worship doesn't have to be pious _ as long as you believe in
the basics,'' said Faith Chapman, who defined the basics as belief
in Jesus Christ as Savior. ``God is either male or female, if we
are created in God's image.''
</P>
<P>
   Faith Chapman and her husband, Sid, are a retired couple from
Connecticut and have attended church regularly since their marriage
in 1955. They like the liberal leanings of Congregational theology.
</P>
<P>
   So does Meg Morris, who was raised a Catholic but grew to
dislike the religion's formality and structure and rules regarding
women. During their courtship, she and Gary often rode a tandem
bicycle past the historic church while training for a race. They
decided to wed there and continued to attend services after the
ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now I look forward to Sundays,'' Meg said. ``And for our son,
I think it's important that he grow up with that connection with
church and God and for him to enjoy it.''
</P>
<P>
   Victor Diamond grew up Jewish, and says he still ``doesn't
believe in Jesus the way others in the congregation do.''
</P>
<P>
   While describing himself as ``not the most religious person in
the world,'' the young dentist said it's important that his
children grow up with values and spirituality.
</P>
<P>
   ``I go to church for the family time together,'' he said. ``And
I enjoy the sermons.''
</P>
<P>
   His wife, Trisha, was raised as a Lutheran. She said she came to
West Parish after seeing other Cape Cod churches spurn a young
woman who was eight months pregnant with twins and wanted to stand
before an altar to marry the father. West Parish did not spurn
them, and the couple were wed in the historic Congregational
meeting house.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't turn sinners away,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has always been a caring church _ a friendly church _
regardless of who ministers it,'' said Jane Clingham, who has been
a member for 21 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Each minister comes in and cooperates with the congregation,
but each has his own ideas and goals, too,'' said Silja Emrich, who
joined West Parish in 1957. ``Each leaves his own mark, and with
each we've learned and grown.''
</P>
<P>
   Guided by a covenant
</P>
<P>
   Instead of a cross, a gilded rooster on a weather vane sits atop
the steeple of the West Parish Meeting House. Brought over from
England in 1723, the rooster is a symbol dating back to the Last
Supper, according to parish historian Bob Russell.
</P>
<P>
   When Jesus told his disciples that they would soon desert him,
Peter protested. Jesus said, ``Truly I tell you, this very night
before the cock crows thrice, you will deny me three times.'' When
the prediction came to pass, Peter heard a cock crow and broke down
and wept.
</P>
<P>
   Ever since, Russell explained, the crowing rooster has been a
reminder for Christians to stand up for Jesus.
</P>
<P>
   Like the crowing rooster, the covenant has been part of West
Parish longer than any current member can recall. Although
associated with the United Church of Christ, each Congregational
parish has its own such set of rules.
</P>
<P>
   The covenant provides clues to what the congregation was
concerned about at the time of adoption, Baer said. West Parish
decided ``pettiness, gossip and slander'' were of such magnitude
that the covenant should require members to agree to give up such
actions ``in our dealings with one another and with all people.''
</P>
<P>
   It is unclear exactly when this covenant was adopted, Baer said,
and time may be nearing for the congregation to consider revisions.
</P>
<P>
   It is a process even older than this historic meeting house,
dating back to Henry Jacob, who decreed Congregational churches are
constituted ``by a free mutual consent of believers joining and
covenanting to live as members of a holy society together in all
religious and virtuous duties as Christ and his Apostles did
institute and practice in the Gospel.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Dart writes for the Washington bureau of Cox News Service.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
