<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-18 13:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1517 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-BOOK-LIFE-BOS &LR;      08-18 0757
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-LIFE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RECONCILIATION FOUND AFTER `LIFE' OF TURMOIL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID MEHEGAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
MORE THAN ONE LIFE 
By Miloslava Holubova (translated, from the Czech, by Alex Zucker
with Lyn Coffin and Zdenka Brodska) 
Hydra/Northwestern University Press, 104 pp., $22.95 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   This poignant novel of a family dogged by silence and longing
cannot help recalling Tolstoy's sentence that ``all happy families
are alike, but every unhappy family is unhappy in its own way.''
Expressed happiness can be hard to understand, but unhappiness that
is unclear to the one who suffers it, and who cannot express it to
those close to him, can have the most far-reaching and
unpredictable effects.
</P>
<P>
   The female narrator is one of four children of a prosperous
Prague businessman and his wife in the 1920s and '30s. On the
surface, all appears to be well, but it becomes clear that the
father, called only Dad, is bitterly unhappy. He is given to rages
over small provocations or imagined slights, is convinced his wife
and children do not love him, and in raging about these grievances
manages, tragically, to make them come true. His children are
afraid of the perpetual stormy atmosphere and so avoid their
father.
</P>
<P>
   ``For how long were Dad's screaming accusations, his demands for
love and respect, nothing but an annoying burden? Dad and the
burden were so tightly intertwined, it was impossible for us to
shed the burden without shunting him aside as well.'' The
atmosphere at home is poisonous. In the mid-1930s, the father has a
brief fling with a much younger woman, then demands a divorce from
his wife. Overnight, the family disintegrates. Soon after, the
father attempts suicide and fails.
</P>
<P>
   After the communist takeover in 1948, the mother emigrates to
England with one of the grown children and eventually dies there,
while the father is seen in Prague, lonely and disengaged, until
he, too, dies in 1955.
</P>
<P>
   There is little action in this book, published in the Czech
Republic in 1994 by Miloslava Holubova, one of the literary
activists in the Prague Spring that ended with the Russian invasion
of 1968. We never learn exactly what the father's problem is. We
infer that the mother is cold and distant, but we do not see it. It
seems that the father is passionate and affectionate and needy, and
the very outpouring of his need ends up driving away those he loves
the most.
</P>
<P>
   However, though the father is the main character, the driving
emotion of the story is the desperate need of the daughter to
forgive him for his behavior and herself for her alienation, as a
child and adult, from him. The story is structured around her
meeting a gentle elderly man, whom she calls ``Eldergent,'' who is
interested in her story; he becomes the listener who allows her to
pour it out.
</P>
<P>
   The essence of her story is that children cannot grow up fully
until they can understand and forgive their parents _ whether such
forgiveness is earned or not. ``And did it bother us that he lived
in hell?'' the narrator writes. ``Not really. We were amazingly
good at not thinking about it.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the daughter finds the peace she seeks. Just before
the Soviet invasion, one of her brothers, who lives in Canada,
writes to say he is coming home for a visit. He wants the four of
them, now in their 50s, to carry out, 12 years after their father's
death, his wish that his ashes be scattered on scenic Blue
Mountain, where the family held outings when the children were
small.
</P>
<P>
   In carrying out out this rite, the four find the reconciliation
they long for. The narrator writes, ``At last Mojmir (one of her
brothers) said it for all of us: `I'm glad that Dad brought us
here,' and by here we all knew that he meant more than just the
place.'' She reflects, ``Sometimes change happens one step at a
time, sometimes by leaps and bounds. And each new insight springs
the lock on a secret door opening into a new, brighter space,
rinsed clean by the rain.''
</P>
<P>
   Reading this story, and seeing this tempestuous character at its
center, it is hard to see why the adult narrator would feel any
guilt, in retrospect, about her and her siblings' treatment of
their father _ such a man, we think, would drive anyone away. Yet
one cannot choose one's parents, and the need to understand why
they behaved as they did, what demons tormented them, is part of
finding the serenity and courage to be a parent oneself. In this
respect, even unhappy families are somehow alike.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
