u a BC-COX-MILLENNIUM-NEWWOR     08-18 2655
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COX-MILLENNIUM-NEWWORLD22 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CHRISTIANITY AT 2000: Shaping, and shaped by, America
 &HT;    Eds: This is the third installment in Cox News Service's
Millennium series, Christianity at 2000. The first installment, in
January, focused on the birth of Christianity nearly 2,000 years
ago. The second installment looked at the spread of Christianity
through Europe. This third installment looks at Christianity in the
New World. (Followup stories to this installment will move for the
weekend of Aug. 29.) The fourth installment, due at Christmas, will
look at Christianity's future.
 &HT;    This package includes photos and the following stories, all of
which are embargoed until Sunday, Aug. 22: MILLENNIUM-NEWWORLD,
-BARNSTABLE, -CATHOLIC, -BLACK and -PROFILES. This package will be
the CoxNet Focus page for this weekend. It will be available to
non-Cox papers (for a $20 download fee) by 5 p.m. Friday at
www.nytsyn.com/pageexpress.
 &HT;    Stories are moving in National and Lifestyle categories.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By Gayle White
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ On a Sunday in downtown Atlanta, weekday traffic
congestion is mercifully absent. Office buildings are shut down
tight, stores are closed and the sidewalks are not crowded with
visitors. But there is plenty of life in some of the city's oldest
churches.
</P>
<P>
   At Central Presbyterian Church across from the state Capitol,
tables are set with white tablecloths and red napkins for the
old-fashioned Sunday dinner the church has hosted since many of its
middle-aged members were children. Next door, at the Shrine of the
Immaculate Conception, a priest will offer food of a different kind
as he prepares the bread and wine of the Eucharist that Catholics
consider the body and blood of Christ. And, around the corner at
Trinity United Methodist, adults are gathered in Sunday School to
share their stories with their new minister, the Rev. Cornelius
Minor, assigned to the church just this summer.
</P>
<P>
   A few blocks away on Auburn Avenue, a sign in front of Big
Bethel African Methodist Episcopal Church apologizes for
construction: ``Please Pardon Our Progress.'' At historic Wheat
Street Baptist Church, young Jasmine Garrett is being baptized into
the fold. ``My dear sister,'' the Rev. Michael Harris calls her as
he pushes her under water in the name of the Father, Son and Holy
Ghost. Across Auburn Avenue in the new sunlight-filled Ebenezer
Baptist Church, Atlanta's church of Kings, the Rev. Mary Finley is
praising God, proclaiming, ``Church, this is the day that the Lord
has made. We should rejoice and be glad in it!''
</P>
<P>
   Some of these houses of worship have seen the town once called
Terminus through Civil War and Civil Rights, through booming growth
and urban decline. But they are only a handful of almost 2,000
churches scattered across metro Atlanta from Buford to Brooks.
Those, in turn, are a tiny sampling of more than 250,000 Christian
congregations in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   From the simplest clapboard cabin where unaccompanied voices are
raised in hymns hundreds of years old, to the most modern
mega-church with its orchestra and drama troupe, Christian
congregations are part of the warp and weft of America's history
and culture.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond their buildings are a network of clinics and hospitals,
schools and universities, soup kitchens and homeless shelters
operated in the name of Jesus, the Nazarene man born some 2,000
years ago whom Christians regard as the messiah.
</P>
<P>
   His American followers have created powerful lobbying groups in
Washington and in state houses across the country where they are
part of the establishment and the anti-establishment on issues from
race relations to labor law to medical research. Since colonial
days, Christian people and churches have played significant roles
in the good, bad and ugly of American history _ they have preached
slavery and abolition, segregation and integration, war and peace,
social reform and the status quo.
</P>
<P>
   Christian voices have produced the literature, theater, art and
music of their country _ from Southern Catholic Flannery O'Connor's
writings to the singing style of rock 'n' roll's King, Elvis
Presley, whose feet were firmly planted in gospel music. Phrases
from the Christian scriptures, such as ``prodigal son'' and ``good
Samaritan'' have become common usage.
</P>
<P>
   Even the names of many of America's children _ Mary and Matthew
and Mark _ are from the Christian gospels. And the best known of
modern-era American reformers _ Martin Luther King Jr. _ is the
namesake of an earlier Christian reformer.
</P>
<P>
   But as American culture has changed, so has American
Christianity. The oldest groups _ the Episcopalians and
Presbyterians, for instance _ have influence that exceeds their
numbers, while conservative Christians, under the label
``evangelical'' have set up not only powerful churches but a
parallel culture. They have borrowed some elements from the
American-born Pentecostal movement, an exuberant form of
Christianity that accepts such practices as speaking in unknown
tongues and which, from its beginnings a century ago, has become
the fastest-growing form of Christianity around the world.
</P>
<P>
   Worshipers entering a modern evangelical or Pentecostal church
are likely to hear tunes that could come from rock and country
radio stations. At home, they can watch sweaty preachers behind
plexiglass pulpits speaking to a television audience of millions.
Or, in their cars they can opt for Christian music, Christian talk
radio or even the daily news from a Christian point of view. They
can subscribe to Christian newspapers and Christian magazines, shop
for Christian greeting cards and gifts at Christian stores, and
wear T-shirts and baseball caps with Christian slogans to Christian
concerts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there's any question that it's a two-way
street,'' said Erskine Clarke, professor of American religious
history at Columbia Theological Seminary, an institution of the
Presbyterian Church (U.S.A.) in Decatur. ``On the one hand, it
would be very difficult to understand traditional American values
and institutions apart from western Christianity ... On the other
hand, Christianity in this country is, in many ways, distinctly
North American.''
</P>
<P>
   It has not, however, remained in North America. An unprecedented
missionary force, followed by international broadcasts, have taken
Christianity, American style, around the world, imprinting
proselytes with a faith filled with Western cultural icons.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no doubt that Christian missionaries also brought
along western culture,'' said Stephen Gunter, professor of
evangelism at Emory University's Candler School of Theology.
</P>
<P>
   North America's multifaceted brand of Christianity is manifested
in styles as diverse as its beginnings.
</P>
<P>
   Long before the so-called Founding Fathers sailed from Britain,
Spanish Catholic priests traveled into the Southwestern United
States and Florida to convert Native Americans. Others, mostly
French, brought Catholicism down the Mississippi River out of
Canada.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, in 1492 when, as the child's poem goes, Columbus sailed
the ocean blue, he expressed hope in his first diary entry that he
would be able to contact native peoples to ``determine the manner
in which may be undertaken their conversion to our Holy Faith.''
</P>
<P>
   The Catholic presence in America is easily seen in the names of
cities such as St. Augustine, Los Angeles and San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   With the British Colonial movement, Anglicanism came to North
America, bringing the first wave of the Protestantism that was to
dominate American society. In this country's first English
settlement, Jamestown, the Book of Common Prayer was gospel. Within
a few years of the 1607 settlement, law compelled residents to
attend worship services and catechism classes, and imposed a death
penalty _ never really enforced _ for three unexcused absences.
There were also laws against gaming and intemperance.
</P>
<P>
   This stringent approach to Christianity showed shades of the
Puritanism that was soon to come to more northern colonies _
Massachusetts, Connecticut and New Hampshire_as dissenters from
Anglicanism fled England. The Puritans, whose name came from their
desire to purify the church of England from such fancies as liturgy
and clerical robes, in turn exiled people who failed to live up to
their high standards.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, Rhode Island soon became a refuge for Baptists _ but was
still rooted in Puritanism.
</P>
<P>
   Puritans ``set the pace for the religious life of New England,''
wrote Catherine L. Albanese, author of ``America Religions and
Religion.'' They tried to shape government according to what they
saw as Biblical teaching, extending their belief in a
congregation-based structure to a suspicion of federalism in
government. Because of their belief in education, they established
schools, including Harvard and Yale universities.
</P>
<P>
   Puritans were not the only Christian souls seeking religious
freedom to come to North America. They were joined by the new wave
of Roman Catholics who founded Maryland _ and soon faced
discrimination in their own colony, the French Protestant Huguenots
in the Carolinas, Quakers in Pennsylvania, and Protestant sects
from Germany, Holland and Sweden in the Middle Atlantic colonies.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, circuit riders were carrying Methodism to the
farthest corners of the new land, and the American Episcopal church
separated from its English home church soon after the colonies won
their independence from the monarchy.
</P>
<P>
   The dominant segment of American society was the converged
membership of these groups _ ``a quite white, middle class,
mainstream Protestantism,'' said David Hackett, a associate
professor of religion at the University of Florida. ``The influence
has been tremendous and pervasive and long-lasting.''
</P>
<P>
   Hackett credits this generic Protestantism with giving Americans
a strong dose of individualism, which can be traced back to
Reformation doctrine that people are ultimately responsible for
their own relationship with God. He also sees it in the American
impulse to be thrifty and work hard, qualities that have led to a
strong emphasis on capitalism, economic development and
materialism.
</P>
<P>
   Protestants established laws that closed businesses on Sunday,
and set up entertainment standards that today are regarded as
prudish. Married couples on TV in the 1950s and early '60s _ such
as Rob and Laura Petrie on ``The Dick Van Dyke Show'' _ had to
sleep in twin beds; Lucille Ball and Ricky Ricardo had to film the
``I Love Lucy'' episodes about the birth of Little Ricky without
once using the word ``pregnant.''
</P>
<P>
   Although there were other voices _ especially the growing
Catholic church and the socially active black Protestant
denominations _ the one that ruled was ``the dominant voice of the
dominant class,'' Hackett said. ``They stamped the world in their
image.''
</P>
<P>
   A sort of ``secularized Christianity'' or ``residual
Protestantism'' is so much a part of American culture that people
do not even notice it or define it as such, Hackett said. ``It is
part of the air we breathe. We don't see it. It's the way we are.''
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, it may be the absence of state sanction for any one
form of Christianity that has contributed to its pervasiveness and
endurance as an American cultural force.
</P>
<P>
   In this nation's earliest days, its founders realized they had
diverse ideas about church and government, practice and doctrine.
If they were to form a more perfect union, they knew there could be
no established church.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, when the Bill of Rights was written for the new
Constitution, it expressly forbade government enforcement of any
religious belief. But it also clearly guaranteed the right to
follow one's faith without government interference.
</P>
<P>
   The result was a free market and an aggressive effort among some
quarters to proselytize, adding to the numbers and the coffers of
churches.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a church couldn't get a congregation to support it, it
simply withered on the vine,'' said Edwin Gaustadt, author of
``Religious History of America,'' and professor emeritus of
religion at the University of California, Riverside. ``Many people
thought that was a mistake. In the long view of history, it has
worked much better for the United States than the system in
European nations where churches continued to have state support.''
</P>
<P>
   That lack of security gave American Christianity a need for
renewal and revival. Great revival movements have spawned new
fervor and some new forms of Christianity, including modern-day
Pentecostalism.
</P>
<P>
   Older denominations have split and merged, taking on new names
and modifying their doctrine, powerful African-American
denominations developed, and some new religions evolved, such as
the Christian Scientists, Jehovah's Witnesses and Latter-day
Saints_ all made possible by the free enterprise system of religion
in America. And waves of new immigrants have made Catholics the
single largest Christian group in the country.
</P>
<P>
   After a lengthy visit to America, Frenchman Alexis de
Tocqueville wrote in 1835, ``There is no country in the world where
the Christian religion retains a greater influence over the souls
of men than in America.'' Many would question whether that holds
true at the end of the millennium.
</P>
<P>
   On paper a far larger percentage of Americans are church members
than in the earliest days, when barely one in 10 Americans were
likely to belong to congregations. The main reason for that is not
an increase in religious commitment but a slackening of membership
standards, said Bruce Holifield, professor of American church
history at Emory's Candler School of Theology. Around the time of
the Revolutionary War, church membership involved lengthy training
and questioning, and a willingness to subject oneself to the
discipline of the congregation, he said. Many more people attended
church than joined.
</P>
<P>
   A Gallup poll conducted in May 1999 showed that 71 percent of
those questioned _ who were overwhelmingly Christian _ claimed to
be a member of a church or synagogue, and 44 percent said they
attend almost every week. Studies of actual people in the pews put
that figure lower.
</P>
<P>
   The influence of this country's historically dominant faith has
been diluted in the modern age by differences within Christianity
and increasing numbers of non-Christian immigrants.
</P>
<P>
   ``My guess is that about 20 percent of Americans are diligently
practicing Christians from the 17th century to the present,'' said
Holifield, but they are more diverse in their beliefs and practices
than their ancestors. He predicts that no single religious group in
the future will be able to wield the kind of power the Protestants
did for the nation's first 150 years.
</P>
<P>
   The May Gallup poll shows that many Americans agree. Sixty-two
percent of those questioned said religion as a whole is losing its
influence on American life, compared to 32 percent who felt it was
increasing. At no time since 1957 has a Gallup poll shown that a
majority of Americans believed religion is gaining in influence.
</P>
<P>
   ``By 1999, we are unmistakably and undeniably a pluralistic
nation,'' Gaustadt said. ``We've been one for a long time, but
people could ignore the evidence. I don't think it's possible to
ignore any more.''
</P>
<P>
   Christians continue to influence American culture ``from the
grass roots up _ that is from the local communities and from human
hearts,'' he said, and that is the way faith should exert its
influence.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's probably impossible to separate American culture from its
biblical roots as far as values are concerned,'' Gaustadt said,
``but as far as power structures are concerned, I think it's not
only possible to separate them, but absolutely essential to do
so.''
</P>
<P>
   Gayle White writes for The Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
