<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-18 13:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1520 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-COX-MILLENNIUM-BLACK2     08-18 1754
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COX-MILLENNIUM-BLACK22 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CHRISTIANITY AT 2000: From slavery's chains, a force for
transformation
 &HT;    Eds: This is the third installment in Cox News Service's
Millennium series, Christianity at 2000. The first installment, in
January, focused on the birth of Christianity nearly 2,000 years
ago. The second installment looked at the spread of Christianity
through Europe. This third installment looks at Christianity in the
New World. (Followup stories to this installment will move for the
weekend of Aug. 29.) The fourth installment, due at Christmas, will
look at Christianity's future.
 &HT;    This package includes photos and the following stories, all of
which are embargoed until Sunday, Aug. 22: MILLENNIUM-NEWWORLD,
-BARNSTABLE, -CATHOLIC, -BLACK and -PROFILES. This package will be
the CoxNet Focus page for this weekend. It will be available to
non-Cox papers (for a $20 download fee) by 5 p.m. Friday at
www.nytsyn.com/pageexpress.
 &HT;    Stories are moving in National and Lifestyle categories.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By John Blake
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The view that greets people who drive through Atlanta
at night is dramatic.
</P>
<P>
   A sparkling collection of high-rise office buildings, banks and
hotels greet motorists on the Downtown Connector as the freeway
cuts through the city. The sleek skyline is testimony to Atlanta's
growing power and prestige.
</P>
<P>
   Just before Grady Memorial Hospital stands yet another Atlanta
landmark. But this one is easy to miss. It's a faded, blue neon
sign that declares, ``Jesus Saves.''
</P>
<P>
   The sign, attached to Big Bethel African Methodist Episcopal
Church _ the city's oldest black church _ has offered comfort to
generations of blacks who had little hope of gaining power or
prestige.
</P>
<P>
   It was the church that held them together when racism threatened
to tear them apart.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was that psychiatrist office that you don't have to pay
for,'' said Big Bethel's pastor, the Rev. James Davis. ``It's that
entertainment center that's free. It is everything to a people that
have nothing. Without the black church, we as a people would not be
what we are.''
</P>
<P>
   Nor would America be what it is.
</P>
<P>
   As Christianity approaches the millennium, the black church has
raised its profile. Gospel music blares from movie soundtracks and
McDonald's commercials. Cable television is full of black _ and
white _ preachers delivering sermons filled with the poetic rhythms
of traditional black preaching. Dr. Martin Luther King Jr.,
inextricably linked to the African-American church, has become an
American icon.
</P>
<P>
   But despite this growing recognition, the value of the black
church is still underrated, said Robert Franklin, president of the
Interdenominational Theological Center (ITC), a religious graduate
school based in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Franklin said the black church, by launching the civil rights
movement, inspired liberation struggles in places as diverse and
distant as Central America and China.
</P>
<P>
   ``It helped reposition Christianity not as a religion for the
oppressors and as the ideology for dominant classes,'' Franklin
said. ``It was the black church's reposition of Christianity that
made it more appealing to other Third World people who were very
ambivalent about Christianity's relevance.''
</P>
<P>
   The black church's beginning was bitter, forged in the crucible
of slavery. Scholars estimate that the first black churches were
created in the 1790s when slaves left the segregated pews of white
churches to form their own houses of worship. Big Bethel, first
known as ``Union Church,'' was formed in 1847.
</P>
<P>
   These first black churches offered a brief refuge from slavery,
a place where enslaved blacks could throw themselves into worship _
shouting, stomping, weeping, even collapsing on the floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Given the difficult and dehumanizing nature of their work,
they created a sacred space as a zone of ultimate freedom,''
Franklin writes in ``Another Day's Journey.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Aware that they would soon have to return to the boredom and
dread of field work, slaves threw themselves fully into the worship
experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Toby Sanders, 37, the son of a preacher and a recent graduate of
ITC, said the emotion of the black church restores his soul. Black
church spirituals such as ``His Eyes On The Sparrow,'' he said,
touch him in a way that white hymns do not.
</P>
<P>
   ``Black music is the most evocative and emotional music in the
world,'' Sanders said. ``It's very personal. It's gotten me through
some difficult times.''
</P>
<P>
   The black church has gotten many people through difficult times.
During segregation, Big Bethel became the church for many of
Georgia's first black elected officials, teachers and
entrepreneurs. Morris Brown College, the state's only college
founded by blacks, started in the church's basement.
</P>
<P>
   The church held political rallies, voter registration drives and
graduation ceremonies. Courtship, business connections, political
favors _ all were secured within Big Bethel's walls, said Herman
``Skip'' Mason, an Atlanta historian and ordained minister.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no such thing as the separation of church and state
at Big Bethel,'' Mason said.
</P>
<P>
   Such was the case at most black churches where the mission was
both sacred and secular, transforming lives and society.
</P>
<P>
   Martin Luther King Jr. expressed this vision powerfully in an
article he wrote for the Christian Century magazine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any religion that professes to be concerned about the souls of
men and is not concerned about the slums that damn them, the
economic conditions that strangle them and the social conditions
that cripple them is a spiritually moribund religion awaiting
burial,'' King said.
</P>
<P>
   The civil rights movement that King led could not have existed
without the black church's spiritual inspiration.
</P>
<P>
   ``The South is a very different place than it was 50 years ago
and that's been because of the civil rights movement,'' said Andrew
Billingsley, author of ``Mighty Like a River.'' ``The civil rights
movement was made possible because of the black church. The black
church provided spiritual resources, leadership and places to
meet.''
</P>
<P>
   Big Bethel continues to carry on such a mission today. The
tactics, however, have changed. Forty years ago, blacks wanted to
sit at the front of the bus. Today, they want to learn how to own
the bus company.
</P>
<P>
   Economic empowerment is the magic phrase that black churches are
brandishing now. New problems require new tactics. A march does
little to correct problems such as the growth of single-family
families, the widening gap between the black middle-class and
underclass, and the spread of AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   Big Bethel's Davis said the church is reviving its community
through entrepreneurship. When Davis became pastor in 1992, the
church had not bought property in 40 years. The Auburn Avenue
neighborhood that it stood in was degenerating into a collection of
boarded-up houses, dilapidated businesses and grungy nightclubs.
</P>
<P>
   In the past five years, the church has bought 13 pieces of
property in the area, including a nightclub, a grocery store, and
several small buildings. One structure will house a federally
insured credit union, and the hope is that others will be
transformed into a multi-purpose community center that will handle
everything from day care to job training.
</P>
<P>
   The church sees a divine obligation to remain in the inner city.
</P>
<P>
   ``If everybody is going to run from the valley, we're saying
that the valley is damned,'' Davis said. ``If there's anything
we're saying it's that it's in the valley where ministry should be
developed. That's where you get the best results.''
</P>
<P>
   Other leaders within the black church community have drawn
similar conclusions, deciding it is up to them to revive the black
community. Even conservative scholars think faith-based
institutions offer the best chance of changing the lives of poor,
inner-city blacks.
</P>
<P>
   So outreach programs have become a mainstay of most major black
churches.
</P>
<P>
   New Birth Missionary Baptist Church in Decatur developed a
program that has the church adopting welfare families and providing
them with financial assistance while leading them toward
independence. And Antioch Baptist Church North offers several
innovative programs to reach drug addicts.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, in an effort to place their own houses in order, a
new generation of black pastors is going back to school to earn
business degrees. Some churches, seeking greater economic control
and self reliance, have even hired business experts.
</P>
<P>
   ``The black church has traditionally been a church of volunteers
that work very well on programs like feeding programs and clothing
drives,'' Billingsley said. ``But if you're doing things like
economic community development, ministers have to get technical
assistance.''
</P>
<P>
   The rise in recent years of the black mega-church _ New Birth
Missionary Baptist Church and World Changers are two of the largest
in metro Atlanta _ is creating yet another challenge within the
black community.
</P>
<P>
   More members _ mega-churches have at least 5,000 congregants and
often four times that number _ mean more political power for the
church. But the intimate style of worship that has been a mainstay
within the black church is difficult to hold onto at mega-churches,
some members say.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't really know everybody,'' said Angella Christie, a
member of New Birth, which has 23,000 members. ``You feel like
you're more at a university, where there's more responsibility for
you to grow because one pastor can't talk to 23,000 people.''
</P>
<P>
   And ITC's Franklin is concerned that the rise of more affluent
black churches could also erode the church's tradition of activism.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we're not careful, we're going to drift into cultural
Christianity,'' Franklin said. ``The black middle-class will be
completely assimilated into the ethos of the surrounding culture
with its emphasis on individualism and materialism. I hear it all
the time around me and it makes me nervous.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis, however, sees progress around his church. It continues
fulfilling the mission that began at Big Bethel more than 150 years
ago, telling black folks that Jesus saves.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want to be landowners,'' Davis said. ``We're trying
to restore our community and we're trying to make a commitment that
honors the presence of the Lord's house in it.''
</P>
<P>
   John Blake writes for The Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta,
Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
