<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-18 13:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1522 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-COX-MILLENNIUM-CATHOL     08-18 2118
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COX-MILLENNIUM-CATHOLIC22 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CHRISTIANITY AT 2000: Catholicism thriving as church of
immigrants
 &HT;    Eds: This is the third installment in Cox News Service's
Millennium series, Christianity at 2000. The first installment, in
January, focused on the birth of Christianity nearly 2,000 years
ago. The second installment looked at the spread of Christianity
through Europe. This third installment looks at Christianity in the
New World. (Followup stories to this installment will move for the
weekend of Aug. 29.) The fourth installment, due at Christmas, will
look at Christianity's future.
 &HT;    This package includes photos and the following stories, all of
which are embargoed until Sunday, Aug. 22: MILLENNIUM-NEWWORLD,
-BARNSTABLE, -CATHOLIC, -BLACK and -PROFILES. This package will be
the CoxNet Focus page for this weekend. It will be available to
non-Cox papers (for a $20 download fee) by 5 p.m. Friday at
www.nytsyn.com/pageexpress.
 &HT;    Stories are moving in National and Lifestyle categories.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By Kim Sue Lia Perkes
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO, Texas _ Franciscan friar Herbert Jones stands in
front of the his congregation calling out the names of states like
a teacher checking attendance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nebraska.'' Applause.
</P>
<P>
   ``Illinois.'' Applause.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maine.'' Applause.
</P>
<P>
   After exhausting the list, he asks: ``Did I miss any states?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Kansas,'' a woman tells him. The congregation applauds.
</P>
<P>
   On any Sunday, crammed into one of America's oldest Roman
Catholic churches, San Jose in San Antonio, tourists from across
America, mostly descended from European immigrants, worship beside
the predominantly Hispanic congregation.
</P>
<P>
   Together, the San Jose worshippers represent the old and new
faces of American Catholicism, an immigrant church that now makes
up a quarter of the nation's population.
</P>
<P>
   Once a church that mostly grappled with America's crowded
eastern shores of poor, unskilled immigrant laborers from such
countries as Ireland, Germany, Poland and Italy, the Catholic
Church in the United States will end the millennium with a chasm
between its now largely white assimilated members and a new crop of
immigrants from Latin America, Asia and Africa.
</P>
<P>
   ``The distinct cultures, languages and diversity in the church
is a beautiful thing, but it is not without tension,'' said Bishop
Joseph A. Fiorenza of Houston, president of the National Conference
of Catholic Bishops. ``We are one family, and that's what we have
to continually talk about to our people.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the first Catholic, Christopher Columbus, set foot in the
New World in 1492, the church in America has weathered a roller
coaster ride of internal challenges, from its treatment of Indians
to dealing with the economic and ethnic tensions among its
immigrant flock.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the continuing drama plays out in a church struggling to
find enough priests to serve both its English-speaking and
non-English-speaking parishioners while trying to provide adequate
social services, education and Masses for its varied cultures and
age groups.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those are big problems for the church,'' said Catholic
sociologist and best-selling author the Rev. Andrew Greeley of
Chicago. ``The Catholic Church is confusion and crisis at the
institutional level and flourishing at the parish level.''
</P>
<P>
   The challenge, many Catholic scholars agree, is bigger than any
conflicts between the Vatican and American Catholics over such
issues as birth control.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my opinion, the ideological issues ... are white people's,
college-educated issues,'' said the Rev. Norbert Brockman, a
political science and history professor at St. Mary's University in
San Antonio. ``A big issue is going to be the question of what is
the role of the church with the decline of clergy? That's a very
critical question.''
</P>
<P>
   Priests and nuns have always played an important role in
America's church and social development, from creating schools and
hospitals to backing labor unions and social justice.
</P>
<P>
   The first clergy in the New World were Franciscan friars,
brought by Spanish explorers to set up missions, like San Jose in
1720, that served double duty as government outposts and Indian
conversion centers. The first one was established in St. Augustine,
Fla., in 1565.
</P>
<P>
   But as the colonies emerged in the Northeast, most Catholics
were barred from voting or holding public office by the predominant
Protestant society. Catholics sought refuge in Maryland, but
Protestants passed laws making it illegal for Catholics to
construct public houses of worship.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually John Carroll, a Jesuit priest who was the son of an
aristocratic Catholic family in Maryland, would become head of the
first diocese in the United States, founded in Baltimore in 1789.
He would wrestle with his own priest shortage to serve the
estimated 35,000 Catholics then in the United States _ numbers that
paled compared to Protestants.
</P>
<P>
   All that would change in the late 19th and early 20th centuries
when millions of European Catholics, escaping poor economic
conditions and political unrest, came to the United States in
search of a better life. Coming with them were priests _ lots of
priests _ who would follow the poor, unskilled immigrant laborers
from crowded ethnic ghettos in New York to cities and farm towns
across the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Under this migration, Catholicism became the largest
denomination in the nation _ a place it still holds today.
</P>
<P>
   As the church exploded with immigrants, numbers alone did not
protect Catholics and their priests from discrimination. They were
denied jobs, tarred and feathered, even hanged for their beliefs.
In the pews, Catholics themselves were prejudiced against their own
brethren, building churches and communities that resulted in ethnic
enclaves.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Irish bishops were never crazy about having a lot of
Italians in their diocese,'' said Larry Cunningham, a theology
professor at Notre Dame University.
</P>
<P>
   The descendents of those immigrants, educated and middle-class,
would blend together in the suburbs in the late '40s, '50s and
'60s, giving rise to well-heeled, Anglo Catholics more likely to
identify themselves by the states they live in than their ethnic
heritage.
</P>
<P>
   More than 70 percent of the church's adherents in the United
States today are Anglo, but the fastest-growing communities in the
church are its Hispanic, Asian and African populations.
</P>
<P>
   ``It means the church, internally, has to deal with issues of
race on a large scale,'' said Jim Davidson, a Catholic sociologist
at Purdue University.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Catholic Church estimates a quarter of its population
is Hispanic, and by far the largest influx of the church's
immigrants are coming from Mexico and South America, where the
populations are 85 to 95 percent Catholic. Like the European
immigrants before them, they are mostly poor and laborers. They are
spreading out across the United States, bringing growing Hispanic
populations to the South, Midwest and Northeast.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chicago has a larger Hispanic population than San Antonio
right now,'' said the Rev. David Garcia, the rector at San
Antonio's historic San Fernando Cathedral. ``I was in Milwaukee in
June, and there is a Hispanic population growing there now, and the
same thing in Minneapolis-St. Paul.''
</P>
<P>
   In South Bend, Ind., home of Notre Dame, there are 4,000
Hispanics, Cunningham said. ``And we don't even have 100,000 people
in South Bend,'' he added. ``And I don't think there is a Hispanic
priest in South Bend.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of the church's Asian and African immigrants are coming to
the United States as college students, for jobs they have waiting
for them or to be reunited with family members, said Fiorenza,
bishop of the Galveston-Houston diocese. ``There are a lot of
Nigerians, particularly,'' said Fiorenza, who has 50,000 of them in
his diocese alone. ``A lot of them are professional people _
engineers and doctors.''
</P>
<P>
   The National Conference of Catholic Bishops counts 2 million
Asians, 2.3 million African-Americans and 1 million African
immigrants among its flock.
</P>
<P>
   The majority are worshipping in their own ethnic churches.
</P>
<P>
   ``For Koreans, it's a language problem,'' said Chun Huh of St.
Andrew Kim parish in Houston. ``Many feel comfortable when the
Masses are in Korean.''
</P>
<P>
   To meet the needs of its growing ethnic communities, the
Catholic Church actively promotes the priesthood among immigrants.
</P>
<P>
   ``Priests are ordained to serve all Catholics, but often priests
from a particular culture group can be more effective in
ministering to their own people,'' said Bishop Roger L. Schweitz,
head of the church's committee on vocations.
</P>
<P>
   This year, one-fourth of the 500 priests ordained were from the
church's minority groups. Only 10 percent were Hispanic.
</P>
<P>
   Some dioceses in Texas and California _ the two states with the
largest Hispanic populations _ are making the Spanish language a
requirement for ordination.
</P>
<P>
   ``But having Father McFadden on the altar is the not the same as
having Father Gonzalez, who understands their language and their
culture,'' said Jesuit scholar Thomas Reese of New York.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, there are fewer than 50,000 priests and 85,000 nuns
serving the nation's 62 million Catholics.
</P>
<P>
   So few women are joining the church's religious orders today
that many of the orders are expected to close in the next 20 years,
Cunningham said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bigger problem is the average age of priests in this
country is increasing every year,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The average age of diocesan priests is 59. For nuns, it's 67.
</P>
<P>
   The Catholic Church is counting on the people in the pews to
take up the slack.
</P>
<P>
   ``A shortage of priests does not mean a dearth in ministries,''
said the Rev. Herbert Jones, who pastors the 1,000 mostly Hispanic
parishioners who belong to San Jose. ``The Catholic Church is
furiously training people. If there is anything different for the
new millennium, it is this.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the 1960s when Vatican II _ the council in Rome that
ushered in church reforms _ declared that the people of God are the
church, the doors flew open for laity to accept roles in the church
that were almost the exclusive domain of priests and nuns. Lay
people now are running many of the church's schools, hospitals and
religious programs.
</P>
<P>
   But only priests can celebrate Mass.
</P>
<P>
   On a sultry summer Sunday, Jones celebrates the Mass at San Jose
in English while mariachis _ a group of musicians _ accompany the
church choir, singing hymns in Spanish. During the Mass, women read
Scripture and serve as Eucharistic ministers.
</P>
<P>
   A few miles away at San Fernando Cathedral, Deacon Doroteo
Pedroza baptizes 40 babies during a service.
</P>
<P>
   Ordained deacons, who must be male, are taking the burden off
priests by performing baptisms, marriages and funerals. They also
provide marriage and bereavement counseling and make hospital
visits.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need a lot more,'' Pedroza said of the diaconate that has
tripled in the past two decades to almost 13,000. ``The church load
is getting heavier and heavier.''
</P>
<P>
   Less than 300 miles from the Mexican border, San Fernando
Cathedral absorbs many of the immigrants coming from Mexico and
South America. ``Every single day we have people coming in asking
for food,'' Pedroza said.
</P>
<P>
   Each Sunday, the downtown cathedral offers six Masses, drawing
an average attendance of 5,000 _ more than double its membership.
``The church holds 600 people,'' Garcia said. ``It's packed.''
</P>
<P>
   Among its Sunday parishioners are new immigrants from south of
the border, but sometimes the definition of immigrant is in the eye
of the beholder.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our church was here before there were any Anglos in the state
of Texas, so who is the immigrant?'' Garcia asked.
</P>
<P>
   During their noon mariachi Masses, San Fernando and San Jose
play host to Anglo-Catholic vacationers who want to worship in one
of the church's old Spanish missions and sample the flavor of its
Hispanic culture.
</P>
<P>
   On a recent Sunday, tourists and parishioners at San Jose were
reminded of one way the church breaks down cultural barriers.
</P>
<P>
   Sixteen years ago, Rick Marxkors, the descendent of German
immigrants, met his wife-to-be at a San Antonio insurance office. A
first-generation American, Norma Marxkors, is the daughter of
Mexican immigrants.
</P>
<P>
   The Franciscan friar summoned the couple before the altar, where
they danced to the mariachi band.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were married 12 years ago right here in San Jose,'' Jones
said. The congregation broke into applause.
</P>
<P>
   Kim Sue Lia Perkes writes for The Austin American-Statesman,
Austin, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
