<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-18 13:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1524 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-COX-MILLENNIUM-PROFIL     08-18 3096
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COX-MILLENNIUM-PROFILES22 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CHRISTIANITY AT 2000: One nation, many creeds
 &HT;    Eds: This is the third installment in Cox News Service's
Millennium series, Christianity at 2000. The first installment, in
January, focused on the birth of Christianity nearly 2,000 years
ago. The second installment looked at the spread of Christianity
through Europe. This third installment looks at Christianity in the
New World. (Followup stories to this installment will move for the
weekend of Aug. 29.) The fourth installment, due at Christmas, will
look at Christianity's future.
 &HT;    This package includes photos and the following stories, all of
which are embargoed until Sunday, Aug. 22: MILLENNIUM-NEWWORLD,
-BARNSTABLE, -CATHOLIC, -BLACK and -PROFILES. This package will be
the CoxNet Focus page for this weekend. It will be available to
non-Cox papers (for a $20 download fee) by 5 p.m. Friday at
www.nytsyn.com/pageexpress.
 &HT;    Stories are moving in National and Lifestyle categories.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By Gayle White
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The landscape of Christian America is as varied as the country's
physical surface. Some American churches grew out of immigrant
groups, including some of the country's earliest settlers. Others
are made in America, products of the American experience. Here is a
roundup of the major Christian sects in the United States. Since
membership requirements vary from denomination to denomination,
figures included are the inclusive U.S. membership _ including not
only full, confirmed members but children and other affiliates who
may not appear on official rolls of some groups.
</P>
<P>
   ADVENTISTS
</P>
<P>
   Adventists take their name from their eagerness for Jesus'
imminent return to the world _ the second Advent. Adventism today
traces its roots to an American movement called the Millerites,
named after William Miller, who became convinced that Jesus would
come to earth again between March 21, 1843, and March 21, 1844.
</P>
<P>
   When nothing happened, Miller associate Samuel Snow recalculated
and determined that Jesus would return on Yom Kippur, the Jewish
Day of Atonement, which in 1844 would be Oct. 22. According to some
accounts, so sure were some of Miller's followers that Jesus would
take them to heaven that they disposed of their property and met in
fields to wait.
</P>
<P>
   As one Adventist publication puts it, ``The day came, but the
Lord did not.'' Oct. 22, 1844, came to be known as the Great
Disappointment. Although many of Miller's followers gave up the
faith, others decided that, on that day in heaven, preparation for
Jesus' return to earth had begun.
</P>
<P>
   Major group
</P>
<P>
   _ Seventh-day Adventist Church: This church, the largest group
many times over, was co-founded by Ellen White; her husband, James;
and Joseph Bates, and recognizes Saturday as the Sabbath,
emphasizes healthful living and calls for abstention from alcohol,
tobacco, coffee and tea.
</P>
<P>
   _ Membership: 825,654
</P>
<P>
   BAPTISTS
</P>
<P>
   John the Baptist baptized Jesus in the River Jordan, according
to the gospels, and Baptists, the largest non-Catholic Christian
group in the United States, follow his lead in emphasizing baptism
by immersion in water as a ritual symbolizing entry into the
kingdom of God. Baptists began to gain their identity in the
Puritan Separatist movement of the 17th century. Early leaders were
a young Anglican clergyman named John Smyth and Thomas Helwys, whom
he baptized.
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, the best-known early Baptist is Roger
Williams, who founded the colony of Rhode Island as a refuge from
religious persecution. Williams and a group of friends were
baptized in 1639 and formed the First Baptist Church of Providence.
</P>
<P>
   Major groups
</P>
<P>
   _ Southern Baptist Convention: Founded in Augusta, Ga., in 1945
in a split over slavery, this is the country's largest non-Catholic
Christian group.
</P>
<P>
   _ Membership:15.9 million
</P>
<P>
   _ National Baptist Convention, U.S.A., Inc.: Not only the
country's largest black Baptist group, this is believed to be the
country's largest African-American organization of any kind.
</P>
<P>
   _ Membership: 8.2 million
</P>
<P>
   _ National Baptist Convention of America Inc.: Second largest of
the African-American Baptist bodies.
</P>
<P>
   _ Membership: 3.5 million
</P>
<P>
   _ Progressive National Baptist Convention Inc.: Founded in 1961
by Martin Luther King Jr. and other leaders in the Civil Rights
movement who were dissatisfied with the response to the movement
among leaders of the National Baptist Convention.
</P>
<P>
   _ Membership: 2.5 million
</P>
<P>
   _ National Missionary Baptist Convention of America: Resulted
from a publishing dispute within the National Baptist Convention of
America Inc. in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   _ Membership: 2.5 million, mostly in the far west.
</P>
<P>
   _ American Baptist Churches in the U.S.A.: Originally known as
the Northern Baptist Convention, this group is generally to the
left of the Southern Baptist Convention.
</P>
<P>
   _ Membership: 1.5 million, largely outside the South.
</P>
<P>
   CATHOLICS
</P>
<P>
   For the first few hundred years after Jesus, there was a single
church, a situation that changed when the head of the church of
Rome and the head of the church of Constantinople officially
excommunicated each other in 1054, creating the branches now known
as Catholicism and Orthodox Christianity.
</P>
<P>
   Long before the British Protestant settlers set foot on American
soil, Spanish Catholic priests came into the Southwest and French
Catholic priests came down the Mississippi in hopes of converting
Native Americans. Catholic priests are believed to have come to the
new world with Columbus in 1492, and missionaries followed with
other explorers. Although many perished, one established the first
permanent parish in North America at St. Augustine, Fla., in 1565.
Roman Catholics founded Maryland in 1634, although they were later
restricted there.
</P>
<P>
   Although most American Catholics are part of the Roman Catholic
church, there are other branches, known as the Eastern Rites, still
under the authority of the pope but with their own customs and
bishops.
</P>
<P>
   Major group:
</P>
<P>
   _ Roman Catholic Church: The largest single body of Christians
in the United States, the American church remains under the
authority of the pope and has an extensive network of cardinals,
archbishops and bishops.
</P>
<P>
   _ Membership: 61.2 million
</P>
<P>
   CONGREGATIONALISTS
</P>
<P>
   Taking their name from the belief that power should reside in
the local church, this movement grew out of the Separatists within
the Church of England during the reign of Elizabeth I. At a time
when Anglicanism was still strictly enforced by penalty of
imprisonment, a group of Congregationalists fled England and
eventually sailed to Cape Cod on the Mayflower.
</P>
<P>
   They did not set up a church until after they were joined a few
years later by a second group of settlers led by John Winthrop. A
series of splits and mergers led to the present configuration of
congregationalist groups.
</P>
<P>
   Major group:
</P>
<P>
   _ United Church of Christ: By far the largest body with
Congregational roots, this is the product of mergers with bodies
from other traditions.
</P>
<P>
   Membership: 1.4 million
</P>
<P>
   DISCIPLES AND CHRISTIANS
</P>
<P>
   Barton Warren Stone was ordained a Presbyterian minister in 1798
in Cane Ridge, Ky., but he was uncomfortable with certain aspects
of Presbyterian doctrine, especially the idea of salvation and
eternal life only for those selected in advance by God. Eventually,
Stone and some fellow Presbyterians of like mind withdrew from the
church and called themselves ``Christians only,'' referring to
their church as the Christian Church or Church of Christ.
</P>
<P>
   While Stone built his movement in Kentucky, another
Presbyterian, Thomas Campbell, was making his way to Southwest
Pennsylvania where he called for a return to the unity and
simplicity of primitive Christianity and thus began a movement
known as the Reformers or Disciples.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, the two movements met and became known as the
American Restoration movement.
</P>
<P>
   Major groups:
</P>
<P>
   _ Churches of Christ: The largest of the Stone-Campbell groups,
this body has no central headquarters and generally does not use
instruments in worship.
</P>
<P>
   _ Membership: 1.8 million
</P>
<P>
   _Christian Churches and Churches of Christ: Members of this
group do not consider it a denomination, and government is strictly
congregational.
</P>
<P>
   _ Membership: 1.1 million
</P>
<P>
   _ Christian Church (Disciples of Christ): Considered the most
liberal of the three Restoration groups, the Disciples of Christ
are now also the smallest.
</P>
<P>
   _ Membership: 879,436
</P>
<P>
   EPISCOPALIANS
</P>
<P>
   In 1534, Henry VIII of England wanted to divorce his wife,
Catherine of Aragon, because she had not borne him a son. One thing
stood in Henry's way _ the Roman Catholic Church's stance against
divorce. With Henry's urging, Parliament passed two acts in 1534:
One declared that the Roman Catholic pope had no authority in
England; the other established the Church of England with the
monarch as its head.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a temporary return to Catholicism under Mary Tudor, who
became known as Bloody Mary, Henry's church survived and gained a
firm foothold in North America with the settlement of Jamestown in
1607.
</P>
<P>
   The colonial church remained firmly under the Church of England
until 1782, when the Rev. William White, rector of Christ Church of
Philadelphia and a former chaplain of the Continental Congress,
made a proposal for a United States Church.
</P>
<P>
   Major group:
</P>
<P>
   Episcopal Church: This is the mainline Anglican church in the
United States and the only one recognized by the international
Anglican communion.
</P>
<P>
   _ Membership: 2.5 million
</P>
<P>
   LUTHERANS
</P>
<P>
   On Oct. 31, 1517, as the story goes, Catholic monk Martin Luther
posted his famous 95 Theses on the door of the Castle Church in
Wittenberg, Germany, opposing the Catholic church's sale of
indulgences, or grants of forgiveness of sin.
</P>
<P>
   Although Luther advocated reform within the church, the
deteriorating relationship between Luther, his followers and the
church ensured that Lutherans would have to leave Catholicism in
order to carry out their teachings.
</P>
<P>
   Lutheranism came to North America in the 1600s through Dutch and
Scandinavian immigrants to the Hudson and Delaware River valleys.
Lutheran congregations were formed throughout the New World.
</P>
<P>
   Major Groups:
</P>
<P>
   _ Evangelical Lutheran Church in America: A product of the
merger of three major Lutheran groups in 1988, this is the
country's largest Lutheran body.
</P>
<P>
   _ Membership: 5.1 million
</P>
<P>
   _ Lutheran Church, Missouri Synod: This more conservative
Lutheran group remains independent of the Evangelical Lutheran
Church in America but cooperates in many endeavors.
</P>
<P>
   _ Membership: 2.6 million
</P>
<P>
   METHODISTS
</P>
<P>
   Anglican clergyman John Wesley is credited with starting the
Methodist movement, but his younger brother Charles, famous for his
Protestant hymns, actually convened the first meeting of the Holy
Club of young men at Oxford University that fostered the movement.
John, the older brother, took over the club in 1729 and led the
group to apply a method of prayer and fasting to their daily lives.
For this, they were nicknamed the Methodists.
</P>
<P>
   In 1738, John had what is known as the ``Aldersgate
experience,'' during which, he wrote, he felt his heart ``strangely
warmed.'' He began to preach with new enthusiasm and gained many
followers.
</P>
<P>
   England's Methodists sent their first ministers to the colonies
in 1769, to be followed in 1771 by another team that included
Francis Asbury, who became known as the ``Wesley of America.''
Asbury stayed through the Revolutionary War, riding thousands of
miles on horseback to spread the gospel and set up Methodist
societies.
</P>
<P>
   After the Revolution, the Anglican bishop of London refused to
send more men to minister in America, and John Wesley decided to
ordain some ministers for the mission himself in 1784. This marked
the separation of the Methodists from the Church of England.
</P>
<P>
   Major groups:
</P>
<P>
   _ United Methodist Church: This is a majority-white mainline
Protestant group with worldwide missions and an extensive social
ministry within the United States.
</P>
<P>
   _ Membership: 8.5 million
</P>
<P>
   _ African Methodist Episcopal Church: This largest of the
predominantly black Methodist denominations began in 1787 when
former slave Richard Allen, a licensed preacher, and several other
black worshipers walked out of St. George's Methodist Episcopal
Church in Philadelphia after being chastised for being in a
white-only gallery.
</P>
<P>
   _ Membership: 3.5 million
</P>
<P>
   _ African Methodist Episcopal Zion Church: The A.M.E. Zion
church grew out of the John Street Methodist Episcopal Church in
New York City in 1796 when a group of black members formed their
own chapel, incorporated in 1801.
</P>
<P>
   _ Membership: 1.25 million
</P>
<P>
   _ Christian Methodist Episcopal Church: In 1870, white members
of the Methodist Episcopal Church, South (later incorporated into
the United Methodist Church) agreed to a proposal by black members
to form a separate denomination.
</P>
<P>
   _ Membership: 719,000
</P>
<P>
   ORTHODOX CHRISTIANS
</P>
<P>
   Split from the Roman Catholic Church near the beginning of the
second millennium, Orthodox Christianity is similar to Catholicism
in its rich ritual and its ecclesiastical structure. Many of
America's Orthodox Christians are in identifiable ethnic groups;
however, in recent years this branch of Christianity has drawn many
new converts, including evangelical Christians who find a
continuity and historical connection there.
</P>
<P>
   Major Groups:
</P>
<P>
   _ Orthodox Church in America: With Russian roots, this group
came to Alaska in 1794, long before its purchase by the United
States. Originally known as the Russian Orthodox Greek Catholic
Church of America, it was granted independence, known as
autocephaly, by its Mother Church, the Russian Orthodox Church, in
1970.
</P>
<P>
   _ Membership: 2 million
</P>
<P>
   _ Greek Orthodox Church: The first church of this branch of
Orthodox Christianity in the United States was chartered in New
Orleans in 1864. Greek Orthodox Americans are under the
jurisdiction of the Ecumenical Patriarchate of Constantinople in
Istanbul.
</P>
<P>
   _ Membership: 1.95 million
</P>
<P>
   PENTECOSTALS
</P>
<P>
   Known for their exuberant worship, Pentecostals take their name
from the day of Pentecost, chronicled in the New Testament Book of
Acts when the Holy Spirit descended on Jesus' disciples and enabled
them to speak and understand strange languages, prophesy and heal
people.
</P>
<P>
   The modern day Pentecostal movement began around the turn of the
20th century. Although there were some earlier events associated
with the movement, it seemed to take flight under the preaching of
William J. Seymour, an African-American man who conducted Bible
studies at 312 Azusa Street in Los Angeles, a site now widely known
as the birthplace of modern Pentecostalism.
</P>
<P>
   Major Groups:
</P>
<P>
   _ Church of God in Christ: The largest Pentecostal body in the
world, this predominantly black group was founded by Charles H.
Mason, and incorporated in 1907 in Memphis.
</P>
<P>
   _ Membership: 5.5 million
</P>
<P>
   _ Assemblies of God: Organized in 1914 in Hot Springs, Ark.,
this is the largest predominantly white Pentecostal denomination.
</P>
<P>
   _ Membership: 2.5 million
</P>
<P>
   _ Pentecostal Assemblies of the World: This predominantly black
but integrated group is the largest of the so-called Oneness
Pentecostal groups that teach there is only one divinity _ or, that
Jesus is the Father, Son and Holy Spirit.
</P>
<P>
   _ Membership: 1 million
</P>
<P>
   _ Church of God: Headquartered in Cleveland, Tenn., this church
grew out of a revival at Camp Creek in Cherokee, N.C. It should not
be confused with the Church of God headquartered in Anderson, Ind.,
which is not Pentecostal.
</P>
<P>
   _ Membership: 753,000
</P>
<P>
   _ International Church of the Foursquare Gospel: Founded by the
famous Aimee Semple McPherson, this Los Angeles-based denomination
came out of the Assemblies of God.
</P>
<P>
   _ Membership: 229,600
</P>
<P>
   PRESBYTERIANS AND REFORMED
</P>
<P>
   The father of Presbyterianism and the Reformed tradition is John
Calvin, who, at age 27 in 1536, published his ``Institutes for the
Christian Religion,'' advancing the idea of the ``elect,'' or the
concept that God first chooses people for eternal life before they
decide to follow God.
</P>
<P>
   John Knox, a Catholic priest from Scotland, studied under Calvin
and established the Presbyterian church in his homeland. In 1560,
the parliament of Scotland renounced the Roman Catholic Church in
favor of the Reformed Church. A conference in England gave the
church the Westminster documents, which serve as the foundation for
the faith in the English-speaking world.
</P>
<P>
   A clergyman named Francis Makemie is often called the Father of
American Presbyterianism because of his efforts to organize the
church in the colonies. He founded a church at Rehoboth, Md., in
1684, and, in 1706, helped organize the first long-standing
American presbytery.
</P>
<P>
   Major groups:
</P>
<P>
   _ Presbyterian Church (U.S.A.): Presbyterians were divided over
the issues of slavery, revival and missions, and by 1861, there
were four different branches of the church, two each in the north
and the south. After the Civil War, the two Southern groups merged,
as did the two Northern groups. But it was not until 1983, at a
gathering in Atlanta, that the main branches of the church came
together again to form this denomination.
</P>
<P>
   _ Membership: 3.6 million
</P>
<P>
   _ Reformed Church in America: Established in 1628 by early
settlers in New York as the Reformed Protestant Dutch Church, this
group claims to have the longest continuous ministry of any
Protestant denomination in North America.
</P>
<P>
   _ Membership: 304,000
</P>
<P>
   _ Presbyterian Church in America: This denomination,
headquartered in Atlanta, was formed in 1973 as a splinter group of
the Southern branch of the mainline Presbyterian Church in protest
of what organizers saw as liberalism within the denomination.
</P>
<P>
   _ Membership: 267,700
</P>
<P>
   _ Christian Reformed Church in North America: Formed in Michigan
in 1847, this group was briefly affiliated with the Reformed Church
in America.
</P>
<P>
   _ Membership: 201,700
</P>
<P>
   Sources: ``Believers and Beliefs'' by Gayle Colquitt White,
Berkeley Publishers; ``Yearbook of American &AMP; Canadian Churches,''
1998, 1999, Abingdon Press; ``Handbook of Denominations in the
United States,'' 10th edition, Abingdon Press.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
