<SLUG> BC-NYHAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALEXANDER YIELDS WITH GRACE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID NYHAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The way Lamar Alexander quit the Republican sweepstakes was
positively presidential: a fast, hard decision, with no whining,
calmly and crisply accomplished, presented matter-of-factly,
gracefully, intelligently.
</P>
<P>
   Bereft of money, having guessed wrong about the saleability of
his issue package and smothered by the media's tropism toward
richer or more flamboyant rivals, he bowed out like a mannerly
guest finding himself at the wrong house party. He did it in a
manner Dan Quayle could learn from.
</P>
<P>
   ``We never embarrassed anybody,'' New Hampshire strategist Tom
Rath said of Lamar's effort. ``I never had to apologize for my
association with him.'' It turns out Alexander's best shot came in
'96. ``The insiders, the people who really get it, know how close
we came'' last time, shrugged Rath.
</P>
<P>
   It was a combination Dole-Forbes uppercut-haymaker that pushed
Alexander down to third in New Hampshire in 1996, behind Pat
Buchanan and Bob Dole. Lamar was the Republican Clinton feared
would give him the hardest time. But Forbes dumped a ton of
anti-Lamar TV in New Hampshire, and that depressed Alexander's
vote, enabling Dole to squeak into second and survive. Dole told
his wife he'd quit the race if he ran third, but he came in second
by a nose.
</P>
<P>
   This cycle Mrs. Dole came in ahead of Lamar. Go figure. Lamar
tried gimmicks, and they didn't work. In '96, he tried walking
across New Hampshire, playing the piano at rallies and flashing his
plaid shirt. His hole card in '96 was ``winnability.'' He could
actually win, his partisans argued, and Bob Dole or Buchanan or
Forbes or the rest of them so clearly could not.
</P>
<P>
   This time Alexander had top-flight help where it counted, Terry
Branstad, Iowa's governor for 16 years, and Tom Rath in New
Hampshire. But ``winnability'' was another candidate's issue. And
George W. Bush had the money to neutralize Forbes's megaton of
bucks. Bush and Forbes dropped more than $2 million to finish 1-2
in the Ames, Iowa, straw poll. That cheesy little gimmick to extort
a half-million dollars in voter fees left Lamar a forlorn sixth.
</P>
<P>
   ``He looked at me and said, `This makes it easy,' '' said Rath
of Alexander's decision to fold. ``Easy'' is not quite accurate.
Quitting the cause on which you've spent seven years and upwards of
$10 million or more is not a decision taken lightly. But the
magnitude of the defeat made it simple. George W. got 7,418 votes
for the $800,000-plus he invested, the best $100-per-vote deal he
ever made. Forbes got 4,921 votes for his $1.5 million-plus, so he
paid more than $300 per vote. Elizabeth Dole's 3,410 votes cost her
only $200,000 or so, so she got a bargain at only $60 and change
per vote.
</P>
<P>
   Lamar ($80 per vote) has the satisfaction _ if that's the right
word _ of knowing that of all five candidates finishing ahead of
him, their sum total of elective experience is five years in office
_ all Bush's. Forbes, Dole, Gary Bauer, and Pat Buchanan all ran
ahead of Lamar. None of the four was ever elected to any public
office. And it's highly unlikely any ever will be.
</P>
<P>
   But there has to be something screwy in the GOP when four people
never elected to anything run ahead of a man who has been governor
twice (Alexander) as well as a former vice president and US senator
(Quayle), two other senators (John McCain and Orrin Hatch) and a
congressman (John Kasich). Think about it. The antigovernment
themes plumbed by Ronald Reagan and his imitators are flushing out
the elected officials. The antigovernment party devours its own
seed corn.
</P>
<P>
   For my money, Lamar would have been the strongest GOP candidate
for '96, but I doubt any of them could have toppled Clinton. This
time, Alexander's ``winnability'' rationale was usurped by Bush.
And Lamar never came up with a resonating message. He cobbled
together a package of profamiliy policies, tax breaks, and
schooling nostrums. But we were not electing a president to run the
public schools, a scheme which he accused Gore of to absolutely no
avail.
</P>
<P>
   I still see Lamar as more presidential than any Republican in
the field. In terms of tolerance of personality, stability of
character, personal discipline, and moral probity _ all the
qualities voters insist they want _ he is a superior individual.
But you can't reason with voters dispassionately. You have to win
them over emotionally, as Reagan did.
</P>
<P>
   It's Bush's nomination to lose. Forbes's loot makes him a
factor, but not a president. Buchanan probably follows Bob Smith
through the exit marked ``Third Party.''
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Dole had a good day in Ames but may be too overmatched
to begin at this level and be taken seriously. And by finishing
eighth in Ames behind Alan Keyes, a crank's crank, Quayle cooked
his own goose. That leaves McCain as best bet to stop Bush in New
Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes and the rest of the cultural conservatives who trail in
his wake cannot lick the Democrats. The United States is not like
those Kansas creationists who think Darwin is only a town in
Australia. The Republicans need a grownup to win. This time it's
McCain; last time it was Lamar. Life, as a guy named Kennedy once
shrugged, is unfair.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(David Nyhan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
