<HEADLINE>
CHRISTIAN GROUP, BANK BATTLE OVER HOMOSEXUALITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIEGO RIBADENEIRA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The explosive issue of homosexuality has set off a dispute
between the conservative Christian organization Focus on the Family
and Mellon Bank, which has refused to do business with the group
because of its stance against homosexuality.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, James Dobson, Focus on the Family's president, told
listeners of his widely-broadcast radio program that Mellon Bank
has refused to do business with the Christian ministry, saying the
bank did not want to deal with a group it called ``family
unfriendly.''
</P>
<P>
   The public battle between Mellon Bank and Focus on the Family
started when the Christian ministry, based in Colorado, recently
asked Mellon Bank to help manage its growing gift annuity program.
</P>
<P>
   Dobson asked listeners to respond directly to Mellon Bank and a
recorded message at the groups headquaters gave telephone numbers
for the bank's president and chairman as well as the ministry's
main switchboard.
</P>
<P>
   Following hundreds of phone calls to Mellon, Ronald Gruendl, a
bank spokesman, said the potential business deal ``ended when it
was discovered that our non-discrimination policy and federal and
state guidelines, which have been upheld in court, and Focus on the
Family's mission statement are in conflict. Our reason for not
doing business with them was purely a business-related matter.''
</P>
<P>
   Gruendl also said that Mellon has asked Focus to ``retract their
statement, publicly apologize to Mellon for making such an
incorrect statement and ask their audience to refrain from further
calls to Mellon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Failure to adhere to our request may result in legal action,''
Gruendl said.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week, Mellon, which is based in Pittsburgh and is
one of the nation's largest financial services corporations, issued
a new terser statement saying the bank chose not to deal with Focus
``for appropriate business reasons.''
</P>
<P>
   After Mellon turned down setting up an account for Focus on the
Family, Tom Mason, executive vice president for the ministry said
he met with David Holtz, a Mellon vice president. During the
meeting Mason said he stressed to Holtz that while Focus supports
the civil rights of homosexuals it does not believe gays should be
treated as a ``protected class.''
</P>
<P>
   Holtz, according to Mason, said such a view conflicts with the
bank's policy and was one of the ``problems'' that prevented Mellon
from entering into a business deal with Focus on the Family.
</P>
<P>
   The ministry's mission statement is ``to cooperate with the Holy
Spirit in disseminating the gospel of Jesus Christ to as many
people as possible, and, specifically, to accomplish that objective
by helping to preserve traditional values and the institution of
the family.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Religion Notes
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --An elderly Rwandan cleric accused of participating in the
genocide in Rwanda has been ordered turned over to the United
Nation's International Criminal Tribunal for Rwanda by the 5th
Circuit Court of Appeals, based in New Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   Writing for the court, US Circuit Court Judge Emilio Garza said
there is sufficient evidence to establish probable cause that
Elizaphan Ntalirutimana, 75, a Seventh-day Adventist clergyman,
took part in the crimes for which he's charged and that the US
extradition agreement with the tribunal is constitutional.
</P>
<P>
   The cleric is accused of exhorting a large, mostly Tutsi group
of men, women and children to seek refuge in a church and hospital
complex and then participating in a daylong attack on the refugees
by Hutus _ using guns and machetes _ that led to hundreds of
deaths.
</P>
<P>
   He also is accused of being part of a group of Hutus who
continued to carry out attacks against Tutsis who escaped the
church massacre.
</P>
<P>
   Following the genocide, in which more than 500,000 mostly
Tustsis were massacred, Ntalirutimana left Rwanda for the United
States, where he eventually settled in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Garza's ruling was lauded by human rights advocates.
</P>
<P>
   ``The decision is tangible proof of the US support for the rule
of law,'' said Michael Posner, executive director of the Lawyers
Committee for Human Rights. ``It sets an important domestic
precedent as Mr. Ntakirutimana is the first person that the United
States has been asked to surrender to either of the international
criminal tribunals.'' The other tribnal is investigating war crimes
in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --For those who think Guardian Angels are just a myth, Ken
Wagner, a Brookline, Mass. author with a professional background in
economic development, claims they aren't. He says his own guardian
angel has been communicating with him for more than 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   And to help others who may be dubious about guardian angels,
Wagner has published a ``how-to'' booklet entitled ``How to Contact
Your Guardian Angel.'' Among other things, the booklet, which
Wagner says was directly inspired by his guardian angel, recommends
ways to communicate with your guardian angel, through prayer,
meditation or writing.
</P>
<P>
   The booklet can be obtained for free by sending a
self-addressed, stamped envelope to Box 233, Brookline, MA 02446.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Diego Ribadeneira's e-mail address is religion(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-18-99 1345EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990818.0116 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-18 13:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1540 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-WOM-KENWORTHY-ART-BOS     08-18 1038
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOM-KENWORTHY-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHE HANDLED PERSONAL TRAGEDIES WHILE LEARING TO HELP OTHERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA HUEBNER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- To become a good athletic trainer, a student must
learn how to interpret pain. Care for the wounded. Comfort psyches
as well as bodies; be someone to lean on during a crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Tragically, Kate Kenworthy is at the head of her class.
</P>
<P>
   The 22-year-old from Lincoln, R.I., didn't get to many Bay State
Road parties as an undergraduate at Boston University. There wasn't
much weekend window shopping along Newbury Street, or even many
long, quiet Saturday afternoons in the library. Instead, she was
working various part-time jobs, arguing with insurance companies,
paying the bills or explaining to creditors why she couldn't,
trying to scrape together mortgage money to save the family home in
Providence while in turn taking care of her sick mother and younger
brother.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, most college students go out on a Friday or Saturday
night to relieve their stress,'' said Kenworthy last week, pausing
during her first week as a graduate assistant athletic trainer at
BU before leaving for preseason camp as trainer for the women's
soccer team. ``I would just lay home on the couch, curl up, and
watch a movie. That would be my big release.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite responsibilities and grief that no one her age should
have to endure, Kenworthy excelled academically. Graduating in May
with a 3.76 grade point average, she was honored a month later with
a $5,000 postgraduate scholarship from the National Association of
Collegiate Directors of Athletics. Out of 101 nominees, only 16
students received the award; Kenworthy was one of four in Division
1. She also has received two scholarships from the National
Athletic Trainers Association.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's won every scholarship she's ever been nominated for,''
said Maria Hutsick, head athletic trainer at BU.
</P>
<P>
   She's also won something far more lasting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I possibly could have fallen apart and just given up on
everything,'' said her brother, Ben McLellan, now 20 and a
sophomore music student at Rhode Island College. ``I don't know
what would have happened (without her).''
</P>
<P>
   It was 16 years ago that Kenworthy's mother was diagnosed with
multiple sclerosis, and was forced to quit her job during
Kenworthy's junior year at LaSalle Academy in Providence.
Meanwhile, Kenworthy's father had contracted hepatitis; after a
lengthy illness he died in hospice of liver failure, just before
his 50th birthday, on the day Kenworthy graduated from high school.
</P>
<P>
   Although she wasn't told of his death until she got home that
night, Kenworthy said, ``I kind of had a feeling, because I heard
the phone ring early in the morning. I was like, I'm not going to
think about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, during Kenworthy's sophomore year at BU, her mother's
condition worsened rapidly. Soon her mother was alternating between
hospital and nursing home, her only daughter coming home from
college every weekend to see her, relieving her grandmother from
bedside duty, quizzing the doctors on her care, fighting to keep
insurance coverage going, helping Ben with his college
applications, trying all the while to keep pace with her
schoolwork.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's amazing what you'll do and not even think about it when
you have to,'' said Kenworthy, whose two older brothers live
outside of Rhode Island.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was unbelievable,'' said McLellan. ``She was just getting
us by so we weren't in the street, basically. She had to budget
everything. I don't know how she did it.''
</P>
<P>
   In February 1998, her mother unexpectedly died of complications.
Again, Kenworthy tried not to think about it. ``I did everything I
had to do physically to get everything taken care of, and I just
didn't deal with it (emotionally) until the summer,'' she said.
``School was kind of a blessing, because I think I would have lost
my mind.''
</P>
<P>
   On June 27, 1998, she married Tom Kenworthy, the man she calls
her ``saving grace'' since they began dating three years ago.
(``It's the other way around,'' insisted her husband, a teacher and
head football coach at LaSalle Academy, earlier this week. ``She
doesn't need much help getting through what she needs to get
through. It seems like everything that happened has made her
stronger.'') About a month after the wedding, she said, Kenworthy
woke up one morning with the loss hitting her like a tornado.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh my God,'' she remembers thinking.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout Kenworthy's long ordeal, Hutsick and others at BU
have been watchful, helping when they could. ``She won't tell you
what's going on with her unless you ask her,'' Hutsick explained.
``She never brings it up as an excuse for anything, never `woe is
me.' We don't know how she does it because she never seems to stop.
I don't know if you'd call us her surrogate parents, but we try to
look out for her.''
</P>
<P>
   Hutsick was so impressed that she chose Kenworthy to be her
graduate assistant this year, breaking the precedent that graduates
be sent off to other schools to gain more-varied experiences.
``She's a very rare kid that comes along once in a million,''
Hutsick reasoned.
</P>
<P>
   Now it's time for Kenworthy, as an athletic trainer who needs to
be ready for something to go wrong at any moment, to put to use the
sad lessons of the past few years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like I'm so much more empathetic to people now, to
their pain,'' she said. ``It's made me a much more sensitive person
and, I think, more mature. That's the most positive thing I took
from it. It's hard, but you definitely have to look at the positive
side of things because I know people who have gone through a lot
worse.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the next few years, while working as a trainer on various
Terrier teams as part of her graduate assistanceship, Kenworthy
said she hopes to pursue a doctorate and become a teacher in her
field, reaping what she called the rewards of helping people learn.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's my plan,'' she said brightly last week. ``I'm hoping I
can handle it.''
</P>
<P>
   Is there much doubt?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
