<SLUG> BC-CAREERS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TV SHOWS OFFER A FEW LESSONS ON WORKING LIFE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAVE MURPHY  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ You're so wiped out at the end of the day that
all you want to do is flop on the sofa, grab the remote control and
have a few laughs. You certainly won't move up in the world that
way. Or will you?
</P>
<P>
   Sure you will. Think about television comedies for a minute:
They have the same characters every week _ from charming to
memorable to downright weird. They start out fresh, but get stale
in a hurry.
</P>
<P>
   And God knows plenty of them are about nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Sound familiar? In that great bumbling wasteland, though, there
are a few classics _ and they stand out for the same reasons that
great workplaces stand out. They may have a star or two, but mostly
they have a talented ensemble. And they offer their own sort of
diversity, even when their cast is whiter than Edgar Winter at an
Internal Revenue Service audit.
</P>
<P>
   All the characters have qualities that make them stand out as
individuals, and new people are brought in to keep it fresh. Once
in a while, they do something completely unpredictable, just to
keep their sanity.
</P>
<P>
   Here are five classic workplace comedies, and a lesson you can
learn from each:
</P>
<P>
   _ ``The Mary Tyler Moore Show'': When the show started in 1970,
the first line of the theme song was, ``How will you make it on
your own?'' That's an awfully condescending way to start a TV show,
but few women back then had high-powered careers, and moving into a
town as the associate producer of a TV news show could be enough to
scare anyone, especially if your boss looks like Edward Asner.
</P>
<P>
   If you want a high-powered career, though, you have to take a
few of those scary steps. Mary Richards pulled it off, of course.
</P>
<P>
   Within a year, the first line of the theme song had been changed
to _ ta da! _ ``Who can turn the world on with her smile?'' All
right. So progress wasn't exactly swift.
</P>
<P>
   Even if you look at only TV shows about TV shows, the last
decade has offered us Murphy Brown, a woman who didn't just hold a
career, but thrived in one. (Career lesson-within-a-lesson: Don't
have children just as a plot device.) And now there's
``SportsNight,'' with women starring as the producer, assistant
producer and night producer.
</P>
<P>
   The ``SportsNight'' women are all confident and capable in their
jobs, with personalities every bit as quirky as the men's. The only
person who seems to have it together is Isaac, the executive
producer, an African-American man.
</P>
<P>
   The working world does indeed move forward, even if it's at the
pace of rush-hour traffic.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``WKRP in Cincinnati'': In a memorable episode, bumbling boss
Arthur Carlson decides to hand out turkeys on the air as a
Thanksgiving promotion for the radio station. Only one problem: He
hands them out from a moving helicopter.
</P>
<P>
   ``The turkeys are hitting the ground like sacks of wet cement!''
WKRP news director Les Nessman screams.
</P>
<P>
   Turkeys can't fly. Remember that next time you hire someone.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Taxi'': Sometimes bosses can be the most evil, underhanded,
snarling little creatures who ever ...
</P>
<P>
   Actually, you're better off paying less attention to the evil
Louie and focusing more on Andy Kaufman's lovable Latka, a
soft-spoken immigrant with a deer-in-the-headlights quality.
</P>
<P>
   Every once in a while, though, Latka's dark side appears in the
form of smooth-talking gigolo Vic Ferrari, way too slick and way
too confident for anyone to stomach.
</P>
<P>
   You need a split personality to survive in the world of work
these days. Even if you prefer being as gentle as Latka, get Vic to
negotiate your salary.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``MASH'': In the show's next-to-last episode, Margaret decides
to bury a time capsule so that people 100 years in the future will
understand what it was like to be in the Korean War. But all she
wants to bury is the regular-Army sort of stuff, like boots and
duty rosters.
</P>
<P>
   So Hawkeye starts a capsule of his own, showing how big of a
nuisance the war has been to people's lives, with things like
bunion pads and a bottle of cognac.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, though, he realizes that he's found the perfect
items for Margaret's time capsule: things like Radar's forgotten
teddy bear, representing all those who went to Korea as boys and
came home as men; and Henry Blake's fishing lure, for all those who
never made it home.
</P>
<P>
   You need a sense of purpose to make your work worthwhile, but it
takes a lot of ``little'' things to make it memorable.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Cheers'': Yes, a bar can be considered a workplace,
especially if you're a journalist over the age of 40.
</P>
<P>
   Near the end of the show's final episode, as Sam walked toward
the back of the bar, he stopped long enough to straighten a picture
of Geronimo. It was a gesture that meant absolutely nothing, and
absolutely everything.
</P>
<P>
   The picture had belonged to Nicholas Colasanto, the actor who
had played Coach. Colasanto had died during the course of the
series.
</P>
<P>
   We all lose people we care about. But their pictures live on, as
long as we take the time to straighten them.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dave Murphy is the careers editor of the San Francisco
Examiner, P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. His electronic
mail address is murphy(at)examiner.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
