<SLUG> BC-SILICON-GAP-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VALLEY OF THE GUYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNDA GOROV  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALO ALTO, Calif. _ It's Friday, just shy of 9 p.m., and the
after-work crowd is waiting for a table, waiting for a bar stool,
waiting for a woman, any woman at all.
</P>
<P>
   Straight from their office cubicles and computer terminals, the
software engineers and Internet entrepreneurs who spill onto the
sidewalks are mostly male, mostly without female companionship for
the evening. The scene resembles a beer commercial, except that few
of them appear overjoyed to be hanging out with the guys, again.
</P>
<P>
   As Richard Dominguez, a 31-year-old electronics technician from
San Jose, put it, ``To get a date, you either have to look like a
model or have the money. It's like a role reversal, where the women
are the ones who get to be picky about us.''
</P>
<P>
   Dominguez has not had a date in months, but he is hardly alone.
As the men who live and work in Silicon Valley note with
frustration _ and the women who do the same note with some
satisfaction _ the region has developed a guy glut to go with its
semiconductors and personal computers. It's like Alaska, only with
better weather and richer men.
</P>
<P>
   The imbalance is evident everywhere in Silicon Valley, from San
Jose's cyber cafes to the Palo Alto hotel where an organization
called American Singles recently held its convention. Men
outnumbered women to such a degree that the San Rafael-based
group's chairman, Rich Grosse, actually got to sit out some dances.
Explained Andy Miller, a 23-year-old computer engineer from
Mountain View, ``Go to a concert, go to whatever, it seems like
it's all guys.''
</P>
<P>
   To avoid the all-guy scene night after night, product marketing
manager John Dang and his male friends have developed a strategy:
Each e-mails the women he knows and invites them to get together as
a group for drinks after hours. It is a way for everyone to
prospect without pressure. ``It depends on the guy, but there is a
strategy to meeting women,'' said Dang, 28, who recently went on
what he deemed a successful first date with certainty of a second _
with a woman who lives in Seattle. ``I invite my friends, they
invite their friends. Everyone invites all the ladies they can
think of. It's what you have to do around here.''
</P>
<P>
   Evidence of excess men, however, is more than anecdotal,
although there is plenty of that. Nationally, single women
outnumbered single men about 43 million to 36 million in 1997, the
most recent figures available from the US Census Bureau. Similar
surpluses of single women hold true in most major cities.
</P>
<P>
   But in Santa Clara County, which encompasses the high-tech world
known as Silicon Valley, the odds are reversed. In this small slice
of America, there are 5,400 more single men than single women
(including people who are widowed and divorced), according to US
Census and demographic data compiled by Claritas Inc., an
Arlington, Va., market research firm.
</P>
<P>
   Compared with the nearly 1.3 million people age 15 and older who
live in the county, that might seem like a minuscule amount of
extra men. But it is enough to make Santa Clara County one of the
few major metropolitan areas where the odds tend to be in a woman's
favor.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do these parties all over the world and we get too many
women, except in the Silicon Valley,'' said Grosse, of American
Singles. ``Women complain bitterly that there are not enough men to
dance, except in the Silicon Valley. Sometimes I have to ask eight
women to dance to keep them happy, except in the Silicon Valley. .
. . Those guys are hungry down there.''
</P>
<P>
   That does not, of course, mean there is someone for every woman
in the cities south of San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   For starters, some of the single men are probably gay men
working in high tech or living in Silicon Valley because they are
unable to afford the even pricier real estate in the Bay Area.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is the age of the bachelors to consider and their
outlook on professional versus personal lives.
</P>
<P>
   Organizations and individuals who specialize in making that
perfect match said most are 24 to 35, since the computer industry
tends to attract younger employees. They said many spend too much
time at their terminals, too little time cultivating outside
interests. Gosse noted that more than a few are new to the United
States, drawn by the demand for their computer skills but
unfamiliar with American dating. Robin Anderson, who owns Premier
Matches in Belmont, went so far as to call some of them
unsocialized.
</P>
<P>
   ``Absolutely there are more men than women in that age group.
They're all over the place,'' she said. ``My feeling is it doesn't
make them any more emotionally available. . . . Either they're so
wound up in making their mark or they aren't socialized or they
just aren't ready yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Katia Dimitrov, a 29-year-old marketing analyst, ``Sure
there are lots of guys, but they're all the same guy. There's no
variety.''
</P>
<P>
   Men out in groups of two, three, even six, on a recent weekend
disputed that they were to blame for their inability to attract a
date, although many conceded they were concentrating on their
careers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Quite honestly, I don't have time for it anyway,'' said Joe
Vause, 35, who works in business development at a new Internet
company. ``With any luck, in three or four years I will have time,
but it's going to have to wait.''
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Ted Nannariello, 27, admitted to an unwelcome
drought. The computer engineer, dressed in a special edition ``Star
Wars'' trilogy T-shirt, called women ``picky,'' not just in Silicon
Valley, but especially here.
</P>
<P>
   Raymond ``Tim'' Mitchell, a 40-year-old Cadillac mechanic, said
most women will not even talk to him because he does not stand a
chance to make millions on computer stock options. His friend,
general building contractor Christopher Scott, insisted women have
gone snooping into his finances.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really happened,'' said Scott, 44. ``I've been out on a
date and I went for an after-dinner drink at her house and my
portfolio was up on her computer. She said she had my driver's
license and was able to get all this information on me. She was
really proud of it. I said goodbye.''
</P>
<P>
   During his time in Silicon Valley, Gamon Yaklich, 23 and in
software sales, said he has discovered what works: talking to women
about something other than megahertz or megabytes. He said he does
all right. His last official date was five months ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Women can give you the cold shoulder very easily here, and
they do,'' Yaklich said. ``I found it much easier to meet women in
college.''
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, couples can be seen nuzzling on the street
throughout the Silicon Valley. Whole families crowd into
restaurants. Getting a date is not an impossibility. Still, Bethany
Glover began calling her girlfriends after the San Jose Mercury
News dubbed the region ``Guyville U.S.A.'' and urging them to move
to Santa Clara County.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm telling them, `Honey, you've got to come down here,' ''
said Glover, a Harvard Law School student who is home for the
summer. ``There have got to be some good catches among the dorks.''
</P>
<P>
   Glover, engaged to be married in September 2000, can look on the
singles scene with a certain detached bemusement. So can Crystel
Milon, 30, who has a steady date, but still gets asked out _
sometimes when she is standing beside her boyfriend. She tells
about young men with six-figure incomes pulling out their credit
cards in clubs and offering to pay for women's drinks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's ridiculous how many men approach you,'' said Milon, a
saleclerk at an upscale Palo Alto boutique. ``They'll just say,
`Order whatever you want, it's on me.' They don't even want
anything for their money.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Glover, ``They do it because they can.''
</P>
<P>
   One 29-year-old bachelor who works in the high-tech financial
side said that sort of standard concerns him. He could easily
afford to pay for strangers' drinks. But he would rather not be
judged by his bank account.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look around,'' he said, declining to give his name and point
up his plight. ``Sometimes all you see are men, men, and more men.
But I figure it's like anything. If you try hard, you'll succeed no
matter the environment.'' He said his most recent date was just the
night before. He expects to call her again.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-18-99 1349EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990818.0120 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-18 13:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1563 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-WOM-VIDEO-BOS &LR;      08-18 0510
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOM-VIDEO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VIDEO TELLS THE STORY OF TEAM SPORTS AND GIRLS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN BICKELHAUPT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   About three years ago, Ann Troussieux of California was looking
around video stores in search of a tape that might show her then
4-year-old daughter what girls were doing in the world of sports.
She found videos about ballet, about gymnastics, or ones with
well-known (male) jocks like Steve Young, but nothing that showed
girls playing team sports.
</P>
<P>
   So, based on the research that had come out showing the positive
effects on sports on girls, combined with the lack of videos that
expressed that, Troussieux said she decided to fill the void.
</P>
<P>
   She called up friend and filmmaker Shelley Frost, and the two
went to work.
</P>
<P>
   The result is ``Real Girls, Real Sports,'' a half-hour video
that was released last month is available for $14.95 on the
Internet through www.amazon.com and www.throwlikeagirl.com.
</P>
<P>
   Frost, who had made three other videos, including one called
``Baby Mugs!'' of shots of babies, that sold over 500,000 copies,
and ``Kidstuff with Dick Clark,'' said she wanted to stay in the
video business, but with a different focus.
</P>
<P>
   She has a son _ not a daughter _ ``but I remember my teen years
well, and thought this had a lot of merit.''
</P>
<P>
   The two women went to soccer teams, softball teams, and boys'
and girls' clubs to interview hundreds of girls for the video. They
narrowed it down to five girls and their parents, ranging from
6-year-old Hannah, who is learning softball, to Sanam, a
13-year-old soccer player.
</P>
<P>
   The video that cost the two women less than $10,000 to produce
at times looks more like a home movie than the slick sneaker ad
that shows girls extolling the benefits of sports. And it's not
obviously not easy to elicit articulate ideas from the younger
girls with questions like, ``How does your body feel when you
play?'' (answer from the 6-year-old: ``I feel happy.'')
</P>
<P>
   But the older girls offer more thought-out ideas, like
12-year-old Katie, who talks about the boys in school putting down
the girls.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't think we can do as much, sport-wise, so they'll
challenge us to a basketball game at lunch, and I think the girls
really try and rise to the occasion,'' she says. Adds Sanam: ``I
don't care, I just want to do what I like to do.''
</P>
<P>
   The coaches and parents have their say too, as Hannah's mother
acknowledges: ``She's gained a lot of confidence, and we had
nothing to do with it.''
</P>
<P>
   The women producers, whose goal is to get the video on TV,
recently got a deal from Beyond Words Publishing to write a
companion book that will expand on the video by talking to women
who already have made it in sports, like Olympian softball player
Dot Richardson, or in their careers, like an astronaut, or a
company CEO.
</P>
<P>
   At any rate, Frost said she believes she's moved beyond the
children's videos she used to produce.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this can make a difference in lives,'' Frost said.
``Baby Mugs didn't.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
