eve of big anti-government rally Thursday. By Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   NKOREA-MISSILE (Tokyo) _ North Korea said Wednesday that it was
ready for negotiations over its reported plan to test launch a
long-range ballistic missile. The conciliatory gesture came amid
other indications that the country is willing to resolve the issue
through dialogue. By Calvin Sims.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   DRUG-USE-SURVEY (Washington) _ A new survey finds that drug use
among teen-agers has dropped to 9.9 percent from 11.4 percent in
1997. Overall drug use for the population as a whole is stable. By
Irvin Molotsky.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   JUDGES-DEATH-PENALTY (Atlanta) _ In a highly unusual meeting
that has angered death penalty opponents, southern federal judges
from the 11th circuit court of appeals are having a conference at a
super luxury resort on how to expedite capital punishment,
demonstrating the determined attempt to keep the death penalty
alive in the South. By David Firestone.
</P>
<P>
   LUTHERAN-EPISCOPAL (Denver) _ Amid intense and unusual church
politics, the legislative assembly of the nation's largest Lutheran
denomination has gathered to debate one of the most important
ecumenical proposals of the last 50 years, a sweeping agreement for
close cooperation between the Evangelical Lutheran Church in
America and the Episcopal Church, a plan that some are likening to
a marriage. If passed, it would bind the two denominations, each
highly influential among American Protestants and with a combined
membership of nearly 8 million people, in a pact to recognize each
other's sacraments, share clergy members where needed and engage in
joint missionary and social service work. By Gustav Niebuhr.
</P>
<P>
   DEPAW-GIFT DePaw University in Indiana gets one of largest gifts
ever, $130 million in Time Warner stock. By Jacques Steinberg.
</P>
<P>
   MISSING-EXEC (Chicago) _ The Coast Guard scoured Lake Michigan
on Wednesday for a paper company executive and his two daughters
after their sailboat was found drifting in the water. By Andrew
Bluth.
</P>
