<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-18 14:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1601 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-JOEMURRAY-COLUMN19-CO     08-18 0718
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOEMURRAY-COLUMN19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TALL TALES &AMP; SHORT STORIES: The trouble with being Hungary
 &HT;    (Eds: Last in a series. Cox Newspapers senior writer Joe Murray
reported from Eastern Europe during a visit 10 years ago, just
before the fall of the Berlin Wall. This summer he returned to
write about the changes that have led three former Eastern Bloc
countries _ Hungary, the Czech Republic and Poland _ to become the
newest members of NATO. At the end of the series, CoxNet will
compile some of these columns into our weekly Focus page, good for
running as a Perspective-type page or op-ed feature. The pages are
available for sale to non-Cox papers at
www.nytsyn.com/pageexpress.)
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By Joe Murray
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUDAPEST _ Hungary's geography is its history, both past and
future.
</P>
<P>
   Professor Ferenc Gazdag, 52, director of the Institute for
Strategic and Defense Studies for the past eight years, makes the
point well.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hungary is located at the very center of the conflict between
East and West,'' he said. The Kosovo war was no exception.
</P>
<P>
   Of the NATO countries, Hungary is the only one bordering all of
the former republics of Yugoslavia, in particular Serbia, which
includes 300,000 Hungarians living there as a minority.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, as a result of Hungary's territory being carved up after
World War I, there is a minority of Hungarians in all of its
neighboring countries.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hungary is the only nation in Europe that is surrounded by
themselves, by Hungarians,'' Professor Gazdag said.
</P>
<P>
   So it is that Hungary has ``a special interest in seeing
democracy spread and succeed'' throughout the region to bring
freedom to Hungarians everywhere, the professor said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The country, for centuries, has shared the same values as
Western Europe. Now, all of the political parties have agreed on
this much, to turn West.''
</P>
<P>
   Being a member of NATO, Gazdag said, is crucial for a smaller
country like Hungary.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you are not a member, you have no choice but to accept
their decision because of their power. If you are a member, you
have the power to influence that decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Hungary came eagerly into NATO, a move favored by 85 percent of
the voters in a referendum on joining.
</P>
<P>
   But the timing could not have been worse.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the NATO membership finally arrived, it was in the form
of the Kosovo war,'' Gazdag noted. ``It is like, `Welcome, and here
is your bill, please.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The feelings against air strikes ``were quite strong'' in
Hungary, he said. For one thing, there was the fear of refugees
pouring across the borders, though that never happened.
</P>
<P>
   But with the embargo against Serbia, the Hungarian economy has
paid a high price in the loss of exports.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not a matter of theory for us,'' the professor said.
``It is reality.''
</P>
<P>
   Now Hungary is faced with ``the delicate balance,'' Gazdag said,
``of keeping its borders open with Yugoslavia,'' serving as it does
as a channel for goods from Russia, including electrical power and
oil and gas pipelines.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Hungary waits for membership in the European Union,
which, Gazdag said, ``is the payoff'' in the form of aid for
economic development.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is our dream to join as soon as possible,'' he said. ``Up
until now, we are paying the price to be a part of the European
community. On the other side, we are not getting any of the special
funds to help our development.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Hungary's relations with the United States, ``We believe
the U.S. still has a role to play in Europe's security,'' he said.
``Only the U.S. has the capacity to stop the aspirations of
countries like Russia and China.''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout much of history, Hungary has served as a ``ferry
country'' between East and West, connecting one with the other.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is now our hope to anchor this small country on the Western
side,'' Gazdag said. ``If it is so, Hungary can be very optimistic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Still, we are on the borderline. This is the geography, and we
cannot change our geography.''
</P>
<P>
   (Joe Murray, editor-publisher emeritus of the Lufkin Daily News,
is senior writer for Cox Newspapers. Mailing address is P.O. Box
151108, Lufkin, Texas, 75915; e-mail jmurray(AT)lcc.net.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
