r p BC-BUSH-LAWSUITS-TEX     08-18 1044
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-LAWSUITS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AGENCY LAWSUITS COULD AFFECT BUSH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JAY ROOT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ As Gov. George W. Bush crisscrosses the country
in his bid for the White House, he is being targeted back home by
lawsuits that could wind up as fodder for political opponents.
</P>
<P>
   In one case, the controversy surrounding Bush's 1960s-era
service in the Texas Air National Guard _ and questions about how
he got in _ has become a subject of exploration. In another, Bush
has been subpoenaed to testify about a whistle-blower case
involving a politically connected funeral home company.
</P>
<P>
   Attorneys on both sides say politics has not affected their
approach to the lawsuits, but experts say candidates who run for
president can expect distracting and sometimes embarrassing legal
fights.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the greatest disadvantages of being a front-runner is
the nearly guaranteed onslaught of legal complaints,'' said Larry
Sabato, political scientist at the University of Virginia. ``That's
another (Bill Clinton) legacy.''
</P>
<P>
   In less than two weeks, the state attorney general's office will
go to court to try to quash a subpoena for Bush's testimony in
connection with the whistle-blower lawsuit involving funeral home
giant Service Corporation Int.
</P>
<P>
   ``We seek to find out what he knows and when he knew it,'' said
Derek Howard, a lawyer representing Eliza May, who claims she was
fired from her job as director of the Texas Funeral Service
Commission for pursuing an investigation of the funeral home's
embalming practices.
</P>
<P>
   Howard said the governor's political ambitions have no bearing
on the lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would be proceeding exactly how we are currently with or
without a presidential bid,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Nor are the lawsuits distracting the governor from his official
duties, Bush spokeswoman Linda Edwards said.
</P>
<P>
   ``A governor is high profile, and people often think of a
governor when they're naming people in a lawsuit against the
state,'' she said. ``It's part of being a public official.''
</P>
<P>
   Here is a rundown of some of the legal maneuvering involving the
governor or his office:
</P>
<P>
   _May contends that the Bush administration and a Democratic
state senator pressured her to drop her agency's investigation of
Service Corporation, the world's largest funeral services company.
</P>
<P>
   Houston-based SCI faces a record fine of $450,000 based on
allegations by the commission that unlicensed and unsupervised
workers were embalming bodies for the corporation's homes in Hurst
and Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   May is suing the state commission, the funeral home company, and
the company's chief executive officer, Robert Waltrip. The lawsuit
notes that Bush received $35,000 from SCI's political action
committee for his 1998 re-election bid, and that lawmakers who
sought information about the inquiry also received thousands of
dollars in contributions from the funeral home giant.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Bush, his staff, nor any state lawmaker is listed as a
defendant in the case.
</P>
<P>
   An SCI spokesman called the lawsuit politically motivated. Bush
filed an affidavit saying he played no role in May's Feb. 8 firing
and had no involvement in the state's investigation of the company
or any discussions with commission members or SCI officials about
the case.
</P>
<P>
   An SCI lobbyist gave a different story to Newsweek, saying Bush
ran into Waltrip outside his office and asked him if ``those people
\Rare\S still messing with you.''
</P>
<P>
   A hearing on the motion to quash Bush's subpoena is set for Aug.
30.
</P>
<P>
   _Lawyers for Lawrence Littwin, fired in 1997 as director of the
Texas Lottery, have notified the attorney general that they want to
question Bush about Littwin's lawsuit against Gtech, the company
that operates the game. Attorney General John Cornyn will fight any
subpoenas of Bush in the case, a spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   Littwin contends that he was fired for aggressively pursuing
what he believed were contract violations by Gtech. According to
court records, Littwin is pursuing a link that was alleged between
ex-Gtech lobbyist Ben Barnes and Bush. The lawsuit makes note of
allegations that Barnes, as House speaker in 1968, helped Bush get
into the Air National Guard to avoid serving in the Vietnam War.
</P>
<P>
   An unsigned letter sent to federal prosecutors in 1996, and
later obtained by Littwin's lawyers, alleges that a deal was
brokered whereby Gtech would keep its contract and Barnes would not
reveal his role in helping Bush get into the Guard.
</P>
<P>
   Gtech spokesman Marc Palazzo said ``that scenario goes well
beyond being factually incorrect. It's bizarre.'' He declined to
comment further about the suit because the case is pending.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, whose father was a Houston congressman at the time, has
denied that he used influence to get into the Guard. Barnes has not
revealed whether he had a role.
</P>
<P>
   _In two separate whistle-blower lawsuits, three former employees
of the governor's Criminal Justice Division claim they were fired
for reporting alleged violations of the law.
</P>
<P>
   In one suit, former employees Valerie Curbo and Carol
Funderburgh contend that a supervisor made disparaging remarks
about homosexuals when describing proposals to award crime victim
grants to gay rights groups.
</P>
<P>
   The other suit had been thrown out by a Travis County judge, but
last month an appeals court overturned the decision and revived the
lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   _The Sustainable Energy and Economic Development Coalition, a
Texas environmental group, has sued the Office of the Governor,
alleging violations of the Texas Open Records Act.
</P>
<P>
   At issue is a clean air initiative spearheaded by the governor's
office.
</P>
<P>
   The coalition contends that the governor's office is withholding
documents related to its effort to persuade ``grandfathered''
industrial plants to give up their exemptions to modern clean air
laws voluntarily.
</P>
<P>
   The governor's office said it has given the coalition all the
records related to the program and called the lawsuit a publicity
stunt.
</P>
<P>
   (Jay Root is Austin bureau chief for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call him at (512) 476-4294, or e-mail:
jroot(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
