<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-18 14:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1606 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r d BC-GETTINGJUICED-TEX     08-18 1118
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GETTINGJUICED-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXOTIC FRUIT DRINKS ARE EVERYONE'S FAVORITE SQUEEZE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BEVERLY BUNDY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Apple and orange? Kids' stuff. Grape? How ``passe.'' Cranberry?
So 1989.
</P>
<P>
   There's a brave new world of juices out there, and Americans are
bellying up to the bar to give them a try.
</P>
<P>
   Lime cactus quencher.
</P>
<P>
   Hibiscus cooler.
</P>
<P>
   Orange octane.
</P>
<P>
   Cranberry Saint Johnswort.
</P>
<P>
   Orchard oasis.
</P>
<P>
   From single-serve bottles in the convenience store cooler to
freshly squeezed iced quarts at the neighborhood health store to
family-size exotics in the supermarket aisles, consumers are
tapping into juices in a big way.
</P>
<P>
   The end-of-the-century trend to reach for ``grab-and-go'' food
to eat on the way to work, after a workout or sitting at the
computer is feeding the juice frenzy. Although soft drinks, coffee
and sports drinks have their places, they can't replace a sit-down
meal. Juice can.
</P>
<P>
   Like a lot of trends, the burgeoning juice market can be traced
to California.
</P>
<P>
   ``Juices really took off along coastal areas of the country,
particularly California,'' says Dan Titus, president of Juice
Gallery, a multimedia publishing and restaurant consulting firm for
the specialty foods service industry. ``There is a lot of
disposable income there, and a high awareness of health benefits.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1990, the Juice Club, the nation's first smoothie bar, opened
in San Luis Obispo, Calif. Juice Club was later renamed Jamba
Juice, and it's now a franchise of 250 smoothie bars. (Jamba Juice
recently acquired Zuka Juice, making it the second-largest player,
next to Smoothie King, in the juice bar jungle.)
</P>
<P>
   But the storefront operations are just one segment of the juice
movement. Juice bottlers are also experiencing ballooning growth
and adding products at a rapid clip.
</P>
<P>
   R.W. Knudsen has been producing natural juices since 1960, and
now has 200 flavors under that name and its Santa Cruz brand, an
all-organic line. Now the company is pumping up its Rocket Juice _
fresh-squeezed, all-natural and nutritionally fortified juices and
smoothies. It's 14 Carrot Calm includes passion flower and
chamomile, as well as antioxidants, vitamin C and folic acid.
</P>
<P>
   Knudsen spokeswoman Kirsten Spielmann sees the 78 million baby
boomers leading the trend, although she is quick to add that not
all boomers are alike.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are so many different reasons why consumers drink the
juice they do,'' Spielmann says. ``There's the environmentalist who
drinks organic juice because it's better for the planet; there are
people who want the nutriceuticals for health reasons; the
convenience seekers who reach for the aseptics for their kids; the
taste-sensation seekers who like the sensual pleasures of a coconut
or a mango.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think people are avoiding food and beverages that are high
in fat, high in sodium, things with preservatives,'' says Bruce
Langer, vice president of Langers Juice, another California company
that has been around since 1960. ``People realize consuming
vitamins and minerals is very important. They may not like taking a
pill, but they'll eat or drink something that has an enhancement.''
</P>
<P>
   To that end, Langers produces a ``100'' line that is 100 percent
juice with no added sugar and that provides 100 percent of the
daily requirement of vitamin C. ColdBuster 100 is an orange blend
pumped up with zinc and echinacea.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the whole craze can be put down to boomers who have
given up cigarettes and alcohol as they've aged and are looking for
some new indulgence, albeit a healthy one. Titus of Juice Gallery
doesn't disagree.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll have people over to the house and make up a batch of
smoothies and throw in some 151 rum,'' he says. ``They figure
they're one ahead with the smoothie and one behind with the rum, so
they end up at par.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   EL TOMATE CALIENTE
</P>
<P>
   Yields 4 cups
</P>
<P>
   2 cups tomato juice
</P>
<P>
   1/2 small jalapeno, chopped
</P>
<P>
   2 pinches cayenne pepper
</P>
<P>
   2 slices onion, chopped (about 1/4 cup)
</P>
<P>
   2 pinches parsley
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons garlic power
</P>
<P>
   Place all ingredients in blender and mix on high speed for 30
seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Pour into tall glasses and serve.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per cup: 33 calories, 0 fat, 8 grams
carbohydrates, 1 gram protein, 0 cholesterol, 442 milligrams
sodium.
</P>
<P>
   _''Great American Smoothies'' by Gabriel Constans (Avery, $9.95)
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   THE BETA-CAROTENE QUEEN
</P>
<P>
   Yields 4 cups
</P>
<P>
   2 apricots, pitted and sliced
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups carrot juice
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup peeled and sliced mango
</P>
<P>
   1 cup peeled and chopped papaya
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons frozen orange juice concentrate or 1 cup fresh
orange juice
</P>
<P>
   Place all ingredients in a blender and blend on low for 1
minute.
</P>
<P>
   Pour into tall glasses and serve.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per cup: 100 calories, 0 fat, 24 grams
carbohydrates, 2 grams protein, 0 cholesterol, 29 milligrams
sodium.
</P>
<P>
   _''Great American Smoothies''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   KIWI FRUIT COCKTAIL
</P>
<P>
   Serves 3-4
</P>
<P>
   1 frozen banana
</P>
<P>
   3 fresh, ripe kiwi fruit
</P>
<P>
   1 cup apple juice
</P>
<P>
   2 cups coconut-fruit juice blend
</P>
<P>
   Strawberries, for garnish
</P>
<P>
   Peel fresh, ripe banana and freeze until hard. Peel and slice
kiwi fruit. Break banana into small chunks. Combine kiwi, banana
and juices in blender. Puree smooth. Garnish servings with fresh
strawberries.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving for 4: 156 calories, 3 grams
fat, 44 grams carbohydrates, 1 gram protein, 0 cholesterol, 40
milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   _''Super Smoothies'' by Candia Lea Cole (Woodbridge, $12.95)
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   PINEAPPLE ZEST
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4
</P>
<P>
   1/4-1/3 cup dried cranberries
</P>
<P>
   1 cup fresh pineapple chunks
</P>
<P>
   1 medium-large, fresh, red-skinned apple, lightly peeled
</P>
<P>
   1 to 2 tablespoons orange juice concentrate (or 1/4 teaspoon
orange flavoring)
</P>
<P>
   1/8-1/4 cup fresh, raw almonds, optional
</P>
<P>
   1 to 2 tablespoons honey
</P>
<P>
   1 cup apple juice
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup pear juice or water
</P>
<P>
   Combine cranberries, pineapple, fresh apples, honey and juices
in blender. Puree until smooth. If using nuts, grind to fine powder
using an electric seed grinder before adding to blender.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving without almonds: 111 calories,
0 fat, 29 grams carbohydrates, 1 gram protein, 0 cholesterol, 4
milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   _''Super Smoothies''
</P>
