   OTHER NATIONAL NEWS . . .
</P>
<P>
   SKOL-SUMMIT _ COLUMBUS, Ohio _ A violence prevention specialist
keynotes the Safe Schools Summit in Columbus, Ohio, sponsored by
Gov. Bob Taft and Attorney General Betty Montgomery. The two-day
summit is in reaction to the recent school violence and concern
over increasing problems with juvenile
</P>
<P>
   crime. (Wagner, Dayton Daily News). 20.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: ETA: 9 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   HARTSFIELD _ ATLANTA _ Atlanta's Hartsfield International
Airport was without power for 22 minutes starting at 2:26 a.m. EDT
Wednesday. Georgia Power says the main lines to the airport failed.
Because of power problems, airport trains didn't run and the air
conditioning shut down, creating travel misery Wednesday. Full
power was to be restored by 1 p.m. EDT. 18. (Montgomery/Puckett,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution). WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   GENE-ALTERING _ Emory researchers have genetically engineered
mice to be more sociable, by implanting a gene from a species of
vole known for being gregarious and monogamous. No, it's not
available for use on co-workers, neighbors or relatives, but
someday the experiment could lead to treatment for autistic
children. With art of sociable voles vs. antisocial voles. (Kim,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in (a) General News and (l) Lifestyle categories.
</P>
<P>
   UNC-CHANCELLOR _ Chapel Hill's interim chancellor, appointed
following the death of Michael Hooker, is Bill McCoy, a former
BellSouth exec in Atlanta. who faces a tough job following Hooker's
unexpected death from cancer. UNC is facing budget shortfalls and
legislative opposition to the university system's efforts to sell
several billion in bonds for new buildings and other improvements.
(Burritt, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 25.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS-DROPOUTS _ WASHINGTON _ The political battlefield is
littered with the bodies of high-flying presidential candidates who
crashed and burned. Like Texas Sen. Phil Gramm, who outspent his
candidates in primary elections four years ago but managed only a
handful of votes. Or John Glenn, the astronaut-turned-senator who
seemed to have the right stuff but whose candidacy fizzled on the
launch pad. What did these presidential wannabes learn from their
humbling electoral defeats? How hard was it to cope with resounding
rejection? (Shepard, Cox News Service). 25.
</P>
<P>
   Moving in (w) Washington and (p) politics categories.
</P>
<P>
   BAXTER-COLUMN _ Newt Gingrich's messy divorce is probably the
final nail in his political coffin. (Baxter, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 10.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   SIERRA _ When Milton Boyle returned to his homeland of Sierra
Leone earlier this year, fighting swept through the capital of
Freetown. Peeking out the window as he cowered on the floor, Boyle
saw rebel soldiers committing atrocities. But he is ready to
forgive, in the name of peace. Nevertheless, the recent peace deal
ending Sierra Leone's brutal civil war is highly controversial. It
gives rebels who, as a means of sowing terror, lopped off the hands
of thousands of civilians and children, several seats in a new
government. U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan has urged that the
deal be implemented. But Human Rights Watch says the deal rewards
brutal criminals _ in contrast to the treatment afforded Slobodan
Milosevic, who was indicted in the midst of the Kosovo crisis. Is
forgiveness, even of unspeakable atrocities, sometimes warranted to
save a country from the total destruction of war? Or do such deals
reward and even encourage grotesque criminal behavior? We look at
the issue through the eyes of metro area Sierra Leoneans, some of
whom are once again considering going home. (Melvin, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 35.
</P>
