NYT-08-18-99 1439EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990818.0128 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-18 14:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1612 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r k BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX     08-18 0733
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHY DO SUCH FOLKS STAY IN THE PRESIDENTIAL RACE?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILL THOMPSON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's hard to imagine what sort of self-deluding fantasy caused
Lamar Alexander to run for president _ and caused him to keep
running for years after voters had made it perfectly clear that
they had no interest in him.
</P>
<P>
   But give him credit for finally facing reality the other day and
withdrawing from a race in which his only identifiable function was
to whine about the apparent invincibility of front-runner George W.
Bush. After finishing a dismal sixth in the Iowa straw poll over
the weekend, Alexander wisely gave up the ghost in his no-chance
campaign for the Republican Party's 2000 presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, Alexander did not give up his penchant for
sniping at Bush _ even though the former Tennessee governor
grudgingly conceded the inevitability of the current Texas
governor's nomination to head the GOP ticket. Alexander refused to
endorse Bush, steadfastly clinging to the ridiculous proposition
that Bush is not ready to be president.
</P>
<P>
   Bush refused to be lured into a spitting contest with an
ex-candidate whom he had already vanquished.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lamar is a good man who poured his heart into his campaign,''
Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   No surprise there. Bush is always more gracious to his opponents
than his opponents are to him.
</P>
<P>
   The first time Bush ran for governor, incumbent Ann Richards
spent the entire campaign lobbing petty, personal insults at Bush.
He never returned the fire, choosing to devote his time and energy
to articulating his vision for the future of Texas. He just isn't
interested in negative campaigning.
</P>
<P>
   Before Alexander dropped out of the race, it was easy enough to
dismiss his negativity as a symptom of desperation. Bush's
fund-raising juggernaut had made it virtually impossible for an
also-ran such as Alexander to corral campaign contributions;
frustration can engender bitterness.
</P>
<P>
   But why keep up the attack after quitting the campaign? When
Ohio Rep. John Kasich folded his tent several weeks ago, he
immediately endorsed the front-runner and enthusiastically jumped
aboard the Bush bandwagon.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Alexander will get with the program after he's taken some
time to wrestle with the disappointment of shutting down a campaign
that dominated his life for more than six years. He's probably
earned the right to sulk for a while.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's Dan Quayle. The only thing the ex-veep has earned
is the scorn of sensible Republicans who would like to know why in
the world he decided to get into the presidential race. He wasn't
qualified to be president when he was vice president, and he's not
qualified now.
</P>
<P>
   How unqualified is he? Well, he finished behind Alan Keyes in
the Iowa straw poll _ and absolutely no one considers Keyes to be a
serious contender for the Republican presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Quayle's insistence on remaining in the race proves beyond any
doubt what some of us have been saying about Danny Boy all along:
Once a nitwit, always a nitwit.
</P>
<P>
   The other Republican contenders are hardly nitwits, but most of
them seem to have put their brains on ice while mindlessly pursuing
a goal that they cannot attain. For all his money, Steve Forbes
will never be the Republican nominee for president. For all her
experience, charm and charisma, Elizabeth Dole is destined to
finish up the track in this particular presidential race.
</P>
<P>
   The others _ Gary Bauer, Pat Buchanan, Keyes, Orrin Hatch, John
McCain _ are beating their heads against a brick wall. Maybe
they're doing it because it will feel so good when they stop;
surely none of them can believe that he will overtake Bush.
</P>
<P>
   They are all interesting candidates. They all have something to
offer in the way of ideas or leadership or just plain
entertainment. But they are going nowhere.
</P>
<P>
   The also-rans and the Bush-haters were hoping that the Texas
governor would stumble in the Iowa straw poll, that the Bush
bandwagon would be derailed in the first formal test of the 2000
campaign. He didn't. It wasn't.
</P>
<P>
   The Bush Express keeps rolling on. Destination: White House.
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Thompson is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can contact him at (817) 390-7787. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
