 AM-R-NYT-BUDGET  
(gm) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; FOR THURSDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Thursday, Aug. 19.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   TURKEY-QUAKE (Istanbul) _ Ledeall on the earthquake: The death
toll climbs to 3,500 as workers continue digging for survivors. By
Stephen Kinzer.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   TURKEY-CENTER (Izmit, Turkey) _ The story from the city at the
center of the earthquake. There are incredible scenes of
destruction; the oil refinery is still burning and exploding. By
Edmund L. Andrews.
</P>
<P>
   And
</P>
<P>
   TURKEY-SCENE (Dateline to kum) _ A second feature, details to be
determined, on the aftermath of the earthquake in northwest Turkey.
By Celestine Bohlen.
</P>
<P>
   YUGOSLAVIA-POLITICS (Belgrade) _ Political developments on the
eve of big anti-government rally Thursday. By Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   NKOREA-MISSILE (Tokyo) _ North Korea said Wednesday that it was
ready for negotiations over its reported plan to test launch a
long-range ballistic missile. The conciliatory gesture came amid
other indications that the country is willing to resolve the issue
through dialogue. By Calvin Sims.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   DRUG-USE-SURVEY (Washington) _ A new survey finds that drug use
among teen-agers has dropped to 9.9 percent from 11.4 percent in
1997. Overall drug use for the population as a whole is stable. By
Irvin Molotsky.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   JUDGES-DEATH-PENALTY (Atlanta) _ In a highly unusual meeting
that has angered death penalty opponents, southern federal judges
from the 11th circuit court of appeals are having a conference at a
super luxury resort on how to expedite capital punishment,
demonstrating the determined attempt to keep the death penalty
alive in the South. By David Firestone.
</P>
<P>
   LUTHERAN-EPISCOPAL (Denver) _ Amid intense and unusual church
politics, the legislative assembly of the nation's largest Lutheran
denomination has gathered to debate one of the most important
ecumenical proposals of the last 50 years, a sweeping agreement for
close cooperation between the Evangelical Lutheran Church in
America and the Episcopal Church, a plan that some are likening to
a marriage. If passed, it would bind the two denominations, each
highly influential among American Protestants and with a combined
membership of nearly 8 million people, in a pact to recognize each
other's sacraments, share clergy members where needed and engage in
joint missionary and social service work. By Gustav Niebuhr.
</P>
<P>
   DEPAW-GIFT DePaw University in Indiana gets one of largest gifts
ever, $130 million in Time Warner stock. By Jacques Steinberg.
</P>
<P>
   MISSING-EXEC (Chicago) _ The Coast Guard scoured Lake Michigan
on Wednesday for a paper company executive and his two daughters
after their sailboat was found drifting in the water. By Andrew
Bluth.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   HOUTKIN-DAY-TRADING (Undated) _ Harvey Houtkin, chief executive
officer of All-Tech Investment Group, one of the nation's largest
day-trading firms, fervently believes that securities regulators
are out to get him. But he also has absolutely no doubt that he
will go down in history as a man who made Wall Street a better
place for the small investor. By Gretchen Morgenson.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-MESSAGING (Palo Alto, Calif.) _ In the latest round in
its battle with America Online over instant messaging, Microsoft is
publishing the code to its instant messaging service in the hope
that other developers will use it. By Matt Richtel.
</P>
<P>
   SAKS-OUTLOOK (Undated) _ Saks Inc. shares plunge as much as 29
percent after the retailer warns that earnings this year will fall
short of expectations because of problems at its Saks Fifth Avenue
department stores and its regional chains.
</P>
<P>
   FOODLION-HANNAFORD (Undated) _ Food Lion Inc., one of the
largest grocers in the Southeast, has agreed to buy Hannaford
Brothers, a big chain in New England, for $3.3 billion. By Dana
Canedy.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-ECON (Beijing) _ Looking at China's efforts to fight
deflation and what it may mean for its currency. By Seth Faison.
</P>
<P>
   KOREA-DAEWOO (Seoul, South Korea) _ Daewoo Group meets with
foreign creditors for the first time since the escalation of the
conglomerate's crisis this summer to negotiate nearly $10 billion
in debt.
</P>
<P>
   VESPA-INVEST (Rome) _ The Italian maker of the Vespa motor
scooter, immortalized by Gregory Peck and Audrey Hepburn in ``Roman
Holiday,'' is about to get an an American investor. Piaggio Veicoli
Europei SpA says it is in advanced talks on a sale of a stake in
the company to Texas Pacific Group, already an investor in
Piaggio's Italian rival Ducati. By John Tagliabue.
</P>
<P>
   NEWSCORP-EARNINGS (Undated) _ The News Corp., the media company
controlled by Rupert Murdoch, says its fiscal fourth-quarter profit
fell 20 percent on costs associated with the start up of its Fox
news channel and lower revenue at The Sun newspaper. The results
were weaker than expected.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ Stocks were mixed in early afternoon. At
1:30 p.m. the Dow industrials were down 77, while the Nasdaq index
was up 3. By Robert D. Hershey Jr.
</P>
<P>
   ECONSCENE (Undated) _ The weekly Economic Scene column. By
Michel M. Weinstein.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY &LR;  (``k'' code)
</P>
<P>
   Bob Herbert's ``In America.''
</P>
<P>
   William Safire is on vacation.
</P>
<P>
