<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-18 15:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1650 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s BC-FBN-FASSEL-HNS &LR;      08-18 1172
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FASSEL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FASSEL MAKES THE RIGHT CALL ON FAMILY MATTERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEVE CAMPBELL  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ His gravely ill mother needed him. Now. Not when
it would be a little more convenient. His family needed him. Now.
Not when it would be a little more convenient. His football team
needs him all the time, judging by the round-the-clock,
round-the-calendar application of nose to the grindstone.
</P>
<P>
   A convenient time for Jim Fassel to tear himself away from his
responsibilities as coach of the New York Giants?
</P>
<P>
   Wait till next career.
</P>
<P>
   Fassel knew what he needed to do, and it wasn't quit his job. He
knew where he and his priorities needed to be, but it wasn't that
simple. National Football League coaches aren't in the habit of
giving themselves permission to be human.
</P>
<P>
   Fassel needed a little reinforcement.
</P>
<P>
   He needed a little peace of mind, some sort of assurance that
leaving his team for a few days during training camp didn't make
him unfit for office at Giants Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   He needed to hear from Giants defensive coordinator John Fox.
</P>
<P>
   More than a decade ago, Fox was trying to make a name and a
career for himself. Fox was in his first year as defensive
coordinator at the University of Pittsburgh, and his mother, Kaye,
was critically ill in San Diego. She had cancer. She was running
out of time.
</P>
<P>
   Fox had a scrimmage that he was absolutely convinced couldn't go
on without him. He left the day after the scrimmage to be by his
mother's side. He got there five minutes after she died. He'll
regret it to the day he dies.
</P>
<P>
   ``What he said to me was, `This is a prime example of why you've
got to take care of family business right now,''' Fassel said.
</P>
<P>
   Fassel was back for football business at the State University of
New York at Albany campus Tuesday morning. He had been away since
Thursday, when he left camp to be at his 76-year-old mother's side
at the Mayo Clinic in Scottsdale, Ariz. Dorothy Fassel is off a
ventilator and receiving dialysis treatments for kidney problems.
She is feeling strong enough to insist that her son get back to
work.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've made the statement to our staff, and I've made the
statement to my players at different times: We need your undivided
intention, your focus,'' Fassel said. ``This is an all-consuming
business. The only thing that should come in front of that would be
your family if they need you. I've told them that, so I need to
heed my own advice.''
</P>
<P>
   It says a lot about the coaching culture that Fassel would find
it necessary to do any soul-searching at all when it comes to
tending to a loved one. The work of NFL coaches, in particular,
never seems to be done. It's not a profession. It's an obsession.
</P>
<P>
   Practices. Meetings. Videotape sessions. Exhibition games.
Regular-season games. Playoffs. Evaluating college prospects.
Evaluating and recruiting free agents. Mini-camps. More mini-camps.
Training camp. Life is what happens to other people.
</P>
<P>
   NFL coaches wear their single-mindedness, their workaholism,
like a badge of honor. If an NFL coach ever figured out how to win
while working a 9-to-5 schedule, his colleagues would look down on
him for not breaking something so he'd have to spend time fixing
it.
</P>
<P>
   No wonder coaches burn out faster than double-A batteries. No
wonder the Jets' Bill Parcells refers to two years as a head coach
as ``a lifetime.'' No wonder Jimmy Johnson shows up for work one
day in January fully intending to resign. Johnson allowed himself
to be talked into giving the Miami Dolphins one more chance because
he, like so many others, is addicted to the chase of championships.
</P>
<P>
   Remember how Johnson's voice broke that day, describing the
changes that came over him after his mother's death the previous
month? The day after her death, Johnson had been on the sidelines
for a Monday night game against Denver. He missed the viewing of
her body and was having a hard time forgiving himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``You talk to coaches around the league, and they say, `First
comes my religion and second comes my family and third comes
football,''' Johnson said. ``And yet, they work at football 15, 16
hours a day, seven days a week. Well, that tells me football was
first. They go to church for an hour a week and they're with their
family two hours a week. So it looks to me like it was football, a
little bit of family and a little bit of religion.''
</P>
<P>
   Dan Reeves spent weeks last season ignoring a burning sensation
in his chest similar to the one that led to two angioplasties in
1990. Reeves wound up undergoing quadruple-bypass surgery that
doctors suspect came just in time to head off a massive heart
attack. He was on the sideline for a playoff game 26 days after the
bypass surgery.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be more stressful not to coach,'' Reeves explained.
</P>
<P>
   St. Louis Rams coach Dick Vermeil, the founding father of the
burnout syndrome, didn't leave his team for a single day last
season after a fire killed his sister-in-law and seriously injured
his brother. And the Rams were 4-11 and headed nowhere at that
point.
</P>
<P>
   Former Redskins coach Joe Gibbs used to sleep in his office
three nights a week. His wife periodically sent tapes to keep him
up to date with the lives of their children. Parcells couldn't find
the time to attend the Hall-of-Fame induction of Lawrence Taylor,
the player most responsible for making Super Bowl winners out of
the 1986 and 1990 Giants. The Jets, you see, had a scrimmage. So
when Fassel abruptly left training camp, Giants players understood
the significance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him that I think that the best coaching decision he has
ever made was to go home and see his mother,'' Giants defensive end
Michael Strahan said. ``Had he not, his mind wouldn't have been
here and he would have regretted it. I think he did the right
thing.''
</P>
<P>
   He did the human thing _ in a sport that isn't in the habit of
recognizing humanity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes you can get caught up in the business and not
realize that the guys really are your family, and that you do have
a family outside of this,'' Strahan said. ``When you see somebody
on the team who is having a situation like Coach Fassel has, it
makes you realize you need to get closer.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first thing I did was call my mom, just to give myself a
little better feeling. Also, you try to console him and let him
know we're all behind him. We're with him. The last thing he needs
to worry about is us.''
</P>
<P>
   The Giants gave Fassel one less worry by pounding the Minnesota
Vikings on Friday night, 36-21. Fassel watched the first half on
television in his mother's hospital room. He watched the second
half at his hotel, surrounded by other family members. It was a
great escape from life.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, being back at work presents another set of realities.
``It's good to have you back,'' John Fox said upon spotting Fassel
back in camp. Fox couldn't resist adding, ``Get some rest.''
</P>
<P>
   There's work to be done, and it can't wait.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
