<HEADER>
A1655 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k BC-RAISA-GORBY-ILLNESS-N     08-18 2390
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAISA-GORBY-ILLNESS-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORBACHEV'S SAD MISSION: TO SOOTHE HIS AILING WIFE, RAISA 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (To publish this ``separate buy'' article, it must be purchased
_ the rate is not prohibitive _ from one of these New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives: 
 &HT;    (--U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at
1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697. 
 &HT;    (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-798-0970;
fax, 310-798-7338.) 
 &HT;    
 By GIULIETTO CHIESA  
 c.1999 La Stampa  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   MUENSTER, Germany _ It's a little past 11 at night, and Mikhail
Gorbachev has just appeared on the tree-lined path that leads to
the hotel. He's walking slowly, with his shoulders hunched over and
his arms behind his back. He's wearing a blue T-shirt and a pair of
new blue jeans. A few steps behind him, one of two bodyguards is
carrying the black bag that goes with Gorbachev wherever he goes.
It's a reminder of the famous ``nuclear'' bag, which hasn't been
his for years now. But this bag remains filled with mysterious
things the former Soviet president doesn't want to be without.
</P>
<P>
   I don't remember having ever seen Gorbachev so strained. It
makes me think of that photograph of Raisa and him on the mobile
staircase of the airplane that had just landed in Moscow, after
they had been held for three days under house arrest by armed
emissaries of the August 1991 coup. His wife was visibly shaken,
but the eyes of the president were flashing like those of a tiger.
</P>
<P>
   Now the light is gone in that weary gaze. He's clearly moved and
gives me a quiet hug. ``So good of you to come, let's go get
something to eat.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, he's tired. He says so: ``The first 10 days were very rough
_ I was alone. Irina (his daughter) came once she'd settled things
in Moscow and brought along the grandchildren (Xenia and Nastia). I
wanted _ and had _ to stay with Raisa Maksimovna all the time. They
were sleepless nights both for her and for me, and I had to help
her change her position every 10 minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   With a melancholy smile, he goes on: ``Now I've got a terrible
back pain that never lets up. You know, it's exactly like that kind
of movement they advise weightlifters to avoid, where you bend over
to lift something. And I did it 40 times a night!''
</P>
<P>
   He eats some salad and a yogurt, but I can see that he wants to
talk, to tell his story. Things are going a little better now, he
tells me. Irina goes to the clinic early in the morning to see her
mother and stays there till 2 p.m. Then it's his turn to take care
of Raisa until the evening.
</P>
<P>
   ``We talk a lot. I don't leave until I see that she is
relatively calm. For the first few days she was so exhausted. She
suffered a lot. The treatment is so violent, so harsh,'' he sighs.
</P>
<P>
   He shows me the most recent batch of letters of support. On top
of a pile is one from Vitali Tretiakov, a mutual friend, director
of the Nezavisimaia Gazeta. I catch a glance at phrases that I too
would have liked to write: ``Mikhail Sergeivich, I'm with you. But
please think of your own health too, try not to overdo things.''
</P>
<P>
   Gorbachev shakes his head forcefully. ``No! I am not leaving
here, no matter what happens, I am staying with her. Do you see? It
makes all the difference for her, and also for me. In certain
moments of life you realize that some things have become crucial.
You feel friendship, human warmth in a completely different way. I
tried to understand the nature of this illness, but then I gave up.
I have confidence in the doctors. But I feel that it is vital to
stay close to her. And Professor Buchner (the head doctor) says the
same thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Raisa Maksimovna had learned of the diagnosis only a few days
earlier. The compassionate attempt to keep her mind free of the bad
news couldn't last for long. It was one of her own questions that
put Gorbachev up against the wall.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never told her a lie in my entire life. She knows that _
so she didn't ask the doctor, she asked me. I told her yes, it was
a form of leukemia, one of the many different ones. She closed her
eyes and remained silent for 40 minutes. I didn't dare to break
into that silence, which seemed to last an eternity. That was the
hardest moment. I tried to imagine what she was thinking. Then
Professor Buchner arrived and he helped me by explaining everything
to her in complete candor. He showed her the lab reports and told
her there was hope. He was persuasive, and he provided a bit of
relief for me too.''
</P>
<P>
   The internal medicine clinic at University Hospital in Muenster
is one of the world's finest treatment centers. Gorbachev and Irina
recount in detail all the steps, from discovering the illness to
her hospitalization in Germany. The original diagnosis was made in
Moscow by Dr. Andrej Vorobiof of the Central Clinic, the famous
``ZKB'' of the Kremlin.
</P>
<P>
   It was Vorobiof who stressed the urgency of a full examination
and suggested the best therapeutic facilities in the world. That
was on July 21. The German and U.S. ambassadors in Moscow were
immediately contacted and they responded within a few hours with
proposals for treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Muenster was chosen because of its proximity to Moscow. On Fri.,
July 23, the German doctors, Buchner of Munster and Mertelsmann of
Freiburg, were already in Moscow to confer with Vorobiof. They
confirmed his diagnosis, and by Sun., July 25, Raisa was already in
the high-tech room of the transplant department of the Muenster
clinic.
</P>
<P>
   To enter this room you must remove all your clothing, put on
sterilized clothes and cover your mouth with a mask. The hundreds
and hundreds of letters that keep arriving for Mrs. Gorbachev are
not even allowed into the ward. They are rerouted to the hotel room
of Karen Karagesianz, the press secretary of The Gorbachev
Foundation, who interrupted his vacation in order to be at the
former Soviet president's side.
</P>
<P>
   Next morning, I enter that hotel room _ insofar as one can say
``enter'' _ for there is already a huge stack of letters and the
bed can be reached only by a slalom through the packages of mail.
It takes hours just to hurriedly open the letters, in order to look
at the signatures, but a team of secretaries would be needed to
read and organize them.
</P>
<P>
   I cannot help but inquire: how did Raisa get to Muenster so
fast? It's certain that she came by plane. And not on a commercial
flight. I can't resist asking: Was it the Russian government? Did
Russia provide a plane? Gorbachev shakes his head. He would rather
not talk about this. Irina also keeps mum, despite herself.
</P>
<P>
   Two days earlier, following most all of the others, a telegram
arrived from Boris Yeltsin (after those from the Clintons, Gerhard
Schroeder, Lionel Jospin, the Nazarbayevs, George Bush, Mrs.
Thatcher and countless other world leaders, past and present, as
well as Nobel Prize winners and international cultural and
religious figures).
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin's telegram reads: ``I want to express my deep concern
for the ordeal that your family is going through. I know well how
hard it is to experience the illness of a loved one. More than
ever, in moments like these, mutual support, warmth and caring are
needed. I wish for you, my esteemed Mikhail Sergeivich, strength
and perseverance and, for Raisa Maksimovna, courage in her struggle
against the disease as well as a speedy recovery.''
</P>
<P>
   It's the first time in the last nine years that Boris Yeltsin
has addressed himself directly to Mikhail Gorbachev, and the former
Soviet president clearly doesn't want to stir up any controversy.
He remarks: ``They're kind words, a very nice gesture.''
</P>
<P>
   So I have to look elsewhere to quench my curiosity about what
airplane carried the patient and Gorbachev from Moscow. It turns
out that it was a plane that departed from a Swiss airport and was
flying the Swiss flag. It also appears (although this remains
unconfirmed) that the aircraft was rented by the Greek shipowner
Lazis, a close friend of the Gorbachev family since faraway 1992.
</P>
<P>
   So the Gorbachevs didn't get their airplane from the Russian
government. Or was it that they didn't ask for one and simply
preferred to arrange things by themselves? Right now there's no
answer to these questions and, in the final analysis, they're of
little importance in light of the human drama confronting Gorbachev
and his wife.
</P>
<P>
   Next morning, while Irina takes her turn in the clinic and after
Mikhail Sergeivich finishes updating reporters, we go for a long
walk in the park.
</P>
<P>
   People stop and stare at Gorbachev. You can hear the screeching
of brakes _ it's as if they come from the thousands of bicycles on
the winding streets of Muenster and the green plains of Westphalia.
Occasionally someone comes up to Gorbachev and shakes his hand.
Others simply say, ``Thank you.''
</P>
<P>
   A well-dressed, elderly gentleman says to him, first in German
and then in English: ``You are the Napoleon of our time.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Thank you,'' Gorbachev says, in a forceful German _ and then,
snickering to me sotto voce: ``It is not a great compliment. He
ended up on Saint Helena. And besides he was more of a general than
a reformer.''
</P>
<P>
   Raisa slept better, he says, and the temperature she was running
since the night before last has disappeared. So Gorbachev is in a
better mood. And while it's too bad that it has come at such a
time, he's clearly happy with the coverage of Raisa's story in the
Russian media. It's a kind of moral recompense that seems to
somewhat soothe the wounds of being ignored for so long.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you want to know something?'' he asks. ``I never expected
this from the Russians. I thought it would take a whole generation
before they understood. But I see that not one bad word has been
written against her, or against me. It's as if our pain has broken
through all of that lack of understanding.''
</P>
<P>
   He has tears in his eyes, and this time he doesn't try to hide
them. He shakes his head and puts his fingers over his eyes _ then
takes a newspaper clipping from his pocket. ``Read this.''
</P>
<P>
   And while he tries to recompose himself, I read an article from
Izvestiya, headlined ``Ledi Dostoinstvo,'' the Lady of Dignity:
``Maybe we Russians are becoming people again. ... We seem not to
have lost the capacity to share the pain of others. ... It may be
only this sad occasion, but we are showing great respect for two
people who love each other, Raisa and Mikhail.''
</P>
<P>
   With interest, I read on: ``Diminutive and elegant, with
sophisticated tastes, she is not like the others. She has been the
symbol of a country that wanted to free itself from its dreary
greyness. People didn't understand her, or perhaps they didn't want
to understand her. Maybe too much was asked of them when the couple
was in power. But it's also true that no one was able to bend their
will and subordinate them.''
</P>
<P>
   And did Raisa read the article? ``Yes, she read it and cried. I
think she has never read so many expressions of tenderness and
admiration for her before.''
</P>
<P>
   Mikhail Sergeivich once again has the look of somebody ready for
battle. ``I remember,'' he says, ``how they wrote that Raisa went
shopping in London with an American Express card, when we didn't
even know what a credit card was. Or when they spread rumors that
Raisa was spending great sums of capital to compete with Nancy
Reagan, when in actual fact all of her wardrobe and personal things
were made for her by Tamara Makeeva in Moscow.''
</P>
<P>
   Mikhail Gorbachev is smiling, as if a great weight has been
lifted from him.
</P>
<P>
   Later, in his hotel room, he shows me the telegram sent by Bill
and Hillary Clinton: ``For a long time we have admired your grace
and composure while supporting the unprecedented changes throughout
the courageous political activity of your husband. ...''
</P>
<P>
   In a certain sense, it's the same acknowledgment that came from
Isvestiya, only this time expressed in English.
</P>
<P>
   Gorbachev searches through the load of letters and finds one
from Giulio Andreotti, the former Italian prime minister: ``Dear
friend, I am following with great concern what's happening to
Raisa, and I hope you will consider me at your disposal for
whatever you may require. You are in my prayers.''
</P>
<P>
   It pleases Gorbachev; he speaks with simple, grateful words:
``You know, some letters arrive written just as you might think
they would be, but it's very satisfying to get them anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   That evening, after finishing his turn at Raisa's bedside, I
find Gorbachev again walking around the gardens in a light summer
rain that gives off a warm, fragrant mist. In the quiet there, his
voice comes, as if he is thinking out loud, firm and soft, but also
with the resoluteness of a decision already made: ``Raisa said
something very important to me today. 'When I recover, if I
recover, let's find a little house somewhere, near the sea, where
there's a lot of sunshine, so that we can enjoy these last years we
have.' And I thought to myself: 'Yes, she's really right. It's time
to live out fully, with our feelings, these last years we have.'''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Giulietto Chiesa is the Moscow bureau chief of La Stampa. He
covered the former Soviet Union, and the political career of
Mikhail Gorbachev, from his ascendancy in 1985 through his
resignation as president in 1991, as well as his post-Cold War work
as head of The Gorbachev Foundation: An International Foundation
for Socioeconomic and Political Studies. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Chiesa is also the author of several books about Gorbachev and
Russia, including ``Tiempo di cambiare'' (``Time of Change'')
written with Roy Medvedev, 1990; ``Cronache del golpe rosso''
(``Chronicles of the Red Coup''), 1991; ``Transition to
Democracy,'' 1991; and ``Russia addio'' (``Farewell to Russia''),
1997. Among many awards, Chiesa has received the Premio
Saint-Vincent for journalism, in Italy, and he was named last
year's best foreign correspondent in Moscow by a jury of Russian
journalists.) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ------------------ &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
