<TEXT>
<P>
   Raisa Gorbachev, the former Soviet first lady, was admitted to
the University Hospital in Muenster, Germany, on July 25 to undergo
chemotherapy for leukemia. Mikhail Gorbachev, who is at his wife's
bedside, has for the first time in nine years been greeted by Boris
Yeltsin, in a telegram to the hospital _ although, indeed, it
arrived after other messages from the Clintons, Margaret Thatcher,
George Bush and scores of world leaders. The New York Times
Syndicate is offering an exclusive report from inside the clinic:
``Gorbachev's Sad Mission,'' slugged BC-RAISA-GORBY-ILLNESS. The
author, Giulietto Chiesa, Moscow bureau chief for La Stampa, has
covered Gorbachev since 1985 and written numerous books about
Russia.
</P>
