<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-18 15:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1660 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k BC-PATRICIA-IRELAND-INTE     08-18 1855
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PATRICIA-IRELAND-INTERVIEW-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EVENTS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 PATRICIA IRELAND ON CLINTON, SOFTBALL with JANET RENO and OTHER &HT;     (To publish this ``separate buy'' article, it must be purchased
_ the rate is not prohibitive _ from one of these New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives: 
 &HT;    (--U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at
1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697. 
 &HT;    (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-798-0970;
fax, 310-798-7338.) 
 &HT;    
 By RUTH CONNIFF  
 c.1999 The Progressive  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   Patricia Ireland, president of the National Organization for
Women, is probably the most visible representative of feminism in
the United States. She's always in the hot seat _ called upon to
account for everything from feminists' ``coziness'' with the
Clinton administration to the perception that feminists are a bunch
of man-bashing radicals.
</P>
<P>
   In her own life, Ireland has been through a lot of changes. She
writes in her autobiography, ``What Women Want'' (Dutton 1996),
about her seven-year career as an airline stewardess, as well as,
years later, breaking the ``glass ceiling'' by becoming one of the
first women to make partner in a corporate law firm.
</P>
<P>
   We met for a couple of hours in her corner office at NOW's
national headquarters in Washington, D.C.
 &UR; -0- &QL;
</P>
<P>
   RUTH CONNIFF: You tell a story in your book about a bomb threat
while you were working as an airline stewardess. The pilot asked
you to stay on the plane to cook him a steak.
</P>
<P>
   PATRICIA IRELAND: Right, everyone else got off, while the plane
was about to be exploded at any moment, as far as we could tell.
</P>
<P>
   Q: You decided to turn off the grill and get off the plane too,
and to tell the pilot to cook his own steak. Was that a turning
point for you?
</P>
<P>
   A: Oh, yeah. There were those little progressions. I don't think
anything radicalized me as much as being a stewardess. It was what
made those blinders fall from my eyes. ... Why in the world was I
standing in an airplane that might be blown up at any minute while
this guy was sitting in the crew lounge safe and waiting for his
steak? Get serious!
</P>
<P>
   There were a number of moments like that. That one just struck
me particularly because it was so outrageous. Because planes WERE
being blown up. It wasn't like it was a fantasy.
</P>
<P>
   I came up in school when all of these movements were out there:
the free-speech movement, the civil-rights movement, the
women's-rights movement. The anti-war movement was very big when I
was in college. And I was an armchair supporter. I thought, ``Yeah,
that's great, I agree with that.'' But I was never active at all.
It really wasn't until something touched me personally that I
recognized you have to learn to fight back. And if you have a
movement, you're more likely to have success.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How did you get from stewardess to corporate lawyer?
</P>
<P>
   A: Because (at the airline) I discovered the disparity in the
benefits that the women got vs. what the men got _ it had been
totally illegal for years. And yet nobody among us had known our
rights. I didn't even have to file a lawsuit. I just had to go to
the Labor Department.
</P>
<P>
   Just as now, women who are being pushed off public assistance
don't know that they still should and can get food stamps and child
care. Years ago we didn't know it was illegal for the company to
have this benefit package that covered men's families but not
women's. And nobody challenged it.
</P>
<P>
   So when I figured out how many years the company had gotten away
with that _ how much money women and their families had been ripped
off for the corporate bottom line _ I just figured I wanted to go
to law school and know more about how to enforce those rights.
</P>
<P>
   All through law school I took courses I thought I'd use _ law
and the poor, civil rights and the law, women's rights and the law,
social policy and the law. I got my lowest grades in corporate law.
I never took securities law. And I really thought I was going to do
international law work, and especially international human-rights
work.
</P>
<P>
   Then I discovered that to get to do international law I would
have to move to Washington or go out to L.A. I really loved Miami,
so that was private international law _ private business
transactions. I looked at all my friends who were going into Legal
Services or becoming public defenders, and I just figured I would
be very frustrated by doing that. Also I found, much to my
surprise, that in representing a lot of these corporations that
needed affirmative-action plans, I could go in as their lawyer, and
they knew I was on their side, and without a big fight I could get
them to do things I could not possibly have gotten them to do as a
plaintiffs' counsel.
</P>
<P>
   Q: You and other feminists have been accused of not wreaking
havoc or taking shots at President Clinton. Barbara Ehrenreich
wrote an op-ed in The New York Times accusing you of being too cozy
with him. And I went to a press conference at the Democratic
Convention where Gloria Steinem and other prominent feminists said,
``We've got to vote for him because he's the only one who can undo
the welfare legislation he just signed.''
</P>
<P>
   A: Right. But we were never part of that. And we never endorsed
him. I was arrested in front of his White House protesting the
welfare repeal. And one of the things I was peeved at Barbara about
was for saying I had gone to the Democratic Convention and danced
the macarena. I never went inside the Democratic Convention. I went
there to see if we could get some demonstrations going on welfare.
</P>
<P>
   But mostly I went to Chicago because we had meetings with
Clinton administration officials who were trying to negotiate on
what they could do to settle us down about welfare. They wanted to
meet with us and hear from people we had gathered together about
the tie between domestic violence and poverty. They were in the
process of writing the rules on welfare: Could you get a temporary
exemption for women in poverty because of horrendous violence in
their lives? How did you deal with women who were stalked or
attacked in the workplace and therefore couldn't keep a job?
</P>
<P>
   We didn't endorse Clinton, we took him on full force over the
poverty issue and over lesbians and gays in the military, and yet
because we go in the door and negotiate about these issues,
suddenly we're ``in his camp.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: Didn't NOW pull its punches when it came to the sexual
accusations against Clinton?
</P>
<P>
   A: No. Go back and look at the web and some of the transcripts.
I have called him everything on television. I've said we weren't
defending him, that his actions were indefensible. You know, I've
been very hard-edged about what he's done.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Are we better off with Clinton than we would have been with
Bush or Dole?
</P>
<P>
   A: Yes. And at the same time, I really think Clinton has got a
very serious problem. Clinton is beyond what even the worst of the
culture of men usually behave like. When I was a stewardess, the ad
campaigns were ``We really move our tails for you'' and ``Fly me.''
I saw some of the worst of the worst of guys when they were away
from their families and thought they could do anything they wanted.
And when I first heard this story, I could not imagine even the
most outrageous pilot or passenger I knew dropping trousers and
asking for a blow job. What is that about?
</P>
<P>
   So I think he's got a serious problem. And that's why, again,
we're so focused on trying to get more candidates we can trust into
the political pipeline. I think I've been pretty hard on Clinton.
But it isn't what some of the reporters wanted to hear or see. I
think what they wanted was to say, ``Oh, the feminists are
defending Clinton.'' And, true, the real news would be if all the
feminists agreed.
</P>
<P>
   Q: You caused some problems for Janet Reno when she arrived in
Washington by revealing that you played softball with her.
</P>
<P>
   A: Yes, yes _ I really thought that was most amusing. I was
trying to put forward a different image from the one that got
across. Of course, every softball team I know and every soccer team
_ I wouldn't say they're all lesbian, but ... that was an amusing
little sidelight.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Does Reno play softball a lot? Are you still playing against
her?
</P>
<P>
   A: No. We played when we were both much younger, in a women's
law league _ all women lawyers. It was great. It was one of those
things for some of us who missed Title IX, and didn't get to play
sports in high school and college. The first time I could look out
there and go, ``Hmmm, they're not covered in right field, that's
where this ball is going,'' and I was able to hit it where I wanted
to _ that felt like a real accomplishment! Especially for someone
who had no sports skills growing up. It's just a fun thing. And
Reno was a heck of a player. I mean, she was scary.
</P>
<P>
   I remember I was playing first base when she was batting, and
when she was running the bases you definitely did not want to make
the mistake of being on the baseline. She was just an aggressive,
physical player. And I admired that, at the same time as it scared
me. When I met her, I just thought: Wow, who is this tall, strong,
aggressive player? Turned out to be Janet Reno.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What do you think about how Monica Lewinsky ended up? Was she
exploited or not?
</P>
<P>
   A: I think she's very young. I think you don't show your thong
bikini underwear to your employer without giving a signal of some
sort that you'd welcome a sexual advance. And I don't think anybody
tried to coerce her into anything, except Ken Starr and his merry
band of men.
</P>
<P>
   And at the same time I fear that she will live to regret this,
although she seems temporarily to be riding high. Part of what
happens with any young woman who comes to see her only value as her
sexual appeal and her conventional attractiveness, who is so
obsessed with her body being too large, and trying to fill that
insecurity with attention from men, is that the ageism of the
culture catches up to her.
</P>
<P>
   You are only sexually attractive, conventionally, for a very
brief period in an otherwise long life. And if you don't have
something else about yourself that you value _ forget about whether
the rest of the world values it, but just start with yourself _ you
don't have anything to fall back on. When the next boss or series
of bosses are looking at the younger and younger women, what is she
going to have to feel good about herself? What does she value in
herself? And what does she have to offer of value that she's going
to present to the world? I worry about that. In that sense, I think
she has made some really big mistakes that are going to catch up to
her.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Ruth Conniff is Washington editor of The Progressive
Magazine.) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   -------------------- &QC;
</P>
