<SLUG> BC-CIR-Q&AMP;A-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPUTER QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
(jt) 
 By J.D.BIERSDORFER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. How big can an attachment file be for an e-mail message? Is
there an official size limit to how much you can send?
</P>
<P>
   A. In theory, there are no official size limits across the
Internet pertaining to e-mail attachments. In practice, however,
many e-mail system administrators regulate attachment sizes to
avoid clogging their lines with megabytes of data and filling user
mailboxes on their mail servers. These size limits vary with each
system and usually range from 2 to 4 megabytes, but check with your
Internet service provider.
</P>
<P>
   The Microsoft Network, for example, limits inbound and outbound
messages to 2 megabytes total (including the message text and the
attached file). America Online also maintains an approximate
2-megabyte limit for messages between AOL and other service
providers, but if you have an AOL account and are sending a file to
another person using AOL, you can send about 8 megabytes.
</P>
<P>
   To provide some control, many e-mail programs will let users
specify a maximum size for attachments in the program's settings.
Some programs will also give users the option of breaking a large
attachment into several files that can download more quickly on the
other end. If you have a large file to send, you may want to reduce
its size with compression software or use a third-party
file-splitting program (available on many shareware Web sites) to
send the file in chunks.
</P>
<P>
   Circuits invites questions about computer-based technology, by
postal mail to Questions, Circuits, The New York Times, 229 West
43d Street, New York, N.Y. 10036-3959 or by e-mail to
Q&AMP;A(AT)nytimes.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
