A1690 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l BC-GLADSTONE-HOME-IMPROV     08-18 0616
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLADSTONE-HOME-IMPROVEMENT-art-ADV05-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR RELEASE: SUN., SEP. 5, 1999. 
 HOME IMPROVEMENT QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS
</HEADLINE>
  By BERNARD GLADSTONE 
 Includes illustration. 
 Copyright 1999 Bernard Gladstone 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: Our new house has flush doors that are simply painted. I
would like to somehow ``dress them up'' get rid of the flat, dull
appearance and make them look more like a paneled door. Have you
any suggestion as to how I can create the look of a paneled door,
without replacing them and preferably without covering them with
any type of wallcovering?
</P>
<P>
   A: Use some standard picture frame molding to assemble four,
five or six ``frames'' in the sizes desired for each raised
``panel'' on the door. Or have a local dealer who sells and
assembles picture frames make them up for you. Then glue these
frames, properly spaced, to the door face as shown here, arranging
them to create the desired ``raised panel'' effect. Then paint as
usual.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Can you tell me the best way to take paint off my kitchen
cabinet doors?
</P>
<P>
   A: Take the doors off so you can work on them in the garage or
basement. Remove all handles, hinges and other hardware, then use a
semi-paste, non-flammable chemical paint remover to strip the paint
off while the doors are laying flat on a bench or table. Spread the
remover on in thick layers with a minimum of brushing and allow to
soak in for 15 or 20 minutes. Scrape off the softened residue with
a dull putty knife and repeat if necessary. Finally, wipe off the
surface with steel wool that has been dipped into solvent
recommended for that brand of paint.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I am going to install a new flagstone walk in place of the
existing concrete walk leading to my front stoop. I will set the
stones in cement, and fill the joints between them with mortar.
Many of the flagstones will have to be cut to size before I can
install them so can you tell me how to cut them where necessary?
</P>
<P>
   A: The easiest way is to use a portable circular saw equipped
with a masonry-cutting abrasive blade. These power tools can be
rented, although you may have to buy your own blade. The saw is
usually used to make progressively deeper cuts on one side, then
the stone is turned over and tapped along this cut with a hammer to
break off the waste.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Our house once had ivy growing on the brick wall on each side
of the house. This ivy was removed by the previous owner, but there
are still lots of little stem pieces visible where not all of the
vine was removed. I've tried scraping, rubbing with steel wool and
scrubbing with detergent, but the particles are still visible. What
can you suggest?
</P>
<P>
   A: This is a difficult task that usually requires either
pressure washing with a suitable chemical (not a job for the
do-it-yourselfer) or using a wire wheel attached to an electric
grinder. Either way, the task must be done carefully to avoid
damaging the brick and safety goggles must be worn to protect your
eyes.
</P>
<P>
   Questions about home-repair problems should be addressed to
Bernard Gladstone, care of The New York Times Syndication Sales
Corp., 122 E. 42nd St., New York, N.Y. 10168. Questions of general
interest will be answered in this column; Mr. Gladstone regrets
that unpublished letters cannot be answered individually.
</P>
<P>
   NOTE: Drawing captioned ``DECORATING A PLAIN DOOR'' goes with
this column.
</P>
<P>
   CAPTION: Wood picture frames glued to face of door create
appearance of ``raised panels'' on flush door.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; -0- &QL; 
 &UR; Copyright 1999 Bernard Gladstone &QL; 
 &UR; Distributed by New York Times Special Features &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
