<HEADER>
A1701 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d BC-FOOD-CYBERSPICE19-COX     08-18 0875
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-CYBERSPICE19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    No culinary conundrum is too difficult to solve
 &HT;    By Betty Parham
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   No matter how experienced a cook may be, it is inevitable that
there will be times when something comes up in the kitchen that
presents a problem. An unavailable ingredient, an unfamiliar
technique or any number of unforeseen situations can arise,
prompting a cook to reach for the phone or a favored cookbook
looking for solutions.
</P>
<P>
   By now every cook with a computer knows that it would take 10
lifetimes to run out of ideas for what to make for dinner, so
jam-packed is cyberspace with recipes
</P>
<P>
   The Internet also is an outstanding resource for solving cooking
problems. But unlike a search for recipes, it's better to know
where to look in a search for solutions. Here are some addresses
you may want to bookmark:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  At www.learn2.com/browse/foo.html, one of the first things
you'll learn is how to boil an egg. After the basics, there are
lessons on how to carve a turkey; choose a knife, cooking oil or
wine; clean a fish, eat sushi and get rid of fishy smells; make a
great pot of coffee or tea; and make a roux, sourdough starter,
flavored vinegars, foamed milk, pizza dough and rice _ for
starters.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Then there's Betty Crocker at www.bettycrocker.com/recipes
</P>
<P>
   /guide/index.html to guide you through the minefields of creme
fraiche, sharpening shears, insulated cookie sheets, decorating
with fresh flowers, freezing cabbage, drying tomatoes, smashing
peppercorns, making garnishes, peeling kiwis, roasting garlic and
much more.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The information at the Better Homes and Gardens Kitchen
Cooking Encyclopedia at www.bhglive.com/food/cookhelpers
</P>
<P>
   /encyclopedia/index.html is, well, encyclopedic and easy to
access as well. There are easy-to-follow instructions and hints on
just about anything from pulling taffy to carving a goose. Useful
charts include emergency substitutions and cooking for a crowd.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  If it's a technique you need boning up on, check out Cuisine
Magazine's Kitchen Tested Tips and Techniques at www.augusthome
</P>
<P>
   .com/cuitips.htm.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Epicurious weighs in with another excellent problem-solving
site, ``1,001 Tips From Great Cooks'' at
food.epicurious.com/eeating
</P>
<P>
   /e02secrets/aindex.html. Searchable information is listed from A
(how do make acidulated water) to Z (everything you want to know
about zest).
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  There's lots of practical info at Fabulous Foods Cooking
School, at www.fabulousfoods.com/mainframe.html, where you will
find such topics as measuring, making stock and bread and boning a
chicken breast.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  It's always helpful to see a picture of the dish accompanying
a recipe, and www.augusthome.com/cooking/cuisine/RECIPES
</P>
<P>
   /marshs.htm goes a step further to provide pictures of the
step-by-step preparation.
</P>
<P>
   This is just a sampling of a multitude of sites that, combined,
probably answer every kitchen question ever asked. Links to the
sites already mentioned and to many more are at
www.kitchenlink.com/cgi/publicframes?page &QC; faqs.
</P>
<P>
   MAIN DISH SALAD
</P>
<P>
   Margarita Shrimp Salad
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 servings Preparation time: 1 1/4 hours Cooking time: 20
minutes
</P>
<P>
   For the shrimp:
</P>
<P>
   1 pound shrimp (16-20 size)
</P>
<P>
   1 cup lime juice
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup white tequila
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons triple sec
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon red pepper flakes
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon kosher salt
</P>
<P>
   For the salad:
</P>
<P>
   1 cup diced roasted red
</P>
<P>
   pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 cup diced roasted yellow pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 cup roasted corn kernels
</P>
<P>
   1 cup chopped, seeded tomato
</P>
<P>
   1 (15-ounce) can black beans, rinsed and drained
</P>
<P>
   2/3 cup thinly sliced red onion
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup chopped cilantro leaves
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon seeded, minced jalapeno pepper
</P>
<P>
   For the vinaigrette:
</P>
<P>
   1 1/4 cups light olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup white wine vinegar
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup lime juice
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup cilantro leaves
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1/8 teaspoon cayenne pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 avocado, coarsely diced
</P>
<P>
   To assemble:
</P>
<P>
   Lime juice
</P>
<P>
   Finely chopped cilantro
</P>
<P>
   Baked tortilla strips
</P>
<P>
   In a medium bowl, mix shrimp, lime juice, tequila, triple sec,
red pepper flakes and salt. Marinate shrimp 30 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, roast peppers and corn on grill or under broiler.
Slice corn from cob and put in a large bowl. Peel charred skins
from peppers, then dice and add to corn. Add tomatoes, black beans,
onion, cilantro and jalapeno.
</P>
<P>
   To make the vinaigrette: In the bowl of a food processor, place
olive oil, vinegar, lime juice, cilantro, salt and cayenne pepper.
Blend well. Add avocado pieces and process just until blended. Too
much will make it too oily.
</P>
<P>
   Remove shrimp from marinade and grill for 5 minutes, total,
turning once.
</P>
<P>
   To assemble: Add hot shrimp to salad mixture. Toss with 1/2 cup
vinaigrette. Dip glass rims in lime juice and then into minced
cilantro leaves. Spoon salad into glasses. Garnish with lime slice,
cilantro leaves and baked tortilla strips.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 468 calories, 32 grams protein, 20 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 38), 42 grams carbohydrates, 172
milligrams cholesterol, 725 milligrams sodium, 8 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Betty Parham writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
