<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-18 16:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1702 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d BC-FOOD-JAM-RECIPES1STTA     08-18 1965
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-JAM-RECIPES1STTAKE19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Yes, you can can
 &HT;    By Reagan Walker
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jam and jelly making may seem more like a science experiment
than cooking. After all, there are strict guidelines, some special
tools and some funny ingredients like pectin involved.
</P>
<P>
   Don't let that intimidate you. Or squelch your creativity. I've
discovered that half the fun is making combinations you truly can't
find in the grocery store, like tart orange and Grand Marnier and
ginger and peach.
</P>
<P>
   Any jam or jelly recipe will break down into four essential
parts: fruit, pectin, acid and sugar.
</P>
<P>
   Fruit gives jams and jellies their characteristic flavor and
color. It also provides part of the pectin, acid and liquid
required for successful jell formation.
</P>
<P>
   Pectin is the substance that causes jams and jellies to jell.
Some fruits, such as apples, can have enough natural pectin for
jell formation. The riper the fruit, the less natural pectin it
contains. Luckily, commercial pectin may be used (and I highly
recommend it for beginners).
</P>
<P>
   Acid also is needed for jell formation, as well as flavor.
Fruits vary in acid content. Lemon juice or citric acid is commonly
added when fruits are low in acid.
</P>
<P>
   Sugar not only provides flavor and helps with jelling, but it's
also a preserving agent.
</P>
<P>
   We provide you here with everything you need to know to get
started, from equipment to recipes. And this is a great project to
share with a friend. Set aside a half-day or day, gather the fruits
and jars and have a jam session.
</P>
<P>
   RESOURCES
</P>
<P>
   There are a number of books and Web sites out there on the
topics of food preservation, including jam and jelly making. It's
important to get reliable and safe information. A call to your
county extension office always is the best place to start. Or, if
you are online, you can have the University of Georgia Cooperative
Extension Service's resources at your fingertips.
</P>
<P>
   Here's what you do: go to www.fcs.uga.edu
</P>
<P>
   /outreach/coopex. Then you'll be given a menu of choices. Choose
``food safety and preservation,'' then ``publications and
resources,'' and then ``food preservation.''
</P>
<P>
   Another good source is the ``Ball Blue Book Guide to Home
Canning, Freezing and Dehydration'' ($5.95), which can be purchased
by calling 1-800-392-2575 or sending a check with name and address
to Alltrista Consumer Products, P.O. Box 2005, Department MK,
Muncie, IN 47307.
</P>
<P>
   EQUIPMENT
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Saucepans for boiling lids and cooking fruit.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  For jelly, a bag or pouch for extracting fruit juices. The bag
can be made of several thicknesses of closely woven cheesecloth or
firm unbleached muslin. Be sure it is washed and rinsed well after
each use.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Boiling water canner or a deep cooking pot with lid and rack.
(I used a 10-quart stockpot with a colander basket.) The jars
cannot rest directly on the bottom of the pot (thus the rack) and
you must have room for 1 inch of water above the jars and another
inch boiling room.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Canning jars (see below) with new lids. Jam and jelly recipes
usually call for half-pint, or 8-ounce, jars. Be sure all jars are
free from cracks and chips. Remember that lids can only be used
once (but the bands that screw on around them can be reused.)
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Tongs for removing jars from boiling water.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  A wide-mouth funnel is not absolutely necessary, but it sure
does make pouring the jam or jelly into the jars a whole lot
easier. If you see one, pick it up.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The advanced jelly maker will want a jelly or candy
thermometer for making products without added pectin.
</P>
<P>
   _Cooperative Extension Service,
</P>
<P>
   University of Georgia
</P>
<P>
   PREPARING JARS
</P>
<P>
   Usually, half-pint jars are used for jams and jellies. First,
wash the jars, along with the lids and screw bands, in hot soapy
water or the dishwasher and rinse thoroughly. Dry and set the bands
aside.
</P>
<P>
   Next, sterilize the jars. Place the jars on a rack in a deep pot
or canner and cover with water. Jars must be totally submerged.
Bring the water to a boil; boil jars 10 minutes, and then allow
jars to remain covered in hot water until ready to use, removing
one at a time as needed.
</P>
<P>
   Place the lids in a separate saucepan and cover with water.
Bring the water to a simmer (180 degrees) and heat for 10 minutes,
then allow to rest in the warm water until needed, removing one at
a time. Do not boil the lids _ that may result in seal failure.
</P>
<P>
   _``Ball Blue Book Guide''
</P>
<P>
   PROCESSING JAMS AND JELLIES
</P>
<P>
   All jellied products must be processed in a boiling water bath
to prevent mold growth. Some cookbooks and recipes may suggest that
you simply need to pour the hot liquid into a hot, clean jar, put
on a hot lid and invert for five minutes. But that method has not
been proven to be failsafe when it comes to preventing spoilage. So
play it safe and go with the water bath.
</P>
<P>
   Pour the hot jam or jelly mixture into the hot, sterilized jars,
leaving 1/4 inch head space. Wipe the jar rims and close with
treated canning lids and screw bands. Place on a rack in a large
pot or canner filled with boiling water. The water should cover the
jars by at least 1 inch, with additional room for boiling. Cover
the pot or canner. Bring the water back to a boil and boil gently
for five minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Then remove the jars to a protected surface and cool, away from
drafts. Do not move jellied products for 12 hours after they're
made; moving them can break the jell. After 12 hours, check the
seal, remove the screw band, label and store in a cool, dry, dark
place.
</P>
<P>
   The shorter the storage time, the better the product. Though
cooked jellied products should keep for at least a year, their
flavor and quality begin to decrease within a few months.
</P>
<P>
   _Cooperative Extension Service, University of Georgia
</P>
<P>
   COMMON QUESTIONS
</P>
<P>
   Q: Why is it necessary to process jellies, jams, conserves,
preserves and marmalades?
</P>
<P>
   A: Mold and other spoilage microorganisms can grow when the seal
is not airtight. Processing pushes air from jars and helps ensure a
good seal.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Where can I get jars, pectin, canners and other equipment?
</P>
<P>
   A: Hardware stores usually are excellent sources for jars,
tongs, canners and equipment. There's also a mail-order form for
canners and other equipment in the boxes of Ball jars. Discount
stores like Wal-Mart and Target sometimes carry the equipment,
though it varies by season and geographic location (summertime and
rural areas are your best shot). Grocery stores also carry jars,
lids and pectin. Look near the freezer bags and containers, though
the location can vary.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Can I use honey or corn syrup in place of sugar when I make
jelly?
</P>
<P>
   A: Light, mild-flavored honey or corn syrup can be used, but not
to completely replace sugar. In products with added pectin, up to 1
cup of honey can replace an equal amount of sugar for a recipe that
yields 6 half-pint jars. Honey can replace up to half of the sugar
in recipes with no added pectin, but there will be a honey flavor.
</P>
<P>
   Corn syrup can replace half the sugar if powdered pectin is
used, and 2 cups per batch if liquid pectin is used.
</P>
<P>
   Artificial sweeteners cannot be substituted for sugar in regular
recipes because the sugar is needed for jelling.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Can I make jelly without added sugar?
</P>
<P>
   A: Yes, there are methods, but recipes should come from a
reliable source. Contact your county extension office for
directions and recipes.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Can I double a jam or jelly recipe?
</P>
<P>
   A: It's best not to. The cooking time changes in relation to the
proportion of ingredients when you increase the recipe. The bigger
the batch, the worse the problem. Small batches of jelly are easier
to handle and are more apt to be successful.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Since the fruit in jam is mashed anyway, can I use mushy
fruit?
</P>
<P>
   A: Mushy fruit may be overripe and have very little natural
pectin and acid. You can use it, but it may never jell and the
flavor may not be good. Always add pectin if you use overripe
fruit, and never use moldy fruit.
</P>
<P>
   Q: My jam tastes like wine. What happened?
</P>
<P>
   A: It fermented, due to an improper seal and possibly a poor
recipe.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Why is my jelly bubbly?
</P>
<P>
   A: If the bubbles are active, it's a sign of spoilage. Throw it
out. Stationary bubbles indicate that the jelly was poured too
slowly or from too great a height into the jars and air was
trapped.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What makes jelly too stiff?
</P>
<P>
   A: It was either overcooked or had too little sugar or too much
pectin.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How can I decrease the amount of foam that forms on my jelly?
</P>
<P>
   A: The foam that forms from the boiling process will not hurt
the product but will detract from the appearance. Adding 1/4
teaspoon butter or margarine will help eliminate foam. Foam also
can be skimmed from the surface of jam before pouring into jars.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What can be done to make soft jellies firmer?
</P>
<P>
   A: There are several methods for remaking a failed batch of
jelly safely. Contact your county extension office for directions.
</P>
<P>
   _Cooperative Extension Service, University of Georgia
</P>
<P>
   CONDIMENT
</P>
<P>
   Hot Pepper Mint Jelly
</P>
<P>
   Makes 5 half-pint jars
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 15 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 25 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Camille Berry, mother of William, who took the photographs with
this story, is such an experienced jam maker that she operates on
instinct. This combination was her creation. It's delicious with
cream cheese but also will work well as a glaze for meats,
especially lamb and chicken.
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup diced hot peppers (4-5 red or green; any variety will
do)
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup diced green bell peppers
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup chopped fresh mint
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups apple cider vinegar
</P>
<P>
   6 cups granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   6 ounces liquid fruit pectin (such as Certo)
</P>
<P>
   Green food coloring
</P>
<P>
   Put hot peppers, green peppers, mint and vinegar in food
processor or blender and process until well-blended. In medium
saucepan, combine blended ingredients with sugar and bring to boil.
Allow to simmer for 10 minutes. Remove from heat. Add pectin and
stir. Return to heat, bring to a boil and boil for 1 minute. Pour
mixture through a strainer lined with cheesecloth (or skim mixture
with spoon). Add few drops of food coloring and pour into hot,
sterilized jars, leaving 1/4 inch head space. Clean rims
thoroughly, place lids on jars and process in boiling water 5
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Per teaspoon: 22 calories, no protein, no fat , 6 grams
carbohydrates, no cholesterol, 2 milligrams sodium, no fiber.
</P>
<P>
   CONDIMENT
</P>
<P>
   Uncooked Strawberry Jam From Fresh Fruit
</P>
<P>
   Makes 5 half-pint jars
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 25 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Standing time: 24 hours
</P>
<P>
   Every rule has an exception. This is the only kind of jam that
does not have to be processed in a water bath. In fact, there's no
cooking involved. But freezer jams must be kept in the freezer or
refrigerator, and they only last two or three months. Still, it's a
very quick way to take care of an overabundance of fruit.
</P>
<P>
   1 3/4 cups crushed strawberries (about 1/2 quart)
</P>
<P>
   4 cups granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   1 pouch (3-ounce) liquid pectin
</P>
<P>
   Place strawberries in an extra-large bowl. Add sugar, mix well
and let stand for 10 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Measure lemon juice into a small bowl. Add liquid pectin and
stir well. Stir into fruit and continue stirring for 3 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Pour jam into freezer containers or canning jars, leaving 1/2
inch head space. Cover containers. Let stand at room temperature
until set (up to 24 hours). Freeze or refrigerate. _ University of
Georgia Cooperative Extension Service
</P>
<P>
   Per teaspoon: 14 calories, no protein, no fat, 4 grams
carbohydrates, no cholesterol, no sodium, no fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
