<HEADER>
A1703 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d BC-FOOD-JAM-RECIPES2NDTA     08-18 1882
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-JAM-RECIPES2NDTAKE19-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA: no sodium, no fiber.
</P>
<P>
   CONDIMENT
</P>
<P>
   Plum Jelly
</P>
<P>
   Makes 2 or 3 half-pint jars
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 20 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 35 minutes
</P>
<P>
   A friend of mine told me pectin was for sissies. So I tried this
recipe, which does not call for pectin. But you'll see it listed in
the list of ingredients anyway. That's because I could never get
the jelly to sheet properly. So I threw in the pectin at the last
minute. Call me a sissy. But my jelly is darn good. You can give
the hard way a try. With perfectly ripe fruit, you may be
successful. But keep the pectin on hand anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Plum juice (1 pound plums and 2 cups water)
</P>
<P>
   Granulated sugar ( 3/4 cup to each cup of juice)
</P>
<P>
   1 package (1 3/4 ounce) powdered pectin (optional)
</P>
<P>
   To prepare juice: Wash plums. Crush fruit (with the back of a
spoon or a wooden mallet), add water, cover and bring to a boil
over high heat. Reduce heat and simmer 15 to 20 minutes or until
the fruit is soft. Extract juice by pouring the plum mixture into a
jelly bag or pouch made with several layers of cheesecloth or
muslin set inside a strainer. Allow the plums to cool slightly,
then gather the cloth up and squeeze the juice into a bowl. Be
careful _ the fruit will still be quite hot.
</P>
<P>
   Measure juice into a saucepan. Add 3/4 cup sugar for every cup
of juice (I had 2 cups of juice so I needed 1 1/2 cups of sugar).
Stir well. Boil over high heat to 220 degrees or until the mixture
sheets from a spoon.
</P>
<P>
   Remove from heat; quickly skim off foam. Pour into hot,
sterilized half-pint jars, leaving 1/4 inch head space. Wipe rims
clean, secure lids and process in a boiling water bath for 5
minutes. _ University of Georgia Cooperative Extension Service
</P>
<P>
   Per teaspoon: 14 calories, no protein, no fat, 4 grams
carbohydrates, no cholesterol, no sodium, no fiber.
</P>
<P>
   CONDIMENT
</P>
<P>
   Raspberry Rum Jam
</P>
<P>
   Makes 8 half-pint jars
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 5 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 25-30 minutes
</P>
<P>
   One of the sweetest books I found was Joan Hassol's ``Well
Preserved: A Jam-making Hymnal'' (Fireside, $11). It's a
sentimental sharing of recipes, and oh, what wonderful combinations
Hassol shares. Like this Raspberry Rum Jam. I've already had
requests from friends to make more.
</P>
<P>
   4 cups whole, fresh or frozen unsweetened raspberries
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 packages powdered pectin
</P>
<P>
   7 cups granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup rum
</P>
<P>
   Combine the raspberries and lemon juice in a heavy, nonreactive
pot. Bring to a boil. Add the pectin and return to a boil. Add the
sugar, stirring constantly. When the jam sheets off the spoons
(leaving a path when you run your finger along the back of the
spoon), add the rum and boil for another minute or so, making sure
the jam still sheets off the spoon. Pour into hot, sterilized
half-pint jars, leaving 1/4 inch head space. Wipe rims clean,
secure lids and process in a boiling water bath for 5 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Per teaspoon: 15 calories, no protein, no fat, 4 grams
carbohydrates, no cholesterol, no sodium, no fiber.
</P>
<P>
   CONDIMENT
</P>
<P>
   Ginger Peach Marmalade
</P>
<P>
   Makes 8 half-pint jars
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 25 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 25 minutes
</P>
<P>
   If you've already made peach cobbler and peach ice cream and
still have an abundance of peaches, this recipe is ideal. It's an
old favorite with a new flavor twist _ ginger. This is great on
bread and muffins, but also makes a wonderful glaze for roast
chicken.
</P>
<P>
   8 large peaches, pitted and peeled
</P>
<P>
   2 large oranges, unpeeled and cut into sections, with seeds
removed
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup chopped preserved ginger
</P>
<P>
   1/2 to 1 cup water
</P>
<P>
   1 package (1 3/4 ounce) powdered pectin
</P>
<P>
   8 cups granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   Into a food processor fitted with the cutting blade, chop the
peaches, oranges and ginger until they are a fine pulp. You should
have 4 cups of fruit to work with. Put the mixture into a large,
nonreactive pot with water, the amount of which depends on the
thickness of the fruit. Simmer for 10 minutes on very low heat.
Then bring to a boil, and add the pectin. Bring to the boil again
and add the sugar, stirring costantly.
</P>
<P>
   Cook on low heat, stirring constantly, allowing the marmalade to
bubble a little, for approximately 10 minutes. At that time, turn
off the heat and place a spoonful of jam on a cold plate in the
refrigerator. If in 10 minutes it has developed a skin, it is
ready. If not, return to the heat and keep cooking, and try again
in a few minutes. When ready, pour into hot, sterilized half-pint
jars, leaving 1/4 inch head space. Wipe rims clean, secure lids and
process in a boiling water bath for 5 minutes. _ ``Well Preserved:
A Jam-making Hymnal,'' Joan Hassol (Fireside, $11)
</P>
<P>
   Per teaspoon: 18 calories, no protein, no fat , 5 grams
carbohydrates, no cholesterol, no sodium, no fiber.
</P>
<P>
   CONDIMENT
</P>
<P>
   Apple-Lemon Marmalade
</P>
<P>
   Makes 8 half-pint jars
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 25 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Soaking time: overnight
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 50 minutes
</P>
<P>
   This is a delicate marmalade, so choose the most flavorful
apples you can find. The fall harvest in Ellijay could provide good
stock. This comes from a lovely book by Anne Gardon, ``Preserving
for All Seasons'' (Firefly Books, $24.95).
</P>
<P>
   4 lemons
</P>
<P>
   3 cups water
</P>
<P>
   3 pounds cooking apples (about 12 medium)
</P>
<P>
   6 cups granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   6 mint sprigs, tied up in cheesecloth
</P>
<P>
   Cut lemons in two and slice thinly, removing pits. Soak in water
overnight. Cook over moderate heat until peel is tender, about 10
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Peel and core apples. Cut in thin slices. Combine apples, lemons
with their liquid, sugar and mint.
</P>
<P>
   Bring to a boil while stirring. Reduce heat and cook for 30
minutes. Mixture will be slightly thickened. Remove mint. Pour into
hot, sterilized half-pint jars, leaving 1/4 inch head space. Wipe
rims clean, secure lids and process in a boiling water bath for 5
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Per teaspoon: 15 calories, no protein, no fat , 4 grams
carbohydrates, no cholesterol, no sodium, no fiber.
</P>
<P>
   CONDIMENT
</P>
<P>
   Tart Orange Jelly
</P>
<P>
   With Grand Marnier
</P>
<P>
   Makes 6 half-pint jars
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 20 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Dripping time: 2 hours
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 40 minutes
</P>
<P>
   This tasted luxurious and makes a wonderful gift. Hold on to
this recipe for the citrus season just before the holidays. It will
be a wonderful way to make use of a crate of oranges.
</P>
<P>
   For juice extraction:
</P>
<P>
   6 oranges, each cut into 8 pieces
</P>
<P>
   2 large lemons, each cut into 8 pieces
</P>
<P>
   For the jelly:
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons strained fresh lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons Grand Marnier
</P>
<P>
   6 1/2 cups granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 3-ounce pouch plus 2 tablespoons liquid pectin
</P>
<P>
   Extract the juice: With a food grinder fitted with the coarse
blade, coarsely grind the oranges and lemons, or in a food
processor mince them, pulsing the motor several times and scraping
down the sides. In a large saucepan combine the fruit and 3 1/2
cups cold water. Bring the liquid to a simmer over medium-low heat,
stirring occasionally, and simmer, covered, for 15 minutes. Ladle
the mixture into a jelly bag set over a large heatproof bowl and
let it drip, undisturbed, for 2 hours.
</P>
<P>
   If you do not have a jelly bag, line a fine-mesh strainer with
layers of cheesecloth, muslin or a damp tea towel and suspend over
a large, nonreactive bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Do not squeeze the jelly bag, but occasionally rub it gently and
scrape the juices from the outside with a spatula into the bowl. If
there is less than 3 cups of the extracted juice, pour a small
amount of hot water into the jelly bag and let the mixture drip
until there is 3 cups juice.
</P>
<P>
   Make the jelly: In a heavy 8-quart kettle, combine the extracted
juice, the lemon juice, the Grand Marnier and the sugar and cook
the mixture over high heat, stirring constantly, until it comes to
a full rolling boil that froths up toward the top of the kettle and
cannot be stirred down. Stir in the pectin, bring the mixture to a
full rolling boil again, stirring constantly, and boil it, stirring
constantly, for 1 minute. Remove the kettle from the heat, skim off
all the froth and pour into hot, sterilized half-pint jars, leaving
1/4 inch head space. Wipe rims clean, secure lids and process in a
boiling water bath for 5 minutes. _ Gourmet, September, 1985
</P>
<P>
   Per teaspoon: 21 calories, no protein, no fat , 5 grams
carbohydrates, no cholesterol, 1 milligram sodium, no fiber.
</P>
<P>
   CONDIMENT
</P>
<P>
   Apricot Jam
</P>
<P>
   Makes 9 half-pint jars
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 10 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 20-25 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Kim Curley, host of WSB's ``Food and Wine'' show, spent a
morning making jam with me, sharing the fact that her grandmother
always relied on the recipes inside the Sure Jell pectin box. But
occasionally, she'd throw in a twist _ one small box of raspberry
Jell-O. Either way, this recipe is a gem.
</P>
<P>
   5 cups chopped apricots (about 3 pounds)
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   1 box (1 3/4-ounce) powdered pectin
</P>
<P>
   7 cups granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   Put the apricots and lemon juice in a large saucepan and stir in
the pectin. Bring mixture to a full rolling boil over medium-high
heat, stirring constantly. Add the sugar quickly (and the raspberry
Jell-O, if using) to the fruit mixture, return to a full rolling
boil and boil exactly 1 minute, stirring constantly. Remove from
heat. Skim off any foam and pour into hot, sterilized half-pint
jars, leaving 1/4 inch head space. Wipe rims clean, secure lids and
process in a boiling water bath for 5 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Per teaspoon: 14 calories, no protein, no fat, 3 grams
carbohydrates, no cholesterol, no sodium, no fiber.
</P>
<P>
   BREAD
</P>
<P>
   Biscuits
</P>
<P>
   Makes 6 biscuits
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 10 to 15 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 20 minutes
</P>
<P>
   I've tried many biscuit recipes but lately keep coming back to
this one. It can be doubled, and it's also good with buttermilk
instead of cream. But the cream does give it a bit of a scone
characteristic, which makes these absolutely ideal for butter and
jam.
</P>
<P>
   2 cups all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon baking powder
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   6 tablespoons unsalted butter, cold
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup heavy cream
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 425 degrees and lightly grease a baking sheet.
In a large bowl, sift together the flour, baking powder and salt.
Cut 5 tablespoons butter into bits and with your fingertips or a
pastry blender, blend bits into flour mixture until it all
resembles coarse meal. Add cream, stirring with a fork until just
combined. Transfer mixture to a lightly floured surface and gently
knead about 3 times until it just forms a dough. Pat dough into a 6
1/2-inch round about 1/2 inch thick.
</P>
<P>
   Using a 2 1/2-inch round cutter, cut out biscuits and arrange
about 1 inch apart on baking sheet. Gather and pat out scraps and
cut out more biscuits. Melt remaining tablespoon butter and lightly
brush on biscuits. Bake biscuits in middle of oven until pale
golden and cooked through, about 20 minutes. _ Gourmet, February
1999
</P>
<P>
   Per biscuit: 296 calories, 4 grams protein, 17 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 53), 30 grams carbohydrates, 51
milligrams cholesterol, 737 milligrams sodium, 1 gram fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Reagan Walker writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
