<HEADER>
A1704 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d BC-FOOD-JAMS19-COX     08-18 0770
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-JAMS19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Do-it-yourselfers can't keep a lid on their creativity when it
comes to mixing ripe fruit with sugar in hopes of getting jars full
of colorful condiments that fly off the shelves
 &HT;    By Reagan Walker
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Pull the biscuits from the oven, puffed and golden.
Take one, split it and quick, while the steam escapes, crown each
half with a pat of butter and a jewel of jam.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe a ruby-red raspberry, sweet yet tart. Or amber apple
jelly, subtle and smooth.
</P>
<P>
   Take a bite, close your eyes and most surely a queenly
apparition of your grandmother will appear.
</P>
<P>
   Well, maybe not.
</P>
<P>
   My grandmother felt so downright unshackled by the arrival of
convenience foods, the Ball jars were never seen again.
</P>
<P>
   So each time I'd see jam and jelly jars at a roadside stand or
farmers' market, I'd wonder: How can you take the colors of a
rainbow, give them vibrant substance and taste and put them in a
jar, to be dolloped out on a whim?
</P>
<P>
   The answer is not as magical as I imagined _ though as I
finished my first batch of jam (raspberry rum) this summer, I felt
a certain special power.
</P>
<P>
   Linda Liles, 50, of Cedartown, Ga., who also has experienced the
joy of jam making for the first time this summer, knows what I
mean.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just a feeling you get after you're done and you look at
your jars and the beautiful fruit and you know you did it,'' said
Liles, who's recently traded urban life for country living. ``It's
easy to walk into the store and buy it, but you did this with your
own hands.''
</P>
<P>
   There are signs that we are not alone in venturing into this
nostalgic art. ``We are having a very good sales year,'' said Judy
Harrold, spokeswoman for Alltrista Consumer Products Co., maker of
Ball and Kerr jars. Harrold said that while jar sales have been
increasing slowly throughout the '90s, a sharper increase over last
year's 4.7 million cases is expected this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of it is good growing seasons; some of it may be Y2K
concerns and some of it may be the return to home arts,'' Harrold
said.
</P>
<P>
   The company's research shows folks typically like to can
vegetables and make jams and jellies to have control over the
quality of ingredients. ``After that, people say it's just for the
sheer enjoyment of it, as a hobby and for relaxation,'' Harrold
said. ``And jams and jellies are always good places to start.''
</P>
<P>
   Good because jams and jellies don't require a significant
investment in special equipment or lengthy preparations. The fruit
tree in your back yard, a trip to a U-pick farm or organic market
or a visit with a friend who gardens will provide you with the
goods. Then you'll need jars and lids, tongs, a deep stockpot and a
rack for the jars to sit on.
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, making jams and jellies simply requires
cooking down ripe fruit with sugar, adding some pectin and pouring
into sterilized jars. Then, boil the jars in a water bath to seal
the deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``As you do it more, you'll learn to get the fruit at just the
perfect time, and it will always be better than store-bought,''
said Suzanne Franklin, 44, of Dawsonville, Ga., who's been making
jams and jellies for 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, you usually can't find combinations like ginger and
peach or hot pepper and mint on the grocery shelves. ``I like to
mix apple and grape. That makes real good peanut butter and jelly
sandwiches,'' said Erris Brown, 67, who has a farm in Haralson
County, Ga., and has been a jam maker for 50 years.
</P>
<P>
   Many jam and jelly makers say they enjoy sharing the experience
_ both in making and in giving. Brown often works with her daughter
and daughter-in-law. Lori Wilkins, 25, a family and consumer
science specialist with the Gwinnett County Extension Service
(Ga.), makes peach and strawberry jams with her mother to give as
Christmas gifts. ``It's great to make some with ripe summer fruit.
Then you have a head start on the holidays,'' said Wilkins. Jams
and jellies usually are tasty for up to a year.
</P>
<P>
   Add a beautiful label and tie on a hat of calico fabric with
some raffia, and you'll have a gift that speaks thoughtfulness _
something that required more effort than the swipe of a credit
card.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the trick is keeping the jams and jellies on the
shelf. Chances are the stock will dwindle each time the toaster
pops up or a pan of biscuits is pulled from the oven. But that's
OK. Make jam or jelly once, and you'll always have the magic.
</P>
<P>
   Reagan Walker writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
