<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COURTS-INTERNET-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURTS EMBRACE CYBERSPACE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PETER HARTLAUB  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ When the suspect in a high-profile Yosemite
murder case was scheduled for an arraignment at the federal
courthouse in Fresno last month, staff members there braced for a
media circus of O.J. Simpson-trial proportions.
</P>
<P>
   That's exactly what they got: A pack of reporters, bulky
satellite trucks in the parking lot and even a legal pundit or two.
</P>
<P>
   But the least of their problems, surprisingly, has been meeting
the demand for records. Since the case broke, almost every legal
document related to the case of Cary Anthony Stayner has appeared
on the court's World Wide Web site an hour after filing.
</P>
<P>
   Posting records on the Web is a growing trend in California
courthouses, where the public can cut through multiple layers of
red tape with a few strokes on a computer keyboard.
</P>
<P>
   The Northern District federal courthouse, based in San
Francisco, has a Web site (www.cand.uscourts.gov) that is even more
advanced than the Fresno site and most others in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've looked at the other Web sites,'' said Northern District
clerk Rich Wieking. ``Ours is as good as, if not better than, the
best of them.''
</P>
<P>
   If a federal court case breaks with as much public interest as
Stayner's, officials in the Northern District say they are ready to
post documents on the Web. Stayner is accused of killing a
researcher at the Yosemite National Park and reportedly confessed
to killing three visitors to the park earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   Other jurisdictions could have used such a service.
</P>
<P>
   Meeting the document needs for the O.J. Simpson murder trial and
civil lawsuit was a hassle for the staff of the Los Angeles
Superior Court, who had to print numerous copies of inch-thick
documents, selling them for 57 cents per page.
</P>
<P>
   While the staff in the Eastern District managed to avoid that
nightmare, the Stayner case wasn't the first major news event to
get an assist by a Web site.
</P>
<P>
   Court documents from the case of Theodore Kaczynski, the
convicted Unabomber, have been on the Web for months.
</P>
<P>
   ``After having Kaczynski in our district, I wasn't looking
forward to having such a high-profile case,'' said Marianne
Matherly, deputy in charge of the U.S. District Court clerk's
office, who handles media requests for the Stayner case.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it went quite well.''
</P>
<P>
   The Northern District Web site includes detailed maps to each of
its courthouses, downloadable forms, court calendars for each judge
and new civil case filings, which are updated daily.
</P>
<P>
   Assistant U.S. Attorney Matthew J. Jacobs said prosecutors
juggle cases in different courtrooms and appreciate the Web access
to court calendars.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very helpful,'' Jacobs said. ``I've used it, and I know
others have used it frequently.''
</P>
<P>
   In the long run, he hopes entire cases end up on the computer.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of paper that gets used in litigation, both
civil and criminal,'' Jacobs said. ``For some cases, (paperwork)
can end up filling a whole room, or several rooms.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
