A1733 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-CATSKILLS-ART-870(2TA     08-18 0931
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CATSKILLS-ART-870(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROM THE BORSCHT BELT, TODAY'S BEET SALAD 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By TRACIE ROZHON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ELLENVILLE , N.Y. _ Maybe it's the tiny glossy photograph of the
bowler hat and hatrack tacked to the wall of the foyer. Maybe it's
the amber plastic beads substituting for a door to the funky aqua
and white kitchen with the Italian molded chairs. Or maybe it's the
young woman with shingled hair, a graphic designer/wire sculptor
who wears her tank top and Dickies painter's pants with elan and
who has turned the old plastics factory here in the Catskills into
her personal retreat.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever it is, it's not your grandmother's Catskills.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, this is still the land of mobile homes and mountains, of
high grass and old farmhouses. It's still the land of abandoned
borscht belt bungalow colonies and tacky trout fishing souvenirs.
But now it is also a land of young New Yorkers, many of whom labor
in the design fields, who have begun to buy weekend and even
year-round houses in Ulster, Sullivan and Delaware Counties. These
men and women say they come for the serenity, the friendship and,
perhaps most important, the prices. Farmhouses with more than 100
acres go for less than $200,000; a cottage with 18 acres and a pond
sold for $65,000. A tiny house on one Main Street just went for
$23,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's your New York City types like me,'' said Ellen
Swandiak, the West Village graphic designer who is celebrating her
first summer in the white vinyl-sided factory in Ulster County.
(``Everyone has a name for their place up here,'' she said. ``Mine
is The Lab.'') ``Then there's your Hasidic types. Then you have
your gays. Then you have the ashrams. Then you have your rednecks _
all in the same spot.''
</P>
<P>
   In this population amalgam, the new people are not exactly
embraced by the local residents, but they are tolerated. There is a
grudging understanding that they fill up the cabins and create the
herb-suffused restaurants with names like Le Potagerie. In Sullivan
County, for example, the median yearly income has risen from
$33,884 to $45,000 in the last nine years, a rise that Jonathan
Drapkin, the county manager, links to an influx of new homeowners.
</P>
<P>
   The low house prices have a lot to do with the Catskills' allure
for the newest settlers _ Ms. Swandiak says that 20 friends have
moved to the mountains _ but so do the rusted-out pickup trucks.
``It's about getting sick of the snobbery,'' she said. ``In the
city, everyone asks: `Am I wearing the right things? Am I thin
enough?' Here, it doesn't matter.''
</P>
<P>
   Joe Dolce, an editorial consultant to magazines and to a new
fashion wire service, moved to the Sullivan County town of
Wurtsboro several years ago, in the vanguard of the new wave. He
shares Ms. Swandiak's Catskills vision.
</P>
<P>
   ``All day long we spend our energies searching for the chic and
sleek,'' he said. ``We want to spend the rest of our time where
absolutely nothing is in fashion, and that just about sums up
Sullivan County: the anti-sleek.''
</P>
<P>
   Not quite. Ms. Swandiak said she spent no more than $75 on any
piece of furniture, plucked from local thrift shops and auctions,
but each was chosen and is displayed with a designer's eye. Dolce,
too, boasted of his shopping prowess: ``Nothing costs more than
$100, including the red Formica table and four chairs.''
</P>
<P>
   Dolce's little gray-green '40s bungalow might once have been one
in a million, but now it's one of a kind. He ripped out walls and
created a cathedral ceiling. ``We put in an old claw-foot tub and
tiled,'' he said. ``We rebuilt the outdoor shower. This year, we're
painting the bedroom all white.'' But they're not ripping out the
knotty pine. Or the multicolored Christmas bulbs strung around the
cornice. Or the plastic deer on the refrigerator.
</P>
<P>
   Dolce and a handful of other New Yorkers live on a tiny street
in the section of town called Wurtsboro Hills. You can identify
their bungalows by the designer touches: red caladiums in
earthenware pots on a handkerchief-size patio; a brand-new trellis
leading to a guest cottage; perfectly patinated 1930s green lawn
furniture with flowered pillows on a screened-in porch.
</P>
<P>
   Wurtsboro, with its giant gas station, its real-estate offices
and its restaurants, Irish bar to French bistro, is one of the
larger towns in Sullivan County: its population hovers just under
1,200. Wurtsboro Hills was built in the '30s and '40s as a summer
community, where the water ran through above-ground pipes and was
turned off in October, then turned on again in May. Now the
newcomers have dug wells and insulated their houses. Still, the
section is about 60 percent summer people, 40 percent year-round
residents.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander Polakov, a Manhattan writer and graphic designer,
bought a Wurtsboro Hills bungalow that he had visited as a child: a
little cottage he has transformed into shelter-magazine chic.
``Wurtsboro is rare for the Catskills,'' he said, explaining why he
and so many of his friends have chosen the area. ``It's intact;
it's a real place. It's not as much of a ghost town as some
others.''
</P>
<P>
   In Wurtsboro, there are antiques shops, an ice cream shack
called Custard's Last Stand, a gym, a tattoo parlor, a pet shop and
a Harley-Davidson dealership. The full-time residents may drive the
Harleys, but everyone buys the ice cream cones.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Wurtsboro is close to Mountain Dale, which until a few years ago
looked like many Catskills towns: somewhat seedy. There are still
some boarded-up shops, but there are also signs of renewal: a new
balcony along Main Street and freshly painted shop fronts _ and For
Rent signs in the windows. There are hanging baskets with pink
petunias spilling from them.
</P>
<P>
   In other towns that ring the Catskill Mountains, things are not
so rosy. At midday in early August, Fleischmanns (pop. 346) in
Delaware County looked dusty and virtually abandoned. Yet the
newest inhabitants are delighted with the place. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Jee Levin, 27, and her husband, Randy Buck, 32, have just signed
a contract to buy a foursquare, turn-of-the century brown shingled
house at a corner on Wagner Avenue, once a prosperous street of
grand Victorian mansions. They are following their friends: five
other couples who have bought houses within 30 minutes of one
another. The listing price on their immaculate house, with a
raucous stream running across the back of the property, was
$69,500.
</P>
<P>
   The Wagner Avenue mansions appear to be well tended (``You don't
see any For Sale signs on them, do you?'' Buck asked, already
chauvinistic about his town.) But the town has a certain aura of,
well, poverty: empty stores and sagging sidewalks. There are no
pink petunias here. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Prince, a local real estate broker, was asked about finding
a place in Fleischmanns. ``Oh, that's easy,'' he said. ``The whole
town is for sale.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Like many towns in the Catskills _ towns like Loch Sheldrake and
Livingston Manor and Pine Hill _ Fleischmanns looks as if it needs
an infusion of money. Look what just such an infusion has done for
Margaretville, another once-sleepy backwater about five miles away.
On almost every block, at least one magnificent Victorian bears
signs of recent restoration, and the downtown is jumping, as much
as a place with a population of 690 can jump.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at Fleischmanns, it has equally beautiful antique
Victorian houses,'' said Jonathan E. Korn, a Margaretville
real-estate agent. But Margaretville has been lucky enough to land
the area's major supermarket, as well as new stores and
restaurants. Margaretville was also lucky _ in a macabre way _ to
be hard hit by flooding in 1996. Insurance paid for new sidewalks
and a new Main Street. Mayor Bill Hubbell also credited the
newcomers.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people are from New York,'' he said, ``and they've
brought fresh thoughts to the mountains.''
</P>
<P>
   Korn moved to Margaretville part time four years ago and has now
cut his ties to Manhattan: two weeks ago, he sold his city
apartment. He flipped through a book of listings: ``This is in the
New Kingston section, the TriBeCa of Margaretville,'' he intoned
with a straight face. ``Six acres, glorious valley. The owner calls
it Snow Beach _ $139,000. My God, that's the price of a studio in
the city. And look at this little cottage for $59,000. We're
showing it 10 times a day!''
</P>
<P>
   The agent took a visitor on a tour. ``You'll see a lot of people
like me, gay people,'' he said. ``But we don't want Margaretville
to be known as a gay place.'' He pointed out a stylish house on a
hill. ``That sold to straight people.'' He paused. ``Thank God.''
</P>
<P>
   Prices in Margaretville are higher than those in surrounding
communities. ``We're having a boom,'' Korn said, ``but the prices
here are still half the price of a house in Woodstock.'' But
there's a reason, he added: ``Woodstock is 45 minutes closer to the
city.''
</P>
<P>
   Buck, an art director for FAO Schwarz, and Ms. Levin, a food
stylist, advise young or impecunious house hunters to go the extra
distance. ``Look beyond the two-hour range,'' he said, referring to
the driving distance from midtown Manhattan. ``Look into the
two-and-a-half, even three-hour drive if you really want something
amazing. If you want Duchess County, you'd pay at least $225,000
for our house.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Buck also warned prospective buyers not to fall into the Land
Trap. ``Everybody gets carried away with 10 or 15 of their very own
acres,'' he said. ``But you'll pay more. And you'll pay more taxes.
Do you really have to call the woods yours?'' He and Ms. Levin
found that a lot of land was on steep mountainsides where no one
could build. ``You can get less acreage and more house for the same
amount of money,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   It all depends what a buyer is looking for. Buck and Ms. Levin
like a village feeling. Piyawat Pattanapuckdee, a clothing
designer, bought 18 acres and a cabin in Spring Glen for its
isolation and serenity. Bernard Figueroa, a shoe designer, lives in
the woods nearby, on 37 acres. ``An old guy had used the place to
go hunting and shoot targets with his children,'' Figueroa said.
``There were just beds.''
</P>
<P>
   He created a big square living room and a little square
bathroom. ``It's not all fixed up,'' he said in his thick French
accent. ``You know, it's not about showing off,'' he said. ``It's
not about fancy. It feels like being in the woods. Because that's
exactly where you are.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
