<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOLPHIN-LAWSUIT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COALITION SUES GOVERNMENT TO PROTECT DOLPHINS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JANE KAY  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The Earth Island Institute and nine other
environmental groups filed a lawsuit Wednesday against the U.S.
Commerce Department, alleging that commercial tuna boats in the
Pacific Ocean continue to deplete the dolphin population.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit contends that an agency of the Commerce Department
in April wrongly weakened the protections offered by the ``Dolphin
Safe'' label on cans of tuna. Congress adopted the label in 1990 as
a way to ensure consumers that packers and processors were buying
and selling tuna from U.S. and foreign fleets that didn't net tuna
when dolphins were swimming nearby.
</P>
<P>
   Deep sea boats set nets to operate like big drawstring purses,
first encircling, then cinching up large schools of yellowfin tuna.
But the ``purse seine nets'' can also trap, crush and drown
dolphins that frequently swim above the fish, the lawsuit said.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit names as defendants Commerce Secretary William Daley
and the National Marine Fisheries Service.
</P>
<P>
   Because of tuna fishing, more than 7 million dolphins have died
over the past 40 years, making it ``the largest scale slaughter of
marine mammals in the world,'' the lawsuit says.
</P>
<P>
   But the National Marine Fisheries Service concluded in April
that it couldn't determine that encircling dolphins with nets
during tuna fishing significantly harms dolphin populations.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, under the current rule, fishing fleets can use the nets
when dolphins are present, yet sell under the ``Dolphin Safe''
label unless international observers on board the boats actually
see dead or seriously injured dolphins.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit, filed in the U.S. District Court in San Francisco,
seeks to overturn the Marine Fisheries Service decision.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit says the government's action will have ``a direct
and immediate'' impact on the northeastern offshore spotted
dolphins, eastern spinner dolphins and coastal spotted dolphins.
</P>
<P>
   Research to date does not indicate that fishing with purse seine
nets poses a long-term threat to the populations, said Scott
Smullen, a spokesman for the National Oceanic and Atmospheric
Administration, the branch of the Commerce Department that oversees
the fisheries service.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past years, the purse seine technique has improved
dramatically, Smullen said.
</P>
<P>
   Under the International Dolphin Conservation Program Act of
1997, the fisheries service is required to survey dolphins in the
eastern tropical Pacific to try again to determine whether purse
seine fishing is depleting the populations, particularly spinner
and spotted dolphins. Final results are due in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Palmer, a spokesman for Earth Island Institute, said, ``We
feel that the research done so far by the National Marine Fisheries
Service staff scientists and the Inter-American Tropical Tuna
Commission already shows that populations are not rebounding and in
some cases are still declining.''
</P>
<P>
   Several processors and packers of canned tuna have pledged to
maintain the pre-April standard of not encircling dolphins. The
list includes StarKist, Bumble Bee and Chicken of the Sea, which
sell 90 percent of canned tuna in the United States.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
