<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-18 16:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1758 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-AUDIO-KULANJAN19-COX     08-18 0345
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUDIO-KULANJAN19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The Taj travels to Africa
 &HT;    By Steve Dollar
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Taj Mahal's musical passport has been stamped so many times it
must be falling apart. The peripatetic guitarist stays in motion,
whether he's reaching back to unearth the prewar roots of country
blues or touring the Caribbean islands, the better to master
rhythms that are part of his genetic history. Mahal's latest
project is a collaboration with Toumani Diabate, the Malian master
of the kora, a stringed instrument that uses a large gourd as a
resonator. Along with a small band of musicians from Mali, the pair
creates a quietly captivating fusion of American blues and two
streams of traditional music: that of the Mande griots
(historically, praise songs for royalty) and wassoulou, or hunters'
music.
</P>
<P>
   Those distinctions begin to blur almost as soon as the album
begins. The harplike flutter of the kora's strings finds an earthy
counterpoint in Mahal's flat-picking guitar style, just as his
gruff voice is offset by vocalist Ramatou Diakite's gracefully
longing soprano. The song ``Queen Bee'' sets the stage, as the
ensemble seeks common ground. The music, recorded last April in
Athens by producer John Keane, radiates warmth and informal humor,
as when Mahal sings the glories of Toumani's wife, ``Fanta Sacko.''
The tune features Mahal's jaunty New Orleans-style piano, lyrics
sung in Cajun French and the fleet, delicate melody of the balafon,
an African xylophone.
</P>
<P>
   It's disarmingly heartfelt stuff. As with guitarist (and former
Mahal bandmate) Ry Cooder's acclaimed meetings with Mali's Ali
Farka Toure, the project offers a conveniently broad and engaging
entry point into the sounds of West Africa.
</P>
<P>
   Taj Mahal and Toumani Diabate perform at Africa Fete on Sunday
at Variety Playhouse.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kulanjan''
</P>
<P>
   Taj Mahal/Toumani Diabate. Hannibal/Rykodisc. 12 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A
</P>
<P>
   _Steve Dollar writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
