<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-ANALYZE19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    In the last analysis, it's funny enough
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Analyze This'' (R)
</P>
<P>
   Accustomed to expressing his feelings with a bullet, gangster
Paul Vitti (Robert De Niro) is not a natural candidate for
psychotherapy. But in this slick farce, the shiny-suited mobster
winds up in the bland suburban office of Ben Sobol (Billy Crystal),
a nebbishy psychiatrist whose clients run toward long-marrieds
bored with their sex lives.
</P>
<P>
   Planning for a meeting of New York's rival mob families, Paul
has had trouble sleeping. And breathing. He'd rather think it's
heart trouble than his doctor's diagnosis: a sissy-sounding ``panic
attack.'' That's what leads him to demand some quality shrink time
with Ben. Or else.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the good doctor has to face the moral quandary of
helping Paul become ``a happy, well-adjusted gangster.''
</P>
<P>
   Harold Ramis (``Groundhog Day'') directs with a sleek
professionalism, but the movie won't surprise you.
</P>
<P>
   You get mob jokes, therapy jokes and parodies of scenes from
``The Godfather.'' It never hits the giddy heights a top farce
reaches, but the stars (plus Lisa Kudrow as Crystal's fiancee) make
it worthwhile.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   _ Steve Murray writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
