<TEXT>
<P>
   Mini video reviews
</P>
<P>
   By Steve Murray and Jill Vejnoskac. 1999 Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``EDtv'' (PG-13) _ Matthew McConaughey plays the subject of a
24-hour-a-day documentary in Ron Howard's comedy. Yeah, it's too
much like ``The Truman Show'' for its own good, but the slick
packaging and strong cast (including Jenna Elfman, Ellen DeGeneres
and Martin Landau) help it stand on its own. Grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   _Steve Murray
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Playing by Heart'' (R) _ This would-be Altmanesque tapestry
about a group of people looking for love in Los Angeles becomes a
deeply annoying exercise in overwriting. That's because
writer-director Willard Carroll is clearly in love with his own
voice, making every character speak in the same overly articulate,
precious way. The good, wasted cast includes Sean Connery, Gena
Rowlands, Gillian Anderson and Angelina Jolie, who cuts through the
twee dialogue with a vibrant, party-girl performance. Grade: C
</P>
<P>
   _Steve Murray
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Office Space'' (R) _ An amusingly and eerily familiar comedy
for anyone who's ever struggled against the monotonous mind control
of a large corporate workplace. After wittily building audience
resentment for nearly 90 minutes, writer-director Mike Judge (TV's
``Beavis &AMP; Butt-head,'' ``King of the Hill'') seems to pull his
punches with a less-than-apocalyptic ending. Grade: B-
</P>
<P>
   _Jill Vejnoska
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``200 Cigarettes'' (R) _ Like a New Year's Eve nightmare writ
large, numerous New Yorkers struggle to hook up with someone on the
way to an end-of-1991 party. Most of the characters are obnoxious
and sex-obsessed, but a few performances, the only-in-the-'80s
outfits and, most especially, the music, shine through. Grade: C+
</P>
<P>
   _Jill Vejnoska
</P>
<P>
   Steve Murray and Jill Vejnoska write for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
