<HEADER>
A1763 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-AUDIO-MINIS19-COX     08-18 0497
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUDIO-MINIS19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mini CD reviews
 &HT;    By Sonia Murray, Eileen M. Drennen, and Shane Harrison
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QR;  R&AMP;B
</P>
<P>
   ``Bitter''
</P>
<P>
   MeShell Ndegeocello. Maverick. 12 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A
</P>
<P>
   If there's anything to be ``Bitter'' about after listening to
this album, it's that this magnificent bass player isn't _
noticeably anyway _ playing. That aside, this is the third in a
series of incredible, cohesive explorations of emotion by arguably
the best thing to come out of R&AMP;B this decade, MeShell Ndegeocello.
Stripped of the dense, lush arrangements that made predecessors
``Plantation Lullabies'' and ``Peace Beyond Passion'' so engaging,
this nearly naked effort tugs at our hearts with prominent acoustic
strings, coupled with Ndegeocello's usually strong writing. With
each song she slowly fleshes out the inseparable insecurities
(``Fool of Me'') and ecstasies (``Satisfy'') that come when you let
someone in.
</P>
<P>
   _Sonia Murray
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  POP
</P>
<P>
   ``Broken Things''
</P>
<P>
   Julie Miller. HighTone Records. 12 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   Ghostly, melancholy and unexpected, Julie Miller's songs are
like fireworks stands along the great Americana highway. Her images
may be rooted in the real, but her obsessions spring from the
shadows between this world and the next. With husband Buddy Miller
on guitar and backing vocals (and able assists from Patty Griffin,
Victoria Williams and Steve Earle) she sings her well-made tales of
love and ashes with a voice that swings from kidlike highs to
reedier depths. The album's centerpiece is the title track, which
constructs a modern hymn of surrender upon the chorus ``you can
have my heart, if you don't mind broken things,'' bolstered by
cello, bass, piano and Emmylou Harris' celestial harmonies.
</P>
<P>
   _Eileen M. Drennen
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ROCK
</P>
<P>
   ``Come Pick Me Up''
</P>
<P>
   Superchunk. Merge. 13 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   Few bands make music with as much apparent joyousness as
Superchunk. The enthusiasm is so infectious that you can forgive
the looming shadow of the Pixies that hangs over every note. These
four indie rock poster children from North Carolina have cranked
out stuff like this for a decade: solid, tuneful and fun. ``Come
Pick Me Up'' makes a fine addition to the band's catalog, working
its punky magic incrementally. The first listen passes without
incident. Play it again and you're mumbling, ``Hey, that song is
kinda cool.'' Soon, you just have to shake your head to ``Hello
Hawk'' again or marvel one more time at the charmingly incongruous
strings on ``1000 Pounds.'' It may not set the world on fire, but
it's not Nirvana-lite or a funk-rap-metal hybrid, putting ``Come
Pick Me Up'' miles ahead of the music spewing from the maw of the
American corporate rock machine.
</P>
<P>
   _Shane Harrison
</P>
<P>
   Sonia Murray, Eileen M. Drennen, and Shane Harrison writes for
the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
