<SLUG> BC-AUDIO-RAP19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Kool Keith trips up on spacey fantasies
 &HT;    By Steve Dollar
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hip-hop's answer to such extraterrestrial personages as Sun Ra,
George Clinton (in his ``Mothership Connection'' phase) and that
androgyne who fell to Earth, David Bowie, the rapper known as Kool
Keith fancies himself a starship trouper. The erstwhile founder of
Ultramagnetic MCs reinvented himself as Dr. Octagon a few years
back and became a fringe sensation. Portraying an alien sex fiend
who spewed untidy rhymes, Keith got over on sheer audacity and
comic perversity. DJ Automator (Dan Nakamura) was his secret
weapon, though, cutting up Pachelbel's Canon and '70s porn
soundtracks with heavy metal riffs and video-game bleats.
</P>
<P>
   Now calling himself Black Elvis, Keith's back with a sequel. But
what seemed fresh now looks more like a gimmick. The run-on
cadences jump with hilarity, as the opening track challenges
hip-hop posturing: ``Why are you making those mean faces in your
videos with the fish-lens effects?'' And, on such tracks as
``Supergalactic Lover'' and ``Master of the Game'' (with the late
Roger Troutman), Keith finds inspiration in old-school funk and R&AMP;B
grooves. But the sci-fi themes, like the rapper's throwaway
approach to lyrics, wear thin over 17 tracks. And without the
Automator around to scramble expectations, ``Black Elvis'' is a
persona that's all punch line and no punch.
</P>
<P>
   Take consolation in this, however: You can buy a ``Black Elvis''
wig, just like the one Kool Keith wears, for $20.
</P>
<P>
   _Steve Dollar
</P>
<P>
   Kool Keith brings the ``Black Elvis Tour,'' with special guest
DJ Spooky, to the Masquerade on Aug. 27.
</P>
<P>
   ``Black Elvis/Lost in Space''
</P>
<P>
   Kool Keith. Ruffhouse/Columbia. 17 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C+
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
