<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWIMMING-POOL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE POOL WANTED PALMS, SO IT MOVED TO MIAMI 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By JULIE V. IOVINE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Hold the chain saw _ I'm moving to Florida!'' Daniel R. Lewis,
an insurance heir, recalled telling his construction workers as
they were revving up to add a $1 million indoor swimming pool to
his 8,000-square-foot house in suburban Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis, a director of the Progressive insurance company, founded
by his father, had decided that the house was simply not
distinguished enough for the swimming pool he had in mind: part
Roman Baths of Caracalla, part Eastern European shvitz, or sweat
bath. Oh, and part art installation, too.
</P>
<P>
   Miami was a much more natural fit.
</P>
<P>
   The pool house _ a minimalist marble nirvana so sleek it looks
as if some ancient ruin had been tossed into a stone tumbler and
polished _ has now been appended to a 1920's Mediterranean-style
villa in the Coconut Grove section of Miami, surrounded by swaying
palms and an artfully dilapidated wall of coral arches.
</P>
<P>
   No one was happier about the last-minute change of venue than
Jackie Ferrara, a New York sculptor, and William Bialosky, a New
York architect, who had been hired to collaborate on Lewis' dream
design.
</P>
<P>
   Bialosky knew exactly how the pool and bathhouse had to work. As
Lewis' nephew, he had often accompanied Lewis to the old-fashioned
neighborhood bathhouses in Cleveland, with their customary hot
rooms, followed by cold dips followed by card games, pirogis and
cigars _ a routine loosely adapted from ancient bathing rituals.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a rite of passage in our family,'' Bialosky said. ``Dan
and I used to go a lot when we were growing up.''
</P>
<P>
   But it was Ms. Ferrara's miniature study models of Roman
bathhouses lined up on a shelf in her SoHo studio that had
entranced Lewis when he visited her in search of art for his
sculpture collection.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bathhouses are one of my favorite places,'' Lewis said. ``I
love the history of how they evolved from a community service for
people who couldn't afford plumbing into places where people
socialized. And when I walked into Jackie's studio and saw these
models, I thought, `Aha!'''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Ferrara's fascination with baths is more geometric than
social. (``Jackie is infatuated with brick arches you can't walk
through,'' Bialosky said.) She is known for her austere geometries
in projects like the tiled-arch motif on the shuttle platform in
Grand Central Terminal and a new red granite amphitheater at the
Los Angeles County Museum of Art. Her imagery often combines the
archaic and the futuristic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm drawn to things that are not easy to put a date on,'' she
said. ``I read a lot of science fiction. `Blade Runner' is my
favorite movie.''
</P>
<P>
   For the Lewis bathhouse, Ms. Ferrara and Bialosky put an
L-shaped pavilion and a lap pool at the edge of a wide green lawn.
For the pool, which is 4 feet deep, 12 feet wide and 75 feet long,
Ms. Ferrara composed an extravagantly elegant backsplash of arches
etched in beige and rose-colored marble (from Greece by way of Long
Island City).
</P>
<P>
   Bialosky noted that the earlier pool design, for the house in
Cleveland, also had arches but that they came to vivid life only
when set against the crumbling coral arches that already lined the
property.
</P>
<P>
   A 90-foot-long marble colonnade with a redwood trellis as a roof
contains the rooms for the shvitz. There's the requisite hot room,
which Lewis can turn on from his airplane. The room, a marble-clad
cell with walls that gently stack ziggurat-style up to a ceiling
made of circular glass block, heats up to 180 degrees and is
equipped with the traditional wooden buckets for pouring cold water
over the head when the heat becomes unbearable.
</P>
<P>
   There's also a shock-therapy shower running with water
refrigerated to 50 degrees. The hardy can proceed to swim laps or
collapse in what Bialosky calls ``the wet living room'' _ an
8-by-12-foot ledge at poolside where the water is six inches deep.
</P>
<P>
   On the upper floor, there's a card room with marble walls and a
mahogany card table that Ms. Ferrara fashioned in the spirit of
Charles Rennie Mackintosh. Poker is the game of choice, and Ms.
Ferrara, her client said admiringly, keeps a note pad recording
winnings that go back several years.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis said he and his wife usually invite seven or eight couples
at a time to enjoy the pool and bathhouse, which he described
succinctly as linear, clean and spectacular.
</P>
<P>
   On occasion, masseuses and manicurists are stationed in the hot
room. The unisex changing room is stocked with bathing suits in
every size, for those who want to wear a little something. Guests
don robes for dinner, which is served on a terrace.
</P>
<P>
   Enjoying the bathhouse, Lewis said, is ``the true focal point of
the evening.''
</P>
<P>
   ``People feel indulged,'' he said. ``It's obviously very
casual.''
</P>
<P>
   And chances are that Miami's weather, unlike Cleveland's, is
always permitting.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-18-99 1659EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
