<HEADER>
A1820 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-COWBOY-POETRY-NYT     08-18 0733
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-COWBOY-POETRY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COWBOY POETS AT HOME ON THE WEB 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Wyo., Calif., Texas, N.D., Wash.)   (af)  
 By MICHAEL POLLAK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   What, you may ask, is cowboy poetry?
</P>
<P>
   Cowboy poetry is for people who define ``deconstruction'' as
what you do when you break camp, but who find meter and mood and
metaphor in the rough beauty of that camp.
</P>
<P>
   Cowboy poetry is for people who think The New Yorker is someone
to feel sorry for and The Paris Review is where The New Yorkers go
to watch fancy ladies dance the cancan. It is also for people who
know better but do not care.
</P>
<P>
   It is for people who know that plain and straight does not mean
stupid, who would rather risk being trite than being untrue, and
who agree with John Ford that if the West did not really happen
that way, it should have.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cowboy poetry is simple, it's to the point, it tells a story
and is fun, or thoughtful, or even very sad (and we hope it
rhymes),'' Michael ``Coyote'' Schroll wrote by e-mail. ``There are
a lot of cowboy poets out there, some say 100,000 of us (I wonder
about those figures, though; anyone can call themselves a poet) all
trying to tell their stories in a simple way that our friends can
understand and appreciate.''
</P>
<P>
   Here, from www.cowboypoems.com, is a tiny sample from Schroll,
who bills himself as Wyoming's resident cowboy poet: &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (italics)The cowgirl looked into his eyes
</P>
<P>
   He took her breath away.
</P>
<P>
   She knew he rode for X BAR 9
</P>
<P>
   Her words he couldn't say. . . .''(end italics)
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboy Cattle-Log (cattle-log.com) is a mix of Western
music, literature, tourism and merchandise links based in Recluse,
Wyo., including Dry Crik Press and Cattle Call Magazine. Cattle
Call has a Featured Poet page (cattle-log.com/callpoet.html). This
is from ``Fallin' Asleep'' by Fred Engel:  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (italics)Late in the evenin', when the
</P>
<P>
   Sun's gone down,
</P>
<P>
   And I'm in my blankets,
</P>
<P>
   I've spread on the ground,
</P>
<P>
   My mind starts driftin'
</P>
<P>
   While lookin' up at the sky,
</P>
<P>
   And thoughts cross my mind,
</P>
<P>
   That make me wonder why. ...(end italics) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I've for a long time written these little stories and these
things that rhyme, and then I found out it was called cowboy
poetry,'' Engel, a cattleman, said by telephone. He says of the
poetry, ``It's a genuine attempt to keep the undisputed symbol of
the American West alive.''
</P>
<P>
   Engel reads a poem each week on KPIG radio (107-oink-5 FM) in
Freedom, Calif. He guesses that his poem ``Attention Vegetarians''
got the most response. ``I wrote that at the time when Oprah got in
trouble with the Texas cattle feeders.'' (The poem ends:
(italics)``Just sit down and relax, and pass the steak sauce if you
please.'')(end italics)
</P>
<P>
   In 1985, the first Elko, Nev., Cowboy Poetry Gathering was held
at the Western Folklife Center. Its Web site, www.westfolk.org,
highlights the 1999 gathering in January, with links, history and
stories. Users with Real Player can listen to a lot of poetry.
Similar gatherings, attracting big audiences, have spread to
Alpine, Texas, Riverton, Wyo., Medora, N.D., and many other places.
</P>
<P>
   There is poetry about the buffalo soldiers and about rural
women. (See Barney Nelson's speech at the Westfolk site on the need
for poems (italics) ``about the ten thousand antelope, wildflowers,
redtails and dawns we saw while driving the kids to school.'')(end
italics)
</P>
<P>
   And there are Irish cowboy poets, like John P. Doran, ``the
Celtic cowboy.'' His Web site, www.cowboypoet.com, combines poetry
and his day job, outfitting wilderness trips in Washington State.
</P>
<P>
   Doran grew up on a ranch in Twisp, Wash., and remembers asking
his father if he could learn to play the bagpipes. ``I don't see no
reason; it's in your heritage,'' his father told him. He said
cowboy poetry is ``the same old Irish tradition of telling the
story in verse.''
</P>
<P>
   His personal totem is the coyote: &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (italics)High above the valley floor,
</P>
<P>
   where the rocks are sharp and bare,
</P>
<P>
   he sits back on his haunches
</P>
<P>
   and drinks in the cool night air.
</P>
<P>
   He sings a song of freedom,
</P>
<P>
   of the wilds and of the night
</P>
<P>
   and bestows his nocturnal hymns
</P>
<P>
   to a horse-thief moon so bright.
</P>
<P>
   Then it made me think that I was him
</P>
<P>
   upon that distant hill.
</P>
<P>
   For my spirit soared and my heart found peace
</P>
<P>
   just to know he's out there still.(end italics)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
