<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-18 17:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1824 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-SPOLETO-NYT &LR;      08-18 1141
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPOLETO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO WORLDS (WELL, AT LEAST ONE) STILL SPIN AT SPOLETO 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By ANNE MIDGETTE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SPOLETO, Italy _ At 8:30 p.m., the piazza in front of the
cathedral here is empty. Late sun strikes gold from the high bell
tower, but the square is steeped in silvery shadow, and the air is
so unseasonably cool that the musicians playing on the steps of the
Teatro Caio Melisso are comfortable, rather than sweltering, in
their formal tails.
</P>
<P>
   Only a few people are sitting in the chairs in front of them.
Across the square a couple of cocktail drinkers watch from the
handful of tables huddled in front of the restaurant Tric Trac. The
musicians finish, to a scattering of applause, and the Teatro Caio
Melisso prepares for a performance of ``Les Porteurs d'Eau'' by the
Theatre Talipot from Madagascar that only a few dozen people will
attend.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first week of the festival is always slow,'' said sculptor
Robin Heidi Kennedy, a local resident, red velvet glowing from the
empty seats around her.
</P>
<P>
   In a town like Salzburg or Bayreuth, using the words ``slow''
and ``festival'' in the same sentence might imply the kiss of
death. But in Italy, one expects invited guests to come a little
late. And the Festival of Two Worlds in Spoleto, while it has moved
far from the kind of informal happening it was when Italian
composer Giancarlo Menotti founded it in 1958, still offers
something of the casual intimacy that characterized it when Jerome
Robbins and Luchino Visconti were fixtures, and young musicians
named Yo-Yo Ma and Jacqueline Du Pre or luminaries like Sviatoslav
Richter made impromptu appearances in the noontime concerts.
</P>
<P>
   Established though it is, Spoleto, which ran this year from
mid-June to mid-July, still relies on a personal touch, announcing
noontime programs at the last minute, or loading audiences for the
series Music in Secret Umbria into buses and driving them out for a
picnic and concert in Romanesque churches nestled in the hills,
like a good host showing the area to out-of-town guests. Menotti,
creator of ``Amahl and the Night Visitors,'' holds the unofficial
title of most-performed living composer. Still, the German
newspaper Rheinischer Merkur is not alone in assessing him as
``cleverer as a festival founder than as a composer.''
</P>
<P>
   Today the mainstream classical-music world looks askance at his
operas, condemning them as popular and facile (even as American
opera companies seek out new narrative, tonal works to lure the
audiences that used to flock to Menotti's pieces). His festival, on
the other hand, is an acknowledged institution, unusual in Europe
for its equal emphasis on music and theater, film, art and dance.
</P>
<P>
   The 1999 program included a new monologue by Nobel Prize winner
Dario Fo, a theater piece by French film director Eric Rohmer, a
concert by pianist Jean-Yves Thibaudet (who played here at earlier
stages of his career) and Menotti's staging of Prokofiev's
seldom-performed opera ``War and Peace.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Spoleto was started to prove that the arts could turn the
economy around in a small, depressed town,'' Menotti said over
lunch recently. A village that used to boast but a single hotel now
has a full complement of pensione and ristoranti for the annual
influx of guests; and more and more well-heeled foreigners are
buying and restoring houses in the area.
</P>
<P>
   Menotti has changed his economic outlook as well. Now 88, the
man who once said he wanted to live out his old age in a cottage by
the sea resides during the year in a full-blown castle in Scotland,
with his adopted son, Francis, his son's wife and their two sons,
Claudio, 12, and Cosimo, 8.
</P>
<P>
   The Italian press has called Menotti the Sun King of Spoleto: a
benevolent but all-powerful ruler with a whim of iron. But the
second of his ``two worlds,'' the United States, countered monarchy
with democracy in the best American tradition at Spoleto's American
colony in Charleston, S.C., founded in 1977. When Menotti tried to
designate Francis as his heir, the board of Spoleto U.S.A.
rebelled, and the elder Menotti finally cleared the field in 1993
and retreated to Umbria, severing ties with the Charleston festival
altogether.
</P>
<P>
   Italy has no problem with dynasties: Francis Menotti has served
as the festival's president since 1993, and this year he officially
took over as artistic director. Born Francis Phelan in
Pennsylvania, a former professional ice skater and actor who used
to appear in Menotti works (like the play ``The Leper,'' which was
written for him), he was adopted in 1974, at age 36. He proclaims
himself dedicated to continuing the festival in his father's spirit
while solidifying an organizational structure that has been
dependent on Giancarlo Menotti's whim.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Testimony to the weather vane changes of his decrees are the
short tenures of some of the festival's artistic and music
directors. Thomas Schippers, who served a long tenure as artistic
and then music director until 1975, was followed by a string of
short-termers: Massimo Bogianckino, Romolo Valli, Rafaello de
Banfield. ``Four or five years,'' Menotti has said, ``then I think
that we should get some new view in here.'' This year was the first
for the newest director, the British conductor Richard Hickox.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   In conversation, Menotti bubbled with charm and anecdote,
opinions about the evils of modern stage direction, and concern
about how to fit the huge cast and chorus of ``War and Peace'' onto
the diminutive stage of the Teatro Nuovo. Still, he would hardly
have undertaken the Herculean task of staging the work had the
scheduled director not pulled out at the last minute. In any event,
the co-director, Roman Hurko, did most of the heavy lifting, with
Menotti presiding over an occasional rehearsal.
</P>
<P>
   The staging hardly won raves: reviews described it as naive,
rudimentary and even ``in an antiquated Bolshoi style.'' Yet the
ensemble was roundly praised, and Hickox, who had devoted
considerable time to auditioning the students who play in the
Spoleto Festival Orchestra, was hailed for creating ``a vibrating
cosmos of tender lyricism.'' The event made a good case for
revivals of an opera that the expert on Russian music Richard
Taruskin calls ``Prokofiev's masterpiece.'' Opening night of ``War
and Peace'' was sold out.
</P>
<P>
   Festival regulars often wax nostalgic about Spoleto's glory
days; and there is no question that the festival, like its founder,
has lost some of its energy. Yet the Festival of Two Worlds
prevails.
</P>
<P>
   ``That the festival has hardly lost its freshness is
demonstrated by the program of this 42nd edition,'' said the German
daily Sueddeutsche Zeitung. ``Where else in Europe can you find
such a constellation'' of different shows and events?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
