<HEADLINE>
KANSAS CITY STAR BUDGET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Kansas City Star plans to move the following stories for use
by clients of the NYTimes News Service for AMs and PMs of Thursday,
August 19. If you have any questions, please call The Star's News
Desk at (816) 234-4720.
</P>
<P>
   BOMB _ For more than 80 years, chemical weapons and other
ordnance from a World War I-era research project have lay buried
beneath a cozy upscale D.C. neighborhood. They're even digging up
the backyard of the South Korean ambassador. 27. David Goldstein.
</P>
<P>
   JOHN _ Arizona Sen. John McCain speaks to the VFW convention.
Photo. 20. Scott Canon.
</P>
<P>
   RUSS. Major Gen. Antonoich Zolotarev, Institute of Military
History, Russia, speaks at the VFW convention on Wednesday. He's
co-chairman of U.S.-Russia Joint Commission on POWs and MIAs. This
is the joint commission looking into whether American service
personnel from the Korea, Vietnam or Cold wars were spirited into
the former Soviet Union. Photo. Brian Burnes. 15.
</P>
<P>
   AIR: Air pollution officials revealed this week that KC's
``crisis'' earlier this summer over losing federal transportation
money because of bad air wasn't a crisis after all. Mid-America
Regional Council's computer model has been updated, showing our
air's OK, meaning governors from both states didn't really have to
request the introduction of reformulated gasoline. But they're
going ahead anyway with RFG, because it'll only make the air
cleaner. Confused? So were they. Jeffrey Spivak. 20.
</P>
<P>
   MIKE. First-grader Michael Scherzer had a rare form of leukemia
that didn't respond to chemotherapy. Now, after four bone marrow
transplants and a lot of support from the community, he's better.
Wednesday was his first day back at school in Olathe. Mhari Doyle.
20. Photos.
</P>
<P>
   SERBS: During the height of the Balkan war, Father Alexander
Bugarin watched news accounts of atrocities committed against the
Muslim ethnic Albanians in Kosovo. Now, with the Kosovars back
home, the Serbs are suffering much the same fate in waves of
retribution. Bugarin, pastor at St. George Serbian Orthodox Church
in Kansas City, Kan., can only wonder: Where is the American
outrage now? Malcolm Garcia. 15. Photo.
</P>
<P>
   BUREAU. Johnson County, Kan., where the numbers of county
employees has soared, shows what's happening nationally: a new
Census Bureau study finds that the total state and local government
workers in the U.S. has grown. In Kansas, on a per capita basis,
the state has the sixth-highest number of government workers in the
country. Missouri is in the middle. 25. John A. Dvorak. Chart
</P>
<P>
   OZ. What's are the next hurdles the Oz theme park has to clear?
Grace Hobson.
</P>
<P>
   TITLE _ The country's largest title insurer acquires the
11-office operation of Olathe, Kan.-based Security Title. Eric
Palmer. 450 words.
</P>
<P>
   STAFF (column) _ Readers share more of their most-hated business
buzzwords. Diane Stafford
</P>
<P>
   ROYALS. Kansas City at New York, 6:35 p.m. Dick Kaegel. 16-18.
</P>
<P>
   VANOVER. Gunther Cunningham says Tamarick Vanover is going to
get on the field and he's going to get the ball. And not just as a
special teams player. How Cunningham can do that with Vanover
filling the team's fifth receiver spot remains to be seen. Adam
Teicher. 18-20.
</P>
<P>
   POZ. Joe Posnanski column from Chiefs training camp.
</P>
<P>
   AJGA19. What are the chances that the next Tiger Woods or Sergio
Garcia is playing in today's final round of the AJGA tournament at
Oakwood Country Club in Kansas City? A feature look at how some
kids make the junior circuit a stepping stone to professional golf.
Howard Richman. 16-18.
</P>
<P>
   KANSAS. Football feature from University of Kansas preseason
camp. Bob Dutton.
</P>
</TEXT>
