<HEADER>
A1846 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-CHRISTENING-GIFTS19-C     08-18 0156
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHRISTENING-GIFTS19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Give a lasting memory
 &HT;    By Marylin Johnson
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   After a christening, friends and family often celebrate with
parents at a reception, brunch or party. Appropriate gifts should
be lasting mementos, which might be engraved with the baby's
initials or date of the christening. Silver is a typical gift and
could include a picture frame, a small comb and brush set, a mug or
cup or a fork-and-spoon set. Other silver suggestions: a baby
rattle, a Bible with a silver overlay, a keepsake box or a
christening cup that holds the water used in certain baptisms and
christening ceremonies. A bit more whimsical gift might be a small
toy, a piece of clothing such as a cotton bib or booties or a set
of children's china.
</P>
<P>
   Marylin Johnson writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
