</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Track down hard to find items
 &HT;    By Marylin Johnson
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Having trouble finding a particular item? We'll try to
help you locate it. But due to the volume of mail, we cannot track
down every request. Write us at Buyer's Edge Find It, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta, GA 30302; e-mail us
at buyersedge(at)ajc.com (please include your name, the city you
live in and daytime phone number); or call 404-582-7642.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Last year I bought a tin of fruit jellies from the food
department at Neiman Marcus in Lenox Square. I went back several
times, but they have run out. Can you find out when I can buy these
candies again?
</P>
<P>
   _Lydia S. Vicente, Lilburn
</P>
<P>
   A: Even the tin looks good enough to eat. And so do the candies
_ colorful fruit ``slices'' that have soft centers and are coated
in sugar. Churchill's Natural Luxury Fruit Jellies ($12.50 for a
9.52-ounce tin) are once again at Neiman Marcus and come in such
flavors as raspberry, apple, tangerine, peach, pineapple, plum and
blackberry. Information: 404-266-8200.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Where can I find powdered vanilla? I use it in my coffee that
I buy by the cup at Caribou, but I can't get any information on
where to find it in retail stores. This vanilla makes an excellent
topper for plain coffee.
</P>
<P>
   _ Tamara Williams, McDonough
</P>
<P>
   Another vanilla question: A recent recipe in the Food section
called for Nielsen-Massey Vanilla. Can you tell me where it's
available?
</P>
<P>
   _ Joanne Schmidt, Atlanta
</P>
<P>
   A: Vanilla originated in Mexico and was brought to Europe in the
1500s. Grown mainly in Madagascar and Indonesia, the vanilla bean,
or pod, is the only edible fruit-bearing orchid. Since 1907,
Waukegan, Ill.-based Nielsen-Massey has been making a Pure Vanilla
Powder ($4.99 for a 2.5-ounce bottle) and a Pure Vanilla Extract
($4.99 for a 4-ounce bottle; $7.99 for an 8-ounce bottle). They are
available at Whole Foods Market, 2111 Briarcliff Road N.E.
(404-634-7800).
</P>
<P>
   Q: I am looking for a line of hair products by the name Bumble
and bumble. I have looked everywhere, but no one seems to have
them. Thanks a bunch!
</P>
<P>
   _Leslye Vaughn, Lawrenceville
</P>
<P>
   A: Here's the buzz on Bumble and bumble. It's a trendy New York
hair salon founded more than 20 years ago by Michael Gordon. Models
as well as regular folk flock there to get the newest cuts and
colors. The staff also styles hair for fashion and beauty stories
in such magazines as Vogue, Harper's Bazaar and Town &AMP; Country. The
salon developed its own line of shampoos, conditioners and other
styling products ($9-$20), which are available in salons across the
country. In Atlanta, look for the line at: Studio Oliver, 789
Argonne N.E. (404-607-9757); Parkside Hair Studio, 1451 Piedmont
Ave. N.E. (404-873-2546); and the Austin Avenue Barber shop, 914
Austin Ave. N.E. (404-523-2324).
</P>
<P>
   Q: I am looking for a soap called Maja. It smells like
sandalwood and has a Spanish dancer on the wrapper.
</P>
<P>
   _ Mary Ann Miller,
</P>
<P>
   Peachtree City
</P>
<P>
   And this Maja plea: I am looking for a soap called Maja that
used to be carried by JC Penney. Now I can only find it in a
Spanish drugstore in Miami. Is there some place locally to buy it?
</P>
<P>
   _ Carol Murphy, Woodstock
</P>
<P>
   Yet another soapy request: I am looking for Castile bar soap.
It's in a white package with red and blue lettering and has coconut
as an ingredient.
</P>
<P>
   _ Ben Thomas, Peachtree City
</P>
<P>
   A: Let us get on our soap box. First up is Maja, a
clean-smelling sandalwood soap. It's imported from Barcelona,
Spain, and comes in a dramatic black box accented with a Spanish
dancer and colorful red and orange flowers. A 5.2-ounce, round bar
is $6 at King's Drugs, 2345 Peachtree Road N.E. (404-233-2101).
</P>
<P>
   Now for Castile. Reader Thomas knows his soap. Kirk's makes the
all-natural Coco Hardwater Castile bar soap from coconut oil. It's
$2.99 for a 4-ounce bar at Miller's Rexall Drugs, 87 Broad St.
(404-523-8481). According to the manufacturer, you can also use
this soap as a shampoo, since it ``makes handfuls of creamy lather
and rinses in a flash.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: I'm looking for the laundry stain remover ``Easy Wash'' made
by Reckitt &AMP; Colman of Wayne, N.J. It's the best I've ever used.
For about a year, A&AMP;P carried it. But those stores are gone. And I
have only one bottle left. Can you help?
</P>
<P>
   _ Shirley Watson, Alpharetta
</P>
<P>
   A: Washing clothes will be a snap now that you can replenish
your supply of Easy Wash. According to spokeswoman Deborah
Valerian, this laundry stain remover has ``limited distribution,''
but loyal fans love it so much that the company makes it available
via mail order. Call 1-800-456-9477. A 22-ounce bottle is $1.99; a
32-ounce bottle is $2.49.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Does Heinz still make ketchup in a glass bottle? Everything I
find is in plastic squeeze bottles that make the most disgusting
sounds when squeezed. It's just a personal pet peeve, I know.
</P>
<P>
   _ John E. List, Atlanta
</P>
<P>
   A: Hurry and stock up. To help celebrate the 130th anniversary
of Heinz, the company has brought back the classic glass ketchup
bottle _ until Sept. 30 _ in a larger, 24-ounce, size. It's
available at most grocery stores, including Cub Foods at 1701
Mountain Industrial Blvd., in Stone Mountain, where we found a
bottle for 98 cents. We also spotted it at Kroger, 10779 Alpharetta
Highway, in Roswell for 99 cents and at Ingles Supermarkets, 2546
Powder Springs Road in Marietta for 99 cents.
</P>
<P>
   Incidentally, the best way to get ketchup out of the
narrow-necked glass bottle is to tap it on the neck. The perfect
spot? On the embossed ``57'' number.
</P>
<P>
   _ Contributing: Michelle C. Brooks
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
