<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
 (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Thursday, Aug. 19, sent to computer graphics clients of The New
York Times News Service. For information call 212-556-4204.) 
(th) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Lethargic thunderstorms focused heavy rains near Arizona's Grand
Canyon on Wednesday, prompting the National Weather Service to
issue small stream advisories for flooding. Moisture that fueled
the thunderstorms, originating over Mexico and the Gulf of
California, was drawn northward by a high pressure system parked a
few thousand feet above Oklahoma.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, thunderstorms will expand westward into the deserts of
southern California as the lofty high drifts westward toward the
mountains of New Mexico. As the high shifts west, a potent jet
stream disturbance will be able to slide into the Ohio Valley from
the southern Great Lakes.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, showers and thunderstorms will erupt as very warm
and humid air is lifted by the system. A few thunderstorms will
approach severe levels, with large hail and damaging winds posing a
threat. Downpours are possible.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a broken line of showers and thunderstorms will again
flare in Florida along the leading edge of the sea breeze as it
forges inland from the Atlantic and lifts hot, humid air.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, the mercury soared to 100 degrees at Dallas for the
22nd consecutive day. Temperatures should reach triple-digits again
Thursday afternoon, but the string may break Friday as slightly
cooler air arriving a few thousand feet above the ground mixes down
to the surface.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday morning will start cool across the Northeast, with
temperatures staying below seasonal levels as a high pressure
system from Canada noses southward.
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: HURRICANE HUNTER
</P>
<P>
   A suspicious cluster of thunderstorms over Mexico's Yucatan
Peninsula and the adjacent Bay of Campeche caught the attention of
forecasters at the National Hurricane Center the past few days. So,
Wednesday, an Air Force Reserve hurricane hunter aircraft was
dispatched to investigate the possibility that the batch of showers
could organize into a tropical storm. Because tropical systems
often form over remote areas that are bereft of weather
observations, forecasters must rely on aircraft reconnaissance to
gauge the vital signs of these potentially dangerous systems.
</P>
</TEXT>
