<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZMAG19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Fortune notes firms on the fast track
 &HT;    By Tom Walker
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Technology and industrial companies dominate the
latest Fortune (Sept. 13) list of America's fastest growing
companies, two of which are based in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Profit Recovery Group International, which uses special audits
to help clients find lost profits, ranks 40th overall based on a
formula that includes three-year revenue and per share earnings
growth. Premiere Bancshares ranks 75th.
</P>
<P>
   ``This year's list of fastest-growing companies is notable not
only for the staggering profit and revenue gains posted by these
100 businesses, but for the impressive returns they produced for
investors,'' the magazine says.
</P>
<P>
   Atop the list is Siebel Systems, a San Mateo, Calif., software
manufacturer.
</P>
<P>
   Four reasons for bullishness
</P>
<P>
   Esquire (September) came out with a stock market ``crash''
edition last year just as the market tanked in the worst correction
in eight years. As a result, contributing editor Ken Kurson claims
that this lends credibility to his latest forecast that the Dow
Jones industrial average will hit 15,000 by August 2001.
</P>
<P>
   He gives four reasons for the forecast: pent-up demand for
stocks by aging baby boomers; recovering corporate earnings;
continued consumer spending in a minimal-inflation economy; and the
recovery of depressed foreign markets, which will promote
profitable foreign trade.
</P>
<P>
   Too cool for school
</P>
<P>
   Maybe mutual funds should be managed by youngsters, Bloomberg
Personal Finance (September) suggests. Take the case of Alec
Hufnagel, a Scarsdale, N.Y., high school junior who turned $500,000
into $1.7 million in eight weeks trading stocks and options in
companies such as eBay and Amazon.com.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for Hufnagel, age 15, the money was hypothetical.
It was traded as part of Investment Challenge, one of a growing
number of stock market games designed to acquaint students with the
basics of investing.
</P>
<P>
   Among other such games are the CNBC Student Stock Tournament,
Salomon Smith Barney Young Investors Network and The Stock Market
Game.
</P>
<P>
   Worth mentioning . . .
</P>
<P>
   _ Money (September) says the extended bull market has instilled
a level of confidence in investors unmatched in recent history. The
problem is that many overconfident individuals taking command of
their own portfolios are making costly mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   _ The founders of Home Depot _ Bernie Marcus and Arthur Blank _
are on the cover of one more magazine: Atlanta-based Business to
Business (August).
</P>
<P>
   _ In a special two-week ``bonus'' edition, Business Week (Aug.
30) offers 21 ideas for the 21st century. Separate articles look at
trends and possible scenarios on topics such as technology, energy,
the environment, religion and management.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
