<SLUG> BC-CIR-GEEK-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAKING INTERNET MUSIC TO THE LIVING ROOM 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For those tired of listening to their MP3 collections through
computer speakers or the headphones of a portable player, there is
now a way to transport the Internet music experience to the living
room.
</P>
<P>
   Netdrives in Ithaca, N.Y., has developed a compact disk player
for home stereo systems that can play traditional CDs and disks
recorded in the MP3 file compression format that is popular among
Internet music aficionados.
</P>
<P>
   The company says the component, called the Brujo (pronounced
BREW-hoe), is the first consumer MP3 player that is PC free,
meaning that it never needs to be connected to a personal computer.
Instead, song files are downloaded from the Internet, then
transferred, or ``burned,'' onto a standard recordable CD.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because of the Brujo, MP3s are no longer limited to computer
speakers,'' said Jennifer Wolfe, the president of Netdrives. The
Brujo comes with a remote control.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike many commercial CD players, which can hold five or more
CDs at once, the Brujo has only one disk tray. But because a
standard CD can hold more than 11 hours of MP3 music files there
should be no concern about disk swapping unless you are playing a
regular CD.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, if you intend to make MP3 CDs, you will need a CD
recording drive for your computer. So Netdrives sells a companion
product called the Burner, a rewritable CD recorder that works with
Macintosh and Wintel computers.
</P>
<P>
   The devices cost $300 each or $550 when bought together. They
are available on the company's Web site at www.netdrives.com.
</P>
<P>
   _ TIM HILCHEY
</P>
<P>
   __
</P>
<P>
   EBAY ADDICTS COME UP FOR AIR
</P>
<P>
   Now eBay users can bid and run. In an effort to differentiate
itself from competitors, the auction giant has started a paging
service that will update users on the progress of their auctions
when they are away from their computers.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of eBay users were telling us they go out and get
busy,'' said Kevin Pursglove, a spokesman for the company,
countering the popular image of his customers. ``They've lost track
of time. When they get home, the auction has ended and they've been
outbid. If there is some way that we could have notified them, they
would have skipped the second course or cut their cup of coffee.''
</P>
<P>
   The service, playfully titled ``eBay-a-go-go,'' costs $55 for
about 500 messages and uses any wireless device that offers text
messaging. Individuals can use their own devices or buy one from
eBay. The service notifies users when they have won an item, been
outbid or sold an item. Users can sign up through
www.skytel.com/ebay.
</P>
<P>
   Users are apparently clamoring for still more. They want the
ability to bid on the run. ``Eventually, the idea is to make it a
two-way service,'' said Pursglove.
</P>
<P>
   _ JENNIFER 8. LEE
</P>
<P>
   __
</P>
<P>
   REAL FEEL SIMULATIONS TRY TO BRING GAMES TO LIFE
</P>
<P>
   Imagine taking a Nantucket fishing expedition without leaving
home? Or how about hustling colleagues in a game of snooker between
meetings? Starting this winter, armchair athletes will be able to
ditch their traditional joysticks and keyboards for a new line of
inexpensive sports simulation accessories called Real Feel from
Miacomet.
</P>
<P>
   The first accessory, due in October, lets players slide a pool
stick across a small sensor that translates motion into an
on-screen image. Real Feel's second release, scheduled for January,
is a 30-inch replica of a fishing pole that simulates the tugs and
pulls of fishing. A minnow may pose little challenge, but a
50-pound bass will have anglers wrestling in their chairs.
</P>
<P>
   Founded on the belief that the space bar and enter key do not
provide a realistic enough game experience, Miacomet of
Springfield, Mass., hopes to attract a wide range of consumers,
from arcade-goers to weekend anglers. Though Real Feel products,
expected to cost $50 to $100, will come with software, they also
will work with other brands and will be compatible with PCs and
video game consoles.
</P>
<P>
   And for those who could not catch a fish in a bathtub, Miacomet
is developing baseball, snow boarding, golf, football and soccer
simulators.
</P>
<P>
   _ ROD KURTZ
</P>
<P>
   __
</P>
<P>
   CELL PHONES ARE NO. 1 WITH BUSINESS TRAVELERS
</P>
<P>
   Modern travelers will use cell phones in the car, on the street
and even while standing beside another telephone. That is one of
the conclusions of a new survey of the technological habits of
1,000 business travelers conducted by the research firm Greenfield
Online.
</P>
<P>
   A cellular telephone is the No. 1 piece of electronic gear
carried by travelers, with seven out of 10 travelers surveyed
toting one.
</P>
<P>
   The vast majority, 94 percent, of those who carry cell phones
use them in cars. Nearly two-thirds, however, said they make calls
while walking.
</P>
<P>
   Half of those surveyed make calls on their cell phones from
offices, hotels and airports while traveling, although wired phones
are plentiful. Margot Turk, Greenfield's director of NetReach
Services, said respondents were not asked why they make cell phone
calls from places where other phones are available.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think that it's convenience. If you use your cellular
phone, you don't need to worry about the 15-digit calling card
number. You don't need to wait in line for a pay phone,'' Ms. Turk
said.
</P>
<P>
   Only about half of the business travelers surveyed carry laptop
computers on business trips, a figure that surprised Rudy Nadilo,
Greenfield's chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, e-mail still has a ways to go in being the
mainstream business communications tool,'' Nadilo said.
</P>
<P>
   Only about 36 percent of the respondents own pagers. Hand held
PC/personal digital assistants have not reached high levels of
usage among business travelers. One in 10 surveyed take such a
device on trips. However, among those who own such devices, 92
percent take them on trips. And the survey found that the most
popular device was the Palm Connected Organizer, owned by 77
percent of those surveyed who owned a hand held PC.
</P>
<P>
   _ STEPHEN C. MILLER
</P>
<P>
   __
</P>
<P>
   FOR HANDS-OFF USERS A FOOT-GUIDED MOUSE
</P>
<P>
   Robert J. Thompson, an entrepreneur in Pacific, Mo., has come up
with an alternative for people who, because of a disability or
simple wrist pain, cannot use a mouse. He calls it the FootRat.
</P>
<P>
   The FootRat, as you might suspect, is a cursor-control device
that can be manipulated with your feet. It does not look like much
_ just a black plastic shell that fits over a regular mouse. It
comes with an elastic strap to fit over shoes and an anti-static
pad called a RatMat.
</P>
<P>
   Other accessories include footpedals, to be used by the other
foot, that substitute for a mouse's click buttons. The product also
comes with free software that can enable FootRat users to use
keystrokes for mouse clicks instead. All are for sale on
www.touchtime.com; the FootRat sells for $29.95.
</P>
<P>
   John W. Senders, a University of Toronto professor who
specializes in ergonomics, has not yet used the FootRat but says
that Thompson has hit on a ``very good idea.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The use of footpedals in general is always overlooked by
people who design things,'' Senders said.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, adapting to foot controls is not easy. ``But easy is
a relative term,'' Thompson said. ``The first time using a mouse,
it was unlike anything I had ever done before.''
</P>
<P>
   _ LISA GUERNSEY
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
