<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-18 18:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1908 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l BC-KIDS:BABY-AMERIKAN-CL     08-18 0982
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KIDS:BABY-AMERIKAN-CLASSACTS-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE BABY AMERIKAN STORY 
 FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE 
 FROM THE FORT WORTH STAR-TELEGRAM
</HEADLINE>
  World rights. 
 By JESSAMY BROWN 
 Copyright 1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Who is Baby Amerikan and why was he in the news?
</P>
<P>
   He is the first baby born in America to parents who escaped the
war in Kosovo. His father, Naim Karaliju, and his mother, Lebibe
Karaliju, were among 453 refugees brought in an airlift to Fort
Dix, N.J., on May 5, and Amerikan was born less than 24 hours
later.
</P>
<P>
   The child's birth drew national attention, and President Clinton
wished the infant well.
</P>
<P>
   ``We named him Amerikan as a sign of our appreciation to this
country,'' Naim Karaliju told reporters.
</P>
<P>
   At Fort Dix, an Army base, refugees got ID cards and medical
exams before being resettled in places such as Detroit, Fort
Worth-Dallas and New York. Amerikan _ who is a U.S. citizen because
he was born in this country _ and his family moved to Dallas on
June 4 to be with relatives. There are 33 family members living in
Dallas in all.
</P>
<P>
   The Karalijus had fled their farm in a Kosovo village of about
300 after Serbian soldiers burned their home to the ground and
killed an aunt and uncle, according to news reports. Kosovo is a
region within Serbia, one of two provinces in Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Why is Baby Amerikan back in the news?
</P>
<P>
   Just two months after the Karaliju family moved to North Texas,
they were in the news again. This time an article in the Aug. 2
edition of the New York Post said that Amerikan's father had
complained that the agency that was helping the family resettle did
not fulfill promises to provide cash, rent money and help finding
jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are having a hard time. There is not enough money to buy
milk for the baby,'' Naim Karaliju was quoted as saying through a
translator.
</P>
<P>
   That was not the end of the story, however.
</P>
<P>
   National media reported the family's statements the next day.
But the Philadelphia Daily News published a piece that said that,
despite what Karaliju had said, his family was not suffering. The
reporter said the Karalijus had a furnished apartment. Chip
Corcoran, executive director of Refugee Services of North Texas,
was quoted as saying that the family had access to cash, food
stamps, medical care, English classes and job training. Deborah
DeWinter, associate director of Church World Service, which
oversees Refugee Services of North Texas, said that Amerikan's
father had turned down several job offers.
</P>
<P>
   That same day, Aug. 3, the New York Post ran another article
that said that United Parcel Service had offered Karaliju a job
after executives from the shipping company in New York read about
the family in that newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   But again, the story was not over.
</P>
<P>
   In an Aug. 6 article in The Dallas Morning News, Karaliju
acknowledged that his family's needs had been met by the
resettlement agency, which had provided more aid than was required
by the government. Records showed that three months' rent on the
family's $750-a-month north Dallas apartment was provided, as well
as furniture, dishes and hundreds of dollars in food and cash. The
Karalijus, the story said, also receive more than $550 a month in
food stamps.
</P>
<P>
   This time, Karaliju acknowledged he had worked a construction
job for about six weeks. He told the newspaper that what worried
him were his family's long-term needs: ``We have a lot of food _ no
problem. The problem is, I don't know if I'm going to have enough
money later.''
</P>
<P>
   What is the U.S. policy for helping Kosovo refugees, and did
Baby Amerikan's family receive the aid it should have?
</P>
<P>
   In April, the U.S. announced that it would take up to 20,000
refugees who had escaped the war. More than 10,000 ethnic Albanians
who live in Kosovo had been killed and an estimated 900,000 were
forced from their homes by Serbian forces. Many of these Kosovars
escaped to neighboring countries such as Macedonia. The U.S.
airlift, which brought 12,085 Kosovo refugees to America, was begun
to relieve overcrowded refugee camps in Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
   The State Department has said that it will pay to send back home
Kosovo refugees who arrived before July 31.
</P>
<P>
   Ten national agencies receive government money to resettle
refugees in the United States. The State Department requires that
refugees be provided a minimum of one month's rent, food, clothing,
``safe, decent and sanitary housing'' and access to English
classes, said Corcoran.
</P>
<P>
   The Karaliju family was among approximately 400 Kosovo refugees
resettled in Texas. According to Corcoran, the refugees got what
they needed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Baby Amerikan is healthy and well-fed. The family is doing as
best as we can expect being just recently removed from a war
zone,'' Corcoran told CLASS ACTS.
</P>
<P>
   Terminology to know:
</P>
<P>
   Refugee: A person who flees to a foreign country to escape
danger or social, religious or political persecution. Usually this
move is not planned and the person may not have brought along any
belongings. He or she might not know anyone in the new country or
speak the language.
</P>
<P>
   Immigrant: A person who moves from his or her native country to
another country to live permanently. There is often a long wait to
get the U.S. government's permission to come to America.
</P>
<P>
   Resettlement: The process of providing money, housing, food and
services to help refugees rebuild their lives. In the United
States, 10 agencies do this work.
</P>
<P>
   Ethnic cleansing: Killing or driving groups of people from their
homes because they have a different background in terms of their
common history, language, customs and characteristics.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; -0- &QL; 
 &UR; Copyright 1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram &QL; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &QL;
</P>
