<HEADLINE>
BOOKS: ``EYE OF THE GREAT BEAR'' 
 FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE 
 FROM THE FORT WORTH STAR-TELEGRAM
</HEADLINE>
  World rights. 
 By MITA LAKHIA, 7th Grade Student Reporter 
 Copyright 1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``EYE OF THE GREAT BEAR''
</P>
<P>
   Author: Bill Wallace.
</P>
<P>
   For: grades 3 to 6.
</P>
<P>
   Publisher: Pocket Books, 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Price: $14 hardcover.
</P>
<P>
   Pages: 161.
</P>
<P>
   We all know that the best part of Independence Day is the
fireworks. For most of us, that is. However, this is not the case
with 11-year-old Bailey Trumbull. Why? He has his reasons.
</P>
<P>
   At one point in our lives we have all been teased for one thing
or another and know how horrible it can be. In this story, Bailey
has the same problem _ his brothers and friends tease him about his
jumpiness _ and like most kids, he overreacts and thinks the
problem is bigger than it actually is.
</P>
<P>
   Bailey knows he's not a coward, he just has to get everyone else
to believe it. This story, which takes place near Abilene in 1899,
is very enjoyable and easy to relate to.
</P>
<P>
   Reviewer's 1 - 10 rating: 9.
</P>
<P>
