<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-IMPROVEMENT-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOME CLINIC: FITTING AND INSTALLING BASEMENT DOORS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By EDWARD R. LIPINSKI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Many older homes have exterior basement doors made of wood.
Unless they are maintained properly, these old doors can become an
eyesore, and as the boards age they will shrink and allow rainwater
to leak through. If you have such a door on your basement entry
well, consider replacing it with a modern heavy-gauge steel door.
It is more durable than a wooden one; it also provides a stronger
barrier against intruders and requires less maintenance.
</P>
<P>
   Installing one is not difficult and can be accomplished with a
few basic hand tools. Usually one person of average size can handle
this job without help. However, the installation procedures will
vary somewhat depending upon the type of foundation (called the
well foundation) that surrounds the basement entryway.
</P>
<P>
   There are two types. One has sides that slope from the ground to
about three feet on the house wall. The other type of foundation is
level with the ground, but there are wooden walls on either side
that rise from the well foundation level to the top of the opening
in the house foundation. The doors hinge from these walls. With the
flat foundation, you will first have to mount a metal housing with
sloping sides. The doors will be mounted on this. Since the housing
butts against the house, you may have to cut back some of the
siding so everything fits precisely.
</P>
<P>
   Before you can order a door, you will have to take some
measurements of the well foundation. Measure the width from the
outside of one wall to the outside of the opposite wall; call this
W-1. Measure across the inside width of the well foundation
opening, W-2. Determine the length of the foundation from the house
wall to the outside front edge of the foundation, L-1; and the
length of the well opening from the house wall to the inside edge
of the well foundation, L-2. If you have a flat foundation, take an
additional measurement, the height of the well foundation to the
height of the opening in the house foundation.
</P>
<P>
   As you are taking these measurements also look carefully at the
top of the foundation walls to see if they are relatively flat and
smooth. If they are not, you will have to order special foundation
plates.
</P>
<P>
   With these measurements in hand, you can order a new door. Your
local home center may stock metal basement doors, or look in the
Yellow Pages under ``doors'' for a nearby dealer; or you can order
directly from a manufacturer. The dealer will have charts that
allow you match your figures with the appropriate-size door.
</P>
<P>
   If the new door is smaller than the well opening, you can modify
it by adding extension panels. These are metal plates that attach
to the door frame and span the gaps across the width and height of
the opening. The manufacturer's charts specify which panels are
needed to adapt the door to your well opening. For a flat
foundation, manufacturers offer a sloping frame. This mounts
directly onto the well foundation and to the adjacent house wall.
</P>
<P>
   When you have the door and framing, you can mount them in place.
First remove and discard the old door and all of the wooden framing
pieces. Next examine the well foundation for defects like cracks,
holes or crumbling masonry. These should be repaired before
proceeding further.
</P>
<P>
   If the top surfaces of the well foundation are rough or uneven,
install the foundation plates first. The foundation plates and all
metal framing pieces are anchored to the masonry with expansion
fasteners (these are usually provided by the manufacturer). Place
the plates on the foundation walls and mark the position for the
anchors holes. Drill into the concrete with a masonry drill bit
then insert the expansion plugs. Reposition the plates and secure
them by driving the fasteners into the plugs. Next attach the door
frame with anchors. Make sure it is square and level (you may have
to insert shims in some places to correct distortions). Finally,
bolt the door flanges to the frame and attach the doors to the
flanges. Lubricate the torsion cams on the doors with light oil,
then slide the torsion bars in place (not all doors have torsion
cams).
</P>
<P>
   When the doors are in place, apply a bead of caulk around the
perimeter of the frame then paint the doors and all exterior metal
parts with a high-gloss alkyd metal enamel. Choose a color that
will reflect sunlight.
</P>
<P>
   Installation procedures may vary, but in most cases the
manufacturers provide detailed step-by-step instructions and all
the necessary hardware.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
