<SLUG> BC-DRUG-USE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DRUG USE AMONG TEENS DROPS BUT IS STABLE FOR OVERALL POPULATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK HELM  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Saying teen-agers have ``turned the corner'' on
drugs, Health and Human Services Secretary Donna Shalala and White
House drug adviser Barry McCaffrey announced Wednesday that illicit
drug use among people ages 12 to 17 fell last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``These findings show our message of no tolerance for drugs is
working,'' McCaffrey said in releasing the results of an annual
household survey of 25,500 people 12 and older.
</P>
<P>
   The survey found that in 1998, 9.9 percent of teens under 17
were ``current users'' of drugs, meaning they had used drugs within
the previous month, down from 11.4 percent in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The rate was highest in 1979, when 16.3 percent of teens under
the age of 17 were classified as current drug users. The rate
dropped to 5.3 percent in 1992, then gradually rose until last
year.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton said the report showed that young people were
``getting the message that drugs are wrong and illegal and can kill
you.''
</P>
<P>
   The number of teens saying they had tried drugs at least once in
their life also was down, falling from 18.8 percent in 1997 to 16.4
percent last year. The decline was driven by 16- and 17-year-olds,
with the percentage in those ages who have used drugs dropping from
30.7 percent to 26.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the battle against illicit drugs we've turned the corner
... but we have a long way to go,'' Shalala said.
</P>
<P>
   However, the survey reported that despite the drop in use among
teens under 18, overall drug use in the United States remained
steady last year because of increased use among young adults 18 to
25.
</P>
<P>
   According to the survey, 16.1 percent of young adults were
current users, up from 13.3 percent in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   ``This group is a real challenge for our country because it's
much harder to change the way people think about drugs as they get
older,'' McCaffrey said.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, about 13.6 million Americans, or 6.2 percent of the
population, used drugs at least once a month in 1998, nearly the
same as in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   In total, 78 million Americans had tried illegal drugs at some
point in their lives, the survey reported. Marijuana is the
country's most popular narcotic, with nearly 37 million people
having tried it.
</P>
<P>
   The survey also measured the use of tobacco and alcohol.
</P>
<P>
   The number of Americans 12 and older who had smoked a cigarette
in the previous month fell last year to 60 million, or 27.7 percent
of population, from 64 million, or 29.6 percent in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   But the number of young adults aged 18 to 25 who smoked in the
previous month climbed from 40.6 percent in 1997 to 41.6 percent
last year. That compares with 34.5 percent in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   The number of drinkers in the United States held steady in 1998,
with 113 million Americans 12 and older having had at least one
drink in the 30 days before the survey was conducted. Of these
people, about 33 million were considered binge drinkers, meaning
they drank five or more drinks on one occasion.
</P>
<P>
   Although drinking is illegal for anyone under the age of 21,
more than 10 million young people 12 to 20 had had a drink at least
once in the previous month, the report said. That number has
remained steady since 1994.
</P>
<P>
   ``While we're pleased that the number of kids drinking hasn't
gone up, we as a country need to remind ourselves that alcohol is a
deadly drug for teen-agers and cannot be tolerated,'' McCaffrey
said.
</P>
<P>
   The survey, which is based on interviews conducted nationwide
throughout the year, also tracked drug use of among minority
groups.
</P>
<P>
   The survey also said:
</P>
<P>
   _ The percentage of blacks of all ages using drugs grew from 5.8
percent in 1993 to 8.2 percent last year, the report said. The
trend for Hispanics was similar, from 4.4 percent in 1993 to 6.1
percent last year.
</P>
<P>
   _ A total of 130,000 people were using heroin in 1998, double
the number in 1993. In addition, the age of heroin users was
dropping. In 1997, the typical heroin user was 17.6 years old the
first time they tried the drug, down from 18.3 in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   _ The number of cocaine users remained the same in 1998 compared
to 1997 at about 1.75 million. However, there were increases among
teens and young adults.
</P>
<P>
   _ The number of cigar smokers increased last year to 15 million,
6.9 percent of the population, from 13 million, 5.9 percent of the
population, in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   (Mark Helm can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address mark(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
