<SLUG> BC-CIR-STAR-TREK-BEEP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHERE NO BEEP HAD GONE BEFORE 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 (Eds: The byline is correct)  
 By JENNIFER 8. LEE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Like an aging movie star, the beep has seen its glory days in
Hollywood fade over the last 30 years, paralleling its fall in the
public sphere. The 1960s television series ``Star Trek'' and its
later offshoots provide a case study of how the beep has fallen
from high-tech symbol to low-tech annoyance.
</P>
<P>
   In the original series, which ran from 1966 to 1969, the beep
was a star. Machines on the bridge of the starship Enterprise
emitted a constant backdrop of beeping and booping to accompany the
plot line. During the height of the 1960s space race, beeping was
considered cutting-edge chic.
</P>
<P>
   In recent ``Star Trek'' incarnations, however, the beep makes
only cameo appearances. Gurgling, swishing and speaking have taken
its place. The banishment of the beep was a conscious decision by
the producers of the pilot of ``Star Trek: the Next Generation'' in
1986.
</P>
<P>
   ``We pulled up the sound of the bridge from the original
series,'' said Peter Lauritson, who has worked as a producer on
``Star Trek: The Next Generation,'' as well as the later series
``Deep Space Nine'' and ``Star Trek Voyager.'' ``It was a loud,
constant, harsh environment. In contrast to that, we tried to make
things softer and calmer.''
</P>
<P>
   Like the electronic interface designers of today, the ``Star
Trek'' producers tried to serve the esthetic thresholds of humans.
The ``Star Trek'' characters live aboard the ships for years on
end, Lauritson said. ``The reality is they wouldn't be able to take
it,'' he noted.
</P>
<P>
   ``We tried to keep the sounds fairly gentle and minimal until
something needed to be said with the sound. We were hoping it would
convey sophistication, that things had advanced.''
</P>
<P>
   In ``Star Trek: The Next Generation,'' the sound designers aimed
for a so-called pastel range of electronic sounds that were muted
and subtle. But then they realized even the harsh beeps and boops
had a necessary role.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the background sounds in ``Deep Space Nine'' and
``Star Trek Voyager'' aimed for a more ``primary'' sound palette,
with harsher electronic noises.
</P>
<P>
   ``We originally went overboard in making things so sophisticated
that it was boring,'' said Lauritson. ``We had to start backing off
of that a little bit to get a little more life into the scene.''
</P>
<P>
   The beep's prestige has diminished as it has become more
mundane. ``I think that the beeps and the boops sounds in the
earlier days were kind of a futuristic signature,'' Lauritson said,
``whereas now, they're kind of everywhere.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-18-99 1803EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990818.0205 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-18 18:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1925 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-SCREENWRITING-2TA     08-18 1282
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-SCREENWRITING-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SMALL-SCREEN HELP FOR BUDDING FILMMAKERS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif. )   By ERIC A. TAUB   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Computer programs to help screenwriters have been around for
more than a decade, since writers began dropping the IBM Selectric
typewriter in favor of the Apple Macintosh. But in the last few
years, they have come to include not only simple aides but also
complex systems offering, like the hyperbolic movie industry
itself, bloated promises that you'll soon be writing a blockbuster
with ``passionate themes'' and ``unforgettable characters.''
</P>
<P>
   Of all writers, those who create film and television scripts
strike out the most. Scripts often sell for the wrong reasons: The
writer is a friend of a producer. The writer has persuaded a star
to participate. Projects that are universally disliked are suddenly
loved once money is committed.
</P>
<P>
   Screenwriters know that even if their films are produced, most
of what they write may never be heard or even read, buried under a
mountain of rewrites or hidden in a sea of descriptive action meant
to capture the imagination of one of the scores of people who will
have to sign off on the sale.
</P>
<P>
   Unless you're part of the tiny fraternity of screenwriters who
can sell a script based on a two-sentence idea, you must create a
story that a reader _ whether a low-level employee, studio
executive, agent or star _ immediately finds compelling. You must
quickly show that the characters are complex and fresh, the
situation unique and intriguing, the dialogue biting and germane.
</P>
<P>
   If you're looking for the equivalent of a digital dishwasher, a
program into which you can dump all your words and receive a clean,
finished script, don't waste your time. Writing programs do not
evaluate dialogue and narrative. Rather, all these programs try to
help the writer think more critically. Each tries to give rules for
character development, conflict, plot and resolution, while the
user enters information or answers multiple-choice questions about
the intended story. Some programs can be mastered in a few minutes;
others require days.
</P>
<P>
   If you insist on software that features the latest in computer
graphics, choose carefully. Several packages remain mired in a
1980s style, using fixed, primitive screen layouts and built on
inflexible databases that tend to crash.
</P>
<P>
   Has a screenwriting program, like a word processor, become a de
rigueur tool for the budding filmmaker? Of course not. In fact,
some of these programs seem to exist on disk for no other reason
than that they can: a book version of the same material would often
suffice. However, if you find that critical prodding helps you
think more rigorously, then each of the four programs examined here
is worth a look. All are available through the Writers Store in Los
Angeles (writersstore.com).
</P>
<P>
   ``Plots Unlimited'' (Ashleywilde; $199; Macintosh and Windows 95
or later.) Writers stuck for story ideas, or those unable to figure
out where their story should go next, may benefit from Plots
Unlimited. Created by Tom Sawyer, head writer-producer for the
television series ``Murder, She Wrote,'' the program requires
minutes to master.
</P>
<P>
   Think of it as a thesaurus of story ideas, with one choice
leading to other logical options among the 5,600 situations
available from the program's database. It's perfect for television
writers looking for new twists to old ideas.
</P>
<P>
   Writers first name the project, and then pick the number of
characters and their relationship to one another from 165
alternatives, or specify the type of story they are developing
(like romance or married life). If you have little idea of what
your story is about, the Master Plot option lets you combine
general statements that spell out the protagonist, the action and
the resolution.
</P>
<P>
   If Howard Koch and Julius and Philip Epstein had had Plots
Unlimited, they could have begun their work on ``Casablanca'' by
choosing to develop their screenplay via the story option. This
classic film is a triangle between a woman, her husband and her
former lover. Picking the marriage option brings up 290 conflict
situations, like ``Carol, wife of Jack, runs into an old lover,
Gary, and has no choice but to borrow money from him.'' (Don't
worry: the program allows each character's name to be changed.)
</P>
<P>
   The user can look for story options that either take the story
forward or fill in preceding events. One of the three forward
suggestions for the scenario above is, ``Jack's wife, Carol, finds
herself in the power of a former lover, Gary.'' Each successive
step can be previewed to see where the story will lead and, if
inappropriate, rejected for other permutations.
</P>
<P>
   The program has a clunky interface that requires the user to
allocate additional memory. Each suggestion appears in a small
window and type size, neither of which can be changed; even though
character names can be personalized, the generic names provided by
the program incongruously continue to be used by parts of the
program. The program is available on floppy disk only,
necessitating an external drive.
</P>
<P>
   Plots Unlimited's suggested plot development ideas, while
numerous, are neither exhaustive nor gospel. However, if all you
need is a way to jump-start your thought processes with some basic
plot twists, then it can help. Of course, if you don't care about
using a computer, the course contains the same information, in its
book of the same name.
</P>
<P>
   ``Writepro'' (The Writepro Corp.; $149.95;
</P>
<P>
   Macintosh 6.0.5 or later and Windows 3.1 or later.)
</P>
<P>
   While the program bills itself as ``for novelists and short
story writers,'' Writepro is just as valuable for screenwriters,
because the writing lessons it teaches are universal.
</P>
<P>
   Created by Sol Stein, a novelist, book editor and publisher of
writers like James Baldwin and Lionel Trilling, Writepro takes the
user through elementary, essential rules for creating well-written
material.
</P>
<P>
   Divided into eight lesson plans, Writepro gives rules for
characterization, dialogue and plot development are given; then the
writer enters a description of the character or scene and is asked
to re-evaluate that work to insure that it is true to the form of
good storytelling.
</P>
<P>
   Stein presents a number of bare plot points that the writer must
embellish. What does your fictional character want? How do
antagonists _ obstacles or events _ prevent the main character from
achieving his goal?
</P>
<P>
   Once the user has finished one part of the story, a complication
is presented. The main character, a woman, meets an attractive man
at a party. The story's antagonist is there also, forcing us to
consider how both elements will change the story's direction.
</P>
<P>
   As Stein points out, as the story continues, the obstacles must
get stronger. If one conflict is resolved, the next must be greater
in intensity. ``If the villain appearing at the party was a
surprise to our heroine,'' he writes, ``then there better be a
bigger surprise when she gets home.''
</P>
<P>
   Stein's program is unrelenting in its demand that you re-examine
your work. Yet the tone is friendly, more like that of a supportive
teacher watching over your shoulder than a stern taskmaster as you
learn to tighten dialogue by removing redundant lines, intensify
characters' conflicts and enhance characterization.
</P>
<P>
   There is no chance to work on your own story ideas while using
Writepro, but the program is a useful tool for novices. The
program's small font and screen size cannot be enlarged. However,
maneuvering between screens and lessons is simple to master. The
program is available on floppy disk only.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``John Truby's Blockbuster'' (Truby's Writers Studio; $295;
Macintosh 7.0 or later and Windows 3.1 or later.)
</P>
<P>
   For John Truby, a longtime writing instructor, the key to a good
screenplay is to follow his 22 steps. These include brainstorming,
developing the premise and fleshing out the plot. They are in turn
divided into four categories: idea, character, plot and scene
creation.
</P>
<P>
   The program has a colorful, but small interface that cannot be
enlarged to fill the screen of today's 17-inch monitors. Beginners
can use the ``quickstory'' path and develop a few of the levels to
get an idea of how stories are created.
</P>
<P>
   You start by brainstormingyour story, jotting down ideas about
the plot and characters. At the start of each lesson, a comment
screen pops up, indicating what type of information is required.
Clicking on one button brings up a condensed version of Truby's
writing course; clicking on another illustrates how a well-known
film script would handle the lesson.
</P>
<P>
   For example, once you enter step two, developing initial scenes,
Truby cautions that you should ``expect that the order of your
scenes will change radically by the time you have finished
developing your story.'' When creating dialogue, the writer is
advised to rewrite each scene three times: first composing words
that explore the action, then inserting ``moral'' dialogue that
explores underlying emotions. Finally, dialogue should be reviewed
again for the inclusion of key words that move the story forward.
</P>
<P>
   After reading Truby's thoughts and examples, you enter the
requested information. The screens can be printed individually or
all together.
</P>
<P>
   Once finished, you are presented with a list of common
screenwriting mistakes and asked to check off the elements missing
from your story. While all of your original work can be printed,
the lessons cannot.
</P>
<P>
   The program does not have the look of modern software; on the
Mac platform, users are cautioned to disable a system extension
before use. But doing so prevents signing on to the Internet; the
extension must be enabled and the computer restarted before that is
possible.
</P>
<P>
   Still, this was the best program of those reviewed, filled with
valuable information, useful tips and good illustrations from
classic films.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dramatica Pro'' (Screenplay Systems; $399; Macintosh 7.0 or
later and Windows 95 or later.)
</P>
<P>
   If you're the type of person who hates to read manuals, this
program is not for you. On the other hand, if you're looking for a
piece of software that can raise more questions about your story's
plot, characterization, individuals' motivations, inner thoughts,
moral dilemmas and course of action than you may even care to know,
then Dramatica Pro deserves consideration.
</P>
<P>
   The program, developed by two screenwriters, takes users through
what they call ``a new theory of story.'' The underlying premise is
that ``story forming,'' creating the dramatic skeleton of a story
stripped of its illustrations, is a different process from ``story
weaving,'' the telling of a story to the audience. Both should be
developed separately.
</P>
<P>
   Dramatica offers more than 32,000 story forms, which eventually
become narrowed down to one as the user continues to answer
questions about the story. Our Casablanca screenwriters would have
been asked to consider issues like: ``Does Rick use a logical
method of problem solving or an intuitive method?'' ``Do actions
force decisions, or decisions force actions?'' Does the struggle
between Rick and Ilsa ``involve a manner of thinking or demeanor?''
</P>
<P>
   The process can take days to complete. After the user runs
through the various story forms, it is suggested that it be done
two more times to check for accuracy. It is a tedious process, but
it forces the writer to think carefully about the structure and
implications of the story.
</P>
<P>
   Where the other programs look outdated, Dramatica Pro is a
visual breath of fresh air. Virtually all elements of the software
are customizable, including overall screen size, font and font
size. Characters can be assigned one of scores of thumbnail
portraits to help personalize each.
</P>
<P>
   Follow the entire process and you'll be presented with a report
on your screenplay that could be almost as large as the final work.
The process can be so daunting and complex that Dramatica classes
are held at the company's Los Angeles offices to help users master
the program. With each release, the company has tried to simplify
the software, reducing the size of its printed manuals and
substituting lay terms for technical jargon.
</P>
<P>
   The program is overengineered for my taste, and there are so
many tasks to accomplish and so many areas to cover that you begin
to wish you could get on with the job of writing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
