<HEADER>
A1928 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-LONG-ISLAND-COTTAGE-7     08-18 0813
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LONG-ISLAND-COTTAGE-780(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRISONERS OF EDEN 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By ANNE RAVER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   They had gone out to Long Island to see about a summer rental,
and as soon as they saw the cinder-block cottage in Springs, they
fell for it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was buried in thick, overgrown, decrepit greenery, with big
chokecherries growing right outside the door and wild roses
climbing over everything,'' said David White, who grew up on Cape
Cod, so his heart went out to this landscape.
</P>
<P>
   There were a few native azaleas near the door and some pale pink
dogwoods smothered in honeysuckle. Cedars, ailanthus and oaks had
seeded themselves all around the house, and the eastern side,
toward the water, was a wall of bullbrier.
</P>
<P>
   ``The house was musty and damp,'' said Robert Jakob, who grew up
among farmers in Germany. ``And there was only one door, on the
north side, so you had to go all the way around to get back in.''
</P>
<P>
   But it was a room with possibilities: 20 by 30, with a high
gable 17 feet up. A picture window faced east, across a patch of
brown lawn, a picnic table, a birdbath _ and then the wall-o-weeds.
Small windows on each side of the cottage let in more light, though
they were largely obscured by vines creeping over the house. And
there was a fireplace.
</P>
<P>
   The rental agent started to say that people would be traipsing
through the place, as it was for sale, when they looked at each
other and knew who had to buy it. Then they spent the next 20 years
learning from the land and cherishing the little house at its
heart.
</P>
<P>
   White, Robert Rauschenberg's exhibition curator, is the pruner,
the shaper. Jakob, a graphic designer and artist, is the plantsman.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't wait to get my hands on a chain saw,'' White said.
``I saw all these things buried, waiting to be revealed.''
</P>
<P>
   He started sawing deadwood out of the cedars, which were scrawny
and thin from being smothered in vines. Others lay fallen from a
storm, rotting in a heap on the south side of the house, where
Jakob envisioned a flower garden.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just a diagonal path winding through a few summer flowers,
like black-eyed Susans and hollyhocks,'' Jakob said, padding
barefoot down a brick path he laid years later. ``It was free-form
at best.''
</P>
<P>
   He also wanted to plant an orchard in front of the house, by the
road. So they had a nurseryman take down the towering trees of
heaven.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somebody came by and said, `Why did you do that?' and we felt
bad,'' said Jakob, whose voice bears a trace of Germany. Very tan,
in old white pants and a white shirt, a cigarette dangling from his
hand, he lends a Mediterranean air to the late-bloomers: blue
salvia, achillea, crocosmia and the delicate white flowers of
oxydentera, a species gladiolus that makes the hybrids seem blousy
by comparison.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both David and I were hesitant to cut anything down,'' he
said. ``Though I admire the kind of ruthlessness of `bring in the
bulldozer.' Our neighbor erased everything.''
</P>
<P>
   He doesn't really mean it. These two are notorious for moving
things, like the peach trees that weren't happy in front of the
house, so now they're in the vegetable garden; the cedars that now
border the edge of the perennial garden cast a bit of shade and act
as a backdrop to set off the colors of the garden.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, White was tackling the wilderness. ``The blueberries
came back, and a nice stand of shadblow,'' he said. ``I remember
seeing the wonderful mottled bark showing through the bullbrier.''
He uncovered a young beech, which like everything else grew fat and
tall once it got light and air. Ferns sprouted in the sandy soil,
and mallows started blooming in the bulrushes.
</P>
<P>
   ``You see more birds, too,'' White said. ``Goldfinches and
warblers and red-winged blackbirds.''
</P>
<P>
   They lived in one room for six years before expanding the house,
opening it up with french doors and bigger windows and adding a
two-story tower. It has a bedroom upstairs, an aerie that looks out
on the blue water of Accabonac Harbor, and a sunny library and
guest room downstairs.
</P>
<P>
   The french doors to the east and south created a powerful axis
that Jakob could not help but carry forward as his gardens grew.
The free-form flower garden turned into four square beds, with
brick paths and a long allee of clipped hornbeams extending the eye
far into the distance. You want to go there, but you want to
linger, too, in the doorway, where a tiny blue clematis winds
through the fragrant white climbing rose, Sombreuil.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it rains, you should smell the Rosa primula,'' Jakob
said, fingering the spicy little leaves of the yellow rose.
</P>
<P>
   The garden has taken over Jakob's life. ``I have no time to
draw,'' he said. ``I long for just two pots on the terrace, and
then we could go away to Greece.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   Then he asks, ``Did you see the persimmons?'' and heads down the
brick path toward his vegetable garden, which is really an orchard
full of peaches, plums and sour cherries growing over Black Prince
tomatoes, chard, leeks, basil, fennel and long-leafed, deliciously
bitter arugula he orders from Pinetree Garden Seeds in New
Gloucester, Maine.
</P>
<P>
   Jakob grew up in the fertile Ried Valley between Mannheim and
Frankfurt. His father was a baker with an orchard full of apricots,
plums and apples for his tarts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes I thought I was deprived, not inheriting land,''
Jakob said, pulling a few small carrots out of a sandy plot beneath
an apricot tree. ``But in the garden, I see I'm copying what I saw
as a boy.''
</P>
<P>
   Jakob never sprays anything in his garden, including the fruit
trees. He believes in the power of compost, which builds good soil,
which grows healthy plants, which can resist disease and insects.
</P>
<P>
   We carry fresh basil back to White, who is chopping garlic and
tomatoes in the kitchen. The house feels like an open pavilion with
inviting paths stretching in all directions. There are no screens
on the doors or windows to inhibit light or breezes _ or bugs, for
that matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they get bad at night, we put a coil under the dinner
table,'' White said. ``And we have mosquito nets over the beds.''
</P>
<P>
   There are other gardens hidden behind the cedars, and as in a
big house with many rooms, it takes a while to discover them. Go
through the hornbeam hedge and it feels like Tuscany: an urn and
columnar junipers in the middle of drought-tolerant plants like
verbascum, butterfly weed, sage and crocosmia.
</P>
<P>
   ``I heeled in some irises here, and they really liked it'' Jakob
said. Soon he was buying things at Heronswood Nursery in Kingston,
Wash., like Solfaterre, an apricot crocosmia with bronze leaves,
and Digitalis lutea, a foxglove with a pale yellow bloom. The man
just can't stop.
</P>
<P>
   ``At first, I thought I'd just restrict myself to lavender and
santolina, but I can't,'' he said, staring at the styrax in the
corner.
</P>
<P>
   Across a grassy field shaded by a single great sycamore maple is
a meditative place that White hopes will remain simply green. Ferns
under the locust trees, a few magnolias, rare to the trade.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wonder if I could sneak a blue bellflower in with the
ferns,'' Jakob said, mumbling Campanula something-or-other.
</P>
<P>
   We eat our meal here, feet resting on warm stonework laid in
triangles and diagonals by Jakob, who was inspired by the fanciful
tilework of Aphrodisias, an ancient city in Turkey. It's one of
those wonderful ruins they don't have time to visit.
</P>
<P>
   Jakob keeps snapshots of crumbling hillside cottages in Greece
to remind himself of life before the garden.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
