<HEADER>
A1932 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-BRIDES-BOOK-REVIEW-NY     08-18 1041
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRIDES-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE LANGUAGE OF LOVE: A BABYLON OF EMOTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Production notes at end of review.) 
(nk) 
 By RICHARD EDER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Global village'': what an appropriate phrase, though not the
way it is mostly used, implying technological neighborliness among
three billion people and, who knows, ads that chirrup, ``You've got
a friend at the Bank of Wuppertal'' once your mortgage, having
bopped among half a dozen spots around the United States, begins to
bop globally as well.
</P>
<P>
   Villages are more complicated than that: often, to modify Yeats'
``great hatred, little room,'' a matter of great distance, little
room. Think of Thomas Hardy and Robert Frost. Today, of course, the
world flies, tours, migrates and settles at a smart clip. A result
_ since humans do after all gravitate to humans and even fall in
love _ can be intimacy rent by strangeness.
</P>
<P>
   Only a few contemporary novelists have touched on this, notably
Diane Johnson, whose crystal thermometer has recorded several
multinational conjugal fevers. Elena Lappin's ``Foreign Brides''
shatters the thermometer. Its women skitter wildly and erratically,
like beads of mercury abruptly unconfined. Ms. Lappin skitters with
them: Her sentences and scenes are uprooted along with her
characters, zigzagging against expectations and sometimes running
right off her own screen.
</P>
<P>
   Rarely does the author paragraph on a jacket flap suggest so
closely what we will read: ``born in Moscow and grew up in Prague
and Hamburg.''
</P>
<P>
   ``She has lived in Israel, Canada and the United States, and now
lives in London. From 1994 to 1997 she was editor of The Jewish
Quarterly. She is working on her first novel, `The Nose.'''
</P>
<P>
   Talk about skittering: Could Ms. Lappin have written this
herself? The places figure in the stories, there is a goading
nibble to the rhythm, and the end is a comic double take.
</P>
<P>
   But I hope to read ``The Nose.'' To say that ``Brides'' is
uneven, though it is true, is misleading. The stories lurch like a
foal finding its feet; the stumbles show comic promise and serious
purpose; the leaps claim unclaimed ground.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Noa and Noah,'' the comedy is hard to resist. Noa is an
Israeli; Noah, a visiting British Jew who wins her with his
prosperous business air, London liveliness and sexy habit of
murmuring when they make love. (Noa's Israeli boyfriends keep a
brooding silence at such moments.) Disillusion sets in when Noah
takes her back to London. The airy cosmopolitan is merely an
assistant debt collector. His main recreational interest is the
Tottenham Spurs soccer team, and the sexy murmur is a tortured
reciting of the players' names so as to retard climax.
</P>
<P>
   Rebellion follows; instead of the kosher butcher prescribed by
Noah's bossy mother, Noa patronizes rosy Joe McElligott, who
displays ``various pink sections of dead pigs in his window with
such pride and delight that it almost made Noa's mouth water.'' So
does Joe. From buying his chickens _ seasoning them lustily and
instructing them to ``act kosher'' _ she goes on to take advantage
of his convenient delivery service for a blithe fling.
</P>
<P>
   There are shrewd underpinnings to the fun: the difference
between Israeli and European Jewish cultures, the reinventing that
a foreigner has to do and beneath all this, marriage itself as a
foreign country. In the rougher ``Peacocks,'' a young woman leaves
Moscow for London for an arranged marriage. Her husband's address
is promisingly posh; he, however, is the butler. The story turns
weird rather than funny, signaling the more sinister aspects of
marrying foreign, but it is excessively contrived.
</P>
<P>
   There is contrivance, too, in ``Black Train'' _ Ms. Lappin's
MacGuffins need to go on a bland diet _ but also a quiet
perceptiveness. A Czech woman, exiled in 1968, marries a prosperous
American plumber. He is kind but she is torn between reaching for
what she has lost and grasping what she has achieved. She dreams of
being buried under thousands of trees in her green suburb; her
psychiatrist gives her the haunting advice to ``hang on to that
image until I have learned the names of all those trees, in
English.''
</P>
<P>
   In ``Michael Farmer's Baby,'' the woman is neither a bride nor
foreign. But she comes to a maternity ward with a false pregnancy,
having for 20 years been in love with her employer, a professor who
eventually moved away after a few rare bouts of casual sex. Not
only has she imagined a baby but also _ reading through the
professor's collection of Victoriana _ an identity: that of an
Irish servant who murdered her husband because she was in love with
her master. It is a very odd place that Ms. Lappin has taken us to;
her art is gradually to erode the oddness and leave us moved.
</P>
<P>
   There are other odd and moving foreign conditions. In the
wonderfully uncombed ``Inhaling New York'' the foreigners are the
American protagonist's English husband and a 14-year-old son from
the differently foreign land of teen-age culture. In ``Bad
Writing,'' a German woman endures marriage to a coldly vicious
American by dissolving her reality into text _ here is critical
theory with nerves and a heart _ and writing contradictory versions
of it.
</P>
<P>
   One of the finest stories and certainly the most perfectly
balanced is ``When in Palestine, Do as the Romans Did.'' It returns
us to Noa, who is now 40 and taking a holiday from Noah and their
children. She goes to Eilat, once a Middle East flash point and now
a cosmopolitan beach resort. Norwegians, Tunisians, French,
Russians and others sun and oil themselves and read Danielle Steele
in as many different translations. (Noa has met the global village
and it is kitsch.)
</P>
<P>
   Noa strikes up acquaintance with an Italian carabiniere detailed
to the United Nations forces. What follows is an exquisite, comic
and sobering dramatization of frontiers: between a world and a
world, between intimacy and distance, between dismay at what is
strange and its ineradicable allure. Perhaps the use of fences is
not just to separate; it is also to draw us to press ourselves up
against them and take the pain.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `FOREIGN BRIDES'
</P>
<P>
   By Elena Lappin
</P>
<P>
   208 pages. Farrar, Straus &AMP; Giroux. $22.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
