<HEADER>
A1943 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRO     08-18 0791
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE BLOBIFICATION OF MODERN DESIGN
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: This story also moved in the ``l'' lifestyle file)  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   Novelist  &UR; Tom Wolfe &LR; , who between novels wrote books critical of
modern painting and architecture, considers the state of design and
bangs his walking stick on the floor in the latest issue of Men's
Journal.
</P>
<P>
   Citing such titans of design as  &UR; Raymond Loewy &LR;  (whose credits
include the Studebaker and Postal Service eagle) and  &UR; Harley Earl &LR; 
(General Motors cars), Wolfe complains about today's designers of
`` `blobjets,' roundish, childish blob-like objects that now come
in every form from the iMac computer to the Mazda Miata, the Ford
Taurus and the reborn Volkswagen Beetle. These objects are not
meant to be exuberant, much less elegant. The key adjective is
childish.''
</P>
<P>
   Wolfe names names. ``The art world's idea of a great designer is
the Frenchman  &UR; Philippe Starck &LR; ,'' whose interiors, says Wolfe,
look like backdrops for male models, ``the ones with the eight-day
growth of beard, the hangdog slouch and the glum look of a
recovering codeine addict who just flunked out of his 12-step
program. ...
</P>
<P>
   ``In a worshipful piece, the New York Times named him one of the
giants of 20th century design and said his work `revolves around
fear of rejection.' Marvelous.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ANSEL ADAMS FIND &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Ten  &UR; Ansel Adams &LR;  photos of San Francisco's then-new Grace
Cathedral, taken perhaps in the mid-'40s, have been discovered in
the cathedral basement, where they had been stored _ and forgotten
_ 40 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Cherie Dunn, who's on the cathedral's Art Council, says the
group hopes to display the photos for the congregation's 150th
anniversary, in December.
</P>
<P>
   Before that, however, they're in need of proper museum-quality
framing, which (along with insurance) will cost somewhere between
$3,000 and $5,000. Grace is looking for an Adams angel.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
