<P>
   &UR; SNIFFING WITH YOUR DOG &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DeAnn Lowell &LR; , founder of Peppermint Pets, explains why an
adjustable cotton collar stuffed with a blend of herbs is a good
idea for both human- and dogwear: ``Our ancestors were very
familiar with the physical and emotional benefits of aromatic
plants and oils. Much of what they learned about aroma therapy,
they picked up by watching animals in nature. ... The fragrance of
our collars promotes an emotionally balanced and calm environment
for pets and people, so we can both be more actualized.''
</P>
<P>
   And if you can't understand why you would want to be
``actualized,'' the company provides some hard facts you might want
to mention at a dinner party: ``If the densely packed olfactory
membrane in the canine nose was laid out in a single layer, it
would cover an area equal to over 65 percent of the dog's body
size'' (or an eensy weensy portion of the state of New Jersey).
``By comparison, the olfactory membrane in a human nose is about
the size of a postage stamp.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
