<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-18 18:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1947 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-BRIDGE-OPERA-GALATI-A     08-18 0887
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRIDGE-OPERA-GALATI-ART-720(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE OPERA'S DIRECTOR, YES, BUT NOT A DICTATOR 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill.)  (EDS: This is the third article in a series on the making of ``A
View From the Bridge,'' an opera adapted from Arthur Miller's 1955
play.) 
(ART ADV: Photo of set designer Santo Loquasto is being sent to NYT
photo clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by
calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By BRUCE WEBER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ It was four years ago that Frank Galati was named
director of ``A View From the Bridge,'' an adaptation of Arthur
Miller's 1955 play that will have its world premiere at Lyric Opera
of Chicago on Oct. 9. He will not meet the cast, however, until
rehearsals begin in September.
</P>
<P>
   That may be the most obvious indication of the delicate role
played by an opera director, who is responsible for the production
as a whole but lacks the supreme control of a theater director.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't cast this, except to be a kind of counselor, which
has always been my role in opera,'' Galati said of the work, which
was created by the composer William Bolcom and the librettist
Arnold Weinstein. Galati is in Toronto to begin work on a musical
based on the children's books of Dr. Seuss.
</P>
<P>
   The casting of ``View'' was left to the Lyric creative staff,
which chose Kim Josephson as Eddie Carbone, the Brooklyn stevedore
brought to a tragic end by his desire for his 17-year-old niece;
Catherine Malfitano as his wife, Beatrice; Juliana Rambaldi as
Catherine, the niece, and Gregory Turay as Rodolpho, the Italian
immigrant who steals Catherine's affections and moves Eddie to the
betrayal that brings about his demise.
</P>
<P>
   ``In an opera, the vocal demands are so immense; I can't make
that decision,'' Galati said. ``That's a huge difference, because
in a play _ a musical, too _ I'm the guy.''
</P>
<P>
   There are a number of directors, highly knowledgeable about
music, who specialize in opera _ Colin Graham and Francesca
Zambello, to name two of the best-known. But convention has it that
even they yield the casting duties to the producing company.
</P>
<P>
   ``Directors tend to be most passionate about the theater part of
the opera,'' said Samuel Smith, the spokesman for Opera America, an
umbrella group for professional companies. And, in fact, the opera
stage has long been a venue for interlopers from the theater and
even the movies. Lyric's production of Bolcom's 1992 opera,
``McTeague,'' was directed by Robert Altman.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, though he has significant experience in opera, Galati's
renown is as a director of plays and musicals. A fixture at both
the Steppenwolf Theater and the Goodman Theater in Chicago, he won
a Tony Award for directing his own adaptation of ``The Grapes of
Wrath'' in 1990 and is perhaps best known for his first musical,
the Broadway hit ``Ragtime.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A View From the Bridge'' is a first as well, of course, a
well-known drama receiving brand-new treatment as an opera. That
complicates Galati's task further, or at least puts more pressure
on him. Lyric is spending $1.4 million on the production, which,
like all new American operas, faces desperate odds if it is to
enter the repertory. Of 125 world premieres at American opera
companies in this decade, only about a dozen have had second
productions, and though operas tend to stand or fall on the
strength of their scores, ``View'' will not stand any chance of
surviving if Galati's staging is lackluster.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a way it's liberating,'' said Galati, choosing not to focus
on the future of the work before it actually exists. ``Because it's
a new work, I have a certain freedom to explore the stagecraft and
the storytelling conventions. If you do a `Tosca' or a `Traviata'
or even `Pelleas et Melisande' '' _ all of which Galati has staged
for Lyric _ ``there are these huge expectations about something
everybody knows.''
</P>
<P>
   As a straddler of forms, 55-year-old Galati seems almost curious
himself about their separate concerns. A bearish man with a kindly
manner _ think of Santa Claus with a buzz cut _ he is a versatile
theater personage, a former actor and a writer whose adaptation
(with Lawrence Kasdan) of Anne Tyler's novel ``The Accidental
Tourist'' was nominated for an Academy Award. He has also written a
screen version of Miller's ``American Clock.''
</P>
<P>
   In his directorial work Galati is attracted to the big casts and
grand gestures of pageantry, ``The Grapes of Wrath'' and
``Ragtime'' being prime examples. It is a predilection, he said,
born of his work at Lyric, and before that, the Chicago Opera
Theater. Asked about the difference between directing theater and
opera, Galati said with a shrug, ``They sing.''
</P>
<P>
   Even in a musical, he said, the voices do not become the
controlling elements they do in opera. ``I'm not being frivolous
when I say `they sing,''' he said. ``As a director of plays, one of
the things you have to find in a play is the music. You have to
find its rhythm, its tempo. On a technical level, you could say
that in directing plays, finding the musicality is an imperative.
In an opera, the momentum is implicit in the musical score. It's up
to the composer and the conductor to move the scene. It's not my
department.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
