u v BC-HEARST-NEWS-ADVISORY-     08-18 0083
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEARST-NEWS-ADVISORY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORS:  
  
</HEADLINE>
  
 Wednesday, Aug. 18, 1999
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Hearst News Service plans the following additional story for
Thursday:
</P>
<P>
   KEATING-BUSH (Washington) _ With questions about possible drug
use continuing to dog leading Republican presidential contender
Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, a prominent fellow Republican
governor on Wednesday urged Bush to get any past misdeeds out in
the open. By DAN FREEDMAN.
</P>
<P>
   The Hearst News Service/Washington
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-18-99 1814EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990818.0222 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-18 18:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1949 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-BRIDGE-OPERA-GALATI-A     08-18 1113
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRIDGE-OPERA-GALATI-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 TORONTO: my department.''  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The difference begins with casting, which in opera is
particularly complex and risky. Most projects, after all, are cast
years in advance and, as Matthew Epstein, Lyric's artistic
director, said, `` X, who is the greatest singer in the world
today, may have no voice in four years.''
</P>
<P>
   Also to be considered are the preferences of the director.
``Frank needs ensemble actors,'' Epstein said. ``That's what he
comes out of, ensemble theater, and it's what opera should be
about, but isn't always. Frank would not work well in a situation
with a superstar. And in this case, even a big name like Catherine
Malfitano, she's someone who prefers to work in an ensemble
situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Galati's wishes had to do with the physical presence of the
singers, a particular concern in a new work where verisimilitude is
a powerful tool with which to woo the audience. In a classical
opera, where the audience arrives more accepting of the fact that
the conventions of storytelling will be bent to serve music, that
is less of an issue. ``So Desdemona is fat, so what?'' Galati said.
</P>
<P>
   In ``View,'' the story revolves around the discomfiting animal
urge _ Eddie's lust for Catherine _ of a largely inarticulate
laborer. Josephson, a burly linebacker type, was the last principal
to be cast; a German baritone had originally been cast but asked a
year ago to be replaced, fearing he would not be able to sing
persuasively in Brooklynese, or even in English. In replacing him,
Galati argued against some other, less physically robust
candidates.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not even an acting thing,'' Galati said. ``Eddie Carbone
is a stevedore. So I said, `Look, I know you've got to have someone
with the vocal chops, but you got to have a guy.' In fact, you
can't do the drama unless you have the guy and the gal. She's got
to be a babe, someone who makes a man who is otherwise grounded in
a marriage, a relationship that's real and sanctioned, cross the
border. They've got to be convincing in their physical presence if
they're going to satisfy the audience's totally understandable
demand for convincing representation of psychological reality.''
</P>
<P>
   (An interesting dilemma has just arisen. Ms. Rambaldi, a married
woman in her 30's who is to play the teen-age virgin Catherine, has
announced that she is pregnant.)
</P>
<P>
   As a director of performers who are singers before they are
actors, Galati said that he compared singers to Shakespeareans, and
that his experience had been that they are pleased to work with a
director who can help them do what they do second best. In turn,
they educate him; frequently, he said, he has made unrealistic
demands, like asking a singer to perform a difficult passage while
being lifted or lying down.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you work on Shakespeare, these characters, their
necessity, is verse,'' he said. ``That's the way they live, in
utterance and expressiveness. The same is true in opera; in a great
opera, the source of the music is inside the character, so the
character is the agent of this mode of expressiveness. You could
say, after all, that speech aspires to song.''
</P>
<P>
   The opera will be played on a single set, and Galati had long
discussions with the designer, Santo Loquasto, and the projection
artist, Wendall K. Harrington, about his needs, which include a
number of places for the chorus to enter and exit and to witness
the playing out of the domestic drama. In Galati's vision, the
chorus represents Eddie's neighbors in Red Hook, Brooklyn, a
tightly knit community with a common set of values and a unified
dread of the taboo Eddie is threatening to violate.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my baby thinking about this, I imagine the chorus will have
a strange, surreal role in underscoring the privacy of the drama as
well as its public impact,'' Galati said.
</P>
<P>
   On the set, which is being built at the San Diego Opera scene
shop, the interior of the Carbone apartment is toward the left of
the stage, flanked by the shipyard exteriors of Red Hook. There are
several walkways suggesting the gridwork of the Brooklyn Bridge,
and in the rear, at the right, is an industrial-size garage door
suggesting the entrance to a warehouse. One of Ms. Harrington's
three projection screens forms the angled roof of an apartment; the
others will be in the rear of the stage. The images to be projected
will also underscore the private-as-public theme: blowups of
domestic images like sinks and shaving mirrors and stoves with
pasta pots in counterpoint to local exteriors.
</P>
<P>
   ``The garage door that slides up _ it's a huge aperture, very,
very powerful,'' Galati said. ``It can be backlit, a floodlight on
figures standing in that doorway, and in thinking about the
behavior of the chorus, I had this image: the garage door opens and
there are all the women in the chorus, standing in slips and bare
feet, and they're all brushing their hair. It's a collective
representation, in large scale, of a moment of intimacy between
husband and wife.''
</P>
<P>
   Loquasto said that the strength of the set was that it would be
as suitable for the play as for the opera, and Galati agreed, with
a caveat: the set is in scale with the Civic Opera House, a
3,600-seat auditorium, and the grandeur of opera.
</P>
<P>
   ``The orchestral force and choral force, and the dissonances and
harmonies that Bolcom is combining in his score, this is a giant
pouring forth of musical information,'' Galati said. ``The house
invites it, and the staging has to accommodate it. The story has to
reach to the rafters, and they go way up there. Santo's set, in
terms of its geometry, is suited to the play, but in terms of the
scale and the gestures it will allow, it is suited brilliantly to
the scale of the event of an opera.''
</P>
<P>
   Which brings Galati back to his theme: they sing. ``I do think
that part of the operatic mystery is virtuosity itself,'' he said.
The distinguishing ingredient in opera ``is sort of like the
ingredient present when you go to the circus,'' he continued. ``You
have a singer, in the way you have a tightrope walker, high above
the audience, stepping on a wire that is so thin in order to sing
those achingly pure and beautiful melodies, pianissimo. It's the
kind of virtuosity you see in those who test themselves to the
absolute limit. What if they fall? What if the pianissimo cracks?
You live in fear in the audience, just as the singer does. It's the
most difficult test the human voice can endure, and it is happening
in front of us. Now.''
</P>
<P>
   For the director, ``the profound question,'' he said, is how
much to serve the singer, how much to push. ``My impulse is always
to make it harder,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
