<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-18 18:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1950 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-NORTON-THEATER-ART-2T     08-18 0971
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NORTON-THEATER-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A WHITE KNIGHT FROM THE COMPUTER KINGDOM MAKES HIS MARK IN THEATER
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Calif.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By MEL GUSSOW   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ At a fund-raising event, James Houghton, the founder
and artistic director of the Signature Theater Company, asked Peter
Norton, a wealthy California art collector and philanthropist, for
``a modest contribution.'' Norton is a man of impulse known for
grand gestures: recently he bought J.D. Salinger's letters to Joyce
Maynard at auction at Sotheby's (for $156,500) to return them to
the author.
</P>
<P>
   ``What would be an immodest contribution?'' he asked Houghton.
The two agreed that nothing would be more immodest than pledging
enough money, in Norton's words, ``to have one's name slapped on
the theater's building.''
</P>
<P>
   This week Houghton announced that Norton was giving the
Signature $600,000, almost half the theater's annual budget. As a
result, the theater will be named the Signature Theater Company at
the Peter Norton Space. A ceremony to that effect is planned for
Sept. 13, at the start of the Signature season, which will be
dedicated to the plays of Maria Irene Fornes.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting on the stage one day this week as workers began moving
in scenery for the first Fornes production, Norton and Houghton
talked about their collaboration, what it meant for the company and
how it fit in with Norton's other philanthropic activities.
</P>
<P>
   Norton generally gives cultural grants to the visual arts. As a
collector specializing in ``cutting-edge contemporary art,'' he has
often supported young artists and he regards the Signature as an
extension of that activity.
</P>
<P>
   Although Norton is by his own admission a neophyte in theater,
for several years he has admired the Signature's work. ``If an
ordinary small theater company is a sundial,'' he said, ``this is a
Swiss watch.''
</P>
<P>
   Or, as Houghton said, ``This is a small company with a big
idea.''
</P>
<P>
   By focusing on a single playwright for an entire season, the
theater can show the arc of a writer's career and illuminate a
lesser-known side of a body of work. The Signature began in 1991
with a series of plays by Romulus Linney and has since given a
stage to, among others, Edward Albee, Horton Foote (who won a
Pulitzer Prize in 1995 for ``The Young Man From Atlanta,'' first
presented during his Signature season), Sam Shepard, Arthur Miller
and, last year, John Guare.
</P>
<P>
   Each of the writers has been actively involved in the season.
``The playwrights are in the mix every step of the way,'' Houghton
said. ``When they feel they are embraced, all the defensive walls
go down and the real collaboration begins to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   The theater has grown from a nomadic off-off-Broadway company to
an influential organization with a modern permanent home at 555 W.
42nd St. The first season cost $35,000. Gradually the budget has
grown to $1.4 million.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Houghton has made his own reputation as a
producer and director. He is also artistic adviser to the Guthrie
Theater in Minneapolis and he has succeeded Lloyd Richards as the
artistic director of the National Playwrights Conference at the
Eugene O'Neill Theater Center in Waterford, Conn.
</P>
<P>
   He said that he hopes to have a synergy between the O'Neill,
which does readings of new plays in the summer, and the Signature.
With the help of Norton's grant, Houghton plans to increase his
program for young writers in residence. The grant is unrestricted
and may also be used to ease the company's cash flow problems, to
attract other donors and for the 10th-anniversary season, in which
there will be a festival of new works by house playwrights.
</P>
<P>
   ``At a big institution, ponderous wheels roll,'' Norton said.
``Write the same check to the Met and it wouldn't even be noticed.
Here you can turn on a dime. You have flexibility, and the bang for
the buck is enormous.'' While Norton joked about wanting his name
prominently on the marquee, he and Houghton made it clear that
Norton's signature on the company would be minimal. Such restraint
is in keeping with his profile to date.
</P>
<P>
   Norton, who said his background was ``as a nerd,'' made his
fortune with a microcomputer software business. In 1990 he sold it
to devote himself to art collecting and philanthropy. He said he
expected other computer entrepreneurs to follow his path: ``You've
got to remember that high-tech money is new money and philanthropic
money is generally old money. High-tech fortunes haven't been
around long enough. Let those people become elderly, in the endgame
strategies of their lives, and they'll start doing what Carnegie,
Rockefeller and Mellon did in their old age.''
</P>
<P>
   Norton, 56, said he is a bit of an anomaly: ``When I was first
threatened with prosperity, I started studying the natural history
of American wealth. It's basically a curve. You make it, you use it
and you throw it away. That's called shirt sleeves to shirt sleeves
in three generations. Usually the generation that makes money
doesn't know how to use it, and having made some money I wanted to
have the fun of using it.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The alternatives? ``You can use money to make more money. That's
essentially Donald Trump's story,'' he said. ``You can use it to
empower public service careers. That's essentially the Kennedy and
half the Rockefeller story. You can use it for freedom _ being a
playboy. You can use it for philanthropy. I was too much of a bozo
to go into business again, I didn't have political ambitions, and
loose cars and fast women didn't suit me.'' That left philanthropy.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In 1989, with his wife, Eileen, he established the Peter Norton
Family Foundation, which in 10 years has made grants of more than
$15 million in the fine arts, including $1.2 million to museum
curators to buy works for permanent collections. Among the
recipients are the Museum of Contemporary Art in Los Angeles, the
Museum of Fine Arts in Boston and the Museum of Modern Art and the
Whitney Museum of American Art in Manhattan. The Whitney has a
floor named after Norton. He has also given more than $4.6 million
in social service grants for programs benefiting women and
children.
</P>
<P>
   The Nortons live in Santa Monica, Calif., and have two
apartments in Manhattan (one designed by Maya Lin), with room
enough to display a substantial part of their art collection.
``It's an evangelical mission,'' he said, ``trying to seduce
conservative art patrons to be more interested in what the
youngsters are doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking about his philanthropy as well as his collecting, he
said, ``I'm a dabbler by nature, a dilettante.'' He added, ``I
don't want to toot a big horn, but broadly speaking I like to
support innovation where it seems to be needed.''
</P>
<P>
   About the Signature Theater, he said, ``Here's innovation, an
ecological niche being discovered, almost invented. This is a
theater that's about celebrating and nurturing writing.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the Salinger letters (written 27 years ago to Ms.
Maynard), he said, ``Those letters were up for auction and a lot of
people felt strongly that it was a bad thing and that they ought to
go back to him. I didn't feel strongly that way.'' But when he
heard that a group of people were putting together a consortium to
buy them, he said, ``Don't bother,'' and he bid for them.
</P>
<P>
   He said that once he bought them, he did not read them: ``From
all reports, the letters were really boring.'' Then he mailed them
to Salinger's agent _ and has never heard a word from the author.
</P>
<P>
   Summing up his highly individualistic behavior as a benefactor
in the arts, he said, ``What's the social utility of the rich? It's
to do the things that otherwise can't be done.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
