u w BC-KEATING-BUSH-HNS &LR;      08-18 0396
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KEATING-BUSH-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOV. KEATING SAYS BUSH SHOULD DISCLOSE ANY PAST INDISCRETIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDS: Filed in ``w'' and ``p'' categories.)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN FREEDMAN  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With questions about possible drug use continuing
to dog leading Republican presidential contender Gov. George W.
Bush of Texas, a prominent Republican fellow governor on Wednesday
urged Bush to get any past misdeeds out in the open.
</P>
<P>
   ``George W. Bush should address issues about private conduct,''
Gov. Frank Keating of Oklahoma told reporters. ``In today's world,
every one of us who serves in public office needs to answer
questions about conduct that is arguably criminal.''
</P>
<P>
   Keating, chairman of the Republican Governors Association and an
enthusiastic Bush supporter, stressed that he ``doesn't think
there's anything there'' in Bush's background. Keating added that
whatever misdeeds Bush may have committed ``were largely carousing
in nature.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I really have tremendous admiration for Bush, but I think
these kinds of questions are legitimate,'' Keating said.
</P>
<P>
   Keating spoke out just as Bush reacted testily to more questions
about whether he had used illegal drugs in the past.
</P>
<P>
   Bush branded rumors about his personal life ``ridiculous and
absurd,'' and repeated his view that fishing for dirt in
politicians' past lives is tantamount to a sport. ``That's the game
in American politics, and I refuse to play it,'' Bush told
reporters in Austin, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Bush and his spokeswoman, Karen Hughes, have frequently used
this line of reasoning to sidestep direct answers to questions
about drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Keating, asked whether he believes Bush should put the matter to
rest by admitting whatever it is he did, responded: ``I do.''
</P>
<P>
   Answers to such questions ``are not disabling, but they're
certainly relevant to candidacies,'' Keating said. ``The public is
very forgiving ... especially of youthful indiscretions.''
</P>
<P>
   Keating is head of the organization representing 31 Republican
governors, including Bush.
</P>
<P>
   A total of 22 Republican governors have endorsed Bush, making
them a key constituency in Bush's early rise to the top of the GOP
pack chasing the party's 2000 presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Freedman can be reached at 202-298-6920 and, by e-mail, at
dan(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
