A1956 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-FLUTE19-COX     08-18 0450
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLUTE19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    3,700 flutists from around the world blow into Atlanta
 &HT;    By Judith Green
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It was a big day in River City, Iowa, when 76
trombones caught the morning sun.
</P>
<P>
   But that's peanuts compared with the 3,700 flutes coming to
Atlanta for this weekend's annual convention of the National Flute
Association. That's 8,170 feet of shining silver.
</P>
<P>
   How many flutists, and what they are to do and play and hear,
have preoccupied Amy Porter, associate principal flute of the
Atlanta Symphony Orchestra, for 18 months, ever since she was named
program chair for the conference.
</P>
<P>
   It's been up to her to find the speakers and performers, design
the brochure and coordinate the logistics for this immense
undertaking. The 7,000-member NFA is the largest association of its
kind in the world, Porter says, and more than half its people will
be under the roof of the Atlanta Hilton &AMP; Towers today through
Sunday. They're coming from as far away as Venezuela, Belgium and
Kazakhstan.
</P>
<P>
   The convention offers lectures and workshops, master classes,
flute choir reading sessions and every kind of performance, from
serene Indian music to hot fusion jazz. Exhibitors and vendors will
offer all manner of flute paraphernalia, from $15,000
professional-quality instruments in gold (by the premier American
maker Gemeinhardt in Elkhart, Ind.) to flute note pads, tote bags
and sheet music.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have the best feelings about featuring my local
colleagues,'' says Porter. Among the conference participants will
be ASO principal flute Christina Smith and ASO piccolo Carl Hall,
who will perform the premiere of a concerto written for him by
Martin Amlin in Saturday evening's concert. Members of the Marietta
Flute Choir, the Atlanta Area Honors Flute Choir, Atlanta Music
Academy and Hotlanta are serving as ushers, gofers and helpers.
</P>
<P>
   Headline acts include the percussion ensemble Nexus and Swiss
contrabass flute Matthias Ziegler, who perform Friday, and Jim
Walker and his jazz ensemble Free Flight, whose gala concert closes
the conference Sunday. Jazz flutist Normal Rangell is to perform,
and so are William Bennett of the English Chamber Orchestra, Joshua
Smith of the Cleveland Orchestra and Irish flutist Brian Dunning.
</P>
<P>
   National Flute Association
</P>
<P>
   8 a.m.-11 p.m. today-Sunday. Day/concert passes for the general
public are $10 if purchased before 6 p.m. and $15 after. Exhibition
passes are $15. Atlanta Hilton &AMP; Towers, 255 Courtland St. N.E.
Information: 661-299-6680.
</P>
<P>
   Judith Green writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
