<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-18 18:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1957 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-POLITICS-DROPOUTS-081     08-18 0984
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLITICS-DROPOUTS-0819-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    FOR PRESIDENTIAL CANDIDATES WHO CRASH AND BURN, DEFEAT IS
FLEETING
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (p) politics categories.
 &HT;    By SCOTT SHEPARD
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The winners of presidential elections ultimately
belong to the ages, but the losers belong to the families, close
friends and staunch supporters who share the agony of their defeat.
</P>
<P>
   At least until the losers set off on their next political quest.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once it enters the bloodstream, the disease of running for
president can only be cured by embalming fluid,'' the late Mo
Udall, defeated by Jimmy Carter in the 1976 Democratic primaries,
once quipped.
</P>
<P>
   Most of those who crash and burn en route to the White House,
like Lamar Alexander and John Kasich did in the Republican contest
this summer, eventually return to the political battlefield in some
capacity _ but rarely with the same bloodlust for the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Like Texas Sen. Phil Gramm, who outspent his opponents in GOP
primary elections four years ago, but managed only a handful of
votes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I spoke, and it turned out no one was listening,'' said Gramm,
resorting to the self-deprecating humor that is typical of those
who have failed in their bids for the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Or like John Glenn, the astronaut-turned-senator who seemed to
have the right stuff 15 years ago but whose candidacy fizzled on
the launch pad.
</P>
<P>
   Glenn has rarely spoken of his disastrous campaign for president
in 1984. But he spoke about the stigma of defeat with The
Washington Post three years ago: ``You wonder whether people are
going to look down their noses at you and say, 'Boy, is he a
dumbbell for trying to run for president! What made him think he
could do that?' But when I came back to the Senate, I threw myself
into my committee work, and nobody thought I was any less capable
because I tried for a higher office.''
</P>
<P>
   For all of them, though, regardless of how many times they fail
in politics, losing the presidency is a painful, gut-wrenching
experience, as two-time Democratic nominee Adlai Stevenson captured
so accurately in an often-borrowed lament of losers: ``I'm too old
to cry, but it hurts too much to laugh.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The kind of effort you have to put into one of these campaigns
is so substantial and costly in terms of money and emotion that you
couldn't be human and not be pained by losing,'' said noted
presidential historian Robert Dallek. ``These are real-life
aspirations of human beings that we watch die on Election Day.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, author Richard Ben Cramer, in his book ``What It Takes''
about the 1988 campaign, captured a rarely seen moment of human
frailty in presidential politics: two-time presidential loser Jesse
Jackson gathering Dick Gephardt into a bear hug on the night of the
Michigan primary as Gephardt, realizing his dream had ended, wept
``on the breast of the only man in that room who could really
understand.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew the end was coming, but it was still so depressing,''
said former Gephardt aide Linda Moore, now the deputy director of
political affairs in the Clinton White House. ``You work so hard
for so long and it ends so suddenly.''
</P>
<P>
   So suddenly, in fact, that Gephardt and his wife Jane, after his
official withdrawal from the race, had to leave a campaign staff
party to get home before his Secret Service protection expired that
evening at midnight. ``He turned into a pumpkin,'' Moore said.
</P>
<P>
   ``To say it deflates you is a massive understatement,'' former
Tennessee Sen. Howard Baker once said of his unsuccessful 1980
campaign for the GOP nomination. He compared it to the death of his
wife. ``You feel just drained ... you feel empty.''
</P>
<P>
   And often, in the bone-tiring whirl of modern presidential
campaigns, the candidates are the last to know when they have lost.
</P>
<P>
   Former President George Bush, writing in 1988 about coming up
short in the 1980 GOP contest, confessed that it took longtime
confidante Jim Baker to silence his vows to carry on the campaign
against Ronald Reagan, the ultimate winner. ``The campaign is
finished, George,'' Baker informed him.
</P>
<P>
   Some never get that far.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Babbitt, always popular with reporters, was one of the
early casualties of the 1988 Democratic contest, dropping out
before some news organizations had even published profiles of the
former Arizona governor.
</P>
<P>
   ``The press won't have Bruce Babbitt to puff up anymore,'' he
declared in a tone of mock vengefulness on the day that he dropped
out.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Bush, Babbitt, Howard Baker and Gephardt, like so
many others who have sought the presidency, eventually bounced
back. Bush was elected president in 1988. Babbitt has been
secretary of the interior since 1993. Baker became the Senate
Majority Leader, then White House chief of staff for Reagan. And
Gephardt is the Democratic Leader in the House of Representatives.
</P>
<P>
   Similary, Glenn became an elder statesman in the Senate and
eventually made a triumphant return to space. And Gramm got his
first committee chairmanship in the Senate, a position of influence
that exceeds the power of any post he held while pursing the
presidency.
</P>
<P>
   But some never lose the urge. Bob Dole, who lost in 1996, 1988
and 1980, is ``looking for opportunities'' to get out on the
campaign trail again, for his wife Elizabeth Dole, according to
Linda Duvall, Dole's pollster in the 2000 campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not many individuals get a chance to be in a position to run
for president of the United States,'' said Duvall, who worked for
Gramm in 1996. ``So you would hope that there's no recriminations,
that there's no sense of bitterness. They should be proud that they
got to the point of where they could run for president. I hope
that's what they're left with.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
