<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-18 18:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1960 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-BELLSOUTH-WEB19-COX     08-18 0509
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BELLSOUTH-WEB19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BellSouth answers call for payment services on Net
 &HT;    By Michael E. Kanell
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ BellSouth Corp. joined the growing ranks of companies
offering Internet billing, announcing Wednesday a new Web site that
allows consumers to receive and pay their bills online.
</P>
<P>
   The arrangement, available via the company's Web site
(www.bellsouth.com/bill), lets residential customers pay BellSouth
bills with credit cards or an automatic withdrawal from a checking
account. Customers may also pay through their banks or an
electronic bill provider like Atlanta-based CheckFree, options
which have been available for some time.
</P>
<P>
   Customers may choose to stop getting paper bills sent by mail,
although they will receive an e-mail notice about bills they have
not yet looked at. When they are online, customers with questions
about their bills can click on that portion of the bill and receive
an explanation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are always looking for better ways for customers to do
business with us, and we can provide better customers service by
doing business over the Net,'' said Brad Hahn, senior manager for
electronic commerce at BellSouth Consumer Services.
</P>
<P>
   With more than 21 million households online nationally, the idea
is catching on, at least partly because companies see it as a low
cost way to offer round-the-clock billing services that eliminate
paper and mailing charges. Customers are likely to be attracted by
the ability to pay bills any time, but also to bundle many bills
together for payment.
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth believes about 5 percent of customers in its
nine-state region _ about 700,000 households _ are interested in
using the Net to pay phone bills. According to the Yankee Group,
nearly 80 percent of customers who want to pay online would choose
to use a central site, while 20 percent would prefer to use
individual Web sites. Of those who would choose a central site, 84
percent say they want to use their bank's site.
</P>
<P>
   MCI WorldCom has offered a similar online option to residents
since March, according to spokeswoman Teresa Byrne. ``We are very,
very interested in e-billing.''
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T also lets customers pay online, and offers the option of
clicking on an unfamiliar telephone number to find out whose
listing was called, said AT&AMP;T spokesman Andy Boisseau. ``This gives
them the opportunity to interact with bills in ways they could not
before.''
</P>
<P>
   Both BellSouth and MCI WorldCom say they also plan a
click-to-identify feature.
</P>
<P>
   Laurinda Wilson, spokeswoman for CheckFree, said the company has
agreements to handle bill paying with BellSouth, MCI WorldCom, AT&AMP;T
and GTE. CheckFree has about 13,000 Net users paying bills online,
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts at Jupiter Communications estimate that 16 million U.S.
households now use the Net for paying bills, checking account
balances and making stock trades. That figure will grow to 27
million within three years, says Jupiter.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
