<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-18 18:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1964 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l BC-FRAZZLEDPARENT-COLUMN     08-18 0831
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRAZZLEDPARENT-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE MEDIA ARE THE MISCHIEF
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CATHERINE NEWTON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Reading the newspaper the other night, my vigilant parental eye
spotted this headline: Doctors urge limiting TV time for kids.
Apparently those doctors in the American Academy of Pediatrics have
issued yet another recommendation on parenting. Frankly, as I
skimmed through the story, this one made me a little nervous.
</P>
<P>
   After more than two years of intense study on the matter (which
may at least partially explain why I can't get a doctor[ human] on
the phone when I call my pediatrician's office), the herd of
healers has[ have] arrived at the landmark ruling that watching TV
isn't really very good for kiddos. It seems the 55,000 members of
the academy have agreed that too much media influence _ especially
television, but also including movies, video games, computer games,
music videos, radio, the Internet and books _ can lead to a scourge
of societal ills that will leave us with chain-smoking, Uzi-toting
tots with a tendency to lay into the ice cream.
</P>
<P>
   To cut down on the number of fat, mean babies we're producing in
this country, the good doctors' new policy statement includes the
simple recommendation that pediatricians request, along with a
medical history of their little patients, a complete media history
on each and every child.
</P>
<P>
   Uh-oh.
</P>
<P>
   Now, usually I find the AAP a helpful source for my many
parenting concerns. When I have a burning question on acellular
pertussis vaccine, I turn to them for an update. And who else would
take the time to answer my long list of queries about ultraviolet
light?
</P>
<P>
   And, in truth, I could see that the AAP had some valid points.
After all, at the very minute I was reading about the policy
statement, my own two kids were strewn about on couches, chomping
chips and riveted to the 32nd showing of ``The Parent Trap''in our
own living room.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the idea of a media history made me sweat, for two
reasons: First, it means there will be something else to record and
remember about my children. Obviously those well-meaning
pediatricians have no idea that I have been unable to perform even
the simplest tasks in this respect. The binders that hold my kids'
yearly physical exam reports are covered with a thick film of dust.
The photo albums are half-empty relics on the bookshelves. A good
detective, inspecting my home, might assume its young inhabitants
had disappeared sometime around 1996. And it gets worse: I couldn't
tell you if my kids are current on their tetanus shots, or when
they last went to the dentist. I had to make up a poem to remember
my second child's birth date. (You won't forget it anymore,
Hadley's birthday is Sept. 24).
</P>
<P>
   But the challenge to my overcrowded mind is a minor concern
compared with the pain and humiliation of actually facing the
checklist when a receptionist hands it over on a clipboard in the
waiting room.
</P>
<P>
   Here's what I see shaking out as I fill it in.
</P>
<P>
   Media History Survey of Your Child
</P>
<P>
   1. Does your child have a history of interacting with any of the
following? (check all that apply)
</P>
<P>
   Television? The VCR? Pokemon shows, the Red and Blue games, or
the PokeRap? Playstation _ or N64?
</P>
<P>
   ``Hmmm. This is easy so far. Check. Check. Check, check, check.
And double check. And don't forget the Pokemon Web site while we're
at it. And the Pokemon Snap and Pokemon Stadium. And that new
yellow game, too, or is that something different?''
</P>
<P>
   2. Do you use television as a crutch or a bribe, offering it,
for example, as an incentive for getting up in the morning?
</P>
<P>
   ``Check _ but do you have a better idea? Food doesn't excite my
son in the morning, and yesterday I found him standing up, with his
head against the wall, mostly asleep in the shower.''
</P>
<P>
   3. Have you ever experienced blackouts where you can't remember
what you've watched on TV the night before?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure.''
</P>
<P>
   4. Have the members of your family ever experienced conflict
over the television in your family, perhaps resorting to physical
fighting over what programs you watch?
</P>
<P>
   ``Check _ but this was a long time ago _ before everyone got his
or her own TV.''
</P>
<P>
   5. Have you ever lied to a friend, telling them you couldn't
attend an event because you were afraid of missing some TV?
</P>
<P>
   ``Surely, you're not including movies here?''
</P>
<P>
   6. Do your kids think that what happens on television is real?
``It's not?''
</P>
<P>
   This whole media history thing was giving me a major migraine.
And little Annie was just in the middle of telling Jessie that she
really is Annie and not her twin Hallie, and that part of ``The
Parent Trap'' always makes me and my kids cry, it's so happy.
</P>
<P>
   So I did what any good parent would do. I folded up the paper
and snuggled into the couch with my kids.
</P>
<P>
   And we watched some TV.
</P>
<P>
   _ (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
