</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-MEMORABILIA-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW COMPANY BANKS ON MARKET FOR GOLF MEMORABILIA 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla.)   (bl) 
By MARGARET ANN MIILLE   
 Herald-Tribune, Sarasota, Fla.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARASOTA, Fla. _ It seemed simple enough: Build a windowed case
or two displaying replicas of antique golf memorabilia.
</P>
<P>
   But that idea has evolved into a much more ambitious project
since it was hatched three years ago by business associates Ki
Cuyler and Henry Van Beck of Sarasota.
</P>
<P>
   It has spawned a privately held company called Antique Golf
Collectibles that has attracted to its board the likes of David
Clark, former executive vice president of Mellon Bank, and Robert
Hannan, former vice chairman of Eckerd Drugs.
</P>
<P>
   And it does more than produce copies of turn-of-the-century golf
club heads and balls.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the group announced that it would kick off its own
international golf tournament next year at the Oaks Country Club in
Osprey, about 10 miles south of Sarasota.
</P>
<P>
   In keeping with the vintage theme, those games will be played
with hickory clubs and gutta percha balls similar to those used in
the early 1900s. Golfers will dress in the style of that era.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's gone a long way in a short time already,'' said Van Beck,
company general manager and chief operations officer.
</P>
<P>
   Though display cases comprise the bulk of its merchandise,
Antique Golf Collectibles also sells golf T-shirts for $30, gutta
percha golf balls for $5; long-nosed putters for $95; and sets of
hickory golf clubs for $950.
</P>
<P>
   Van Beck and Cuyler, a sales consultant, discovered a relatively
open playing field three years ago when they began researching this
niche industry.
</P>
<P>
   They launched their trial balloon in late January, displaying
about 12 cases of merchandise at the annual Professional Golf
Association trade show in Orlando.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea was to see what other people in the golf field really
thought about it,'' Van Beck said. ``If there is anything else like
it in the world of golf, it would be at that show.''
</P>
<P>
   But they didn't see themselves coming and going. And they sold
everything they had brought.
</P>
<P>
   It was there that they met Stefan White, an English collector of
antique golf clubs who agreed to market their tournament in Great
Britain. He also will add his own merchandise to that sold by
Antique Golf Collectibles.
</P>
<P>
   Golf rose in popularity in the early 1900s, fueled by a change
in the materials used in the production of equipment that made
prices more affordable.
</P>
<P>
   ``It suddenly enabled everyone to have a go,'' White said.
</P>
<P>
   At this point, the process of making replicas from molds
acquired over the years by Cuyler operates on a cottage industry
scale. Van Beck said about 30 people, most of them artists, have so
far assembled about 2,600 display cases of resin replicas from
their workshops and homes.
</P>
<P>
   Van Beck makes the rounds, delivering materials and retrieving
finished products that he stores in Sarasota warehouses.
</P>
<P>
   But that method may change as demand increases for the cases,
which cost up to $30,000.
</P>
<P>
   Antique Golf Collectibles markets its three product lines to pro
shops, golf retailers, art galleries, commercial interior designers
and wholesalers.
</P>
<P>
   Van Beck said he has been scouting sites that could handle
increased production volume. But he doesn't know how soon they may
be needed. Geographical factors that favor the Sarasota area
include proximity to overseas shipping facilities in Tampa and
local weather that allows the sport to be played throughout the
year.
</P>
<P>
   Cuyler expects the tournament next year to reap more foreign
contacts. Agreements have already been brokered to host the event
in Japan, Australia, Sweden, France and Great Britain.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the people that we are dealing with in the tournament are
all influential people who can help market our products,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Margaret Ann Miille writes for The Herald-Tribune, Sarasota,
Fla., which is a member of The New York Times Regional Newspaper
Group. This article was distributed by The New York Times News
Service.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
