<SLUG> BC-FLA-SCHOOL-VOUCHERS-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VOUCHER STUDENTS OPTING FOR PUBLIC SCHOOLS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JANET MARSHALL   
 NYT Regional Newspapers   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TALLAHASSEE, Fla. _ The notion of public money being channeled
into private schools is at the heart of the national voucher
debate. But in Pensacola, Florida's voucher testing ground, more
parents are using vouchers to send their children to
higher-performing public schools than to private schools.
</P>
<P>
   The choice doesn't surprise school officials, who figured free
transportation to public schools, plus limited space in private
ones, would keep many children in the district
</P>
<P>
   But while the option may bring comfort to those who feared a
mass exodus from public schools, it also creates some logistical
headaches.
</P>
<P>
   At A.K. Suter Elementary in Tallahassee on Tuesday, principal
Beverly Patteson was struggling with bus schedules. Taking voucher
students home Monday had taken longer than expected, because they
live in parts of town not zoned for the school. The delay kept a
bus driver from picking up high school students, a situation
Patteson doesn't want to repeat.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick Heffernan, a voucher advocate and president of
Floridians for School Choice, hopes the number of people who picked
public over private schools will help shift the voucher debate away
from inflammatory issues of religion and state. Several lawsuits
have been filed in Florida challenging vouchers, arguing in part
that directing public money to private schools is unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   ``What there ought to be is a recognition that this isn't an
issue of private schools vs. public schools,'' Heffernan said.
``The issue has been, for 20 years for me, the issue of who should
decide where a child goes to school.''
</P>
<P>
   About 860 elementary students in Pensacola qualified for
vouchers because their schools, A.A. Dixon and Spencer Bibbs
Advanced Learning Academy, received F grades from the state. The
grades are based primarily on test scores. Of those 860, about 140
left their schools, with about 80 choosing other public schools and
57 enrolling in private ones.
</P>
<P>
   The reasons parents opted for public schools vary.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some because it's close and some because it's a particularly
good school and some because they have had a relative there,'' said
Escambia County School District spokeswoman Barbara Frye. .
</P>
<P>
   Limited space in private schools willing to accept vouchers was
almost certainly a factor. Ninety-two students applied for 58 seats
at area Catholic schools, and those not chosen in a lottery had to
pursue another option. The fifth area private school to accept
vouchers had space for six kids, four of whom enrolled. At the
Catholic schools, 53 students ended up enrolling, said Sister Mary
Caplice of the Congregation of Notre Dame. The other five for whom
seats were available backed out at the last minute.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had an inkling that there would be parents who would choose
to go to higher-performing public schools,'' said Karen Chandler,
spokeswoman for the state Education Department. ``We knew there
would be a mix.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike in public schools, transportation is neither free nor
guaranteed at private ones, though some help with car pools. Just
one of the Catholic schools here provides free or reduced-price
lunches to poor students.
</P>
<P>
   This year, only students at the two failing schools in Pensacola
qualified for vouchers. Statewide, however, 78 schools are now
considered failing. Unless they improve, the voucher program could
grow exponentially. What kind of logistical problems might that
create?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know,'' Frye said. ``Right now, we're dealing with
relatively small numbers. You can make anything work at that
level.''
</P>
<P>
   (Janet Marshall is a reporter in the Tallahassee Bureau of the
New York Times Regional Newspapers. This article was distributed by
The New York Times News Service.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
