<HEADER>
A1984 &Cx1f; ttg-z
a l BC-SWARTZ-COLUMN-$ADV24-     08-18 0796
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWARTZ-COLUMN-$ADV24-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SURVIVING A BAD CASE OF THE CREEPS
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Tuesday, Aug. 24) 
 (nk) 
 By SUSAN SWARTZ   
 Santa Rosa (Calif.) Press Democrat   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the morning when I revealed the Swiss army knife under my
sleeping bag my friends laughed and asked if I'd planned to defend
myself with the corkscrew or the manicure scissors.
</P>
<P>
   By then I could laugh, too. It was a dazzling morning and
someone handed me a cup of coffee and someone else started cooking
breakfast. We had sun and a whole day to eat and read and swim in
the warm green lake. Life was good. The only thing making scratchy
noises in the bushes were lizards. But, you know, sometimes you
just get so scared.
</P>
<P>
   I would like to say you get scared for no good reason but we all
know it's justified. This summer an argument could be made for
never going out into the woods again. And I'm not talking about the
``Blair Witch Project,'' I'm talking about good old American
everyday horror.
</P>
<P>
   At some point between the confession in the Yosemite murders and
after the Atlanta slayings but before the Los Angeles Jewish day
care shootings, I came down with the creeps. I had nightmares. I
was distracted. I'd say things like, ``I'm not a timid person but
...''
</P>
<P>
   It's true that things don't usually bother me, except for scary
movies, like the one mentioned above and which I've already been
warned of. But there was something hanging around that was
bothering more than me. A woman at work said she dreamed about a
serial killer. A friend felt unnerved on her morning walk on
familiar streets. A woman who has lived alone for years spent most
of one night peeking through the curtains at a strange van parked
on the street. A couple planning a week's backpacking in Yosemite
said maybe they'd go to Shasta instead.
</P>
<P>
   I kept telling myself that even Carole Carrington said what
happened to her family was a one-in-a-million thing and that we
can't be afraid to live. But I couldn't shake it.
</P>
<P>
   A friend called to say she about died that day of fear. She was
in her office when she heard a skirmish out by the security desk.
She hit the floor, dialed 911 and looked up to her television,
where at that very moment, CNN was recapping the story of the
Atlanta day trader who killed family members and colleagues.
Fortunately, at my friend's office things were quickly and safely
handled and the troubled visitor was found to be unarmed. Still he
did have a beef with someone in the building and managed to terrify
everyone within earshot.
</P>
<P>
   So, when the all-women campout came up, it didn't seem like the
best timing.
</P>
<P>
   The night before we left for the lake I woke up in my own bed
worried about being worried.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, I had a bad case. No one else in the group was hesitant
about sleeping out. They said things like ``who would dare bother
all of us?'' One of them even brought along a murder mystery.
</P>
<P>
   It was a long night. I didn't sleep much but every time I woke
up in our big tent _ having been granted the spot in the middle _ I
tried to focus on the stars through the window flap and not my
morbid imagination. The next day the crummy fear was gone and when
I floated in that delicious water and stared up at the fuzzy yellow
hills I realized I was on the lookout for deer and not killers. I
had broken through.
</P>
<P>
   It still makes me mad, though, to have been hit so hard with the
creeps. Mad at myself for being such a big baby but also because
all the shrinks and all the experts cannot keep sick people from
running amok. I'm mad at those who say we are a violent country as
if we're supposed to accept it and mad that we have more guns in
this country than common sense.
</P>
<P>
   I'm sick that President Clinton has to go on TV almost weekly to
say his prayers are with the families and victims of another
killing spree. I want him to pray for a way to prevent the next
spree.
</P>
<P>
   Another day three of us were walking on a trail and a man coming
toward us suddenly veered our way and held out his hand. In it was
a bouquet of Queen Anne's Lace and cornflowers. He offered it to
one woman and she hesitated. But then she took it and thanked him
and he walked off and so did we.
</P>
<P>
   She said when she saw the man approaching she noticed he was
swinging a stick. She hadn't seen the flowers in his other hand.
</P>
<P>
   So, the message upon the message is that sometimes when we're
worrying about a stick we get flowers. And while we are never
perfectly safe in the woods or camping or even at work, we are
likely to be imperfectly safe.
</P>
<P>
   (Susan Swartz is a columnist for The Press Democrat in Santa
Rosa, Calif., which is part of the New York Times Regional
Newspaper Group. Her e-mail address is sfswartz(AT)pressdemo.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
