<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRIMES-HUMOR-COLUMN-$ADV20-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`BLAIR WITCH' FICTIONAL FILMMAKERS GET WHAT THEY DESERVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Friday, Aug. 20)  
 (bl)  
 By DAVID GRIMES   
 Herald-Tribune, Sarasota, Fla.)   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   I read in the paper that some real-life witches are offended by
the movie ``The Blair Witch Project'' because it depicts witches in
an unflattering way.
</P>
<P>
   ``It defames us and it makes us less human,'' said Teri Kalgren,
co-founder of the Witches Education Bureau in Salem, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   The film ``both exploits and reinforces negative stereotypes
about witches: that they are evil murderers of children and
adults,'' said Phyllis Curoff, a New York attorney and, needless to
say, a witch.
</P>
<P>
   I can only speak for myself, but I do not think ``The Blair
Witch Project'' does any harm whatsoever to the image of real-life
witches. In fact, if I were a witch, I think I'd be proud.
</P>
<P>
   While it is true that the witch in ``The Blair Witch Project''
appears to kill three young filmmakers who get lost in the woods,
whatever she does to these three jerks is, in my opinion, not a
crime but a public service.
</P>
<P>
   For starters, the filmmakers have about as much business going
on a three-day camping trip in unfamiliar woods as I do assembling
a fission reactor in my backyard tool shed.
</P>
<P>
   These morons do not take more than two or three steps into the
woods before they are hopelessly lost and screaming and cursing at
each other at the top of their lungs.
</P>
<P>
   We're talking about the kind of people who would have trouble
finding the bathroom in their own apartment, let alone reading a
contour map by firelight.
</P>
<P>
   Once they discovered that they were lost, if they had just sat
down on a log and maybe whimpered softly to themselves, it is
likely that someone would have rescued them fairly quickly,
especially given the fact that their car was parked only a few
hundred feet away, probably with the keys locked in it, the lights
on and the engine running.
</P>
<P>
   But no, they start hollering at each other, using the kind of
language normally associated with combat troops and guests on the
Jerry Springer show. Their language is bad enough to scare any
other campers out of the area, or at the very least dissuade them
from offering any assistance. You end up hoping that these
potty-mouths get gored by an enraged deer or, at the very least,
are attacked by a swarm of yellowjackets or Lyme-disease-carrying
ticks.
</P>
<P>
   When they're not stripping the bark off the trees with their
language, these losers are smoking like fiends, sending billowing
clouds of poisonous gas into the atmosphere on a magnitude not seen
since Chernobyl.
</P>
<P>
   You would think with all the smoke being exhaled by these bozos
that they could easily be spotted by a forest ranger peering
through binoculars from atop a fire tower several counties away.
</P>
<P>
   It would have been a nice cinematic touch if these three
nicotine addicts had been blasted with a high-pressure hose or
maybe beaten with shovels or buried under a mound of dirt by
firemen trying to protect the forest, the woodland creatures and
the ears of any sensitive campers and/or witches who happen to be
hanging around the area.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, the directors of ``The Blair Witch Project''
didn't ask me to approve their script beforehand, which could
explain why the fireman scene is missing and also, probably, why
the movie has grossed something like 42 bazillion dollars.
</P>
<P>
   There is nothing in ``The Blair Witch Project'' that a real
witch should find demeaning or offensive. If anything, the Blair
witch comes across as a little too caring and sensitive, as it
waits far too long to send these annoying twits off to that Great
Film School In The Sky.
</P>
<P>
   All I know is that if the Wicked Witch of the West were still
around, these three dopes would have been toast by the end of the
first scene.
</P>
<P>
   (David Grimes is a columnist for The Herald-Tribune, Sarasota,
Fla., which is a member of The New York Times Regional Newspaper
Group. This article was distributed by The New York Times Regional
Newspaper Group.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
