<TEXT>
<P>
   (gm) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Thursday, Aug. 19, Page 1. The NYT frontpage advisory, with layout
description, will move by 7:30 p.m. ET. The NYT News Service Night
Supervisor is Pat Ryan (888-346-9867).
</P>
<P>
   TURKEY-QUAKE (Istanbul, Turkey) _ Hundreds of relief workers
from more than a dozen countries stream into Turkey and immediately
join the frantic search for survivors of Tuesday's devastating
earthquake. Although Turkish and foreign workers rescued many
people from the rubble of collapsed buildings, the death toll
climbs steadily. According to an official count, 3,479 bodies have
been recovered, and more than 16,000 people are listed as seriously
injured. By Stephen Kinzer. 1,300 words.
</P>
<P>
   With:
</P>
<P>
   TURKEY-CENTER (Izmet, Turkey) _ People here spent their day
digging, sifting, grieving and increasingly despairing that those
who have not escaped from the rubble by now are probably dead. They
watched as bulldozers and front-end loaders tried to unearth
bedrooms, which is where most people were when the earthquake
struck. Then in the swirl of dust and smoke and sweltering heat,
residents picked through the rubble with hammers and chisels and
bare hands. As delicately as archaeologists, they teased out shreds
of clothing, old photos, scraps of furniture and, inevitably, the
bodies. By Edmund L. Andrews. 1,200 words.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   METLIFE-SUIT (Undated) _ Metropolitan Life Insurance has agreed
to a $1.7 billion settlement of class-action lawsuits by
policyholders, contending they were deceived by the sales practices
of the company, the nation's second-largest life insurer. (Summary
from wires.) By Barry Meier.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-ARTS (Tokyo) _ Famous art is leaving Japan. Only a handful
of bankers and art dealers know for sure where it is going. The
paintings, including large numbers of van Goghs, Modiglianis,
Renoirs and Picassos that vanished into Japan more than a decade
ago, are being resold abroad as a result of the country's economic
collapse. ``We have already lost so much; we are losing so much
still _ and I don't mean just we Japanese,'' said Shin'ichi Segi,
an art critic who has tried to track the migration of paintings in
and out of Japan with only limited success. ``The trail is going
cold, perhaps forever.'' By Stephanie Strom. 1,700 words.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-ECON (Beijing) _ In a drastic move aimed at reversing a
steady fall in prices, Chinese officials announce that they will
stop all new production of a broad range of ordinary consumer
items. By withholding approval for any new production lines, while
allowing existing output to continue, officials apparently hope
they can shackle China's deflation, which threatens to seriously
undermine economic growth, which is faltering. By Seth Faison.
</P>
<P>
   NY-PAROLE (New York) _ Memos unearthed by the U.S. attorney's
office in its investigation into Gov. George Pataki's fund raising
provide a rare view of the close ties between Pataki administration
officials and aides at the governor's political arm. By Clifford J.
Levy and Laurie Flynn.
</P>
</TEXT>
