<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANADA-WATER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CANADA BACKS MORATORIUM ON SALE OF GREAT LAKES WATER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By COLIN NICKERSON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTREAL _ Signaling its resolve to become the first nation to
outlaw bulk exports of water, Canada Wednesday threw its support
behind a six-month moratorium on the large-scale removal and sale
of water from the Great Lakes.
</P>
<P>
   Canada also suggested it will enact laws this fall to keep its
wealth of water out of foreign hands, a move seemingly directed
against the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The goal, said Foreign Minister Lloyd Axworthy, ``is to protect
all of our water against removals.'' Such a ban could have
long-term consequences for the United States, where agribusiness
and other heavy consumers of water see Canada as the potential
savior in an increasingly dry future.
</P>
<P>
   The six-month moratorium was urged by the International Joint
Commission, the US-Canada agency that regulates the Great Lakes. In
a report released Wednesday, the commission declared there is ``no
surplus water'' in the five lakes, which constitute the world's
largest renewable supply of fresh water.
</P>
<P>
   The Joint Commission hinted that next year it may call for far
more sweeping protections for Great Lakes water. But Canada does
not want to wait, and is scrambling to enact federal legislation to
ban bulk exports of water from its lakes, rivers, underground
reservoirs, and Arctic ice fields, including its portions of the
Great Lakes.
</P>
<P>
   Although not directly related, the moratorium and the report
from the joint commission were released as a drought has stricken
much of the eastern United States and Canada, a natural calamity
that points to the vulnerability of even the most water-rich
nations.
</P>
<P>
   Canada's immediate and strong support for the moratorium showed
Ottawa's determination not to allow the country, which holds
one-fifth of the world's fresh water supply, to become a giant
reservoir for the parched farmlands of the United States or the
arid nations of Africa, Asia, and the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
   ``Canadians must work together to protect our watersheds and
ensure the preservation of fresh water supplies for future
generations,'' Environment Minister David Anderson said at a news
conference.
</P>
<P>
   Canada's aggressively anti-export stance on water represents a
surprising departure for a nation that has depended on the
exploitation of oil, ores, and other nonrenewable resources for
much of its wealth.
</P>
<P>
   The nation possesses far more fresh water than its relatively
small population could conceivably ever use. On a per capita basis,
Canada boasts 11 times as much renewable fresh water as the United
States, and quantities of water locked in ice fields or far
underground are even vaster.
</P>
<P>
   But strong public opposition to the idea of bulk water exports
suggest that Canadians are deeply fearful their nation will one day
be coerced into watering the farms of the American Southwest or
slaking the huge thirst of the Third World.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once you turn on the tap, there's no turning it off,'' said
Maude Barlow, chairwoman of the Council of Canadians, a nationalist
organization that has warned that the United States will seek to
use the North American Free Trade Agreement to force open the
Canadian floodgates.
</P>
<P>
   Many analysts, including economists of the World Bank, predict
that water will become the most precious resource of the 21st
Century, and a cause of wars, political tensions, and
megabillion-dollar deals.
</P>
<P>
   Already, American companies have sought to haul off supertanker
loads of water from Ontario and British Columbia, although the
deals have been blocked by last-minute intervention by Ottawa and
provincial governments.
</P>
<P>
   The United States, although rich in water in its own right,
suffers from serious shortages in key agricultural zones, such as
the Southwest. Since the 1950s there have schemes to divert
Canadian rivers and even entire watersheds to irrigate farmlands
from Colorado to California.
</P>
<P>
   As American water tables drop under rising urban and
agricultural demand, those schemes seem less harebrained and more
visionary. North of the border, realization that the nation's water
trove could be diverted to the United States has put the scare into
Canadian lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   Axworthy Wednesday suggested that the proposed ban on bulk
removals from the Great Lakes sought by the International Joint
Commission does not go far enough since since exporters might be
allowed to draw off water to meet emergencies, such as a severe
drought.
</P>
<P>
   ``The conditions outlined may be too permissive,'' Axworthy
said.
</P>
<P>
   The concern in Canada is that water might eventually be defined
as a ``commodity'' or ``good'' under US-Canada trade agreements.
This could allow the United States to force Canada to open its
lakes and rivers to exporters.
</P>
<P>
   In any event, controlling Canada's water reserves will not be as
simple as passing a federal law. Although Ottawa has say over
waters shared with the United States, such as the Great Lakes, most
water rights belong to the provinces. Some, like Ontario and
British Columbia, seem receptive to a ban on bulk exports.
</P>
<P>
   Impoverished Newfoundland, on the other hand, sees a potential
bonanza in its thousands of untapped lakes, and may soon give the
go-ahead to a plan by homegrown entrepreneurs to export supertanker
loads of water to the Mideast.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
