<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990818.0251 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-18 18:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1999 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-JFKJR-MEMORABILIA19-C     08-18 0965
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JFKJR-MEMORABILIA19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    eBay a hit for Kennedy memorabilia
 &HT;    By Jill Inkrott
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ On July 16, John F. Kennedy, Jr.'s Piper Saratoga
plane plunged into the ocean.
</P>
<P>
   On July 20, at 11:42 a.m., an unspecified issue of George, the
magazine Kennedy founded, was sold on Internet auction site eBay
for $86.
</P>
<P>
   Even before Kennedy was buried at sea July 23, Americans'
unabashed affection for memorabilia and buying had blossomed anew
on the 24-hour flea market called eBay. JFK Jr.-related items, some
tacky, some tasteless, some worth saving, flowed onto the auction
list.
</P>
<P>
   And people are buying.
</P>
<P>
   More than 2,000 items have already closed for bidding and 500 or
so continue to be up for grabs. At Amazon.com, about 120 JFK Jr.
items are on the block.
</P>
<P>
   While most articles have been issues of George or other
magazines featuring Kennedy, the selection has ranged from snow
globes, memorial T-shirts and beanbag bears to autographed dollar
bills, Web site domains and a receipt for Christmas lights
purchased at FAO Schwarz in 1961 by ``Mrs. John Kennedy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If I decide I really want something, price doesn't matter to
me,'' said Heidi Braatz of Dublin, Ohio, who bid on the memorial
beanbag bears because she collects them and is interested in the
Kennedy family.
</P>
<P>
   An autographed dollar bill went for $418.88, one of many
lithographs of his famous salute for $127.50, memorial T-shirts for
as much as $21.50. And Aug. 8, someone bid $10,000 for a letter
that Kennedy hand-wrote and signed in 1985 to a Mr. Friedersdorf,
assistant to the president for legal affairs, thanking him for
arranging a White House visit so Kennedy could invite Ronald Reagan
to a Kennedy Library fund-raiser.
</P>
<P>
   ``The letter itself is a piece of history,'' said Philip Chen of
Berkeley, Calif., who bid but did not win it. ``And JFK Jr. himself
is another piece of history.''
</P>
<P>
   George Lesko, who runs a video news-clipping service in
Pittsburgh, Pa., wanted to own a piece of that history for
investment. He paid $510 for an autographed photograph of Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am very unhappy because I have gotten e-mails offering
everything from signed golf balls to baseballs to photos for much
less ... I wonder what these are worth,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   According to appraiser Claudia Miller, an accredited and senior
member of the American Society of Appraisers, the photograph should
increase in value, depending upon the market, amount of related
memorabilia available, authenticity and condition of the item. She
thought $10,000 ``a bit pricey'' for the letter, however, she said
that the bears, of which Beverly Hills Plush has produced 25,000
sets of two, were a ``rip-off'' as a collectible item.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no such thing as a limited edition these days,'' said
Miller.
</P>
<P>
   Some bidders, like Amy Alsbury, are baby boomers who lived
``through the fascination and assassination eras of John Kennedy.''
Others are twenty-somethings simply interested in the Kennedy
legacy.
</P>
<P>
   Tina Kelly of West Chester, Ohio, bought the bears for her young
daughter ``so later when she is older she would have them to help
join past with present.''
</P>
<P>
   Numerous bidders, though, examined their conscience before
bidding on any items.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do believe that a person should be allowed to rest in peace
for a respectful amount of time before others try to make money off
their untimely passing,'' said Kelly Ann de los Santos of Del Rio,
Texas. ``I don't know what that would be, although certainly longer
than has been seen of late.''
</P>
<P>
   Anthony Roberts, owner of Iowa-based A.A.C.S. Autographs, which
began selling autographed photographs on Aug. 5, said that his
company did sufficiently wait.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got these photos from the forensic authenticators a day or
so before Kennedy's tragic death. We chose to wait a significant
amount of time before posting the items on eBay out of respect for
the Kennedy family,'' Roberts said.
</P>
<P>
   Bidders, though, have come to expect a sale immediately after a
celebrity death.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it had been a saltwater aquarium with broken pieces of
plastic plane in it _ that would have been in really bad taste and
I would have never have placed a bid on that,'' said Bill Whitaker
of Colebrook, N.H.
</P>
<P>
   Local antique and collectible dealers are not carrying JFK Jr.
items, but bookstores have felt the crunch as consumers flocked to
buy magazines and books.
</P>
<P>
   ``George was never a good seller,'' said the manager of Dicken's
Book Shop in Lebanon, who did not wish to give her name. ``But they
flew off the shelves after he died.''
</P>
<P>
   Ray Saunders, a salesman at Barnes &AMP; Noble Booksellers, said
that a number of people have come in requesting Kennedy books and
magazines, forcing the store to order more to meet demand.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think people are curious about who he was,'' Saunders said.
``And they're thinking that sometime in the future the items will
be collectibles.''
</P>
<P>
   Some consumers are showing restraint. Asking prices have
consistently decreased. At the end of July, sellers began bidding
at around $20 for a single issue featuring Kennedy. The average has
since dropped to around $5.
</P>
<P>
   But people are still buying JFK Sr. memorabilia today. Five
hundred items relating to the assassinated president are available
on eBay, and Beverly Hills Plush has issued commemorative beanbag
bears for Robert Kennedy as well. There are about 150 Richard
Nixon-related items available on the 25th anniversary of his
resignation, although that pales in comparison with Marilyn Monroe,
who has about 1,700 collectibles available on eBay.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mother still collects anything Elvis,'' said Jennifer
Hanson, of Scottsdale, Ariz.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-18-99 1838EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
