<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-18 18:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2002 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-AMIRAULT-OVERTURN-BOS     08-18 1100
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMIRAULT-OVERTURN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONVICTED CHILD ABUSER'S BID FOR NEW TRIAL THWARTED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SACHA PFEIFFER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Ending a 15-year legal odyssey that fueled a national
debate about the reliability of child testimony, the state's
highest court Wednesday overturned a judge's decision granting a
new trial to Cheryl Amirault LeFave, who was convicted in 1987 of
sexually abusing children at her family's day care center.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling by the Supreme Judicial Court means that LeFave,
whose controversial conviction was reversed last year, will almost
certainly be returning to prison in a month.
</P>
<P>
   James Sultan, LeFave's defense attorney, said LeFave will no
longer seek relief in state courts. He said he and LeFave will
decide in the next month whether to begin a federal court appeal of
her conviction or to seek clemency from Governor Paul Cellucci.
</P>
<P>
   But Middlesex District Attorney Martha Coakley said she expects
LeFave to be returned to prison to resume her 8- to 20-year
sentence when the SJC decision formally takes effect in 28 days.
And a Cellucci spokesman said the governor is likely to defer to
the decision of the SJC.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will continue my fight from behind the wall,'' said LeFave,
41, who has been free since 1995 when her conviction was first
overturned in another lower court ruling also vacated by the SJC.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am outraged to think I have to go to prison,'' she said at a
press conference after learning of the SJC decision while she
worked at a local insurance company.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm hurt. I'm very hurt,'' said LeFave, her voice trembling.
</P>
<P>
   Sultan remarked that ``only in Massachusetts, the home of the
Salem witch trials and Sacco and Vanzetti, are the verdicts allowed
to stand.
</P>
<P>
   ``Go away! That's essentially the message the SJC has given us.
But we're not going away. We're going elsewhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Sultan said he will have to decide whether to quickly put
together a federal appeal in hopes of keeping LeFave out of jail or
to spend time fashioning a more organized filing even if LeFave
must spend time in prison in the meantime.
</P>
<P>
   The high court's decision Wednesday also throws into doubt the
future of Gerald ``Tooky'' Amirault, 45, LeFave's brother, who was
convicted in a separate trial in 1986 and remains incarcerated.
</P>
<P>
   Attorneys for LeFave had argued that she was entitled to a new
trial on two grounds: inadequate legal counsel by her former
attorneys, and ``newly discovered evidence'' indicating that
preschool children can make up and believe stories suggested to
them through overly aggressive questioning by investigators.
</P>
<P>
   Their arguments won the support of Superior Court Judge Isaac
Borenstein, who granted LeFave a new trial in June 1998. In his
stinging, 140-page ruling, Borenstein labled as ``incredible''
testimony by child witnesses that described talking robots, public
torture of animals, and being tied naked to a tree in front of the
school.
</P>
<P>
   But in Wednesday's unanimous decision, the high court ruled that
Amirault's previous lawyers had not caused her to suffer ``a
substantial risk of miscarriage of justice,'' and that so-called
new evidence was ``not remarkably different from that presented by
or available to the defendant at trial.''
</P>
<P>
   As a result, concluded Chief Justice Herbert P. Wilkins, who
authored the 19-page decision, LeFave's ``allegedly new evidence
lacks the characteristics necessary to qualify as newly discovered
evidence that could warrant granting a new trial.''
</P>
<P>
   Coakley, whose office prosecuted the case, applauded the high
court's ruling.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today's decision vindicates all of the children who testified
to devastating abuses suffered at the Fells Acres Day School,''
Coakley said in a statement. ``It is our hope that those victims --
many of whom watched in silence while the defendants pursued appeal
after appeal -- will now be able to put their terrible ordeal
behind them.''
</P>
<P>
   Contacted Wednesday, the parents of several of the victims, many
now in their 20s, declined to comment. But one mother, speaking
anonymously, said she was relieved the long-running case seems to
have come to a close.
</P>
<P>
   ``These child were sexually abused, and there are no ifs ands or
buts about that in my mind or the minds of any of the people who
were involved,'' she said. ``Justice should have been served a long
time ago, and hopefully it will be now.''
</P>
<P>
   The Amirault family was thrust into the public eye in 1984, when
Violet Amirault, her son Gerald, and her daughter, Cheryl, were
charged with raping and assaulting children at Fells Acres, their
family-run day care center in suburban Malden.
</P>
<P>
   Gerald Amirault was convicted in 1986 and sentenced to 30 to 40
years; his mother and sister were found guilty the following year
and sent away for 8 to 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   Gerald Amirault has since lost three appeals of his conviction,
once in Middlesex Superior Court and twice before the Supreme
Judicial Court. Violet Amirault and LeFave had also lost several
appeals until last year, when Borenstein ordered a new trial.
</P>
<P>
   In his highly critical decision, Borenstein wrote that
investigators were out to get the Amiraults from the beginning, and
he faulted interviewers for using overly suggestive techniques with
the toddler-aged child witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   His criticism was echoed by the Amirault's supporters, who
branded the investigation a ``witch hunt'' and accused prosecutors
of ignoring medical evidence, or lack thereof, in the face of
public hysteria over similar alleged multiple-victim child abuse
cases nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   In his 140-page ruling, Borenstein wrote that physicial evidence
of abuse by LaFave was at best inconclusive, and almost
nonexistent, and that the children's testimony had been ``forever
tainted'' by repetitive and leading questioning techniques by
investigators.
</P>
<P>
   But the high court said Wednesday that Borenstein's assertion
that there was no evidence to support the children's testimony
``discounts the child witnesses' symptoms that were consistent with
sexual abuse and the corroborating testimony of the children's
parents.''
</P>
<P>
   LeFave and her mother had been granted a new trial in 1995 by
Superior Court Judge Robert Barton, who ruled that their rights to
confront their accusers had been violated by a special courtroom
seating arrangement for the child witnesses. But the SJC vacated
that ruling.
</P>
<P>
   LeFave and her mother continued to stay out of prison while
subsequent appeals where heard.
</P>
<P>
   Violet Amirault died of cancer at age 74 in September 1997.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
