<HEADER>
A2004 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a BC-EDUCATION-TEXAS-HNS &LR;      08-18 0896
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDUCATION-TEXAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH PICKS LAWYER TO OVERSEE TEXAS' PUBLIC SCHOOLS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By KATHY WALT 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Gov. George W. Bush named as commissioner of
public education Wednesday an Odessa lawyer who promised to ``stay
the course'' on tough education standards but who doesn't know
where he stands on private school vouchers.
</P>
<P>
   Bush named James E. Nelson to oversee Texas' public schools,
which educate 3.9 &UR;  &LR; million students. He succeeds Mike Moses, who is
leaving to take a post at Texas Tech University in Lubbock.
</P>
<P>
   In his new role, Nelson will head up the Texas Education Agency,
which sets standards for the state's more than 1,000 school
districts. The new commissioner will be entering territory that at
times was like a mine field for his predecessor _ particularly when
it came to dealing with the State Board of Education.
</P>
<P>
   During his four years as commissioner, Moses was caught in
battles between social conservatives and the liberal and moderate
factions on the board _ especially when it came to adopting
curriculum standards, investment policies, textbook adoptions and
basic skills testing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm an open person,'' Nelson said in response to questions
about how he will deal with the dynamics on the state board. ``I
don't keep secrets. I don't have an agenda other than what's up
front.''
</P>
<P>
   Although a number of career educators had been in the running
for the post, Bush said he picked the 49-year-old father of three
because he wanted ``an educational entrepreneur.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I was looking for someone ... willing to challenge the status
quo,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   Since March 196 Nelson has chaired the State Board for Educator
Certification. Bush appointed Nelson to this citizen-advisory
committee, which is charged with establishing credentials for
teachers, licensing them and holding colleges and universities to
teacher-preparation standards. He also is a past president of the
Ector County School Board and the Texas Association of School
Boards.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jim Nelson is committed to local control of schools, he
believes in setting high standards, and he believes in holding
school districts accountable for results,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson in turn praised Bush and Moses, saying that the reading
initiative they spearheaded ``will leave a legacy that you can be
proud of all of your life, and I think it will be a legacy that any
governor in this country would be proud to have.''
</P>
<P>
   Referring to Moses, Nelson said, ``If I can be half the
commissioner that he has has been during my time, then I know I
will be successful.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I have every intention of staying the course,'' he said.
``What has been accomplished over the (past) 4 1/2 years needs to
continue.''
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, he referred to raising standards and emphasizing
local control, adding, ``I know that the people in Austin don't
have all the answers.''
</P>
<P>
   On two controversial education issues _ charter schools and
tax-funded vouchers for private education _ Nelson indicated
different levels of commitment, at least at this point.
</P>
<P>
   He said he supports expanding the number of publicly funded
charter schools, which Bush has touted as one way of providing
parents with an option for their children's education, despite
serious problems a few charter schools are experiencing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know there have been problems with a very small number of
the charter schools,'' he said. ``You need to give parents
choices.''
</P>
<P>
   But on the subject of vouchers _ which Bush has endorsed as a
way of providing more options for parents of children in failing
schools _ Nelson said he does not know whether they would hurt
public schools. Voucher legislation has failed in the last three
legislative sessions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure,'' he said. ``I would have to think long and
hard, but I don't think it's something the commissioner of
education is going to have to spend a lot of time worrying about.
I'm not going to be the commissioner of voucher schools, I'm going
to be the commissioner of public schools.''
</P>
<P>
   He also said his job as chief of the public school system would
be to see to it that voucher proponents have very few
low-performing schools from which to lure students away. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Nelson's appointment is subject to confirmation of the Texas
Senate, which does not meet again until 2001. He said he hopes to
be on the job shortly after Labor Day but must close down his legal
practice in Odessa first. Moses' last day on the job is Sept. 3.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's choice for education commissioner was met with mixed
enthusiasm from a number of statewide education groups.
</P>
<P>
   Doug Rogers, executive director of the Association of Texas
Professional Educators, said that group is prepared to work with
Nelson but had hoped that the governor would appoint ``someone with
classroom experience.''
</P>
<P>
   The Texas State Teachers Association praised Bush's selection.
``We are comfortable with Commissioner Nelson's leadership style
and have enjoyed a cordial and professional relationship with him
during his tenure as head of the (teacher certification board),''
said TSTA president Ignacio Salinas.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas Classroom Teachers Association said Nelson is familiar
with education policy and is ``fair-minded and very open to
listening to a variety of perspectives.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
