<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-18 18:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2008 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-TURKEY-SCENE-ART-650&AMP;     08-18 1214
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TURKEY-SCENE-ART-650&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN TURKEY, A STRUGGLE TO SURVIVE IN A DEVASTATED LANDSCAPE 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also TURKEY-QUAKE, TURKEY-CENTER.) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 1-888-603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(th) 
 By EDMUND L. ANDREWS    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   IZMIT, Turkey _ Engulfed in the darkness of collapsed concrete
early Tuesday morning, Nuray Yildiz heard people screaming her name
but could not answer with more than gasps.
</P>
<P>
   Gulping fresh air from a small pathway through the debris, the
14-year-old spent the next twelve hours clawing her way out while
her parents and neighbors tried to dig their way in without
accidentally killing her.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had thought, I cannot die but I am waiting to die,'' the
brown-haired teen-ager recalled Wednesday. ``When I realized I
could breathe, I knew I wasn't completely underground and had a way
out.''
</P>
<P>
   Nuray's 10-year-old brother, Omer, never did find a way out. Nor
did her aunt in the room next door. Nor did at least a thousand
others who died in this gritty industrial city near the epicenter
of Turkey's most brutal earthquake on record.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, as the quake's death toll across Turkey climbed,
people here spent their day digging, sifting, grieving and
increasingly despairing that those who had not escaped from the
rubble were probably dead.
</P>
<P>
   They watched as bulldozers and front-end loaders tried to
unearth bedrooms, which is where most people were when the
earthquake struck before dawn on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Then, amid dust and smoke and sweltering heat, residents picked
through the rubble with hammers and chisels and bare hands. As
delicately as if they were on an archaeological dig, they teased
out shreds of clothing, old photos, scraps of furniture and,
inevitably, bodies.
</P>
<P>
   There was no shortage of heroes or valiant efforts. But there
was a desperate shortage of equipment and rescue workers, who were
stretched over thousands of individual catastrophes spread over
hundreds of square miles.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, for all the good will, Izmit remained wildly out of
control Wednesday. Soldiers and relief workers were all but
invisible at many of the worst sites. And just a few minutes' walk
from where Nuray and her family had pitched a tent of scrap wood
and carpets, Turkey's biggest oil refinery continued to burn
uncontrollably and spew vast clouds of black smoke for the second
full day.
</P>
<P>
   The closer one traveled to Izmit itself, the more pervasive the
destruction. Here, minarets on many local mosques looked like twigs
snapped in the wind. Along Highway E-5 through the center of town,
buildings on almost every block had been either flattened or ripped
open as if a hurricane had swept through. Many leaned more steeply
than the Tower of Pisa.
</P>
<P>
   Men and women tended to divide their labor. Women congregated in
improvised camp sites, caring for children. Men stayed near the
piles of rubble, heaving aside rock and searching for bodies.
</P>
<P>
   Typically, the bulldozers and other heavy construction equipment
would lift off ceilings and carve a path through to where the
bedrooms were supposed to be. Neighborhood men and boys then did
the more delicate job of sifting for bodies and personal
belongings.
</P>
<P>
   But there weren't nearly enough government bulldozers, and it
was not until 2:10 p.m. Wednesday afternoon that one even turned up
on the street where Hakki Ercan grieved over the multiple deaths in
his family.
</P>
<P>
   Ercan, 64, had managed to persuade a private construction
company to lend its bulldozer for the five-story apartment building
owned by a relative.
</P>
<P>
   But by Wednesday afternoon, he was coping with death from two
forms of collapse. The first came when his daughter-in-law was
crushed under under four stories of concrete. The second was when
his son, who had been pulled out by neighbors and taken off in an
ambulance, found out his wife was dead. Ercan's son suffered a
heart attack and died shortly after he arrived at the hospital.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the worst tragedy I have ever seen in my life,'' said
Ercan, a burly gray-haired man. Casting aside Turkish male
stoicism, he wept.
</P>
<P>
   Yumus, Ercan's 16-year-old nephew, added: ``We felt death, and
I'm still feeling death. I just want to get out of this hell.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   But there was no leaving. Atmis Euler Mahalles spent hours
Wednesday afternoon gingerly chipping away at the building next to
the Ercans'.
</P>
<P>
   The task was both dangerous and horrifying. The sea-blue,
five-story building had split in two, with the top two stories of
the right side plunging straight down to ground level while the
left side remained bizarrely normal.
</P>
<P>
   Still buried in the rubble was an eight-year-old girl. Mahalles,
a friend of the girl's family, stooped below a crumbling concrete
precipice that jutted out from what had been the third-floor
balcony but was now just five feet off the ground.
</P>
<P>
   Using hammer, chisel and metal-cutters to snap the mangled steel
reinforcements, Mahalles poked and scraped beneath the precipice in
a painstaking effort to reach inside. A blue-and-green highchair
lay crunched in the rubble.
</P>
<P>
   Under a shared tent just across the road from the garish
yellow-and-green facade of an Aktuel supermarket, mothers,
grandmothers and children huddled with Nuray Yildiz, angry at their
helplessness.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why do you even bother writing pointlessly in your notebook?''
erupted Hatice Hasan, a mother in her 30s, as a reporter
approached. ``What we need is help! We need food and medicine.''
</P>
<P>
   Like everyone else under the tent, neither Mrs. Hasan nor her
8-year-old son Huseyin had eaten anything all day. Like them, she
had no money, no home and no possessions. And like them, she had
yet to see a social worker or government official since the
earthquake occurred.
</P>
<P>
   But unlike the others, Mrs. Hasan had yet another imperative:
her son Huseyin has leukemia, needed blood and was weakening
quickly. No one had a car to drive them to their pediatric hospital
in Istanbul.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why aren't the Americans doing anything?'' she lashed out in a
rage. ``Where is the government? They haven't done one thing for
us!''
</P>
<P>
   Then she dissolved in tears, quickly followed by the other
women.
</P>
<P>
   Lurking just a short distance behind the women was yet another
menacing problem and perhaps the most dramatic sign of how
overwhelmed the Turkish government was Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Down a short road behind the supermarket lay the huge refinery
owned by Turkey's state-owned Tupla oil company. It had burst into
flames shortly after the earthquake hit Tuesday morning and been
throwing up plumes of smoke as high as 200 feet.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday afternoon, Turkish officials insisted they had the
fire extinguished. In reality, the fire was still going strong and
the refinery site had been almost entirely abandoned.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, military airplanes doused the site with water
sporadically during the morning and early afternoon as government
officials waited for more powerful fire-fighting equipment from
France and Germany.
</P>
<P>
   But around 4 p.m., the refinery erupted in a spectacular new
blaze that was visible from miles away and at midnight it was still
raging.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
