<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-18 19:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2019 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-RUSSIA-DAGESTAN-BOS &LR;      08-18 1692
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-DAGESTAN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIFFICULT TERRAIN EXPECTED TO PROLONG DAGESTAN ACTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DMITRY SHALGANOV AND DAVID FILIPOV  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOTLIKH, Russia _ From a trench on a hill overlooking the front
lines in Dagestan, the new Russian commander-in-chief, Colonel
General Viktor Kazantsev, gestured at the surrounding mountains
that have become both his best ally and his greatest enemy.
</P>
<P>
   After 12 days of heavy aerial and artillery bombardment of
positions held by Islamic rebels, Russian troops have fought their
way to the commanding heights overlooking Botlikh, the center of
the battle with some 2,000 militants.
</P>
<P>
   But once the troops get up there, they see that the rebels have
many more places to hide in the caves and craggy slopes in this
barren Caucasus frontier land. And they see that there are even
more mountains to conquer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like trying to find 124 needles in 10 haystacks, and you
don't have a magnet, and the needles can kill you,'' said a
grim-face Russian soldier, peering through the sights of his
Kalashnikov assault rifle from his post on one of the hills.
</P>
<P>
   Russian leaders in Moscow say they will crush the rebels and
wrap up the fighting within a week. But nothing about the fighting
around Botlikh indicates a quick and easy end to the conflict. It
is the greatest challenge to Russia's authority over this southern
region since federal troops fought a bloody and disastrous
1994-1996 war against separatists in neighboring Chechnya, some of
whom now lead the Dagestan rebels.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, the Russian military said they had lost eight dead
and 20 wounded in heavy fighting around Tando, a rebel-held village
several miles north of Botlikh. The rebels reported light losses,
but said more than 60 Russian soldiers were killed. Neither figure
could be independently confirmed, but the village was still in
rebel hands at nightfall.
</P>
<P>
   Government troops backed by jets and helicopter gunships also
claimed control of the Kharami mountain pass on the border between
Dagestan and Chechnya, which has served as an important
infiltration route for the rebels, according to the Russian
Interior Ministry.
</P>
<P>
   Russian troops around Botlikh said their units had suffered a
number of casualties that the military had yet to admit. Many of
these men were still trapped in areas close to the fighting.
</P>
<P>
   Even as General Kazantsev insisted Wednesday that the
surrounding villages would be freed ``in a matter of days,'' a
helicopter flew in to an improvised airfield _ avoiding the better
but more vulnerable aerodrome where rebels shot down three federal
helicopters last week _ to carry away more wounded.
</P>
<P>
   The Russians say the rebels, who invaded Dagestan from Chechnya
on Aug. 7 and proclaimed an independent Islamic state, are trapped.
Russia's Interior Ministry says a large force of up to 2,000
insurgents are surrounded in the villages around Botlikh, Ansalta,
Rakhata and Tando.
</P>
<P>
   Pro-Moscow Dagestan police and volunteer forces say another
force of up to 2,000 men is trying to cross into Dagestan from
Chechnya at the border village of Andi, near the Kharami pass.
Russian spokesmen speak of hundreds of rebel casualties and tell of
radio intercepts that reflect dissension and panic among the
rebels.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the rebel's supreme commander, Shamil Basayev, put
his troops on alert in preparation for the next stage of his
assault on Dagestan. Stage two, code named ``Imam Gamzat Bek,'' is
believed by the Russian military to involve an attack on two major
cities on Dagestan's lowland border with Chechnya, Kizlyar and
Khasavyurt.
</P>
<P>
   In Moscow, the prospect of a new Chechen attack is a source of
dread. Military analysts express amazement at how easily the rebels
crossed into Dagestan, and how slowly the Russian military reacted.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we are observing in Dagestan gives us no reason to
believe in the quick victory our military leaders are talking
about,'' commented Alexander Golts, a military analyst for the
magazine Itogi. ``They've learned nothing from the shame of
Chechnya.''
</P>
<P>
   The Kremlin has admitted its displeasure by replacing Interior
Ministry Colonel General Vyacheslav Ovchinnikov with an army
general, Kazantsev, as its commander in the campaign. Russian
military sources said that Ovchinnikov was ``unprepared'' for
mountain warfare and had trouble ``organizing troops.''
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, Russian Defense Minister Igor Sergeyev arrived in
Dagestan to oversee the campaign. While Sergeyev expressed
confidence that the battle would be over soon, the Dagestanis are
becoming restless.
</P>
<P>
   They fear that war could spread to the breakaway republic of
Chechnya next door, which declared a state of emergency after
Russian forces launched air strikes last week on the Chechen side
of the border.
</P>
<P>
   ``When are we going to admit that this is a full-scale war?,'' a
Dagestani official, Gadzhi Makhachev, told a meeting of military
leaders that was shown on Russian television. Makhachev, who wore
combat fatigues, said 25,000 Dagestanis had volunteered to fight
the rebels but lacked proper armament.
</P>
<P>
   ``Give us cannons, mortars, helicopters, everything that the
enemy has,'' Makhachev said.
</P>
<P>
   The volunteers have been a big surprise for Chechen-led rebels,
who were most likely hoping for at least some popular support for
their self-proclaimed indepedent Islamic republic from the mainly
Muslim Dagestanis.
</P>
<P>
   According to Russian military sources, a Jordanian-born rebel
commander who goes by the name Khattab, whose wife is from
Dagestan, had guessed that there would be no problem winning over
the population of this impoverished and disaffected region. No
doubt Khattab counted on the fact that Dagestan, a fragile
patchwork of 40 ethnic groups, is a land rife with internal
tensions.
</P>
<P>
   But Dagestanis, despite voicing displeasure with the way that
Moscow ignores their plight, are showing themselves even less
willing to come under the thumb of their Moslem neighbors, the
Chechens.
</P>
<P>
   ``And besides, how can these people be Muslims, if they bring
violence to other Muslims?,'' said Mogamed Debirov, a Botlikh
resident manning a makeshift checkpoint on a hill overlooking town.
Debirov's men have 20 rifles supplied by the federal troops, but no
bullets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone is ready to fight but we have no weapons,'' said
Muradis Guseinov, 34, a Botlikh resident who served as a
paratrooper the Soviet military in Afghanistan. Young, unemployed,
and with few prospects for a better life in this impoverished
mountain village, Guseinov knows he is just the kind of man the the
insurgents would like to recruit.
</P>
<P>
   ``They probably thought that they would get support here,'' he
said. ``They were very wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dagestanis have already helped the federal troops. As well
as the rebels prepared for their offensive _ Russian intelligence
and Dagestani police now say they knew of the militants' plans to
invade months ago _ the locals know the rugged, roadless terrain
even better. With Dagestanis' help, Russian police said Sunday they
were able to locate a group of rebels hiding in a cave on a
mountain known as the ``Wasp's Ear.'' Federal forces bombarded the
rocks above the cave, trapping and killing everyone inside, they
said.
</P>
<P>
   The Dagestanis have also given the Russians permission to
bombard their towns to drive out the rebels, removing a potential
source of tension that was always present in the Chechnya conflict.
There, federal troops turned even loyal Chechens into rebels with
their brutal and indiscriminate bombing. Here, the Russians have
tried to be cautious, refusing to attack towns where the rebels are
holed up among Dagestani civilians.
</P>
<P>
   One of these towns is Ansalta, where Imzat Muslimova, 28,
stepped outside her modest farmhouse Aug. 7 to find dozens of
well-armed men in combat fatigues waiting in her courtyard _ the
Islamic militants led by Basayev and Khattab. ``Imam Gazi
Magomed,'' the first stage of Basayev's plan, had begun.
</P>
<P>
   ``They came in while we were asleep, they didn't wake people up,
they just sat in the yard, a few of them in every yard,'' said
Muslimova last week in the region's capital, Makhachkala. She is
among the 10,000 Dagestanis who have fled the fighting. ``They took
away the policemen's guns _ there were just four boys in the
precinct, what could they do? They said `We are of Islam, we won't
do anything bad to you, we are against Russia, we want Islamic
rule.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Muslimova said the men of her village were still there, virtual
human shields for the rebels. Prevented from attacking the village,
Russian warplanes has launched dozens of raids in the surrounding
mountains to strike rebels whenever they try to move.
</P>
<P>
   The accuracy of those sorties has been in question from the
outset, when a Russian jet mistakenly bombed the village of Omala
in the former Soviet republic of Georgia, wounding three residents.
Russia at first denied the bombing, but Wednesday the foreign
ministry issued an apology to Georgia and offered compensation for
the Aug. 9 incident.
</P>
<P>
   Russian police have issued daily reports saying Khattab, the
Jordian-born field commander of the rebels, had been badly wounded.
But reporters who saw Khattab Monday said the burly commander only
had a bandage around his right hand.
</P>
<P>
   Russian officials have charged that many of the rebels are
foreign mercenaries who are funded by unnamed ``Islamic states.''
But reporters who have visited rebel bases say their fighters
include mainly young men from Chechnya, Dagestan and other parts of
the predominantly Muslim Caucasus Mountains.
</P>
<P>
   And while the Russians' sheer superiority in firepower and men
seems to point to a sure victory, the only sure thing in Botlikh
this week was the way that the helicopters continued to land,
flying in ammunition and flying out casualties.
</P>
<P>
   All the while they avoided the airfield where the tail of one of
the downed helicopters protruded from the wreckage, its rotor
whirling in the gust like a weathervane.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Shalganov reported from Botlikh, Filipov wrote and reported from
Moscow.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
