<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-18 19:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2020 &Cx1f; tta-z
u e BC-JAPAN-ARTS-2TAKES(TRI     08-18 1134
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-ARTS-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ART TREASURES BOUGHT BY JAPANESE IN BETTER TIMES NOW QUIETLY RESOLD
ABROAD 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By STEPHANIE STROM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ With the stealth of a cat burglar, famous art is leaving
Japan. Only a handful of bankers and art dealers know for sure
where it is going, and they are not talking.
</P>
<P>
   The paintings, including large numbers of van Goghs,
Modiglianis, Renoirs and Picassos that vanished into Japan more
than a decade ago, are being resold abroad as a result of Japan's
economic problems. The paintings' whereabouts are now becoming even
greater mysteries.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have already lost so much; we are losing so much still _
and I don't mean just we Japanese,'' said Shin'ichi Segi, an art
critic who has tried to track the migration of paintings in and out
of Japan with only limited success. ``The trail is going cold,
perhaps forever.''
</P>
<P>
   Official trade figures show that from 1987 through 1991, the
Japanese spent more than 1 trillion yen, or $8.7 billion at current
exchange rates, on art. Many art dealers and scholars said the
actual value was probably triple that amount.
</P>
<P>
   Japanese collectors bought at least five of the most expensive
works of art ever sold at auction, but only one, van Gogh's
``Sunflowers,'' is still in Japan, in the corporate collection of
Yasuda Fire &AMP; Marine Insurance Co.
</P>
<P>
   The other four _ van Gogh's ``Portrait of Dr. Gachet,'' Renoir's
``Au Moulin de la Galette'' and Picasso's ``Acrobat and Young
Harlequin'' and ``Pierrette's Wedding'' _ have left Japan,
apparently ending up in Europe or the United States, along with
countless other paintings bought by the Japanese when their bubble
economy was at its peak.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a loss of face associated with this art,'' said Chieko
Hasegawa, owner of the Nichido Gallery in Ginza. ``The sale of
these paintings sends two messages: that you have financial
difficulties and that you paid too much for them from the start.''
</P>
<P>
   The flurry of Japanese purchases in the late 1980s and early
'90s sparked a wave of resentment in the art world comparable with
the uproar that ensued when Japanese companies bought Rockefeller
Center in New York and the famous golf course at Pebble Beach,
Calif. Curators and dealers regarded the Japanese purchases as
losses. Some of the most prominent pieces disappeared into private
homes and were rarely seen.
</P>
<P>
   Inevitably, the trophy prices that Japanese investors paid for
real estate collapsed. Confronted with the fact that the value of
their collateral did not match the value of their loans, banks
began staking claims to whatever assets they could get their hands
on, including art. In some cases, financial institutions even lent
money to collectors expressly for the purpose of purchasing art, so
that art was the collateral. More rarely, the financial
institutions themselves bought paintings.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, many of the paintings purchased during that time ended up
in the financial system. Although the rest of the world considers
them treasures, in Japan they are literally bad assets, commonly
referred to as ``bad-debt art,'' the legacy of an era of profligate
spending and lending that many would like to forget.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, some paintings have been located. The San Francisco
Museum of Modern Art, for instance, recently acquired 10 works from
Fukuoka City Bank, but the museum initially had to swear not to
identify the specific works, the deal or the seller. Since then,
however, the bank itself has talked about the sale.
</P>
<P>
   But ``Dr. Gachet'' and ``Moulin de la Galette,'' the two most
expensive paintings ever bought at auction, have not been traced.
In the spring of 1990, Ryoei Saito, then president of Daishowa
Paper Manufacturing Co., paid a total of $160.6 million for the two
paintings. Soon afterward Saito sent shivers through the art world
when he said he intended to take the paintings to his grave,
literally.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, however, bad debts caught up with Daishowa and Saito.
His creditors cut off his control of Daishowa and seized the
paintings, which then disappeared into their warehouse.
</P>
<P>
   The responsibility for selling the paintings fell to Fuji Bank,
one of Daishowa's biggest creditors, and for five years, art
dealers and collectors courted the bank. But Fuji held on to the
paintings until 1997, when it sold ``Moulin de la Galette'' to an
unidentified foreign buyer. Segi believes that it fetched roughly
$52.1 million, or two-thirds of the $78.1 million Saito paid for
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dr. Gachet'' has also been sold by Fuji, art dealers said, but
no one knows who bought it, or when or for how much, although
dealers assume that it sold for less than the $82.5 million it cost
Saito. One recent report on German television said the piece had
been sold to an American investor for $43 million, but art experts
are dubious.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Fuji Bank declined to comment, as did Sumitomo Bank, Mitsui
Trust &AMP; Banking Co. and several other Japanese financial
institutions whose names have been linked to art sales.
</P>
<P>
   The banks' silence is partly an effort to protect themselves.
The rules delineating ownership of property seized as collateral
are murky in Japan, art experts said, and bank executives place a
premium on their relationships with borrowers.
</P>
<P>
   And despite pressure from the government for reform, the process
of selling off ``bad-debt art'' is proceeding very slowly, as most
negotiations do in Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Christie's Japan has been paying polite calls on collectors and
banks since 1992, when it became clear that an economic tailspin
would start pushing sales of art bought during the bubble. Last
year Christie's effort paid off when it won the right to sell some
500 works of art in the collection and warehouses of the bankrupt
Lake Corp., giving the auction house its best year ever in Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Findlay, Christie's international director for 19th- and
20th- century art, said the Japanese had been deeply disappointed
by the yawning gap between the book value of the art they hold and
its market value. Christie's initial bit of business tended to be
appraisals aimed at helping sellers meet their accounting needs.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they could take a $2 million loss that year, we helped them
select the painting and get it sold,'' Findlay said.
</P>
<P>
   The art market has also started picking up steam, so that the
gap between book value and market value has narrowed, encouraging
financial institutions to sell.
</P>
<P>
   But ownership issues still loom large, Findlay and others say.
``These paintings do not belong to the banks,'' Segi said. ``They
exist in a kind of no man's land between their owners and the
financial institutions that have seized them as collateral.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   He said a potential buyer would have to get the approval of both
the nominal owner of the painting and the financial institution
holding it. The heavy emphasis on relationships in Japanese
business means that many owners can choose not to sell their
holdings. For instance, a bank may elect to keep a painting in its
warehouse in lieu of selling it, so long as the original owner
continues to make interest payments on his outstanding debts.
</P>
<P>
   ``A person has to die or declare legal bankruptcy before the
ownership problems clear up,'' Segi said, and people rarely declare
bankruptcy in Japan.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The death of Saito, erstwhile owner of ``Dr. Gachet'' and
``Moulin de la Galette,'' in March 1996 probably had as much to do
with Fuji's decision to sell it as any improvement in the art
market or government pressure, a Fuji official hinted.
</P>
<P>
   The Chiyoda Fire &AMP; Marine Insurance Co., an affiliate of the
Toyota group, recently arranged the sale of a Braque that belonged
to Tomonori Tsurumaki, a former real estate and race track mogul
with loose ties to Japanese gangsters whose business was all but
bankrupt. Tsurumaki himself helped Chiyoda with the sale, Segi and
others said.
</P>
<P>
   Findlay of Christie's said that ownership issues were less
complex here than many suggest. ``Anyone who can produce the work
of art is in a position to sell it,'' he said. ``In Japan, many
dealers and agents peddle transparencies and color copies of works,
and they are usually fishing for offers or trying to get free
appraisal advice. I prefer to deal only with individuals or
companies who can actually show me the works of art.''
</P>
<P>
   Christie's may also be deferring to the Japanese respect for
relationships and original ownership. It is currently the custodian
of what is perhaps the most mysterious painting in modern history,
``Pierrette's Wedding,'' which was part of the collateral retained
by Lake when GE Capital Corp. bought Lake's consumer finance
business.
</P>
<P>
   The painting was taken from Tsurumaki as his business empire
crumbled and was stored in the warehouse of Mitsui Trust for a
time. Findlay confirmed that the painting was no longer in Japan,
where it was exhibited only once before Tsurumaki was forced to
part with it. But Findlay insisted it was not for sale.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not even in the private market,'' he said. ``It is not being
offered. I don't think this is the right time.''
</P>
<P>
   Has Tsurumaki requested that Christie's hold off on a sale of
the elusive ``Pierrette,'' hoping perhaps that he might one day
retrieve it? Tsurumaki is not saying, and neither is Findlay.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``These paintings coming out of Japan are being bought by
wealthy people who lead private lives,'' Findlay said. ``That's not
unusual. The buyers of 70 percent of the works sold at auction are
not identified.''
</P>
</TEXT>
