<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-18 19:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2024 &Cx1f; ttc-z
u v BC-LADN-BUDGET &LR;      08-18 0511
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LADN-BUDGET </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Daily News plans to move the following general
stories for use by NYTimes News Service clients, AMs and PMs of
August, Aug. 19 and thereafter. For questions about stories, please
contact Jeremy Bagott at the Daily News, (818) 713-3702.
</P>
<P>
   QUAKE-SOCAL (Los Angeles) _ Turkey was installing a network of
sensors that could have given them advance warning of the
devastating temblor, but it was too late. Now Southern California
is getting the improved sensors, which scientists say could
eventually warn of a major quake. The work of Southern California
quake research is only now beginning to pay off, and scientists and
emergency services officials say the region is about as ready as it
can be for The Big One. By Michael Coit. (Will move in the ``n''
California news file.)
</P>
<P>
   LAPD-SIS (Los Angeles) _ Speaking publicly for the first time
about the fatal shooting of two robbery suspects, Police Chief
Bernard C. Parks defended the actions of the Special Investigations
Section, saying it handles the toughest cases. Parks also warned
that Los Angeles is a ``target-rich'' environment for terrorism and
hate crimes such as last week's shooting at the North Valley Jewish
Community Center as he escalated his call for tougher gun controls.
By Rick Orlov. (Will move in the ``n'' California news file.)
</P>
<P>
   BEAR-DEATH (Los Angeles) _ Highway 126 was closed briefly at
dawn today after a trucker hit and killed a bear near Piru _ the
fourth bear accident on the rural highway in as many months.
Experts say a recent fire in the area, about 30 miles northwest of
Los Angeles, is driving the California black bears to new habitat.
By Bhavna Mistry. (Will move in the ``n'' California news file.)
</P>
<P>
   SHOOTING-911 (Los Angeles) _ They were voices of fear, confusion
and calm. Such were the calls released on Wednesday as recorded
over the city's 911 emergency system on Aug. 10 as callers reported
the shooting that Buford O. Furrow told authorities he carried out
at the North Valley Jewish Community Center. By Rick Orlov. (Will
move in the ``a'' national and ``n'' California news file.)
</P>
<P>
   VENDING-CRACKDOWN (Los Angeles) _ Several pushcarts were loaded
on flatbed trucks and trunks filled with burritos and squid were
confiscated as part of health inspectors' new crackdown on illegal
street sales. The new push came to address the complaints of
residents and business owners about sidewalk vendors. By Jesse
Hiestand. (Will move in the ``n'' California news file.)
</P>
<P>
   PENNIES-CRUNCH (Los Angeles) _ Wells Fargo Bank is having a hard
time getting its hands on cash. Pennies, specifically. The San
Francisco-based bank was going to award one million pennies _ along
with a number of other prizes _ to its one-millionth Internet
customer, but can't scrape together enough copper. ``We can't get
one million pennies,'' said Kathy Shilkret, Wells spokeswoman.
Wells Fargo isn't alone. By Deborah Adamson. (Will move in the
``n'' California and ``f'' financial news file.)
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
