<SLUG> BC-OBITUARY-WAREHAM-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RICHARD WAREHAM, 78; LED DESIGN OF POLAROID SX-70 CAMERA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TOM LONG  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Richard Rogers Wareham, who led design of Polaroid Corp.'s SX-70
camera in the 1970s, died, apparently of a heart attack, Aug. 7 in
his home in Lake San Marcos, Calif., just before his 79th birthday.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Wareham worked at Polaroid when the high-technology company
was one of the largest and fastest-growing firms in Massachusetts.
For his achievements in designing the SX-70 camera under the
leadership of Edwin Land, Polaroid's founder, he was promoted to
assistant vice president and senior engineering fellow.
</P>
<P>
   He retired after 33 years at Polaroid in 1982, the same year
Land left the company.
</P>
<P>
   The SX-70, first of the cameras to use Polaroid's card-like
color film, was introduced in 1972 and marketed nationally in 1973.
Development of the SX-70 film and camera, and building factories to
make them, cost several hundred million dollars.
</P>
<P>
   By Land's order, Mr. Wareham and a few other camera engineers
began late in the 1960s to work secretly on the ninth floor of 565
Technology Square in Cambridge. Like other small groups Land
assigned to work on different aspects of the system, Mr. Wareham's
team was isolated in the manner of the so-called ``Skunk Works'' at
Lockheed Aircraft, which developed the U-2 spy plane in the 1950s.
Land told Mr. Wareham to assume success with development of a
``chemical curtain'' that would allow the film to be developed
outside the camera _ years before this success was achieved.
</P>
<P>
   Noted for his sense of humor, Mr. Wareham commented on the
stresses of high-speed industrial development by saying: ``We're
one happy, small family _ we fight most of the time.'' Of Land's
persuasiveness, Mr. Wareham said he would ``sell me the shirt off
my own back.'' But he added: ``Anything he suggested was not
off-hand. . . . It was well thought out. . . . He wasn't really
asking people to jump seven feet in the air and stay there.''
</P>
<P>
   He was born in Lynn, Mass. He graduated from Phillips Academy in
Andover in 1940, and attended the Massachusetts Institute of
Technology.
</P>
<P>
   A reserve officer trainee at MIT, Mr. Wareham served with the
Army Engineers in Europe, including the Battle of the Bulge in
1944, and in Asia, finishing at Okinawa in 1945.
</P>
<P>
   After World War II, Mr. Wareham went to United Shoe Machine
Corp., where he worked as an engineer for five years. Concluding
that USMC offered ``a lot of fun but no future,'' Mr. Wareham went
to MIT's placement office in Cambridge to check for openings. He
was told of a ``funny company around the corner.'' It was the
prospect closest to MIT, and it was a very cold day, so he went and
was hired.
</P>
<P>
   He and his family lived for many years in Marblehead, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   In 1987, after 42 years of marriage, Mr. Wareham's wife, Eve
Stone Wareham, died of cancer.
</P>
<P>
   He leaves his second wife, Betty; two daughters, Gayle Richards
of Rochester, N.H., and Judy Wareham of Marblehead; a sister, Jane
De Wolfe of Marblehead; and two grandsons.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-18-99 1903EDT &QL; 
