<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TURKEY-CENTER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SURVIVORS SAY MANY COLLAPSED BUILDINGS WERE POORLY BUILT 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also TURKEY-QUAKE, TURKEY-SCENE.) 
(th) 
 By CELESTINE BOHLEN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ISTANBUL, Turkey _ According to a neighbor who jumped out of bed
when the floor beneath him began to shake and sway, the building
across the street collapsed in 27 seconds flat.
</P>
<P>
   His son, out on the balcony, yelled back to his father, ``It is
the mosque, the mosque.'' But when Umut Umutoglu went out into the
predawn darkness Tuesday, he saw through a cloud of dust that the
newly built mosque was intact, while a five-story apartment
building next door had been reduced to a pile of tangled metal and
concrete rubble.
</P>
<P>
   Avcilar, a new neighborhood on the western edge of this giant
sprawling city, suffered more from Tuesday's devastating earthquake
than any other part of Istanbul, most of which was shaken but
largely left intact. Here, several dozen buildings were destroyed,
some collapsing face forward onto the sidewalks, others tilting
like sinking ships onto neighboring walls.
</P>
<P>
   The destruction in Avcilar seemed selective, leaving behind an
odd checkerboard pattern of buildings that remain standing, next to
houses that were utterly wrecked by the wrath of the quake.
</P>
<P>
   According to local residents, the selection was not so random.
The difference between the buildings that fell and those that
didn't lay, they said, in the quality of the construction, in the
corners cut by contractors who mix too much sand into cement and
use cheap iron in their rush to build housing for Istanbul's
exploding population.
</P>
<P>
   ``The contractor was not a good person,'' said Omar Talu, 50, an
electrician who was surveying the debris that had once been home to
friends and neighbors. ``He especially cheated on cement.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the 17 people who lived in the apartment block on Erdek Lane,
only six survived, Talu said.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the residents of this neighborhood are immigrants from
the Turkish countryside who have flocked to the city in the last
decade, bringing its population to an estimated 12 million.
Apartment houses sprang up like mushrooms on the city's edges,
alongside flimsy makeshift shanties.
</P>
<P>
   Up the street from Umutoglu's house, Hassan Gunay, 50, also an
electrician, waited somberly for word of his cousin, the last
unaccounted-for member of a family of relatives who came to
Istanbul three years ago from Southeast Turkey. The family members
were killed Tuesday morning when their building came crashing down
around them. Only the cousin's body has not been found, Gunay said.
</P>
<P>
   According to Gunay, the house where his relatives lived had been
built without a building permit. Three times, local officials had
ordered a halt to construction but in the end, the building, with
its eight apartments, went up anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Early Tuesday morning, local civil defense officials appeared at
the site, digging through the rubble with their bare hands and
pulling out survivors. By Wednesday the count was official: Of the
35 people who lived in the building, 12 were killed including the
contractor and members of his family.
</P>
<P>
   ``He probably cheated on materials,'' said Erkut Oner, a civil
defense official who Wednesday was keeping crowds of onlookers away
from the site.
</P>
<P>
   At the site of another collapsed building, several dozen army
trucks were parked along a highway as hundreds of soldiers sifted
rubble by hand in hopes, one onlooker said, of finding survivors.
</P>
<P>
   Here, and all across Istanbul, families were settling down for
the night in local parks, parking lots and other available open
space, fearing aftershocks that could still bring down buildings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our house is standing but it has cracks all through it,'' said
Beyhan Balci, a 47-year-old woman whose family was sharing a
makeshift tent with neighbors. ``We are waiting for the inspectors
to come and give us a report.''
</P>
<P>
   But as Istanbul was taking stock of the damage Wednesday, life
in this enormous city was returning back to normal. Tourists
flocked to the city's famous sites, none of which apparently
suffered in the quake.
</P>
<P>
   When the great Ottoman architect Sinan was building mosques in
Istanbul in the 16th century, he first built the foundations and
then let them settle for two years before completing construction.
</P>
<P>
   ``If all the buildings in Istanbul had been built that way, then
none would have collapsed,'' said Erkan Tezkan, a geophysicist who
now works as a tour guide.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
