<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-18 19:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2038 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-SIERRA19-COX     08-18 1113
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SIERRA19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Painful dilemma for Sierra Leone
 &HT;    By Don Melvin
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ For Amadu Jabbie, forgiveness is a bitter pill to
swallow, even if it means saving his homeland from ruin.
</P>
<P>
   Jabbie, who lives in the Atlanta area, wants Sierra Leone to
prosper. He dreams of returning and running a business there. He
knows the country needs peace.
</P>
<P>
   But when rebel fighters rampaged through Freetown, the Sierra
Leone capital, in January, burning, pillaging and killing, they
came upon Jabbie's nephew, 20-year-old Umaru Sesay.
</P>
<P>
   First they cut off Sesay's arms and legs. Then they shot him
dead.
</P>
<P>
   That kind of crime, along with thousands of others just like it,
Jabbie finds hard to forgive _ even if it might mean peace and the
end of a brutal, destructive civil war.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1991, that war has ravaged Sierra Leone, a West African
country slightly smaller than South Carolina. At least 20,000
people have been killed, according to the U.S. Agency for
International Development _ 50,000, according to the organization
Human Rights Watch _ and more than half the country's 5 million
inhabitants have been forced from their homes.
</P>
<P>
   The war, some observers say, has more to do with the country's
wealth of diamonds than with ideology. At any rate, it has helped
maintain Sierra Leone's status as the least-developed country in
the world. Average life expectancy in the country, according to the
United Nations, is 37 years.
</P>
<P>
   In their drive to oust the elected president, Ahmad Tejan
Kabbah, rebels of the Revolutionary United Front sowed terror by
chopping off one or both hands of uncounted thousands of civilians
_ men, women and children.
</P>
<P>
   Now, people are being told that _ in the interest of peace and
even, perhaps, a small measure of prosperity _ these acts must be
forgiven.
</P>
<P>
   Or even rewarded.
</P>
<P>
   On July 7, in Togo, Kabbah and Foday Sankoh, leader of the
Revolutionary United Front, signed a peace agreement. The agreement
offered members of the RUF _ the group blamed for wanton
amputations _ ministerial positions. And it gave Sankoh ``the
status of vice president'' and the chairmanship of an ``autonomous
body'' responsible for regulating Sierra Leone's ``strategic
mineral resources'' _ including diamonds.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement also required the government of Sierra Leone to
``grant absolute and free pardon and reprieve to all combatants and
collaborators in respect of anything done by them in pursuit of
their objectives.''
</P>
<P>
   Regional leaders also signed the accord, as did Francis Okelo,
the U.N. secretary-general's special representative for Sierra
Leone. Okelo added a disclaimer that said the amnesty did not apply
to gross violations of human rights, but the United Nations has
been criticized by human rights groups for signing the deal at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you want peace at any cost, you just say, `OK, here's the
government,''' said Reed Brody, advocacy director for Human Rights
Watch. ``If you want a good foundation for a lasting democracy,
people who systematically chop off the hands of civilians and
children should be in jail, not in the government house.''
</P>
<P>
   But Peter Bell, president of CARE USA, the Atlanta-based
international relief organization, and a former board member of
Human Rights Watch, said it is possible to be too dogmatic about
punishing every single violation of human rights.
</P>
<P>
   Bell said he did not want to take ``hard and fast views'' on the
treaty in Sierra Leone because he is not an expert on the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you're talking about is a trade-off between cessation of
the violence and the killing versus justice for horrendous
humanitarian crimes,'' he said. ``This is not a dilemma to be taken
lightly.''
</P>
<P>
   Most human rights organizations, Bell said, would take ``a very
strong, principled position'' in favor of justice and punishment.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the same time, the most basic right of people is the right
to live,'' he said. ``And, in my view, another fundamental right is
the right to peace.'' Still another, he said, is the right to
development and to the basic necessities of life.
</P>
<P>
   The desire to punish gross violations of human rights in
absolutely every case, Bell said, must be balanced against the
killing, malnutrition and disease that are the consequence of war.
</P>
<P>
   Justice or peace?
</P>
<P>
   In the Sierra Leonean community in the Atlanta area, estimated
at a few thousand people, that argument seems to rage not between
different people, but inside the hearts and minds of individuals.
</P>
<P>
   Milton Boyle, who lives in the Atlanta area, was trapped in
Freetown in January when rebels stormed into the city in an assault
that killed about 5,000 people. Peering out a window, he saw people
used as human shields and houses set on fire. He heard people
screaming for their lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw the terrible atrocities these guys committed,'' he said.
But, though it is ``a very tough task for all of us, a tough deal
to swallow,'' he said he is willing to forgive.
</P>
<P>
   ``For some of us, we just don't have any other choice but to
welcome them,'' he said of the rebels. ``These guys don't have
anything to lose. They will just devastate the whole country. Some
of us don't want to lose any more family.''
</P>
<P>
   Jabbie wants peace so he can return to Sierra Leone. ``No place
like your home, sir,'' he said emphatically.
</P>
<P>
   And his 75-year-old mother, Sallay, prays all the time that she
will be able to go home.
</P>
<P>
   But in a recent interview, Jabbie went back and forth, seeming
to argue both sides of the question. He did not believe in granting
amnesty to such criminals, he said, but he would do it if it was
for the good of the country. Though he did not think it would work.
</P>
<P>
   A few hours later, in a telephone call, he continued the
conversation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to take a stand on the peace accord, which I believe is
inimical to the country,'' he said. ``I believe if people live by
the sword, they should die by the sword. And I don't believe there
should be any amnesty.''
</P>
<P>
   SIERRA LEONE AT A GLANCE
</P>
<P>
   _ Area: 27,699 sq. miles
</P>
<P>
   _ Capital: Freetown
</P>
<P>
   _ Government: constitutional democracy
</P>
<P>
   _ Population: 5,080,004
</P>
<P>
   _ Ethnic groups: 20 native African tribes, 90 percent; Creole,
10 percent
</P>
<P>
   _ Religions: Muslim, 60 percent; indigenous beliefs, 30 percent;
Christian, 10 percent
</P>
<P>
   _ Languages: English, Mende, Temne, Krio
</P>
<P>
   Source: 1998 CIA World Factbook
</P>
<P>
   ON THE WEB:
</P>
<P>
   Sierra Leone factbook from the CIA:
</P>
<P>
   www.odci.gov/cia/publications/ factbook/sl.html
</P>
<P>
   Sierra Leone's unofficial site:
</P>
<P>
   www.Sierra-Leone.org/
</P>
