<SLUG> BC-BUSH-SUIT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONTEMPT MOTION FILED AGAINST BUSH 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN W. GONZALEZ 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Eliza May, fired earlier this year as the chief
regulator of the Texas funeral industry, asked a state court
Wednesday to hold Gov. George W. Bush in contempt for filing what
she called a ``false, misleading and deceptive'' affidavit about
his role in her ouster.
</P>
<P>
   Bush maintains he had nothing to do with May's firing in
February. He's fighting attempts to force his testimony in May's
wrongful firing lawsuit against the Texas Funeral Service
Commission and others.
</P>
<P>
   The contempt motion, which a Bush spokesman described as an
abuse of the legal system, was submitted a few hours after Bush
seemed to contradict his July 20 sworn statement about May's
dismissal.
</P>
<P>
   Bush acknowledged that in 1998 he had a fleeting conversation
with an executive and a lobbyist of Service Corporation
International Inc., a Houston-based funeral services provider whose
officials had questioned May's regulatory tactics. The officials
objected to the way May pursued allegations that workers at two
SCI-affiliated funeral homes had done embalming without proper
licenses.
</P>
<P>
   On Aug. 5, Bush submitted an affidavit in May's case stating,
``I have had no conversations with SCI officials, agents or
representatives concerning the investigation or any dispute arising
from it.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush also swore that ``I have no personal knowledge of relevant
facts of the investigation, nor do I have any personal knowledge of
relevant facts concerning any dispute arising from this
investigation.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush on Wednesday stood by his sworn statements and repeatedly
described May's whistle blower lawsuit as ``frivolous.'' Bush also
renewed his claim that he ``did not have any knowledge at all'' of
SCI's dispute with regulators.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a 20-second conversation. I had no substantive
conversation with the guy,'' Bush said, adding, ``I don't remember
what I said.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's brief encounter with SCI president Robert Waltrip came
while Waltrip was in the Capitol meeting with a top Bush aide about
regulatory concerns. Johnnie B. Rogers, an SCI lobbyist who was at
the meeting, told Newsweek magazine that Bush asked Waltrip if the
commission was ``still messing with you,'' and then asked Rogers
``are you taking care of him?''
</P>
<P>
   May contends those simple questions indicated Bush had some
appreciation of SCI's dispute with regulators. Citing the magazine
account, May's motion states that ``Bush swore that he has had `no
conversations' with any representative of SCI concerning the
investigation or dispute. That is untrue. Gov. Bush swore that he
had `no personal knowledge' of relevant facts concerning the
investigation or dispute. That also is untrue.''
</P>
<P>
   The motion said Bush's insistence that his affidavit is accurate
is ``completely implausible.'' It said Bush ``testified falsely for
the purpose of obstructing justice and the proceedings of this
court,'' and it asked that the court ``impose proper sanctions,''
including fines, against the governor.
</P>
<P>
   Bush wasn't aware of the contempt motion when he answered
reporters' questions Wednesday, but later spokesman Linda Edwards
said ``this is nothing more than a publicity stunt and an example
of the frivolous misuse of the civil justice system.''
</P>
<P>
   May's attorney, Charles Herring Jr. of Austin, could not be
reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's sworn statements were filed in response to a motion filed
by Herring that seeks to force Bush's testimony in May's civil suit
against the commission and SCI.
</P>
<P>
   A hearing has been set for Aug. 30 to decide whether Bush must
give a deposition in the case and provide May with reams of
subpoenaed documents.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
