<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-18 19:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2044 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-BAXTER-COLUMN19-COX     08-18 0596
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BAXTER-COLUMN19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Divide between Gingrich, Hastert one of lessons learned and
applied
 &HT;    By Tom Baxter
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ In last week's New Republic, there was a relative
oddity: a positive story about House Speaker Dennis Hastert.
</P>
<P>
   Plodding, dull old Coach Hastert has taken more than his share
of lumps since it was left to him to pick up the pieces of the
Republican House leadership. But as this story points out, he has
managed to get the Republicans to stop throwing so many rocks at
each other, and he has cobbled together a modest record of
achievement, including the vote on the $792 billion tax cut bill,
from which only four Republicans defected.
</P>
<P>
   The Hastert story isn't nearly as racy as recent revelations
about former Speaker Newt Gingrich's plans to divorce his wife amid
reports that he is having a romance with a young House Agriculture
Committee staffer who sings in the Catholic University National
Shrine Choir. But they come around to the same point.
</P>
<P>
   Read together, these stories make clear what was implied in
Gingrich's hasty exit from elective office last year. They put the
historian who deemed himself a world historical figure firmly in
the past tense.
</P>
<P>
   Hastert, the New Republic story says, has accomplished a good
deal simply by hearing his members out and making them feel like
part of the team. You may remember that Gingrich had an entire
complicated schematic _ ``Listen, Learn and Lead'' _ based on this
very principle.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, by all accounts, Gingrich never paid the slightest
attention to a number of allies who warned him that running ads in
congressional campaigns attacking President Clinton over the Monica
Lewinsky scandal could disastrously backfire. Even after his
miscalculation slashed the GOP majority to a hair, after he had
given up the job he spent a career pursuing, Gingrich is said to
have held out the hope that the Cox report on Chinese spying would
precipitate that wave of moral repulsion he had counted on with
such unhearing confidence.
</P>
<P>
   The Hastert story is evidence that it really doesn't require a
Napoleon to execute what in the final analysis is a fairly
conventional conservative agenda, and not some futuristic
revolution. Rather, it takes a leader who can practice what he
preaches.
</P>
<P>
   Which brings us to the divorce story.
</P>
<P>
   The line between public and private hypocrisy is a hard one to
draw. Gingrich does not deserve a free pass because he waited until
he was a private citizen to acknowledge the sins he committed when
he was a public official and the standard bearer for what he
presented as a moral cause.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, divorcing his wife for a younger woman does
not make him one bit more a hypocrite than Peter Jennings or George
Will, birds of the same feather who feasted with an even more
unseemly relish on the Lewinsky affair. In fact, while behind the
scenes he sought to exploit the White House sex scandal, Gingrich
publicly showed a measure of discretion _ understandably so, in
retrospect.
</P>
<P>
   But in attempting to topple a president for carrying on in much
the same manner he was, he showed a tin ear for the moral
inclinations of Americans, who are more prone to forgive the
forgiving, assume some fault in their leaders and harbor a deep
distrust for those who too often point fingers away from
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Look up Lincoln, on the people and the various ways you can fool
'em. It's a lesson the historian never learned.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
