u a BC-JUDGES-DEATH-PENALTY-     08-18 0682
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JUDGES-DEATH-PENALTY-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGES' CONFERENCE ON DEATH PENALTY HAS DEFENSE LAWYERS IN AN
UPROAR 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla., Ga., Miss., Texas, Ala., La., N.C., S.C., Va., W.Va.,
Md., Del.)  (nk) 
 By DAVID FIRESTONE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A conference for federal and state judges on the death
penalty, which begins Thursday at a luxury golf resort near here,
is drawing widespread criticism from defense lawyers for its
emphasis on methods to speed up state executions.
</P>
<P>
   The three-day gathering of Southern judges, organized by the
11th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals, which is based here, is being
held at the Chateau Elan Winery and Resort in Braselton, Ga., about
30 miles from Atlanta. Although its organizers say the purpose of
the conference is to promote fairness in capital cases, that
subject does not appear on the printed agenda, which was provided
to The New York Times by a critic.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the principal subject of the conference appears to be
``improving the process'' of death penalty cases in the three
states of the 11th Circuit _ Georgia, Florida and Alabama _ and
removing some of the procedural barriers thrown up by defendants to
slow down their executions.
</P>
<P>
   One of the planners of the conference and a principal speaker is
Judge Edward E. Carnes of the 11th Circuit, whose nomination to the
federal appeals bench in 1992 by President George Bush caused a
raucous Senate fight because of his outspoken advocacy of the death
penalty and his work to reduce post-conviction appeals.
</P>
<P>
   Carnes is scheduled to speak on ``the procedural, practical and
political problems that impede implementation of improvements'' to
the death penalty process. The conference includes several similar
sessions, including a detailed look at the process in Texas, which
has had 184 executions since 1982, the most of any state. One
45-minute session during the three days is devoted to comments from
defense lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   Death-penalty appeals have become a defining issue for the 11
regional circuits of the federal Appeals Court, several of which
grew markedly more conservative after appointments during the
Reagan and Bush years. In particular, two Southern circuits on
either side of the 11th have become known for repeatedly refusing
to grant new hearings to defendants convicted of capital crimes.
Several defense lawyers said the conference appeared to be intended
to bring the 11th Circuit more in line with the rest of the South.
</P>
<P>
   ``From what I've seen of the conference's missions and goals, it
does appear that Judge Carnes is trying to help judges find ways to
expedite the death penalty process,'' said Michael Mears, state
director of Georgia's death penalty defense office, who is
scheduled to speak during the session for defense lawyers. ``I'm
trying to keep an open mind here, but it's hard to see any other
way to interpret that kind of language. If it was about fairness,
you'd think there'd be a session on providing adequate counsel, but
that's not on the agenda.''
</P>
<P>
   Stephen B. Bright, director of the Southern Center for Human
Rights in Atlanta, wrote a lengthy letter to Judge R. Lanier
Anderson, chief judge of the 11th Circuit, urging him to cancel the
conference because of a ``lack of balance.'' He charged that the
apparent purpose of the meeting was to turn the courts of the 11th
Circuit ``into the kind of death mills that the state and federal
courts in Texas have become.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson, an appointee of President Jimmy Carter, wrote back
that Bright had misconstrued the purposes of the symposium. In an
interview Wednesday, Anderson said the conference was intended to
reduce the risk of error in capital cases and improve fairness.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, it's not our purpose to rush defendants to
execution,'' said Anderson, who is based in Macon, Ga. ``The courts
are interested in having cases decided with appropriate expedition,
but only after full and adequate litigation and discussion of every
issue. We certainly did not intend there to be any perception of
one-sidedness.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Anderson said he was not aware of criticism from Bright and
other lawyers that it was inappropriate to discuss executions at a
luxury golf resort. He said the site was chosen because it was
centrally located and attractive enough to get participants to
come.
</P>
<P>
   Each of the 93 judges and lawyers invited are required to pay
his or her own way. The brochure sent to the participants includes
a list of the resort's seven restaurants, and also notes the wine
tastings, saunas and four golf courses that are available. One golf
course costs $135 per round.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   In most states, it takes years for a prisoner to be executed
after being convicted of a capital crime, due to an array of appeal
rights that include an appeal to the federal courts. Many elected
officials and prosecutors have argued that these delays have in
effect vitiated legitimate death-penalty statutes, and have
searched for ways to reduce grounds for endless appeals.
</P>
<P>
   One supporter of the death penalty, Attorney General Thurbert
Baker of Georgia, said the conference was a perfectly appropriate
forum to discuss ways of making the system more efficient.
</P>
<P>
   ``An efficient system is one that is beneficial to the victims
of these crimes, and also to the defendants and the courts that
have to process their cases,'' said Baker, who is scheduled to
speak at the conference. ``You want a system that moves these cases
as expeditiously as possible, but in a fair and just manner. It's
unfair to the defendant to wait forever to get an answer on a
post-conviction appeal.''
</P>
<P>
   The 11th Circuit has a far more moderate reputation on such
appeals than either the 4th Circuit, comprising the Carolinas,
Maryland, Virginia, West Virginia and Delaware, or the 5th, which
includes Texas, Louisiana and Mississippi.
</P>
<P>
   Where appellate judges in those circuits are the most aggressive
in the nation in rejecting the appeals of death-row convicts, those
in the 11th Circuit are considered less ideologically rigid and
more independent, said Howard O. Hunter, dean of the Emory
University Law School.
</P>
<P>
   But some death-penalty lawyers said they believed the circuit
had become more conservative since Carnes was appointed. John
Blume, a Cornell University law professor who defends capital-case
prisoners in the South, said the circuit now rules less often in
favor of defendants, which he said was not surprising given Carnes'
outspokenness on the subject.
</P>
<P>
   Carnes, who did not return a phone call Wednesday, wrote
Alabama's rigorous death penalty statute and was in charge of
defending capital-case appeals for the state attorney general's
office, where he often clashed with lawyers who said the process
was unfair because blacks were frequently excluded from Alabama
jury panels. Although he won praise from some liberal voices for
supporting civil rights statutes, he also lobbied Congress to
restrict the right of state prisoners to appeal their convictions
to federal courts and most civil rights groups bitterly fought his
nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Another prominent federal appeals judge speaking at the
conference is Edith Hollan Jones of Texas, who is scheduled to
discuss the 5th Circuit's experience in dealing with death-penalty
appeals, which are rarely supported in her district. Jones has
become known for her anger at defense lawyers who try to delay
executions through a flurry of legal maneuvers, at one point
writing that such lawyers should be stricken from the bar and not
allowed to practice law for several years.
</P>
<P>
   The outspoken positions of Jones and Carnes have made them among
the most visible targets of the death-penalty bar. Ronald Tabak, an
attorney with Skadden Arps in New York who is co-chairman of the
American Bar Association's death-penalty committee, said Texas'
record of executing prisoners without adequate counsel made it one
of the worst places from which to learn a lesson in procedure.
</P>
<P>
   But Dean Hunter of Emory Law School said he doubted that the 12
judges of the appeals court would be so easily swayed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a wide range of a judges, and a pretty balanced group,''
he said. ``The ones I know are unlikely to be railroaded in one
direction or another.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
