u f BC-LUCENT-EXCEL-BOS &LR;      08-18 1132
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LUCENT-EXCEL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LUCENT TO BUY ANOTHER BAY STATE SWITCHING FIRM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER J. HOWE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- In what is starting to feel like a weekly event,
Lucent Technologies, the world's biggest telecommunications
manufacturer, says it will take over another Massachusetts company,
this time Excel Switching Corp., for $1.3 billion in Lucent stock.
</P>
<P>
   Excel would be the sixth company this year based in
Massachusetts, or descended from a Bay State startup, to join the
Lucent stable, and the third in just the last month.
</P>
<P>
   The deal would push total Lucent employment statewide to more
than 10,000, ranking it near Fidelity Investments, Raytheon, Star
Market and Stop &AMP; Shop as top private employers.
</P>
<P>
   And many industry observers doubt Lucent's Bay State shopping
spree is over yet, given the passel of cutting-edge telecom
startups, many of them lining Interstate 495, that could fill
niches in Lucent's product line and grab future growth.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's deal apparently made Excel founder and chairman
Robert P. Madonna a near-billionaire, raising the value of the 27.2
million Excel shares he reported owning as of March to $974 million
if converted to Lucent stock at Wednesday's closing price. Almost
all of Excel's 460 employees, 370 of whom work on Cape Cod, are
shareholders and enjoyed Wednesday's 26 percent runup in Excel
shares as well.
</P>
<P>
   Based in an industrial park behind the Barnstable airport, just
downwind from the Cape Cod Potato Chip factory, Excel makes
telephone switching equipment that, broadly speaking, has
encouraged innovation in telecommunications the same way as the
move from mainframes to personal computers fostered a vibrant
software-writing industry in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Excel switches help drive such as things as networks for new
phone companies competing with Baby Bells, voice calling over the
Internet, office voice mail, fax forwarding to electronic mail, and
systems that will transfer an incoming office phone call to
someone's portable telephone.
</P>
<P>
   Lucent switches generally come with all the software built in,
like an old-style mainframe computer. In contrast, 11-year-old
Excel sells switches that can be programmed and adapted by others
and ``scaled up'' as a business's needs grow. Excel has sold its
products in more than 70 countries.
</P>
<P>
   Lucent projects the market for such ``open-access'' products
could reach $5 billion by 2003 and sees Excel as a strong way to
jump quickly into a market it now largely does not serve.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think this industry can expand even quicker if we adopt
this open-architecture approach,'' said Dan Stanzione, Lucent's
executive vice president and chief operating officer, who said
Excel's products cover ``a new and emerging sweet spot in the
market.''
</P>
<P>
   While Lucent would not comment on what if any Massachusetts
companies it has in its sights, some of the companies cited by
industry analysts Wednesday as possible future Lucent takeover
candidates include:
</P>
<P>
   -- Broadband Access Systems of Marlborough, which has developed
and is running final pre-market tests on systems to carry voice
calls and high-speed Internet access over revamped cable television
systems such as MediaOne's in Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   -- C-Port Corp. of North Andover, which makes highly
programmable processor chips used in a wide range of telecom
systems such as fast World Wide Web page downloaders.
</P>
<P>
   -- Sonus Networks Inc. of Westford, whose products help convert
voice telephone calls into a form that can move over the Internet,
at much lower cost than long-distance phone carriers.
</P>
<P>
   -- Taqua Systems of Centerville, which makes voice switches used
by competitive local phone companies.
</P>
<P>
   Lucent said it expects to complete the Excel acquisition during
the last three months of this year. It will offer 558 of its own
shares for every 1,000 Excel shares outstanding, making the deal
worth about $1.3 billion based on Lucent's closing price of 64 3/16
in New York Stock Exchange trading. Excel leaped 7 1/16 to close at
34 5/8.
</P>
<P>
   Madonna played down his new fortune. ``From day one, our
mission, when we were five people in a garage, was the same as it
is today, to bring open programmability to a traditionally closed''
field of technology, he said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was never a value thing from a money standpoint, it was,
`We need to accomplish this mission.' It's still just the
beginning,'' said Madonna, who will take an as-yet unspecified
senior post with Lucent. Excel is to remain in Hyannis.
</P>
<P>
   Excel's history is the classic high-tech success story, with the
twist that it all happened on Cape Cod rather than Kendall Square,
Route 128 or Silicon Valley.
</P>
<P>
   Madonna founded Excel in 1988 after the company where he was
engineering director, Lantel, moved off the Cape to Marlborough.
Starting with a half-dozen employees in Sagamore Beach, Excel moved
to Hyannis in 1995 and went public in late 1997.
</P>
<P>
   It has since grown to fill four buildings and employ 460 people,
many enticed from better-known high tech hotbeds by the perk of
living on the Cape, and its net profits have been growing nearly 90
percent a year since 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Lucent, a corporate descendant of the old Bell Systems Western
Electric phone-making unit, has been on a $32 billion acquisition
spree since it was spun off from AT &AMP; T three years ago, including
more than $5 billion in deals in the last two weeks. Some analysts
question whether Lucent may begin choking on all the new businesses
it must assimilate.
</P>
<P>
   In part Lucent has been under pressure to keep up with San
Jose-based Cisco Systems, a computer networking firm that has done
over $1 billion of deals in the last week.
</P>
<P>
   As more and more of all kinds of telecommunications moves from
systems designed to carry voices _ the traditional phone network _
to systems designed to carry digital data, Cisco and Lucent are
seen as the leading combatants in an epic battle to control the
telecom-network market, with Lucent under special pressure to boost
its data communications presence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lucent is becoming the East Coast Cisco,'' said Blaik Kirby, a
principal with consultants Renaissance Worldwide. While Lucent has
been offering rich prices, Kirby said the Excel deal and others
``make sense. They've been best-of-breed acquisitions.''
</P>
<P>
   In a related development Wednesday, Lucent said it is extending
until next Tuesday its offer to buy stock in SpecTran, a Sturbridge
speciality cable maker it agreed to buy last month for $9 a share.
Lucent said 47.1 percent of SpecTran shares had been tendered as of
midnight Tuesday, so it is giving SpecTran owners _ some of whom
have sued because they call the price too low _ another week to
consider selling.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
