u a BC-LUTHERAN-EPISCOPAL-NY     08-18 1070
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LUTHERAN-EPISCOPAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LUTHERANS SPLIT ON WHETHER TO FORM CLOSE TIE WITH EPISCOPALIANS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Colo., Minn., Iowa, N.J., N.Y.)   (bl)  
 By GUSTAV NIEBUHR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ As leaders of the nation's largest Lutheran
denomination gather to debate one of the most important ecumenical
proposals in decades, controversy over that proposal has produced
an unusually energetic display of the push and pull of politics
within a church.
</P>
<P>
   Lutherans who oppose the proposal have set up a hospitality
suite in a downtown hotel, with a map of the United States on one
wall, showing how it fared recently in nonbinding votes among
regional Lutheran bodies across the country.
</P>
<P>
   But one floor up in the same hotel, the proposal's supporters
have their own ``reception center'' and are distributing a daily
newsletter urging delegates to vote in favor of the proposal.
</P>
<P>
   At stake is a sweeping agreement for close cooperation between
the Evangelical Lutheran Church in America and the Protestant
Episcopal Church in the United States of America, a proposal that
many here liken to a marriage. If it is passed Thursday by the
Lutherans' Churchwide Assembly, their top policy-making body, it
would bind the two denominations, with a combined membership of
nearly 8 million, in a pact to recognize each other's members and
sacraments, exchange clergy members where needed and join in
missionary and social service work.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal, for ``full communion'' between the two churches,
was hammered out in discussions among Lutheran and Episcopal
theologians over three decades. But it has become a subject of
great dispute since the Assembly at its last meeting on Aug. 18,
1997, rejected a similar proposal for full communion with the
Episcopalians by a slim margins.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The measure fell six votes short of the required two-thirds
majority, out of 1,039 votes cast, even as the Assembly voted to
adopt a full communion agreement with three other Protestant
churches.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Now, for what will certainly be the last time this century,
Lutherans have opted to consider an agreement with Episcopalians
again, working from a somewhat revised document titled, ``Called to
Common Mission.'' (The assembly will also consider a full communion
plan with the nation's small Moravian Church, a measure that is not
controversial and is expected to pass.)
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of the Lutheran-Episcopalian proposal, like Lutheran
Bishops Stephen Bouman of New York and Roy Riley of New Jersey,
said it would allow the two denominations to pool scarce resources
in rural and inner-city areas, where collaboration, rather than
competition, would mean a stronger ministry and greater social
programs.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this is a defining moment for Lutherans, at least for
a generation,'' Bouman said, adding that the two denominations, in
the New York area, could better serve their immigrant members if
they worked together. Lutherans in New York, he said, worship in 16
different languages and will soon add a 17th, with the organization
of a Swahili-speaking congregation in Queens.
</P>
<P>
   Riley said the proposal's approval would also provide an
important symbol of Christian unity. Jesus, he said, preached that
unity among believers helped spread the Gospel's teachings. But
when churches appear unable to cooperate, he said, ``I think that
sends an enormously negative message to the world.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   But opponents, like Professor Todd Nichol, a church historian at
Luther Seminary in St. Paul, Minn., and the Rev. Roger Eigenfeld of
Mahtomedi, Minn., said the proposal would require Lutherans to go
against their traditional understanding of how the church
functions, by requiring that they accept Episcopalians' beliefs
about the office of bishop _ specifically, that bishops belong to
the ``historic episcopate,'' an unbroken line of religious
leadership stretching back to earliest days of Christianity.
</P>
<P>
   ``The basic issue here is, this imposes a condition for unity,''
said Nichol, ``which we do not think consistent with Scripture or
the Lutheran confessions.''
</P>
<P>
   Eigenfeld described the idea of the historic episcopate as ``a
top-down model.'' He added, ``The reason I'm opposed to it is, it's
an outmoded hierarchical system, which is not going to carry us
into the 21st century.''
</P>
<P>
   Other opponents have said full communion is not necessary for
churches and pastors to pursue ecumenical work on the local level.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Evangelical Lutheran Church has bishops, they are
elected for six-year terms, rather than for life as in the
Episcopal Church, and return to being pastors after their terms
have ended. In addition, some at the assembly in Denver said, many
Lutherans in the upper Midwest, the faith's historic heartland,
retain a historic suspicion of bishops, a legacy of their
Scandinavian immigrant ancestors who came to America determined not
to allow bishops the sort of power they had in their native lands.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Organizing against the full communion proposal gained steam last
February, when opponents of it gathered at Eigenfeld's church,
which has a congregation of 8,000. More than 200 people came from
14 states and produced a statement they called the Mahtomedi
Resolution, which rejected the proposal for full communion, while
still calling for Lutherans to work with ``our Episcopal
neighbors.''
</P>
<P>
   But leading supporters of full communion with Episcopalians were
determined not to be out-organized. ``When we got to Philadelphia
two years ago, we were really surprised by the organized
opposition,'' said Riley, referring to the last meeting site of the
Churchwide Assembly, where the full communion proposal failed. He
said he and four other prominent Lutherans mailed information to
the assembly's delegates in July supporting the proposal. ``Even
though we were in the strong majority, we had to be organized,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   After hearings and discussion on the full communion proposal
Tuesday afternoon, Bishop Curtis Miller of the Western Iowa Synod
said he thought the vote Thursday would be ``impossible to
predict.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I just hope the conversation can be handled in a respectful
and informative way, so people can discern the Spirit's leading,''
he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
