<SLUG> BC-NERF-TOY-ART-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEATTLE MAN'S ODD BALL NOW PART OF NERF LINEUP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TRICIA DURYEE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Seattle resident Mike McGonigle never invented a thing
in his life until Halloween 1993, when the San Francisco 49ers were
creaming the Los Angeles Rams.
</P>
<P>
   At the peak of his frustration and boredom, he threw a foam
pumpkin decoration against the wall and it spiraled right back to
him. Within hours, he had sawed off the end of his purple and gray
Nerf ball, and his invention was born: a pass-back, spiraling
football.
</P>
<P>
   And this year, Hasbro _ the creators of Nerf _ adopted the ball
into its line of spongy play toys. Now the ball that McGonigle
invented on the fly is available for children ages 6 and up to play
endless hours of football by themselves.
</P>
<P>
   With a nice spiral pass, the flat end of the Nerf football will
make even contact with the wall, and it will bounce a nice spiral
right back to passer. Throw a lousy pass, and it's unpredictable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why didn't anyone think of it before?'' asked Webb Nelson,
McGonigle's partner, who as president of Play Visions of
Woodinville helped bring the idea to Hasbro. When thinking about
how McGonigle came up with the idea, he said:
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes it's best when life can be serendipitous.''
</P>
<P>
   As a day trader, buying and selling stocks as short-term
investments, McGonigle is well-acquainted with serendipity. In
1986, he got fired from a computer programming job because he
traded on company time. McGonigle now covets his freedom, and
enjoys watching his idea flourish from his apartment in downtown
Seattle, where he's most comfortable in shorts, a T-shirt and a
pair of flip-flops.
</P>
<P>
   Locally, Toys ``R'' Us at Seattle's Northgate Mall sells the
Nerf Turbo Blast-Back Footballs at $9.99 apiece. FAO Schwarz lets
them go for $16 each.
</P>
<P>
   McGonigle is optimistic about the odd-looking football's future,
partly because of its simplicity.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not one of those high-tech toys with a microchip,'' he
said, noting that it came about at a time when Hasbro had pretty
much tried all variations of the football.
</P>
<P>
   There have been Nerf balls with fins, multicolored versions,
some with aerodynamic grooves and far-flying ones. But this one has
a different function, McGonigle says. It returns without a partner,
and stands without a tee.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Kihara, sales leader and supervisor for Bellevue's FAO
Schwarz, said the Blast-Back Football looks like the head of a
rocket or bullet because one of its ends is rounded off. ``It's
something different,'' he said. ``It solves some of the basic
problems of a regular football.''
</P>
<P>
   It's also a bit heavier and more durable than the average Nerf,
making it more appropriate for outdoors than for indoors. The new
Nerf bears the official NFL logo. And McGonigle and Nelson said the
Nerf's commercials feature Brett Favre, quarterback for the Green
Bay Packers, along with other leading NFL players.
</P>
<P>
   Although neither of them have seen the commercials, they have
been told the advertising campaign will begin this football season.
</P>
<P>
   At times, it's more than McGonigle expected.
</P>
<P>
   It was particularly depressing when he was awaiting his patent.
McGonigle wondered why it was taking so long. Then he discovered
his lawyer still had the file in his office, wasting more than a
year of McGonigle's time.
</P>
<P>
   But when he paired up with Nelson, the ball started rolling. As
a toy manufacturer and importer, Nelson was able to put out a
version in limited circulation. Nelson also had connections to
Hasbro, and in October 1998, they signed a contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I first saw it at the (New York) toy fair, I realized it
really happened,'' he said. Nelson and McGonigle got $25,000 for
the initial contract with Hasbro. About 100,000 of the balls have
sold to date and Hasbro expects to sell 2 million to 5 million this
year alone. McGonigle and his partner stand to make as much as $1.1
million each on a return of 22 cents for every Turbo Blast-Back
Nerf football sold.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kids will invent games with this,'' McGonigle said. ``I know
they will.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
