u a BC-UNC-CHANCELLOR19-COX     08-18 0757
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UNC-CHANCELLOR19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Former BellSouth chairman to lead UNC-Chapel Hill
 &HT;    By Chris Burritt
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHAPEL HILL, N.C. _ A year from now, former BellSouth Vice
Chairman Bill McCoy hopes to retire, once and for all. Until then,
the 65-year-old man in dark pinstripes and gold cuff links is back
at his alma mater as interim chancellor.
</P>
<P>
   McCoy is steering UNC-Chapel Hill, North Carolina's flagship
university, through turbulent times until his permanent replacement
is hired next year.
</P>
<P>
   Students are returning to a historic campus still shaken by the
unexpected death of popular Chancellor Michael Hooker, 53, who died
in June of lymphatic cancer.
</P>
<P>
   McCoy also is having to deal with deepening financial worries,
after the state Legislature refused this summer to approve a $3
billion construction package for North Carolina's 16 public
universities.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't help that UNC-Chapel Hill already was grappling with a
projected $11.6 million budget shortfall. An estimated $5 million
stemmed from an embarrassing oversight by finance officials. They
failed to realize that in the coming year, the university will be
responsible for 27 pay periods, not the usual 26.
</P>
<P>
   ``The budget snafu and the failed bond issue were blows to
Carolina's credibility,'' chided a recent editorial in The Chapel
Hill Herald.
</P>
<P>
   The budget shortfall has since been reduced to $6.8 million, but
it required the elimination of 13 jobs. Though he had no role in
the payroll miscalculation, McCoy said it won't happen again.
</P>
<P>
   He plans to focus on the university's planning and budgeting _
less visionary than some of Hooker's endeavors, but crucial at this
time, some believe.
</P>
<P>
   Hooker, a 1969 UNC graduate, gained popularity as chancellor by
visiting each of North Carolina's 100 counties. After UNC defeated
rival Duke in a men's basketball game, Hooker allowed celebrating
students to hoist his body and pass him atop the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   McCoy, by contrast, has a penchant for finance, not body
surfing.
</P>
<P>
   ``His experience in business will directly apply to what we need
to accomplish on the business side of the university,'' said Jane
Stine, a UNC systems programmer and chair of the Employee Forum,
which represents nonfaculty staff. ``I've been extremely impressed
with his quick grasp of the situation here.''
</P>
<P>
   The lean, graying interim chancellor leans over a glass-topped
table in South Building, a corner of the university home to Yackety
Yack yearbooks dating back to the 1930s.
</P>
<P>
   McCoy is reserved and methodical in his style and in his
expectations for UNC.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I can keep some of the important things moving along,
maintaining the historic momentum of this school, I will be glad
about it,'' said the 1955 UNC graduate from Snow Hill, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   After serving as a Marine Corps helicopter pilot, he earned his
reputation as a financial whiz over 35 years in telecommunications,
mostly at BellSouth Corp.
</P>
<P>
   In 1982, McCoy played a critical role in the spinoff of
Atlanta-based BellSouth during the breakup of AT&AMP;T. He rose to
chief financial officer and vice chairman and, in 1986, became
president of BellSouth Enterprises, which grew to 17,000 employees
in nonregulated industries such as cellular phone service.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is not an effusive sort of guy, a backslapper,'' said Dick
Yarbrough, a retired BellSouth vice president. ``If he had any
emotional bent, it was toward the University of North Carolina. I
think he probably bleeds Tar Heel blue.''
</P>
<P>
   McCoy impressed then-UNC President C.D. Spangler, a Charlotte,
N.C., billionaire who served on BellSouth's board of directors.
Another BellSouth director, Charlotte banker Cliff Cameron, served
on UNC's Board of Governors.
</P>
<P>
   After McCoy retired from BellSouth, Spangler and Cameron
convinced him to join UNC's General Administration, responsible for
the 16 public universities, as vice president of finance.
</P>
<P>
   He retired from that post in January, hoping to relax with his
wife, Sara, play golf and visit with grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   In April, after Hooker went on medical leave, McCoy began a
two-month stint as UNC-Chapel Hill's acting chancellor. Following
Hooker's death, he agreed to return on an interim basis.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do not think students are looking for a visionary, or for
Bill McCoy to lay out a 10-point plan for what he is going to do,''
said Nic Heinke, 21, the student body president. ``But they are
looking for strong leadership.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
