<SLUG> BC-LION-HANNAFORD-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BELGIAN COMPANY SCOOPS UP HANNAFORD BROS. 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS REIDY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SCARBOROUGH, Maine _ Continuing a wave of consolidation in the
supermarket industry, Hannaford Bros. Co. said Wednesday it has
agreed to be purchased by the Belgian parent of North
Carolina-based Food Lion Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Delhaize-Le Lion SA of Belgium plans to buy Scarborough-based
Hannaford for $3.6 billion, about $600 million more than what
investors had estimated Hannaford to be worth.
</P>
<P>
   The entire US supermarket industry is spooked by the aggressive
inroads made onto their turf by Wal-Mart Stores Inc., which sold an
estimated $36 billion worth of food last year, according to the
Food Institute. The trade group pegs total 1998 sales at
supermarket chains at about $415 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Supermarket chains feel they need size to fight Wal-Mart, and
acquisitions, even pricey ones, are the fastest way to bulk up.
</P>
<P>
   When the sale is completed, Delhaize will be the sixth biggest
grocer in the United States. It will also mean that most big New
England grocery chains, including Stop &AMP; Shop, Shaw's, and Star
Markets, will be owned by European companies.
</P>
<P>
   Hannaford, which also does business under the Shop 'n Save name,
operates six of its 152 stores in Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   In the Boston area, Hannaford also operates an on-line grocery
home delivery service called HomeRuns.
</P>
<P>
   Consumers who use HomeRuns should see no changes as a result of
the acquisition, Hugh G. Farrington, Hannaford's chief executive
officer, said at a news conference here.
</P>
<P>
   Delhaize has an on-line delivery service in Europe, but Food
Lion does not, said Paul A. Fritzson, Hannaford's chief financial
officer.
</P>
<P>
   Though such on-line delivery services have been rapidly
proliferating, none is believed to be profitable.
</P>
<P>
   In the last few months, Hannaford has been looking to sell
pieces of HomeRuns to investors in an effort to help finance the
expansion of the service to other cities.
</P>
<P>
   Delhaize is ``definitely interested'' in HomeRuns; what has yet
to be determined is whether Delhaize wants to own 100 percent of
HomeRuns or whether it will pursue Hannaford's plan to seek other
investors for it, Fritzson said.
</P>
<P>
   As a publicly owned mid-sized chain with $3.3 billion in 1998
sales, Hannaford had to make a move to get bigger, Farrington said;
either it had to buy someone else or be bought itself.
</P>
<P>
   After Hannaford's largest stakeholder indicated this past spring
it was leaning toward cashing out its stock, Hannaford began
actively courting large suitors to see how much they were willing
to pay. If the price was right, Hannaford was prepared to sell. As
it turned out, the price was sky-high.
</P>
<P>
   ``If all the bids came in at 55 a share, we wouldn't be talking
to you today,'' Fritzson said. ``At 79 a share, we couldn't walk
away.''
</P>
<P>
   In the present environment of ever larger giants, it was going
to become ``tougher and tougher and at some point impossible'' for
a mid-sized chain to deliver growth and value to shareholders, said
Farrington, explaining why Hannaford couldn't stand pat.
</P>
<P>
   Crowded into a corner of New England, Hannaford has chafed at
its geographical restraints. In the early 1990s, it bought chains
in North Carolina and Virginia as a way to fuel growth.
</P>
<P>
   CNBC reported Tuesday that Royal Ahold NV, the Dutch parent of
Stop &AMP; Shop Cos., was eager to buy Hannaford.
</P>
<P>
   Later it was reported that a bidding war had broken out, and
investors speculated that interested parties included some of the
largest US operators, including Albertson's and Safeway.
</P>
<P>
   Even after they merge, Food Lion and Hannaford will have
combined sales of only $13.5 billion, much less than the food sales
of such giants as Wal-Mart, Ahold, Kroger Co., and Albertson's.
</P>
<P>
   With the completion of the Hannaford sale, European companies
will control much of the New England grocery business.
</P>
<P>
   Besides Ahold's Stop &AMP; Shop, J Sainsbury plc owns Shaw's
Supermarkets Inc. of East Bridgewater, Mass. and recently bought
Star Markets Co. of Cambridge, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Why are European food operators invading the United States, and
US supermarket chains mostly staying at home? (Wal-Mart is the one
exception. It recently bought a British grocery chain.)
</P>
<P>
   Europe is a mature market with little room for growth,
Farrington said, and a food investor can earn far better returns in
the United States than in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Farrington said there will be no layoffs at Hannaford as a
result of the sale. He will continue to run Hannaford, and stores
in the chain will keep their names.
</P>
<P>
   With 1998 revenues of $10.2 billion and headquarters in
Salisbury, N.C., Food Lion operates 1,258 stores in states from
Pennsylvania to Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Don't expect consolidation to stop anytime soon, said editor
Craig Faucher of the Griffin Report of Food Marketing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
