<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWBORNS-THYROID-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUDY SUGGESTS NEED FOR THYROID SCREENING AMONG PREGNANT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DOLORES KONG  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Children born to women who had even a mildly underactive thyroid
during pregnancy are nearly four times as likely to grow up with
significantly lower IQs, suggests a study that raises for the first
time the possibility that thousands of newborns are at risk each
year.
</P>
<P>
   Based on these findings, the authors of the report in the
current New England Journal of Medicine conclude that routine
screening of pregnant women for an underactive thyroid may be
worthwhile.
</P>
<P>
   ``With systematic screening, we could be able to protect the IQ
of. . .somewhere between 1 and 2 out of 100 kids,'' said Dr. James
E. Haddow, lead author of the study and medical director of the
Foundation for Blood Research, a nonprofit medical research and
education institute based in Maine.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Lawrence Wood, president and medical director of the Thyroid
Foundation of America, a patient advocacy group in Boston, agreed
with the study's conclusion. ``What would you think if you were
pregnant? Might you want to jeopardize your kid's IQ?''
</P>
<P>
   But other physicians familiar with the study said it is too
early to say that a mother's mild but untreated thyroid deficiency
causes the apparent difference in IQ, or to call for widespread
testing along the lines of prenatal screening for Down syndrome and
other conditions. They also contended that the average IQ
difference, of seven points, is relatively slight and within the
normal range of variation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not pooh-poohing it. I'm not dismissing it. But I am
trying to place it in perspective so there isn't panic in the
streets when this article hits the airwaves,'' said Dr. Michael F.
Greene, director of maternal fetal medicine at Massachusetts
General Hospital and chairman of the committee on obstetrical
practice for the American College of Obstetricians and
Gynecologists.
</P>
<P>
   For nearly 100 years, it's been known that children can develop
mental retardation and other problems as a result of their mothers'
severe thyroid deficiency, or their own. Such deficiency can come
from a lack of dietary iodine, an autoimmune disorder that leads
the body to attack the thyroid gland, or other factors.
</P>
<P>
   Since the late 1970s, newborn screening to diagnose and treat
such severe deficiency within the first few weeks of life has
helped virtually eliminate so-called cretinism in the United States
_ retarded mental and physical development that usually led to a
lifetime of institutionalization. Also reducing the risk has been
the addition of iodine to salt and other measures. About 1 in 4,000
babies are born at risk of the extreme hypothyroidism according to
the thyroid foundation's Wood, who is an internist at MGH's thyroid
unit.
</P>
<P>
   This is the first study to so carefully document a link between
a mother's mild thyroid deficiency and the IQ of her child. Thyroid
problems, particularly the early stages of underactive thyroid _ or
hypothyroidism _ are among the most easily missed of medical
ailments. Millions of Americans, primarily women, have thyroid
disease, and many of them do not know it. Symptoms include fatigue
and sluggishness, and risk factors include having such other
autoimmune diseases as Type I diabetes or rheumatoid arthritis.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement released in response to the study, Dr. Duane
Alexander, director of the National Institute of Child Health and
Human Development, supported the idea of early detection and
treatment of hypothyroidism in pregnant women as part of prenatal
care, just as there is prenatal screening for other conditions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know that the health of the mother can be a key factor in
her baby's health,'' said Alexander, whose institute helped fund
the study. ``This study suggests that hypothyroidism might be added
to the group of correctable maternal conditions that can influence
the long-term health of the child.''
</P>
<P>
   But in an editorial accompanying the study, Dr. Robert D.
Utiger, a New England Journal deputy editor, said that before
routine screening is introduced, steps to increase dietary iodine _
like making sure prenatal vitamins have iodine and increasing
iodine in salt and other foods _ should be taken first.
</P>
<P>
   The study involved the analysis of stored blood samples
collected from more than 25,200 pregnant women between 1987 and
1990, and the identification of women who had low thyroid
stimulating hormone (TSH) and their children, and those who had
normal levels. The study's co-authors came from the Foundation for
Blood Research, the New England Newborn Screening Program in
Jamaica Plain, Children's Hospital, Beth Israel Deaconess Medical
Center and Dartmouth Medical School.
</P>
<P>
   Once the children reached 7 to 9 years of age, they were given a
battery of 15 tests relating to intelligence, school performance
and other measures by the researchers.
</P>
<P>
   Of the children born to the 47 women who were found to have had
low TSH during pregnancy without being diagnosed and treated, 19
percent of them had IQ scores of below 85 points. A score of below
85 usually indicates below-average intelligence and trouble in
school. The average IQ score for this group was 100.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, only 5 percent of the study's 124 children whose
mothers had normal TSH levels during pregnancy had IQ scores of
below 85 points, according to the study. The average IQ score for
this group was 107.
</P>
<P>
   In a heartening note, the study found that the 15 children born
to women who continued to have low TSH levels during pregnancy
despite being diagnosed and treated for the thyroid problem grew up
with nearly the same IQ scores as the children who were born to
healthy mothers.
</P>
<P>
   Because the study does not prove cause and effect, MGH's Greene
urged caution in interpreting the results.
</P>
<P>
   It could be that the same autoimmune disorder that leads a
woman's body to start attacking the thyroid gland also leads to an
attack on the fetus, thus possibly affecting IQ, Greene said. In
fact, he added, women with hypothyroidism have a higher risk of
miscarriage in the first trimester, perhaps as a result of such an
autoimmune response.
</P>
<P>
   While Greene voiced caution, he also said if one of his patients
wanted to get tested for TSH, he would explain his reservations and
then order the test if she still wanted it.
</P>
<P>
   The TSH test costs about $40 to $50 commercially, but could be
done more cheaply if done as part of a massive screening program,
according to study author Haddow. In addition to receiving funding
for the research from the federal government, Haddow and his
colleagues were supported by the Thrasher Research Fund and Knoll
Pharmaceutical Company, a maker of a thyroid hormone replacement.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
