<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-18 19:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2077 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-SITE-SANTA-FE-ART-2TA     08-18 0898
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SITE-SANTA-FE-ART-2TAKES-$ADV22-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXPLORING `PLACE' CAN BE TRICKY WHEN THE PLACE IS SOMEONE ELSE'S  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, AUG. 22) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By RUTH LOPEZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA FE, N.M. _ The biennial exhibition of international
contemporary art that opened here last month was devoted to
exploring the meaning of ``place.'' But even before the opening
festivities were over, two installations had been shut down
precisely because of their locations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Looking for a Place'' was the title of the third biennial
sponsored by SITE Santa Fe, a nonprofit arts center in a city
that's a magnet for tourists.
</P>
<P>
   ``The heart of the biennial is the search for places charged
with meaning,'' said Rosa Martinez, the independent curator who put
the exhibition together, ``to explore their potential and their
energies, and to heighten the sensibility of spectators.''
</P>
<P>
   She added that she wanted the notion of place to extend beyond
the geographical to psychological and political space. ``What I am
drawn to is work created with a spectator and their participation
in mind,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But the participation took an unexpected turn after two works of
art were set in places that could be considered nerve centers of
this tricultural region: a graveyard belonging to a largely
Hispanic Roman Catholic parish, and a lake on one of the nearby
Indian Pueblos.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the previous two biennials, which were largely contained
in SITE Santa Fe's gallery space, an 18,000-square-foot former beer
distribution warehouse, this year's exhibition included 10 other
venues, from a room at a motel to an old village dance hall to the
Los Alamos airport.
</P>
<P>
   Louis Grachos, the arts center's director, saw it as a good way
to involve the community. For Ms. Martinez it was also a political
act, a breaking away from what she called the nice, white museum
walls.
</P>
<P>
   The biennial's planners received official permission to use all
of the sites. But they may have lost sight of the fact that in this
rapidly developing area, protecting your place can be tantamount to
survival. Some of the places chosen for the exhibition already
belonged, spiritually, to others, and were already imbued with
their own potent meanings.
</P>
<P>
   One of them was San Ildefonso Pueblo, 21 miles northwest of
Santa Fe, perhaps the most well-known of the northern New Mexico
pueblos because of the highly collectible black pottery made there.
On its land is the Black Mesa, a sacred spot, where the Pueblo
fought against the Spanish in 1694.
</P>
<P>
   According to the proposal she submitted, the Mexican artist
Yolanda Gutierrez intended her installation ``Nos Susurra el Rio y
Silva la Serpiente/The River Whispers to Us and the Snake
Whistles'' to be ``a new symbol of brotherhood between the North
American and Mesoamerican cultures.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Gutierrez built an 82-foot-long snake of styrofoam and
covered it with ears of yellow and blue corn, then floated it on a
lake at the pueblo. Two days later it was gone, removed after
religious elders objected to the piece. While the feathered serpent
Quetzalcoatl was a central deity of the Aztecs, snakes hold
different, and more negative, meanings for the Pueblo people.
</P>
<P>
   The problem may have been that the religious elders were
offended by the symbolism, or it may have been a power struggle
between them and the governing body of the tribe, which approved
the project without community involvement. More than likely it was
both.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Gutierrez, who does not speak English, said she regretted
not giving a community presentation about her work. ``There wasn't
anyone available to help translate,'' she said, and on the day of
the installation there was no time to explain what she was doing
because a rainstorm was brewing and the focus was on getting the
piece in the lake quickly.
</P>
<P>
   The second work that stirred protective feelings was installed
at Our Lady of Guadelupe cemetery on the edge of downtown Santa Fe.
The Swedish artist Carl Michael von Hausswolff's installation ``Red
Night'' was a simple project consisting of about a half-dozen
spotlights covered with red filters and timed to bathe the
graveyard in red light from dusk to 11 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Permission for the installation had been granted by the city,
the neighborhood association and the church's parish council. But a
parishioner with relatives buried in the cemetery attended the
opening ceremony, found the project offensive and asked the pastor
to have it removed.
</P>
<P>
   What Von Hausswolff had hoped to accomplish by lighting the
cemetery, he said, was to draw attention to a forgotten place. ``It
was almost like a garbage dump,'' he said of the somewhat neglected
burial ground, and because of his installation it had been cleaned
up. Then the attention had taken another form.
</P>
<P>
   ``When one does outdoor projects, one has to be prepared for
what might happen,'' said von Hausswolff, who stood outside the
long and narrow cemetery on the fourth, and last night it was
lighted. The parish allowed the installation to remain that long to
give him an opportunity to document it.
</P>
<P>
   During a panel discussion on the proliferation of biennials that
was part of the opening weekend, the first question from the
audience had to do with the two removed artworks. Was finding
something ``radical'' always the goal of a curator in selecting
work?
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``You want to bring in ideas that you support, ideas that you
find challenging,'' said Okwui Enwezor, the director of the
forthcoming Documenta XI in Kassel, Germany. He asked,
rhetorically, whether the illumination of the cemetery had been
radical. ``I think it is important to ask that question,'' Enwezor
said.
</P>
<P>
   Harald Szeemann, the director of the Venice Biennale and a
member of the panel, offered a more blunt explanation to a reporter
afterward. ``This is what happens when you take art to the
peasantry,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Martinez, an independent curator from Barcelona, Spain, who
directed the recent Istanbul Biennial, said she had chosen artists
for ``Looking for a Place'' who would ``seek to incite emotions.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The ideal biennial is a profoundly political and spiritual
event,'' Ms. Martinez said.
</P>
<P>
   One result is that no painters were invited _ painting had not
``renovated'' itself, she said _ and the exhibition, which
continues through December, is instead rich in photography as well
as installation and video art.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Martinez is eager to cross boundaries in her definition of
an artist. Among the participants exhibiting in the SITE Santa Fe
gallery is the group Greenpeace, which is showing several huge
photographs documenting its environmental actions.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Martinez said she had invited the activist group to
participate because it illustrated how to think about certain world
problems. The only difference between Greenpeace and the other
participants, she said, is that ``Greenpeace participants do not
call themselves artists.''
</P>
<P>
   Another illustration of Ms. Martinez's desire to make
environmental concerns part of her examination of the meaning of
place is ``Map,'' a 25-by-48-foot arrangement of clear marbles by
the Beirut-born artist Mona Hatoum; in the shape of the world, it
dominates the floor of the main hall. The loosely situated marbles
are easily disturbed by the vibrations set off by people walking
nearby _ a metaphor, Ms. Martinez said, for the fragility of the
earth.
</P>
<P>
   The Iranian photographer Shirin Neshat's video ``Rapture,''
examining male and female space in the Islamic world, emerges as
one of the biennial's strongest works. Two black and white
projections face each other: on one side are Iranian women wearing
chadors, on the other are the men. It is impossible to watch both
at the same time, and the viewer is forced, with each turn of the
head, to remain in the middle.
</P>
<P>
   The Argentine artist Sergio Vega contributes a diorama examining
the idea of paradise. It is a continuation of work that Vega, who
lives in New York, began with a show in March at Basilico Fine Arts
in Soho.
</P>
<P>
   It is not surprising that one of the most successful of the
off-site installations _ a piece that takes the area head-on and
encourages spectators to explore its contextual landscape and
social setting _ comes from the one artist who lives in New Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Charlene Teters, a Spokane Indian who is on the faculty of the
Institute of American Indian Art in Santa Fe, plays off the
monument in the center of the city's plaza and notoriously
dedicated to ``the heroes who died in various battles with savage
Indians.''
</P>
<P>
   At the height of the American Indian Movement in the 1970s,
someone climbed over the fence surrounding the obelisk and chipped
out the word ``savage.'' Teter's obelisk of adobe bricks, which
sits in front of the New Mexico State Capitol Building, bears a
single word: ``Savage.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Martinez said she was satisfied with the results of the
biennial, even though two of the works had been taken down almost
as soon as the show opened.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we cannot see this snake in the lake of San Ildefonso
Pueblo for six months, we will see it in the documentation,'' she
said. ``The miracle has happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Installation work, of course, is by its very nature ephemeral,
never created to last.
</P>
<P>
   ``It may have been a little bit more ephemeral than expected,''
she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
