u i BC-AMNESTY-TIMOR-BOS &LR;      08-18 0639
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMNESTY-TIMOR-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MILITIA ATROCITIES IN TIMOR CITED BY RIGHTS GROUP 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds.: T. Kumar is cq)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN DONNELLY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Less than two weeks before a vote on East Timor's
future, anti-independence militias connected to Indonesia's
military have killed, tortured and illegally detained activists,
Amnesty International charged Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Indonesian government, which annexed East Timor 24 years
ago, denounced the report, calling it one-sided. ``We are doing the
best we can in maintaining security in East Timor,'' said Sofi
Suarma, an official at the Indonesian Embassy here. ``The situation
has improved recently.''
</P>
<P>
   But T. Kumar, the human rights group's advocacy director for
Asia and a former political prisoner in his native Sri Lanka, said
Indonesia has failed to protect the pro-independence movement while
allowing the militia nearly free reign. The vote is set for Aug.
30.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign of violence, he said, continued Wednesday with
militiamen brandishing guns, spears and machetes, injuring several
independence supporters near the western border town of Maliana.
</P>
<P>
   Anti-independence factions ``continue to enjoy the support or
acquiescence of the Indonesian military and police,'' the Amnesty
report said. The violence has killed dozens of civilians and
displaced tens of thousands of people. Kumar said about 200
pro-independence activists have been arrested in the past month.
</P>
<P>
   Since January, when Indonesian President B.J. Habibie
surprisingly offered the 800,000 people of East Timor a vote to
gain full independence or remain part of Indonesia as an autonomous
region, violence has surged in the region.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though Habibie made a promise, the militia is basically
out of control in East Timor,'' Kumar said Wednesday at a news
conference. ``We hope by releasing the report now, it will increase
pressure on the Indonesian government to fulfill the promise it
gave.''
</P>
<P>
   East Timor activists have captured international attention for
their long struggle for independence. Two leaders, Bishop Carlos
Ximenes Belo and Jose Ramos-Horta, received the Nobel Peace Prize
in 1996. The country, for generations a Portugese colony, appeared
on the verge of independence in the mid-1970s when Indonesia
brutally invaded and massacred tens of thousands.
</P>
<P>
   Even though most observers predict that a majority of East Timor
residents would vote for independence, the referendum could still
be postponed.
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations has delayed the vote twice already, and its
officials could do so again if the security situation worsens. The
UN headquarters was a target of anti-militia activists, and
analysts believe that UN observers could face further danger.
</P>
<P>
   ``The United Nations could be caught in the middle,'' said
Jonathan S. Paris, a fellow at the Council on Foreign Relations and
co-editor of ``The Politics of Post-Suharto Indonesia.''
</P>
<P>
   If UN observers are in danger, ``the question then would be
whether the US Marines would come in to help them,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   For Paris, the increase in violence was predictable.
</P>
<P>
   The anti-independence forces _ portions of the military,
Japanese business interests and nationalist Indonesians who fear
other independence movements will try to break away from the nation
_ ``have such clear-cut losses with an independence vote. And those
people who stand to lose have so much control and power now,''
Paris said.
</P>
<P>
   East Timor's future has also played a role in the run-up to
parliament's upcoming vote on Indonesia's presidency, which pits
Habibie against front-runner Megawati Sukarnoputri. Megawati has
said Habibie ``ignored the constitution'' by agreeing to the East
Timor vote, but she said her government would respect the outcome.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
