<HEADLINE>
TEEN DRUG USE IS DOWN, US SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By EUN LEE KOH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Teen drug use dropped last year, but use among
young adults continued to increase, signaling worrisome trends for
the group, the government announced Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Health officials, releasing the annual National Household Survey
on Drug Abuse, reported that the rate of drug use among the general
population has steadied.
</P>
<P>
   Although the drop among teens is encouraging, ``we have a long
way to go,'' said Donna Shalala, secretary of Health and Human
Services.
</P>
<P>
   The survey, which interviewed 25,000 people ages 12 and up,
found that 9.9 percent of teens, ages 12-17, had used some sort of
drugs in 1998, down from 11.4 percent in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Among young adults, ages 18-25, the figure rose to 16.1 percent,
a rate that has been inching up since 1994, when usage was at 13.4
percent. In particular, cocaine usage rose to 2 percent last year
from 1.2 percent in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Officials attributed the growing statistic to the fact that the
same group of people who used drugs as teenagers are using drugs
now as young adults.
</P>
<P>
   The survey estimated that about 13.6 million people had used
drugs in 1998, a slight decrease from the 13.9 million in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Shalala said the leveling of drug use in the general population
shows that the nation has ``turned the corner'' in the battle
against illicit drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Teen drug use had shot up in the mid-1990s, but has leveled off
since then. Earlier reports of decline have been met with
cautiousness, but health officials said this year's survey results
gives them renewed confidence that a real decline is under way.
</P>
<P>
   According to the survey, the percentage of teens who had ever
tried drugs had also dropped, to 16.4 percent last year from 18.8
percent in 1997. The survey also showed a decline in the use of
marijuana _ by far the most popular drug _ to 8.3 percent from 9.4
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, however, teen drug use is almost twice as high as it
was early in the decade, when usage was at a low of 5.3 percent.
Marijuana use among youth was also at its lowest in 1992 at 3.4
percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``The message is finally getting through,'' Shalala said. ``But
we have a long way to go because more than a million young people
are dependent on drugs. ...That's a million too many.''
</P>
<P>
   According to the survey, marijuana draws nearly twice as many
users as cocaine, LSD, heroin and other drugs combined. Some 11
million Americans smoked marijuana last year, similar to last
year's figures.
</P>
<P>
   The survey also found tobacco use to be at its lowest recorded
rate _ about 27.7 percent of Americans admitted to smoking last
year, a slight drop from the 29.6 percent in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   But the rate of teen smoking has remained steady at about 18
percent, and among young adults, the rate has increased to 41.6
percent in 1998 from 40.6 percent in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past couple of years, the rate of drug use has
increased among minority groups. The percentage of blacks using
drugs rose to 8.2 percent last year from 5.8 percent in 1993. Drug
use among Hispanics rose to 6.1 percent from 4.4 percent during
those years.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the increase among some groups, health officials
remained optimistic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our number one mission is to educate and enable our young
people to reject illegal drugs,'' Shalala said. ``That means
pushing ahead until we are not only around the corner, but we are
all the way home.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
