<DOCNO> NYT19990818.0305 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-18 20:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2087 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-FBN-GALLOWAY-TEX     08-18 0823
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-GALLOWAY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EVEN THOUGH FADED AWAY, DYNASTY TALK HASN'T DIED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WICHITA FALLS, Texas _ Membership is in steady decline. ``The
Glory Days Gang'' is now more exclusive than ever. Time flies in
football. It's amazing how quickly heroes are reduced to relics.
</P>
<P>
   A mere three NFL seasons ago, the Dallas Cowboys were a mighty
dynasty. But today?
</P>
<P>
   ``What we once had, we probably took for granted,'' said
receiver Michael Irvin as training camp opened last month. ``It's
human nature that only after you lose something special do you
finally come to appreciate it.''
</P>
<P>
   Pausing, Irvin added, ``Now we are trying to get it back. And
that's the hardest part.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the impossible part. The Cowboys of the '90s will not be
the Cowboys of '99. Raw numbers tell the story _ only 10 players
remain with three Super Bowl rings from the decade. Only 15 are on
the roster from the most recent Super Bowl victory, January of '96.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been gone just four years, but it's amazing how many guys
on this team that I don't know,'' said free-agent signee Mark
Stepnoski, an original member of the dynasty foundation group.
</P>
<P>
   Troy Aikman is another key dynasty alum. He went on record early
in this training camp as saying he would be retired by now if he
didn't think the Cowboys could and would return to Super Bowls.
</P>
<P>
   Safety Darren Woodson has his three rings, and refuses to
discuss any other team goal other than winning the Super Bowl
again.
</P>
<P>
   Irvin agrees totally.
</P>
<P>
   Stepnoski watched his teammates from afar for four seasons _
``afar'' being wherever the Houston-Tennessee-Oilers-Titans
happened to be located, which was Houston, Memphis and then
Nashville.
</P>
<P>
   His return to the Cowboys in the off-season was a football
natural. The Cowboys needed a veteran, quality center and, at age
32, Stepnoski fit the description. Plus, he had the old Valley
Ranch roots along with two Super Bowl rings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was tired of not winning, I know that,'' said Stepnoski, who
accepted the free-agent riches offered by Houston after the 1994
season.
</P>
<P>
   But in his Dallas return, was a thought also given to helping
revive the glory days of the '90s?
</P>
<P>
   ``Not really,'' said Stepnoski, shrugging. ``I don't know our
team well enough at the moment to have an opinion on Super Bowls or
anything like that.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I did like was after a bad season (the 6-10 record in
'97), they came back and played well last year. They flipped the
record back to 10-6, and even with the disappointments in the last
part of the season, turning around a team in this league is harder
than most people think.''
</P>
<P>
   Stepnoski is optimistic about the Cowboys being a team on the
upswing under Chan Gailey's coaching guidance.
</P>
<P>
   ``But,'' he added with a smile. ``I know if you're not talking
Super Bowl in Dallas, no one wants to hear about it. The good and
the bad is that everyone is spoiled. But that speaks to the history
of the team.''
</P>
<P>
   Going into this training camp three weeks ago, there was reason
for optimism. Not necessarily Super Bowl optimism. But a strong
free-agent class, including Stepnoski, combined with high hopes for
the rookie draft class, cast a positive glow over the campus of
Midwestern State University.
</P>
<P>
   The Deion-Leon issue was even being shoved a bit to the
background.
</P>
<P>
   But while Gailey won't admit it, and neither did Aikman
Wednesday, camp progress has been minimal _ actually, there might
have been no progress thus far. The scene is murky, to say the
least.
</P>
<P>
   Three key components of the offense _ new receiver Rocket
Ismail, starting guard Everett McIver and tight end David LaFleur _
have contributed nothing. Because of injuries, none of the three
has taken an exhibition game snap, although LaFleur is expected to
play Saturday night in New England.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the expanded role in the offense of running back
Chris Warren is on hold again this week. He missed much of last
season with a severe groin muscle strain, and the ailment has
flared again.
</P>
<P>
   The defense has its Leon-Deion issue, but cornerback has also
become an injury hole, and ailing free-agent linebacker Quentin
Coryatt is waiting on his first snap in two years. There is,
however, a better balance of good news-bad news on defense, because
of the camp emergence of young linemen Peppi Zellner, Ebenezer
Ekuban, Nathan Davis and Brandon Noble, and rookie linebacker Dat
Nguyen.
</P>
<P>
   Also on the upside, and Gailey points this out repeatedly, the
regular season opener is still 24 days away.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not where we want to be, but we have time to change
that,'' Gailey said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Glory Days Gang,'' however, is as impatient as the common
fan. They still talk Super Bowl, even in the midst of a training
camp full of injury blahs.
</P>
<P>
   Old habits are difficult to change, no matter what reality might
suggest. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-18-99 2006EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
