<DOCNO> NYT19990818.0312 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-18 20:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2097 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-SIBLEY-HOMILY19-COX     08-18 0993
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SIBLEY-HOMILY19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Celestine Sibley homily
 &HT;    By the Rev. Patricia Templeton
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   EDITORS: The Rev. Patricia Templeton is associate rector of St.
Timothy's Episcopal Church, Signal Mountain, Tenn.
</P>
<P>
   Heavenly God, we thank you that by water and the Holy Spirit you
have bestowed upon this your servant the forgiveness of sin, and
have raised her to the new life of grace. Sustain her, O Lord, in
your Holy Spirit. Give her an inquiring and discerning heart, the
courage to will and to persevere, a spirit to know and to love you,
and the gift of joy and wonder in all your works. Amen.
</P>
<P>
   This prayer is not one that is normally heard at a funeral. It
is a baptismal prayer, one that sums up the characteristics that we
hope will distinguish the life of a baptized Christian _ a life
sustained by God and marked by forgiveness and grace, curiosity and
discernment, courage and perseverance, faith and love, and joy and
wonder.
</P>
<P>
   I cannot think of better words to describe the life of the
valiant woman we are here today to remember, to honor, and to
commend to the care of a loving God _ Celestine Sibley.
</P>
<P>
   Celestine was a woman of great faith, a woman whose life was
sustained by God. Hers was not an ostentatious, preachy, pious kind
of faith, but a lived one.
</P>
<P>
   It was evident in the well-worn Bible beside her favorite
reading chair, and the snippets of Scripture that frequently
appeared in her writings.
</P>
<P>
   And it was evident in her ability to see that all people are
created in God's image, her ability to respect the dignity of every
human being _ whether it be her homeless friends or the governor.
Celestine knew that the best way to show her love of God was to
love the people God has created.
</P>
<P>
   One of Celestine's favorite hymns was the one we sang at the
beginning of this service, ``Come, thou fount of every blessing.''
It strikes me as characteristic of her in its honest portrayal of a
life of faith _ that we are all prone to doubts and wanderings, but
even then we are sustained by the grace of a God who searches us
out and knows us.
</P>
<P>
   The last time I talked to Celestine, a few days before she died,
she said, ``I want you to know that I am going to be OK.''
</P>
<P>
   These were not the words of a woman clinging to a false hope
that some last-minute miracle was going to rid her of cancer.
Celestine was much too honest and smart for that.
</P>
<P>
   These were the words of a woman who knew, as St. Paul says, that
neither life, nor death, nor angels, nor rulers, nor things
present, nor things to come, nor height, nor depth, nor anything in
all creation can separate her from the love of God.
</P>
<P>
   Celestine's spirit was one that knew and loved God. Perhaps
because of that faith and love, she was blessed with the gifts
enumerated in the prayer for the newly baptized.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly hers was an inquiring and discerning heart. From the
time she was a teenager she made her living by inquiring. She had
the wonderful ability to be truly interested in almost anything and
anyone. She could never understand how anyone could possibly be
bored when life was so interesting.
</P>
<P>
   Celestine's inquiring heart was one of the things that made her
a great reporter. But what distinguished her was the combination of
her innate curiosity with the gift of discernment. She
instinctively knew what would make a good story, just as she could
instinctively discern the truth of a situation.
</P>
<P>
   But her gift of discernment really shone in her ability to see
the extraordinary in the ordinary events of life.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to look sharp, you have to pay attention, to catch
small, quiet, often fleeting blessings and know them for what they
are,'' she wrote. Celestine, perhaps more than anyone I've known,
had the ability to do that.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting under an apple tree, learning to ride a bicycle,
salvaging furniture from a dump, holding a baby, going to work each
day, talking with family and friends _ these ordinary moments
contain life's most extraordinary blessings, as she frequently
reminded us in her columns.
</P>
<P>
   ``An awareness of the nowness of happiness is not easy to come
by,'' she wrote. It was that awareness, that ability to discern, to
know happiness at the time it happened, that distinguished
Celestine.
</P>
<P>
   That does not mean that her life was a bed of roses. She was no
stranger to tragedy, illness, death and struggles to feed a family.
But through it all Celestine had the courage to will and to
persevere.
</P>
<P>
   Like the valiant woman in the book of Proverbs, Celestine rose
while it was still dark to begin her work. She did not eat the
bread of idleness.
</P>
<P>
   Some might call her perseverance stubbornness. She insisted on
driving until the doctor ordered her not to. She insisted on coming
to work long after others would have stayed home.
</P>
<P>
   At the end, she faced her death as she lived her life, with
courage and grace. Strength and dignity were indeed her clothing.
</P>
<P>
   And finally, among Celestine's greatest gifts was her joy and
wonder in all God's works.
</P>
<P>
   She delighted in the joys of nature _ the flowers in her garden,
walks in the woods, trips to the mountains and the beach.
</P>
<P>
   And most of all she found joy in the wonder of relationships _
with her children and grandchildren, with her beloved Muv and Jack.
And with her countless friends and readers. Celestine had the most
amazing capacity for friendship of anyone I've ever known.
</P>
<P>
   And so today, her children, grandchildren and friends rise up
and call her blessed, and say to her, ``Many women have done
excellently, but you surpass them all.''
</P>
<P>
   And now Celestine, may the angels lead you into paradise.
</P>
<P>
   May Muv and Jack and all the saints rise up to greet you and
bring you into the holy city Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   May the choirs of angels receive you.
</P>
<P>
   And may you rest in peace and joy eternally. Amen.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
