<DOCNO> NYT19990818.0313 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-18 20:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2098 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-SIBLEY-MEMORIAL19-COX     08-18 1047
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SIBLEY-MEMORIAL19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Goodbye, to a `lady of great gifts'
 &HT;    By Dan Hulbert
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Reluctant to release her but happy to celebrate her,
Atlanta on Wednesday said goodbye to Celestine Sibley.
</P>
<P>
   The people she touched during her many years as a newspaper
writer could never all fit under one roof, but several hundred of
them managed to cram into the memorial service at North Avenue
Presbyterian Church. It was there that The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution reporter and columnist used to claim balcony
seats in the 1940s, so that she could get a clear view of the
stained-glass windows and explain their Bible stories to her
children.
</P>
<P>
   It was a lovely, dignified service, televised live on
WXIA-Channel 11, which Sibley undoubtedly would have called too big
a fuss. The crowd was a decidedly ``Celestine'' mix: media
personalities and just-folks sitting elbow to elbow, answering the
ministers in traditional call-and-response style. The only
adornment was an altarpiece of ordinary flowers _ bluebells,
daisies, black-eyed Susans _ so breezily jumbled together that the
writer herself might have scooped them from the north Fulton garden
her readers knew so well.
</P>
<P>
   Later, at a reception after the service, many funny stories were
told to ward off tears, but that age-old strategy didn't always
work.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel as though my roots have been chopped off, because I'm a
small-town girl like she was,'' said Kay Kephart, a Druid Hills
housewife and community volunteer, her voice cracking. ``Celestine
was my aunt, my neighbors, all my friends who used to sit around
talking on the front porch.''
</P>
<P>
   Declaring Sibley ``a lady of great gifts, honesty and heart,''
Rep. John Lewis (D-Ga.) invoked the more mischievous side of the
columnist. When Lewis was named a ``saint'' by Big Bethel AME
Church a few years ago, he joined Sibley _ the only white person
ever to receive that honor _ in the Big Bethel choir.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told Celestine I wasn't much of a singer,'' Lewis recalled
with a smile, ``And she said, `Neither am I. Stand next to me, and
we'll both pretend.'''
</P>
<P>
   In the service's prelude, the achingly sad strains of Samuel
Barber's ``Adagio for Strings'' conveyed the sense of loss, the
silencing of the backyard bard who wrote of politicians and
vagabonds, philosophy and trivia, gardens and books, cabbages and
kings. Then, as if to nip grief in the bud, the audience rose and
boomed out an almost defiant rendition of ``Come, thou fount of
every blessing.'' The hymn was a favorite of Sibley, who died of
cancer Aug. 15 at age 85 and took a hand in planning the service
with family members in recent weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Not by coincidence, probably, another of the selections was
Sibelius' ``Be Still, My Soul,'' which was played just a few months
ago at the memorial for actress Mary Nell Santacroce, another
Atlanta institution and an old friend of Sibley's.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps taking a cue from Sibley's 10,000 columns, eulogists
Bill Emerson, former Atlanta bureau chief for Newsweek, and Jack
Nelson, former Constitution reporter and retired Washington bureau
chief of The Los Angeles Times, managed to pack deep affection and
raucous humor into brief speeches.
</P>
<P>
   ```Heaven Bound' is the theme of this celebration, and she will
hoot at that,'' Emerson declared. ``Just 10 days ago she told me,
`Get them to stop this legend talk _ tell them I'm not a legend!'
Well, there's going to have to be some celestial intervention to
edit out all the legend talk.''
</P>
<P>
   Emerson painted a woman far tougher and more determined than her
readers might have guessed. Once he heard a commotion outside his
departing train and looked out to see the long-legged Sibley,
``running like a maniac'' alongside, banging her typewriter on the
locked doors until Emerson managed to haul her aboard.
</P>
<P>
   ``Celestine was not a goody two shoes,'' Emerson said. ``If you
were seriously rude to Celestine or one of her friends or family,
she would tack your hide across her next column. ... She wrote
about buds opening, fragrances wafting, love triangles, grisly
murders _ she loved murders.''
</P>
<P>
   When Sibley planned a farewell trip to her beach house on Dog
Island, Fla., she told Emerson, ```If that doctor tries to stop me
I'll push him out the window.'''
</P>
<P>
   Nelson said of Sibley, ``No one was better at standing beside
you in time of trouble.'' He quoted former Georgia congressman Jim
Mackay as saying, ``She loved people in all walks of life in
Georgia, and she has received that love back _ and it's not easy to
be loved if you're a newspaper person.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the distinguished guests were former Gov. Samuel Ernest
Vandiver and his wife, Sybil.
</P>
<P>
   Sibley's many and varied friends in attendance included Ruth and
Ruby Crawford, twins with whom she often lunched downtown in the
1940s, who came to the service in matching peach floral outfits.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're from a small town, we had so many things in common with
her,'' said Ruby. ``One thing we always knew _ on the first freeze
of the fall we would be out in our gown-tails at midnight bringing
in the potted plants. We took comfort in knowing that Celestine was
out in her gown-tail, too.''
</P>
<P>
   There was perfect rightness in the presence of the choir from
Big Bethel, whose aformentioned ``Heaven Bound'' morality play
Sibley attended nearly every year. The choir sang ``Steal Away,'' a
spiritual near to the columnist's heart. She once wrote that when
she tried to sing it with the choir, ``I couldn't get a word out _
I cried like a fool.'' The rendition at the service had the same
effect on many of her old friends. Singing with a hushed power,
like a wave that builds and builds but never breaks, the choir
concluded the song with the line, ``I ain't old got long to stay
here.''
</P>
<P>
   Many testified that the words and memory of Sibley will stay
long indeed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll remember her,'' Emerson declared, ``as long as we
remember anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Big Bethel's postlude was that old rouser, ``When the Saints Go
Marching In.''
</P>
<P>
   ``She used to pat her feet to that song,'' said choir member
Gregory Coleman. ``Ooooooh, she loved it.''
</P>
<P>
   Staff writer Gayle White contributed to this article.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
