<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-18 20:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2108 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-STAROFDAVID19-COX     08-18 0352
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STAROFDAVID19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mississippi school bars Jewish star
 &HT;    By Anne Rochell Konigsmark
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Officials at a Mississippi high school have forbidden
a Jewish student to wear a Star of David necklace because they say
it looks like a gang symbol.
</P>
<P>
   The parents of Ryan Green plan to file a lawsuit Friday in
federal court against school officials, charging that their son was
denied his constitutional right to religious freedom.
</P>
<P>
   Ryan, who was given the necklace over the summer by a relative,
wore it to school on the first day of class last week, according to
officials. A teacher saw it and told him to tuck it into his shirt
or leave it at home.
</P>
<P>
   When his parents heard about the ban and protested, the Harrison
County school board held a hearing Monday night. The board voted
unanimously to uphold the ban.
</P>
<P>
   The Harrison County sheriff's office said the six-point star,
known around the world as a symbol of the Jewish faith, also is a
symbol used by the Black Gangster Disciples along the Mississippi
Gulf Coast.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has nothing to do with religion,'' said Frank Baskett, a
spokesman for the sheriff's office. ``This is a safety issue. If
the black gangsters stopped using a six-point star and started
using a crucifix, I would be back in school tomorrow advising them
to ban crosses from school property.''
</P>
<P>
   The Harrison County schools prohibit students from wearing
anything that can be construed as a gang symbol. Baskett said if
school officials allow Green to wear his necklace, then all of the
gang members will ``become Jewish and claim religious sanctuary''
to wear them as well.
</P>
<P>
   David Ingebretsen, head of the American Civil Liberties Union in
Mississippi, said fear of gangs is no excuse for taking away
religious freedom.
</P>
<P>
   ``Schools should be able to find a way to protect religious
expression and still have a safe environment,'' said Ingebretsen,
who is helping the Greens with their case. The Greens could not be
reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
