<SLUG> BC-MARKET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOW STUMBLES, DROPPING 1.3 PERCENT 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By ROBERT D. HERSHEY Jr.    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Stock prices slumped Wednesday as investors took
profits from the recent rally, the dollar weakened and
interest-rate jitters continued.
</P>
<P>
   Bond prices rose, causing the yield on the bellwether 30-year
Treasury to flirt with a level just under 6 percent, a key
threshold in market psychology.
</P>
<P>
   After approaching its mid-July peak on Tuesday, the Dow Jones
industrial average gave ground early Wednesday, steadied, then
stumbled again in the final 30 minutes to finish with a loss of
125.70 points, or 1.13 percent. IBM was a prominent late casualty.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pullback in the dollar, certainly against the yen, has
weakened stocks,'' said Elaine H. Yager, a senior analyst at Herzog
Heine Geduld.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts also said some investors were cashing in profits ahead
of the expiration of options contracts on Friday and the Federal
Reserve's policy meeting on Tuesday, which is widely expected to
result in a quarter-point rise in the overnight lending rate among
banks.
</P>
<P>
   A surprisingly strong earnings report by Dell Computer and a
recommendation of eight Internet stocks by Merrill Lynch's
influential analyst, Henry Blodget, helped keep the Nasdaq average
in positive territory most of the day before it, too, slipped and
ended down 13.49 points, or 0.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Investors in the bond market were buoyed by official purchases
and continued the previous day's strong rally, pushing the 30-year
issue during the day to just under 6 percent, a quarter percentage
point less than a week ago, before finishing right at 6 percent.
The rate on the 10-year bond, a benchmark for mortgages, eased a
bit further, to 5.86 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Fears about a string of interest rate increases appear to be
subsiding on the comforting news this week that inflation remains
in check.
</P>
<P>
   ``The stock market continues to trade without a lot of
conviction,'' said Richard E. Cripps, chief strategist at Legg
Mason Wood Walker in Baltimore. ``But seeing the long bond rally is
probably the best thing.'' Trading volume remained subdued.
</P>
<P>
   The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index fell 11.32 points, to
1,332.84, or 0.8 percent, midway between the other major indexes.
</P>
<P>
   IBM was the biggest factor in the decline of blue-chip Dow
index, skidding 4|, to 123~, after changing hands as high as 129|.
</P>
<P>
   But 20 of the other 29 stocks in the index also fell, with
American Express losing 3, to 137\, Johnson &AMP; Johnson 2[, to 96
3/16, and Minnesota Mining 2], to 95 9/16.
</P>
<P>
   Blodget, the Merrill Lynch analyst, recommended eight Internet
stocks he saw as benefiting from this year's holiday shopping
season, perhaps tripling revenue from online sales and advertising.
</P>
<P>
   He predicted the shares, which ``offer a sound way to play the
fundamental strength and renewed investor enthusiasm'' expected in
coming months, would surge 50 percent to 100 percent by yearend.
</P>
<P>
   All his picks rose. Amazon.com jumped 3~, to 113[, America
Online 1 11/16, to 99 3/16, and Yahoo 6 3/16, to 145 1/16. His
other picks were Etoys, Excite at Home, Lycos, Inktomi and
Barnesandnoble.com.
</P>
<P>
   A lesser factor in Wednesday's session was a report that
Fidelity Investments, the biggest mutual fund group, sold a net
$4.6 billion of technology stocks during the second quarter,
shrinking positions in America Online, as well as in Texas
Instruments, Oracle and Intel.
</P>
<P>
   Dell Computer, which reported a bigger-than-expected earnings
gain after Tuesday's close, gained 3 7/16, to 44 9/16, adding about
as much to the S&AMP;P 500 performance as IBM subtracted. Only 112
index components rose, compared with 370 that fell.
</P>
<P>
   Saks Inc. dropped 1 13/16, to 17 3/16, after warning of lower
profits this year; Talbots, another retailer, climbed 1 15/16, to
32 9/16, on sharply higher quarterly earnings. Reader's Digest rose
1], to 33, after announcing tripled earnings that beat forecasts.
</P>
<P>
   Hannaford Bros. soared 9 1/16, to 72}, on a deal to be acquired
by Food Lion, which slumped 2 11/32, to 8 13/16.
</P>
<P>
   On the New York Stock Exchange, 1,799 issues fell compared with
1,195 that rose; 65 stocks made 52-week lows, while 51 reached new
highs.
</P>
<P>
   Volume of 677 million was slightly below Tuesday's 690 million.
</P>
<P>
   Overseas, stocks advanced about 0.5 percent in London but fell
that much in Frankfurt. Sao Paulo's Bovespa and Mexico City's Bolsa
skidded 2.37 percent and 2.12 percent, respectively, while Tokyo
showed little change.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
