<SLUG> BC-POSTAL-AWARD-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JURY AWARDS WOMEN DAMAGES IN SUIT AGAINST POSTAL SERVICE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DEBORAH TEDFORD 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ A Houston mail clerk has been awarded nearly $890,000
in damages, lost wages and interest, after a jury found the U.S.
Postal Service had retaliated against her for filing discrimination
complaints.
</P>
<P>
   Another clerk involved in the same case was awarded $10,000 in
damages and $3,000 in back pay, plus interest.
</P>
<P>
   The amount of the damages was $500,000 less than a jury had
awarded Diana Lyn Gamboa in February after finding she and fellow
clerk Linda D. Slusser were victims of retaliation.
</P>
<P>
   In an amended judgment filed Tuesday, U.S. District Judge
Vanessa Gilmore said federal law sets a $300,000 cap on total
damages that can be awarded to parties in a single lawsuit filed
against a large employer.
</P>
<P>
   Gamboa and Slusser were clerks at the North Houston Mail
Processing Center when they filed suit in 1994. They claimed that
they and hundreds of employees in the Postal Service's Houston
District were subjected to retaliation for filing complaints with
the service's equal employment opportunity office.
</P>
<P>
   The women said they were targeted for harassment because they
filed EEO complaints _ on their own and in behalf of other
employees _ about the poor working environment at the Postal
Service.
</P>
<P>
   Gamboa, an official with the American Postal Workers Union,
filed dozens of complaints on behalf of union members and
represented 50 employees in labor disputes. Slusser also filed EEO
complaints for herself and for co-workers.
</P>
<P>
   The women said the retaliation ranged from being denied bathroom
breaks to suspension without pay to termination.
</P>
<P>
   Gamboa said Postal Service officials monitored her EEO
activities in a computer database shared by management, labor
relations and the union. She said she was harassed almost
continually.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, confidential information about medical treatment
she was undergoing was made available to unauthorized personnel at
the Postal Service, court documents indicate.
</P>
<P>
   In September 1992 Gamboa filed a complaint alleging that her job
was eliminated because of her EEO activity. Court documents state
that an administrative judge with the Equal Employment Opportunity
Commission held a hearing and recommended a finding of
discrimination based upon retaliation.
</P>
<P>
   Six months before the lawsuit was filed, Slusser said she saw
supervisors harassing Gamboa. When Gamboa filed an EEO complaint
listing Slusser as a witness, the women were suspended for 30 days.
</P>
<P>
   Gamboa was fired June 17, 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Jurors found that the service had intentionally retaliated
against both women for filing the discrimination complaints.
</P>
<P>
   The jury awarded Gamboa $800,000 in damages, but Gilmore reduced
it to $300,000, the legal cap.
</P>
<P>
   She was also awarded $264,604 in lost wages, plus interest, from
the date she was fired until the date of the judgment, and another
$322,955 plus interest in pay that she would have earned had she
continued in her post until 2003, the year she turns 55.
</P>
<P>
   Slusser, who is still employed by the Postal Service, was
awarded $10,000 in damages and $3,000 in back pay, plus interest.
</P>
<P>
   Gilmore also ordered the Postal Service to pay the women's
attorney's fees _ $374,734.
</P>
<P>
   Norm Scherstrom, spokesman for the Postal Service, declined
comment, saying the service is considering an appeal.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
