</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEATWAVE-VACATION-1200(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOT SPOTS LOSE VACATION CROWDS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Minn., S.C., Fla., Ga., Colo., Nev., Ohio, Pa. Texas, Va.,
Alaska , Calif., N.J., Del., Wash., Mich.)   By EDWIN McDOWELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Everybody talks about the weather, but this summer lots of
vacationers have been doing something about it _ namely, avoiding
or minimizing the effects of a heat wave that has had much of the
nation sweltering through one of the hottest summers in recent
years.
</P>
<P>
   With temperatures soaring to triple digits, crowds have been
bigger than ever at beaches, water parks, mountain resorts and
air-conditioned malls, while attendance has lagged at amusement
parks, golf courses and shops in the torrid zones. If not locked
into nonrefundable airline tickets or hotel reservations, many
American vacationers have been doing their best to escape the heat
and humidity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I planned to take my vacation in the Southeast,'' said Steve
Loucks, a recent transplant to Minneapolis from Virginia. ``But
after I read about the heat and humidity back there I decided go to
a cool spot.'' On Sept. 3, Loucks will fly to Alaska for a week.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Moluf of Naperville, Ill., a bartender, was looking for a
place where he and a dozen relatives could get together, but
because of the heat they did not even consider the East Coast.
Instead, they spent last week at Winter Park, a Colorado ski resort
whose Web site advertises ``Beat the Heat Getaways'' from dozens of
U.S. cities.
</P>
<P>
   ``That promotion has done wonders, because we've had people come
from Florida, Georgia, Texas and all over, just to cool off,'' said
Joan Christensen, a Winter Park spokeswoman. But people fleeing the
sun have not only been staying at resorts, they have been dropping
in on friends and acquaintances.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year my husband and I didn't have any summer visitors,''
Ms. Christensen said, ``but this year we've had friends come visit
for a total of about 30 nights, mostly friends from states where
it's boiling hot.''
</P>
<P>
   At Yellowstone National Park, where the weather this summer has
been warm but not punishing, attendance rose 5.7 percent in June
over the same period last year and rose 0.4 percent last month. ``A
lot of the visitors are probably people who were escaping the heat
back East,'' said Marsha Karle, a park spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   The twin attractions of gambling in an air-conditioned city are
paying off big for Las Vegas, Nev., which earmarked $5 million to
attract visitors this summer.
</P>
<P>
   The number of visitors rose 13.3 percent in June over the same
month last year, the biggest monthly increase in almost five years.
As a bonus, for those who ventured outside, the city set a record
for the most July days _ 14 _ in which the maximum temperature did
not hit at least 100 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   But record temperatures in much of the nation this summer have
been highs, not lows.
</P>
<P>
   In Myrtle Beach, S.C., one of the many hot states, crowds this
summer have flocked to the beach and to stands selling drinks and
ice cream, but not to the Pavillion Amusement Park.
</P>
<P>
   ``The heat has hurt,'' said Glenn West, director of marketing
for the Pavillion. ``When the heat index gets above 100, people
stay away. And we had 10 days in a row during July and August where
the heat index has been over 100.''
</P>
<P>
   Heat and humidity have played havoc with attendance at other
amusement parks, cutting into concession sales as children and
parents have returned to the air-conditioned comfort of home or
hotel rather than wilt outdoors. But attendance has held up at
water parks in most parts of the country.
</P>
<P>
   Big crowds have been reported at Soak City, part of the Cedar
Point amusement park and resort in Sandusky, Ohio; Schlitterbahn
Water Park Resort in New Braunfels, Texas.; Wildwater Kingdom in
Allentown, Pa., and Hurricane Harbor in Los Angeles, whose pool has
constant 2-foot waves.
</P>
<P>
   Not so on the golf course. From the Carolinas to Michigan,
soaring temperatures have kept some of the most dedicated golfers
off the links in mid-afternoon and early evening despite efforts to
lure them with lower fees. ``In this part of the country it's
unusual to have temperatures in the 80s at night, but we had them
in July,'' said Brett Marshall, executive director of the Golf
Association of Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   The Furnace Creek Golf Course in California's Death Valley
National Park, the hottest spot in North America, prohibits play
from noon to 4 p.m. As if to atone for the inconvenience, it offers
a $25 ``extreme golf six-pack'' consisting of green fees, cart,
clubs, balls, tees and a gallon jug of water.
</P>
<P>
   This month, though, Death Valley has had a number of days when
the daily high temperature has been below 110 degrees _ in other
words, almost balmy, compared with the 129 degrees recorded last
July (5 degress less than the record temperature set in 1913).
Those milder temperatures might account for the apparent increase
in American travelers to Death Valley this summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not so bad because it's not humid,'' said Maria Malone, a
teacher in Minneapolis who spent Monday night at Death Valley with
her husband, George, a teacher in St. Paul. Neither of them minded
the 115-degree temperature on a picnic that day.
</P>
<P>
   ``We came to Death Valley,'' Malone said, ``because it's a
beautiful nature area and we like to hike and take photographs.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   In many cities, including beach resorts, the combined heat and
humidity probably made it feel like, or worse than, Death Valley.
For six weeks in a row through July, crowds at the beaches in Ocean
City, N.J., exceeded 100,000 each Saturday and each Sunday. Farther
down the coast, in Delaware, crowds have flocked to Rehoboth Beach.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our ice cream sales are down compared with last year,'' said
Ed Fornwalt, owner of the Royal Treat Breakfast and Ice Cream
Parlor in Rehoboth. ``When you get hot sun and burning sand, people
don't want to walk to buy ice cream or much else. They want the
beach or an air-conditioned mall.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There were about three weeks when the tremendous heat cut down
on foot traffic and that affected business downtown, because people
were hugging the water line,'' said Carol Everhart, executive
director of the Rehoboth Beach Chamber of Commerce. ``But we've had
one perfect beach day after another.''
</P>
<P>
   People from Houston, San Antonio and other hot spots in Texas
have been flocking this summer to Corpus Christi, whose site on the
Gulf of Mexico has helped moderate summer temperatures that
frequently exceed 90 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   In some places, however, it is the absence of heat that has
caused concern. At Mount Ranier National Park near Ashford, Wash. _
a park that draws about 2.4 million visitors a year, and which
early this month attracted Vice President Al Gore and Albert Gore
III, his 16-year-old son _ attendance is down from last year,
possibly way down.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had horrible weather in the Northwest this year, cool
and rainy instead of warm and dry,'' said Bob Dopiriak, the fee
coordinator at Mount Ranier. ``When you can see the mountain from
Seattle, it's a 14,000-foot billboard, and the visitors come,'' he
said. ``But when you can't see it through the clouds and rain, a
lot of them don't bother.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
