<HEADER>
A2126 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-CYC-LANCE-MONEY19-COX     08-18 0566
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CYC-LANCE-MONEY19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Armstrong endorsements reach $6 million
 &HT;    By Suzanne Halliburton
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ It's been less than a month since Lance
Armstrong became an international celebrity by winning the
prestigious Tour de France. But during that time, big-money
corporations have been pitching six to seven-figure endorsement
deals to the Austin resident in an attempt to get the world's top
cyclist to be their corporate spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong has signed new endorsement deals, some going through
the year 2004, with a total value of $6 million since his victory
ride on the Champs Elysees in Paris on July 25.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lance is somewhat astounded by what's happening now,'' said
Armstrong's agent, Bill Stapleton, president of Capital Sports
Ventures in Austin.
</P>
<P>
   ``The numbers are pretty staggering, and he's really
flattered.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to his new endorsement deals, he has signed a
contract extension with his team, U.S. Postal, which will pay him
$2 million in 2000, or five times his base salary in 1999.
Combining salary and endorsements, Armstrong should make $5 million
just in 2000, or about $100,000 more than Emmitt Smith did playing
running back for the Dallas Cowboys last fall.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong has pledged to donate at least $250,000 to his Lance
Armstrong Foundation from his 2000 salary.
</P>
<P>
   In the coming weeks, people throughout the United States will be
able to see Armstrong in television commercials for Bridge
Information Systems, the largest provider of financial
</P>
<P>
   news and information in North America, American General
Insurance, and the U.S. Postal Service. In the week after his
victory, he was the subject of a ``Just Do It'' commercial by Nike
Inc., one of his apparel and equipment sponsors.
</P>
<P>
   Bridge Information Systems also has purchased a large video
screen in New York's Time Square to play its Armstrong commercial.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lance Armstrong's energy, intelligence, and ability to compete
successfully in every part of the world exemplify the qualities we
believe characterize Bridge and the Bridge family of companies,''
said Tom Wendel, Bridge chairman and chief executive officer.
</P>
<P>
   Also after his win, Armstrong agreed to a $500,000 movie deal
from Bud Greenspan and his production company and a $400,000 book
contract from Penguin Putnam Inc. The book, which will detail
Armstrong's battle with cancer and triumphant win in France, is due
in stores next spring.
</P>
<P>
   Stapleton would not reveal specifics of contracts, but said that
companies are paying a minimum of $500,000 annually to have
exclusive rights to Armstrong and at least $250,000 to use the
cyclist's name or image in their commercial pitches.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong also has been a popular motivational speaker since he
was diagnosed with advanced testicular cancer in October 1996.
Before the Tour de France, he made $30,000 per speech. Stapleton
said companies now are offering between $75,000 to $100,000 per
speech.
</P>
<P>
   There is at least one corporate executive who has expressed
disappointment that he didn't jump sooner on the Armstrong
bandwagon.
</P>
<P>
   ''We could have had him for $50,000 before the race,'' said
American Isuzu general manager Bob Reilly, whose company had a
corporate tie-in with the Tour de France. ``Now he's, what, $5
million?''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
