<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Not all's well in Primera
 &HT;    By Wendy Parker
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Primera Division season starts Sunday, and
Barcelona and Real Madrid, the overpowering giants of the Spanish
game, face some intriguing challenges. The two clubs, who together
have won 14 of the last 15 league championships, know too well that
possessing vast riches and the ability to buy the best players in
the world won't necessarily result in satisfaction. Or happy camps.
</P>
<P>
   For Barcelona, which won by a comfortable 11 points over Real
Madrid a year ago, reversing a recent string of poor European play
is essential. For the most part, Barca has an intact group of
regulars that, arguably, forms the best team in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Rivaldo, the subject of $50 million Manchester United transfer
rumors, probably will be the world player of the year for 1999. He
had 19 goals while Luis Enrique added 18, and Catalan hero ``Pep''
Guardiola returned from injury late in the season to inspire the
title drive. Forward Dani comes from Mallorca to give depth for the
Champions League.
</P>
<P>
   Dutch manager Louis van Gaal has eight countrymen on his roster,
including twins Ronald and Frank de Boer, striker Patrick Kluivert
and goalie Ruud Hesp. But unlike the beloved Johan Cruyff in the
'70s and '80s, van Gaal hasn't ingratiated himself to Barca fans,
who chronically carp about too many foreigners. Falling short of
expectations could make things worse.
</P>
<P>
   Real Madrid, European champions in 1998, fell apart last season,
mired in a coaching change and infighting that is far from being
resolved. Ex-Arsenal striker Nicolas Anelka got his wish to play in
Spain _ for a $36.6 million transfer price, the second-highest on
record _ but fitting him in could be tricky for manager John
Toshack, the subject of firing speculation. The club spent $80
million over the summer, so demands are notoriously high.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest concerns are on defense, where Michel Salgado (Celta
Vigo) and Julio Cesar (Valladolid) are the main additions. Up
front, Anelka must mesh with the electrifying Raul, who led Spain
with 25 goals, and Fernando Morientes, with 19.
</P>
<P>
   Valencia has a shot at its first league title since 1971 because
Claudio Lopez, second in the Primera with 21 goals, decided not to
transfer. He and Adrian Ilie form a powerful scoring duo, and the
club has improved the midfield by getting Oscar Garcia from Barca.
Former Mallorca boss Hector Cuper already has made a splash, as
Valencia upset Barca last week in the Spanish Super Cup.
</P>
<P>
   Cuper's old club, which had a best-ever third-place finish and
was runner-up in the European Cup Winners' Cup, will be hard
pressed to repeat because of heavy player losses. Celta Vigo was
fifth and could push the leaders with midfielder Alexander Mostovoi
and new strikers Benni McCarthy and Ivan Kaviedes.
</P>
<P>
   _ The darkhorses: Athletic Bilbao finished eighth despite its
Basque-only policy and wants to hold on tight to Ismael Urzaiz, who
had 16 goals.... Deportivo La Coruna faded down the stretch, while
Espanyol qualified for the UEFA Cup.
</P>
<P>
   _ Looking to do better: If Jimmy Floyd Hasselbaink continues
where he left off at Leeds, Atletico Madrid has hope to return to
the elite.... Denilson would like to forget last season at Real
Betis, which went through four coaches, but the prospects aren't
encouraging.
</P>
<P>
   _ Just glad to be here: Real Zaragoza, Real Sociedad and
Valladolid can't challenge the elite. Promoted Malaga and Sevilla
would love to reach the safety of mediocrity.
</P>
<P>
   _ Relegation zone: Rayo Vallecano and U.S. goalkeeper Kasey
Keller will struggle mightily to stay up, as will fellow newcomer
Numancia. Alaves, Racing Santander and Oviedo might be endangered
again.
</P>
<P>
   _ TV talk: After one season on ESPN2, the Primera Division will
be available only on pay-per-view. The new ESPN Extra will show
live games starting Sept. 11, supplanting Monday replays on ESPN2,
which will show one last freebie on Aug. 30 at 12:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Yugo-Croatia a scoreless draw
</P>
<P>
   The tension before the game was high in anticipation of the
first meeting, and it soared again after a light failure early in
the second half of Wednesday's Euro 2000 qualifying match between
Yugoslavia and Croatia in Belgrade. After 10-minute delay, the
rivals battled to a 0-0 draw. Several fans shouted anti-government
slogans in the darkness, including some calling for the resignation
of Yugoslav president Slobodan Milosevic. The game had been
postponed from March because of NATO bombing raids on Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   England: Gullit to get axe?
</P>
<P>
   Newcastle manager Ruud Gullit vowed to persevere despite rumors
of his dismissal. The Magpies fell to 0-3-0 Sunday in a humiliating
4-2 loss at Southampton.... Arsenal's injury situation took another
hit Monday when midfielder Emmanuel Petit was lost for 2-6 weeks
with a knee injury.... Manchester United captain Roy Keane will
announce his future plans at the end of the season, when his
contract expires. He is locked in a salary dispute with club
management, which now might be precluded from putting him on the
transfer list ...Robbie Keane (no relation), a 19-year-old scoring
sensation at Wolves of the First Division, is on his way to
Coventry City for $9.6 million.
</P>
<P>
   Germany: Top teams stumble
</P>
<P>
   An injury-time goal by Giovanne Elber earned defending champion
Bayern Munich a 2-2 draw with Hamburg in the Bundesliga opener
Saturday, while Bayer Leverkusen was held to a 0-0 draw with
Duisburg, as some of the German favorites started slowly. Borussia
Dortmund fell 1-0 to Kaiserslautern, as Olaf Marschall scored the
lone goal.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico: Puebla rises again
</P>
<P>
   After being relegated from the Mexican first division, Puebla
came up with a novel _ and controversial _ way of staying up. Club
officials went out and bought Union de Curtidores, the side which
had replaced it through promotion. On Saturday, the ``new'' Puebla
got a first-half goal from Jafet Soto to beat Celaya 1-0 in the
first weekend of the Torneo Invierno.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
