<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: DEATH TAKES A HOLIDAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also JUDGES-DEATH-PENALTY) 
(DW) 
 By BOB HERBERT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Chateau Elan resort in Braselton, Ga., is a nice place. It
has seven restaurants, four golf courses, several tennis courts, an
equestrian center, a winery, a huge outdoor pool and a spa.
</P>
<P>
   It's a great place to kick back, wiggle one's toes and compare
notes on ways to speed up the process of sending human beings to
their death, which is a main topic of conversation at the resort
this week.
</P>
<P>
   Hurry, hurry, hurry. Judges from the 11th U.S. Circuit Court of
Appeals, which covers Georgia, Florida and Alabama, are concerned
that it takes too long to get condemned criminals executed. But
these judges are not stupid. (Not all of them, anyway.) They know
that it's a lot more fun to talk about thwarting a careful review
of death penalty cases or denying adequate legal counsel to the
condemned or figuring out ways to execute the mentally ill if those
conversations can be interspersed with a round of golf, a
refreshing dip in the pool or a few stimulating sips from a mint
julep or a healthy shot of Kentucky bourbon.
</P>
<P>
   So, in the extreme comfort zone of Chateau Elan, they are
holding their State Capital Cases Symposium. They have invited as
their special guests some of the most rabid death penalty advocates
from that most rabid of death penalty states, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   A session devoted specifically (and, you can bet, fondly) to the
death penalty experience in Texas is to be led by the infamous
Edith Hollan Jones, a judge of the Fifth Circuit Court of Appeals.
Ms. Jones was once very high on the list of judges considered for
appointment to the U.S. Supreme Court by former President George
Bush. She is a death penalty champion who unabashedly favors
curtailment of post-conviction review. Once, during a last-ditch
oral argument on the eve of an execution, she famously complained
that the proceedings were keeping her from a birthday party for one
of her children.
</P>
<P>
   Another participant scheduled for that session is Michael
McCormick, the presiding judge of the Texas Court of Criminal
Appeals. In addition to being a death penalty zealot, McCormick has
long complained that the Supreme Court was wrong when it ruled in
1963 that states were required to provide lawyers for poor people
accused of felonies.
</P>
<P>
   As you can see, this is a tough crowd.
</P>
<P>
   It would be tragic if Texas managed to export its warped sense
of justice and blind efficiency in capital cases to other states in
the South, and perhaps beyond. Stephen Bright, director of the
Southern Center for Human Rights, has tried for many years to bring
competent legal counsel to the accused in capital cases across the
country. He said the process in Texas ``has the integrity of a
professional wrestling match.''
</P>
<P>
   Bright noted that Texas is a place where a defendant can stand
``virtually defenseless'' before a system that permits executions
in cases where there is no real adversarial process to determine
guilt or innocence, where in some cases lawyers have actually slept
through the trials, and where there is no real post-conviction
review.
</P>
<P>
   Putting aside the grotesquely inappropriate setting, the problem
with the gathering of judges and other criminal justice officials
at Braselton is not so much that there are zealots and extremists
among them, but that they are clearly setting the agenda. Their
goals are the wrong goals for a just and civilized society.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Baird, a former judge of the Court of Criminal Appeals
in Texas, said in an interview this week that the current emphasis
on speeding up the process undermined the whole point of a careful
review of capital cases, which is to insure that we don't kill an
innocent person or someone whose rights were violated in the
proceedings that resulted in a death sentence.
</P>
<P>
   The chief judge of the 11th Circuit, R. Lanier Anderson III,
denied that the desire for speedier executions was an overriding
concern of the symposium. He said he wanted all cases under his
jurisdiction decided fairly. He quickly added, ``But on the other
hand, we are interested in resolving cases with what I call
appropriate expedition.''
</P>
<P>
   The term has a ring to it. Appropriate expedition. It sounds at
least as innocent as compassionate conservatism.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
