<P>
   The New York Times News Service will move the following
entertainment/arts articles this week for release Sunday, Aug. 22,
1999. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT &AMP; ARTS (Moved in `e' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FEATURE story &LR;
</P>
<P>
   WHITE-RAP-MUSIC (Undated) _ Rap _ like most everything from the
blues to alternative rock before it _ has been officially embraced
by those who originally ostracized it, avariciously consumed by
those who it was invented in part to declare independence from. Of
course, rap has been integral to pop music and suburban youth
lifestyle since at least 1986, when the first rap album (by the
Beastie Boys) crossed over to number one on the Billboard charts.
But the difference is that back then, when white kids _ the Beastie
Boys, Rick Rubin and hard-rock bands like Faith No More and Anthrax
_ were getting into rap, it was a genre they were only just
discovering. Soon after, rappers began appearing who spoke almost
solely to white concerns, like Me Phi Me and Kid Rock, but they
didn't succeed because then because they were too early (and not
very good either). But today, rap is like the Beatles. It is a
birthright, something many white kids grow up listening to, a
standard by which they calibrate their lifetime notion of pop
music. By Neil Strauss. &UR;  &LR; (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FILM AND VIDEO &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ALBERT-BROOKS-FILMS (Los Angeles) _ A look at film director,
Albert Brooks, whose latest movie ``The Muse'' will open Friday.
Previous films that he has written, directed and starred in are:
``Real Life,'' ``Modern Romance,'' ``Lost In America,'' ``Defending
Your Life,'' and ``Mother.'' By Margy Rochlin. (Moved). Photo.
</P>
<P>
   TASTE-OF-CHERRY-VIDEO (Undated) _ In the way of most films by
the great Iranian filmmaker Abbas Kiarostami, ``Taste of Cherry''
approaches large questions through a constrained and fascinating
tale. By Peter M. Nichols. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DANCE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   FOUNTAIN-DANCE (Undated) _ The quirky story-ballet of Rostislav
Zakharov's ``Fountain of Bakhchisarai,'' which, though dating from
1934, had never been seen in New York until the Kirov Ballet
brought it to the Metropolitan Opera House this summer.
``Fountain'' arrived with a strange reputation. Based on a poem by
Pushkin, it dates from the time when Socialist Realism dominated
the arts in Soviet Russia. So it was easy to fear that it would toe
a dull party line. Instead, despite its occasionally trite score by
Boris Asafiev, it proved lively. By Jack Anderson. (Moved). Photo.
</P>
<P>
   LIVE-SAX-ACTS (New York) _ Two bare-chested men, wearing
tartanless kilts and effeminate jazz shoes, dance and play the
saxophone; the same pair, dressed in tuxedos, speak to each other
through bullhorns, slap each other's faces or grab each other's
crotches without flinching, all the while exchanging gentlemanly
chitchat; finally, as two guys in business attire, they wheel and
deal on the telephone. These are just some of the loaded images
that the choreographer-dancer Dan Dorfman and the
composer-performance artist Dan Froot have devised for their three
comic duets, ``Horn'' (1990), ``Bull'' (1994) and ``Job'' (1996),
respectively. The roughly 20-minute pieces have been performed
several times since their premieres as ironic accents in Dorfman's
and Froot's individual performance gigs. Now they will present them
as an evening unto themselves under the title ``Live Sax Acts'' at
Dance Theater Workshop. By William Harrris. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CLASSICAL MUSIC &LR;
</P>
<P>
   RABIN-RENARDY-MUSIC (Undated) _ Sony Classical's Masterworks
Heritage series was conceived to celebrate the past, but with a new
CD devoted to the violinists Michael Rabin and Ossy Renardy (MHK
60894), the label is also paying homage to two artists cut down in
their prime. Both players were already superior musicians when they
died, and in certain circles their demise still elicits palpable
regret. By David Mermelstein. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   SALZBURG-FESTIVAL (Undated) _ Salzburg is in good part a city of
shopkeepers, and streets are jammed with visitors spending money.
How much of a magnet the music festival is, and how much the small,
pretty and reasonably historic city surrounded by Alpine scenery,
is hard to judge. A lot of visitors, and they are 40 percent from
German-speaking places, don't look as if they can afford $400, or
even $100 tickets; residents often appear more prosperous than
their customers. Calls for a small-scale, small-budget, homegrown
festival have been heard, but businessmen are not protesting too
loudly about Gerard Mortier, who has ran the festival since 1991.
By Bernard Holland. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ART &LR;
</P>
<P>
   STILL-LIFE-ART (Amsterdam, Holland) _ A new show at the
Rijksmuseum here, ``Still Life: Paintings From the Netherlands,
1550-1729,'' with 70 carefully selected paintings, many on loan for
the occasion, claims to be the first exhibition to display all the
different types of still life from the golden age of Dutch and
Flemish painting. And it succeeds in demonstrating why they were so
popular in their day and why they are attracting new interest
today. The show runs in the Rijksmuseum's South Wing through Sept.
19 and will then be on display from Oct. 31 to Jan. 9 at the
Cleveland Museum of Art, which has a rich collection of still life
of all periods and is a co-organizer of this exhibition. By Alan
Riding. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   SITE-SANTA-FE-ART (Santa Fe., N.M.) _ The biennial exhibition of
international contemporary art that opened here last month was
devoted to exploring the meaning of ``place.'' But even before the
opening festivities were over, two installations had been shut down
precisely because of their locations. ``Looking for a Place'' was
the title of the third biennial sponsored by SITE Santa Fe, a
nonprofit arts center in a city that's a magnet for tourists. By
Ruth Lopez. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TELEVISION &LR;
</P>
<P>
   TV-BEHIND-THE-MUSIC (Undated) _ In the two years since it was
first broadcast, ``Behind the Music'' has become the music
industry's closet compulsion. Members of the media elite may not
blithely volunteer the information, but just start asking and
you'll be amazed at how many people admit to watching. ``Behind the
Music'' is ``Entertainment Tonight'' without the heavy cheese
factor, ``Biography'' minus the historical pretensions. It's a
simple, brilliant formula: a one-hour documentary about the ups and
downs of music careers, with subjects from Fleetwood Mac to David
Cassidy to the Red Hot Chili Peppers to Madonna. By Karen Schoemer.
(Moved).
</P>
<P>
   TV-STRANGE-JUSTICE (Undated) _ ``Strange Justice,'' a Showtime
drama (which has its premiere next Sunday night) is about the
controversial confirmation hearings of Clarence Thomas. Directed by
Ernest Dickerson, who has previously been director of photography
on six Spike Lee films, ``Strange Justice'' stars Delroy Lindo as
Clarence Thomas and Regina Taylor as Anita Hill, the former
colleague who testified that he had sexually harassed her. By
Bernard Weinraub. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   BESTSELLERS (Undated) (Moved.)
</P>
<P>
   PAPERBACKS (Undated) (Moved.)
</P>
