<HEADLINE>
INTELLIGENCE OFFICIAL IN ENERGY DEPT. DENIES RACISM IN ESPIONAGE
INQUIRY 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By WILLIAM J. BROAD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A top intelligence officer at the Energy Department strongly
denied on Wednesday that any racism was involved in his
department's yearslong investigation of a Los Alamos National
Laboratory scientist, Wen Ho Lee, for allegedly passing atomic
weapons secrets to the Chinese.
</P>
<P>
   ``Race was never a factor,'' the officer, Notra Trulock, said in
an interview. His department sent the names of about a dozen
suspects to the FBI, only three of which were Chinese-Americans and
the rest Caucasians, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We heard lots of talk about ethnic targeting,'' Trulock said,
referring to a counterintelligence technique that focuses on
particular ethnic groups because intelligence services often single
out people who may have cultural or political sympathies with
foreign countries.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we tried hard to be careful'' and to avoid any hint of
ethnic targeting, he said. ``That gets ugly real fast.''
</P>
<P>
   The Chinese-American suspects, he said, included Lee, his wife,
Sylvia, and a third unidentified individual. Lee eventually became
the primary suspect in the spying case, which was made public
earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   Lee, who was born in Taiwan, worked at the Los Alamos nuclear
weapons laboratory in New Mexico for more than two decades before
he was fired in March for violations of security rules. He has
denied spying for China and has not been charged with any crime.
</P>
<P>
   Trulock's denial of ethnic bias was prompted by the assertions
of the former head of counterintelligence at the Los Alamos
laboratory, who on Monday and Tuesday was quoted as saying that Lee
had been unfairly singled out because of his race.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a key factor,'' the former head of counterintelligence
at Los Alamos, Robert S. Vrooman, was quoted as saying in one of
the interviews. ``There were 83 people who went to China'' from the
New Mexican weapons lab in the 1980s, any one of whom might have
leaked secrets, Vrooman said.
</P>
<P>
   Overseeing all the Energy Department's counterintelligence
operations, including those at Los Alamos, Trulock in 1995
spearheaded the investigation of alleged Chinese espionage at the
nation's nuclear weapons laboratories and last year was a secret
star witness before a select House committee that eventually made
the issue public. The committee, in its report, charged that China
had stolen information about America's most-advanced nuclear arms.
</P>
<P>
   Vrooman's comments were apparently the first time an
investigator had publicly raised the issue of racial bias, though
some Chinese-American rights groups had previously done so.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
