<SLUG> BC-RUNAWAY-GROOM-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`RUNAWAY GROOM' MARRIES, BUT QUESTIONS LINGER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ELLEN BARRY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LITCHFIELD, Ct. _ A week after he removed his ``wanderguard''
security anklet and drove to New York City, the 74-year-old nursing
home fugitive who dubbed himself the ``Runaway Groom'' has, it
seems, made good his escape.
</P>
<P>
   It was last Tuesday when Harry Strouse left his Litchfield
nursing home and just kept going. Two days later, while state
police were searching for him and his attorney was pressing for his
return, he married 56-year-old Molly Bennett Aitken at City Hall in
New York, surfacing publicly only to vow to a reporter that he was
never coming back.
</P>
<P>
   By Wednesday, Strouse and Aitken were enjoying their first week
of matrimony at a sprawling green farmhouse full of Hummel
figurines and cockatoos in Athol, Mass. Although he had been
instructed by his lawyer not to speak to the press, Strouse
playfully knocked on his head to indicate that he was of sound
mind. Meanwhile, staff at the Rose Haven Convalescent Home, who had
given him a bracelet to prevent him from wandering off in a
disoriented state, said they were not expecting to see Strouse
again. And romantics everywhere were cheering an old man's lunge
toward freedom.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's my hero,'' said Sergeant J. Paul Vance of the Connecticut
State Police, who called off their case after seeing the couple's
marriage certificate. ``I tell my wife, `Now don't be pushing me
now.' ''
</P>
<P>
   But around Litchfield, where Strouse had lived for more than 30
years, two distinct possibilities hung in the air: Either Molly
Aitken had rescued Strouse from a nursing home he despised just as
his lawyer was stripping his decision-making power away from him;
or she had taken advantage of a disoriented and helpless old man
with a fortune his attorney described as ``a couple million
dollars'' and no heirs.
</P>
<P>
   Strouse on Tuesday fired the longtime attorney and friend who
had protested most vociferously against Aitken's role. Peter Litwin
had gone public with his misgivings about Strouse's sudden
marriage, arguing that his client had been diagnosed with dementia.
Litwin would not comment for this article.
</P>
<P>
   But Litwin's arguments have convinced many in town that the
marriage is darkly manipulative. For one thing, Strouse is openly
gay and had shown little interest in women. And several of
Strouse's friends said it was clear his mind had been slipping
precipitously in recent months. Strouse had been placed in Rose
Haven at the end of May because he had been found wandering around
his neighborhood late at night in a disoriented state, said Rose
Haven staff.
</P>
<P>
   And when he turned up missing, Litwin's concern went beyond the
legal obligations of a responsible lawyer, said one friend.
</P>
<P>
   ``Circumstances like this make a real dividing line between your
protection under the law and your protection by the community you
live in,'' said Joseph Tyler, an antique dealer who rents his shop
from Litwin.
</P>
<P>
   A different story comes from Burstein, a New York attorney who
took on Strouse as a client this week after he fired Litwin. She
says Strouse and Aitken had recently rekindled an old friendship,
and that Strouse had called Aitken crying, threatening to kill
himself if she didn't help him get out of Rose Haven.
</P>
<P>
   After they had crossed the New York state border that day, ``he
said, `Molly, you know I wanted to marry you 23 years ago, and I
have nobody, I'm alone and vulnerable,' '' Burstein said. ``I'm not
sure he was as articulate as all that. I'm not saying this is
Burton and Taylor, but she does love him as a friend. She is a
bighearted, generous, flamboyant woman.''
</P>
<P>
   She said Strouse had been in a foggy mental state when he
checked into Rose Haven and he had granted Litwin considerable
decision-making power that he later regretted. A hearing scheduled
for Thursday could give Litwin the status of ``conservator'' for
his estate, meaning the attorney would have more power over all
Strouse's decisions, and Strouse ``was horribly anxious about it,''
Burstein said.
</P>
<P>
   No one really knows how bad Strouse's mental state was, but in
hair salons and pharmacies all over town last week they were
willing to speculate. The verdict at the Patco Handy Store was
romantic, whereas the assembled crowd at Shear Perfection leant to
the gold-digger theory. Everyone had an opinion.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing that scares all old people is that they get into
these situations and they lose all control,'' said Hubert Van Asch
Van Wyck, who runs Black Swan Antiques on Bantam Road. ``People of
my generation, all of our parents are dying and going into nursing
homes, so it's a very timely story.''
</P>
<P>
   After Strouse's whereabouts were pinned down this week,
attention swung to his new bride, Molly Bennett Aitken, a mother of
six who has been living in New York. This is not the first time
that Aitken has found herself answering questions about strange
disappearances. She surfaced in the news about 10 years ago, when
she witnessed the dramatic airport abduction of seven Chinese
farmers she was hosting on her Athol farm. Aitken was at John F.
Kennedy airport greeting the delegation of 15, who she planned to
host on a 30-acre replica Chinese village on her Athol farm, when a
group of Asian men abducted seven of them.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, police officials in New York speculated the
abduction was either a kidnapping or part of a scheme to help them
defect.
</P>
<P>
   Burstein, who has known Aitken for four or five years, could not
comment on the 1990 abduction. She described Aitken as ``the kind
of person who believes she's saving the world,'' and said she fully
accepted Strouse as her third husband.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think she expects to be married to (Strouse) for the rest of
her life,'' Burstein said.
</P>
<P>
   The unfolding of this story has left friends and neighbors
scratching their heads, trying to figure out what to make of
Strouse running off with a woman they had never heard of through
decades of friendship _ and without getting in touch with them.
Thomas McBride, 70, a friend for more than 30 years, said the last
time he saw Strouse, several months ago, Strouse was ``lost'' and
not himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think he knows what happiness is now,'' said Thomas
McBride. ``He's in bad shape.'
</P>
<P>
   Many more simply wished Strouse well. As Bart Geissinger read a
newspaper account of his elderly friend's recent activities, a
smile spread across his face.
</P>
<P>
   ``I almost feel like there's an angle,'' said Geissinger, a
jewelry store manager who fixed Strouse's watch chain for years.
``Maybe he's got something figured out.''
</P>
<P>
   And others, while expressing their concern about his welfare,
said the move did not seem uncharacteristic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not terribly surprised that he might go off on an
adventure,'' said Peter Tillou, an art dealer and neighbor for 20
years. ``I laugh, because I know Harry, and Harry is full of
beans.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Globe correspondent Michael Mayo contributed to this story from
Athol, Mass.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
