<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-18 20:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2147 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-YUGOSLAVIA-POLITICS-8     08-18 1027
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YUGOSLAVIA-POLITICS-825&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YUGOSLAV-CROAT SOCCER GAME PRODUCES NO GOALS AND NO TROUBLE 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By STEVEN ERLANGER    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia _ A long-awaited, once-postponed and
politically charged soccer match between Yugoslavia and Croatia
passed off peacefully and rather anticlimactically Wednesday night,
finishing 0-0, much like the summer's demonstrations against the
rule of Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   But there was a taste for what might come at a major opposition
rally planned for Thursday night in Belgrade when a transformer at
the Red Star stadium failed a few minutes into the second half, and
the lights went out.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly chants aimed at Milosevic echoed around the stadium,
with many of the 60,000 people there yelling, ``Slobo leave!'' and
a popular, rhyming chant that goes in part, ``Slobo, you've sold
out Kosovo!''
</P>
<P>
   The game was televised nationally, but those chants were not
heard by viewers.
</P>
<P>
   The wait for the lights to come back on stretched on for 40
minutes, and officials gave some consideration to replaying the
whole game Thursday night. That led to immediate Balkan-style
speculation that the Milosevic government had intentionally blown
the power to make sure that the game would conflict with the
opposition rally.
</P>
<P>
   In an indication of the government's nervousness about Thursday,
however, state television news announced that police had arrested a
man from Cetinje with ``an explosive device fitted with a timer,''
apparently intended to be set off during the rally in front of the
Federal Parliament building.
</P>
<P>
   The police then warned, the announcer said, that others could be
planning such attacks, and they advised people to be careful,
especially regarding their children.
</P>
<P>
   The broadcast seemed a patent effort to discourage people from
attending the opposition rally, the first in Belgrade since the
Kosovo war. But the opposition is divided, and its best orator, Vuk
Draskovic of the Serbian Renewal Movement, has decided not to
attend _ at least as of Wednesday _ as has the former army chief of
staff, Momcilo Perisic.
</P>
<P>
   Another well-known opposition figure, Vesna Pesic of the
Alliance for Change, who had also been expected to speak, instead
traveled to Montenegro _ for safety, she said. Prosecutors asked
police to investigate her on felony charges for seeming to urge the
violent overthrow of Milosevic by citing ``the Romanian example,''
an apparent reference to the 1989 uprising against the Romanian
dictator Nicolae Ceaucescu.
</P>
<P>
   In a telephone interview Wednesday, Ms. Pesic said the charge
was ludicrous, but she left ``because you never really know with
them,'' meaning the government. Asked if the much ballyhooed rally
would be important now after so many defections, she said: ``Only
if the police or the regime starts a battle or an incident. It's
now just one of the rallies.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, in the southern city of Nis, Alliance leaders attracted
more than 20,000 people Wednesday to an anti-Milosevic rally. Zoran
Djindjic, the head of the Democracy Party, said Thursday's protest
in Belgrade would bring the end of Milosevic closer. ``Stage two of
Milosevic's replacement begins in Serbia tomorrow,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Milosevic appeared to be moving to flummox the
opposition again and to call their bluff, with a spokesman
suggesting that new elections might be called soon.
</P>
<P>
   Ivica Dasic, the spokesman for Milosevic's party, said: ``We
believe that there are more important things on the nation's agenda
than the elections, but if the opposition wants that, so be it. We
are ready.''
</P>
<P>
   Draskovic favors new elections but the opposition generally has
been wary, worried that the government might manipulate the voting.
</P>
<P>
   Opposition analysts and officials also say that they are not
ready for elections and not sure they could win one now against
Milosevic, especially in coalition with Vojislav Seselj, the
Serbian ultranationalist who heads the Serbian Radicals.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Seselj had said that the government was ready for
new elections and the opposition only has to agree to them.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Pesic of the Alliance for Change, which does not include
Draskovic, said her coalition probably would not boycott new
elections, as it did in 1997. But she suggested that the Alliance
would seek to turn the elections into ``a referendum on Milosevic''
by running a slate of nonpartisan experts.
</P>
<P>
   An opinion poll released Wednesday indicated that more than 70
percent of Serbs surveyed want a new government and an end to the
country's isolation. The poll of 1,000 people last week by the
independent Partner Marketing Research Agency suggested that
Milosevic and his allies could expect only 24 percent support if
elections were held now. The various opposition parties and
alliances would get around 40 percent, 18 percent would not vote
and 11 percent were undecided.
</P>
<P>
   But the margin of error was unclear, and private polling for the
opposition parties has produced pessimism among their staff about
new elections.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In Wednesday night's soccer match, a qualifying round for the
European championship, the players, who are professionals, behaved
sportingly toward each other. The game was originally scheduled for
March 27, but was postponed because NATO had begun bombing on March
24.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd was cheerfully venomous toward the Croatian team,
drowning out the Croatian national anthem and shouting, over and
over again, ``Kill the Ustashe,'' the Croatian fascists of World
War II. They seemed more fervent against the Croatians than against
Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   There were dire predictions of what might happen should the
Yugoslav side lose to the Croatians, whom they had not played since
1991 and the breakup of the Yugoslav Federation.
</P>
<P>
   Ivan Radovanovic, an independent analyst here, said it would
have been ``dangerous for the regime to lose this game,'' because
it would serve as another example of ``how the country has gone to
hell and how this regime has destroyed everything, including the
soccer team.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
