</P>
<P>
   TURKEY-QUAKE (Istanbul, Turkey) _ More than 1,000 relief workers
from 19 countries join the frantic search for victims of Tuesday's
devastating earthquake as grieving survivors raise an outcry over
shoddy construction practices and lax government regulations.
Although rescue workers continue to find people alive under the
rubble of collapsed buildings, the death toll climbs steadily:
According to an official count, 3,879 bodies have been recovered,
and more than 16,000 people are listed as seriously injured. By
Stephen Kinzer. (The story has moved in ``i'' news file.) 1,400
words.
</P>
<P>
   With:
</P>
<P>
   TURKEY-SCENE (Izmet, Turkey) _ People here spent their day
digging, sifting, grieving and increasingly despairing that those
who have not escaped from the rubble by now are probably dead. They
watched as bulldozers and front-end loaders tried to unearth
bedrooms, which is where most people were when the earthquake
struck. Then in the swirl of dust and smoke and sweltering heat,
residents picked through the rubble with hammers and chisels and
bare hands. As delicately as archaeologists, they teased out shreds
of clothing, old photos, scraps of furniture and, inevitably, the
bodies. By Edmund L. Andrews. (The story has moved in ``i'' news
file.) 1,200 words.
</P>
