   Sidebar, TURKEY-CENTER inside.
</P>
<P>
   FOLD
</P>
<P>
   METLIFE-SUIT (Undated) _ Metropolitan Life Insurance Co., the
nation's second largest life-insurer, says it has reached a
proposed settlement of class action lawsuits that charged that the
company used deceptive sales practices to cheat millions of
purchasers of life insurance policies and annuities. The company
placed the value of the settlement, intended to cover 7 million
current and past policyholders, at $1.7 billion, but costs like
lawyers fees and administrative expenses will also come out of that
sum. By Barry Meier. (Scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET in ``f'' news
file.)
</P>
<P>
   BOTTOM
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-ARTS (Tokyo) _ Famous art is leaving Japan, and only a
handful of bankers and art dealers know for sure where it is going.
The paintings, including large numbers of van Goghs, Modiglianis,
Renoirs and Picassos that vanished into Japan more than a decade
ago, are being resold abroad as a result of the country's economic
collapse. ``There's a loss of face associated with this art,'' said
Chieko Hasegawa, owner of the Nichido Gallery in Ginza. ``The sale
of these paintings sends two messages: that you have financial
difficulties and that you paid too much for them from the start.''
By Stephanie Strom. (The story has moved in ``e'' news file.) 1,700
words.
</P>
<P>
   NY-PAROLE (New York) _ Memos unearthed by the U.S. attorney's
office in its investigation into Gov. George Pataki's fund raising
provide a rare view of the close ties between Pataki administration
officials and aides at the governor's political arm. By Clifford J.
Levy and Laurie Flynn. (Scheduled to move by 9:30 p.m. ET in ``a''
news file.)
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-ECON (Beijing) _ In a drastic move aimed at reversing a
steady fall in prices, Chinese officials announce that they will
ban construction of any new factories that make a broad range of
ordinary consumer items, from refrigerators and air conditioners to
candy, apple juice and liquor. The ban also covers the construction
of luxury hotels, apartment and office buildings and department
stores. By Seth Faison. (Scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET in ``f''
news file.)
</P>
<P>
   INSIDE STORIES PROMOTED ON PAGE 1:
</P>
<P>
   STARR-DEPART (Washington) _ Kenneth Starr, the independent
counsel, is quitting as early as October to resume his legal
practice after a five-year investigation into President Clinton's
personal and business affairs. He has decided to remain in office
long enough to put his personal stamp on a final report summarizing
the findings of his inquiries. By Neil A. Lewis and David Johnston.
(The story has moved in ``a'' news file.) 1,100 words.
</P>
<P>
   NKOREA-MISSILE (Tokyo) _ The crisis over a possible long-range
missile test by North Korea appears to be easing, after the
Communist government says that it is ready to negotiate with
``hostile nations'' like the United States, Japan and South Korea,
which have adamantly opposed the missile launch. By Calvin Sims.
(The story has moved in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   LUTHERAN-EPISCOPAL (Denver) _ As leaders of the nation's largest
Lutheran denomination gather to debate one of the most important
ecumenical proposals in decades, controversy over that proposal has
produced an unusually energetic display of the push and pull of
politics within a church. What's at stake is a sweeping agreement
for close cooperation between the Evangelical Lutheran Church in
America and the Episcopal Church, a proposal that many here liken
to a marriage. By Gustav Niebuhr. (The story has moved in ``a''
news file.) 1,000 words.
</P>
