<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-DRUGS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH AGAIN REFUSES TO ANSWER QUESTIONS ABOUT DRUG USE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JULIE MASON 
and KATHY WALT 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Gov. George W. Bush steadfastly refused Wednesday to answer
questions about whether he ever used cocaine even as another
Republican governor and key Bush supporter _ as well as an
unrelenting drumbeat from Democrats and the national media _
demanded that he do so.
</P>
<P>
   Before leaving for a Louisiana campaign swing, Bush held an
Austin news conference to introduce the state's new education
commissioner. But Bush was peppered with renewed questions about
past drug use following a Dallas Morning News story and a New York
Times opinion column that reviewed the controversy over the Texas
governor's refusal to ``catalog my past.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush turned testy at the Texas capitol.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know what happens,'' he said, interrupting a reporter's
question. ``Somebody floats a rumor and it causes you to ask a
question. And that's the game in American politics and I refuse to
play it. That is a game and you just fell for the trap and I refuse
to play.''
</P>
<P>
   No evidence of his purported use of cocaine or other illegal
drugs has surfaced. Bush has acknowledged drinking too much, until
he quit immediately after his 40th birthday. He is 53.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's refusal to answer any questions about alleged illicit
drug use has become fodder for political opponents. On Wednesday,
it became fodder for at least one supporter as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``George W. Bush should address issues about private conduct,''
Gov. Frank Keating of Oklahoma told reporters. ``In today's world,
every one of us who serves in public office needs to answer
questions about conduct that is arguably criminal.''
</P>
<P>
   Keating, chairman of the Republican Governors Association and a
Bush supporter, stressed that he ``doesn't think there's anything
there'' in Bush's background. Keating added that whatever misdeeds
Bush may have committed ``were largely carousing in nature.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I really have tremendous admiration for Bush, but I think
these kinds of questions are legitimate,'' Keating said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush told reporters in Austin he does not know who started the
rumors of cocaine use and does not recall his campaign pinning the
blame on wealthy magazine publisher Steve Forbes, a competitor for
the GOP presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do I think they're being planted?'' he said. ``I know they're
being planted. And they're ridiculous and they're absurd and the
people of America are sick and tired of this kind of politics. And
I'm not participating.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked if his responses amount to a denial, Bush apparently
started to respond, saying, ``I'm ...''
</P>
<P>
   But he left his response hanging there and turned to another
topic.
</P>
<P>
   The highlight of Bush's campaign day was supposed to be a tour
of a Jefferson Parish, La., elementary school at which private
businesses have helped provide computers and paid for Internet
connections. Bush promotes that kind of private-public partnership
as a centerpiece of his Republican campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Bush also said in Louisiana that he may not participate in the
state's nominating caucus unless the state party can guarantee a
fair process.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the system is not open and the rules are fuzzy, and if it's
hard to find places where people can vote, I just think I'm going
to shy away,'' Bush said. ``If it's an open process where people
can participate, then I will participate.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he would rely on the advice of his newly appointed
state chairman in Louisiana, GOP Gov. Mike Foster.
</P>
<P>
   Foster, who was traveling the state with Bush, said details for
the as-yet unscheduled Louisiana caucuses remain uncertain.
</P>
<P>
   Across the nation, states have thrown the traditional nominating
process into disarray, by jockeying primary schedules to give them
more influence in the process. Louisiana in particular has been
trying to position itself as among the first states to vote.
</P>
<P>
   Foster, however, is facing larger problems at home than vagaries
in the caucus system. On Thursday, he is scheduled to testify
before the State Board of Ethics for failing to report on campaign
finance reports his 1995 purchase of former Klansman and
congressional candidate David Duke's list of political supporters.
Foster is expected to be fined.
</P>
<P>
   At an earlier stop in the day, Bush and Foster faced protesters
highlighting the connection between Duke and the two governors.
Foster called the protesters ``another hate group.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They are so bent on trying to develop hate between people,''
Foster said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he did not know the facts but called Foster ``my kinda
guy,'' while he disparaged Duke.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like David Duke's politics, I don't like where his
heart is, I don't like the bigotry and prejudice that he
represents,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   Asked his opinion on the issue before the ethics panel, Bush
said, ``I would tell you I respect him (Foster) a lot. I don't know
all of the facts, I don't know what the facts are, but I do know
that I trust Mike Foster. He's a good man.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush made his remarks while touring Jefferson Elementary School,
where children worked on computers amid cartoonish signs declaring
``I'm Drug Free.'' With that backdrop, Bush was asked once again
about the drug rumors.
</P>
<P>
   Giving no hint of his earlier irritation, Bush said he ``made
mistakes'' in his youth and learned from them, but would not offer
up an ``inventory'' of his transgressions. He said he wanted to
talk about what he believed in.
</P>
<P>
   What he believes in, according to Bush, is local control of
issues such as education. Asked about a recent decision by the
Kansas Board of Education to delete evolution from the curriculum,
Bush said it's not the role of the federal government to make those
decisions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's up to the local people to figure out how fast you
expose children to different thoughts about how the world
started,'' Bush said. ``I have no problem with children learning
about evolution as well as understanding that there are some who
believe in creationism as well. I think it's important that
children be exposed to different thoughts.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
