u i BC-TURKEY-QUAKE-BOS &LR;      08-18 0953
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TURKEY-QUAKE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REFINERY BLAZE THREATENS TO COMPOUND QUAKE'S DEVASTATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JONATHAN GORVETT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ISTANBUL, Turkey _ With international aid pouring into this
quake-ravaged country, foreign aircraft joined Turkey's battle
Wednesday to bring a blaze at its largest oil refinery under
control. The quake's death toll soared toward 4,000 as rescue teams
pulled body after body out of the rubble of crumbled apartment
buildings.
</P>
<P>
   More than 40 hours after one of the century's most powerful
temblors struck, 5,000 people were still trapped in the seaside
town of Golcuk alone, according to Anatolian news agency.
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Bulent Ecevit, besieged and heckled by an angry
populace, insisted his government was doing all it could to unearth
trapped bodies and help the estimated 18,000 people injured by
Tuesday's pre-dawn quake, the nation's deadliest in six decades.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest threat, Ecevit said, came from the raging blaze in
the Tupras refinery near Izmit, the epicenter of the quake nearly
60 miles east of Istanbul. Six storage tanks were ablaze, despite
efforts by firefighters and chemical firefightng foam dropped from
Israeli and private US planes.
</P>
<P>
   Flames and black smoke rose 300 feet from the refinery.
Residents feared that depots less than 1,000 feet away could also
explode. The refinery lies along a major fault line.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the fire spreads ... it would be a new disaster for
Izmit,'' said Memduh Oguz, the governor of this industrial city of
75,000 people. The main concern: a fertilizer facility with 8,000
tons of dangerous ammonia.
</P>
<P>
   The state-run oil plant, built in 1961 under US supervision,
provides more than a third of Turkey's residential- and
industrial-grade fuel. Many of the factories and businesses in the
quake zone _ which account for nearly 35 percent of Turkey's gross
domestic product _ depend on the plant. The quake undoubtably will
set back government efforts to sell off the estimated $2.5 billion
facility.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, an oil slick pushed out nearly a half mile from the
refinery into the gulf, despite the spraying of dispersants by two
Turkish vessels.
</P>
<P>
   Help came from the United Nations, Israel and even historic
antagonists Greece and Cyprus. Wednesday night, the US Navy
dispatched three ships, carrying 2,100 Marines and 1,000 sailors,
to waters off Turkey.
</P>
<P>
   Even disaster search-and-rescue veterans were stunned at the
scope of the destruction. ``This one's worse. Much, much worse,''
said Uri Bremer, whose Israeli team had worked to save lives after
a quake in Armenia and bombings in Kenya and in Argentina.
</P>
<P>
   A Turkish government spokesman admitted that it was impossible
to estimate casualties because wrecked roads and highways make
access impossible to many villages.
</P>
<P>
   Angry residents waited in vain for help. Baris Boster of the
daily paper Cumhuriyet, said that in Yalova, a port some 40 miles
south of Istanbul, no one had come for 10 or 11 hours after the
earthquake.
</P>
<P>
   In Golcuk, resident Hatice Oltuk also complained of no help.
``We just sat in the ruins crying,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   A mountaineering club used ropes and gear to try to pry away
building slabs in areas near Izmit. ``We have bulldozers, but no
cranes,'' said an exhausted volunteer, Mehmet Cagoglu, at another
site in Izmit. ``Without lifting gear, many trapped in the rubble
are unable to be reached and can even be crushed by the
bulldozers.''
</P>
<P>
   Some arriving international disaster specialists criticized the
lack of organization by the government _ and one group, from the
Austrian Red Cross, threatened to pull out in three days unless
they had direction from Ankara.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't been given any locations in which to work or
priorities by the authorities,'' complained the Austrian team's
leader, Raphael Etsikovec.
</P>
<P>
   Blame for the extent of the casualties was also leveled at
building contractors and local authorities _ notoriously corrupt
and reluctant to regulate. The Hurriyet newspaper was even more
blunt, running a front-page banner headline that charged
``Murderers!''
</P>
<P>
   ``Many buildings are built first and permission is granted
later,'' said Ferah Salman, of the Chamber of Turkish Engineers and
Architects. ``In the Istanbul Metropolitan area, 60 percent of the
buildings in planned development areas do not have any planning
permission.''
</P>
<P>
   Since 1990, her group has reported on four major earthquakes in
Turkey, but each time their recommendations have been ignored.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, builders reacted angrily to accusations of
responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``After every earthquake they make do with blaming a few civil
engineers and contractors,'' said the head of the chamber of civil
engineers, Fikri Kaya. ``If you want to find the real guilty ones,
you have to look at successive housing ministers and the officials
at the ministry.''
</P>
<P>
   The area is known for quakes, but this temblor, measured at 7.4
on the Richter scale, was the deadliest to hit Turkey since a 1939
quake. Experts and archival material conservatively put the toll
from that quake at 33,000.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday night, dwindling food supplies in some areas added to
the mood of desperation among the survivors. Crowds mobbed a convoy
of bread trucks that entered Izmit, and at sunset, refugees from
Izmit crowded around small fires, fearful of returning to any
structure while aftershocks continued.
</P>
<P>
   Ali, a Kurdish migrant to the region who lost two brothers when
his apartment building collapsed, stood in despair near one fire.
``We came here to work, to live,'' he said. ``But what have we
found?''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Wire service Material was used to prepare this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
