<SLUG> BC-BAG-HAZARD-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CARRY-ON BAG DANGER LEAVES FAA UNFAZED 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW BRELIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Last month a Harvard Medical School professor and his wife
boarded their Delta Air Lines flight at Logan International Airport
early and settled into their seats on the beginning of a trip _ via
New York _ to Stockholm.
</P>
<P>
   But it almost never took place.
</P>
<P>
   ``As usual, I was sitting in the aisle, and I was reading the
newspaper and I never saw it happen,'' said the 66-year-old doctor
who spoke on condition his name not be printed. ``There was a guy,
trying to put a very heavy suitcase in the overhead bin, and he
lost control. It hit me square on the head, and knocked me out.''
</P>
<P>
   The doctor came to within seconds, but he ``wasn't making any
sense,'' recalled his wife.
</P>
<P>
   Flight attendants asked if there was a doctor on board. One
stepped out of First Class and came back to assist the man. They
were colleagues, and after a few minutes _ including lying down in
the aisle to boost his blood pressure _ the man who had been hit by
the suitcase was feeling better. Paramedics arrived and examined
the doctor in the jetway.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was sure I was going to have a bad headache and stiff neck,
but I wasn't going to abort my trip to Stockholm,'' the doctor
recalled. Delta made him sign a medical release before he could
continue to fly.
</P>
<P>
   A freak accident?
</P>
<P>
   It is not, according to the Association of Flight Attendants and
Russell D. Robison, executive director of Injury Prevention Works,
a Pennsylvania nonprofit committed to preventing airline cabin
injuries. They estimate that, nationwide, 4,000 to 4,500 passengers
each year are injured by falling carry-on bags that range from
suitcases to laptop computers, from ski boots to bowling balls.
</P>
<P>
   With more than 600 million passengers flying this year, the
chances of being hit are remote, but critics _ and some victims _
contend neither the airlines nor the Federal Aviation
Administration are doing enough to regulate carry-on bags.
</P>
<P>
   Last December, the AFA, the flight attendants union, petitioned
the FAA to limit carry-on bags to one per person, limited in size
to its total dimension of width, length, and height not exceeding
45 linear inches, and weighing no more than 13 pounds. Unlike some
other proposals, the one-bag limit would include purses.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to safety concerns, Cynthia Kain, a spokeswoman for
the AFA, said that as planes become more crowded, passengers
cramming carry-ons into overhead bins make boarding and leaving
airplanes more time-consuming.
</P>
<P>
   The FAA did announce earlier this year a public awareness
program with the Luggage and Leather Goods Manufacturing
Association regarding carry-on bags called ``Think Small, Think
Smart, Think Safe.'' By contrast, the FAA heavily promoted a
``turbulence happens'' campaign to reduce turbulence-related
injuries. On average, 58 passengers a year are injured because of
turbulence.
</P>
<P>
   The FAA has stated that policies on carry-on bags should be
written by the airlines; that it is a competitive issue in a
cut-throat industry. Indeed, Continental Airlines is reconfiguring
some of its planes to increase the overhead compartments to permit
more bags on flights.
</P>
<P>
   Anne DeCicco, president of LLGMA, said one consistent policy
would be helpful not only for passengers but also for manufacturers
and retailers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are screaming for standardization because customers don't
know what to buy, and we don't know what to make, and retailers
don't know what to sell.''
</P>
<P>
   And then there is Robison, who has made the issue something of a
crusade. He says policy must come from the government, because
airlines are unlikely to act alone. British Airways did install a
secondary restraint system in overhead bins on some airplanes in
1990 and saw a significant drop in injury claims.
</P>
<P>
   ``Airlines end up having more room in cargo holds for paid
freight and mail,'' said Robison, noting the industry made $12
billion in freight charges last year.
</P>
<P>
   More than 95 percent of the people injured each year are sitting
in an aisle seat, said Robison, and the majority of injuries occur
during the cruise portion of the flight.
</P>
<P>
   Many airlines give warning at the end of a flight about being
careful opening the overhead bin because contents may have shifted
during the flight. Robison believes the warning should be more
forceful and given before takeoff, once the seat belt sign is
turned off, and on landing.
</P>
<P>
   At Logan, a month does not got by without a call to paramedics
to meet a plane because of someone injured by a bag falling on
them.
</P>
<P>
   Jimmie D. Reed, 51, was treated by emergency personnel upon
landing at Logan on June 3 _ one of three people checked out that
month by paramedics, none of whom was hospitalized _ after being
struck by a briefcase during the cruise portion of the flight.
</P>
<P>
   Reed, of Austin, Texas, was traveling with his wife and friends
for a trip to Paris, when someone went to get a blanket out of the
overhead bin and a briefcase hit him in the head.
</P>
<P>
   ``It broke the skin just above my left eye and by the time I got
to the restroom, I was bleeding down the side of my face,'' Reed
recalled. ``I had a black eye the whole time we were in France.''
</P>
<P>
   Last month, paramedics went to airplanes at Logan for carry-on
injuries three more times, one of which involved the Massachusetts
doctor. There were at least three other times people were injured
slightly but required no medical attention.
</P>
<P>
   Reed got a voucher from the airline for his shirt to be
dry-cleaned.
</P>
<P>
   The doctor is still waiting for word one from Delta. There was
no follow-up call, no letter of concern. But his colleague, the
doctor who responded to the flight attendant's call for assistance,
did hear from the airline. Last week he got a gift basket as a
token of thanks.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they sent him a basket of goodies, they could have at least
called to see how I was doing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
