<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-18 20:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2164 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BAYOU19-COX     08-18 2824
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BAYOU19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bayou brothers' bond, skill lead to basketball success
 &HT;    By Mike Tierney
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GALLIANO, La. _ Down the bayou you drive for miles and miles
along the narrow ribbon of water, past weathered trawlers and
houses on cinder block that connect one small town to the next.
Suddenly it appears, mirage-like _ a sprawling, stunning home
straight from the pages of Architectural Digest, fronted by a lake
and impeccably landscaped turf.
</P>
<P>
   You stomp on the brake pedal and climb out of your car to absorb
it all on the hot-as-gumbo summer day, and the humidity steams up
your glasses, adding to the hallucinatory effect.
</P>
<P>
   It is not the only strange sight around. A bit farther down the
road is the homeowner's workplace, a three-story, modern glass
edifice.
</P>
<P>
   A few more blocks, and you're at South Lafourche High, which
houses a 1998 state champion basketball trophy amid the football
prizes for which the area is known. It was wrested away from the
New Orleans parochial schools that wage pitched recruiting battles
over pre-teens and treat the titles as their birthright.
</P>
<P>
   Nor is this an illusion: Two college-bound residents of that
house _ one black, one white _ carry on like the brothers that they
are, genealogy be damned, signing an occasional autograph, sharing
the role of local hero like no other athlete since Bobby Hebert
came out of nearby Cut Off to quarterback the Falcons.
</P>
<P>
   Under a single expansive roof live two-thirds of Georgia Tech's
incoming freshman basketball class _ Clarence Moore and Ross
Chouest, brothers not by blood but certainly by sweat and tears.
When they left the marshlands of south Louisiana this week and
moved to the metropolis of Atlanta, a new chapter began in two
young lives, a chapter that cannot possibly match the one just
ended.
</P>
<P>
   (BREAK)
</P>
<P>
   Ross Chouest needed a tall teammate for his summer-league AAU
squad, someone who could score. Just out of seventh grade, he had a
roomful of trophies to show for individual and team achievements in
youth programs, along with a videotape of a TV interview he had
given. But the kid was tired of being The Man. A mutual friend put
him in touch with Clarence Moore, already beyond 6 feet tall and
outgrowing his nickname, Little Mo.
</P>
<P>
   They could not have come from more contrasting backgrounds.
</P>
<P>
   Ross' father, Gary, is president of Galliano-based Edison
Chouest Offshore, the world's largest privately owned offshore
vessel service company founded by his father, who still puts in
part-time hours at 86. The family employs two full-time
housekeepers, and a cook was on constant duty until recently. The
property, more than 80 acres, includes a guest house, a tennis
court, a pond occupied by swans _ and a gymnasium.
</P>
<P>
   The Chouests _ pronounced Shwests _ fly private planes on
fishing vacations to the islands often enough that catching blue
marlin is routine. They own a houseboat. They just unloaded their
yacht. They are down-home, low-key, humbly grateful for their
materialistic bounty.
</P>
<P>
   Clarence's father _ ``Big Mo,'' although he looks up to his
6-foot-5 son _ is legally blind and cannot work. His mother is
deceased. The Moores' home in Norco, within the shadows of New
Orleans, is modestly appointed but rich in atmosphere, thanks to
his cheery relatives. ``A comedy club'' is young Clarence's
description of his upbringing.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Chouest funded many of his youngest son's summer-league
teams, which drew talent from around the state. When Clarence
joined, he and Ross hit it off, and they were among five players
from that roster to enroll in the eighth grade at Archbishop Hannan
in New Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   They were the building blocks for the Hannan Project, a
basketball blueprint under the school's new coach. Ross bunked at
the Chouests' New Orleans lakefront condominium with his mother,
Carolyn, while Clarence made the weary commute from Norco.
</P>
<P>
   Once basketball practice began, Clarence would stay overnight at
the condo. An AAU coach hired by Gary chauffeured the boys between
their temporary home and school.
</P>
<P>
   Carolyn, a onetime teacher who had home-schooled Ross for years,
assisted Clarence with homework. The one-on-one attention
straightened out Clarence a year after he entered a maze of
in-school suspensions, mainly for cutting up in class.
</P>
<P>
   Then a band of students, two of them players, were caught
stealing firewood from a store, and the Hannan Project crumbled
before the paint was dry. The players were punished. The coach was
fired. Ross chose to withdraw and head back home. Clarence was
gone, too.
</P>
<P>
   But where? ``We had become the best of friends,'' Clarence said
about Ross, who added, ``You can't just take two people, put them
together and (automatically) have them mix. It just so happened me
and Mo got along.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether Clarence cried is a matter of debate _ he says no;
others say yes _ but it troubled him to see the arrangement
collapse.
</P>
<P>
   In Norco, Clarence's mother, Avis, was praying for a better life
for her son. A college graduate who had coped for years with a
variety of ailments, she was concerned about his academic decline
and her helplessness. An idea was floated: Why can't Clarence head
down the bayou and stay in the big house?
</P>
<P>
   For the Chouests, it was a slam-dunk call. They were fond of
Clarence. They had the means to feed another mouth. One of Ross'
three brothers was leaving to get married. Carolyn, who once wanted
only daughters (she had one), stayed up many late nights washing
uniforms as players hung out. No big deal if one moved in.
</P>
<P>
   And Ross had found a kindred spirit in sneakers, someone who
could ripen into a basketball force once his coordination caught up
with his rapid growth rate.
</P>
<P>
   ``We clicked instantly,'' Clarence said. ``There was something
special between us on the court.''
</P>
<P>
   Everyone was on board but Clarence Sr., who initially voted
against the plan. ``Leaving home, it was too early for him,'' he
says now. ``If he'd been 18, I would have thrown him a party. But
15?''
</P>
<P>
   Young Clarence understood: ``I don't think any man wants his son
to move away.''
</P>
<P>
   He and Mom double-teamed Dad. They convinced him that,
educationally and socially, it was the way to go. So, life imitated
art _ if you can call the old sitcom ``Diff'rent Strokes'' art _ as
the Chouests became Clarence's legal guardians.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time I spoke to her,'' Carolyn said about Avis, ``she
cried and said this was an answer to her prayers. I'm not sure if I
could have (let him go). It was a big sacrifice on her part,
knowing she didn't have much time to live.''
</P>
<P>
   From Kmart to Hilfiger
</P>
<P>
   From the time Avis Moore gave birth to her other child, Chris,
now 14, she had been on a precipitous decline. Pulmonary
thrombosis. Diabetes. Lupus. Rheumatoid arthritis. On the rare
occasions that she saw Clarence play, an oxygen tank was at one
side. At the other was Clarence Sr., who needed binoculars even in
tiny gyms to combat his failing eyesight, the possible consequence
of handling chemicals on his former job.
</P>
<P>
   Clarence took to his new digs so warmly that the Chouests
virtually had to push his car toward Norco 1 1/2 hours away to
visit his blood family. What was not to like? He swapped his Kmart
clothes for Hilfiger and Polo, his knock-off sneakers for Nikes.
They bought him a BMW and chipped in $50 a week spending money. He
could focus on jump shots and schoolbooks, and block out the
distractions back home.
</P>
<P>
   Any adjustments were trivial. Clarence found services at the
Chouests' church somnolent. ``I'm used to being pumped up,'' he
said, by roof-raising gospel songs. He missed one of his favorite
meals _ pigs' feet. He did not share the regional passion for
fishing and hunting.
</P>
<P>
   And the Cajun accents? ``They all talk funny here,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, however, ``It was such a blessing,'' he said.
``Everybody gets an opportunity in life. This was mine. I took it
and ran.''
</P>
<P>
   If Clarence needed any reinforcement, it came the day he was
hanging with the old crowd in Norco when one of them shoplifted
some candy. The police picked up Clarence, then released him after
confirming his innocence.
</P>
<P>
   Back in the 'hood, where many of Clarence's buddies were dealing
drugs and staying out all night, they poked fun at his new cultural
tastes, especially music. When he would pop in a Nirvana CD and
sing along, they would say, ``Man, are you turning white on us?''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, they were happy for him. ``Each one told me, `Don't mess it
up down there. Stick with it, bro.'''
</P>
<P>
   The reception from South Lafourche followers was mixed for both
players. Because neither had gravitated through the local school
system, they were seen by some as interlopers, basketball versions
of U.S. Senate candidate Hilary Clinton in New York state. One
teacher vowed never to attend another Tarpons game.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's always been a mindset here that we don't win state but
everybody who wants to play on the team can,'' Carolyn said. ``Some
parents thought their sons perhaps ranked higher ... than Mo and
Ross.''
</P>
<P>
   Clarence won over any skeptics, partly with his dedication. He
has been known to train in the summer heat while wearing a vest
loaded with weights.
</P>
<P>
   And there is the bubbly personality. His philosophy: ``No reason
to be sad about anything. I'm happy 24-7.''
</P>
<P>
   It didn't hurt that most of the locals worked for or with Ross'
father.
</P>
<P>
   And winning cures all, so the two were embraced as sophomores,
their second season, when the Tarpons reached the semifinals of 5A,
the state's largest classification. Ross, with the peripheral
vision of an Imax theater regular, was uncanny at sending special
deliveries to Clarence for easy baskets. But they also could flash.
Ross would drive in while sensing his sidekick on his trail _ just
in case, Clarence would ``woo-woo'' in falsetto _ and bounce the
ball off the glass. Clarence would swoop in, catch it in midflight
and jam.
</P>
<P>
   At home, the boys were treated as equals: same rules, same
clothes, same weekly allowance. When Clarence strayed _ and it was
never far _ he might be denied telephone privileges or friends
dropping by to watch movies and shoot pool. His mother had taught
him to set goals and reach for them. Veering off the straight and
narrow, he reminded himself, ``would jeopardize my future.''
</P>
<P>
   He did wind up in court once, temporarily losing his driver's
license because of a speeding ticket. The judge, a devotee of
Thibodeaux High, ended his stern lecture with a plea that Clarence
go easy on his team next season.
</P>
<P>
   Ross, also well-behaved, recalled a drinking-and-driving episode
in the BMW he received at age 15 _ since replaced by a Mercedes. It
drew the wrath of his normally reserved mother. ``It wasn't pretty
here for a while,'' Ross said.
</P>
<P>
   At least the message got through to Clarence. ``You stay on her
good side, it's smooth sailing,'' he said. ``I know how she can be
from that one experience with Ross. I've never really given her any
opportunities.''
</P>
<P>
   Generosity vs. jealousy
</P>
<P>
   By Clarence's junior year, his mother required oxygen around the
clock. The calls from home to report another hospitalization became
more ominous. Once, as he drove to Norco, ``a feeling came over me
that this was the last time.''
</P>
<P>
   It was. Avis Moore died at age 40.
</P>
<P>
   She was buried hours before South Lafourche played rival
Slidell. The team attended the wake, then lost by 30 points while
Clarence was away mourning.
</P>
<P>
   He was in uniform the next day and, unburdened at last, had a
break-out game. ``I was in a zone,'' he said. The Tarpons, beaten
five times until then, never lost again, exacting revenge against
Slidell in the finals and bringing home the trophy. The parade tied
up traffic like one of the occasional hurricane warning
evacuations.
</P>
<P>
   By their senior season, the legend of the Chouest family was
spreading. How Ross had begun organized ball at age 4 and won his
first national award at 9. How Clarence, banned from youth league
all-star tournaments for four years because he exceeded the height
limit, had found heaven down the bayou while his parents went
through hell back home. How Gary had maximized their potential,
building in the back yard a gorgeous gym with a high-tech cushioned
floor, paying summer-league expenses for the kids, chartering buses
and picking up hotel room tabs for the parents, paying Clarence's
tuition at Hannan ...
</P>
<P>
   The rumors were inevitable: Daddy's deep pockets factored in the
Tarpons' success. A harsh newspaper article in the New Orleans
Times- Picayune _ headlined ``The Best Team Money Can Buy?'' _
addressed talk of mass transfers to the school.
</P>
<P>
   Gary was puzzled. He concedes that his generosity was motivated
somewhat to provide Ross with players and coaches who would help
him improve and attract notice. But he maintains that his dollars
were devoted entirely to the summer leagues so Ross' teams need not
seek corporate sponsorship and so the players could be exposed to
college recruiters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been lucky in life,'' Gary said. ``If you have an
opportunity to help somebody, you try to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, only one other player switched to South Lafourche. As
for Clarence, the Chouests say he was an awkward greenhorn when
they took him in, not the blue-chip player of the year he became.
The state athletics association investigated all three transfers
and found nothing untoward.
</P>
<P>
   A day after the story was published, Carolyn told Gary she was
headed to the hairdresser's in New Orleans. Instead, she marched
into the newspaper, which printed her lengthy letter rebutting
parts of the article.
</P>
<P>
   Clarence and Ross wrote the hubbub off to jealous gossip. ``If I
was getting paid to come here,'' Clarence joked, ``I'd have a big
house on the lake and be driving a Land Cruiser.'' Ross long before
had sensed that some people saw him as pampered, eating from a
silver spoon. ``Comes with the territory,'' he said. His play
belies that stereotype. Tarpons coach Scott Bouzigard said no
player ever worked harder for him.
</P>
<P>
   South Lafourche staggered through an 11-loss season this year
but returned to the championship game. Bouzigard thought the
Tarpons could repeat only by shifting Ross from shooting guard to
point guard, so he could set up Clarence for baskets. ``The bond
they share is what makes them extra-special players,'' said
Bouzigard, who had his own special-delivery boy 22 years ago. The
pass he caught that clinched a state football title for the local
school came from Bobby Hebert.
</P>
<P>
   Early in the game, Clarence was angered by an overly aggressive
foul. He said, ``If Ross sees I'm (angry), he knows to get the ball
to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Consider it done. Clarence rang up 35 points. But the rest of
the Tarpons scored only 13 in a six-point loss.
</P>
<P>
   Tech comes calling
</P>
<P>
   On idle weekends, Clarence and Ross had checked out colleges,
sometimes together, sometimes apart. They braced for the likelihood
of splitting up. ``We were content,'' Clarence said, ``to go our
separate ways.''
</P>
<P>
   Among Clarence's suitors was Georgia Tech, which had been tipped
off by a recruiting analyst. For coach Bobby Cremins, it was love
at first sight. ``Once I saw Clarence play,'' Cremins said, ``I
decided to go all-out. I see somebody I like, I go after him
hard.''
</P>
<P>
   With Ross and Tech, it was more like a slowly budding romance.
If not for the Tarpons' extended playoff run, Cremins might not
have seen him enough to risk a scholarship.
</P>
<P>
   With Dion Glover departing for the NBA, Cremins says, Clarence
could elbow into the lineup. The coach sees in him a dynamic
character who could raise the electricity on the low-voltage Tech
roster.
</P>
<P>
   As for Ross, Cremins says, ``Some people may say he's
questionable for the ACC. But he's a tough kid. He could be a
surprise.''
</P>
<P>
   Housemates for four years, Ross and Clarence will remain so,
sharing an on-campus apartment with two new teammates. ``I think,''
Clarence said, ``we can put up with each other another four
years.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, alone together in the big house, Ross' parents say becoming
Clarence's guardian became mutually beneficial. Without him, Ross
might never have landed at a top-shelf basketball school.
</P>
<P>
   One more thing. ``We are isolated from blacks down here, which
is not good,'' Gary said. The Chouests' interaction with
African-Americans was limited until Ross became involved with
summer-league basketball. ``I saw (Clarence moving in) as a
possible positive influence. It was good for everybody concerned.''
</P>
<P>
   And, with both boys at Tech, he and Carolyn are not forced to
choose between attending games in different cities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both boys have accomplished more than I ever expected,'' Gary
said. ``So everything they do from now is lagniappe, as we say down
here.''
</P>
<P>
   Down the bayou, where seeing is believing.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
