<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-18 20:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2167 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-DAY-TRADING-MARKETPLA     08-18 1134
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DAY-TRADING-MARKETPLACE-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKETPLACE: PIONEER OF DAY TRADING UNDER SCRUTINY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (subs 2nd graf of 2nd take to include title of 2nd book)  (Eds.: Budgeted earlier as HOUTKIN-DAY-TRADING) 
(ART ADV: Graphic on revenue sources for All-Tech is being sent to
NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase
by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By GRETCHEN MORGENSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Harvey Houtkin fervently believes that securities regulators are
out to get him. But he has no doubt that he will go down in history
as a man who made Wall Street a better place for the small
investor.
</P>
<P>
   Judging from his volatile relationship with regulators, Houtkin,
the self-proclaimed father of electronic stock trading, is right
that regulators are on his trail. But while he may well be
remembered for his role in changing the way Americans invest, it is
not at all clear that it has been for the good.
</P>
<P>
   Houtkin (HOWT-kin) is chief executive of All-Tech Investment
Group, one of the nation's largest day-trading firms. And he says
that his company, which provides computerized stock market access
to individuals, enables anyone with a willingness to learn, and
$25,000 to open an account, to make a living trading stocks.
Houtkin, 50, says that All-Tech and companies like it are opening a
world of trading opportunities that had been closed to all but
professionals _ that they have democratized the stock market.
</P>
<P>
   But especially since a day trader killed nine people in Atlanta
in July _ five of them at an All-Tech office _ Houtkin's operation
has come under intense regulatory scrutiny. And Tuesday, the family
of one shooting victim sued All-Tech, accusing it of negligence in
failing to supervise and recognize that Mark Barton, the man who
went on the killing spree, was a volatile person not suited to the
high-pressure business of stock trading.
</P>
<P>
   Houtkin, who would not comment on the lawsuit, is now complying
with a subpoena from Georgia securities regulators relating to
Barton's trading patterns and account holdings. Regulators there
want to know if All-Tech encouraged its customers to go to friends
and family to raise money to trade with, making the traders subject
to regulation as investment advisers. Regulators will probably want
to question Houtkin himself.
</P>
<P>
   The trader has been in the hot seat before, many times. A close
look at his background shows a man driven by almost religious zeal
to storm the ramparts of an elitist Wall Street and the regulatory
machinery that he says protects it at the expense of the little
guy.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   But Houtkin, a heavy-set, brown-haired man of medium height, is
no starry-eyed visionary; his history also reveals a canny mind,
ever ready to seize money-making opportunities, from bartering
penny stocks for goods and services to capitalizing on rules
changes that he himself helped bring about.
</P>
<P>
   Harvey Ira Houtkin was born in Brooklyn and, until he was 23,
lived with his parents in a low-income housing project in the
Sheepshead Bay section. His father was a maker and fitter of
artificial limbs and other prosthetic devices.
</P>
<P>
   Houtkin attended public schools, including the Brooklyn
Technical High School, a school for gifted students, and then
enrolled at City College planning to study dentistry. But in 1967
he says he got an afternoon job as an assistant to a well-known
Wall Street speculator (whom he will not name). Fascinated by the
money he saw his boss making, Houtkin switched to business school.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   After earning an M.B.A. from the City University of New York,
Houtkin went to Wall Street in 1973 to try his hand at trading. He
bounced from firm to firm. ``You don't earn where you learn on Wall
Street,'' he explained. ``You can't make a lot of money as a
trainee.'' His first job paid him $7,500 a year.
</P>
<P>
   In spite of a brutal bear market, Houtkin did well trading
shares of obscure and unknown companies, according to people who
worked with him.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Spira, an investment banker at Chapman Spira &AMP; Carson,
worked with Houtkin in the 1970s. ``Harvey was a nice kid, very
bright,'' he said. ``He always had his own ideas. He was always
ahead of the pack. He always looks for the edge.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Spira recalled that during one period, Houtkin was buying stocks
that were very cheap, then bartering those shares for merchandise
from the companies. ``He bought stock in a film-developing
company,'' Spira said. ``He must have bought it for pennies. Then
he called them up and said, `I'll turn in X number of shares, and
in return you'll develop my film.' He had such a fertile mind.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   In the mid- to late 1970s, Houtkin worked briefly for Carl Icahn
and Asher Edelman, two men who later became famous as corporate
raiders. In 1979, he raised some money and started his own firm,
called Domestic Arbitrage Group Inc.
</P>
<P>
   For a time, all went well, as the firm grew to six offices and
made markets in 500 NASDAQ stocks. But when the stock market
plunged in October 1987, the firm was left on the hook for the
losses of a customer who had traded with borrowed money. The losses
were so big that when Domestic Arbitrage faced the need to cover
them, it had to close its doors.
</P>
<P>
   Houtkin, most of whose assets were in the firm, said this was
when he realized how elitist Wall Street was. Though the regulators
eased the rules a bit and helped big firms avoid collapse after the
crash, he said, ``We were one of the firms allowed to flounder and
fail.''
</P>
<P>
   At a brokerage firm that his brother-in-law had set up after the
crash, Houtkin began trading NASDAQ Stocks, using a three-year-old
electronic trading system that was created by NASDAQ to insure that
customers could get their orders executed at the promised price.
</P>
<P>
   Back then, few used the system _ called the Small Order
Execution System, or SOES _ but Houtkin saw it as a way to profit
by using the split-second capacity of the system to buy stocks from
market makers who failed to update their quotes immediately as
stock prices changed.
</P>
<P>
   Houtkin prospered. But he soon ran afoul of regulators, who had
designed it only for the benefit of individuals working through a
broker. Since Houtkin was benefiting as a professional, the
National Association of Securities Dealers barred him from using
the system for six months. Thus began a running feud with
regulators that continues to this day.
</P>
<P>
   ``They found anything to close us down,'' Houtkin recalled.
``When the NASD wants to charge you with something, they can.
During that suspension was the incubation period for my total
contempt for these people.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   In 1990, state regulators in New Jersey denied an application by
his firm, then called Domestic Securities Inc., to register itself
for business there on the grounds that Houtkin was an undisclosed
principal of the firm and an unregistered broker in New Jersey.
Domestic Securities agreed not to reapply for three years and paid
$50,000 to reimburse the state for its investigation.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Despite his regulatory run-ins, Houtkin was making progress on
two fronts in the early 1990s. One was helping to bring the
misdeeds of big NASDAQ dealer firms, like their conspiracy to
inflate the costs of trading, to the attention of the Justice
Department and the Securities and Exchange Commission
</P>
<P>
   On another front, Houtkin was building his firm _ which had been
now been renamed as All-Tech _ into an electronic trading house for
individual investors. He became an evangelist for electronic
trading, crisscrossing the country leading seminars on trading
techniques and writing two investing books. The first, ``The SOES
Bandits' Guide: Day Trading in the 21st Century,'' was
self-published, and a second, ``Secrets of the SOES Bandit,'' was
put out by McGraw-Hill.
</P>
<P>
   When prosecutors and regulators concluded their investigation of
NASDAQ in 1996, they found that major dealers had rigged prices for
years. One result was new rules for the way investors' orders to
buy and sell NASDAQ stocks were handled, a rule change that
encouraged entrepreneurs to set up electronic trading systems for
NASDAQ stocks. This change ushered in the day-trading phenomenon,
in which retirees, recent college graduates and others sit before
computer screens in brokerage offices buying and selling thousands
of shares, hoping to capitalize on the small price movements of
stocks during the day.
</P>
<P>
   Houtkin's firm was one of the first to capitalize on the change.
Now All-Tech has 25 offices around the country and about 3,000
day-trading customers. Just last week, Houtkin conducted seminars
in Portland, Ore., and Seattle for people interested in becoming
day traders. In Seattle, more than 100 people attended, said one
person who was there.
</P>
<P>
   For all his talk about being an advocate for individual
investors, Houtkin makes a great deal of money. According to
financial statements filed with the SEC when All-Tech sought
unsuccessfully to become a public company, Houtkin had a salary of
$919,231 last year. His brother-in-law Mark Shefts, All-Tech's
president and the husband of Houtkin's sister, had a $943,363
salary. Each also got a $100,000 bonus.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The commissions that Houtkin charges his customers _ $25 a trade
_ are high compared with those at other large firms, which
typically charge $7 to $15 per 1,000-share trade.
</P>
<P>
   Houtkin also makes money as owner of a private company that
conducts the day-trading courses that 85 percent of All-Tech's
customers take. These courses typically run for a month and cost
$5,000, but this fee can later be gradually applied toward
commissions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I honestly believe I'm wearing a white hat, that I'm doing
what's in the best interests of the general public,'' Houtkin said.
``Now, can I capitalize on that? Sure. If I could develop the cure
for cancer, shouldn't I have the right to make money on it?''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Regulators say that Houtkin may underplay the risks associated
with day trading, luring in people who cannot afford to lose the
money that regulators say they almost certainly will. Another
concern is that his and other day-trading firms allow loans among
customers, a practice that may encourage people to trade more often
than they should.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Massachusetts regulators brought a complaint against
All-Tech, saying that it had used deceptive marketing to promote
day trading and engaged in other violations of securities laws,
like commingling customer funds and forging customers' signatures.
Houtkin attributed the infractions to ``a rogue broker,'' but
All-Tech agreed to close its operation in Massachusetts and not
reopen shop there for two years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of my people are outraged that certain regulators are
trying to put a bad face on day trading,'' Houtkin said. ``My
people choose to trade. They are adults. They are not doing
anything wrong. Why assume that trading actively is
irresponsible?''
</P>
<P>
   When asked how many of his customers make money trading, Houtkin
demurs. Still, there is a breathless quality to the promotion of
day trading on his firm's Web site. To the question ``Do I have to
know anything about the stock market?'' the answer is: ``NO! As a
matter of fact, in many instances, the less you know means the less
baggage you have to discard when learning the new trading
techniques that are taught by All-Tech's affiliate, All-Tech
Training Group Inc.''
</P>
<P>
   And can money be lost day trading? The site's answer is this:
``If you are disciplined in following the techniques you will be
taught, losses can and should be kept to a minimum.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Harvey's a salesman, and a good one,'' said Marc Beauchamp,
spokesman for the North American Securities Administrators
Association in Washington. ``But a skeptical consumer would ask,
`If he's found the fountain of wealth, why is he sharing it with
tens of thousands of total strangers in hotel ballrooms across the
land?'''
</P>
<P>
   Houtkin says his business is booming and revenue will hit $30
million this year. The number is not verifiable, but in 1998, the
growth in All-Tech's business was slowing, according to its
financial statements. Commissions were up only 8 percent that year,
versus a 44 percent rise in 1997. And the average commission per
transaction had fallen from $24.32 to $23.52.
</P>
<P>
   Even more startling, the firm registered a $392,558 loss in its
own trading account, a source of profits at All-Tech in both 1996
and 1997. The loss may indicate just how hard it is even for a
professional to make money in day trading.
</P>
<P>
   But Houtkin remains day trading's most vocal cheerleader. ``I
think I'm making a contribution to the financial markets that's
worth more than making another million dollars,'' he said. ``The
day it becomes too difficult or it becomes enough, I'll leave
then.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-18-99 2059EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
