<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-18 20:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2169 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-GLF-ANALYSIS19-COX     08-18 0590
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-ANALYSIS19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Obnoxious fans spoil the moment
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It was all about entertainment and drama Sunday at
Medinah Country Club. Nothing else. It was about Tiger Woods and
Sergio Garcia, who with their ages combined aren't as old as Jay
Haas, lunging and parrying for the world to savor in the final
major championship of the '90s.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, it's the kind of stuff that will push golf more into
the mainstream. The sport now has two stars that can go by their
first names only _ and one of them is not David. The last time
something like this happened, the names were Arnie and Jack.
</P>
<P>
   Ugly as it was that Chicago fans would heckle Tiger Woods, Mike
Weir and Colin Montgomerie during the final round of the PGA
Championship, the blame can be placed on football-mentality golf
followers who were over the Bud Light limit. Woods told reporters
after his post-victory news conference, ``It was nothing racial.''
</P>
<P>
   That Sergiomania could pass Tigermania on a particular day
really should not surprise anyone. This was the beginning, the
first time Europe's teen superstar went head to head with
America's. It wasn't anti-Woods. It became a celebration of
Garcia's newly spotlighted talent and his first contention in a
major.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine how rude Chicago fans would have been had Duval been the
opponent. Ripped in the media all week for his Ryder Cup
compensation stance, Duval might have seen his Oakleys fog up under
the jeering.
</P>
<P>
   How powerful was Garcia's presence Sunday? It's not every day
that the U.S. Ryder Cup captain, at his team-selection news
conference, gets more excited about a European player than about
one of his own. Ben Crenshaw gushed over Garcia, calling him
``absolutely electrifying and captivating . . . magic . . .
charismatic . . . graceful.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the message Garcia sent to Woods on the 13th tee, it was
not a taunt. Call it a don't-forget-about-me gesture from Garcia as
he appeared to point back at Woods after his birdie putt. It was
pivotal, but playful, the same thing that happened on the practice
range hours earlier. After a mammoth drive, Garcia glanced at
Woods, hoping his friend had been looking.
</P>
<P>
   The real shame on Sunday was fan behavior. A barrage of
``you-da-man's'' at golf tournaments has become annoying but
harmless. But the Medinah crowd was uglier than that, and it
continues a problem that has to concern all of golf's governing
bodies five weeks before the Ryder Cup matches in Boston. After an
embarrassing ``War at the Shore'' in 1991 at Kiawah Island, S.C.,
nobody wants the local fans to be Boston Stranglers.
</P>
<P>
   The real problem here is alcohol. One result of the golf boom
has been the changing demeanor of the crowd, and overconsumption of
alcohol has caused some of the new fans to yell things they might
normally limit to living rooms or bars. While most remain
well-mannered and glare at those who act as if they're at Giants
Stadium, the problem is getting worse. Woods often refers to fans
that have had ``a few too many.''
</P>
<P>
   Golf needs to get a handle on the problem now.
</P>
<P>
   One thing is certain: If Woods and Garcia happen to be paired
against each other at the Ryder Cup, the show will be a ratings
fantasy. And while fewer people in Boston will be rooting for El
Nino than were Sunday, it would be a real shame if words from
outside the ropes drew bigger headlines than the play inside them.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
