<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-18 21:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2172 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-FOODLION-HANNAFORD-70     08-18 0739
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOODLION-HANNAFORD-700(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHAIN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Eastern states)  
 FOOD LION TO ACQUIRE HANNAFORD, FORMING 6th-LARGEST SUPERMARKET(bl) 
 By DANA CANEDY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a deal that continues the rapid consolidation of the grocery
business, Food Lion Inc. said Wednesday that it would acquire
Hannaford Brothers Inc. for $3.3 billion, forming the sixth-largest
supermarket chain in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The acquisition gives Food Lion, which is strong in the
Southeast, a presence in the Northeast and enables the chain to
gain ground on Kroger, Safeway, Royal Ahold and other large
competitors that have grown by snapping up rivals.
</P>
<P>
   With the Hannaford acquisition, Food Lion will have more than
1,400 stores throughout the eastern United States from Maine to
Florida, with revenue of about $13.5 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Supermarket operators have been consolidating chains in recent
years to fend off price clubs and discount stores like Wal-Mart
that are increasingly adding grocery aisles to their general
merchandise stores. By combining with other chains, grocers are
trying to cut costs through synergies, expand geographically to
spread marketing and advertising costs over a larger store base and
use their enhanced size to force better prices from manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of the more midsized regional companies may have felt
like they could become disadvantaged by their size relative to
these giants,'' said Sally Wallick, an analyst with Legg Mason Wood
Walker.
</P>
<P>
   Under terms of the transaction, Food Lion, which is controlled
by Delhaize Freres-Le Lion SA of Belgium, will pay $79 a share in
cash and stock for the 152-store Hannaford chain and will assume
$300 million in debt. The acquisition, in which Food Lion has
agreed to pay a 24 percent premium based on Hannaford's closing
price Wednesday, will dilute Food Lion's earnings by 20 percent
next year.
</P>
<P>
   Food Lion said, however, that it expected to generate savings
from the acquisition of $40 million in the first year and about $75
million a year by the third year. The deal was approved by both
companies' boards and is subject to regulatory and Hannaford
shareholder approval.
</P>
<P>
   Food Lion investors were not enthusiastic about the deal,
largely because of the premium and likely earnings dilution,
analysts said. The company's shares fell $2.53125 Wednesday, or 23
percent, to $8.46875. Hannaford Brothers shareholders, meanwhile,
saw their shares rise Wednesday by $9.0625, or 14 percent, to
$72.75
</P>
<P>
   Food Lion, which is based in Salisbury, N.C., has annual revenue
of $10.2 billion. It operates 1,258 stores in the Middle Atlantic
and Southeastern states from Pennsylvania to Florida under the
brand names Food Lion, Kash 'n' Karry and Save 'n' Pack. Hannaford,
which is based in Scarborough, Maine, has annual revenue of $3.3
billion. It operates 152 stores in New England, New York and the
Southeast under the brand names Hannaford and Shop n Save.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``The acquisition of Hannaford into the Delhaize America family
of food retailers will provide an exceptional growth opportunity
for both organizations,'' said Food Lion president and chief
executive Bill McCanless. ``Together we are very complementary
companies, both operationally and geographically.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said the deal, which will not significantly affect the
New York area, unites two chains with strong management. It also
combines Hannaford's expertise in perishable foods and overall
inventory management with Food Lion's marketing focus and
purchasing power.
</P>
<P>
   Hannaford president and chief executive Hugh Farrington called
Food Lion, ``an excellent strategic growth partner in an industry
which continues to consolidate.'' He will run Hannaford for Food
Lion.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Some other recent acquisitions include Royal Ahold NV's purchase
of Pathmark Stores Inc. for $250 million and the assumption of $2.5
billion in debt, and Kroger Co.'s purchase of Fred Meyer Inc. for
$8 million in stock and the assumption of $4.8 billion in debt.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said they expected the flurry of merger activity to
continue as smaller, regional grocers seek deals that will increase
their size. For Food Lion, ``I think they felt that eventually they
would have a very concentrated industry,'' said Meredith Adler, an
analyst with Lehman Brothers. ``And the Belgium parent wanted to be
a player.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
