<HEADER>
A2175 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBA-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT     08-18 0765
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: PRESIDENTS SHOULD STAY HOME  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By GEORGE VECSEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Oh, my goodness, they are at it again. People mooching for
money, people begging for support. I am referring to the
importunate politicians who flocked to Iowa last weekend in the
first hideous threat of yet another presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   From the isolated corner of the world known as the press box, I
would not dare raise questions of foreign policy or taxes. However,
I would submit one modest question to all those who foist
themselves upon us as candidates:
</P>
<P>
   ``If elected, will you swear to never go near a sports event
during your entire term of office?''
</P>
<P>
   I ask this from a career of watching self-indulgent presidents
and vice presidents barge into Final Fours or Super Bowls, thereby
inconveniencing thousands of fans.
</P>
<P>
   A sense of empathy is a good litmus test for our national
leader. We want a president who feels our pain without causing more
of it. We want a president who will not inflict his entourage on
unsuspecting fans who never invited him in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   The events organizers do not have the right to invite a
president to the big game. This is a democracy. Put it to a vote.
How many people want the president dropping in on their World
Series game? Now there is a landslide vote.
</P>
<P>
   The most recent horror show was the final of the Women's World
Cup on July 10, when thousands of fans missed the first half. (All
right, so nobody scored, but that's hardly the point in soccer, is
it?)
</P>
<P>
   Soccer moms and soccer daughters who had paid hundreds of
dollars for tickets were stopped by police on the narrow roads to
the Rose Bowl. Reporters were blocked from the elevator bank by
Secret Service agents.
</P>
<P>
   You learn very quickly not to argue with these blokes, who are
usually in a bad mood because the president is ignoring their
security and logistical advice. Who do they take it out on? You.
Maine Us.
</P>
<P>
   It would make more sense for the president to arrive early and
let traffic flow, but that's not how it works. At the Rose Bowl, we
heard Clinton was running late because he was playing golf, to
which we said, ``Oh, well, as long as it's job-related.''
</P>
<P>
   Do presidents know the misery they are inflicting? As they used
to say in Russia, ``If only the czar knew.'' If the czar wanted to
know, the czar would know.
</P>
<P>
   Presidents wreak havoc by coming to town, any town. A friend of
mine tells of missing the key opening number in ``Chicago'' because
the Clintons decided to take daughter Chelsea to a Broadway musical
for her birthday. Hundreds of New Yorkers and tourists stood out in
the rain while the show started without them. Tough, said the
Secret Service.
</P>
<P>
   This is not a partisan issue, by the way. My toes still tingle
from near frostbite from an encounter with Vice President Bush in
1982 when the National Football League, in all its wisdom, held a
Super Bowl in the frozen tundra of Pontiac, Mich.
</P>
<P>
   The Secret Service had advocated an early arrival at the
Silverdome, but the vice president had a fund-raiser in Detroit, so
he barreled in near game time, forcing buses to disgorge fans and
reporters, who climbed up icy hillsides just to get off the
Interstate. Charming.
</P>
<P>
   These rude bipartisan disruptions could turn me into a one-issue
voter. I just want to hear that Bush, Gore, Dole, Bradley,
whomever, will show a little self-restraint and stay out of our
face for the entire term.
</P>
<P>
   I know that the latest George Bush used to run the Texas
baseball team, and Bill Bradley played for the Knicks, but if
either becomes president, he needs to acknowledge that his life has
changed. The next president should get a high-definition screen the
size of the Oval Office wall, and just stay home.
</P>
<P>
   I would be very happy if all candidates would lay off sports,
unless they can demonstrate a decade or three of legitimate
loyalty. Mayor Giuliani, whatever else one thinks of him, has
earned the right to wear a Yankee cap. He loves that team. He does
not have to try to be even-handed and say he likes the Mets, too.
Mets fans can respect a man who loves his team (even if it is the
haughty, arrogant, carpetbagger-property Yankees, as they might
fulminate in Flushing).
</P>
<P>
   As for other candidates, wearing the ball cap of somebody else's
team in somebody else's state could be the 2000 version of Michael
Dukakis' Snoopy helmet in the tank. Warning to all politicians: the
people can spot a phony a mile away. And on the day of a big game?
Preferably 100 miles away.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-18-99 2102EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
