<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-BOSNIA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: STEALING BOSNIA'S FUTURE 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Thursday, Aug. 19:
</P>
<P>
   International donors should be angered to learn that politicians
from all three of Bosnia's main ethnic groups have stolen as much
$1 billion of the $5 billion in international aid given to the
country since 1995. The unemployed and impoverished people of
Bosnia should be furious. By diverting funds intended to rebuild
homes and roads and to create jobs, the Serbian, Croatian and
Muslim nationalist parties that pushed Bosnia into ethnic warfare
are blighting its hopes for an economically viable peace.
</P>
<P>
   As Chris Hedges reported in The Times this week, antifraud
investigators working for international relief officials in Bosnia
found that local mayors funneled relief money into their own
pockets and those of their relatives and political supporters. One
city, Tuzla, paid to have its newly rebuilt schools repainted four
times last year, at above market prices. Another, Sanski Most, used
municipal funds to build a race track and diverted farm relief
money to the mayor's brother to start a bank.
</P>
<P>
   Corruption has thwarted efforts to revive Bosnia's shattered
economy. Demands for bribes have kept companies like McDonald's out
of Bosnia. Others that did invest have been driven out in
frustration. Volkswagen, which operates an assembly plant near
Sarajevo, is considering leaving over broken government promises.
Bosnian banks have given aid money to fraudulent businesses. Nearly
four years after the war, unemployment remains around 35 percent
and Bosnia is still dependent on foreign assistance. That outside
help will soon dry up unless corruption is brought under control.
</P>
<P>
   International relief officials must share blame for Bosnia's aid
debacle. Corruption could have been reduced if they had heeded
private groups with experience in the Balkans and Eastern Europe
and favored smaller projects that bypassed the state-run companies
and banks Bosnia inherited from Communist Yugoslavia. These
businesses were political fiefs and sources of patronage.
</P>
<P>
   Even now, a shift to smaller projects would allow better
monitoring and foster a new entrepreneurial class. Similar lessons
need to be applied in Kosovo, where the Kosovo Liberation Army must
be prevented from seizing control of local businesses and municipal
governments. The West's effort to end ethnic slaughter in the
Balkans will fail if reconstruction programs there are defeated by
corruption.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-18-99 2102EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990818.0345 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
