<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-BLUTE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EMBARRASSED MASSPORT CHIEF RESIGNS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK PHILLIPS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Massachusetts Port Authority Director Peter Blute was
forced to resign Wednesday, after cruising Boston Harbor on a
taxpayer-funded yacht, drinking alcohol with political operatives
and scantily clad women, then lying to cover up the behavior.
</P>
<P>
   A ``furious'' Governor Paul Cellucci demanded Blute step down,
after photographs were published in The Boston Herald of Blute
partying with the group, which included an unidentified young woman
who bared her breasts to the camera.
</P>
<P>
   Blute said in his letter of resignation that he had made ``an
error in judegement,'' but denied he was fired. Massport's chief
legal counsel, Scott L. Kafker, was appointed interim director.
</P>
<P>
   The events come at a sensitive time for the administration,
which is trying to win approval for expansion of a runway at Logan
International Airport in the face of intense community opposition.
</P>
<P>
   Lieutenant Governor Jane Swift told reporters she and Cellucci
were ``outraged'' at Blute's ``incredibly poor judgment.'' She
praised Blute for his 2 1/2 years of service at Massport, but said
the incident was too serious for him to stay in office.
</P>
<P>
   ``Utilizing state resources for personal use is not
acceptable,'' said Swift, who had worked for Blute at Massport
before being tapped by Cellucci to run for lieutenant governor last
year.
</P>
<P>
   Blute, a former congressman, said Wednesday he had arranged for
Massport to hire the 40-foot cabin cruiser Nauticus, but expected
the agency would be reimbursed for the rental by the ``private
parties.''
</P>
<P>
   Aboard the boat _ where beer and champagne flowed freely _ were
Alexander ``Sandy'' Tennant, a politically-wired GOP operative who
has represented private businesses before Massport; and David
McCool, a Massport lobbying consultant, among others.
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci, on vacation in Florida, released a statement, saying
Blute had ``tarnished the reputation of Massport'' and had ``acted
inappropriately.''
</P>
<P>
   ``These kinds of actions will not be tolerated in our
adminstration,'' Cellucci said. Blute was appointed Massport
director by former Governor William F. Weld after losing his
congressional seat in the 1996 election.
</P>
<P>
   Swift said she and the governor will sever all ties with Tennant
and McCool.
</P>
<P>
   Tennant, a controversial figure known for his heavy socializing
and swaggering professional style, had served as Cellucci's
campaign finance chairman between 1991 and 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, he has helped raise money and used his contacts with
Cellucci to promote his lobbying business. Cellucci has tried to
officially distance himself from Tennant, but likes him personally.
In November, for example, when the New England Patriots announced
they plan to move to Connecticut, Cellucci was enjoying blues music
with Tennant in New Orleans' French quarter.
</P>
<P>
   About a month ago Tennant inquired of MassPort's development
office about the board's process for selecting a developer for 25
acres of East Boston waterfront land. Tennant said he was asking on
behalf of Arthur Winn, owner of the Regal Bostonian Hotel. Winn
could not be reached for comment Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Blute said he and Tennant -- with whom he has had a personal
relationship for 15 years -- had arranged for Massport to pay the
up-front rent for the Nautica for the four-hour cruise around the
harbor. Blute said he and Tennant had planned the cruise some
months ago and that he took a a vacation day from work.
</P>
<P>
   But there were conflicting accounts over how the arrangements
for the boat rental were made and who was to pay the cost.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday evening, just after the cruise ended, Blute told the
Globe that Massport had not paid for the boat rental and that
Maureen Stemberg, a Charlestown woman he said is involved in cancer
charity work, was paying for the cruise.
</P>
<P>
   Blute said Stemberg, the former wife of Staples mogul Thomas
Stemberg, was on the cruise -- and paying for it -- to discuss
cancer charity events. Tennant told the Globe the same story when
explaining why Stemberg -- who has cancer -- was paying for the
cruise. Massport allocates a small portion of its revenues to local
charities.
</P>
<P>
   But Stemberg knew nothing of the cruise until, sitting at a
restaurant on the waterfront in Charlestown Tuesday afternoon, she
was invited aboard for the boat's final leg to its slip at
Commercial Wharf, an associate of hers told the Globe.
</P>
<P>
   Stemberg and the associate, Bob Gersten, were eating at the
Tavern on the Water restaurant at the Charlestown dock when Tennant
came up to them. The Tennant party had taken a break from the
cruise at the restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Gertsen said Stemberg did not initially want to
go aboard the boat, but when she was introduced to a woman in
Tennant's party who said she did fundraising for cancer, she
decided to go.
</P>
<P>
   That woman, sources said, later raised her shirt to defiantly
expose her breasts to a Herald photographer when the yacht docked
at Commerical Wharf.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something (cancer research and fund-raising) Maureen's
very passionate about,'' Gertsen said. ``Maureen was not on that
boat for more than 20 minutes and was a guest of Sandy Tennant.''
</P>
<P>
   Stemberg herself was not available for comment Wednesday. ``We
just thought it would be a little breeze on the ocean,'' said
Gertsen, adding: ``She is very afraid about all of this and fears
leaving the house right now due to reporters already attempting to
enter her building.''
</P>
<P>
   Just before Blute resigned, agency spokesman Jeremy Crockford
said Stemberg had reimbursed the authority $832 for the rent of the
yacht earlier that morning.
</P>
<P>
   But late Wednesday a Massport spokesman acknowledged that Blute
had written a check himself to pay back the authority for the
expense.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview Wednesday, Blute, who serves at the pleasure of
the Cellucci-appointed Massport board, decided to resign because he
saw the ``handwriting on the wall'' following the publication of
the photos and the healdine that read: ``Booze Cruise.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I understand it is in the best interest of everyone that we
clear the air,'' Blute said in a brief interview with the Globe.
``I should have not have been on that boat. It was bad judgement.''
</P>
<P>
   Blute said he had sent an apology to all employees at Massport
for the embarrassment he had caused the agency. He said he did not
want to talk about the conflicting accounts of Stemberg's role and
the rental of the boat.
</P>
<P>
   Though personally liked by Cellucci, Blute was occasionally at
odds with the governor's inner circle. Some questioned his loyalty
to Cellucci, because Blute had been friendly with Treasurer Joseph
Malone, Cellucci's rival in the Republican gubernatorial primary
last year. Blute's wife Robbie had been listed as a Malone
supporter on a fundraising invitation last year.
</P>
<P>
   Swift said that, with the Massport board's approval, the
administration wants Kafker to serve on an acting basis until the
governor and the board choose a permanent successor.
</P>
<P>
   Kafker has been chief legal counsel at Massport since 1993, and
was previously deputy legal counsel to former governor William F.
Weld. Sources said that Kafker is not a candidate for the job on a
permanent basis.
</P>
<P>
   ``My job is to keep keep the place on track and that is what I
intend to do, going full speed ahead,'' Kafker said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Job one is getting people focused on their work, moving past
today's event,'' said Kafker. ``We have a lot to do, modernizing
the airport, moving forward with the airfield improvement project
(which includes a controversial commuter runway proposal) getting
the seaport district under control, doing South Boston development
in a way that is sensitive to the community, and see that the
Worcester Airport transition is completed.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Blute's sudden removal under a cloud of scandal could
have a serious impact on Cellucci's push to expand the runway.
Blute was the public face and lead spokesman for the politically
explosive plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mary Ellen Welch, an anti-runway activist in East Boston, said
the shake-up at Massport will slow down the runway process. `` He
was the team leader and did all the outfront public relations
efforts both with the business community and community groups,''
Welch said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
