<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-AUBURN19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Auburn's demise exaggerated?
 &HT;    By Tony Barnhart
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUBURN, Ala. _ Auburn was two points away from winning an SEC
championship in 1997. But a visitor who reads the newspapers and
listens to talk shows over here these days could come to the
conclusion the school was about to give up football.
</P>
<P>
   All but a handful of preseason publications have picked the
Tigers to finish dead last in the SEC West under first-year coach
Tommy Tuberville. Not only will Auburn finish last, go the
predictions, but they will look ugly doing it with an offense that
couldn't make a first down against tall grass.
</P>
<P>
   Tuberville, playing the low-expectations game, has done nothing
to discourage the prophets of doom. He is candid about Auburn's
shortcomings, which are many. Thus, the perception grows that this
will be a disastrous year on the Plain.
</P>
<P>
   But will it? Yes, there were some gaps in recruiting toward the
end of the Terry Bowden regime, but is Auburn so devoid of talent
that the Tigers will be a total nonfactor in the SEC in 1999?
</P>
<P>
   Most of the concerns about Auburn's offense are valid. Neither
quarterback _ Gabe Gross or Ben Leard _ completed 50 percent of
their passes last season. The top two rushers from a year ago _
Demontray Carter and Michael Burks _ have left the program. The
receiving corps is thin, despite the reinstatement of Clifton
Robinson after his recent legal problems.
</P>
<P>
   But it doesn't mean that Auburn's offense will come to a
standstill against SEC-caliber defenses.
</P>
<P>
   ``We may not have as may athletes as a Florida State, but we've
got guys who can play at this level,'' said Gross, a sophomore. ``A
lot of people have been knocking our offense but we're going to
fool them.''
</P>
<P>
   Gross is locked in a quarterback battle with Leard, a junior
from Hartwell, and true freshman Allen Tillman. While Leard has
provided some competition, Tillman has been slowed by a sore arm.
Gross is expected to be named the starter next week.
</P>
<P>
   Gross will be the first to admit that he doesn't have the
offensive skills of a Quincy Carter, but offensive coordinator Noel
Mazzone won't be asking him to make Carter-like plays to win games.
</P>
<P>
   ``In our situation, the first thing the quarterback will have to
do is not lose the game,'' said Mazzone, who came to Auburn from
Ole Miss with Tuberville. ``We've got to put him in the right
situations and keep mistakes to a minimum.''
</P>
<P>
   One thing's for sure. Auburn will improve its running game,
which was ranked 103 out of 112 Division I teams last fall. The
Tigers will do it with a veteran offensive line (four of five
starters return) and a tailback by committee. Senior Rusty Williams
will be given a shot as will fullback Heath Evans, scatback
Markeith Cooper, and true freshman Michael Owens. There is even
talk of using Robinson, a former high school running back, in
special situations.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson was reinstated to the team last Saturday after pleading
guility to contributing to the delinquency of a minor. Robinson,
21, was charged with having sex with a 15-year-old girl. He pleaded
to a lesser charge and was given a one year's suspended sentence
and 200 hours of community service.
</P>
<P>
   ``Getting Clifton back is huge,'' said Gross. ``We're glad that
he has his legal troubles behind him. We need him on this team
because he can make plays.''
</P>
<P>
   Robinson caught 42 passes for 672 yards last season. He is the
only returning wide receiver who has caught a pass.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you have is an offense with a lot of different pieces,''
said Mazzone. ``We've just got to figure out how they fit
together.''
</P>
<P>
   This Auburn offense, above all else, must end one of its nasty
habits of a year ago when it kept making mistakes and putting the
defense in difficult situations. If it can control the ball and
keep errors down, the defense is good enough to win some games.
</P>
<P>
   Eight starters return on defense, including a front four that
will be one of the nation's best. Defensive end Marcus Washington
(6-4, 235) has been unblockable. Tackle Jimmy Brumbaugh (6-1, 285),
the ultimate warrior, is back after sitting out most of last season
with knee problems. Leonardo Carson (6-3, 280) moves from end to
tackle, while Quinton Reese (6-5, 247) will handle the other end.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there is a better defensive front in the country, I'd hate
to see it,'' said Gross. ``Going against those guys in practice is
really tough.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever optimism that has been generated by Tuberville's
arrival has to be tempered by a daunting schedule. While the Tigers
did buy their way out of a game with Florida State, they must still
play the other five members of the Western Division plus Tennessee,
Florida, and Georgia from the East.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the reality check, right there,'' said Tuberville. ``I
think we've got a chance but I'm trying to be realistic with
everybody.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the teams we play you can't beat with smoke and
mirrors.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
