<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-ITEMS19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tiger Woods: By the numbers
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _
</P>
<P>
   34: Number of consecutive cuts made, which leads the PGA Tour.
Chris Perry is next with 19.
</P>
<P>
   8: Number of consecutive times he has held or shared the 54-hole
lead in a tournament and gone on to win.
</P>
<P>
   12: Top-10 performances this year, out of 16 events, which also
leads the PGA Tour.
</P>
<P>
   68.59: Scoring average in '99, which is, not surprisingly, also
No. 1, by .38 stroke over David Duval.
</P>
<P>
   THUMBS UP
</P>
<P>
   To Steve Elkington for being concerned enough about caddie Joe
``Gypsy'' Grillo to withdraw from the PGA Championship. Grillo
experienced chest pains before the first round and was rushed to
the hospital.
</P>
<P>
   THUMBS DOWN
</P>
<P>
   To PGA of America CEO Jim Awtrey, for telling reporters in a
Tuesday news conference that the players did not desire any form of
compensation, then telling CBS-TV a few days later that a plan
should be established by the end of the year to distribute money
from Ryder Cup revenues to players' charities.
</P>
<P>
   FUTURE CONSIDERATIONS
</P>
<P>
   Two of next year's three rotating major championship venues are
dripping with tradition. The U.S. Open goes to Pebble Beach in
June. The British Open will be played at the Old Course, St.
Andrews, in July.
</P>
<P>
   But in the spirit of the millenium, Y-2-Valhalla?
</P>
<P>
   Well, the answer is an easy one. The PGA of America owns
Valhalla Golf Club in Louisville and will use it as much as
possible. Valhalla also will host the PGA in 2004 and the Ryder Cup
in 2007.
</P>
<P>
   The players view the Jack Nicklaus-designed Valhalla as a
sub-par venue for a major championship, but money talks. Host clubs
usually receive between $5 million and $8 million, and that's a
nice check for the PGA not to have to write.
</P>
<P>
   While there have been rumors that the dynamic Whistling Straits
Golf Club in Kohler, Wis., site of the 1999 National Club Pro
Championship, could replace Valhalla in 2004, PGA officials say the
schedule is firm. The PGA comes to Atlanta's Athletic Club in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta's East Lake Golf Club also will have its share of
national attention. It hosts the Tour Championship in 2000 and the
U.S. Amateur in 2001, eight days after the conclusion of the PGA.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
