<HEADER>
A2183 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-GLF-RYDERCUP19-COX     08-18 0596
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-RYDERCUP19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ryder full of intrigue
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Five weeks before the Battle of Brookline, otherwise
known as the 1999 Ryder Cup, these are the questions that should be
answered eventually:
</P>
<P>
   _ Will the U.S. team members persuade anyone they care more
about repaying the Europeans than paying themselves?
</P>
<P>
   _ If the Americans lose, will anybody believe their priorities
were misplaced?
</P>
<P>
   _ Will U.S. players, including Davis Love III and Tom Lehman,
who were embarrassed by the actions of a few, make certain that
what overshadowed PGA Championship week doesn't resurface at the
Country Club?
</P>
<P>
   _ Will Tiger Woods, with his second major secured and his
confidence at a career high, be the dominant force he logically
should have been two years ago at Valderrama?
</P>
<P>
   _ Will captains Ben Crenshaw and Mark James be able to pair
Woods and Sergio Garcia in singles even though the pairings are
done through a blind draw?
</P>
<P>
   _ Will the American players take more seriously their pre-Ryder
Cup week preparations at Brookline than they did two years ago at
Valderrama?
</P>
<P>
   _ Will Boston's fans, who are known for their boisterous
opinions, remember how nasty the situation got at Kiawah Island,
S.C., in 1991?
</P>
<P>
   If one positive about the Ryder Cup emerged from Medinah, it was
Ben Crenshaw's image. If anyone doubted whether ``Gentle Ben''
could be forceful enough when the situation demanded it, they need
doubt no longer. Two firm Crenshaw moves provided the evidence.
</P>
<P>
   The first came with a bang, as Crenshaw, a day after the meeting
on compensation, said that things expressed there from some players
``burned the hell out of me.'' The second authoritative move came
Monday, when Crenshaw pushed aside a close friendship with Fred
Couples and selected Steve Pate, who while less experienced, had
played in tournaments while Fred played with his children.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. team should be a huge favorite. But that's not new.
While the European team has strength _ Colin Montgomerie, Lee
Westwood, Darren Clarke, Jose Maria Olazabal, Garcia and probable
captain's pick Jesper Parnevik _ it is not a Murderer's Row. The
past two competitions have demonstrated the difference between
appearance and reality. Two years ago, the trio of Woods, Davis
Love and Justin Leonard stumbled to a cumulative 1-9-3 record. Love
was 0-4-0. Woods lost in singles match to Costantino Rocca.
</P>
<P>
   The pressure on the American team will be immense. The United
States used to own the competition, but it has lost two in a row.
And the pressure increased sharply last week because of the
compensation controversy. While the players are promoting a plan to
provide money to their own charities, outsiders surmise that they
are hiding a desire to pocket profits.
</P>
<P>
   The need for a leader on the American team is paramount. It
could be Lehman, captain's pick or not, who pledged weeks ago, ``I
would pay to play in the Ryder Cup team.'' It could be Woods, whose
game provides an intimidation factor sorely missed in Spain. It
could be Payne Stewart, a two-time U.S. Open champion, who is
playing a course with U.S. Open demands.
</P>
<P>
   In the competition, the Woods-Garcia situation will dominate the
news. And while Crenshaw, the ultimate traditionalist, is the last
person who would accept a Woods-Garcia Sunday singles match to be
planned _ each captain independently submits 12 names in order _
you can bet TV will try to make it happen.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
