<SLUG> BC-RUN-TRACK-DRUGS-1200(2TAKES)TRIMS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DRUG TESTS RAISE SUSPICIONS IN TRACK AND FIELD 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Britain, Jamaica, Canada, N.C., Sweden, Switzerland,
Germany,   Greece , Korea)  (Eds: See also RUN-TRACK-NANDROLONE) 
(DW) 
 By CHRISTOPHER CLAREY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEVILLE, Spain _ The world track and field championships will
begin here in the heat on Saturday, and the thousands who will
watch and perspire in person and the millions who will watch on
television in cooler climes will soon have answers to these
questions:
</P>
<P>
   Will Marion Jones become the first woman to win four gold medals
in the same world championships? Will Maurice Greene become the
first man to sweep the 100 and 200 meters? Will anyone find a way
to catch Hicham el-Guerrouj in the 1,500?
</P>
<P>
   But in the aftermath of yet another round of positive drug
tests, there is another, naggingly familiar question begging for a
response: How clean a sport is track and field?
</P>
<P>
   The issue is hardly new, and 11 years after Ben Johnson tested
positive for a steroid after winning the 100 meters at the Summer
Olympics in Seoul, it has again become inextricably linked with a
major event.
</P>
<P>
   The focus on performance-enhancing drugs intensified Wednesday
when another of the sport's biggest stars, the Jamaican sprinter
Merlene Ottey, withdrew from the championships after being informed
that a drug test she was administered in July showed traces of the
banned steroid nandrolone.
</P>
<P>
   The development is the latest setback to track and field's
credibility as it combats the widespread suspicions of rampant drug
use. Earlier this month, the International Amateur Athletic
Federation, the sport's governing body, suspended U.S. 100-meter
champion Dennis Mitchell for two years for testing positive for
testosterone in the spring of 1998. It also confirmed that former
Olympic 100-meter champion Linford Christie had tested positive for
nandrolone: one day before it was announced that former Olympic
high jump champion Javier Sotomayor had tested positive for cocaine
at the Pan-American Games.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a rough month to be a track and field athlete,
especially a sprinter,'' said Ato Boldon, the world 200-meter
champion who has come to Seville but will not compete because of a
hamstring injury.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got more drug questions in the past month than probably
my entire career combined,'' he added. ``It means a lot to me how
we are perceived, and I don't think our public perception has ever
been this bad. We are at an all-time low, maybe close to where we
were in Korea in 1988.''
</P>
<P>
   It was at the Seoul Olympics that year that Johnson's stunning
100-meters victory was overturned after he tested positive for a
steroid.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Kennedy, long the top American 5,000 meter runner, said:
``Before these positive tests, I would have said track and field
was coming on. I think even in the United States it is slowly
making progress, very slowly, and the European crowds have been
excellent this year at almost all the meets. And then the drug
thing kills us. Because when that comes out, that's all the
emphasis is on, and it takes away from some great stories, some
great athletic and personal stories that have nothing to do with
drugs.''
</P>
<P>
   Ottey, who is 39, has never won an Olympic gold medal, but has
won five bronzes and two silvers, and she has won more medals (14)
than anyone in the world championships. As she announced her
withdrawal, she pledged to do her utmost to prove her innocence.
``I owe it to my family, my country, my beloved sport and all my
fans around the world to prove that this is a terrible mistake,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   The IAAF confirmed that Ottey's initial ``A'' sample from a meet
in Lucerne, Switzerland on July 5 had turned up positive for
Nandrolone. The backup ``B'' sample is due to be analyzed in the
next few days at the IOC-accredited laboratory in Lausanne,
Switzerland. If it is also positive, Ottey faces a possible
two-year ban that would effectively end her career and erase her
hopes of competing in her sixth Olympics next year in Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   Christie, who was born in Jamaica but represents Britain, is
also protesting his innocence, and what makes his positive test
particularly surprising is that he is now semi-retired and no
longer takes part in major international competition. He tested
positive at a minor indoor meet in Dortmund, Germany in February.
</P>
<P>
   Arne Ljungqvist, an IAAF vice president and head of its medical
committee, emphasized that it was too early to label Ottey's test
``positive'' because the B sample had yet to be evaluated. He also
indicated that he did not view stars testing positive in bunches as
a predominantly negative development for the sport. He said: ``I
think this is a clear message to athletes around the world: `Look
here. We are really acting. We are taking initiatives and closing
any gap there may have been between those who try to cheat in
different ways and those who try to combat it.' The old saying is
that athletes have sophisticated methods to escape detections and
use substances that cannot be detected. But if that were true, we
would not get these prominent athletes.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course there is a tendency to put us in a negative light
from the media when we show up with a number of positive cases, and
that gives an unfortunate and unfairly bad image: unfair for the
simple reason that we are conducting serious anti-doping
activities,'' he added. ``We have a steadily improving system. We
are by far the federation with the highest number of tests of all
kinds. The easy way out would be to do no tests and receive no bad
publicity.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   In June, when Greene crossed the finish line in Athens after
running the 100 and a world-record time of 9.78 seconds showed on
the clock, Boldon's reaction spoke volumes about what it is like to
be fast in this justifiably leery era. He was delighted that the
time was not 9.79 seconds: the time that Ben Johnson had run in
Seoul.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because of all the parallels,'' said Boldon, who shared his
delight with Greene as they decelerated. ``I'm that aware, and sure
enough, they rounded the time up to 9.79, and as a result, Maurice
had to answer a lot of questions: unfounded I think. But with the
Ben Johnson issue, obviously people feel like, `Who's to say we're
not being tricked again?'''
</P>
<P>
   To address such skepticism, Boldon, Greene and Jones and others
support the institution of blood testing in their sport, which
currently relies on urine testing only.
</P>
<P>
   Top British distance runner Paula Radcliffe, who will run the
5,000 in Seville, wore a red ribbon on her vest during the European
Cup in June to show her support. ``I am not going to name names,
but it must be obvious to anybody in the sport that some of the
improvements people have made are suspicious,'' she told British
reporters then. ``Blood tests are our only defense against
cheats.''
</P>
<P>
   UK Athletics, the governing body in Britain, intends to support
a research project in which British athletes will voluntarily
undergo blood tests and have the results of those tests published
as next year's Summer Olympics approach. Cycling and nordic skiing
already have introduced blood tests in an attempt to combat the use
of EPO, the synthetic hormone that artificially increases endurance
by augmenting the red blood cell count. EPO is currently
undetectable, but both sports have established limits on red blood
cell counts. If an athlete exceeds the limit before a race, he is
not allowed to start for medical reasons but is not subject to a
lengthy suspension.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Blood tests have yet to be proven more effective than urine
tests in detecting steroids, although Ljungqvist said preliminary
research indicates blood tests could prove useful in isolating
human growth hormone, another currently undetectable
performance-enhancing drug. EPO could certainly benefit marathoners
and other distance runners greatly. But Ljungqvist believes the
IAAF, which conducted blood testing trials at major meets in 1993
and 1994 and found no significant evidence of illicit behavior,
would encounter legal problems if it attempted to implement a
program similar to cycling or skiing. He prefers to wait for a
definitive, foolproof test for EPO: a test which he said ``could
come shortly.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Should it require a blood sample, we would certainly proceed
with that,'' he said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
