<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-GAYS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS LAWMAKER RECALLS BUSH'S COMMENTS ABOUT HOMOSEXUALS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By POLLY ROSS HUGHES 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ The state's only openly gay legislator said
Wednesday that Gov. George W. Bush, in a remarkable nose-to-nose
encounter last spring, told him that he should not take personally
Bush's remarks about homosexuals on the presidential campaign
trail.
</P>
<P>
   State Rep. Glen Maxey, D-Austin, whose district includes the
governor's mansion, recalled Bush approaching his desk on the House
floor in one of only two visits Bush made to the House while it was
in session earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``He put his hands on my shoulders and he pulled me in where
almost our noses were touching. It's almost an uncomfortable level
where he gets really close and personal, nose to nose,'' Maxey
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``And he says to me, `I value you as a person and I value you as
a human being and I want you to know, Glen, that what I say
publicly about gay people doesn't pertain to you.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush spokesman Scott McClellan said the story was false.
</P>
<P>
   Maxey, who said he recalled the encounter so vividly because it
was ``amazing,'' said he retorted that when ``you say a gay
person's not fit to be a parent ... that's real personal.''
</P>
<P>
   The exchange, Maxey said, came April 19 on the House floor just
after he says Bush begrudgingly congratulated him for expanding a
children's health insurance program, or CHIP, far beyond a more
modest plan the governor's office had backed.
</P>
<P>
   As Bush greeted lawmakers with friendly slaps on the back, he
made a point of navigating his way to Maxey's desk, Maxey said.
</P>
<P>
   He says Bush remarked on the children's health insurance issue
that ``you crammed it down our throat'' before drawing in close to
Maxey's face and addressing the issue of Maxey's homosexuality.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the most amazing thing for me as a gay person to hear
him say that,'' Maxey told the Houston Chronicle.
</P>
<P>
   McClellan, however, insists that the greeting was short and
simple.
</P>
<P>
   ``He congratulated him on CHIPS. That was the extent of the
conversation. I'm baffled that if (Maxey) was offended four months
ago, he's just now bringing it up, '' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Dawnna Dukes, D-Austin, sits behind Maxey in the House
chamber and said she did overhear the governor's remark about
cramming the health plan down his throat, but said she didn't hear
what was said in the rest of the conversation.
</P>
<P>
   Bush does not usually side with gay activists on legislation
that concerns them, although he has tempered his views by stating
support for the military's ``don't ask, don't tell'' policy and by
chastising state GOP officials in 1998 who made insulting remarks
about a group of gay Republicans who wanted to have a booth at the
state convention.
</P>
<P>
   Bush opposes gay adoptions, saying in March: ``I believe
children ought to be adopted in families with a woman and a man who
are married.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush also opposes including sexual orientation, along with race
and gender, as categories in a hate crimes bill that could be
targeted for stiffer penalties. Bush did not support hate-crimes
legislation that died this year in the state Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Maxey says he shared the encounter with Bush with nearby
minority legislators immediately afterward. Maxey said many of the
minority legislators found it disturbing.
</P>
<P>
   Until this session, Bush's stand on gay issues appeared tame
enough, Maxey said, noting that Bush had said he didn't believe in
discrimination after the state Republican Party barred the gay Log
Cabin Republicans from setting up a booth at the state convention.
</P>
<P>
   ``I intend to treat every person with respect and dignity, and
although I don't agree with the Log Cabin Republicans' agenda, like
gay marriage, I don't condemn the name-calling,'' Bush said in June
1998.
</P>
<P>
   Gays and lesbians protested last spring when Bush backed the
bill to ban homosexuals from adopting or acting as foster parents
for children under the state's protection.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bush's actions in the past year have been a hard thing for us
to swallow,'' said Dianne Hardy Garcia, executive director of the
state Gay and Lesbian Lobby. ``Many of us believed that George Bush
was a decent man and that he was above this kind of anti-gay
prejudice. From what we know personally he has gay friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we now know about George Bush is he'll do whatever it
takes to get elected. If the means hurting his gay friends or
allies, he'll do it. He stopped a hate crime bill, and we've had 30
gay men killed in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Hardy Garcia added that it ``scares me'' if Bush is following
the advice of advisers on gay issues for political gain in his
presidential bid rather than out of personal conviction.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're going to do whatever it takes to get elected, I
think George Bush will step on gay people in a minute's notice
because that's what he's told he needs to do. I think that shows a
lack of morality, a lack of conscience. It really frightens me that
someone like that would be leading our country.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
