<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-18 21:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2189 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-RUN-TRACK-NANDROLONE-     08-18 0432
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUN-TRACK-NANDROLONE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NANDROLONE, AN OLD STEROID THAT LINGERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Czech Republic, Britain, Jamaica, Sweden, Calif.)  (Eds: See also RUN-TRACK-DRUGS) (DW) 
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Nandrolone, the banned steroid detected in the urine samples of
Linford Christie and Merlene Ottey, is hardly considered to be on
the cutting edge of performance-enhancing substances.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nandrolone is an old, old anabolic steroid,'' said Dr. C.
Harmon Brown, an American member of the IAAF medical committee, in
a telephone interview from his office in Foster City, California.
``It's been around for a long time, and it comes in different forms
and most of them are kind of long-acting so they tend to hang in
the system.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is why Brown and many members of the track and field
community are surprised that athletes would choose to take the risk
of using Nandrolone, traditionally an oil-based, slow-releasing
steroid, instead of water-based steroids which are considerably
more difficult to detect with urine tests.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems to me that the thing that people would be using if
anything would be short-acting testosterone because it would clear
the system quickly,'' Brown said. ``I just don't see any rationale
for this. If you are a world-class athlete, someone can knock on
your door anytime, so it's foolish to take any of these things,
especially something that stays in the system for any length of
time.''
</P>
<P>
   Among those who have tested positive for nandrolone in the last
two years are Czech tennis player Petr Korda; British sprinter Doug
Walker, the 1998 European 200 champion, and Cuban high jumper Juana
Rosario Arrendel, who won the gold medal in the women's event at
the Pan American Games.
</P>
<P>
   Arne Ljungqvist, the IAAF's medical committee chairman, said
that he preferred to wait ``quite a while to make a statistical
evaluation'' about nandrolone's prevalence but said that
preliminary laboratory data from his native country Sweden and
other countries indicate that it is being found in ``increasing
amounts'' in urine samples.
</P>
<P>
   ``There could be several explanations,'' he said. ``One, which I
cannot yet endorse, is that certain nutritional supplements may
have appeared on the market that would contain these things. And
you know with nutritional supplements of various kinds, you can
never be sure what they contain. We have steadily issued warnings
to the athletes about their use because you never know. And you
must remember, we have a liability rule that says athletes are
responsible for what goes in their bodies.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-18-99 2112EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990818.0356 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
