<HEADER>
A2190 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-STARR-NYT &LR;      08-18 0373
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-STARR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: FINISH THE JOB, STARR 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Thursday, Aug. 19:
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth Starr is no doubt tired of the public stage. But he
would be making a mistake to resign as independent counsel this
fall, before the completion of a final report on his five-year-old
investigation of President Clinton and his activities. The
independent counsel's duty is not only to oversee the report but to
get it done quickly and be around to defend its conclusions. If the
report is critical of Hillary Rodham Clinton, any delay might be
perceived as intending to interfere with her undeclared Senate
candidacy in New York.
</P>
<P>
   An article in The Times on Thursday says Starr has told a panel
of appellate judges that he intends to appoint a deputy to tie up
the loose ends of his investigation. Previous reports have
suggested that this job could continue into next year. That seems
far too long for an investigation that must have little left to do
beyond writing a final report.
</P>
<P>
   In public comments since Clinton was impeached by the House and
then acquitted by the Senate, Starr has expressed regret that some
Americans feel he has waged a personal vendetta against the
president, and he promised not to ``trash'' anyone in the final
report. He needs to stay on the job to make sure the report is
evenhanded and completed expeditiously so as not to intrude on next
year's political races. An early departure would inevitably
separate him from the drafting of the report and the timing of its
completion.
</P>
<P>
   An unsettling new question about Starr's investigation was
introduced Wednesday by one of the three judges overseeing the
independent counsel. The judge, Richard Cudahy, a Democratic
appointee, complained that his fellow judge, David Sentelle, a
Republican appointee, had held ``informal'' contacts with Starr
about the progress of the investigation and had rebuffed efforts by
the court to determine how much is left for Starr to investigate.
If even the appellate judges in charge of monitoring Starr cannot
measure his progress, the public will have little confidence that
the investigation is being brought to a prompt conclusion.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-18-99 2113EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
