u s BC-BBN-BRAVES-NOTES19-CO     08-18 0652
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-NOTES19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Smoltz keeps his mind on opponent, not pain
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ John Smoltz chooses to focus on the Rockies today and
quit worrying about all that ails him.
</P>
<P>
   The strained groin that forced him out of his Dodger Stadium
start in the fifth inning Saturday is not going to keep him from
making his 21st start of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't wait for it to hurt, even though you know it's
probably going to,'' Smoltz said Wednesday. ``Now it doesn't hurt.
It's out of my worries.''
</P>
<P>
   Smoltz, who has used a lower arm angle in his delivery in his
last two starts, finally had gotten to where his elbow felt more
comfortable. But that doesn't mean he's comfortable with the new
style of pitching.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time out, it's going to be something different,'' said
Smoltz, looking for his first victory since June 18. ``The only
thing it does (for sure) is alleviate the pain. Now, I have to
learn how to do everything else. It's not like I'm super
comfortable.... I don't know how long I'm going to pitch like this,
but I'm more at ease when I go down to warm up for a game. Now, the
challenge is getting outs.''
</P>
<P>
   The three-quarters arm angle would seem ideal for Coors Field,
because it should produce more groundouts. But Smoltz isn't so
sure.
</P>
<P>
   ``You saw (Greg) Maddux give up a bunch of ground-ball hits,''
Smoltz said, referring to Monday night's game, when Maddux allowed
12 hits in the Braves' 14-6 victory. ``This place is this place.
I'm not going to fight the conditions. I don't care how _ I just
want to get a win, help the team win.''
</P>
<P>
   Smoltz is 1-2 at Coors Field with a 7.20 ERA, having allowed 16
earned runs in 20 innings. Today's start is his first in Denver
this season. He beat the Rockies at Turner Field on June 1 when he
pitched six shutout innings. It was his initial start after his
first stint on the disabled list.
</P>
<P>
   Not driving them in
</P>
<P>
   The Braves stranded 11 runners in Tuesday night's 3-2 loss to
the Rockies and went 0-for-7 with runners in scoring position. On
Wednesday, they stranded nine and were 1-for-12 with someone in
scoring position.
</P>
<P>
   The team is hitting .262 with runners in scoring position for
the season, 11th in the National League. With two outs and runners
in scoring position, that number falls to .234, 15th in the league.
</P>
<P>
   ``In '95, we hit .255 as a team, so it had to be less than that
with runners in scoring position, and that's the year we won the
World Series,'' said Chipper Jones, who is hitting .283 with
runners in scoring position. ``It's all about if you get hot at the
right time and play good ball in September. We know we can play
with anybody in baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   The loss of Javy Lopez really hurts, because he was hitting .296
with runners in scoring position. Only Brian Jordan's .324 is
better on the Braves.
</P>
<P>
   ``A big swing of the bat by a guy in the middle of the lineup
could have won us the ball game (Tuesday) night,'' Chipper Jones
said. ``It's going to happen. You can't dwell on it.''
</P>
<P>
   Helms hurt again
</P>
<P>
   Minor-league third baseman Wes Helms, who recently returned from
right shoulder surgery, is out for the year after separating his
left shoulder in a collison at first base Friday. Helms was
examined Wednesday by Braves team orthopedist Dr. Joe Chandler. For
now, no surgery is planned.
</P>
<P>
   In the spring, Helms had surgery to repair a torn rotator cuff
in his right shoulder. He was supposed to be out for the season but
returned to the Greenville Braves, where he was hitting .301 with
26 RBIs in 30 games. Helms will miss his chance at a September
call-up to Atlanta. He played in seven games for the Braves last
September in his first appearance in the major leagues, hitting
.308 (4-for-13) with his first major-league home run.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
