<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-PLANETHOLLYWOOD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: BANKRUPTCY AMONG THE STARS 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Thursday, Aug. 19:
</P>
<P>
   It was just over three years ago that Planet Hollywood was a
very hot stock. The company sold shares to the public at $18 a
share and saw them leap to $32 the very first day they traded.
Arnold Schwarzenegger and Demi Moore were among the celebrity
shareholders who took part in the festivities when the stock began
trading.
</P>
<P>
   There were no festivities Wednesday when the New York Stock
Exchange suspended Planet Hollywood shares from trading and said
they would be delisted. That move came a day after the company said
it would file for bankruptcy under a plan that will render the
shares virtually worthless.
</P>
<P>
   Planet Hollywood, which operates restaurants under that name as
well as under the title Official All-Star Cafe, seemed like a great
concept back in 1996. ``We are up against all restaurants,'' said
Robert Earl, the company's founder, not long after the successful
offering. ``What sets us apart is our merchandising, our stars and
our themes.''
</P>
<P>
   The restaurants soon earned a reputation for poor food at
excessive prices, however, and it turned out that the opportunity
to dine in the vicinity of such memorabilia as Sylvester Stallone's
robe from ``Rocky'' or Judy Garland's dress from ``The Wizard of
Oz'' was not enough to persuade diners to return. Sales peaked in
1997 and have been falling since.
</P>
<P>
   The bankruptcy plan calls for the chain to continue operating
under the ownership of creditors and investors _ including Earl's
family _ who are putting in $30 million in cash. Perhaps Earl, who
will remain as chief executive, can turn things around. But whether
or not he does, the star-struck public investors who loved the
stock in 1996 now have lost everything they invested.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-18-99 2115EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990818.0361 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-18 21:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2197 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-R-TURKEY-CENTER-NYT &LR;      08-18 0755
