<SLUG> BC-FBC-CSUN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GREEN FEELS HEALED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRIS BRANAM  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; LOS ANGELES _ His uniform drenched with perspiration, Kaleon
Green found a spot in the shade during a short break in Cal State
Northridge's football practice Wednesday morning.
</P>
<P>
   His chest was heaving and he was holding his hands on his waist.
But Green wasn't complaining. For the first time in two years, he
has a chance to play in a college football game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just glad to be back,'' said Green, a 6-foot-2, 235-pound
senior linebacker. ``I feel like I'm making progress. I'm making
plays.''
</P>
<P>
   Green was a starter for the Matadors in 1997, but he broke his
leg jogging last summer and missed the '98 season. He participated
in spring practice but didn't make the team's depth chart.
</P>
<P>
   Green is showing this week he's better than third-string.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kaleon is a guy that can definitely help us,'' said Terrance
Johnson, CSUN's linebackers coach. ``He'll definitely play a lot
for us. He's a force.''
</P>
<P>
   CSUN must first hope that Green's appeal to the NCAA for a rare
sixth year of eligibility is granted. After graduating from
Crenshaw High in 1992, Green found out he had cancer and he sat out
two years.
</P>
<P>
   He went to West Los Angeles College, where he competed in '94
and '96, then went to Missouri and left the Tigers' program after
competing in spring practice in '97. Green, 25, transferred to CSUN
and made 26 tackles that season.
</P>
<P>
   __ Impressive rookie: One of the bright spots on the offensive
line has been freshman tackle Nick Longshore, who was an
All-Foothill League lineman at Canyon High last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's had a really good camp,'' CSUN interim head coach Jeff
Kearin said. ``He's really been impressive.''
</P>
<P>
   Longshore is playing well despite losing 20 pounds in the last
three months because of an illness Longshore said doctors haven't
diagnosed. In May, the 6-6 Longshore weighed 275 pounds. He's down
to 255.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was quicker, faster and stronger before I got sick,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   __ Tarnished gold: Jeremy Golden's offseason was forgettable.
</P>
<P>
   Golden, a sophomore safety from Westlake High who led the
Matadors with 94 tackles last year, only made it through a couple
of practices this spring before going out with pain in his knee.
</P>
<P>
   He hasn't been practicing this week, but Golden couldn't even if
he was healthy. He's academically ineligible.
</P>
<P>
   The CSUN coaches aren't sure what is wrong with Golden's knee,
and head athletic trainer Rhonda Lowry said she hasn't been updated
because Golden is getting medical treatment from his own doctor.
Golden hasn't had surgery performed, but Kearin is recommending he
get it done.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jeremy's got a year to (redshirt),'' Kearin said. ``He's just
got to take care of that knee.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Ailing: Jaumal Bradley couldn't keep food down Tuesday night,
but he couldn't stay away from the field Wednesday morning.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley, a senior fullback, showed up at 6:45 a.m. to run
sprints, even though he was sick the night before. He didn't
practice but went to the weight room for two hours.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
