u i BC-TURKEY-FAMILY19-COX     08-18 0780
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TURKEY-FAMILY19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Turkey earthquake devastates Atlanta family
 &HT;    By Arthur Brice and Julie Bryant
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Anesthesiologist Babur Kilic was supposed to board a
plane Saturday to join his wife, their five children and his
parents at their summer home in Turkey. Instead, Kilic left
Wednesday to make funeral arrangements for four of his children and
his father.
</P>
<P>
   Kilic's wife, Jan, and their daughter Natalie, 6, survived
Tuesday's earthquake. So did his mother, Turkan Kilic, although she
is in critical condition and on life-support in a Turkish hospital.
Jan Kilic is being treated at the American Hospital in Istanbul,
but family members in Marietta don't know her condition. Natalie is
reportedly unhurt.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is trying to be strong,'' Cigdem Kilic, Babur Kilic's
sister-in-law, said Wednesday. ``He's very upset, but he's also
thankful that his wife is alive and one of his children is alive.''
</P>
<P>
   The human toll from the quake had climbed late Wednesday to
3,839 dead and nearly 18,500 injured. But more than 10,000 people
are still missing, and the final death count could top 12,000, said
Yavuz Tarcan, the Turkish honorary consul in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``They cannot reach some regions yet,'' said Tarcan, a physician
who practices nuclear medicine in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Tarcan said there are unconfirmed reports that three or four
other people with North Georgia connections also died in the
temblor. The honorary consul's office has been deluged with
telephone calls from worried relatives. Some of the calls, Tarcan
said, also have come from concerned Americans with children
traveling in Turkey or with friends who live in the hardest-hit
areas.
</P>
<P>
   Babur Kilic, known to his friends as ``Bobby,'' was accompanied
to Turkey by his two older brothers, Timur and Cengiz. The three
Kilic brothers are Marietta anesthesiologists who practice at
Wellstar-Kennestone Hospital. All three graduated from the
University of Alabama school of medicine.
</P>
<P>
   Their father, Nizam Kilic, was a retired pediatrician who lived
in Marietta with his wife, Turkan, also a retired physician.
</P>
<P>
   The dead Kilic children were identified as Jeffrey Michael, 6;
Jennifer Kayla, 5; David Tansan, 2; and Katherine ``Katie''
Michelle, who was born Nov. 2, 1998.
</P>
<P>
   They attended Casa dei Bambini Montessori school in Marietta.
</P>
<P>
   Inside Babur Kilic's two-story brick home in east Cobb, about 10
family members and friends gathered Wednesday evening around a
television set, tracking news developments. .
</P>
<P>
   ``It's unbelievable,'' said Jack Kemp, Jan Kilic's father.
</P>
<P>
   Kemp and his wife were traveling to the New England coast for a
seven-week vacation Tuesday when they heard of the quake.
</P>
<P>
   ``At first we heard it wasn't their building,'' Kemp said.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, their relief gave way to shock as official word of
the children's death came by phone call.
</P>
<P>
   Jan Kilic, her children and her in-laws were on vacation in the
resort town of Yalova when the five-story building in which they
were staying collapsed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jan wanted to expose the kids to culture and their heritage,''
Kemp said. ``She's a strong girl. Her faith will see her through
this.''
</P>
<P>
   Jan Kilic owns a contracting firm and builds houses in Atlanta.
She is also active in her church, Kemp said.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere in metro Atlanta, friends and loved ones of the Kilic
family expressed their disbelief that such tragedy could visit such
good people.
</P>
<P>
   Zeynep Karasu, who retired as a pediatrician three years ago,
has known the Kilic family for more than 25 years. She first got to
know Nizam Kilic through their work as pediatricians. Later, his
three sons became doctors, and she worked with them at
Wellstar-Kennestone Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   ``I talked with Babur yesterday,'' she said Wednesday afternoon.
``He didn't know anything. Of course, none of us knew anything. The
telephones were not working.''
</P>
<P>
   She found out Wednesday morning, shortly after Kilic got the
devastating news.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very hard. Very hard,'' Karasu said, her voice breaking.
</P>
<P>
   At the home of Timur Kilic, family members were trying to cope
with the sudden loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not easy,'' said Cigdem Kilic, who has been married to
Timur for 12 years. ``It's terrible. And the way they died. It's
awful.''
</P>
<P>
   Others tried to remember some of the Kilics in better times.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a very, very nice man,'' Mehmet Yildirim, president of
the Turkish American Cultural Association of Georgia, said of Nizam
Kilic. ``He would come to all of our functions. He would donate
money. He was just a gentleman.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
