<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HARTSFIELD19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Power failure at Atlanta airport causes hot hike for travelers
 &HT;    By Bill Montgomery and Patti Puckett
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Caroline Cramer's trip through Hartsfield
International Airport on Wednesday felt sweaty enough to qualify as
a trip to the gym.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just kept getting warmer and warmer and warmer,'' she said
as she waited for her flight to Michigan after walking more than a
mile to reach her gate on Concourse D. ``I'm not going to do my
treadmill today.''
</P>
<P>
   An unexplained failure in an electrical cable sparked a series
of problems that eventually cut off power to the main terminal at
Hartsfield for 22 minutes, starting at 2:26 a.m. Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The world's busiest airport sees few of its 200,000-plus daily
passengers at that hour, with no scheduled passenger flights and
its ``people mover'' train shut down. And, with emergency back-up
lights, the terminal never fully blacked out. But the after-effects
made navigating the airport grueling work for the morning rush.
</P>
<P>
   Power reductions forced airport officials to cut back on air
conditioning and not to run the trains until shortly before noon.
Full power was restored about 11:20 a.m., airport officials said.
</P>
<P>
   With travelers hoofing it between concourses, airport employees
and volunteers rolled out coolers of ice and bottled water. They
offered wheelchairs to older passengers. Some travelers raced
through the airport to meet flights. Businessmen loosened ties as
they rode the moving sidewalks, which never shut down. Even with a
moving sidewalk, it can take a walker in reasonably good shape
about six minutes to get from one concourse to the next, and some
travelers were covering several concourses. Passengers with
international flights faced a hike of up to 1.75 miles from the
main terminal to Concourse E.
</P>
<P>
   Delta Air Lines delayed some flights five to 10 minutes to give
hurrying passengers a break. ``We were lenient,'' said Delta
spokesman Bill Berry. ``Our usual focus is departing on time, but
we felt it was more responsible to the passengers to delay the
flights.''
</P>
<P>
   The power failure did not disrupt operations in the airport
control tower or runway lights and no flights were canceled or
seriously delayed, said Hartsfield Deputy General Manager Mario
Diaz.
</P>
<P>
   Diaz said air conditioning was reduced, not cut off, but
passengers hurrying between concourses to catch planes couldn't
tell the difference. Barry Vermillion of High Point, N.C., awaited
a flight at Concourse D, which was sweltering at about 11 a.m. ``I
had plenty of time, so getting here wasn't really a problem,'' he
said. ``However, it is hot.''
</P>
<P>
   Travelers arriving at distant concourses were surprised to learn
of the long walk to baggage claim and ground transportation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now they're telling me I have to walk a mile and a half,''
said an exhausted Blanche Calhoun of Detroit, who was on her way to
Augusta for a funeral and needed to get from Concourse D to the car
rental counters in the terminal. ``There's always something with
these airports. I can't believe this.''
</P>
<P>
   Hartsfield customer service worker Vilma Villaverde said it made
for a rough morning. ``People were running and they would drop
their tickets,'' she said. ``Some people decided it was too far to
walk, so they asked for a wheelchair. You know, the senior people,
the fat people. The people pushing the wheelchairs got so hot.''
</P>
<P>
   She said about every wheelchair at the airport went into service
on the pedestrian mall Wednesday morning.
</P>
<P>
   The airport's nine trains do not operate between 12:30 and 5
a.m., and so were ``off line'' when the trouble began at 12:41
a.m., said Hartsfield spokesman Dwayne Clark. Six trains were back
in service by 11:45 a.m. All were in operation by Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   The electrical problem began when one of the three main
electrical cables supplying Hartsfield failed.
</P>
<P>
   As workers searched for an answer, the failed cable overheated,
causing two other main cables to fail at 2:26 a.m., said Georgia
Power officials. At that time, two other 1.5-inch feeder cables,
which supply power to the airport trains, also failed.
</P>
<P>
   Dispatching up to 70 workers to the airport, Georgia Power
re-energized one of the two main cables, but asked airport
officials to reduce electrical strain on the cable by reducing air
conditioning and lighting in the main terminal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We asked the six restaurants and some of the concessions in
the terminal, which normally open at 8 a.m., not to open until the
damaged power cable was repaired,'' Clark said.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia Power investigators could not determine Wednesday why
the first cable failed.
</P>
<P>
   Staff writer Richard Halicks contributed to this article.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
