r s BC-BBN-EAST-TEX     08-18 0904
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-EAST-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRAVES ARE VULNERABLE, METS NO LONGER THE JOKERS IN NL EAST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SIMON GONZALEZ 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Mets envisioned themselves as contenders heading
into the season. But in early June, they were reduced to comedians.
</P>
<P>
   There was low comedy: An eight-game losing streak culminated in
the firing of coaches Bob Apodaca, Randy Niemann and Tom Robson,
all close friends of manager Bobby Valentine's.
</P>
<P>
   There was physical comedy: A feud between Valentine and
disgruntled veteran Bobby Bonilla boiled over with a shouting match
in the dugout, with Bonilla inviting Valentine to step inside to
settle their differences.
</P>
<P>
   There was slapstick comedy: After being ejected from a game
against the Toronto Blue Jays, Valentine returned to the dugout
with a fake mustache and dark glasses.
</P>
<P>
   But if anyone was laughing, they were doing so at, not with, the
team. The Mets bottomed out with a 27-28 record.
</P>
<P>
   ``That whole week, everything that could go wrong did go
wrong,'' Mets catcher Mike Piazza said. ``That was tough.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, a little more than two months later, it seems as if the
Mets might have the final chortle.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets are involved with the mighty Atlanta Braves in one of
the best and most unlikely races in the major leagues. The two
teams entered Wednesday's games tied for the top spot in the
National League East with 73-48 records. The Braves fell a
half-game back after losing to Colorado, with the Mets scheduled to
play late Wednesday night in San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   It's an unlikely race because the Braves are the team of the
1990s, while the Mets are one of the doormats of the decade.
</P>
<P>
   In the eight in the '90s that were finished _ 1994 ended with a
players' strike _ the Braves have won seven division titles, four
pennants and one World Series. The Mets had losing records six
times this decade and haven't been in the playoffs since 1988.
</P>
<P>
   ``The postseason is a big motivating force for this team,'' said
Valentine, who is trying to reach the playoffs for the first time
in 12 seasons as a manager, including eight in Texas. ``Guys
understand that a few years ago the Mets were a laughingstock.''
</P>
<P>
   A few weeks ago the Mets were a laughingstock, but after the
eight-game losing streak they while losing just 20]went 46-20.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got that out of our system,'' Piazza said. ``I think it was
inevitable we were going to play better.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the June follies, the Mets were too talented not to.
</P>
<P>
   Their infield of first baseman John Olerud, second baseman
Edgardo Alfonzo, shortstop Rey Ordonez and third baseman Robin
Ventura is perhaps the best defensively in the majors.
</P>
<P>
   Ageless leadoff hitter Rickey Henderson, Alfonzo, Olerud, Piazza
and Ventura, augmented by the emergence of young outfielders Roger
Cedeno and Benny Agbayani, give the team a solid offense.
</P>
<P>
   The rotation is solid, the bullpen deep.
</P>
<P>
   General manager Steve Phillips improved the team by sending two
prospects to the Oakland Athletics for starting pitcher Kenny
Rogers on July 23, then acquired relievers Billy Taylor and Chuck
McElroy, center fielder Darryl Hamilton and utility player Shawon
Dunston at the July 31 trading deadline.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going for it,` Phillips said. ``Now's the time. You
don't know how many times the opportunity will present itself.''
</P>
<P>
   The Braves have failed to win their division only twice in the
1990s, when they were 65-97 in '90 and when they were 68-46 and
second to the Montreal Expos when the players went on strike in
'94. But the Mets sense an opportunity because the Braves _ no
longer appear invincible.
</P>
<P>
   First baseman Andres Galarraga, who hit .305 with 44 homers and
121 runs batted in last season, has missed the season after a
diagnosis of cancer. All-Star catcher Javy Lopez is finished for
the year because of a knee injury.
</P>
<P>
   Their trio of Cy Young Award-winning pitchers _ Greg Maddux, Tom
Glavine and John Smoltz _ suddenly looks mortal. Maddux is 15-6
with a 3.66 earned-run average, but opponents are hitting over .290
against him. Glavine is 10-9 with a 4.17 ERA. Smoltz is 8-6 with a
3.60 ERA and has been on the disabled list twice because of an
elbow injury. He altered his delivery to alleviate the pain in his
most recent start and strained his groin.
</P>
<P>
   However, general manager John Schuerholz recognized his team's
weaknesses at the trading deadline, and acquired shortstop Jose
Hernandez to shore up the offense and Terry Mulholland to provide
depth to the pitching staff.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did all we could do,'' Schuerholz said. ``We helped to fill
the void some.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the problems, the Braves remain one of the best teams in
baseball. Their .603 winning percentage before losing to Colorado
Wednesday was tied with the Mets for the best in the NL, and behind
only the New York Yankees and Cleveland Indians in the majors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without a doubt it will be the most satisfying year we've ever
had if we can overcome all this adversity to win it,'' third
baseman Chipper Jones said.
</P>
<P>
   In Atlanta, winning it doesn't mean the East.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be rewarding to win the division, but the goal
here is to win the World Series,'' right fielder Brian Jordan said.
``We've just got to keep staying together as a team and keep
winning.''
</P>
<P>
   But with the Mets hanging around, winning the East no longer is
a sure thing. And that's no joke. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
