<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-18 21:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2232 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-STARR-DEPART-2NDLD-WR     08-18 0981
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STARR-DEPART-2NDLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARR PLANNING TO RESIGN AS INDEPENDENT COUNSEL, ASSOCIATES SAY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs lede graf to change `last summer's' to `impeachment battle in
Congress')  (sw) 
 By DAVID JOHNSTON and NEIL LEWIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Kenneth Starr, the independent counsel, is quitting
as early as October to resume his legal practice after a five-year
investigation into President Clinton's personal and business
affairs that led to the impeachment battle in Congress, Starr's
associates said on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   According to the associates, Starr has decided that he will
remain in office long enough to put his personal stamp on a final
report summarizing the findings of his inquiries _ a report looming
as a potential embarrassment to Hillary Rodham Clinton as she moves
closer to entering the race for the U.S. Senate in New York.
</P>
<P>
   In recent days, Starr has communicated his plans to the
three-member panel of federal appellate judges that presides over
independent counsel matters, asking that one of his top lieutenants
take over the closing phase of the long inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   The same three-judge panel divided sharply on Wednesday,
declaring there was no basis for it to unilaterally terminate
Starr's investigation. The ruling was apparently unconnected to
Starr's private assurances to the judges that he would soon leave.
The independent counsel law requires the panel to decide every year
whether to terminate an investigation. The law has expired, but it
still governs Starr's operations.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, the opinion exposed harsh differences in how the
judges view Starr's investigation. The two judges appointed by
Republican presidents, David J. Sentelle and Peter T. Fay, lauded
Starr, saying his investigation has been ``unusually productive,''
resulting in not only the impeachment of a president but 24
indictments and 16 convictions. They said that under the law they
were prohibited from delving into the independent counsel's
operation and thus they could not order it ended.
</P>
<P>
   The panel's lone Democratic-appointed judge, Richard D. Cudahy,
said it was useless and wasteful for the investigation to go on.
Cudahy wrote that after President Clinton's acquittal by the
Senate, the investigation had reached ``a natural and logical point
for termination since is is not clear how additional measures
against the principal subject of the investigation could be
pursued.''
</P>
<P>
   Cudahy also complained that he was rebuffed in his efforts to
have the court formally ask Starr how much is left to investigate.
He said that the court's only knowledge of how the investigation
was progressing or whether it was nearing its end came from
``informal contacts'' between Sentelle, the panel's chief, and
Starr.
</P>
<P>
   Starr, a bookish legal scholar who seemed more at home with
abstract constitutional theories than the bare-knuckled world of
criminal prosecutions, would leave with his once-pristine
reputation for probity now tarnished after years of attacks by
Clinton's defenders _ even as Starr unearthed an Oval Office sex
scandal that led to Clinton's impeachment in the House and his
subsequent trial and acquittal in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Starr will also be remembered as the man largely responsible for
the demise of the independent counsel statute, enacted after
Watergate.
</P>
<P>
   Starr has told associates he expects to return to his job as a
partner at the Washington office of Kirkland &AMP; Ellis, where he
specialized in the firm's appellate practice. But associates said
he has not reached a specific agreement with Kirkland &AMP; Ellis, and
representatives of the firm did not return phone calls Wednesday on
the subject.
</P>
<P>
   Starr's communication to the three-judge panel that he was
planning to depart was first reported by ABC News.
</P>
<P>
   Officials in Starr's office said that there had been substantial
progress in writing the final report. Starr is required to file a
report but has leeway in explaining his actions in regard to people
who were investigated but not indicted.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, some Starr associates said, there was a vigorous
discussion as to how he would deal with questions involving Mrs.
Clinton, for whom Starr's office once drafted an indictment that
was never presented to the grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   In June, one associate of Starr said the final report could be
``blistering'' in its description of Mrs. Clinton's behavior, even
though it would only be a recitation of events and unresolved
issues without any explicitly stated judgments. Starr associates
said that the report would inevitably convey a critical view
because it would raise unanswered questions about Mrs. Clinton's
behavior in some land transactions in Arkansas and her testimony
under oath about her actions as a lawyer in those deals.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Edward Page, Starr's spokesman, said that, ``our
final report was never meant to be blistering. We won't
characterize.''
</P>
<P>
   Page said that the final report will include just the facts and
the evidence and ``there won't be accusations.''
</P>
<P>
   Starr and his aides also have discussed how the termination of
the independent counsel statute would affect his inquiry and
whether Starr could turn over all or part of the remaining
investigative matters to career prosecutors in the Justice
Department. Those discussions were exploratory and have not
resulted in any agreement, law enforcement officials said on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Starr has not said publicly what avenues of inquiry remain open.
But lawyers involved in the cases said recently that they center on
whether Mrs. Clinton was truthful in denying a role in firing of
employees at the White House travel office, and the conduct of
Nathan Landow, a Democratic fund-raiser from Maryland, in Starr's
investigation of accusations that Clinton had made a sexual advance
to a White House volunteer, Kathleen Willey, in the Oval Office.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
