<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-18 21:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2233 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-FBN-JONES-EXPANSION-H     08-18 1107
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-JONES-EXPANSION-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN McCLAIN  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
WICHITA FALLS _ Unlike most NFL owners who are waiting for the
Sept. 15 deadline, Jerry Jones is not afraid to publicly support
Houston over Los Angeles in the race to win the 32nd franchise.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Although the Dallas Cowboys would have to share the Texas market
with Bob McNair's expansion team in Houston, Jones believes it is
in the best interests of the Lone Star State and the NFL to have
franchises in both cities.
</P>
<P>
   Calling Houston's chances of getting the expansion franchise
``outstanding,'' Jones would push for an annual regular-season game
between Dallas and Houston under a new scheduling format that is
being considered for the time when the NFL may realign into eight
divisions of four teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, I think Houston has really gotten out ahead of Los
Angeles as far as the likelihood of where this expansion will go,''
Jones said this week at the Cowboys' training camp at Midwestern
State University.
</P>
<P>
   Jones is a Houston supporter because of the stadium financial
plan that includes almost $200 million in public money. And like
almost all of the owners, commissioner Paul Tagliabue and other NFL
executives, Jones would welcome McNair into one of the business
world's most exclusive fraternities.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are many people in the league that, if given a choice
between having a Los Angeles franchise or a Houston franchise,
would rather have a Houston franchise from the standpoint of just
the marketplace alone,'' Jones said. ``Forget the fact that one's
got the stadium in place and the other doesn't.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you look at Los Angeles and what has to be done privately
with the stadium (with no public money), it's a big ticket relative
to what's in place in Houston.''
</P>
<P>
   Before the Oilers moved to Tennessee, they played the Cowboys
every three years under the current scheduling format. If Houston
gets the 32nd franchise, Jones wants to see the Cowboys playing
McNair's team every season.
</P>
<P>
   Although they would remain in different conferences and
divisions, Dallas and Houston could play in each regular season if
the league adopts a proposed scheduling format that would promote
natural rivalries.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the premises behind anything to do with realignment is
how do we create regional interest,'' Jones said. ``It shouldn't
disrupt the traditional rivalries that are already there, but we
can do this with the non-division part of your schedule.
</P>
<P>
   ``What would be ideal would be to schedule a game, like Dallas
vs. Houston, as well as natural rivals in other parts of the
country, where we can create some AFC-NFC rivalries. I wouldn't be
opposed to having home and away (games) in those particular
situations.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the thing that was always missing (when the Cowboys
played the Oilers) _ a real good, tight, predictable, rivalry on
the field between Dallas and Houston.''
</P>
<P>
   Because he owns the Cowboys and knows how to generate revenue
better than any owner in the league, Jones is one of the league's
most influential power brokers. He serves on four of the NFL's most
prominent committees and is instrumental in the league's
decision-making process.
</P>
<P>
   Jones' belief that Houston deserves the expansion franchise and
his influence among the owners are two reasons McNair has sought
Jones' counsel since he became serious about owning a team that
would replace the Oilers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really glad Bob's taken the ball and run with it,'' Jones
said. ``I've seen his approach to how he wants to market the team,
and it's outstanding. It's like a Harvard study. I refer to it all
the time in terms of how he'd like to handle his sponsorships and
relationships.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got a lot of good ideas that are tailored to the
uniqueness of the Houston market. It's a great opportunity. I like
the demographics of Houston as far as where we're trying to go as a
league. For instance, our interests Hispanicly. Our interests as
far as our fan base is concerned minority-wise.''
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles has a league-mandated Sept. 15 deadline to produce a
sound stadium financing plan that must include at least $150
million in public money. So far, the owners have not been happy
with what LA has to offer. The league is looking at other potential
stadium sites like Carson and Hollywood Park.
</P>
<P>
   A source in Los Angeles says LA will mount one more effort to
convince the owners that the New Coliseum at Exposition Park
deserves the team. That plan will center on Eli Broad, who is
partners with Ed Roski, offering to put up much of the money for
the $111 million primary parking garage the NFL is demanding.
</P>
<P>
   Jones believes it is in the NFL's best interests to allow
Raiders owner Al Davis to return to Los Angeles. Jones has been
working behind the scenes for months to help Davis.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to potentially look at Los Angeles by looking at what
Oakland's situation is,'' Jones says. ``That's (his opinion) not
necessarily shared by a lot of people (in the league).
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to (help Davis), not so much for Al but for the league.
We don't need two teams up there (in the Bay Area), and I think the
answer to Los Angeles is that maybe it suits moving a team there.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones believes the Sept. 15 deadline will pass without the
league making a decision on Houston or Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I see happening is nothing acceptable being done by the
middle of September,'' he said. ``I don't think we'll see an
immediate decision that's automatic (to go to Houston).
</P>
<P>
   ``I think what we'll see is a period of time _ more than is
probably needed _ where we say, `Hey, we tried to get the team in
Los Angeles. Let's try to get this thing done (with Houston)
sometime this year.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Some owners are pushing to find out just how much McNair can
afford on an expansion fee. Reports are that he can expect between
$500 million and $600 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't want to say, mainly because I wouldn't want to put
that on Bob one way or another,'' Jones said when asked what he
believes the expansion fee should be. ``But I'll tell you this to
consider, if Houston went back to the AFC Central, that whole group
of teams will be playing in new revenue-producing stadiums.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there's any reason in the world that we
shouldn't be able to come together (on an expansion fee with
McNair) because we all have the same interests. Everybody says,
`We've got to have a team in Houston. We've got to have a team in
Houston,' but it's lip service until we do it.'
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing to remember is that we've still got a lot of work to
do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
