<HEADLINE>
MICROSOFT MOVES AGAINST AMERICAN ONLINE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)   (af)  
 By MATT RICHTEL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ In its latest tweak at America Online, Microsoft
Corp. announced Wednesday that it would release a computer protocol
to enable subscribers of competing instant-messaging services to
communicate with its own customers.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft officials said the move was intended to pave the way
for communication among subscribers of the handful of major
companies offering instant messaging, a feature that allows
computer users to contact one another instantaneously and chat on
line.
</P>
<P>
   Thus far, users of instant-message services have been largely
relegated to sending messages to users within their own service. In
a pitched battle with America Online, which pioneered instant
messaging, Microsoft has sought to deliver messages from its own
subscribers to users of America Online's software without the
company's permission.
</P>
<P>
   America Online, which says it has 43 million users of one form
or another on its instant-messaging software, has accused Microsoft
of hacking into its system to route messages to and from America
Online customers.
</P>
<P>
   At least 14 times, America Online has changed its protocol _ the
specifications that allow two software programs to communicate _
and each time Microsoft programmers have found a way around the
barrier.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft, which has amassed 1.5 million users of its
instant-messaging software in less than a month of service, is not
alone. Other instant-messaging competitors, including Tribal Voice,
which has five million instant-messaging members, have said they
also intend to link to users of America Online's software.
</P>
<P>
   In this respect, the latest twist in the skirmish underscores a
larger issue: with 60 million to 100 million people estimated to
use instant messaging, there is growing momentum among the
competitors to create standards so their subscribers can
communicate.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're at a watershed,'' said Richard Dym, vice president for
marketing for Tribal Voice, based in Scotts Valley, Calif. ``In
order for this form of communication to take the next step, to
maybe even replace e-mail, we need openness.''
</P>
<P>
   Dym said the growing use of instant messaging had started
momentum in the last year to create a standard protocol so
competing services can exchange messages over the Internet. And he
said Microsoft was adding to that momentum by putting its
substantial resources and weight behind the standards quest.
</P>
<P>
   For its part, America Online said it, too, favored open
standards permitting communication among users of different
services. Tricia Primrose, an America Online spokeswoman, said the
company had been working for several weeks with the Internet
Engineering Task Force, which is overseeing the creation of
standards for a protocol.
</P>
<P>
   Dym called it ``a big-time irony'' that Microsoft was releasing
its instant-messaging protocol, since it has jealously guarded the
source code for its operating systems and software programs.
</P>
<P>
   But Rob Bennett, vice president for marketing at MSN,
Microsoft's online division, said the comparison was unfair. He
said Microsoft's willingness to publish the protocol was consistent
with a policy to make its software widely ``interoperable.''
</P>
<P>
   The Internet Engineering Task Force praised Microsoft. The move
will help ``in informing our development of robust, open protocols
for Internet-wide interoperability in this area,'' wrote Vijay
Saraswat and Dave Marvit, who are leading the standards committee.
</P>
<P>
   In another front in the instant-messaging battle, Microsoft
officials said Wednesday that they had identified and reprimanded
an employee who used a false identity to send a message
discrediting America Online to a computer security expert.
</P>
<P>
   The employee sent a message under the name Phil Bucking of
Bucking Consulting, but the security expert, Richard Smith, traced
the message back to Microsoft. Wednesday the company confirmed that
the message had come from an employee, who had stepped forward to
confess.
</P>
<P>
   Bennett declined to say what disciplinary action had been taken,
but defended the employee as having tried to do the ``right thing''
by publicizing what Microsoft contends is a security flaw in
America Online's system. ``This is a case of good intentions and
bad execution,'' he said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1990s, Microsoft dismissed an employee for
anonymously posting criticisms of IBM's competing operating system
on online bulletin boards. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
