<HEADLINE>
NEWS CORP.'S EARNINGS FELL IN 4TH QUARTER 
</HEADLINE>
  (af) 
 By ANDREW POLLACK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ News Corp.'s earnings before an extraordinary item
fell 20 percent in its fourth fiscal quarter, as weak results from
its Fox television network offset strong gains in its Twentieth
Century Fox film division, the company said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Australia-based media company, controlled by Rupert Murdoch,
reported after-tax earnings of $214 million, or 21 cents an
American depository receipt, for the three months ended June 30,
down from $266 million, or 27 cents, in the comparable quarter a
year ago. The results were 3 cents a share below the consensus
estimate of analysts surveyed by the First Call Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Including a one-time cost of $224 million to convert its B-Sky-B
satellite broadcasting service in Britain to digital technology,
the News Corp. reported a net loss of $10 million, or 2 cents an
ADR, in contrast to a net profit a year earlier of $233 million, or
23 cents. Revenue for the quarter edged up to $3.27 billion from
$3.24 billion in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The force was with the company's film division, with operating
income nearly quadrupling in the quarter to $22 million, partly
because of the new ``Star Wars'' movie, which opened in May and has
generated more than $400 million in domestic box office receipts. A
News Corp. spokesman said that strong video sales of ``Titanic''
and ``There's Something About Mary'' also contributed to the gains.
</P>
<P>
   On the negative side, the Fox Broadcasting Co., the television
network, did not attract as much advertising as it had expected in
the May ``sweeps'' period, lowering its profits. For the year as a
whole, the network had an operating loss because of higher
programming costs and losses incurred in broadcasting the World
Series and National Hockey League games.
</P>
<P>
   But Fox is now putting into effect a new agreement with its
affiliated stations that would allow the network to keep a greater
share of advertising revenues.
</P>
<P>
   The company recorded a big decline in income in its magazine
business because of the sale in March of its controlling stake in
TV Guide. Profits in newspapers also declined because of lower
circulation revenues at The Sun in London.
</P>
<P>
   The company also had sizable losses from such new activities as
the Fox News cable channel, satellite operations in Latin America
and various Internet ventures. But executives predict these will
pay off in the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it was a great building year for News,'' David DeVoe,
the chief financial officer, said in a conference call with
reporters.
</P>
<P>
   For the fiscal year, net income fell nearly 41 percent to $678
million, or 67 cents an ADR, from $1.14 billion or $1.17. Revenue
rose to a record $13.59 billion from $12.84 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Separately, Fox Entertainment Group, which is 83 percent owned
by the News Corp., said its net income in the quarter ended June 30
jumped to $35 million, or 5 cents a share, from $3 million, or 1
cent a share, reported a year earlier. Revenue increased more than
12 percent to $1.97 billion from $1.75 billion. Fox Entertainment
encompasses the company's American television, film and sports
businesses.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
