<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-18 22:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2246 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-NY-PAROLE-(TRIMS)-NYT     08-18 1237
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-PAROLE-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. PROBE OF PATAKI FUND RAISING UNCOVERS LINK TO PAROLE PROCESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By CLIFFORD J. LEVY and KEVIN FLYNN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The scribbled note from a political fund-raiser for
Gov. George Pataki to a Pataki administration official carried a
terse directive: ``These are three names that need to be followed
up with.''
</P>
<P>
   What came next were details on three men in New York prisons _
violent felons whose relatives had made sizable donations to the
Pataki campaign in the belief, say prosecutors, that the money
would get the inmates paroled.
</P>
<P>
   The note was among a series of documents unearthed by the U.S.
attorney's office in Brooklyn in its investigation into the
campaign's fund raising, a trove that provides a rare view of
Pataki officials assisting a handful of major campaign
contributors.
</P>
<P>
   The documents, as well as courtroom testimony, recount how the
campaign sent inquiries about the prisoners directly to the
governor's office, which passed them on to the Parole Board, which
is controlled by the governor's appointees. In fact, this week, a
parole official pleaded guilty to lying to federal officials in the
case and insisted in court that the governor's office expressed
strong concern about one of the prisoners, John Kim, who was
ultimately released on parole. The other two, John Jhang and
Boyoung Chung, were not paroled.
</P>
<P>
   While strenuously denying any wrongdoing, even some of the
governor's closest associates privately acknowledge that the
investigation has at times offered an unflattering portrait of the
Pataki administration.
</P>
<P>
   The inquiry now seems to be expanding. The parole officer who
pleaded guilty in the investigation this week, Ronald Hotaling,
strongly suggested in court that Parole Board Chairman Brion
Travis, who was appointed by Pataki, told him of ``the interest of
the governor's office in the release'' of one of the felons.
</P>
<P>
   Several state officials have said that in recent months, the
administration has revamped the Parole Board and greatly reduced
Travis' role in running its day-to-day operations. Thomas Grant, a
spokesman for Travis, declined to comment on the current scope of
Travis' job.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors are also said to be focusing on a separate case
involving whether parole officials gave lenient treatment to Shlomo
Helbrans, a Hasidic rabbi imprisoned in a widely publicized
kidnapping case.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter recently entered into the court record, the
prosecutors say that a parole official ``took steps to facilitate
the release of'' Helbrans because the official felt ``improper
political pressure'' being brought on the rabbi's behalf. Helbrans
was convicted of kidnapping a teen-ager, Shai Fhima Reuven, in
1994, after Shai's mother entrusted him to the rabbi for bar
mitzvah instruction.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Pataki aides dismissed the 20-month-old inquiry as a politically
motivated attempt to embarrass the governor. They said no one
received special favors, noting that of the three prisoners, only
the one with an exemplary prison record was paroled. They said that
Hotaling and Sean McSherry, a parole commissioner convicted of
perjury in the case earlier this month, were hired under Pataki's
predecessors. And both were indicted for lying when questioned in
the case, not for influence-peddling.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Michael McKeon, the governor's press secretary, declined to
comment on specific documents or testimony. ``The prosecutors know
that those members of this administration involved in these cases
handled themselves appropriately and properly,'' McKeon said. ``At
some point, they are going to have to acknowledge that fact. In
fairness, it should be sooner, rather than later.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Helbrans case, prosecutors are examining whether the
parole board acted at the urging of an influential rabbi, Leon
Perlmutter, who has assisted the Pataki campaign in raising money
from Orthodox Jews. In one document, the prosecutors assert that a
parole staff employee was told by a superior that Perlmutter was
someone who could deliver votes and therefore should be listened to
on inmate releases. The employee, who was not identified, was later
contacted directly about several cases, including Helbrans,
according to the record.
</P>
<P>
   Both Helbrans and Perlmutter have denied any wrongdoing. In an
interview last year, Helbrans said, ``I didn't receive any kind of
special treatment.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The inquiry by the U.S. attorney's office for the Eastern
District of New York began in January 1998 after the parents of one
of the three inmates complained to the authorities that a volunteer
Republican fund-raiser, Yung Soo Yoo, had offered to help their son
win parole in exchange for campaign contributions but had not kept
his promise. Yoo is a prominent businessman among Koreans in the
New York region, and all three inmates were the sons of Korean
immigrants.
</P>
<P>
   John Jhang's family gave at least $12,000 in 1994 and 1995 to
the campaign, while Boyoung Chung's family gave $9,500. Neither
inmate was released.
</P>
<P>
   John Kim's family and friends gave several thousands dollars,
prosecutors say. Kim was released after Korean immigrants in Queens
lobbied the Parole Board on his behalf. He was helped by his
family's close ties to Grace Koh, the governor's liaison to Asian
Americans, who also lobbied for his release.
</P>
<P>
   Several officials of the Pataki administration and campaign
later testified before the grand jury. Besides the guilty plea from
Hotaling, the prosecutors won McSherry's conviction on perjury
charges this month. Prosecutors have repeatedly contended that
McSherry caved to political pressure and spearheaded the release of
Kim undeservedly in 1996. McSherry had been known as one of the
most cautious commissioners in making release decisions.
</P>
<P>
   The documents portray a domino effect of inquiries that began
with Yoo, who sent the names of the prisoners to Patrick Donohue, a
Pataki fund-raiser. Donohue then sent the handwritten note to Jeff
Wiesenfeld, director of community affairs for the governor.
Wiesenfeld in turn contacted Travis, asking for information about
the three inmates.
</P>
<P>
   In Kim's case, the documents show that Wiesenfeld, who
supervised Ms. Koh in the community affairs office, tried to get
Kim into a work release program. ``John Kim appears to have made a
stunning turn from a life that was previously influenced and
dominated by gang interactions,'' Wiesenfeld wrote Travis on Dec.
7, 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Travis responded a week later that Kim was not legally eligible
for work release because of his conviction for a violent felony.
But Travis wrote that Wiesenfeld's recommendation would be
considered when Kim was up for parole.
</P>
<P>
   The governor himself is not mentioned in the campaign and
administration records, and there is no evidence that he had any
involvement in the parole decisions. But according to court
testimony, he did cross paths with one of the contributors.
</P>
<P>
   Detective George Slater, an investigator, told the court that
Chung's mother, Incha Chung, recounted how she had met the governor
at a fund-raiser and whispered into his ear that she was ``waiting
for news.''
</P>
<P>
   At that point, Slater said, the governor responded that he did
not know what she was talking about and walked away.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
