<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-ROCKIES19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Walker gives Braves a lesson
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ Larry Walker showed the Braves a thing or two about how
to hit with runners in scoring position.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves, stymied for two days at 1-for-19 with runners
waiting at second or third base, watched Walker slam a 1-2 slider
from John Rocker into the right-field seats in the ninth inning
Wednesday for a three-run home run and a 4-1 Rockies win. It was
the second home run of the game for Walker, who drove in all four
Colorado runs.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's no fun,'' the left-handed hitting Walker said of facing
Rocker. ``I wanted to go around and hit on the right side like I
did with Randy Johnson in the (1997) All-Star Game. He throws so
hard and then he grunts and sounds so mean. Fortunately, he hung a
breaking ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Rocker chose a postgame workout over talking with the media
about the outing that broke a string of 15 2/3 scoreless innings
and brought him his first loss since June 29. It started poorly
with walks to Neifi Perez and Terry Shumpert.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't walk two guys to get to their best hitter,'' Brian
Jordan said.
</P>
<P>
   The best news of the day for the Braves was that Walker, who is
playing with torn cartilage in his left knee, won't be playing
today in the final game of this series, which the Rockies now lead
2-1 after back-to-back wins.
</P>
<P>
   Between the two Walker homers in the first and ninth _ the first
of which ended a 50 at-bat homerless stretch _ was a pitching duel
fitting for any place but Coors Field.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Millwood allowed only two hits in eight innings and
retired the last 19 hitters he faced. He finished with seven
strikeouts and one walk.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was as good a stuff as we've seen this season,'' Rockies
manager Jim Leyland said.
</P>
<P>
   Millwood's only problem was Brian Bohanon was right there with
him, allowing eight hits but only one run and striking out seven
himself.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves started the ninth against closer Dave Veres with a
walk and a stolen base by Andruw Jones, who represented the
go-ahead run in a 1-1 tie. But Veres struck out Jose Hernandez,
Eddie Perez and Gerald Williams to leave the Braves 1-for-12 with
runners in scoring position for the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the difference in 2-0 and 0-2,'' Chipper Jones said of
the last two games. ``We wasted two good outings by our starting
pitchers. It's a shame.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
