<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-18 22:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2256 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-VESPA-INVEST-NYT &LR;      08-18 0781
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VESPA-INVEST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. GROUP SEEKS MOTOR-SCOOTER MAKER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Texas, N.Y.)  (af) 
 By JOHN TAGLIABUE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME _ The Vespa, the perky little Italian motor scooter, was
immortalized by Audrey Hepburn and Gregory Peck in the 1953
American film classic ``Roman Holiday.'' So there seems to be some
poetic justice in the news Wednesday that a group of U.S. investors
is close to a deal to spend about $650 million to acquire a
controlling interest in Piaggio Veicoli Europei SpA, the Italian
group that manufactures the Vespa.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement of talks by officials of Piaggio and the Texas
Pacific Group, based in Fort Worth, came in response to a report in
Corriere della Sera, an Italian daily newspaper. The news ends a
period of speculation about the future of Piaggio, which invented
the sputtering two-wheelers after World War II.
</P>
<P>
   For Italians, the surrender of the Vespa appeared to signal the
loss of yet another of the nation's industrial icons.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's hope they keep the same characteristics,'' said Stefano
Malatesta, 32, a Rome musician, who drove his first Vespa at 14 and
now owns his seventh, a white 125cc BX model.
</P>
<P>
   The puzzling over Piaggio's prospects began after the death in
December 1997 of Giovanni Alberto Agnelli, 33, the company's chief
executive, after an eight-month struggle with abdominal cancer.
Agnelli, an offspring of the family that controls the Italian auto
maker Fiat, was credited with the strategy that returned Piaggio to
profitability last year after several years of losses.
</P>
<P>
   The death in April of Agnelli's mother, Antonella Bechi Piaggio,
a major Piaggio stock owner, is said to have encouraged the search
for a strong new shareholder to insure direction and capital for
the company's future.
</P>
<P>
   Abel G. Halpern, managing director of Texas Pacific Group
Europe, would say only that ``we are in serious discussions'' for
Texas Pacific to acquire a controlling share. A Piaggio executive
referred to ``advanced discussion.''
</P>
<P>
   An agreement would result in the second major recent investment
in the Italian two-wheeled-vehicle market for the group.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, Texas Pacific took over Ducati Motor Holding SpA, the
icon of Italian motorcycle making. Managers hired by Texas Pacific
overhauled Ducati's manufacturing plants, rebuilt the bike's image
and, on the model of Harley Davidson, or maybe Gucci, opened
exclusive Ducati stores, including one on 42nd Street in Manhattan.
Fresh models were rolled out by a new chief designer, Pierre
Terblanche.
</P>
<P>
   In September, Sotheby's Chicago showroom is expected to auction
a one-of-a-kind Ducati, the MH900e, designed by Terblanche, and
collectors are expected to bid at least $500,000.
</P>
<P>
   Federico Minoli, Ducati's chief executive, was quoted Wednesday
as saying that ``our company is not involved'' in the talks. But a
Piaggio executive noted that with a Piaggio deal, Texas Pacific's
portfolio would cover virtually the whole range of motorized
two-wheelers, from tiny 50cc Vespas to Ducati's monster bikes.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said the Ducati experience must have influenced Piaggio
shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   ``Texas Pacific is specialized in buying into a company when it
is underperforming its potential,'' said Michael Millman of Salomon
Smith Barney. ``They are sure to have a vision when they come to
Piaggio.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither Texas Pacific nor Piaggio would say how much money would
change hands if a deal is struck. But people close to the financing
said the price would be roughly $650 million.
</P>
<P>
   In a straw vote at a meeting of Piaggio's major shareholders
earlier this month, a majority agreed to the sale, which could be
formally concluded soon after Italians return from their August
holidays.
</P>
<P>
   No immediate management changes are expected at Piaggio, people
close to the discussions said.
</P>
<P>
   Piaggio, which is based in Pontedera, near Pisa, made aircraft
engines until 1946 when it came up with the Vespa _ Italian for
wasp, and so named because of the pinched shape of the vehicle's
body and its buzzing noise _ as an economical means of
transportation for Italians just emerging from wartime.
</P>
<P>
   By the mid-1990s, a combination of aging products and tough
competition by Japanese leaders, including Honda, caused Piaggio to
suffer two years of losses. Piaggio's comeback began under Agnelli.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, he began a new generation of Vespa, with a bulbous
retro look evoking the original model, which was introduced 50
years earlier. As sales revived in Europe and beyond, Piaggio
reported a profit of $5.4 million in 1998, against losses of $28
million the previous year. Revenues rose 4 percent in 1998, to $1
billion.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
