<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MISSING-EXEC-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BODY OF CHICAGO EXECUTIVE AND ONE MISSING DAUGHTER FOUND IN LAKE
MICHIGAN  
(DW) 

</HEADLINE>
   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Coast Guard searchers found the body of a Chicago
business executive and his 7-year-old daughter floating in Lake
Michigan Wednesday, three days after they had left on an overnight
sailing trip. Also on the trip was a second young daughter, who is
still missing.
</P>
<P>
   The bodies of the 39-year-old businessman, Harry C. Bull, chief
executive of Bradner Central Co., a Chicago wholesaler of paper
products, and his daughter Maddie were recovered Wednesday
afternoon off the coast of Lake Forest, a northern suburb. This was
about 12 miles from where the family's boat was found late Tuesday
south of Waukegan.
</P>
<P>
   Bull, Maddie and the other daughter, Lexi, 5, left Chicago on
Sunday night, on an overnight trip to Waukegan, 40 miles north,
while Bull's wife, Pam, and their infant son remained behind.
Relatives say that the family frequently took overnight trips on
the boat and that Bull was an experienced sailor.
</P>
<P>
   But when there was no contact from Bull on Monday, relatives
alerted the authorities, and a search began at dawn on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Harry had been sailing since he was a little child, and the
girls had been sailing with him since they were 2,'' said Ilyce
Tamkin, a family spokeswoman. ``They loved being on that boat. We
can't imagine what happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Full results of autopsies that were performed Wednesday at the
office of the Lake County Medical Examiner will not be disclosed
until Thursday, but officials there said there was no sign of
trauma on the recovered bodies.
</P>
<P>
   Jim McInnis, a chief warrant officer with the Coast Guard, said
the boat, a 26-foot Grampion named Semper Spero (Latin for Forever
Hope), showed no signs that it had encountered rough seas or bad
weather. Nor, McInnis said, was there any indication of mechanical
problems or other kind of distress.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the boat was found with the swim ladder down and four
life jackets missing. This prompted the authorities to suspect that
Bull and his daughters had entered the water for a swim before
anything went wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``Typically when the girls would want to go swimming,'' Ms.
Tampkin said, ``Harry would take out a bunch of life jackets and
throw them out there so the girls would have something to grab on
to.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials suspended the search for Lexi at dusk Wednesday but
said they would resume at dawn on Thursday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-18-99 2226EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
