<HEADER>
A2263 &Cx1f; tta-z
u f BC-METLIFE-SUIT-1STLD-WR     08-18 1034
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-METLIFE-SUIT-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METROPOLITAN LIFE AGREES TO SETTLE LAWSUITS ACCUSING COMPANY OF
FRAUD
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs 2nd graf to add fact that settlement includes policyholders
of annuities; inserts new 19th and 20th grafs for explanation
concerning why annuity holders are included in settlement)  (sw) 
 By BARRY MEIER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Metropolitan Life Insurance Co., the nation's
second-largest life insurer, agreed on Wednesday to pay hundreds of
millions of dollars to settle lawsuits accusing the company of
cheating customers through deceptive sales practices.
</P>
<P>
   The settlement, which must be approved by a federal judge, would
be the latest in a series of multimillion-dollar settlements by
life insurers accused of fraud. Metropolitan Life valued the
proposed settlement, which is intended to cover seven million
current and former policyholders who bought insurance and annuities
between 1982 and 1997, at $1.7 billion. But it will cost the
company less because of the way it is calculating the settlement,
and because costs like lawyers' fees and administrative expenses,
which could easily exceed $100 million, will also come out of that
sum.
</P>
<P>
   Under the terms of the settlement plan, affected policyholders
can apply for cash payments or added payouts at the time of their
deaths or simply accept bigger death benefits based on a formula
that reflects their ages and the sizes of their policies. The value
is based on what it would cost consumers to buy the additional
coverage the company is giving them, not what it is costing the
company to provide it.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Foley, a spokesman for Metropolitan Life, said the
settlement proposal was intended to cover three federal
class-action lawsuits, which were consolidated four years ago, and
dozens of related actions. All the suits contend the company used
deceptive sales practices.
</P>
<P>
   In reaching the proposed settlement with lawyers representing
policyholders, the company has denied any wrongdoing, Foley said.
</P>
<P>
   Melvyn I. Weiss, a plaintiffs' lawyer in New York involved in
the class-action suits, said that some consumers, depending on the
size of their policies, could receive ``hundreds of thousands of
dollars'' in benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Joanna Connolly, an assistant attorney general in Massachusetts,
which has been investigating Metropolitan Life's sales practices,
said that she had not had a chance to closely study the proposed
settlement but that she expected to do so soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are millions of consumers who have lost considerable
money over the years because they bought these policies,'' Ms.
Connolly said.
</P>
<P>
   Under the proposed settlement, claimants would have two main
ways to seek benefits. They could submit claims to an independent
adjuster who could award them cash, an increase in the death
benefits of their life insurance policies or some combination.
</P>
<P>
   Those who did not seek such a claim could get an increase in
their death benefit. That increase would range from 3 percent to 16
percent of the value of that benefit, with the increase decreasing
with the age of the policyholder, said Foley, the company
spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   The settlement proposal comes as Metropolitan Life, which is a
mutual insurer owned by its policyholders, prepares to convert to a
publicly traded company.
</P>
<P>
   Precisely how much of the settlement will go to policyholders is
not clear. Weiss said that his firm and others involved in the case
had spent more than $45 million on the litigation. Those firms will
also seek additional fees, which in a case against the Prudential
Insurance Company of America amounted to $90 million.
</P>
<P>
   Foley said that the company had already bought reinsurance to
cover the cost of the settlement.
</P>
<P>
   The Metropolitan Life proposal is the latest in a recent round
of class-action settlements by life insurers.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, Prudential said it would pay past and current
policyholders at least $410 million and up to $2 billion to settle
class-action suits. Weiss, the plaintiffs' lawyer, said that his
firm had sued 44 life insurers in recent years, including
Prudential, the State Farm Insurance Cos. and the American General
Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Those cases, like the ones against Metropolitan Life, involved
allegations of misleading sales practices including ``churning,''
the practice of persuading customers to exchange older policies for
newer ones by falsely contending that the new policies were cheaper
or provided more coverage.
</P>
<P>
   In other cases, according to the suits, customers were also told
that because interest rates and dividends were high, their policies
would pay for themselves after seven or eight years. These were
known as vanishing premium policies. When interest rates eventually
fell, out-of-pocket costs increased. Millions of life insurance
customers have complained to regulators that their insurance agents
did not fully explain to them how their policies would perform.
</P>
<P>
   Last November, Metropolitan Life also paid a $25 million civil
penalty to settle a federal inquiry of sales practices in Florida,
where it was investigated for marketing life insurance between 1989
and 1993 as savings and retirement plans.
</P>
<P>
   Foley said the company had settled claims over annuities because
it thought that the insurance industry would see extensive
litigation over the investments. An annuity guarantees a fixed or
variable payment to a customer at some future time, usually
retirement.
</P>
<P>
   The class-action suits contended that the company's sales
representatives persuaded consumers who already had tax-protected
retirement plans like 401(k) plans to buy annuities, which have
similar tax protections, as part of those plans.
</P>
<P>
   Metropolitan Life said that it expected to mail information
about the settlement proposal to affected customers beginning next
week. A hearing on the proposed settlement has been scheduled for
Dec. 2 in U.S. District Court in Pittsburgh, where the class-action
litigation is pending.
</P>
<P>
   ``This settlement provides a fair resolution to issues that have
been the subject of protracted litigation and that have affected
much of our industry,'' Robert H. Benmosche, the company's
chairman, said in a statement.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-18-99 2235EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990818.0401 </DOCNO>
