<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-18 22:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2264 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-RUSSIA-LAUNDER-BANK-A     08-18 0438
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-LAUNDER-BANK-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BANK OF NEW YORK WON'T TALK ABOUT LAUNDERING ACCUSATIONS
</HEADLINE>
  (With RUSSIA-LAUNDER) 
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By TIMOTHY L. O'BRIEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bank of New York, with assets of about $67 billion, is the 17th
largest bank in the country and one of the oldest. And it is not a
company typically found at the center of financial scandals. It is
a conservative, well-regarded institution that earns steady profits
from humdrum businesses like securities processing and trust
management.
</P>
<P>
   The bank also actively courts foreign companies to list their
stock for trading in the United States and has made a big effort in
the last few years to persuade Russian companies to do business
with them.
</P>
<P>
   The bank declined to comment Wednesday on the nature of the
Benex accounts it managed _ whether they were simply cash accounts,
which should have made such large transactions very suspect _ or
whether they might have also included currency trading, in which
case heavy activity in the accounts might not have been unusual.
</P>
<P>
   Bank of New York also declined to discuss what steps it takes to
monitor bank accounts it controls. There are no firm regulations
governing how banks should police suspicious activities and the
banking industry moved aggressively and successfully earlier this
year to avoid tighter money-laundering provisions sought by banking
regulators.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, banks are required to follow ``know your customer''
guidelines that mandate that bank officers should have more than
passing familiarity with people and companies opening accounts with
them.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bank needs to know the clients well enough to know what
kinds of activities are usual and what kinds are unusual,'' said
Nancy Bercovici, a senior vice president with the Federal Reserve
Bank of New York.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last few years, most large banks have installed
computer software that can alert bank officials to unusual
activities based on a customer's profile. Bank of New York declined
to say whether or not it has such a system in place.
</P>
<P>
   If unusual activity occurs in an account, banks file
```suspicious activity reports,''` or SAR's, into a system
monitored by the U.S. Treasury's Financial Crimes Enforcement
Network, as well as the country's five main banking regulators. The
reports are confidential and the Treasury's network declined to
comment Wednesday on whether or not it had received any such
reports recently from the Bank of New York.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-18-99 2235EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990818.0402 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-18 22:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2273 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-TURKEY-FAMILY-1STLEDE     08-18 1023
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TURKEY-FAMILY-1STLEDE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Turkey earthquake devastates Atlanta family
 &HT;    By Arthur Brice and Julie Bryant
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Anesthesiologist Babur Kilic was supposed to board a
plane Saturday to join his wife, their five children and his
parents at their summer home in Turkey. Instead, Kilic left
Wednesday to make funeral arrangements for four of his children and
his father.
</P>
<P>
   Kilic's wife, Jan, and their daughter Natalie, 6, survived
Tuesday's earthquake. So did his mother, Turkan Kilic, although she
is in critical condition and on life-support in a Turkish hospital.
Jan Kilic is being treated at the American Hospital in Istanbul,
but family members in Marietta don't know her condition. Natalie is
reportedly unhurt.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is trying to be strong,'' Cigdem Kilic, Babur Kilic's
sister-in-law, said Wednesday. ``He's very upset, but he's also
thankful that his wife is alive and one of his children is alive.''
</P>
<P>
   The human toll from the quake had climbed late Wednesday to
3,839 dead and nearly 18,500 injured. But more than 10,000 people
are still missing, and the final death count could top 12,000, said
Yavuz Tarcan, the Turkish honorary consul in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``They cannot reach some regions yet,'' said Tarcan, a physician
who practices nuclear medicine at Grady and Emory hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   Tarcan said there are unconfirmed reports that three or four
other people with North Georgia connections also died in the
temblor. The honorary consul's office has been deluged with
telephone calls from worried relatives. Some of the calls, Tarcan
said, also have come from concerned Americans with children
traveling in Turkey or with friends who live in the hardest-hit
areas.
</P>
<P>
   Babur Kilic, known to his friends as ``Bobby,'' was accompanied
to Turkey by his two older brothers, Timur and Cengiz. The three
Kilic brothers are Marietta anesthesiologists who practice at
Wellstar-Kennestone Hospital. All three graduated from the
University of Alabama school of medicine.
</P>
<P>
   Their father, Nizam Kilic, was a retired pediatrician who lived
in Marietta with his wife, Turkan, also a retired physician.
</P>
<P>
   The dead Kilic children were identified as Jeffrey Michael, 6;
Jennifer Kayla, 5; David Tansan, 2; and Katherine ``Katie''
Michelle, who was born Nov. 2, 1998.
</P>
<P>
   They attended Casa dei Bambini Montessori school in Marietta.
</P>
<P>
   Inside Babur Kilic's two-story brick home in east Cobb, about 10
family members and friends gathered Wednesday evening around a
television set, tracking news developments.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's unbelievable,'' said Jack Kemp, Jan Kilic's father.
</P>
<P>
   Kemp and his wife were traveling to the New England coast for a
seven-week vacation Tuesday when they heard of the quake.
</P>
<P>
   ``At first we heard it wasn't their building,'' Kemp said.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, their relief gave way to shock as official word of
the children's death came by phone call.
</P>
<P>
   Jan Kilic, her children and her in-laws were on vacation in the
resort town of Yalova when the five-story building in which they
were staying collapsed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jan wanted to expose the kids to culture and their heritage,''
Kemp said, adding that his daughter is active in her church.
``She's a strong girl. Her faith will see her through this.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Hurd, president of Georgia Anesthesiologists, the
23-doctor group to which the Kilic brothers belong, also cited Jan
Kilic's strong faith.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jan is very religious,'' Hurd said. ``It's very difficult to
come to grips with things if you have no faith in God.''
</P>
<P>
   Hurd said Babur Kilic was supposed to cover for him Tuesday
night but begged off because he had not heard from his wife and was
growing increasingly concerned. Sometime overnight Tuesday, the
hospital called from Turkey to tell Kilic that his wife had been
injured.
</P>
<P>
   ``We initially heard that all the children were dead,'' Hurd
said. ``It was an answer to our prayers that Natalie survived.''
</P>
<P>
   Hurd and family attorney Bill Rogers described the Kilics as
extremely family-oriented and fun to be around. Both men cited the
annual Fourth of July party the Kilics hold at their house for
friends.
</P>
<P>
   The Kilics also had business interests and formed a residential
development company about four years ago called KBJ Corp., Rogers
said.
</P>
<P>
   The company, based out of the Kilic home, most recently
developed Calvary Lake subdivision in Kennesaw.
</P>
<P>
   Rogers, who represents the company, said he spoke with Jan Kilic
only a few days before she left.
</P>
<P>
   ``She said she was going out of the country but I didn't even
ask her where. This just floors me,'' he said Wednesday evening.
</P>
<P>
   ``She is, they both are, two of the nicest people I know,'' he
said. ``In this rush-rush world there is really nothing rush-rush
about Jan. She is so accommodating.''
</P>
<P>
   Other friends and loved ones expressed their disbelief Wednesday
that such tragedy could befall such good people.
</P>
<P>
   Zeynep Karasu, who retired as a pediatrician three years ago,
has known the Kilic family for more than 25 years. She first got to
know Nizam Kilic through their work as pediatricians. Later, his
three sons became doctors, and she worked with them at
Wellstar-Kennestone Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   ``I talked with Babur yesterday,'' she said Wednesday afternoon.
``He didn't know anything. Of course, none of us knew anything. The
telephones were not working.''
</P>
<P>
   She found out Wednesday morning, shortly after Kilic got the
devastating news.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very hard. Very hard,'' Karasu said, her voice breaking.
</P>
<P>
   At the home of Timur Kilic, family members were trying to cope
with the sudden loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not easy,'' said Cigdem Kilic, who has been married to
Timur for 12 years. ``It's terrible. And the way they died. It's
awful.''
</P>
<P>
   Others tried to remember some of the Kilics in better times.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a very, very nice man,'' Mehmet Yildirim, president of
the Turkish American Cultural Association of Georgia, said of Nizam
Kilic. ``He would come to all of our functions. He would donate
money. He was just a gentleman.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
