<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-HOUSE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTONS' HOUSE WISHES: WATER, SECURITY AND GOOD PRICE  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By LISA W. FODERARO    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WHITE PLAINS, N.Y. _ Hillary and Bill Clinton have not been too
picky about minor details, like closets and fireplaces, as they
have searched for a new house. But sources say their wish list
includes a few key things befitting a First Couple.
</P>
<P>
   They apparently want enough land to make the Secret Service
happy, ideally with separate quarters like a carriage house or barn
for agents. They like water: four of the five houses the Clintons
saw on Sunday had a pond, a brook or both, and three had swimming
pools. They wouldn't mind a great room for entertaining. They are
determined to keep the price under $2 million.
</P>
<P>
   Less important are the location and architectural style of the
house.
</P>
<P>
   The houses on their very public tour of Westchester County last
weekend were, geographically and esthetically, all over the map,
running the gamut from a jazzy Colonial built last year in Pound
Ridge, in the northern part of the county, to a 1925 stucco house
with leaded-glass windows in New Rochelle, to the south.
</P>
<P>
   The Clintons are also now leaning toward buying rather than
renting, sources say. Even though the couple leaves Thursday for a
two-week vacation on Martha's Vineyard, their quest for a house
continues.
</P>
<P>
   Their lead broker, Kathy Sloane of Brown Harris Stevens in
Manhattan, is still looking at homes. If Mrs. Clinton runs for the
U.S.Senate from New York next year, as is widely expected, she must
establish a residence in the state by Election Day next year.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Ms. Sloane refused to say precisely what the
Clintons wanted in a home. But others say that most of the roughly
75 properties Ms. Sloane has screened for the Clintons did not
offer enough security and privacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Security issues are very high on the list,'' Ms. Sloane said.
</P>
<P>
   A White House official said Wednesday that the Clintons would
have no further comment on their search until there is a ``ratified
contract.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the special security considerations, the hunt for a
Clinton homestead has been more straightforward than the searches
Ms. Sloane is often asked to conduct for people relocating to the
New York area. ``I've found that many of the families I've worked
with have much more complicated personal requirements,'' Ms. Sloane
said.
</P>
<P>
   The houses the Clintons toured on Sunday are all different. The
lot sizes run from two acres to six acres-plus. The number of
bedrooms ranges from four to seven.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the houses are all essentially traditional in style: Even
the new house has old-fashioned elements like a columned front
porch and dormer windows. Each, real estate agents say, has some
special feature, whether a drop-dead landscape or an unusual
historic detail.
</P>
<P>
   ``They like beautiful settings,'' one broker said.
</P>
<P>
   The New Rochelle house has seven bedrooms, a pond in front and a
pool in back. Its most beguiling feature may be its stained-glass
windows with images depicting the arts. This house, a
Tudor-Mediterranean hybrid, has the smallest tract, however, with
just two acres. It is not even technically for sale, but the owners
are willing to sell to the Clintons.
</P>
<P>
   A house in Mamaroneck, on six and a half acres, resembles a
rambling Currier &AMP; Ives farmstead, with a cedar-shake gambrel roof,
dormers and a giant fieldstone chimney. Inside, the house needs a
lot of updating, but the grounds are spectacular, with a stream,
pond and pool.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday the Clintons lingered longest at a house in the
Edgemont section of Greenburgh. The town is short on cachet, but
this particular house has a Scarsdale postal address and its three
wooded acres are more in keeping with properties in neighboring
Scarsdale.
</P>
<P>
   This is the oldest house of the bunch, a 1901 white Colonial
with large rooms and a separate barn. It is also in a congested
part of the county, within hollering distance of Central Avenue,
whose dizzying number of chain stores serve all of southern
Westchester.
</P>
<P>
   They also looked at a house in Purchase, a wealthy hamlet in the
town of Harrison. The property has four acres and a wide brook. Its
most eye-catching feature may be the dining room, whose walls are
lined, floor to ceiling, with French windows. But with an asking
price of $2.3 million the house might be too dear.
</P>
<P>
   The Pound Ridge house would place the Clintons the farthest from
Manhattan, but would offer a more countrified ambience and make
them neighbors of the actors Richard Gere and Susan Sarandon. The
house, built in 1998, belongs to a builder, and its six and a half
acres include a river, pond and tennis courts.
</P>
<P>
   The price is right, too: $1.7 million.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
