<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHECKCASHING-DISCLOSURE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RULES SEEK NEW DISCLOSURES BY CHECK-CASHING SERVICES
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By MELODY PETERSEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Trying to stem the flow of billions of dollars in
illegal drug profits out of the country, the Treasury Department
announced Wednesday that it would require all check-cashing
businesses and other money servicing firms to register with federal
authorities.
</P>
<P>
   Treasury officials acted after finding evidence that drug
smugglers and dealers were using some small storefront businesses
that cash checks, wire money overseas or exchange foreign currency
to launder money illegally.
</P>
<P>
   Under the new requirements, the businesses must disclose their
locations, the owners' names and the amount of money transactions
that they handle each month. With that information, law enforcement
officials may be better able to track what businesses drug dealers
are using to wire money to overseas bank accounts or convert cash
to money orders that can easily be mailed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will give us, for the first time, a complete picture of the
money-servicing business,'' said Peter G. Djinis, executive
assistant director in the Treasury Department's Financial Crimes
Enforcement Network.
</P>
<P>
   The Treasury Department's new requirement will affect an
estimated 160,000 money servicing businesses across the country,
including those as large as Western Union or as small as the corner
storefront. The registration is part of a series of steps officials
are planning to take to crack down on money laundering, in which
illegal profits from drugs or other activities are disguised to
make them look legitimate. Officials also plan to soon begin
requiring the money-servicing companies to look for and report any
suspected illegal use of their services to the federal government,
Djinis said.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Rochford, deputy general counsel at the National Check
Cashers Association in Hackensack, N.J., said the organization
supported the new requirements, but worried that some of them could
cause extra paperwork and added costs for the businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Rochford said the money-laundering problem occurred at only a
very small fraction of check-cashing businesses. ``We do not deny
that there is a risk,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The companies will be required to register with the federal
government beginning in December 2001 and will be subject to
criminal prosecution if they do not comply.
</P>
<P>
   Law enforcement officials have said that the problem is
especially acute in New York City and its suburbs, where billions
of dollars in illegal drug profits are estimated to flow through
each year. But the illegal money-laundering occurs in cities across
the country, Djinis said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In 1996, federal officials found that check cashers and other
money servicing businesses in the New York metropolitan area were
helping drug dealers funnel illegal drug profits to Colombia. To
try to help stop the crimes, Treasury officials began requiring the
businesses to temporarily report any transactions over $750 if the
money was going to a person or account in Colombia. Officials said
the requirement acted as a deterrent because the number of wire
transfers to Colombia appeared to drop considerably.
</P>
<P>
   The drug dealers use the small cash-checking businesses and
other storefront money servicing businesses to avoid banks, which
are required to report any suspicious activity.
</P>
<P>
   Drug dealers have been known to set up check-cashing businesses,
using the money they have received from selling drugs on the street
to cash customers' payroll checks, which can be more easily
deposited into banks, Djinis said.
</P>
<P>
   Other businesses accept cash from drug dealers, and in return,
give them money orders or wire the funds overseas.
</P>
<P>
   In a 1996 case, federal officials found that business was so
brisk at S &AMP; F Check Cashers, a small business in West New York,
N.J., that employees sometimes called armored cars to pick up the
cash, even though such a business should be getting cash from the
bank, rather than hauling it in.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
