<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-CONSERVATIVE-PARTY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONSERVATIVE PARTY LEADER IN A CHEERY MOOD, COME WHAT MAY  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By ELISABETH BUMILLER    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ ``Look, I survived Bobby Kennedy,'' said Michael R.
Long, who is the chairman of New York's Conservative Party, the
owner of a seriously yuppified Brooklyn liquor store (the 1993
Chateau Margaux is $160 a bottle) and a man who can now make Mayor
Rudolph Giuliani miserable.
</P>
<P>
   ``I survived John Lindsay. I survived Lyndon Johnson. Did the
world change? Did we go out of business? There's an overreaction
that the sky is falling and the world is coming to an end because
Hillary Clinton is running for office.''
</P>
<P>
   Looming Hillary apocalypse or no, Long is in a cheery mood these
days.
</P>
<P>
   He happily insists that he will not be pressured into making a
crucial Conservative Party endorsement of Giuliani in a likely
Senate race just because a lot of important and nervous Republicans
tell him to. He is also happy to say that he doesn't care if he is
blamed by the Republicans for helping to lose the seat, should
Giuliani be defeated by his White House menace. He has principles,
he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've spent my whole life in the Conservative Party supporting
ideas that have consequences,'' said Long, who used to listen to
Ronald Reagan's 1964 ``Rendezvous with Destiny'' speech supporting
Barry Goldwater for president over and over on his record player.
</P>
<P>
   It is entirely possible that Long will get in line behind
Giuliani with minimal fuss. But he has two main conditions: That
the mayor make some compromise about his position on a form of
late-term abortion _ the mayor said Wednesday he was still opposed
to banning the procedure _ and that the mayor not be endorsed by
the Liberal Party, as he has been in the past.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you start endorsing legislative candidates who have the
Liberal line, I would feel better about turning out the lights,
locking the door and going out of business,'' Long said. ``You
can't be committed to two philosophies.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Long is enjoying his moment in the August sun as a
minor party boss with a big-time supplicant. Not even 24 hours
after the more conservative Rep. Rick A. Lazio shelved plans for
the Republican Senate primary this month, Giuliani was on the phone
to Long, asking for a meeting.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, `Can we talk?''' Long said.
</P>
<P>
   What didn't need to be said was that no Republican since Sen.
Jacob K. Javits in 1974 has won statewide office in New York
without the Conservative Party endorsement, which will be essential
upstate in a race as close as Rudy-Hillary is expected to be.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not my way or the highway, OK?'' said Long.``I don't
believe that's Mike Long.''
</P>
<P>
   Long, 59, is a gregarious believer in the Conservative cause who
thinks that Reagan ``changed the whole face of the world,'' and who
was politically ignited by Goldwater at a 1964 speech the
Republican candidate for president made at Madison Square Garden.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   He grew up in the Bushwick section of Brooklyn and Richmond Hill
in Queens. His father was a foreman in the baggage department at
the old Pennsylvania Station. He graduated from Richmond Hill High
School, served in the Marines, got married, owned an ice-cream
store in East New York, served one term as the chairman of
Community School Board 19 in Brooklyn, spent two years on the City
Council and worked his way up in the Conservative Party. He has
nine children.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, Long was paying four tuitions at Bishop Ford High
School in Brooklyn. It was 1983, and he had just come off the City
Council and opened the liquor store. ``And I really didn't have any
money,'' he said. ``And we were getting bills from Bishop Ford
saying, `This is it, we're throwing these kids out of here.'''
</P>
<P>
   Long paid a visit to the school. ``And the brother said, `You
know what?''' Long said. `` `You have nine children. I guess you
did what we asked you to do. Don't mind the dunning letters. I
don't know how long it's going to take you to pay us. Just don't
forget to pay us.'''
</P>
<P>
   Things are better these days. All of Long's children above
college age are employed; Long's daughter Eileen is Lt. Gov. Mary
Donohue's chief of staff. Long's wife, also Eileen, runs Rep. Vito
J. Fossella Jr.'s Brooklyn office. Business is OK at Long's Wine
Factory in Bay Ridge.
</P>
<P>
   So now he is open for business with the mayor, who invited him
to dinner three months ago. ``We talked about nothing for a long
time,'' Long said. He is waiting for the mayor to make a move, and
says he has an open mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's never done anything to me,'' said Long.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-18-99 2245EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
