u f BC-SAKS-OUTLOOK-NYT &LR;      08-18 0890
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAKS-OUTLOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW OWNERS OF SAKS ACKNOWLEDGE ROUGH SPOTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By LESLIE KAUFMAN    c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Saks Inc. said Wednesday that it was not integrating
the disparate parts of its swiftly acquired retail empire as
smoothly as it had forecast at the beginning of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Executives at the company acknowledged significant difficulty in
several crucial parts of the business, including the flagship Saks
Fifth Avenue stores, where analysts say a snooty merchandise mix
has been generating disappointing returns.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are generating year-over-year improvement in sales and
merchandise at Saks,'' said chairman and chief executive Brad
Martin, ``but I set very, very lofty expectations and it is clear I
am not going to achieve all those expectations in the first year.''
</P>
<P>
   Based on these unanticipated shortfalls, the retailer, formerly
known as Proffitt's, with headquarters in Birmingham, Ala., said it
would meet earnings estimates of 18 cents a diluted share for the
second quarter but was lowering estimates for the year to $1.80 a
share from $2.16.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the company said sales in stores open at least a
year would rise 4 percent in 1999, instead of the 6 percent it had
previously predicted.
</P>
<P>
   The news severely shook Wall Street's confidence in the company,
which had recently been a darling of analysts, who saw its stock as
a good value. First Call, which tracks analyst estimates, reported
that at least 7 of the 15 surveyed had downgraded the stock to a
hold from a buy _ a shift that First Call research director Charles
Hill characterized as ``highly unusual.''
</P>
<P>
   The company issued a statement Tuesday, just as the market was
closing, with the revised earnings estimates. The stock, down 27
percent since its close Monday, fell $1.8125 Wednesday, to
$17.1875.
</P>
<P>
   Proffitt's, a fast-growing Southern retailer catering to the
middle market, bought Saks Holdings Inc. last September and quickly
adopted its tony name. On an acquisition campaign since 1994,
Proffitt's had been gobbling up an average of one major regional
chain a year. It now operates 352 stores under 11 different name
plates.
</P>
<P>
   But Saks was a different matter, larger and more upper crust
than the company's previous purchases. This led to gossip among New
York's fashion elite that the new Southern proprietors would
somehow not be chic enough to keep up with it.
</P>
<P>
   Martin acknowledged that the fashion mix at Saks was wrong. But
contrary to expectations, the problem appeared to be that the
stores had become too exclusive, cutting out high-margin crowd
pleasers like two-ply cashmere sweaters in favor of such
look-but-do-not-touch items as obscure haute couture evening gowns.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are certain very highest-end vendors that are not as
profitable as the new management would like,'' said Christine
Kilton-Augustine, a retail and apparel analyst with ING Barings.
``Now they are going through the vendor structure and looking to
extricate themselves from those kinds of deals.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin also acknowledged overestimating return in numerous other
areas. The rate of growth of its credit business was disappointing,
the company said. And Mercantile Stores, a chain it bought from
Dillard's Inc. last fall that specialized in bargain-priced
apparel, was producing only 80 percent of expected revenue.
</P>
<P>
   What angered Wall Street more than the performance of the
company was that management did not see the problems coming. The
revised annual earnings estimate was wide of the original by 30
cents to 45 cents a diluted share.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``What raises the concern was they missed the numbers by so
much,'' said Jeff Edelman, a retail analyst with Paine Webber, who
downgraded his recommendation on the stock Wednesday to hold from a
strong buy.
</P>
<P>
   Edelman predicted that the company would have to perform above
expectation in the future to ``rebuild confidence and
credibility.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin made clear that he thought the error was mostly in poorly
managing investor expectations rather than in poorly managing the
stores. ``The business will still generate double-digit growth,''
he said. ``It will be a solid year, albeit a disappointing one,
versus my expectations.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Martin vowed the company would be more circumspect in the
future. ``We are returning to a much more conservative view of the
world,'' Martin said. ``We have a history of making numbers, not
missing numbers, and from this point on the numbers we sign up for
will incorporate risk involved in our business.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said the new estimates finally provided a realistic
assessment of the company's abilities. ``It is a better buy now
that all the facts are on the table,'' said Craig Weichmann of
Morgan Keegan.
</P>
<P>
   The consensus seemed to be that Proffitt's had the experience to
fix Mercantile Stores, but that it is unclear whether it could
manage the high-wire act between very high fashionability and the
profitability required to make the Saks Fifth Avenue stores meet
its goals.
</P>
<P>
   ``They need to spend less time on the road touting the stock and
more time executing the business,'' said Richard Church, a retail
analyst with Salomon Smith Barney.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
