<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-18 22:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2283 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-POLITICAL-BRIEFS-NYT &LR;      08-18 1055
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLITICAL-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SMITH BOLTS _ AGAIN; UTAH SENATORS' FOOT-IN-MOUTH PROBLEM; GOP
STARS SNUBBING ALABAMA STRAW POLL
</HEADLINE>
  
(ATTN: N.H., Utah, Iowa, Ala., Maine)  (nk) 
 By B. DRUMMOND AYRES Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   First, Sen. Bob Smith of New Hampshire was a Republican
candidate for president. Then, last month, still a presidential
candidate, he switched to the U.S. Taxpayers Party, saying the
Republicans were no longer conservative enough for him. And now?
</P>
<P>
   At one of those ``politics and eggs'' breakfasts Wednesday, this
one with business leaders in Bedford, N.H., he announced that he
was switching again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm an independent,'' he said. ``And I'm enjoying it, frankly.
I feel free.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith did not elaborate other than to say that he had been
reading some of George Washington's writings and that it had led
him to conclude that he did not want to participate in partisan
politics anymore.
</P>
<P>
   Did that mean that he was giving up his presidential quest,
considered quixotic by most political pros except for its
potential, in the event of a nip-and-tuck general election, to cost
the Republican nominee a few votes?
</P>
<P>
   ``I still have a presidential campaign,'' he told the business
leaders. ``At the moment, I haven't made a decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Then he disclosed that his wife, Mary Jo, was hospitalized on
Tuesday with chest and arm pains. For the short term, he said, her
health is his main concern.
</P>
<P>
   Later his campaign office said he would address the future of
his candidacy ``in the next couple of weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   Of Hay and Goats, And Feet in Mouths
</P>
<P>
   Back when he was at his provocative, impolitic best, or worst,
Alabama Gov. George C. Wallace, in a turn of phrase that was a
folksy ancestor to ``telling it like it is,'' would often say that
he was ``putting the hay down where the goats can get it.''
</P>
<P>
   Utah's senators, Orrin Hatch and Robert Bennett, both
Republicans, do not come out of the George Wallace school of
politics, not by a long shot. But lately they have been putting
down a lot of hay _ the kind that has led to charges that they
 &UR; don't  &LR; get it.
</P>
<P>
   Hatch, a late starter in the 1999 presidential race, told the
annual state convention of Utah Republicans a few weeks ago that
among the many things the party had to be proud of was that ``we
don't have the gays and lesbians with us.''
</P>
<P>
   Accused of intolerance by leaders of gay and lesbian groups, the
senator maintained that while he believed that ``homosexuality is
contrary to the Bible,'' he nevertheless was ``tolerant of all
people.'' All he was trying to convey in his convention remarks, he
told The Salt Lake Tribune, was that ``gays and lesbians, by and
large, are very intelligent, highly educated, high-earning people
who support mainly Democrats.''
</P>
<P>
   No sooner was the Hatch brouhaha slipping off the front page
than along came Bennett last week with an assertion in The
Standard-Examiner of Ogden, Utah, that Texas Gov. George W. Bush of
Texas had a lock on the Republican presidential nomination unless
he ``steps in front of a bus or some woman comes forward, let's say
some black woman, with an illegitimate child that he fathered.''
</P>
<P>
   Leaders of the NAACP accused Bennett of ``racist attitudes'' and
said that ``he owes the community and the nation a public
apology.'' They received his ``regrets'' on Monday for ``having
made a comment that has been seen by some as insensitive.''
</P>
<P>
   That very day, Hatch sprang back into the news, this time with a
pointed remark about Al Gore and Bill Bradley, two former Senate
colleagues who are now seeking the Democratic presidential
nomination.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're both stiff, and they're both boring,'' Hatch declared
while campaigning in New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   But didn't they nonetheless deserve some of that famous
congressional comity from an old colleague?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't mean to run anyone down,'' Hatch said, reaching for a
bale of rhetorical hay. ``But why not tell the truth?''
</P>
<P>
   Stars in Alabama? Not the GOP Kind
</P>
<P>
   The way Republican leaders in Alabama figured it, if they
scheduled their own presidential straw poll two weeks after the one
held last weekend in Iowa, and then advertised it as the first and
only early test of Southern sentiment, they could grab a lot of
attention for Alabama and the Alabama Republican Party. But it
looks as if that's not going to happen.
</P>
<P>
   Of all the candidates still running after Iowa, only Alan Keyes
has committed to going to the Aug. 28 event in Birmingham. In fact,
the top Iowa finishers _ Bush, Steve Forbes, Elizabeth Dole and
Gary Bauer _ have all declined invitations, as has Sen. John McCain
of Arizona, the only candidate who did not participate in Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   Straw polls are beauty contests with no official role in the
nominating process, of course, and candidates tend to be ambivalent
about them, participating when they see opportunity and skittering
away when they see risk. For example, Dole saw opportunity in Iowa
and crowed loudly about the importance of the poll there when she
finished an unexpectedly strong third. But when she saw little to
be gained by going to Birmingham, her spokeswoman, Chris Hawes,
said: ``Straw polls don't generate delegates. They aren't the most
efficient way to campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   The chairman of the Alabama Republican Party, Winton Blunt, says
that even if only Keyes agrees to show up, the party will go ahead
with the poll because it is a sure-fire way to energize the state
rank and file for Election 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``If somebody comes,'' Blunt said of any of the leading
candidates, ``it's icing on the cake.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, he had a warning for the timid.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Southern electorate is too important for any Republican
presidential candidate to snub,'' he said. ``If a campaign can risk
snubbing a significant portion of Republican votes, they are
swimming in the pool of presidential politics at their own risk.''
</P>
<P>
   A footnote:
</P>
<P>
   After scheduling a fall straw poll of their own, only to have
most candidates reject invitations to participate, Republican
leaders in Maine, unlike those in Alabama, are having serious
second thoughts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We basically couldn't get commitments from a lot of the top
candidates,'' said Ken Cole, the state's Republican national
committeeman. ``So I don't think it's going to happen.''
</P>
</TEXT>
