<SLUG> BC-SKOL-SUMMIT19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Schools summit targets violence
 &HT;    By Mike Wagner
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBUS, Ohio _ Tears welled in the eyes of those who watched
the images and relived the tragedy of the Columbine High School
massacre.
</P>
<P>
   Wounded teen-agers running from their school and into the arms
of horrified parents. Broken glass and blood-stained carpet in the
school library. Kids saying good-bye to their friends at memorial
services.
</P>
<P>
   The first Ohio Safe Schools Summit started Wednesday with what
it hopes to prevent in this state _ scenes of violence and death at
a school.
</P>
<P>
   ``You look at a video like that and see your worst nightmare as
a parent, educator or just as a human being,'' said Ben Kirby,
director of operations and school safety for the Dayton City
Schools, one of about 700 educators, law enforcement officials and
other people who attended the summit.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have safety plans in all of our 47 buildings and have
coordinated our safety efforts with local authorities,'' Kirby
said.
</P>
<P>
   The two-day summit was created by Ohio Attorney General Betty
Montgomery and Gov. Bob Taft. It is a forum for educators and law
enforcement leaders to discuss how to keep the state's schools as
havens for learning, and to prevent Ohio from experiencing the
violent eruptions seen in Colorado, Arkansas, Kentucky and
elsewhere in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   The themes of the summit weren't new, but re-emphasized by Taft
and Montgomery. They challenged parents, teachers and adults to
involve themselves more in the lives of children, encouraged law
enforcement and schools to work more together and promised to make
school safety and academic achievement their top goals.
</P>
<P>
   The summit, which concludes today, comes at a time when juvenile
crime continues to rise.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, the crime rate in Ohio continues to decline. But
juvenile crime has risen steadily with a 20 percent increase in
juvenile arrests from 1987 to 1996, according to state officials.
During that same period, juvenile drug arrests have tripled.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1997-98 school year 436 kids were caught with a gun in an
Ohio school and more than 100 of those students were in elementary
schools, according to the attorney general's office.
</P>
<P>
   Taft has signed into law school safety legislation aimed at
curbing violence in schools. The law, already in effect for thisthe
upcoming school year, adds two prison terms for crimes such as
assault, burglary and breaking and entering when they are committed
in school ``safety zones.'' The zones include school grounds,
school buses and school activities. Also, The bill would also
empower authorities to expel students for up to a year for
knife-and-gun-related offenses.
</P>
<P>
   Last week in Cleveland, Taft and Lt. Gov. Maureen O'Connor
unveiled a legislative package that attacks juvenile crime and
allows judges to provide stiffer sentences for young offenders.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
