<HEADLINE>
HASTERT MAKES CLEAR HE'S SUPPORTING NETHERCUTT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOEL CONNELLY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ House Speaker Dennis Hastert on Wednesday threw his
bacKi5g behind embattled GOP Rep. George Nethercutt, under fire in
his Eastern Washington district for abandoning his 1994 pledge to
limit himself to three terms.
</P>
<P>
   Although greeted in Spokane by a costumed protester dubbed
``George the Weasel King,'' Hastert`Wldnesday raised money for
Nethercutt and indicated the House GOP leadership will use its
resources if Nethercutt has to fwnd off a Republican primary
challenger next year.
</P>
<P>
   $` ``I support him; I will support him in a primary. He is the
kind of person we need in the U.S. Congress,'' Hastert, a
seven-term Illinois congressman, said later during a Seattle
stopover.
</P>
<P>
   Nethercutt has garnered national publicity for backing off on
his pledge. Cartoonist Garry Trudeau lampooned him as the ``Weasel
King'' in a Doonesbury strip.
</P>
<P>
   Term limits was a pivotal issue in 1994 when Nethercutt, a
Spokane attorney, upset Democratic House Speaker Tom Foley. Foley
had served in Congress since 1964.
</P>
<P>
   But Nethercutt announced in June that he will run again, saying,
``I made a mistake when I chose to set a limit on my service.''
</P>
<P>
   After spending more than $300,000 to back Nethercutt's challenge
in 1994, pro-term limits groups have launched an advertising
campaign against him.
</P>
<P>
   Spokane radio talk show host Richard Clear, a major Nethercutt
booster in '94, has indicated he will run against the congressman
next year.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, Hastert and Rep. Jennifer Dunn, R-Wash., defended
Nethercutt with the same argument used by Foley in his 1994
re-election campaign _ that Nethercutt has collected influence and
seniority in Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has worked his way up on the House Appropriations
Committee,'' Hastert said. Dunn said Nethercutt has accumulated
``terrific clout for the state of Washington.''
</P>
<P>
   Hastert, who has voted for some term limits proposals, said in
Spokane Wednesday that the issue is dead.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't been able to pass that the last four years. I don't
think the support is there in Congress now,'' he said. ``We had a
chance to do it. We brought it to a vote and I don't think we'll
see this again in the near future.''
</P>
<P>
   Two Northwest lawmakers elected in 1994 _ Reps. Jack Metcalf,
R-Wash., and Helen Chenoweth, R-Idaho _ have announced they will
honor their three-term pledge and leave the House next year.
</P>
<P>
   Chenoweth has become critical of term limits, but said recently:
``I gave my word. It was part of the bargain between the voters and
me.''
</P>
<P>
   Hastert on Wednesday termed Washington an important state in
next year's fight for control of the House. ``That's why I'm out
here today,'' he said. Hastert spoke Wednesday night at a
$1,000-a-person dinner with proceeds going to Dunn's political
action committee. Earlier in the day, he attended a $100-a-head
breakfast for Nethercutt.
</P>
<P>
   Metcalf's and Nethercutt's spots are high on Democrats' target
list. And state Sen. Dan McDonald, a Bellevue
Republi_!R1 &LR; KM`eqpected to mount a challenge to freshman Democratic
Rep. Jay Inslee.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans hold a six-seat majority in the House of
Representatives. It would shrink to five if Democrats win a special
election in California to fill the seat of the late Rep. George
Brown, D-Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Hastert is on a seven-state tour touting the $798 billion tax
cut package passed by the Republican-run Congress just before it
adjourned for the August recess.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think the American people want this tax bill. Our internal
polls show it,'' he said in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   Hastert lauded such provisions as elimination of the inheritance
tax, describing the GOP package as ``a fair tax plan for Americans,
especially those who get up every morning and go to work.''
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton has said he will veto the bill.
</P>
</TEXT>
