<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-18 23:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2413 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-BUSH-CONTEMPT19-COX     08-18 1002
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-CONTEMPT19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Contempt order sought against Bush
 &HT;    By Juan B. Elizondo Jr.
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Lawyers for a fired state executive on Wednesday
said Gov. George W. Bush should be held in contempt of court for
filing a false affidavit in a lawsuit involving the Texas Funeral
Service Commission. Attorneys for Eliza May, the former head of the
commission, asked a court to sanction Bush for filing what they
called a false statement while trying to kill a subpoena issued by
May as part of her lawsuit against the state and the world's
largest funeral service company.
</P>
<P>
   May is alleging that Bush played a role in pressuring her to
finish her investigation of Houston-based Service Corporation
International. SCI founder and chief executive, Robert Waltrip, is
a long-time Bush family supporter who contributed to former
President Bush's library in College Station.
</P>
<P>
   The contempt motion against Bush is based on an affidavit the
governor filed last month. In the sworn statement, Bush said, ``I
have had no conversations with SCI officials, agents, or
representatives concerning the investigation or any dispute arising
from it. I have no personal knowledge of relevant facts of the
investigation nor do I have any personal knowledge of relevant
facts concerning any dispute arising from this investigation.''
</P>
<P>
   May's attorneys say the affidavit is false.
</P>
<P>
   They point to quotes in the Aug. 16 edition of Newsweek magazine
in which Johnnie B. Rogers, an attorney for SCI, said he and
Waltrip were in the governor's office in April 1998 to drop off a
copy of a letter demanding that the commission end its
investigation. While there, Rogers said Bush passed by and said to
Waltrip, ``Hey Bobby, are those people still messing with you?''
</P>
<P>
   Bush then, according to Rogers, addressed the attorney, ``Hey,
Johnnie B. Are you taking care of him?''
</P>
<P>
   Bush has acknowledged the exchange, but said it was not
substantive and did not involve the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a 20-second conversation,'' Bush said Wednesday, as
questions of his involvement in the case continued to follow him.
``I had no substantive conversation with the guy. I never sat down
and discussed it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't remember what I said, for starters,'' added Bush, who
became perturbed by reporters' questions over the matter. ``And
secondly, I poked my head in the office for no more than 20
seconds. And that's it. That's all that was discussed. This is a
frivolous lawsuit. It's frivolous.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, Bush spokeswoman Linda Edwards said the contempt motion
was ``Nothing more than a publicity stunt and an example of the
frivolous misuse of the civil justice system.''
</P>
<P>
   The latest court filing likely means that the lawsuit will
remain on the national media radar, where such publications as
Newsweek and Salon magazines have raised questions about Bush's
involvement.
</P>
<P>
   Attorneys for Bush, who has said he has no personal knowledge
about the investigation, said they are reviewing the contempt
motion and are working on a formal response. It is not clear when a
judge will consider the issue. A hearing in the case is set for
Aug. 30 to deal with Bush's request to kill the subpoena.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the head of the board that oversees the funeral
commission authorized the comptroller's office to assume
administrative control of the agency while a new executive director
is sought. But he limited the scope of the comptroller's authority,
making clear that the comptroller should not address the SCI
controversy or other matters that involve license revocations,
investigations or administrative penalties. Comptroller Carole
Keeton Rylander on Monday assigned Deputy Comptroller Mike Regan to
assume control of the funeral commission after Chairman Dick McNeil
told Bush's office that he had no one left at the commission who
could act as director. After May was fired in February, two other
men took over as acting directors, but both have left the
beleaguered agency.
</P>
<P>
   While director of the commission in 1998, May, a Democrat,
investigated SCI's embalming practices. The investigation ended in
proposed fines of $445,000.
</P>
<P>
   May said the company tried to get Bush's office to stop the
investigation and said two top Bush aides threatened to take over
the inquiry if she didn't quickly wrap it up. The fines are
pending.
</P>
<P>
   May sued the state and SCI in March, one month after being
fired. She said SCI illegally interfered with her job and accused
the state of firing her for speaking out about interference from
the Bush aides.
</P>
<P>
   In charging that Bush filed a false statement, May's attorneys
also point to a June 11 court document in which SCI attorneys,
responding to a question, said, ``Mr. Robert Waltrip spoke to
Governor George W. Bush regarding Mr. Waltrip's April 15, 1998,
letter to the Texas Funeral Service Commission.''
</P>
<P>
   On June 16, the company amended its answer to say, ``The
governor exchanged pleasantries with Mr. Waltrip. The very brief
conversation among Governor Bush, Mr. Waltrip and Mr. Rogers was
not substantive; they did not discuss the content of Mr. Waltrip's
April 15, 1998, letter or SCI's complaints about the Texas Funeral
Service Commission's actions.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill Miller, a spokesman for SCI, said the amended answer only
clarified the first statement.
</P>
<P>
   In their motion, May's attorneys, Derek Howard and Charles
Herring Jr., said the original answer makes clear Bush had
knowledge of the investigation and spoke to Waltrip about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Governor Bush could not have made that statement (to Waltrip
and Rogers) unless he had personal knowledge of at least certain
'relevant facts' concerning the 'dispute','' the attorneys wrote in
the contempt motion. ``Obviously he knew of the dispute, he knew
Waltrip's and SCI's general position in the dispute and he knew
that a meeting took place on April 15, 1998 at the governor's
office.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
