u a BC-OBIT-KLEITMAN-ART-NYT     08-18 1003
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-KLEITMAN-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATHANIEL KLEITMAN, SLEEP EXPERT, DIES AT 104 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(sw) 
 By VICKI CHENG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dr. Nathaniel Kleitman, known as the father of contemporary
sleep research and one of the discoverers of rapid-eye-movement, or
REM sleep, died on Friday at the Rehabilitation Center of Beverly
Hills in Los Angeles. He was 104.
</P>
<P>
   The discovery of REM came in 1953. Kleitman and his student Dr.
Eugene Aserinsky at the University of Chicago, recorded regular
periods of jerky eye movements during sleep. They also showed that
people who were awakened in this period, which the researchers
called REM sleep, recalled having dreams, while those awakened in
non-REM sleep did not.
</P>
<P>
   In 1956, Kleitman and another student, Dr. William Dement,
reported that certain kinds of eye movements were associated with
certain types of motion in dreams, and that the average person
dreamed a total of about two hours every night.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the first time, we'd found the dream,'' said Dr. Wilse
Webb, a professor emeritus in psychology from the University of
Florida and a historian of sleep disorders. ``More critically, it
showed that sleep was an active process instead of a passive one.''
</P>
<P>
   Kleitman was ``the first to take a deep, complete, absorbing
interest in sleep, the first to compile the knowledge of sleep into
a unified text, and with his students, the first to map out the
multiple discreet stages of sleep,'' said Dr. Allan Rechtschaffen,
professor emeritus of psychiatry at the University of Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Kleitman's studies at Chicago dispelled the popular myth that
sleep was caused by a lack of blood to the brain, or the collection
of ``fatigue toxins.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1939, the University of Chicago Press published his
collection of sleep studies, ``Sleep and Wakefulness,'' (revised in
1963 and 1987), which ``was the Bible on which contemporary sleep
research is founded,'' Webb said.
</P>
<P>
   Kleitman's work eventually extended into studying sleep cycles.
In an effort to see if human subjects _ namely, himself and an
assistant, Bruce Richardson _ could adapt to a 28-hour day, they
lived in Mammoth Cave, Ky., for over a month in 1938. Since the
temperature in the cave was perpetually 54 degrees and there was no
natural light, there were no environmental cues to the time of day.
Though Kleitman said he could not sleep until 10 p.m. surface time,
Richardson adapted.
</P>
<P>
   In the cave, Kleitman measured body temperature and discovered
that there was a slight but regular fluctuation throughout the day,
and that peak efficiency occurred while body temperature was
highest. He applied this knowledge shortly after World War II,
recommending that soldiers and industrial workers stick to regular
shifts so that their bodies could adjust to a 24-hour cycle,
allowing them to stay more alert than if they continually switched
shifts.
</P>
<P>
   His research took Kleitman to other unusual places. In 1948 he
spent two weeks on a submarine, the Dogfish, studying the sleep
patterns of sailors who might spend days without seeing the sun. He
found that they worked more efficiently if there were fewer split
watches. He also once traveled to Tromso, in northern Norway, to
see if inhabitants of the Arctic Circle, where winter plunges the
sky into months of darkness while summer brings unending daylight,
slept on a different schedule. The answer was no.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1950s, Kleitman performed sleep deprivation experiments,
many on soldiers, to study the effects of lack of sleep. He once
stayed awake 180 hours, or a week plus half a day, and noted that
forcing someone to stay awake was an effective form of torture.
</P>
<P>
   ``One gets to the point where he would confess anything just to
be allowed to sleep,'' he told The Saturday Evening Post in 1957.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the myths that Kleitman helped dispel included the
notion that newborn babies need 20 to 22 hours of sleep a day (he
found that 15 hours was the norm); that an hour of sleep before
midnight is worth two or three hours later on; that dreams last
only a few seconds (they run from 10 to 30 minutes), and that
everyone ought to wake up bright and vigorous after a good night's
sleep (being groggy is normal).
</P>
<P>
   Dement, the former student who is now director of the Sleep
Disorders Center at Stanford University, said, ``The main thing
that Kleitman did was to create an identity for the field.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, many medical centers have sleep research laboratories,
and the subject is taught in an increasing number of medical
schools.
</P>
<P>
   Nathaniel Kleitman was born in Kishinev, Russia, in 1895. He
came to the United States in 1915 and earned his B.S. degree four
years later from what is now City College, in New York. In 1920 he
received his M.A. from Columbia University.
</P>
<P>
   After two years as an instructor in physiology and pharmacology
at the University of Georgia, he returned to graduate school and
earned his Ph.D. in physiology from Chicago in 1923. From then
until 1925, a National Research Council Fellowship allowed him to
study at the University of Utrecht in the Netherlands and the
University of Paris. In 1925 he became a faculty member in
physiology at Chicago, where he would spend the next 35 years,
until his retirement as a full professor in 1960.
</P>
<P>
   In recent decades, he participated in many symposiums on sleep,
dreaming and related topics, said his daughter Esther Kleitman. On
June 2, 1995, at the Associated Professional Sleep Societies
meeting in Nashville, he spoke about subjects like why infants wake
up to nurse. Attendees celebrated his 100th birthday, Dement
recalled, and, ``He was treated like a rock star.''
</P>
<P>
   Kleitman's wife of 50 years, the former Paulena Schweizer, died
in 1977. Besides his daughter Esther, who lives in Los Angeles,
Kleitman is survived by his daughter Hortense Kleitman Snower of
Kansas City, Mo.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
