<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   METROPOLITAN LIFE AGREES TO SETTLE Consumer Suits
</P>
<P>
   Metropolitan Life Insurance agreed to settle class-action and
other lawsuits accusing the company of cheating millions of
customers through deceptive sales practices.
</P>
<P>
   The settlement, which must be approved by a federal judge, would
be the latest in a series of multimillion-dollar settlements by
life insurers accused of fraud. It is intended to cover 7 million
current and past policyholders who bought products between 1982 and
1997 and is valued at $1.7 billion.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA PLANS CURBS ON CONSTRUCTION
</P>
<P>
   Chinese officials announced that they would ban construction of
any new factories that make a broad range of ordinary consumer
items. The ban, which also covers the construction of luxury
hotels, apartment and office buildings and department stores, is
intended to shackle deflation.
</P>
<P>
   A $3.3 BILLION SUPERMARKET DEAL
</P>
<P>
   Food Lion said it planned to acquire Hannaford Brothers for $3.3
billion, forming the sixth-largest supermarket chain in the
country. The acquisition would give Food Lion, which is strong in
the Southeast, a presence in the Northeast and a way to gain on
competitors. The deal continues the rapid consolidation of the
grocery industry.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT TO RELEASE PROTOCOL
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft, in a jab at America Online, said it would release a
computer protocol to enable subscribers of other instant-messaging
services to communicate with its customers.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. TO REGISTER SMALL MONEY DEALERS
</P>
<P>
   Seeking to stem the flow of billions of dollars in illegal drug
profits out of the country, the Treasury Department announced that
it would require all check-cashing businesses and other money
servicing firms _ which drug smugglers and dealers often use _ to
register with the federal authorities.
</P>
<P>
   NEWS CORP.'S EARNINGS FALL
</P>
<P>
   The News Corp.'s earnings fell below analysts' forecasts as weak
results from its Fox television network offset strong gains in its
20th Century Fox film division. The Australia-based media company,
controlled by Rupert Murdoch, reported a 19.5 percent slide in
after-tax earnings to $214 million, or 21 cents an American
depository receipt, for the three months ended June 30.
</P>
<P>
   PILOTS AND AMERICAN AIR STILL DIFFER
</P>
<P>
   American Airlines and its pilots union failed to reach agreement
over the airline's planned integration of Reno Air, which it
acquired, after a last-ditch attempt by a mediator to broker an
agreement between the two sides.
</P>
<P>
   CHANGE OF CONTROL FOR VESPA MAKER?
</P>
<P>
   The Texas Pacific Group is close to a deal to spend about $650
million to acquire a controlling interest in Piaggio Veicoli
Europei, the Italian group that manufactures the Vespa, a perky
little Italian motor scooter immortalized in the 1953 American film
``Roman Holiday.''
</P>
<P>
   IRIDIUM PROPOSES A DEBT SWAP
</P>
<P>
   Iridium, the global satellite telephone company that has filed
for bankruptcy protection, said it had proposed that a group of
bondholders swap $1.45 billion of debt for a 33 percent stake. The
bondholders have not agreed to do so, the company said, although
Motorola, its biggest investor, backs the plan.
</P>
<P>
   DAEWOO MEETS WITH CREDITORS
</P>
<P>
   The Daewoo Group, the struggling South Korean conglomerate, met
with international creditors for the first time since its financial
crisis erupted in mid-July.
</P>
</TEXT>
