<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CRUISE-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AD COLUMN: CUNARD LOOKS TO ITS PAST IN NEW $12.5 MILLION CAMPAIGN 
</HEADLINE>
 (nk) 
 By EDWIN McDOWELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When the Carnival Corp. and a group of investors paid $500
million for the Cunard cruise ship line a little more than a year
ago, some cruise industry executives wondered why. After all, just
a few years earlier, when the Walt Disney Co. was looking to enter
the cruise business, a Disney executive told a British newspaper:
``We have no interest in Cunard or the QE2. It is seen in the
industry as something of a liability.''
</P>
<P>
   While lacking in diplomacy, that assessment was basically
correct. Even though Cunard's flagship, Queen Elizabeth 2, was the
most famous cruise ship afloat, both the ship and the company had
been adrift for several years. The low point occurred during a
trans-Atlantic voyage in December 1994, when the newly renovated
QE2's pipes exploded, toilets erupted and passengers were on the
verge of rioting. That embarrassment cost the ship bookings and
cost Cunard $13 million to settle the claims of angry passengers.
</P>
<P>
   But Carnival executives were confident that in buying Cunard,
whose 158-year-old pedigree and name were unequaled among people
who wanted to travel in style and were willing to pay for it, they
were buying ``a brand equity.''
</P>
<P>
   Within months they merged Cunard with the company's other
upscale brand, Seabourn Cruise Line, and during the next five
months, through the end of the fiscal year that ended Nov. 30,
Cunard wound up with a modest profit of $35 million. While that was
not a bad first step, Carnival, which last year made more than $1
million of profit a day, has larger long-range ambitions for its
acquisition.
</P>
<P>
   Cunard plans to spend $12.5 million on a worldwide all-print
advertising campaign that will get under way by month's end and run
until December 2000. The campaign will appear in 14 newspapers in
the United States, from New York to California, including The New
York Times, The Los Angeles Times, The Philadelphia Inquirer, The
Washington Post, USA Today and The Miami Herald; in nine upscale
magazines including The New York Times magazine, Travel &AMP; Leisure,
Conde Nast Traveler, Gourmet, and Forbes FYI and five travel trade
publications. The same campaign will also appear in Australia, Asia
and Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Dubbed the ``Continuum Campaign,'' the Cunard ads do not seek to
be all things to all cruise line passengers, but to recapture the
elegance and mystique of ocean travel _ of the time, as one ad puts
it, ``when gentlemen on Queen Mary dressed for dinner, and
passengers wore T-shirts  &UR; under  &LR; their clothing.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the motto ``Advancing Civilization Since 1840,'' and with
at least several ads headlined, ``Those who worship change simply
don't understand tradition,'' the ads speak to ``timeless
elegance'' and a ``gracious atmosphere,'' while turning up their
collective nose at ``a world of mass production and glitz.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The campaign's tone is reminiscent of a bygone era _ where
civility and manners were traits of ladies and gentlemen, and
Cunard was the only way to cross,'' said Dorn Martell, senior
creative vice president of Tinsley Advertising of Miami, which has
the account.
</P>
<P>
   The new ads blending Cunard's rich history and past advertising
appeals are based on extensive research. To achieve historical
authenticity, Tinsley researched the Cunard archives at the
University of Liverpool and in the Maritime Museum in Liverpool,
Cunard's original home port.
</P>
<P>
   ``The backgrounds of every ad contain the actual technical
drawings of ships like Aquitania, Oregon, Queen Mary and Royal
George,'' Martell said. ``The illustrations are gleaned from
sources like the original brochure for Lusitania and photos of
classic maritime architecture like the Palladian lounge from
Aquitania, all melded with contemporary images from the QE2.''
</P>
<P>
   Larry Pimental, the chief executive of Cunard and Seabourn,
views this as the perfect time for ads in this style. ``While most
of the cruise industry is trying to differentiate itself from the
formality of classic cruising,'' he said, ``we feel there is a
niche for us where people still desire the graciousness and
elegance that has always been our tradition.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the QE2, Cunard's fleet includes the
700-passenger Caronia, which is expected back in service in
November after being refurbished, and a new ship that is being
billed as the world's biggest ocean liner, planned for introduction
in about three years. The Caronia, formerly the Vistafjord, is a
single-stack liner and the third Cunard ship to bear the Caronia
name.
</P>
<P>
   The overall cruise market reached a record 5.4 million
passengers last year and is expected to continue growing as long as
the economy remains healthy. The luxury cruise segment, generally
thought to be about 15 percent of the market, is also expected to
grow, although competition from luxury resorts will be more intense
than ever. To counter that threat, Cunard is lowering its rates an
average of 20 percent next year, while hoping that its reputation,
tradition and new ad campaign will fill more berths as it sails
into the new millennium.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
