<HEADLINE>
BOXERS EMBRACE BIG BEAR SOLITUDE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT MORALES  
 c.1999 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BIG BEAR LAKE, Calif. _ In the summer, there's hiking, fishing
and boating. Come winter, there's skiing.
</P>
<P>
   This area known for its outdoor sports, however, could soon
become boxing's mecca for training.
</P>
<P>
   Fighters from South Africa, New Zealand, Mexico and Poland _
even less exotic locales like Oxnard, New York and Detroit _ flock
to this mountain hideaway to prepare their bodies and minds for the
ring.
</P>
<P>
   They believe training in high altitude _ 7,200 feet _ improves
their endurance, although doctors debate the effects. The solitude,
they know, bolsters their psyche and allows them to concentrate on
boxing.
</P>
<P>
   The Big Bear boom started nine years ago with just one )Jgamp _
Larry Goossen's Boxing Gym. Local fighters such as Gabriel and
Rafael Ruelas became its mainstays. Today, Big Bear Lake supports
four camps.
</P>
<P>
   ``The appeal for me as a manager is you have isolation, number
one,'' said Scott Woodworth, who has trained his fighters _ Roberto
Garcia, Orlin Norris, Felipe Campa, Israel Correa and Carlos
Madrigal _ here for 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are not a lot of things to do to get in trouble up
there. When you have guys come to Vegas early in their careers,
there are a lot of temptations,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``And the altitude. With that kind of wind, the running and the
training, by the time you get back down to sea level you are going
to have more (stamina) in the (later) rounds.''
</P>
<P>
   The area got a big boost from Oscar De La Hoya, who helped make
it fashionable to train here. Emanuel Steward has a gym here, Kronk
Gym West. Larry Goossen's Boxing Gym is now the Big Bear Boxing &AMP;
Fitness Gym.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this summer, Francois Botha of South Africa and4MM!9non
Briggs both trX&AMP;+$Z(W
</P>
</TEXT>
