<DOCNO> NYT19990818.0420 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-18 23:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2437 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-APOLLO-MEDIA-NYT &LR;      08-18 0714
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-APOLLO-MEDIA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
APOLLO THEATER IS SAID TO REJECT A RICHER BID AS TALKS CONTINUE
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By TERRY PRISTIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Apollo Theater has rebuffed a multimillion-dollar
bid to finance and distribute the weekly program ``It's Showtime at
the Apollo'' and is expected to make a less lucrative deal with
Percy E. Sutton, the former Manhattan borough president, and his
financial backers, officials and lawyers involved in the
negotiations said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   BKS Entertainment, a television syndication company that
distributes and markets programs aimed at minority viewers, bid on
the ``Showtime'' contract on Aug. 6 after learning that Time Warner
was to take control of the board of the Apollo Theater Foundation.
The foundation is the nonprofit organization that runs the theater,
a state-owned Harlem landmark where the popular variety program is
taped. BKS said it was willing to retain Sutton's company, Inner
City Theater Group, as the producer of ``Showtime.''
</P>
<P>
   The program lies at the heart of a lawsuit filed by the state
attorney general's office in November that accused six directors of
the Apollo, including the chairman, Rep. Charles Rangel, a Harlem
Democrat, of failing to collect $4.4 million owed to the theater by
Inner City. Rangel and Sutton, who are political allies, have
denied wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, in the only bid for ``Showtime,'' Sutton's
company offered $250,000 a year for a three-year contract to
produce the program _ a bid that he described Wednesday as only a
``minimum'' figure. The Apollo board rejected the offer at its July
meeting and asked Sutton to increase it. As of late Wednesday, the
terms were being negotiated, lawyers for Sutton said.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney General Eliot L. Spitzer has said that the state's
lawsuit will not be settled unless Time Warner approves the terms
of the deal with Inner City and Sutton's longtime financial backer,
Western International Syndication.
</P>
<P>
   Edward Adler, a Time Warner spokesman, would not discuss the
negotiations Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Without a letter from Time Warner, there is no chance that the
lawsuit will be resolved at a board meeting that was scheduled for
Thursday morning, said Scott Brown, a spokesman for Spitzer. Brown
said that although the language in the settlement agreement does
not specify it, it is understood that other conditions include
Rangel's stepping down as chairman and the addition by Time Warner
of 10 new members to the theater's nine-member board.
</P>
<P>
   Spitzer has approved a settlement provision that exonerates the
defendants in the lawsuit. It says that he has determined that the
Apollo board ``acted in good faith in pursuit of the best interests
of the foundation'' and that Inner City and Sutton ``acted in good
faith in their dealings with the Foundation.''
</P>
<P>
   The agreement would require the Apollo to demonstrate within 30
days that it has received a total of $1 million _ the minimum
amount that Spitzer has concluded that the theater is owed _ from
various sources. Sutton has agreed to contribute $150,000 to the
total amount, which is described in the agreement as a contribution
to pay for future audits of the foundation.
</P>
<P>
   The parties were on the verge of signing the agreement last week
when BKS's offer became public. In the days since, Sutton and
lawyers for the Apollo have sought to plant doubts about BKS's
ability to back up its offer to guarantee the Apollo $5 million
over the next five years.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, Sutton accused BKS of ``showboating'' by arriving
late in the game _ the taping of 12 episodes of the show is
scheduled to begin Aug. 26 _ and making a lavish bid. ``There's no
way on God's green earth that these people could pay a million
dollars a year and make it work,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But BKS, a four-year-old company run by Robert I. Silberberg and
Leonard Koch, both veteran syndicators, already distributes a
weekly music program, ``Russell Simmons' One World Music,'' which
is produced by Black Pearl Entertainment in association with Warner
Bros.
</P>
<P>
   Western International Syndication, which is owned by
Interpublic, gets most of its business from ``It's Showtime at the
Apollo.'' The company also distributes a weekly children's program
called ``Field Trip.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
