<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-18 23:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2446 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBA-YANKS-ROYALS-NYT &LR;      08-18 0832
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-ROYALS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PETTITTE SPARKLES, BUT ROYALS TRIUMPH 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By JACK CURRY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Andy Pettitte was challenging Carlos Beltran and Tim
Spehr in critical situations Wednesday night, but he could have
envisioned that it was Manny Ramirez and Roberto Alomar or Ivan
Rodriguez and Juan Gonzalez. That is what Pettitte could have
imagined against the relatively anonymous Royals because those are
the types of conquests he is chasing.
</P>
<P>
   Pettitte overcame obstacle after obstacle, but he could not
snare Derek Jeter's errant throw to first base on what should have
been an inning-ending double play in the eighth inning and that
buried the Yankees. The ball nicked off Pettitte's glove, dribbled
behind him into foul territory and enabled Rey Sanchez to scoot
home from second with the first run of a taut game.
</P>
<P>
   The first run was monumental as the Royals acted like the
Indians or the Rangers by quieting the Yankees, 3-0, at Yankee
Stadium. Dan Reichert, a 23-year old who entered the game with a
12.08 earned run average, shocked the Yankees by pitching seven
four-hit innings for his second major league victory.
</P>
<P>
   While the Yankees tumbled to 3-3 in their last six games against
the very ordinary Royals and Twins, the sort of sluggish streak
that annoys someone like George Steinbrenner, Pettitte's revival is
what Joe Torre pondered before going to sleep. Pettitte did not
give up an earned run in eight solid innings and has yielded two
earned runs over his last 31 innings for a 0.58 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel good about where I'm at right now,'' Pettitte said.
``I've just got to keep myself here.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Pettitte succumbed because of Jeter's second damaging
error in four games. With runners on first and second and one out
in the eighth, Mike Sweeney lashed a grounder to the right side.
Tino Martinez slid to his knees to snatch the ball and whipped to
Jeter for the first out. Pettitte was sprinting toward first and
would have been in time for the double play, but Jeter tossed the
ball at Pettitte instead of ahead of him and at the base. Pettitte
had to stop, then lunge back to his left and the ball deflected off
his glove.
</P>
<P>
   ``He got there as a quick as he could,'' Jeter said. ``It's a
situation where I threw it on the wrong side. It was a tough play.
Unfortunately, we didn't make it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Royals added two runs in the ninth, off Ramiro Mendoza and
Mike Stanton.
</P>
<P>
   One of the reasons Pettitte struggled so mightily this season is
because he lacked aggressiveness. Pettitte's pitches were crisp,
but he did not attack hitters with confidence. But Pettitte has
regained his passion and he throttled the Royals on no hits in
seven at bats with men in scoring position. He has chopped his ERA
from 5.65 to 4.52, which is lower than Roger Clemens (4.60) and
barely higher than Orlando Hernandez (4.34) and Hideki Irabu
(4.28). ``If you're looking for a bright spot, Andy's the only
bright spot,'' said Torre, after the Yankees were listless against
a young starter for the third straight night. ``We didn't play
well, for sure. Pettitte will stand out with the way he went about
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Pettitte's turnaround has complicated the future. Torre dreads
the decision he will have to make in six weeks because one of his
starters is going to be given a seat in the bullpen for the
post-season. Before Pettitte's recent streak, he was the leading
candidate to be left out in October. Now the skirmish is between
Pettitte and Irabu and the 27-year old left-hander who the Yankees
almost traded might have the edge.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be a tough call,'' Torre said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   If the playoffs started before Wednesday night's games, the
Yankees would play Texas in the Division Series. That is not
comforting news to Pettitte, the Deer Park, Texas, native who is
5-3 with a 6.42 ERA against the Rangers. He is also 0-3 with a
16.05 ERA in three starts at the Ballpark in Arlington, where the
fourth starter would probably pitch. Irabu is 1-1 with a 4.22
against the Rangers, including two solid outings this season.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees and the Indians seem to be running on a collision
course into the American League Championship Series. When Torre
studies those matchups, he will see that Pettitte is 3-5 with a
5.34 against the Indians, including a 10-7 loss in June, while
Irabu is 3-1 with a 4.81. Pettitte has opposed the Rangers and
Indians more frequently, but Irabu has the slightly better
statistics.
</P>
<P>
   Still, after Pettitte struggled for more than three months and
almost had his baseball address changed, he has been superb.
Pettitte's last four starts have been outstanding and have
convinced Torre that he can depend on Pettitte again, which could
nudge Irabu to the bullpen for the post-season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still in the area where you hope to see it again,''
explained Torre, about judging Pettitte. ``If you don't, you've
seen it enough.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-18-99 2351EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
