<HEADLINE>
THOSE ARE FIGHTIN' BUZZWORDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE STAFFORD  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A reader stuck his tongue in cheek and responded to last week's
At Work column, which panned 16 irksome business buzzwords.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thank you from all of us who feel like we're stuck in a
Dilbert cartoon where policies are implemented to facilitate
cross-functional objectives and achieve meaningful synergies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd hate to be deinstalled here at the cube farm,'' he wrote,
asking anonymity. ``Deinstallation would force me to network my
strong interpersonal, communication and multitasking organizational
skills.''
</P>
<P>
   (For the record, the target words last week were: paradigm,
synergy, incent or incentivize, benchmark, best practices, world
class, core competencies, functional silos, actionable, proactive,
branding, re-engineering, rightsizing, delayering, full-time
equivalents and grow, as in ``grow the company.'')
</P>
<P>
   Dozens of readers agreed that the buzzwords had been rendered
meaningless by overuse and misuse. In fact, many consider them
fightin' words.
</P>
<P>
   Several readers sent versions of buzzword bingo-type cards to be
played at meetings and speeches.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had only been in the meeting for five minutes when I yelled,
``Bingo,'' read the testimony from one player who fought back.
</P>
<P>
   Many suggested other buzzword peeves. ``May I add to your hit
list strategic plan?'' wrote one reader. ``On the same level as
proactive, I find this expression odd and redundant. When is a plan
not strategic?''
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, strategic alliance rankles. But the buzzword most
nominated for mercy killing was win-win. ``No solution is equally
good for all,'' said one person. ``Somebody always gets a bigger
piece of the pie.''
</P>
<P>
   Another respondent took aim at critical mass: ``Clearly, this
should be reserved for those who actually understand how to split
an atom.''
</P>
<P>
   One man pointed out how insidious buzzwords can be. I bemoaned
proactive and wrote about ``taking an active step'' instead. That
pushed me ``over the Great Wall of corporate gobbledegook,'' he
wrote. Why not simply ``take a step?''
</P>
<P>
   Workers also despise nouns turned into verbs: dialogue, partner,
decision and calendar. (Come on, are there really people who say,
``Calendar this''?)
</P>
<P>
   Others prefer ``use'' to utilize and absolutely abhor
prioritize.
</P>
<P>
   Readers said they're sick of hearing about stakeholders and
diversity. The latter is so overused it means nothing, several
said.
</P>
<P>
   They hate obfuscations, namely increasing efficiencies and
unexpected opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   They're weary of at the end of the day and at this point in time
_ but those are slightly better than the bottom line.
</P>
<P>
   They are tired of being asked to think outside the box or
brainstorm, even if it would empower them or put them on the fast
track.
</P>
<P>
   And they're annoyed at hyphenated drivel such as value-added,
quality-driven, results-oriented, client-focused and
knowledge-based.
</P>
<P>
   There were more irritations but there's no more space, so with
Round 2, the buzzword diatribe must end.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
